   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.S.-DRUGS (Undated) _ American charities and drug
companies have donated drugs and emergency medical supplies to the
Kosovo relief effort _ with mixed results. By Reed Abelson.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SERBS (Belgrade) _ About 75,000 Serbs have moved from
Kosovo to Serbia proper and refugee aid groups say they are running
out of food for them. This comes on top of 500,000 Serb refugees
from Croatia and Bosnia, according to UNHCR estimates. But the
feeding operation is run by the Red Cross and it apparently stopped
shipping food during the war and has not yet resumed shipments. By
Blaine Harden.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-CONSERVATIVES (Laconia, N.H.) _ Many politically active
conservatives say they are increasingly frustrated and distressed
by the early dominance of George W. Bush in the Republican
presidential race. They accuse their party of sacrificing principle
in the name of pragmatism, prompting some to talk of mounting a
third-party campaign. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   COLO-SCHOOL-MURDERS (Littleton, Colo.) _ Two months after the
school shootings here, interviews with scores of people indicate a
fundamental disconnect between the trouble world of Eric Harris and
Dylan Klebold and the lives their parents thought they were
leading. The interviews paint a portrait of the Harrises and the
Klebolds as caring, conscientious parents who structured their
lives around supporting their children and believed they were on
the right track. By Pam Belluck and Jodi Wilgoren.
</P>
