<P>
   INSURANCE-FRAUD (Undated) _ One of the mysteries about Martin
Frankel, the man authorities suspect of orchestrating a spectacular
insurance fraud, is how a financier who almost never left his
well-guarded Greenwich, Conn., mansion befriended corporate and
religious elites on two continents. The answer appears to be that
Frankel turned to Thomas Corbally, a business consultant whose ties
to powerful people made him an insider at Kroll Associates, one of
America's best-known private investigative agencies. By Joseph Kahn
and Kurt Eichenwald.
</P>
<P>
   COKE-EUROPE (Brussels, Belgium) _ A critical look at the details
of the Coke contamination in Belgium that led to the biggest recall
in its 113-year history. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-UNION-SOUTH (Vance, Ala.) _ Steven Merrill was one of the
first workers Mercedes-Benz hired as it geared up to build sport
utility vehicles here in 1994. He has received steady raises and a
two-month training trip to Germany. He even met his wife on the
assembly line. Now, the United Automobile Workers union is trying
to organize the Mercedes factory, and Merrill does not want any
part of it. By Robyn Meredith.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   PHARMACEUTICALS-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ Not more than a year
ago, many pharmaceutical companies were trying to strengthen their
agricultural holdings for ballast during a downturn in
pharmaceuticals. Now, in an abrupt change for the industry, there
is a flight away from agricultural products. By David J. Morrow.
</P>
