<SLUG> BC-FLASH-FLOODS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLASH FLOODS HAVE KANSAS CITY GASPING AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATT CAMPBELL  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ As Kansas Citians prepared for work Monday
morning, torrential rain triggered flash flooding, trapping people
in their cars and homes and inundating low-lying streets and
highways.
</P>
<P>
   Then in a matter of hours the rain clouds moved on and the sun
shone brightly as people surveyed the damage.
</P>
<P>
   But the storms might return as soon as tonight, bringing more
rain to already saturated ground. The National Weather Service
forecasts a 40 percent chance of rain tonight and a good chance of
thunderstorms Wednesday, Thursday and Friday.
</P>
<P>
   As much as 5 inches of rain fell on parts of the city Sunday and
Monday, pushing the year-to-date total to 10.5 inches above normal.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike flooding Oct. 4, when 11 persons died, no lives were lost
in Monday's storms. But damage was extensive in both floods. On
Monday, buildings collapsed, sections of interstate were closed,
power was knocked out and people had to be rescued from rising
waters.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City Power &AMP; Light Co. reported about 20,000 customers
were without power Monday morning because of lightning and downed
trees. Service was restored to all but about 2,500 by midafternoon.
</P>
<P>
   On the Missouri side of the state line, a young girl reported
seeing another child swept away by Deer Creek near Castle Drive in
Lake Tapawingo. Searchers from the Central Jackson County Fire
Protection District and the Missouri Water Patrol found a backpack,
tricycle and clothing but concluded the items were carried from the
yards along the creek.
</P>
<P>
   In Blue Springs, a pregnant Kansas City woman was rescued a few
hundred feet from Station No. 2 of the Central Jackson County Fire
Protection District.
</P>
<P>
   Between 8 a.m. and noon, the Kansas City Fire Department
responded to 88 flood-related calls, according to spokesman Brad
Humston. During an average 24 hours, the department handles 130
calls for all types of problems.
</P>
<P>
   Residents of the Village Green Apartments near Brush Creek and
the Paseo were spared the devastation of October, in which hundreds
were left homeless. But the rain flooded at least six townhouse
basements.
</P>
<P>
   On the Country Club Plaza, the Brush Creek flood control project
worked as designed, containing the water and channeling it
downstream.
</P>
<P>
   In east Kansas City, water converged from three directions on a
low spot near 40th and Oakley streets, overflowing two small street
drains before gurgling over the curbs and into elevated yards. Then
it kept climbing.
</P>
<P>
   James Robertson, who lives on the west side of Oakley, knew
something was wrong when his telephone went dead. As he stepped out
of bed to check the phone, his feet touched water. He looked out
the window and saw his neighbor's white 1985 Monte Carlo floating
south.
</P>
<P>
   Across Oakley, Kathy Newberry was watching the car drift when
she heard a basement window shatter. She opened her basement door
and saw water rushing across the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, God!'' she exclaimed, aware it was too late to save
childhood photographs she recently had stored there. The water
surged through the window until it filled the basement to within a
foot of the main floor, ruining a freezer, refrigerator and two
washers and dryers.
</P>
<P>
   Next door to Robertson, three girls, ages 8, 11, and 12, paged
their parents to return home as water swept into their bedroom,
soaking plush red carpeting installed after the October flood
caused $25,000 damage to the house. The girls didn't know what to
do until an aunt, who lived five houses north, appeared and told
them to follow her.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you take one wrong step, you float away,'' said 11-year-old
Reeva Ford, who feared she was going to die as her aunt trudged
through the thigh-high water to save her and her two sisters.
</P>
<P>
   The aunt, 27-year-old Nikko Ford, had crossed the street in high
water and then clutched trees to keep her balance as she walked to
the girls' home. She had the two older girls lock their arms around
her elbows and held the youngest girl in front of her as they
headed back up the street.
</P>
<P>
   They cried as they waded, unable to swim and afraid of what
might happen if they slipped.
</P>
<P>
   The girls' parents, Catherine and Dana Ford, returned home to a
scene they've witnessed at least five times since 1977. In the
house, water squished from the carpet with every step. Outside,
shovels and other large tools had been swept out of Dana Ford's
work truck and hurled against a neighbor's fence. Mud caked the
truck's seats. The Monte Carlo, purchased just two weeks earlier
for $2,500, was soaked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Flood insurance doesn't cover your vehicles,'' said Catherine
Ford, who is upset the city had not enlarged the drainage system in
front of her house despite repeated floods at that location.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody is eventually going to lose their life out here,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the worst flooding was reported in Wyandotte County.
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters there pulled more than 25 persons from flooded
houses and stalled cars; three buildings collapsed; and
intersections were closed from Kansas 32 in Bonner Springs to
Southwest Boulevard in eastern Kansas City, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters waded through knee-high water to rescue two persons
from a house in the 1400 block of Washington Boulevard in Kansas
City, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is worse than October,'' said a neighbor, Maxine Elmore.
</P>
<P>
   The roof of McBratney Optical Service in the 1400 block of
Minnesota Avenue collapsed after the foundation of the house next
door crumbled against the building.
</P>
<P>
   McBratney employee Linda Fuqua got stuck in high water near 18th
Street and Washington Boulevard, apparently just moments before the
roof of her building collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I hadn't have gotten stalled, I would have been inside this
building,'' she said. ``Somebody was watching over me.''
</P>
<P>
   High water forced officials to shut down Interstate 35 at 18th
Street and at Interstate 635 from about 9:45 to 11 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   A couple and their dog were rescued by neighbors from their
flooded mobile home in the Woodland Acres mobile home park in
Kansas City, Kan. Rick Mendenhall and Rhonda Aipperspach escaped
through a window into the arms of men secured to utility poles by
ropes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just did what neighbors are supposed to do,'' said one of
the rescuers, who identified himself only as Joe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
