<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEPATITIS-B-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REQUIREMENT HAS PARENTS SCRAMBLING TO OBTAIN CHILDREN'S SHOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARA ROSE WILLIAMS  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Every year about this time, parents scramble
to obtain the vaccines their children need to enter school. But the
rush is more intense this year in Missouri, where seventh-graders
cannot enter school this fall without a hepatitis B shot.
</P>
<P>
   Last week more than 200 people showed up at a Blue Springs
church where the Jackson County Health Department established a
satellite clinic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know some people who came and saw the line and just left,''
said Win Edwards, Blue Springs middle school nurse.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came back later, and there were still lines,'' Edwards
said. ``There are going to be lines and people are going to have to
wait because the law is that there will be zero tolerance. If a
student hasn't got the shots they can't even get through the
door.''
</P>
<P>
   In Kansas the hepatitis B shot is required this year for entry
into kindergarten, but most children already have received the
vaccination, which has been given to newborns since 1994, said
Rosie Howlett, a nurse with the Unified Government Department of
Health in Wyandotte County.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas health officials are recommending hepatitis B shots for
children who will be 11 years old on or before Sept. 1. But the
shots won't be required for seventh-graders until next fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect some lines but nothing like what is happening in
Missouri,'' Howlett said.
</P>
<P>
   Hepatitis B is a liver ailment spread through blood and other
body fluids. In this country, 300,000 people _ mostly young adults
_ are infected annually, according to the Unified Government
Department of Health. The disease kills 5,000 people a year.
</P>
<P>
   Symptoms include fatigue, low-grade fever and sometimes
jaundice. The disease spreads most commonly through sexual contact
and intravenous drug use. But infectious-disease experts are
increasingly concerned about teen-agers and hepatitis B because of
the popularity of tattooing and body piercing.
</P>
<P>
   That, in part, is why health officials wanted adolescents to be
vaccinated before they engaged in risky behavior.
</P>
<P>
   In Missouri the vaccination lines are certain to get longer as
the school days approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most parents usually procrastinate until August and then it is
extremely crazy. The line goes all the way outside, and people get
hot and angry,'' said Bill Schmidt, administrator of the Jackson
County Health Department in Independence.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri school districts will admit seventh-graders if they can
show they have had at least one shot in the three-shot hepatitis B
series. But health officials warn that the second shot is due 28
days after the first, and the third shot is due five months later.
Students who don't follow through could be asked not to return to
school until they have been immunized.
</P>
<P>
   ``With somewhere in the neighborhood of 70,000 seventh-graders
in Missouri, we are talking about a lot of kids who have to have
this vaccination,'' said Sue Denny, health program representative
for the state Department of Health.
</P>
<P>
   In the Blue Springs School District alone, 500 to 600 students
still need their first shots. Blue Springs was one of several
districts that did not participate in an in-school immunization
program run by the Mid America Immunization Coalition in Kansas
City and local health departments.
</P>
<P>
   That program was launched in 1995 to curb the spread of
hepatitis B.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Kinder, deputy superintendent in Blue Springs, said the
district will participate in the immunization program this year.
</P>
<P>
   But even where in-school immunizations were offered, large
numbers of students were not vaccinated, said Leanne Glenn, a nurse
with the Kansas City Health Department. For example, she said, only
30 percent of the sixth-graders in the Kansas City School District
took advantage of the program.
</P>
<P>
   At local health departments in Missouri the shots are free. But
it could cost as much as $175 for the shots at a private
physician's office. In Kansas the shots cost a small administration
fee that varies from county to county.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri Health Department officials and school district nurses
are doing mass mailings that explain the requirement to parents of
seventh-graders. Still, officials are concerned that many children
will show up at school this year without shots.
</P>
<P>
   To head off some of that chaos, some districts are asking for
proof of immunization when students pre-register for classes or
pick up their schedules late in the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents have to realize it is out of our hands here at
school,'' Edwards said. ``Seventh-graders have to have these
shots.''
</P>
<P>
   For information about immunization clinics, call the city or
county health department in your area.
</P>
</TEXT>
