<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 00:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2791 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BBA-WHITESOX-REDSOX-BOS     06-29 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
OFFERMAN, RED SOX HAVE A BLAST
</HEADLINE>
 BBA-WHITESOX-REDSOX-BOS (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
By LARRY WHITESIDE 
c.1999 The Boston Globe 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Maybe it's time to stop trying to figure out how to
improve these Red Sox. Just sit back and enjoy a rather remarkable
stretch of offense and pitching.
</P>
<P>
   You certainly won't see much better offense than the season-high
21-hit attack that finished off the Chicago White Sox Monday night,
14-1. It was such a treat that most of the 24,616 at Fenway Park
hung around wondering how good this team can be, rather than
worrying about the 1 1/2-game deficit to the Yankees in the
American League East. That comes later. Much later.
</P>
<P>
   It had to be fun to watch Bret Saberhagen pitch well enough to
get his fourth victory and second in a row. Normally, seven innings
of work just isn't enough for the veteran righthander. But when you
throw 60 strikes in 79 pitches and unlease a changeup on
righthanded batters who were praying for a curveball, it's OK to
quit a tad early with an 11-0 lead. Afterall, Pedro Martinez got
the night off after just five innings of a 17-1 rout of Chicago
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Saberhagen has to be pleased with himself,'' said Sox
manager Jimy Williams. ``He was very consistent, around the plate,
changed speeds and out in front of hitters. Saberhagen knows how to
pitch. When you kill bat speed, that is the whole key. He did well
tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Which leads you directly to one Jose Offerman, much maligned in
some circles despite the fact he is hitting .301. Offerman had four
hits, including two home runs, and a career-high six RBIs. His
second home run was a seventh-inning grand slam, the first of his
rather interesting career. Sooner or later Red Sox fans will forget
about numbers and accept him as a fine player. His teammates do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jose had a wonderful night,'' said Nomar Garciaparra, who had
quite a night himself (4 for 5, two doubles) in improving his
average to .362. ``It's nice to see a teammate come through.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Offerman, who doesn't say a lot, felt good about Monday
night. The multiple home runs were a career first.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an exciting game for me,'' said Offerman, who had
entered the game in a 2-for-23 skid. ``I know I was in a slump but
I never gave up. I just kept on working. The grand slam? Yeah, I
can finally say I got one.''
</P>
<P>
   And by doing so, he earned the praise of his boss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Offerman really had a special night,'' said Williams. ``But it
doesn't surprise you because he is a professional hitter. I know he
expects a lot out of himself. I just hope that kind of a game can
jump-start him and get him going again.''
</P>
<P>
   The White Sox scored 11 runs in four games and lost three of
them. Boston scored victories of 6-1, 17-1 and 14-1 in which it
collected 48 hits. The only loss was a 7-6 slugfest in which the
Red Sox blew a 5-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The 21 hits were the most since the Sox had 24 in a 17-1 loss at
Texas Aug. 5, 1997. The Sox have won 11 of their last 15 games and
are 19-9 against the AL Central. Since Chicago and Boston meet
again this weekend, it will be easy to see if Monday night's
demolition was real or just Memorex.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was good tonight,'' said Saberhagen when asked about his
performance. ``But I think there is room for improvement. I had a
good changeup. But my curveball was so-so. Fortunately, I think I
recognized it early on and went to the changeup a little bit more
to righthanded hitters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chicago helped. They come out swinging. And when you have a
team swinging early, you're going to get more strikeouts.''
</P>
<P>
   Saberhagen may not be 100 percent happy but his teammates are.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's important,'' said Garciaparra. ``But then our whole staff
is important. It's good to have him back and have him healthy out
there. He hasn't missed a beat, which is really good.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox struck early and never looked back. Singles by Troy
O'Leary, Creighton Gubanich and Darren Lewis highlighted a
three-run surge in the second inning. In the fifth, Offerman hit a
home run off lefthander Mike Sirotka. Boston scored three more runs
in the sixth, in which it sent nine batters to the plate. The Sox
had six singles in the rally _ five after two were out.
</P>
<P>
   Offerman's slam in the seventh followed singles by Lou Merloni,
Jason Varitek, and Lewis. Boston capped off the night with three
runs in the eighth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
