<DOCNO> NYT19990629.0006 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 01:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2794 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-HAKEEM-TRADE-HNS &LR;      06-29 1091
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HAKEEM-TRADE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
and MICHAEL MURPHY 
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
The Dream could be over in Houston.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Rockets have been negotiating an agreement in which Hakeem
Olajuwon, a Houston basketball institution for almost two decades,
would be dealt to the Toronto Raptors for two players and two
first-round draft picks, sources close to the talks said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets have been talking to Raptors officials for more than
two weeks but had not completed the deal as of late Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations, however, became more intense Sunday and Monday and
could lead, sources said, to some slight changes in the offer,
potentially including another draft pick or player.
</P>
<P>
   Rockets officials, citing club policy, refused to comment about
the trade negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing is there will be fewer free agents in the
future under the new collective bargaining agreement,'' a source
close to the trade talks said under the condition of anonymity.
``You can already see more players signed with their teams because
they get more money with their current teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Free agency as we once knew it has been curtailed.''
</P>
<P>
   Olajuwon, the Rockets' most successful and celebrated player in
a 15-year career that followed three seasons at the University of
Houston, led the Rockets to NBA championships in 1994 and '95.
</P>
<P>
   Because there is a league moratorium on trades until Aug. 1, the
Raptors would have to select players on the Rockets' behalf during
Wednesday's NBA draft.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets would acquire the Raptors' two first-round
selections, the fifth pick (acquired from Denver) and the 12th pick
(Toronto's own). The Raptors also would send former Rockets
center/forward Kevin Willis and guard/forward Doug Christie to
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Both players are under contract for one more season. Because
Toronto would be under the salary cap, it would be able to take on
Olajuwon's $14.3 million salary without precisely matching the
salaries of the players dealt.
</P>
<P>
   Willis played two seasons with the Rockets before he was traded
to Toronto last June for Roy Rogers and two first-round draft picks
(with which the Rockets drafted guard Bryce Drew and forward Mirsad
Turkcan). Willis, 36, averaged 12 points and 8.3 rebounds in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Christie, 29, played 3{ seasons for the Lakers and Knicks before
he seemed to blossom in his three full seasons in Toronto. He
averaged 15.2 points, 4.1 rebounds and 3.7 assists in 1998 and a
career-best 16.5 points and 5.2 rebounds in 1997-98.
</P>
<P>
   Sources said, however, that the draft choices would be the
primary motivation for making the trade. The No. 5 pick would be
the Rockets' highest draft position since selecting Olajuwon with
the first pick of the 1984 draft. The No. 12 pick also could bring
a top prospect as scouts have described the upper echelon of this
season's draft as 13 players deep.
</P>
<P>
   But by dealing Olajuwon, 36, the Rockets would begin a
rebuilding process in the wake of a disappointing first-round
playoff loss to the Lakers, the team's second consecutive ouster in
the first round.
</P>
<P>
   The deal also could affect forward Charles Barkley, who is
considering retirement and has said he wanted to return only if he
thought the Rockets were title contenders.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets had planned to eventually rebuild around Scottie
Pippen, signed to a five-year, $67 million contract before last
season, with free-agent additions following the expected
retirements of Barkley after next season and of Olajuwon after the
2000-2001 season. But with the changes in the league's collective
bargaining agreement, most of the league's top players have
re-signed with their current teams, rather than wait for free
agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teams have to build differently than they once did,'' a source
said. ``The draft and exceptions will be the main way people will
add to their team because high-priced free agents won't be out
there as much.''
</P>
<P>
   This past season, Olajuwon made a strong comeback from a knee
injury suffered during the 1997-98 season. He averaged 16.4 points
per game in '97-98, his first season averaging fewer than 20 points
per game.
</P>
<P>
   But Olajuwon bounced back to average 18.9 points per game in
1999. He averaged 9.6 rebounds and 2.5 blocked shots. He also
seemed to grow stronger as the season progressed. Over the last
third of the regular season (17 games), he averaged 19.5 points,
10.6 rebounds and 3.2 blocked shots. But he was outplayed by
Shaquille O'Neal in the playoffs, averaging only 13.3 points as the
Lakers won the first-round series 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets honored Olajuwon before the season's last
regular-season home game, May 5, unveiling a plaque in Compaq
Center commemorating his status as the NBA's all-time blocked-shots
leader.
</P>
<P>
   The day before that game, Olajuwon said he considered getting to
play his entire career in Houston and becoming so closely
identified with his adopted hometown an ``ideal situation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an attachment,'' Olajuwon said. ``I think it's an
ideal situation. How many players get to go to college in one city,
get drafted in that city, play 15 years of his career in that city,
then be part of the group to bring the first championship to the
city? When you look at all the things that have happened, it's all
in the same city.''
</P>
<P>
   Olajuwon helped lead the University of Houston to the NCAA Final
Four in each of his three seasons with the Cougars.
</P>
<P>
   Olajuwon has been named to the All-NBA first team six times and
is a 12-time All-Star. He started eight All-Star Games (none was
played this season).
</P>
<P>
   Olajuwon was the 1993-1994 Most Valuable Player, and was the NBA
Finals MVP in 1994 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy has been the foundation of this team for 15 years,''
Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich said before the season's final
regular-season home game. ``He's had a tremendous influence on my
life and on basketball and this city. He went to college here, and
he won championships here. He was a part of bringing the joy to
this city.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have him as your mainstay, a guy of character like
that, it makes things easier. For me, it's made my job so much
easier to have a star like him. We came from a franchise that was
just an also-ran, fair team to one of the models in this league, a
place where people want to be. He's a very, very big reason that's
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Those sentiments have made the trade more difficult, sources
said. But Monday, time appeared to be running out on sentiment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-99 0105EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
