<DOCNO> NYT19990629.0007 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 01:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2797 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     06-29 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRAN BLINEBURY  
MAYBE it's just the aftereffects of all those tamales, burritos and
jalapeos I consumed at the San Antonio Spurs' victory party. A
recurring bad Dream.
<TEXT>
<P>
   At least that's what one hopes when word comes that the Rockets
have been negotiating for the better part of two weeks on a deal
that would send Hakeem Olajuwon to Toronto for draft picks and a
pocketful of beans.
</P>
<P>
   One thought on the subject:
</P>
<P>
   No.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, three more thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   No. No. No.
</P>
<P>
   Not now. Not ever.
</P>
<P>
   Not if you want to continue to peddle that ``we-are-fam-uh-lee''
line of which the Rockets, particularly on the basketball
operations side, are so proud.
</P>
<P>
   Not if you really want the franchise to stand for something
other than a 7 percent increase in the already exorbitant price of
tickets.
</P>
<P>
   If you trade Hakeem, you end the dream, the fantasy, that has
been his truly remarkable 15-year NBA career and our ride to the
most wonderful of places with him. And you become merely another
factory that sells widgets off the loading dock.
</P>
<P>
   You can rationalize away the disloyal act by saying it is being
done in the name of business. And so that, in two years, you can
say you got something in return before Olajuwon walked out the door
into retirement.
</P>
<P>
   But what you give up is more than just a player on the downside
of a brilliant career, more than a commodity to be bought, sold or
traded. You have given up a piece of your history, your essence,
your soul. And you don't ever get that back.
</P>
<P>
   Bird was a Celtic, Magic a Laker, Jordan a Bull, Isiah a Piston,
and coach Rudy Tomjanovich was _ and is _ a Rocket.
</P>
<P>
   Rudy T, more than anybody with a hand near the trigger on this
deal, knows what it means to wear one _ and only one _ uniform for
an entire career. He, in fact, vetoed a trade and retired rather
than play for another team.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of local icons, let's get this straight: Earl Campbell
should never have been a Saint. Nolan Ryan should never have been a
Ranger. And we should all be spared the sight of Hakeem taking that
last Dream Shake in a garish purple uniform with a cartoon dinosaur
on his chest.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets, as usual, are making no comment whatsoever on a
potential trade. But the phone lines from Canada work both ways,
and it is known that Raptors coach Butch Carter is pushing to close
a deal.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets field phone calls about most all of their players
all of the time. So what's the big news? This time, according to
sources, they are listening, ears pointed in excitement each time
Toronto attempts to tweak the offer.
</P>
<P>
   What they should have done _ and still could do _ is listen and
politely tell the Raptors they can't and won't have any interest.
And it should be Rudy who hangs up the phone.
</P>
<P>
   Olajuwon made Rudy T's career as a coach, giving him the engine
to drive a very basic offense and the linchpin to secure the
defense, not to mention the heart of a champion that has become the
coach's tag line. Without Hakeem, Rudy T doesn't have two
championships on his rsum, doesn't have a house in River Oaks and a
contract that averages $5 million per year, and isn't coaching the
U.S. Olympic Dream Team in Sydney next summer.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Rockets' first-round playoff elimination in May, many
voices in the organization have been whispering that Hakeem no
longer has the drive, the fire, to win. One can only wonder what
they might say about Scottie Pippen.
</P>
<P>
   We know Olajuwon is 36 years old and no longer at the peak level
of the 1994 and 1995 championship seasons. But he still averaged
18.9 points and 9.6 rebounds and was voted third-team All-NBA this
year. To even entertain offers of draft picks for him is the
equivalent of the surgeon trading in the woman who put him through
med school for a younger, firmer trophy wife.
</P>
<P>
   Look at the No. 5 picks in the draft over the past five years:
Vince Carter, Tony Battie, Ray Allen, Kevin Garnett and Juwan
Howard. Only one, Garnett, is a franchise player.
</P>
<P>
   Look at the No. 12 picks: Michael Doleac, Austin Croshere,
Vitaly Potapenko, Cherokee Parks and Khalid Reeves.
</P>
<P>
   Add in Kevin Willis and Doug Christie, and let the Raptors
juggle and tinker and tempt Houston all they want. It is not a
Rockets team that is any closer to contending for a title than one
with Olajuwon.
</P>
<P>
   But this is not about basketball. It's about a society where
loyalty means nothing when corporate downsizing and positioning for
the future will put a few more bucks in a shareholder's pocket.
</P>
<P>
   It's about a time when you probably can trade the Dream, raise
ticket prices and know that the seats will be filled by those who
thrive on indoor fireworks, jiggling girls and blaring music.
</P>
<P>
   It is a more prosperous world in which we live. Just not a
better one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-99 0107EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990629.0008 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 01:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2799 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS &LR;      06-29 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
The cyclical nature of baseball dictates that all teams will go
through stretches when wins are as rare and precious as hits have
been for the Astros over the past two weeks.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even the Yankees, who won an American League-record 114 games
and the World Series championship last year, lost eight of 10 games
during a particularly rough stretch this season.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there's no getting around how poorly the Astros have
played recently, losing nine of their last 13 games and
surrendering first place in the National League Central to the
Cincinnati Reds over the weekend. But while their fans may be
panicking, the Astros have yet to reach that point.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's somewhat ironic that a week ago we had the best record in
the league and everyone was on the bandwagon,'' general manager
Gerry Hunsicker said. ``Did something happen that was so dramatic
that we went from the penthouse to the outhouse?''
</P>
<P>
   The Reds are what happened. While they were winning seven in a
row _ including a four-game sweep here _ the Astros were losing six
of seven, turning a six-game Central lead into a virtual tie with
Cincinnati, which leads the division by a percentage point.
</P>
<P>
   The rapid-fire turnaround has the entire city wondering: What's
wrong with the Astros?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just not hitting,'' first baseman Jeff Bagwell said.
``That's what's wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros hit .151 in the four-game series against the Reds,
and they are hitting .204 over the last 13 games, signifying a
team-wide offensive shutdown. Paul Bako is hitting .118 during that
stretch, Richard Hidalgo .167, Derek Bell .170, Tony Eusebio .182,
Tim Bogar .190, Bagwell .200 and Craig Biggio .245. Almost no one
is safe from this seemingly allergic reaction to anyone standing on
a pitcher's mound.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just have to keep taking extra batting practice and keep
working at it,'' interim manager Matt Galante said. ``The cream
rises to the top. We're not talking about players who we question
whether they can play at this level. These guys are pretty good
hitters.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time the Astros' much-ballyhooed offense
has gone south this season. They hit only .187 during an earlier
12-game stretch, but they somehow managed to win five of those
games while losing just 2{ games in the standings.
</P>
<P>
   Why do the Astros seem prone to such offensive lapses? Consider
the following:
</P>
<P>
   As hard as it may be to accept, 1998 is history. The Astros were
a great team last season when they won a franchise-record 102
games, but injuries have reduced them to merely good. It's
unrealistic to expect them to be the dominant, high-scoring club
most expected before injuries sidelined Moises Alou and Ken
Caminiti, who combined for 67 home runs and 206 RBIs in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it was an aberration when the Astros led the NL in
hitting earlier this season despite being at less than full
strength. And while it's probably safe to assume they are a much
better hitting club than their current 12th-place ranking would
indicate, it would be foolish to discount the impact of injuries to
two of their biggest guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some respects we're very fortunate to be where we are,''
Hunsicker said. ``I'm not sure people realize how special 1998 was.
Not only did we have a good team on paper, but they performed well,
and it's rare when everything comes together like it did for us
last season.''
</P>
<P>
   The absence of hitting instructor Tom McCraw also could factor
into the sporadic offensive production. Since McCraw left the team
to undergo treatment for prostate cancer May 17, the Astros have
gone 19-19 and are hitting .235. They were 23-13 and had a .297
batting average before his departure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we miss Mac,'' Hunsicker said. ``It's hard to qualify
the impact that a coach or manager has on a club. He has a special
relationship with our players.''
</P>
<P>
   And then there is the theory that some of the players who have
been big producers in the past are pressing, perhaps to pick up the
slack of the two missing stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happens sometimes is that when the big guys are
struggling, sometimes the big guys aren't getting good pitches to
hit,'' said Galante, under whom the Astros are 5-9 while manager
Larry Dierker recovers from brain surgery. ``And when the other
guys aren't hitting either, the big guys start swinging at bad
pitches because they think they've got to do it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it starts with the other guys, and then it gets to the
big guys because they try to do everything. We've talked about
this: Do what you can do to win a game. Don't try to hit a five-run
or six-run home run. When you start getting out of the things that
you can do, then you're not performing very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of why the Astros aren't hitting or winning, they
haven't lost faith. With 87 games remaining, they are still
considered the team to beat in the NL Central _ despite the way
things might look now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cleveland just lost four straight,'' Galante said. ``How did
you think that would happen? Chicago (Cubs) lost five straight. The
Mets lost eight straight, and they bounced back pretty well. We're
going to get this thing turned around.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unfortunate that this is happening right now. But if you
look back at all the teams that have gone through this, the one
thing we have to do is keep plugging away and keep hustling.
There's no question about the way we go about our business.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still know we've got a good club. We've just been coming up
short.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-99 0108EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990629.0009 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 01:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2805 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKL-MIRACLE-COMETS-HN     06-29 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-MIRACLE-COMETS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By W.H. STICKNEY JR.  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
The Comets on Monday night came to Compaq Center in search of a
little, but important, piece of WNBA history.
<TEXT>
<P>
   What they got was a glimpse at one of the teams of the future,
the expansion Orlando Miracle, which used the all-around play of
rookie Nykesha Sales to record a 68-66 victory and spoil the
Comets' chance to be the first WNBA team to start a season 8-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of people were disappointed because we didn't
set the new record, being 8-0 or whatever,'' said forward Sheryl
Swoopes. ``And that would have been a great accomplishment, a great
honor. But I'm more disappointed that we didn't play very well, not
that we lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't play very well as a team throughout the entire game.
So that's more important to me and more disappointing to me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Comets will have to settle for a 7-1 record because Sales,
the rookie from Connecticut who sat out all last year while
rehabilitating the right ankle she hurt as a college senior, threw
in a game-high 23 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give Orlando credit,'' said coach Van Chancellor. ``They came
in here tonight and really played well. Sales had 23 points, which
was outstanding for a rookie.''
</P>
<P>
   And Shannon Johnson, whom Chancellor has often called ``maybe
the best point guard in pro ball,'' got 19 points.
</P>
<P>
   And from start to finish, with few exceptions, the ultimate
difference was the intense, energetic play of the Miracle and the
lack of same for the Comets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't get ready to play,'' said Chancellor. ``And Orlando
did a great job. They just played well tonight, and we didn't play
very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Sales said the Miracle made a statement of which others around
the WNBA are certain to take heed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helps us and probably other teams just to see that they're
beatable,'' she said. ``I mean, they're going almost undefeated
every season and only losing a few games. But this shows that if
you have the heart, you can do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Miracle, which won its fourth straight game to improve to
5-3, survived two possessions by the Comets in the final seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Point guard Sonja Henning, enjoying her most successful outing
as a Comet, stole the ball from Johnson with 19 seconds remaining
and the Miracle leading 67-66.
</P>
<P>
   Sheryl Swoopes took a pass from Cynthia Cooper and, after
glancing at the clock and seeing only 15 seconds remaining, tried
to work through a triple team and get off a pass to Tina Thompson
on the left side.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, however, poked the ball away, and both players dived to
the floor near the sideline in an effort to retrieve it.
</P>
<P>
   The ball went out of bounds, but the officials ruled it had last
been touched by Swoopes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would think we would get that call at home,'' Swoopes
said, half-jokingly.
</P>
<P>
   Only 2.1 seconds remained. Orlando, after a 20-second timeout,
inbounded to Taj McWilliams, who was fouled by Janeth Arcain.
</P>
<P>
   McWilliams made one of two free throws for a 68-66 lead with
nine-tenths of a second left, thus leaving the door slightly ajar
for a potential Comets miracle.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson's inbounds pass went to Swoopes, but her 3-point
attempt from deep in the right corner hit the front of the rim and
bounced away.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew they had a really good team,'' said Swoopes. ``I knew
they were going to be completely different from the first time we
played 'em at their place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not that we thought we couldn't be beaten, but I just didn't
think we came ready to play.''
</P>
<P>
   It had been a different story when the teams met in Orlando on
June 10 to begin the season.
</P>
<P>
   Then, despite a sprained right ankle, Cooper teamed with Swoopes
and Thompson to lead the Comets to a convincing 77-63 triumph.
</P>
<P>
   During the morning shootaround Monday, Cooper resprained the
ankle. Though she showed no ill effects, leading the team with 21
points, the Comets' offense seemed out of sync.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one loss,'' said Swoopes. ``We've got 25 more or whatever
(games) to play. It's definitely going to be a learning experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I think we know that when you win games, you tend to
forget about a lot of the things that you need to work on.
</P>
<P>
   ``You kind of forget what has gotten you to that point. And when
you lose, then you start looking back, pointing fingers and saying
it was because of this or that, instead of saying we lost as a
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just didn't play very well. That's the bottom line.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
