   Conservatives are right when they say we shouldn't expect Uncle
Sam to solve all our problems. They're right when they say it's
dangerous to ask Big Brother to correct social transgressions.
They're right when they say Congress should attempt to fix a
societal ill only after everything else has failed.
</P>
<P>
   That's precisely why we need a Constitutional amendment banning
flag desecration, as some members of Congress propose.
</P>
<P>
   Without it, flag burning in America may disappear completely. &QL; 
JUSTICES TOOK FUN OUT OF IT &QL; 
The amendment currently being considered reads: ``The Congress
shall have power to prohibit the physical desecration of the flag
of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   The House of Representatives has passed it, and it's under
consideration in the Senate, where the experts are predicting it
will fail by a few votes.
</P>
<P>
   It must not.
</P>
<P>
   After the Supreme Court decision _ which proved that freedom in
America extends to those whose actions we consider repulsive _
actual flag burning incidents became even more rare.
</P>
<P>
   We should have known it would.
</P>
<P>
   The justices took all the fun out of it.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, a person can go out and spend $5 or $10 or $20 on the
Stars and Stripes, light it up and . . . nothing.
</P>
<P>
   No crowds. No police. No TV.
</P>
<P>
   You're not a protester, you're only a moron. You might as well
skip the middleman and torch the bills.
</P>
<P>
   That's got to change, and the only practical way to do so is to
make flag desecration illegal.
</P>
<P>
   The very day such an amendment is ratified by the necessary
two-thirds majority of states, we can be guaranteed flags will burn
across the land.
</P>
<P>
   And there will be crowds.
</P>
<P>
   And there will be police.
</P>
<P>
   And, most of all, there will be TV.
</P>
<P>
   That's what America is all about.
</P>
<P>
   That's why men like Arizona Sen. John McCain, who desperately
wants to be president, and Arizona Sen. Jon Kyl, who desperately
wants to stop playing second banana to McCain, strongly support the
amendment.
</P>
<P>
   After all, if the protesters get on TV, so will the politicians
who step forward to condemn them.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone involved winds up happy. The flag burners. The
politicians. The TV executives. &QL; 
DETAILS OF LAW UNCLEAR
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there are a few minor details to be worked out.
</P>
<P>
   For example, no one knows exactly how many car thieves, con men,
burglars and armed robbers will go free while police are busy
arresting flag burners.
</P>
<P>
   Also, no one knows what the punishment for flag desecration will
be, since no one knows exactly what ``desecration'' means.
</P>
<P>
   Would it include running shorts designed to look like the flag?
Or paint jobs on automobiles? Or cakes?
</P>
<P>
   Kraft Foods recently sent food editors a recipe for ``flag
cake.'' It uses strawberries, blueberries and whipped topping.
</P>
<P>
   This atrocity can be baked and consumed legally, for now.
</P>
<P>
   But there may come a day, soon, when America's spoiled and
unpatriotic citizens will be forced to relearn a lesson they should
have known all along:
</P>
<P>
   You can't have your flag cake and eat it, too.
</P>
<P>
   E.J. Montini can be reached at (602) 444-8978 or at
ed.montini(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
