<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 10:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2977 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LATHAM-COLUMN30-COX     06-29 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATHAM-COLUMN30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Complaining springs eternal in youth baseball season
 &HT;    By Phil Latham
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARSHALL, Texas _ Do you hear that sound? That tremendous
whoooooosssh?
</P>
<P>
   That is the sound of a collective sigh coming from the mouths of
hundreds of baseball parents. Youth baseball season is over.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't as if we did not love every last moment of watching our
children play. For a fact, it is one of my most enjoyable times of
the year. I wouldn't _ and didn't _ miss an inning of my son
playing.
</P>
<P>
   But there is something sweet about the final out of the final
game, too, once you have either celebrated victory or soothed
defeat. For most kids, soothing defeat takes about as long as
wolfing down a burger at the closest diner. There is something
sweet about that, too. Baseball for these kids is still just a
game.
</P>
<P>
   Don't you wish you could say the same about the parents?
</P>
<P>
   I am convinced that for some parents, youth baseball is not a
game at all, but an all-consuming quest. They intend on turning
little Johnny into the next Wille Mays, Ken Griffey Jr. or Mark
McGuire. This despite the fact that little Johnny cannot make a
basket catch or even catch with a basket. He cannot accurately
throw from the second baseman's fielding position to first base and
he couldn't hit past the pitcher's mound, even off a tee.
</P>
<P>
   To little Johnny, of course, this doesn't matter a bit. He's
getting some exercise, having fun playing the game and, most
important of all, he is a part of a team. The team may not always
be successful, but they win and they lose together.
</P>
<P>
   Far too many parents fail to understand that this is what makes
youth baseball _ or any youth sport _ important. It doesn't have
anything to do with how well your kid plays the game. Should I
repeat that?
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say you shouldn't encourage _ that is, demand _
that your child do his absolute best and give his full effort. That
way he is prepared when you expect not one whit less effort when he
is sitting in a classroom or taking his first job. This is, of
course, assuming that all parents demand the same kind of effort in
the classroom as they do on the baseball field.
</P>
<P>
   As we all know, that just isn't so.
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, I helped teach a Junior Achievement class at an East
Texas junior high school. I talked to the students about the
importance of doing well in class when one burly kid raised his
hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really have to do well, just have to make sure that I
pass my subjects,'' the kid said. ``My daddy says I'm gonna get a
football scholarship.''
</P>
<P>
   Way to go, Dad.
</P>
<P>
   The most amusing time in youth baseball is the naming of the
All-Star teams. Parents who have prayed for an end to the season
suddenly become incensed that their child has not been chosen.
After all, he did get a hit and almost made one catch during the
season.
</P>
<P>
   I'm no great judge of baseball talent, but the two years I've
seen the All-Star selections, they made perfect sense to me. All
the best players I saw made the team. Some good players weren't
there because, of course, there are only so many slots. As with any
such process, there are a few close calls and judgment calls.
</P>
<P>
   In every city I know of, jilted parents have exactly the same
complaints.
</P>
<P>
   As for the complaint that kids of coaches get the best shake in
on the teams and All-Star selections, I'd say, ``Bravo!'' I figure
if a person puts in the sweat _ and there is a lot of it _ to coach
a team, he gets the right to play his child at any position he
wants and bat him anywhere in the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, people are often compelled to coach because their
kids are especially talented, which might well account for a higher
representation on the All-Star teams.
</P>
<P>
   Want your child to play shortstop next season and bat fourth?
Fine, sign up to coach and you'll get no argument from me.
</P>
<P>
   This may strike some of you as unfair but _ surprise! _ life
isn't fair all that often. (Talk to any cancer patient about the
concept of ``fair.'') We aren't doing our kids any favors by making
them think they have some inherent right to fairness, because they
don't.
</P>
<P>
   They do, however, have the right to play. Play. Remember? Repeat
after me: This is a game. This is only a game.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Latham is editor and publisher of the Marshall News
Messenger, Marshall, Texas. E-mail: platham(AT)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
