</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wrestling? Politics? Same game _ different scorecard
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Jesse Ventura is the governor of Minnesota.
Hulk Hogan is running for president, and another former pro
wrestler, Bob Backlund, is campaigning for Congress in Connecticut.
And that's not all.
</P>
<P>
   WWF star Jerry Lawler is thinking about making a bid for mayor
of Memphis, and Harry Venis (Dirty Harry) is already the mayor of
Davie, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   At first I was appalled with the notion of guys in tights
running the country, but the more I think about it, the less
outrageous it sounds. Here's the way I see it.
</P>
<P>
   In politics, it has always been impossible to tell the good guys
from the bad guys until it was too late, because they all look
alike. From their conservative pinstripes and television-ready red
ties to their pricey Italian shoes, each is politically correct.
</P>
<P>
   In professional wrestling, however, there is no such quibble _
the good guys wear white and the bad guys wear black. The only
problem voters might have with such readily identifiable symbols of
virtue and corruption, would be trying to take the entire process
seriously when we're asked to choose between a guy in a black mask
carrying a cat-o-nine-tails, and his opponent in gold sneakers and
a fur-lined cape.
</P>
<P>
   Think about it though. Can a choreographed wrestling match get
much sillier than some of the national conventions we've watched on
television? Surely, no one expects us voters to get serious about a
bunch of political types taking a week off from work and spending
the taxpayers' bucks to run around planting whoopee cushions under
the butt of another delegate who just happens to have a flamingo
tied to his hat.
</P>
<P>
   Why not level the playing field a bit and come clean with the
constituents? Why not swap the political arena for a coliseum of
another sort? A smaller one with ropes, a bell, and a referee? That
way everyone knows nobody's fooling anybody _ what we see is what
we get. How's that for a bureaucratic novelty?
</P>
<P>
   Come election time there'd be no question in the voters' minds
about who's telling the truth. Nobody.
</P>
<P>
   Voters know that a candidate's position on the issues shifts
faster than a Texas Twostep. This week Libby moves a little left of
center because ``W'' is easing right and has been noticeably
praying with everyone. Even his momma, the former first lady,
thought the minister was speaking directly to her son during a
sermon about Moses' leading his people.
</P>
<P>
   On a smaller stage, we find our first lady blatantly switching
baseball teams as well as towns. She can't handle Bill, so she's
going for the Big Apple. How is New York going to be able to trust
her knowing they're getting her on the rebound? Worse, can the
voters live with the annoying suspicion that come 2004, when she
makes her bid for the top spot on the Democratic (or Republican,
should she revert to her youthful inclinations) presidential
ticket, her Yankees cap might be doffed for one belonging to
whichever club's hometown is slipping in the polls?
</P>
<P>
   Can the political types really expect us to buy into the notion
that our presidential wannabes are totally committed to anything
that doesn't guarantee them a quicker climb up the polls? Why don't
they admit it? Politics is showbiz _ all grunts and glitz. We'd all
feel a lot better if candidates fessed up to the fakery and made
honest folks of us.
</P>
<P>
   Wrestling? Politics? Same game _ different scorecard, but at
least no one expects us to believe the WWF is going to erase the
national debt or solve the abortion issue. ``The Undertaker'' has
not promised voters a chicken in every pot, and ``Stone Cold''
hasn't guaranteed 1.5 cars to every citizen above the age of 12.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know how I'd feel about living in a state run by Jesse
the Body, or a country run by the Hulkster, but I know for sure
that I'd really appreciate it if politicians would stop talking out
of both sides of their mouths and speak a few ugly truths at us.
</P>
<P>
   First pin wins.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison,
</P>
<P>
   Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or email: eschuett(AT)nwonline.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
