r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONEYTALK-COLUMN30-CO     06-29 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYTALK-COLUMN30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Retirement savings low across the board
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Mail and e-mail from readers are a blessing. Your
questions keep us at the newspaper in touch with what you really
need, and you let us know when you need to know more about topics
we've covered.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some of the questions you've raised recently:
</P>
<P>
   In response to last week's report on retirement savings, two
readers asked for more information on how much money Americans have
saved to help pay for retirement.
</P>
<P>
   The chart in last week's paper suggested that more than half of
the respondents in a survey had saved less than $100,000, and 9
percent had saved nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Hollinger pointed out that a large percentage didn't answer
the question, and he asked for more details on savings among young,
middle-aged and older people.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the average age is 30, then they are in great shape,'' even
if savings are low, Hollinger wrote. ``Age 40: not too bad. Age 50:
Not good but still time to get going. Age 60: They are in real
sorry shape.''
</P>
<P>
   The Employee Benefit Research Institute responded with a chart
that removes the no-answer people and provides age groupings.
</P>
<P>
   Data from those smaller samples will not be as reliable. But the
numbers are still pretty discouraging. Nearly half of workers aged
54 and older have saved $50,000 or less. Only a third of
leading-edge baby boomers _ aged 46 to 53 _ have saved more than
$100,000.
</P>
<P>
   As the institute observed in its original report, ``The amounts
accumulated by workers as a whole are generally unimpressive.''
</P>
<P>
   A reader wrote that her company has imposed new fees on her
401(k) retirement plan and has given employees the skimpiest
reports on how their investments are doing. She asks, ``Are there
any federal guidelines on what your 401(k) statements should
show?''
</P>
<P>
   The answer will not make her happy. ``The law does not require
an employer to provide an individual benefit statement,'' said
Deidre Koger of the Pension and Welfare Benefits Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Workers are entitled to ask once every 12 months for a report on
their account. The employer must provide the statement, but your
account balance is the only detail that must, by law, be included.
</P>
<P>
   Koger said a majority of employers provide a more detailed
statement every three months, without being required to do so. Some
companies may minimize reporting to keep down administrative costs.
In many cases, it will not be clear whether fees were paid by the
retirement plan or from individual accounts.
</P>
<P>
   The same reader also asked for advice on which mutual funds to
pick for her family's retirement plan. I can't give that kind of
detailed investment advice. Better to hire a professional or to
read a good book, such as the ones listed with the Finding Help
feature on this page.
</P>
<P>
   The main considerations are how much risk you are willing to
take and how long you expect to let your investments grow. You also
should consider what pension and Social Security benefits you
expect, how much you want to spend in retirement and other factors.
</P>
<P>
   Another reader notes that a 12-year-old daughter made money
baby-sitting and asks if the daughter can use it to open a
traditional or Roth individual retirement account.
</P>
<P>
   I asked some experts, who answered yes, but with warnings.
</P>
<P>
   Wendy Rausch of Stein Roe mutual fund family _ which has a fund
designed for children _ noted that the account has to be a
custodial one, set up by a parent in the child's name. But she
warned that the child gets control of the money as soon as she
reaches the age of majority. ``If the child says, 'I want to cash
out and go to Tahiti,' you can't do anything about it,'' Rausch
said. ``You do have to think about whether you trust your child and
will be able to teach them that this is important.''
</P>
<P>
   An education IRA might be a better idea, if the point is to save
for college or any other pre-retirement goal, Rausch added.
</P>
<P>
   There are tax consequences, said Larry W. Nichols, a certified
public accountant in Atlanta. Baby-sitting fees are self-employment
income. If it comes to more than $400, the income is subject to
self-employment tax.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you tried to say, 'I made $2,000 baby-sitting,' and if the
Internal Revenue Service checks that, they might say, 'Where's the
self-employment tax?' '' Nichols said.
</P>
<P>
   Hank Ezell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
