<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 10:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2982 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-MOVIES-TEENS30-COX     06-29 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-MOVIES-TEENS30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Getting around the `R': Teens say it's easy to beat theaters'
system
 &HT;    By John Blake and Lillian Lee Kim
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ An 8 1/2-by-11-inch sign posted at the door to Regal
Cinema's Covington Square 8 multiplex in Lithonia warns patrons of
the latest trend in moviegoing _ absolutely no one younger than 17
admitted to R-rated movies without a parent or guardian.
</P>
<P>
   Three teenagers, puffing cigarettes and hanging outside the
theater, are unimpressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just going to make them want to see it even more,''
says one of the teens, Mike Stone, 17. ``There's enough violence in
the world. People know what's going on. If they don't see it in the
movies, they're going to see it in the news, and it's going to be
real life. There's really no point in stopping it.''
</P>
<P>
   But keeping younger teens out of R-rated movies is just what
many theaters have pledged to do in the wake of recent high school
shootings in Colorado and Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   The extent to which theaters enforce the policy, underscored in
a joint announcement June 9 by President Clinton and the National
Association of Theater Owners, appears to vary widely.
</P>
<P>
   Some theaters have posted warning signs, and others routinely
send staffers into screening rooms to ferret out young teens who've
gotten past the box office by buying tickets to lower-rated films
and then sneaking into R-rated films.
</P>
<P>
   Many teens, however, say that despite promises of extra policing
of admissions they've seen little change and rarely find it
difficult to see any movie they want.
</P>
<P>
   One film many kids want to see is the adult-themed, R-rated
``South Park: Bigger, Longer &AMP; Uncut,'' which opens Wednesday in
metro Atlanta. It's a satire of the nation's R-rated movie
fixation, filled with profanities and violence. ``South Park's''
potty-mouthed kids _ Stan, Cartman, Kyle and Kenny _ sneak into an
obscenity-laced R movie, singing ``Off to the movies we go, 'cause
it's where we learn everything we know.'' The resulting brouhaha
leads to a war between the United States and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   AMC Theaters promises a concerted effort to keep teens 16 and
younger from seeing the movie, and the chain's newest metro Atlanta
megaplex in Kennesaw, which opens Wednesday _ will not only check
IDs at the box office but station staff at screening room doors to
check ticket stubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``For particular pictures such as `South Park,' we're going to
increase efforts to enforce the policy,'' says Rolando B.
Rodriguez, AMC's senior vice president, South Divisions operations.
Also on AMC's list: the Tom Cruise-Nicole Kidman sex study ``Eyes
Wide Shut,'' opening July 16, and the over-the-top high school sex
romp ``American Pie,'' coming July 9. At a Regal Cinema, Michelle
Stringer, 15, says she plans to see ``South Park'' and will likely
use her preferred method of getting into R-rated movies: simply buy
a ticket.
</P>
<P>
   The ploy doesn't always work. ``I've been told I don't look
17,'' Stringer says. But she says her parents are willing to buy
her a ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, there's the rub.
</P>
<P>
   Underage kids are allowed tickets to R-rated movies when they
are purchased by a parent or adult guardian, but some theaters
maintain that the adult must accompany the teenager into the
screening room.
</P>
<P>
   ``The adults get upset,'' says Deante Raston, assistant manager
at a theater in Covington, Ga. ``Even after you tell them the
content of the movie, even after you tell them it has a lot of
cursing, they'll say, 'Why do I have to come in and buy my child a
ticket? I don't want to watch this stinking movie.'''
</P>
<P>
   Raston says after warning one angry parent that his child
couldn't get into an R-rated movie because it contained too much
profanity and violence, the parent replied, ``Well, they hear it at
home.''
</P>
<P>
   Some kids under 17 say their parents don't care whether they see
restricted movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents are like, 'We trust you,''' says Whitney Simmons,
13, while rece see it,'' says 14-year-old Matt Malissa. ``We could
buy tickets for 'Tarzan.' It's not like they guard the doors.''
</P>
<P>
   And as Wijesimghe says, ``A lot of kids look older than they
are.''
</P>
<P>
   But some theaters apparently have stepped up efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Raston says the Covington theater has at least one police
officer patrolling the corridors weekdays and two doing it on
weekends. The theater also sends ushers into screening rooms for
every show.
</P>
<P>
   Raston says it's not too difficult to spot under-age kids in a
darkened theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``By walking every aisle, you can see a head in each aisle. A
lot of kids are not smart enough to sit in the middle (of a row),''
he says. ``And usually if a kid sneaks in the movie, they sit in
the back.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Daniel Furlow, 16, says he recently bought a ticket to
see the R-rated ``The Matrix'' at a different theater with some
other under-age friends and no one asked for his ID. And he scoffs
at the notion that violent movies inspire real-life acts of viole
and Lillian Lee Kim write for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Contributing: Bob Longino
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
