<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 10:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2983 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONLINE-SHABBAT30-COX     06-29 0545
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-SHABBAT30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CD-ROM aims to bring Jews back to the fold
 &HT;    By Douglas Belkin
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Religious law bars Jews from working,
driving, or even flipping a light switch on the Sabbath. So why has
an organization dedicated to bringing Jews back into the fold
released a CD-ROM to help guide them through Sabbath rituals when a
computer is required to view it?
</P>
<P>
   File the answer under D, as in desperate times call for
desperate measures.
</P>
<P>
   Almost two-thirds of the Americans under the age of 40 born to
Jewish parents do not consider themselves Jewish, which means most
Jews are ignoring the Sabbath _ and their Judaism _ altogether,
according to a 1990 survey by the Council of Jewish Federations.
</P>
<P>
   And that, says National Jewish Outreach Program spokeswoman
Melanie Notkin, is a reality that needs addressing. It is also the
impetus for ``Virtual Shabbat,'' a point-and-click primer on how to
prepare for and conduct a Jewish Sabbath service at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot condone someone using this (CD) on Shabbat,'' Notkin
said. ``But if someone was already going to do something on Shabbat
that was not allowed, a virtual Shabbat experience would be better
than none.''
</P>
<P>
   Literature accompanying the disc is even more blunt, warning
that the meltdown of Jewish life is so serious that ``Judaism in
America, as we have known it for the last 3,000 years, will likely
cease to exist in the new millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   The goal of the outreach group, which was founded in New York
City in 1985, is to prevent that loss of identity by connecting
Jews to each other and to their traditions. The disc is aimed at
teaching Jews who are not affiliated with any Jewish organization
how to observe Shabbat. ``It's just another tool to reach people,''
Notkin said.
</P>
<P>
   The computer program begins with two Shabbat candles floating
into the screen on compact discs. After a welcome by the bearded
face of Rabbi Ephraim Buchwald, founder of the National Jewish
Outreach Program, viewers have a choice of entering four different
illustrated rooms: the kitchen, dining room, a synagogue or a
virtual classroom to learn Hebrew.
</P>
<P>
   In the kitchen, viewers can learn the basics of keeping kosher;
in the dining room they can learn several prayers to say before the
meal; and in the synagogue they can learn the rudiments of Judaism
and listen to any of three dozen different prayers.
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, the Shabbat CD should be used during the week and the
information put into practice beginning Friday night at sundown,
Notkin said. The disc is made by the same Manhattan-based group
that started ``Read Hebrew America'' to teach Jews to read Hebrew
and ``Shabbat Across America,'' which organizers said drew about
70,000 Jews who do not usually observe Shabbat into synagogues last
year. All the events target Jewish continuity.
</P>
<P>
   ``My blessing to you,'' Buchwald says on the CD, ``is that you
remain as enthusiastic several years from now as you are during the
experience you are having today.''
</P>
<P>
   Virtual Shabbat can be ordered by calling (800) 44-TORAH.Douglas
Belkin writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
