<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 10:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2986 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBC-TEXAS-GUTSYPITCHE     06-29 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBC-TEXAS-GUTSYPITCHER30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A pitcher who gutted one out for his school
 &HT;    By Rick Cantu
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ D.J. Jones tried to convince himself that the
pain in his gut did not exist.
</P>
<P>
   That was no easy task, considering he pitched the entire spring
with a hernia the size of a baseball. He ignored suggestions of
surgery in February, knowing the procedure would ruin his baseball
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my decision to play,'' the University of Texas junior
pitcher said last weekend. ``It was all up to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking back, it seems incredible that Jones pitched so
effectively in his condition. He played with a special brace that
supported the hernia. He still led Texas pitchers in wins (10),
innings pitched (122), complete games (six) and ERA (4.73).
</P>
<P>
   What Texas fans did not see was the pain Jones endured away from
the field. The hernia hurt whenever he ran or lifted anything
heavy. By the end of the season he felt sharp pains in his stomach
whenever he ate. He lost his appetite in May and was forced to lie
down after every meal.
</P>
<P>
   Texas coaches questioned the gritty left-hander about the hernia
almost daily. They mostly just received blank stares.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't tell them much, because I didn't want anybody to
worry about me,'' said Jones, one of the team's most soft-spoken
players.
</P>
<P>
   ``D.J. is the only person who knows how badly he felt,'' Dwain
Jones said of his son.
</P>
<P>
   Dwain Jones might be the only Texas fan who was relieved when
the Horns were eliminated from the NCAA tournament in a regional at
Houston. For the first time in nearly five months, D.J. would get
the medical care he needed. He had surgery June 4 _ the day after
his 21st birthday _ in a Dallas hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Jones has been ordered to stay away from strenuous activity for
two months. The surgery was a success, and he expects no problems
when he returns for his senior season. He hopes to start to throw
again in late July.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept thinking that the further Texas got (in the playoffs),
the chances were greater that his hernia would blow up,'' Dwain
Jones said. ``It was pretty nasty. I was worried that it might
rupture at any time.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones felt the hernia for the first time in late January. While
jogging at Disch-Falk Field, he felt a twinge on the left side of
his lower abdomen. He did not have it examined until the pain got
worse.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Coach Augie Garrido knew about the injury and was given
frequent medical reports. He relied on Jones to tell him the truth.
</P>
<P>
   Poker-faced Jones admits that he often told Garrido nothing was
wrong, even when the pain was unbearable.
</P>
<P>
   Jones saw four doctors at various times in the spring, and one
insisted that he quit pitching immediately. There was no reason to
risk permanent injury. But as long as he performed well, Jones did
not consider quitting an option.
</P>
<P>
   Showing the determination of a bulldog during the regular
season, Jones threw 122 pitches against Missouri, 129 against
Stanford, 130 against Oklahoma, 130 against Southern California and
153 against Louisiana State. Rarely did he appear to be tired on
the mound.
</P>
<P>
   Jones was nearly heroic in the Big 12 tournament in Oklahoma
City. In a 5-4 loss to Missouri in 11 innings, Jones fired an
amazing 175 pitches. After struggling early in the game, Jones was
nearly unhittable in the latter innings, and Missouri needed an
unearned run in the 11th to beat him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt better the further I went along (in that game),'' Jones
said. ``I've been in games when I threw fewer than 100 pitches and
felt worse than I did against Missouri.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps no one on the team worked harder than Jones. In addition
to starting 17 games, he pitched seven times in relief, earning
three saves. After every home game, he jogged alone on the outfield
warning track to improve his conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   To help ease the pain caused by the hernia, Jones took four
Advil tablets a day the entire season. He will continue to take
pain medication until he recovers fully from surgery. This summer
he has returned to his family's home in Forney, about 10 miles east
of Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Did Jones ever consider taking time off when the hernia started
to break through?
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I did,'' he said. ``I guess I got used to the pain.
I really never knew how bad it was.''
</P>
<P>
   Rick Cantu writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
