<P>
   COKE-DISCRIMINATION _ Possible development in the race
discrimination lawsuit against Coca-Cola Co. A hearing on the
company's motion to dismiss the lawsuit has been set for July 15.
(Unger/Rankin, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   UPS-AIRCARGO _ United Parcel Service agreed to purchase
Challenge Air Cargo Inc., one of Latin America's largest all-cargo
airline. An official announcement is expected today. Challenge Air
operates more than 100 scheduled flights each week between Latin
America and its hubs in Miami and Dallas. UPS' rivals have invested
heavily in the region. (Saporta, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   HUMAN-RESOURCES _ One of the largest gatherings of human
resources professionals is in town, the Society for Human Resources
Management. Lots of sessions on dealing with workplace concerns.
Also checking out the latest HR offerings. (Joyner, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 12.
</P>
<P>
   PRATT _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Boeing is blaming Pratt &AMP;
Whitney for a satellite being placed in the wrong orbit a month
ago. Boeing says there was a glitch in the upper stage RL10 rocket
that Pratt provided for the launch. We'll ask Pratt for reaction.
Also we'll ask about an unattributed blurb in AvWeek that said
satellite manufacturers are looking abroad for launches because
they aren't comfortable with U.S. capability. (Pounds, Palm Beach
Post). 10-12.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH-FUTURE _ The Southern Growth Policies Board releases the
fnal report of the Commission on the Future of the South.(Burritt,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (a) General News and (f) Financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOLOGY
</P>
<P>
   COXNET PTECH PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDS: This is the CoxNet PTECH page for the current week. This
layout is now available.
</P>
<P>
   CoxNet PTECH 0629 _ Like many seniors, Mollie Newman was slow to
join the PC revolution. ``I thought maybe it would be too difficult
for me to learn how to use it,'' the 75-year-old Austinite said
last week. ``I felt like I wouldn't be too interested.'' No more.
In January, on her 75th birthday, Newman bought a Dell Dimension
model and signed up for a computer class from SeniorNet, a
nationwide, nonprofit program designed to make older Americans
comfortable with a computer. (Mahoney, Austin American-Statesman)
WITH PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   TECH BRIEFS
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOBUDDY _ It's the niche not the gadget, that counts in
technology. (Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH SIG
</P>
<P>
   FORUMS _ The Usenet forum was for owners of Chia pets, those
ceramic animals from mail-order TV. And there in the list of
subjects was a query from someone desperate to keep her dog from
chasing cars. A chia dog that chases cars? That would be worth
sending a photographer, if those TV prowl vans don't beat us to it.
And there was another pottery-pet question asking whether a mother
cat would adopt a kitten from someone else's litter. And some
advice on controlling fleas (another startling problem, considering
recent advances in ceramic technology). And someone complaining
that her landlord won't let her keep a ferret. (Stough, Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOBUDDY_ Popular column about personal computing written for
the average user. This week: Using the Web as tech support.
(Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECHTOOLS _ Software reviews. This week: DeLorme' new
topographical map of the United States. (Warner, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   NETWATCH _ What's new on the Web. This week: Presidential
candidates need to be make Web sites more interactive. (Katz,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   CYBERSCENE _ What's new on the Web. This week: Recipe Web sites
with search engines. (Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECH-MEDIA _ What the tech magazines are writing about. (Haddad,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   MAC-REPORT _ News on Apple and its products. This week: Why
Canvas is the ClarisWorks of graphics programs. (Haddad, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECHREPORT _ Tech briefs on new products and developments.
(Clothier, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   POWERUSER-COLUMN _ This column will not move today. (Yandel,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   THE-MECHANIC _ How mechanic's flat-rate works for the consumer.
(Carter, Cox News Service) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   SHARP-DRIVING _ The Honda Odyssey is one of the best minivans
available. (Sharp, Cox News Service) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TECH-WX-RADIO _ A weather emergency alarm can give you a few
precious extra minutes to get to safety when the weather threatens.
Emerson Research, a branch of Emerson Radio Corp., introduced a new
model clock radio this year that incorporates a weather alert
system. The CKW3000 Weather Alert Clock Radio monitors National
Oceanic and Aerospace Administration weather warning radio
frequencies 24 hours a day. When the radio receives a storm warning
signal, it activates a flashing light, an electric alarm or turns
on the audio weather band channel. (Cummings, Dayton Daily News).
11. MOVEDTECH-FITNESS _ Technology can help with your physical
fitness program. Sophisticated electronic gear can be used to make
sure your exercise regimen is efficient, to keep you entertained
while you work out and to keep track of your progress. (Cummings,
Dayton Daily News). 38. MOVED
</P>
