<P>
   LATHAM-COLUMN _ MARSHALL, Texas _ Do you hear that sound? That
tremendous whoooooosssh? That is the sound of a collective sigh
coming from the mouths of hundreds of baseball parents. Youth
baseball season is over. (Latham, Marshall (Texas) News Messenger)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ The 13 Iranian Jews imprisoned as alleged spies
are pawns in the dead-earnest power struggle between elected
moderate President Mohammed Khatami and radical Islamist clergy
hellbent on preserving the extremist theocracy of the late,
founding ayatollah, Ruhollah Khomeini. (Teepen, Cox Newspapers)
MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ While the president and seemingly everyone
else is down on the motion picture industry for its embrace of
violence and sex, I find myself on a different page. What troubles
me most about films these days is, simply, bad taste. (Kleinberg,
Cox News Service) MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Jesse Ventura is the
governor of Minnesota. Hulk Hogan is running for president, and
another former pro wrestler, Bob Backlund, is campaigning for
Congress in Connecticut. And that's not all. At first I was
appalled with the notion of guys in tights running the country, but
the more I think about it, the less outrageous it sounds. (Schuett,
Cox News Service) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ If the political symbol were the
swastika and the religious document came from Mein Kampf, more
Americans would see the two wrongs the U.S. House of
Representatives has committed. That the symbol in question is the
U.S. flag and the document is the Ten Commandments makes the House
no less wrong. A government that orders its citizens how to behave
around a graphic political symbol is not one based on symbolic
freedoms. A government that can decree religious commandments can
call itself just, and moral, and God-empowered, but it cannot call
itself free. (Young, Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
