<DOCNO> NYT19990629.0037 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 10:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2999 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TX-PAROLE-CASES     06-29 1592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TX-PAROLE-CASES </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Todd reading
 &HT;    Eds: With TX-PAROLE-MAIN, TX-PAROLE-FILES, TX-PAROLE-MEMBERS,
TX-PAROLE-COMPUTERS, TX-PAROLE-FIGURES
 &HT;    Parole cases unmasked: How would you vote?
 &HT;    By Mike Ward
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thanks to the lock of secrecy on Texas' parole files,
law-abiding Texans normally can't see what parole board members
consider in deciding which criminals to free early from prison _
and which ones to keep in.
</P>
<P>
   In an exclusive glimpse behind those closed doors, parole
officials recently allowed the American-Statesman to review several
case files _ with names deleted so as not to violate state law. We
culled through the files and listed the information parole board
members said was pertinent to their decision.
</P>
<P>
   Read the facts. Cast your vote and then see how the real board
members decided each one. Your options are to parole, deny parole,
make convict serve all time remaining, or review the case again in
several months
</P>
<P>
   Case One
</P>
<P>
   Age: 18
</P>
<P>
   Gender: Male
</P>
<P>
   Crime: Arson
</P>
<P>
   Sentence: 6 years
</P>
<P>
   Time served: 7 months
</P>
<P>
   Details: Convicted of torching a washateria a year ago, his
first offense. Insists he was only trying to put out a fire someone
else started. Tenth-grade dropout, but attending prison classes to
get GED. No past history of drug or alcohol abuse. Wants to become
a security guard if released. Previously worked as a grocery
stocker. No protests against parole, and his relatives support it.
Considered a low risk.
</P>
<P>
   Case One
</P>
<P>
   Board vote: Review case again in 17 months. Reason: Has not
served enough time yet. Since he has no education, would be wise
for him to get schooling and some vocational training before he is
released.
</P>
<P>
   Case Two
</P>
<P>
   Age: 53
</P>
<P>
   Gender: Male
</P>
<P>
   Crime: Murder
</P>
<P>
   Sentence: 30 years
</P>
<P>
   Time served: 12 years
</P>
<P>
   Details: In 1979, fatally shot 54-year-old rival he said had cut
him with a broken beer bottle and threatened his mother. ``He was
going to be a continuing threat,'' the convict said. Wrapped the
body in plastic and dumped it in a river. Has previous arrests for
public intoxication, aggravated assault, making threats and a long
history of traffic violations. Freed on mandatory supervision in
the late 1980s. His release was revoked in 1997 after he was
arrested for drunken driving and assaulting a cop after a fight
with his wife. No protests against release. Good behavior in
prison. Plans to work for scaffolding firm. Rated a low risk
</P>
<P>
   Case Two
</P>
<P>
   Board vote: Review case again in 20 months. Reason: Seriousness
of offense, history of assaultive behavior and past history of not
following rules when released indicate a disturbing pattern not
worth taking another chance on at present.
</P>
<P>
   Case Three
</P>
<P>
   Age: 21
</P>
<P>
   Gender: Male
</P>
<P>
   Crime: Robbery
</P>
<P>
   Sentence: 7 years
</P>
<P>
   Time served: 21 months
</P>
<P>
   Details: Broke woman's wrist in purse snatching. Was a
17-year-old high-school football star when he committed the crime.
Originally given three years' probation, but was sent to prison for
failing to pay his probation fees and not checking in as required.
His handwritten plea: ``I am very sorry for the crime that I have
committed. . . . If I could change the past I would.'' Has paid
$791 in restitution to the victim. Past history of drug and alcohol
abuse. Good behavior in prison. Has job and plans to rejoin his
family. No protests to release. Rated as low risk.
</P>
<P>
   Case Three
</P>
<P>
   Board vote: Parole in September. Reason: Release him when he has
served 2 1/2 years on his sentence. From one board member who
interviewed him in prison: ``He looks like he's made the turn . . .
He has turned himself around.''
</P>
<P>
   Case Four
</P>
<P>
   Age: 41
</P>
<P>
   Gender: Male
</P>
<P>
   Crime: Cocaine possession
</P>
<P>
   Sentence: 30 years
</P>
<P>
   Time served: 5 1/2 years
</P>
<P>
   Details: Arrested in car containing nine kilos of cocaine worth
$30,000. Insisted he was ``holding it for a friend.'' Initially
charged with drug trafficking, pleaded guilty to lesser charge. The
convict, a former judge and business owner in Colombia, is ashamed
of what he did. Good behavior record in prison. Rated as low-risk
if released. No protests to release. Federal immigration agents
want to deport him because he is not a U.S. citizen.
</P>
<P>
   Case Four
</P>
<P>
   Board vote: Release in September. Reason: Was serious crime,
needs to do more time _ but can do that in a pre-release facility
instead of a prison. When he is eventually freed, will be deported
so little chance he can commit new crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Case Five
</P>
<P>
   Age: 30
</P>
<P>
   Gender: Male
</P>
<P>
   Crime: Aggravated kidnapping
</P>
<P>
   Sentence: 6 years
</P>
<P>
   Time served: 3 1/2 years
</P>
<P>
   Details: When he broke his arm at the nightclub where he worked,
his boss refused to pay the $2,000 bill and fired him. Angry and
facing pressure from bill collectors, he held two female co-workers
at gunpoint in an office to try to get his boss to pay up. No
previous criminal history. Got into fights when first imprisoned,
but recent behavior has been good. High school graduate with 60
hours of college. Wants to work in a restaurant if released. His
family supports parole. Prosecutors have protested any early
release. Rated as low risk if released.
</P>
<P>
   Case Five
</P>
<P>
   Board vote: Release in August. Reason: Has done enough time on
his sentence. Appears to be good risk.
</P>
<P>
   Case Six
</P>
<P>
   Age: 36
</P>
<P>
   Gender: Male
</P>
<P>
   Crime: Home burglary
</P>
<P>
   Sentence: 10 years
</P>
<P>
   Time Served: 7 years
</P>
<P>
   Details: Broke into a house while naked, woman awoke to find him
wearing her underwear and holding a knife at her throat. In one of
his accounts, he said he had to disrobe because he soiled his pants
while driving and was only looking for something to wear. In
another, he insisted ``someone gave me some kind of drug.'' Jailed
15 times for crimes ranging from drugs to assault, though most
charges were dismissed. Has been paroled twice and was rearrested
on new charges. Is serving two 15-year sentences for selling stolen
credit cards and theft. Has good behavior record in prison. Has
completed welding and GED courses. Rated as moderate risk if
released. Victim and prosecutors have protested his release.
</P>
<P>
   Case Six
</P>
<P>
   Board vote: Review case again in a year. Reason: Because of
mandatory supervision release law, will be freed from prison anyway
in 2001. If his good behavior in prison continues, might consider
releasing him early with intensive supervision.
</P>
<P>
   Case Seven
</P>
<P>
   Age: 27
</P>
<P>
   Gender: Male
</P>
<P>
   Crimes: Delivery of cocaine and sexual assault of a child
</P>
<P>
   Sentence: 7 years
</P>
<P>
   Time Served: 6 years
</P>
<P>
   Details: While on probation on a 1991 cocaine charge, he twice
forced a 13-year-old runaway to have sex with him by telling her he
was a member of the Mexican Mafia prison gang and could hurt her
and her family if she refused. Said he doesn't know why he did it.
This is his first time in prison. Good behavior record. A
high-school graduate, is mildly retarded. Wants to become a
carpenter when he gets out. Will live with his mother. Victim has
not protested but a prosecutor has pleaded: ``Please keep this
defendant behind bars for as long as possible.'' Rated as a
moderate risk.
</P>
<P>
   Case Seven
</P>
<P>
   Board vote: Serve all remaining time. Reason: There appears to
be little benefit in letting him out early, even though doing so
would ensure he could be intensively supervised for several months
_ something that will not occur if he serves his entire sentence.
But members felt the gravity of the charge and his apparent lack of
remorse argued against any early release. In any event, he will
leave prison in February 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Case Eight
</P>
<P>
   Age: 39
</P>
<P>
   Gender: Female
</P>
<P>
   Crime: Theft by check
</P>
<P>
   Sentence: 2 years
</P>
<P>
   Time Served: 9 months
</P>
<P>
   Details: In 1989, she wrote $10,000 worth of hot checks for
assorted merchandise at several stores. Initially given probation
but violated the rules by not reporting as required and disappeared
in 1991. Was arrested in 1998 and sent to prison. Has a good
behavior record in prison. Even if the board nixes her release now,
she will be freed on mandatory supervision in May anyway. She has
no history of drug use and has family support. Rated a low risk for
release. No protest letters.
</P>
<P>
   Case Eight
</P>
<P>
   Board vote: Release this month. Reason: She has repaid most of
the losses, and has a job lined up to pay back whatever remains.
Makes sense to let her out now with proper supervision until she
will be released in May anyway under the mandatory supervision law.
</P>
<P>
   Case Nine
</P>
<P>
   Age: 22
</P>
<P>
   Gender: Male
</P>
<P>
   Crime: Drunken driving, injury to a child and assault
</P>
<P>
   Sentence: 7 years
</P>
<P>
   Time Served: 3 years
</P>
<P>
   Details: Freed on mandatory-supervision release a year ago, he
was re-arrested on new charges of cocaine possession and aiding a
juvenile to possess alcohol after police spotted several teenagers
going in and out of his motel room with beer. His previous crimes
include the alleged rape of a 14-year-old girl, a charge that was
plea-bargained to a lesser charge of injury to a child. Had a good
behavior record in prison, and no previous violations while out of
prison.
</P>
<P>
   Case Nine
</P>
<P>
   Board vote: Revoke parole. Reason: Convict is a sex offender
who, by hanging around with teenagers with drugs and alcohol,
indicates he has not changed his ways.
</P>
<P>
   Source: Texas Board of Pardons and Paroles
</P>
<P>
   Ward writes for the Austin American-Statesman
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
