<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TX-PAROLE-COMPUTERS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    todd read
 &HT;    Eds: With TX-PAROLE-MAIN, TX-PAROLE-FILES, TX-PAROLE-MEMBERS,
TX-PAROLE-FIGURE, TX-PAROLE-CASES
 &HT;    Paper chase: Clemency system slow to go digital
 &HT;    By Mike Ward
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUNTSVILLE, Texas _ It's just a laptop computer, parole board
member Rissie Owens says, ``and I haven't really even learned how
to use it yet.''
</P>
<P>
   But officials hope it will soon take Texas' archaic
record-keeping system for parole and clemency cases into the modern
era.
</P>
<P>
   The agency has been repeatedly criticized for its antiquated
and, at times, sloppy record keeping and is poised to go online
within two years.
</P>
<P>
   The $2 million project that is part of a five-year, $30 million
overhaul of prison computer systems, officials say. Currently, the
prison system lives and sometimes dies on a gargantuan mix of more
than 250,000 paper files, folders that must be constantly sorted
and re-sorted at the board's Austin headquarters, with bar-code
stickers attached to track each one. They are then boxed up and
dispatched to the seven field offices where board members work.
</P>
<P>
   Every Wednesday, state-owned vans rendezvous in places like the
McDonald's parking lot in Breham, and at roadside spots in Temple,
Beeville and Synder, where drivers exchange dozens of file boxes
that are either being sent out to board members or returned to
Austin.
</P>
<P>
   At the edge of the new millennium, officials say, no other state
agency remains as reliant on paper files as the Board of Pardons
and Paroles. Some 5,000 files are on the road each month.
</P>
<P>
   But Brian Collier, who oversees that traveling paperwork, said
things could soon change.
</P>
<P>
   Within five years, he says, officials hope to have the 18 parole
board members working from laptops and desktop computers _ so, as
Owens explains it, ``instead of going through these boxes and boxes
of files every week, I could look at an inmate's entire file on the
screen _ and I could do it here in the office, at a (prison) unit,
anywhere I had the computer.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to saving money and expediting the flow of
information for parole officials, Rodriguez and Collier said it
could also curb another paperwork hitch in the current system: lost
files. And even, occasionally, burned files.
</P>
<P>
   Several months ago, officials said, one of the vans caught fire
near Fort Stockton and three boxes of files inside _ about 30 or so
files in all _ were destoyed. Collier said it took several weeks to
reconstruct those files, one page at a time.
</P>
<P>
   Ward writes for the Austin American-Statesman
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
