<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TX-PAROLE-FILES </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    todd read
 &HT;    Eds: With TX-PAROLE-MAIN, TX-PAROLE-FILES, TX-PAROLE-MEMBER,
TX-PAROLE-COMPUTER, TX-PAROLE-FIGURE, TX-PAROLE-CASES
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Many parole documents not seen by public
 &HT;    By Mike Ward
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Not only are the meetings secret where Texas
paroles are decided, but so are the case files that guide those
decisions. In other states those files are open. If Texans could
see them, they'd find:
</P>
<P>
   _ A cover sheet on the convict, including age, crime and rating
on risk if released;
</P>
<P>
   _ Parole summary, including details of the convict's version of
the crime, his or her behavior record in prison, plans if paroled,
details on background such as schooling or vocational skills, IQ
and medical history. A prison employee prepares the summary;
</P>
<P>
   _ Work sheets on what kind of risk the convict will be if
paroled. A parole board worker puts together the work sheet;
</P>
<P>
   _ Paperwork on the convict's prison term, including copies of
the court sentence and other legal documents from public file at
courthouse. Can also include police reports of the crime;
</P>
<P>
   _ Letters from victims and prosecutors, for or against parole;
</P>
<P>
   _ Letters from the convict and his or her family and friends,
for or against parole;
</P>
<P>
   _ Paperwork from previous paroles and revocations, including
previous parole hearings and votes;
</P>
<P>
   _ Minute sheets showing parole members' votes and, if they
approve, the reasons for their vote and conditions of parole, such
as undergoing drug counseling or wearing an electronic monitoring
bracelet.
</P>
<P>
   Ward writes for the Austin American-Statesman
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-99 1038EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
