<HEADER>
A3003 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TX-PAROLE-MAIN     06-29 2891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TX-PAROLE-MAIN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    todd reading
 &HT;    Eds: With TX-PAROLE-FILES, TX-PAROLE-FILES, TX-PAROLE-MEMBER,
TX-PAROLE-COMPUTER, TX-PAROLE-FIGURE, TX-PAROLE-CASES
 &HT;    The secret world of the Texas parole board
 &HT;    By Mike Ward
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ He was 21 when, in a flash of anger, he slammed
his 9-month-old niece to the floor because she was crying. A
cracked skull silenced her forever.
</P>
<P>
   Involuntary manslaughter, the jury called it, and gave the man
18 years in prison for his crime. He has done 10 and, because of
``good time'' laws that speed up the clock on sentences for good
behavior, he is scheduled to walk out of prison in just a few
months.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Friday, three members of the state Board of Pardons
and Paroles sat inside a cluttered conference room in Northwest
Austin, deciding under what conditions the convicted baby-killer
will get his freedom. Same for a rapist with a preference for
14-year-old girls, a trigger-happy gangster who almost killed two
people, a longtime burglar who beat his girlfriend, a schizophrenic
arsonist and more than 100 other imprisoned criminals with
penchants for violence or sex crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Rule No. 1: Protect the public
</P>
<P>
   But the public is nowhere to be found. The deliberations take
place behind closed doors in an increasingly controversial process
by which Texas decides which criminals should be freed early from
prison, under what rules those convicts must live, even whether
execution-bound convicts should receive clemency.
</P>
<P>
   It is also Texas' biggest state secret.
</P>
<P>
   But on this Friday, the parole board gave the press
unprecedented access to the clemency and parole process, as part of
a three-month examination into the inner workings of this mostly
hidden part of Texas' public justice system.
</P>
<P>
   The finding: troubling new questions about whether parole board
deliberations are too secretive and whether the public is being
unfairly left ignorant of criminals' early release from prison.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, parole board members insist that the secrecy is
a byproduct, not the driving force behind Texas' system. Because
members decide cases on their own, not together as a group as in
other states, they say there is no way to conduct the board's
business in public meetings _ and that was never the design.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we opened the current system, we would destroy it,'' argues
Victor Rodriguez, a former Brownsville cop who has been chairman of
the parole board four years. ``The volume of cases is too much for
a public hearing, public access to each one. There's a reason we do
this the way we do, and that is to protect the public safety and
public's interests in the best way possible.''
</P>
<P>
   A growing chorus of critics disagrees. ``Our system needs to be
changed,'' said Jack Kyle, a retired prison administrator who
preceded Rodriguez as chairman. ``The public is going to have to
deal with these people coming out of prison, so why shouldn't they
be allowed to see the process work, to have a voice in it?''
</P>
<P>
   Texas will spend more than $300 million during the next two
years operating its parole system. Only $19 million will go for the
board's operation, roughly what security at the Texas Capitol will
cost.
</P>
<P>
   But its impact on the lives of everyday Texans is great: Last
year alone, it approved parole for 14,000 convicts and set
conditions of ``mandatory supervision'' for an additional 20,000
whose combination of time served and credit for good behavior
equaled their original prison sentence. Meanwhile, almost 9,000
parolees were sent back to prison for new crimes.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the 18 board members sent 13,000 parole violators
back to prison, denied parole for about 55,000 convicts, ruled on
129 requests for pardons, and denied all but one of the 11
last-minute pleas from convicted killers seeking to avoid
execution.
</P>
<P>
   In all, they cast 165,000 votes.
</P>
<P>
   All from behind closed doors.
</P>
<P>
   Making the call
</P>
<P>
   Inside a conference room ringed with stacks of brown file boxes
one Friday, three board members _ Gerald Garrett, Juanita Gonzalez
and Alvin Shaw _ decide the conditions of freedom for the worst of
Texas' worst, those convicts with a history of violence, sex crimes
or gang membership.
</P>
<P>
   Each of these files must be screened not once but twice by the
board, to ensure that the conditions of release are stringent
enough. SISP, this program is called _ parole-speak for Super
Intensive Supervised Parole.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sobering experience to make these decisions, knowing
it's just a matter of time until you get snake-bit by someone who
commits a new crime,'' says Shaw, a former Austin cop who has been
on the board for about two years. ``But public safety always is our
primary concern, even if the public probably doesn't really
understand what we do _ or why we do it.''
</P>
<P>
   At least two board members review each case and approve. If they
disagree, a third member must break the tie.
</P>
<P>
   They can approve or deny paroles or ``set off'' the case for
review again in one to three years. For convicts slated for release
from prison on mandatory supervision, they set only the conditions
of that freedom _ everything from electronic monitoring bracelets
to drug counseling to staying away from schools and taverns and
victims.
</P>
<P>
   On this day, most of the cases are mandatory supervision.
</P>
<P>
   The board members clip along at about one case roughly every
seven minutes, one every four after a reporter stops asking
questions. Thick files take longer. Each must be opened, leafed
through, the pertinent documents perused. Members' votes are then
recorded on the left side of the folder in coded scribble. FI-4,
FI-2, FI-5 . 'Release to a half-way house, on a specified date,
after drug therapy.' E, M, R . 'Require vocational training,
registration as a sex offender, restitution.' And then, two
``ca-chuds'' by rubber stamps: ``Impose SISP. Continue action in
effect.''
</P>
<P>
   By lunchtime, more than 200 folders have been voted and boxed up
again, an assembly line of decisions that take place every day in
the seven regional parole board offices across Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Even at the pace of the morning's votes, there is still time for
occasional banter.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the repulse meter, this one is high,'' Garrett says of the
baby-killer, slowly leafing through a dog-eared 2-inch file on the
table before him. ``Just because she was crying. `Can you believe
that?'''
</P>
<P>
   He slides the file across the table to Shaw. ``Was out twice
before. Violated once when his wife caught him with another woman
and he punched her,'' Shaw says as he reads several pages. ``Bad
news. Bad news.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, he and Garrett decide that because the convict is to
be freed on mandatory supervision anyway in a few months, the best
plan is make him wear an electronic monitoring bracelet and remain
under almost constant surveillance by parole officers when he gets
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ca-chud.''
</P>
<P>
   In five hours, there is similar debate over other cases, each
convict with his or her own peculiar problems, each just a few
months from being released from prison whether the board approves
or not.
</P>
<P>
   Such as a 44-year-old man with a long history of mental illness,
a two-time loser who has been paroled twice before only to be sent
back for new crimes _ most recently for punching his 79-year-old
mother.
</P>
<P>
   And a 39-year-old man convicted of sodomizing a 15-year-old
cousin. He has refused to participate in sex-offender therapy even
though he has admitted molesting a sister, three nieces, eight
cousins and 10 neighborhood girls.
</P>
<P>
   And a 65-year-old arsonist who set fire to his suitcase outside
a parole office, just so he could return to prison.
</P>
<P>
   And a 24-year-old member of the Bloods street gang who racked up
45 disciplinary violations in prison for assaulting guards and
other convicts, destroying state property, even inciting a riot.
</P>
<P>
   On this morning, most of the 200 cases reviewed _ almost
everyone but some killers, rapists and the gang member _ are
approved. In almost every case, the board members worry about
whether the criminal will commit new crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We make the best decisions we can based on what we see in the
file,'' Gonzalez says. ``But we never know for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaw echoes those sentiments. ``These are the kinds of cases we
see every day, people someone else has attempted to raise _ and
failed. And now the public expects us to fix them somehow,'' he
says. ``But we're not miracle workers. We're just the parole board.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too bad the public can't see this. We're very
misunderstood.''
</P>
<P>
   In other states
</P>
<P>
   In other states, the public does see.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do everything publicly,'' explained Ed Leyva, chairman of
Arizona's five-member Board of Executive Clemency. ``People are
cynical, and if we decided issues such as these behind closed
doors, they would wonder whether deals were made.''
</P>
<P>
   Echoed Terry Jenks, director of the seven-member Oklahoma Board
of Pardons and Paroles: ``Releasing people from prison is certainly
something the public should have the opportunity to be involved
in.''
</P>
<P>
   In Arizona, all parole cases must be discussed and voted on in a
public meeting. In Oklahoma, the paroles of all violent and major
felons must be approved in an open meeting while those for petty,
low-risk criminals can be approved administratively _ although the
records are open, so the public can track them. In both states, all
clemency cases for death row convicts are decided in a public
meeting where, as Leyva explains it, ``the inmate or his lawyer
gets a chance to have their say, prosecutors get to have their say,
relatives get to have their say, the public gets to have their
say.''
</P>
<P>
   Some states, such as Illinois, allow for confidential meetings
to protect witnesses or a victim's family. ``For the most part, we
let it all out in the public where it's all there for the public to
understand,'' said Ken Tupy, chief legal counsel for the 12-member
Illinois Prisoner Review Board.
</P>
<P>
   In many states, most parole records are publicly accessible, and
several even post lists of parole-eligible convicts on the Internet
so victims and citizens can protest _ or be alerted _ before a
convict is freed. In Texas, because of a 20-year-old secrecy law,
parole files and parole lists are off-limits.
</P>
<P>
   A irony in Texas: While parole decisions are made privately,
parole revocations by law are to done publicly _ even though the
public rarely attends because hearing schedules are not announced.
</P>
<P>
   Texas officials argue that the other states' openness is
unworkable in Texas because of the volume of cases the board deals
with each year. By contrast, Oklahoma reviewed just 3,000 paroles
last year and Arizona just 1,600, while Texas reviewed more than
69,000.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Texas decided 11 clemency cases last year.
Arizona did five, Oklahoma four.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, Texas parole board members argue that operating
in public would compromise their independence and throw a logjam in
front of the paperwork flow.
</P>
<P>
   ``With our volume, we can't have public meetings on every
case,'' Rodriguez said. ``I think we have a good, fair and just
system in place.''
</P>
<P>
   Misunderstood
</P>
<P>
   On another day, inside a cramped office at El Paso's district
parole office, ``good'' might not be the best description of Texas'
parole and clemency system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Misunderstood'' might be a better one.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez has flown in from San Antonio at dawn to help board
members Thomas Moss and Charles Shipman review and vote in more
than 200 parole and revocation cases. Now, after lunch, he has
settled in for a one-day-a-week ritual for most parole board
members: meeting with the public.
</P>
<P>
   This day, says Rodriguez, is fairly typical.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Guardado asks Rodriguez to make sure that the gang
members who killed his brother, Juan, in a local jail will never be
paroled. ``The system (stinks) because it let (one of the suspects)
go free'' without being charged, he says, lifting a framed portrait
of his brother onto the desk for Rodriguez to see.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe by the man upstairs that there will be justice, but
I can't see that now,'' Guardado says, choking back tears. ``Please
help me.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez cannot. The suspects, he learns, have not yet been
convicted. They are not in prison, but in the county jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people don't understand what the parole board does,
what my job is,'' Rodriguez tells Guardado. ``I have no purview
over this at this time. But I will try and factor in your concerns
at the proper time, certainly, if that is possible.''
</P>
<P>
   He will repeat his explanation to two sisters who want to make
sure the man who killed their sister never moved back to El Paso,
an elderly couple who fear for their imprisoned son, and a woman
whose 15-year-old daughter was killed in 1993 by a hit-and-run
driver whom they tracked down on their own and made sure was sent
to prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``This man has left me without a future for my old age. That was
what I thought of my daughter as,'' Celestina Gutierrez says.
``Please help us.'' Several of the lawbreakers these victims have
come to complain about are not within Rodriguez' grasp. They are
not up for parole any time soon. ``This is very hard sometimes,
talking to these people, trying to help them,'' he says, putting
his face in his hands, after Gutierrez leaves. ``I have to try to
do what I can.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as Rodriguez was explaining the system in El Paso, board
member Rissie Owens did the same thing inside three prisons around
Huntsville. She had arrived to talk to seven convicts whom she was
considering for parole, the few that she sees each week out of the
more than 100 cases she will decide.
</P>
<P>
   On this day, she asks the same questions over and over: Do you
have a parole plan? Do you have a place to live? Why should I let
you out?
</P>
<P>
   ``About the only ones I meet with are ones I have a question
about after I look through their file,'' says Owens, who has been
on the board four years. ``Mostly, they want to know how I'm going
to vote.''
</P>
<P>
   They get no answers. Owens tells them they can find that out
later by having a relative call her office.
</P>
<P>
   During the just-adjourned legislative session, victims advocates
strongly opposed bills to require the parole board to make parole
and clemency decisions in public. Even so, Dianne Clements,
president of the Houston-based Justice for All, the largest and
most influential of Texas' victim groups, says openness could be a
good thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were concerned that the way the bills were written, that
they would create Commutation 101 _ that they would require the
parole board to commute death sentences,'' she said. ``If the
parole board adopted rules to open its process, open its records,
victims and relatives and the public could be the better for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Top-secret files
</P>
<P>
   If the public in Texas has little understanding of the process,
neither do many of the convicts whose lives are governed by it, but
who by state law cannot even see their own files _ short of hiring
an attorney to subpoena them, something most cannot afford.
</P>
<P>
   ``State law requires confidentiality of those files, and it
makes no exceptions,'' explains Laura McElroy, the parole board's
general counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Critics call it the most troubling part of the secretive
process.
</P>
<P>
   Reason: There is little way to detect mistakes in the files,
mistakes that can affect the outcome of a vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen it time and time again over the years,'' says Bill
Habern, a Huntsville-area lawyer who has specialized in parole
cases for two decades. Parole-hearing files and attorneys
interviewed by the Austin American-Statesman underscore his
warning.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, a model convict was denied parole because his file
was mixed up with that of a misbehaving prisoner with the same name
who happened to be housed at the same prison. He was paroled after
the mistake was discovered by his attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Another case file showed that a convict had shot his victim in
the back, and he was denied for parole by board members who later
said they considered him a cowardly criminal. In fact, autopsy
reports that were not in the file disclosed the fatal wound was
underneath the victim's arm _ bolstering his insistence that the
shooting was in self-defense. He, too, was later paroled.
</P>
<P>
   Even the final plea for mercy of Joseph Stanley Faulder, the
Canadian-born killer executed June 17, was hit by a paperwork
mistake. During an Austin federal court hearing last December, it
was revealed that an East Texas sheriff had written a protest
letter asserting that Faulder had killed someone while in prison _
which he never had.
</P>
<P>
   Only a small percentage of Texas convicts up for parole or early
release ever see a parole board member, although in recent months
convicts on death row have had the option. In other states, a large
percentage do _ giving board members, victims and the convicts a
chance to catch errors and speak their minds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those files can be filled with mistakes and lies and no one
will ever know,'' Habern said. ``The secrecy that surrounds this
system is very dangerous. We should open the system up to protect
everyone _ including the public.''
</P>
<P>
   Ward writes for the Austin American-Statesman
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
