 &HT;    
 &HT;    Who makes parole decisions in Texas
 &HT;    By Mike Ward
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ The Texas Board of Pardons and Paroles has 18 members,
including the chairman. Annual salary for the full-time job is
$62,500; $65,000 for the chairman. All are gubernatorial appointees
who serve six-year terms.
</P>
<P>
   Parole approval rates are the percentage of cases in which a
board member voted to grant parole in fiscal 1998. Approval rates
for new members cannot be fairly calculated. The following are the
members of the board:
</P>
<P>
   Victor Rodriguez, Chairman
</P>
<P>
   Age: 42 Residence: Brownsville, Texas
</P>
<P>
   Assignment: Austin, San Antonio
</P>
<P>
   Appointed: 1995
</P>
<P>
   Credentials: Former prison guard. Twenty-one years' with
Brownsville Police, including chief. Former chairman of Texas
Automobile Theft Prevention Authority.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Leaving the board July 11.
</P>
<P>
   Parole approval rate: 14 percent
</P>
<P>
   Lynn Franklin Brown
</P>
<P>
   Age: 52
</P>
<P>
   Residence: Waco, Texas
</P>
<P>
   Assignment: Gatesville
</P>
<P>
   Appointed: 1997
</P>
