<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 10:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3012 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DONNIEOSMOND28-COX     06-29 1109
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DONNIEOSMOND28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Kevin D. Thompson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The year is 1996. Donny Osmond is starring in Andrew Lloyd
Webber's musical, Joseph and the Amazing Technicolor Dreamcoat in
Minneapolis. As he strides to the stage, Osmond begins to perspire
_ profusely.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had this sick feeling in my stomach,'' he remembers.
</P>
<P>
   The stage manager announces it's 15 minutes to show time. Now
Osmond is shaking uncontrollably. By the time the makeup people put
on his wig, Osmond is crying like a lost toddler at an amusement
park. He's sweating so much, the glue from his wig won't even stick
to his forehead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was having a nervous breakdown,'' he says quietly.
``I didn't know what was wrong with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Osmond wasn't suffering a nervous breakdown. He wasn't having a
heart attack or dying.
</P>
<P>
   It may be hard to fathom, but the one-time teen sensation who
began his professional career at age 6 in 1963 on The Andy Williams
Show, was petrified of going on stage.
</P>
<P>
   The forever dimpled pop icon finally came to grips with the fact
that he suffered from social phobia, a rather common social anxiety
disorder that results from a fear of being ridiculed.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that point in time, I said, `I don't care what the tabloids
say, I need some help,''' he recalls.
</P>
<P>
   The 41-year-old Osmond details his painfully emotional battles
with panic attacks in his autobiography, Life Is Just What You Make
It: My Story So Far (Hyperion, $22.95).
</P>
<P>
   In his rather candid book, which was co-written by Patricia
Romanowski (Dream Girl: My Life as a Supreme ; Truly Blessed with
Teddy Pendergrass), Osmond relates what it was like growing up in
front of America in a show business family and writes how difficult
it was to fight the perception he was a washed-up has-been in the
early '80s.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact was, my teen idol years had cost me my credibility as
a singer and as a musician,'' Osmond writes.
</P>
<P>
   The '70s should have been the best of times for Osmond. As the
lead singer of the Brady Bunch-clean Osmond Brothers, Donny was a
bona fide heartthrob before he hit puberty. With a string of
bubblegum hits like Puppy Love and Go Away Little Girl, Osmond was
the Leonardo DiCaprio of the '70s. He was cute, had great hair and
even greater teeth.
</P>
<P>
   But when the music stopped and stage lights dimmed, the kid with
the 500-watt smile was often just another, sad, lonely and scared
little boy.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, when Osmond was 7, he wrote a letter to his mother from
Sweden, practically begging her to bring him home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told her I didn't want any part of this,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The letter was never acknowledged, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``She probably made the right decision,'' says Osmond, noting
that this book strained his relationship with his parents. ``She
really couldn't do anything about it. The mechanism was strong, it
was making money. How could you pull it apart? It just didn't make
sense.''
</P>
<P>
   It may not make sense to many that this 36-year show business
veteran would be afflicted with severe panic attacks. In fact, a
few years ago when Osmond was about to co-host Live with Regis and
Kathie Lee, he threw up the moment before he went on.
</P>
<P>
   You can trace the roots of Osmond's disorder to his almost
demonic need to be perfect and please everyone. Osmond is a classic
Type A personality. That means he works hard to achieve great
things and when he fails, he beats himself up over every mistake.
For Donny Osmond, failure is never an option.
</P>
<P>
   He had to be great in everything he did. Singing. Dancing. Ice
skating. You name it.
</P>
<P>
   Osmond admits his parents weren't that affectionate and were
often hard-driving. While they loved their nine kids, they spent
most of their time overseeing the Osmond family phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were so busy as kids, we never really had time to express
our feelings and to be honest,'' he notes. ``It was, like, `Come
on, get the job done ... be a professional.' Saying that to a 7-,
8-, 9-year-old kid hurts. It can take a toll.''
</P>
<P>
   So Osmond suffered in silence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I covered up my feelings for the sake of my image,'' he says.
``Growing up I had extremes. I had people screaming after me and I
had people spitting at me. As a teenager, you're trying to find
yourself as it is. Dealing with those extremes can mess up a
person.''
</P>
<P>
   For many years, Osmond managed to control his fears. While he
was always nervous before performances, once he heard the applause,
the nervousness would diminish.
</P>
<P>
   But as he got older, the panic attacks got worse. It got to the
point where it was hard to function in normal life. Attending
cocktail parties, for instance, struck sheer terror in Osmond.
</P>
<P>
   With the help of a psychologist, Osmond, who now hosts the
syndicated talk show Donny &AMP; Marie with his sister, took control of
his fear. While Osmond points out he's not completely cured, he has
stopped viewing every mistake as Armageddon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day I'm on television with Marie, I know I'll probably
make a mistake,'' he says. ``I've made some great faux pas in our
shows. But you know what? It's OK. It's fine because we all make
mistakes and you should be able to laugh about them because it
makes you real.''
</P>
<P>
   Osmond, who lives with his wife Debbie and their five sons in
Provo, Utah, is certainly able to laugh more freely. For instance,
when asked what kind of toothpaste the toothy star uses, he cracks,
``I ought to slap you right now. It's so funny, if you asked me
that question five, 10 years ago, it really would've upset me
because I would've been thinking, `C'mon, give me a break. I'm just
normal. My teeth aren't that big.' But I can understand where it
comes from now because that was my image, you know, the guy who
smiles all the time and he sings songs like sweet, innocent,
lollipops, lace, lipstick and all that kind of teeny-bopper
stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   And the answer?
</P>
<P>
   ``I use Colgate.''
</P>
<P>
   Osmond says he would never push his kids into Hollywood's
blinding lights. However, one of his sons is already in a punk rock
band called Sudden Urge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I almost joined the mosh pit,'' says Osmond, referring to when
he attended one of his son's concerts, ``but he said, `No.' He
looked at me and said, `Dad, don't you even think about it.'''
</P>
<P>
   What Osmond mostly thinks about now is getting better and
exorcising his demons.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world is my therapist now,'' he says. ``Now everybody
knows the real me. It was really difficult to be open and honest,
but I'm glad I did it because I feel so much better about myself
since I'm not hiding anything.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
