<SLUG> BC-FASHION-PLUS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LARGE-SIZE MODELS FIND THEMSELVES IN GREATER DEMAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JACKIE WHITE  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star   Charity Shields, a young single
mother, was shopping in a Kansas City store when she was mistaken
for another person _ a model. At size 18, Shields was a bit taken
aback, but the idea so intrigued her that she went searching for a
modeling agency.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three years later she is working regularly for such clients as
Wal-Mart, Lane Bryant Stores and the Jones Store in addition to
holding down a job as a workers' compensation claims adjuster and
caring for her 5-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   Shields is among a growing number of models caught up in the
explosive energy of a profession that used to stigmatize large
women.
</P>
<P>
   Maria Stonestreet, size 14 and a special education teacher in
Lawrence, decided to investigate modeling at the urging of her
brother, Los Angeles actor Eric Stonestreet. She has been so
successful in the Kansas City area that in September she will move
to Chicago to pursue a full-time career.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Smith answered a classified ad for a plus-size model
two years ago. Now Julie Wolf, owner of the Agency, a Kansas City
modeling representative, says, ``I wish I could clone her.'' And
Kim Hoffman, owner of Hoffman Models in Overland Park, says she is
actively scouting for plus-size talent, encouraging people at
weight-loss centers to watch for potential models.
</P>
<P>
   It has not always been so. Christine Alt, a celebrity plus-size
model and frequent spokeswoman, says when she started as a model in
1981, ``there was no such thing as a plus size.''
</P>
<P>
   When she gained weight and moved into large sizes in 1986, there
were only ``two or three agencies and a handful of models.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now there are hundreds out there, instead of just a hundred,''
says Alt who appears on the July//August cover of BBW (Big
Beautiful Woman) magazine.
</P>
<P>
   The plus-size model field probably has quadrupled in most major
cities in recent years, says Catherine Lippincott, director of
public relations for Lane Bryant, the Limited's retail chain that
specializes in large sizes. ``Now you can find just any look you
need,'' in any size, she says.
</P>
<P>
   Plus-size images are gaining prominence. Emme, the stylish blond
model, appears on the cable channel E's ``Fashion Emergency.'' The
high visibility of such celebrities as ABC Television's Star Jones,
Rosie O'Donnell, Cybill Shepherd and Kate Winslet is providing
positive ego reinforcement for many women.
</P>
<P>
   Mode magazine, a publication devoted to large women is in its
third year of publication and added Girl for teens earlier this
year. BBW magazine relaunched on the West Coast earlier this
summer. Anjellika recently was the first plus-size model voted to
an international models' association hall of fame, notes Gary
Dakin, a plus-size model for the Ford Agency in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The field of large-size modeling has grown ``beyond my own
dreams,'' says Susan Georget, the founder and director of
Willhelmina Models' Plus Size division, which is now getting
requests from major European fashion magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, credit in part goes to the apparel industry. Designers
and manufacturers have suddenly awakened to a massive untapped
market of fashion-conscious consumers who until recently had
limited choices beyond pull-on pants and tunics. More and more name
designers including Emanuel Ungaro, Gianfranco Ferre, Givenchy and
Giorgio Armani have added plus-size collections.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely a growth area for us,'' says Tina Hodak, the
St. Louis-based fashion director for Kansas City's Jones Store Co.
The store will debut Lauren by Ralph Lauren in large sizes this
fall.
</P>
<P>
   Alt says the clothing industry boom is also a result of
consumers raising their voices. ``The reason it happened is because
of the women,'' she said. ``They wrote letters. They complained.
They let them know they were sick of stretch green polyester pants.
They were heard.''
</P>
<P>
   And manufacturers are responding in a big way. Lane Bryant has
launched a major promotional effort to address a young, hip
customer. The company contracted with Camryn Manheim of
television's ``The Practice'' to be a celebrity model and broadcast
a New York fashion show on the Web last week.
</P>
<P>
   Today's fashion essentials such Capri pants, drawstring pants
and skirts, cargo pockets and camisole sweater sets are now
flooding stores in all sizes.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, plus-size models did not always enjoy the same
glamorous image as other models. They didn't get paid as much,
either.
</P>
<P>
   Alt says that in her early days, some photographers simply
refused to shoot plus-size models. And smaller models made a point
to ignore them on jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The situation has changed dramatically now and ``the industry is
one big happy family,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly the stigma has mostly disappeared. Rates have almost
closed ranks, says Ford's Dakin, and discrepancies in treatment
have dropped if not totally disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Jessica La Voie, a young Kansas City area woman, is working
quite happily as a size 14 with New York's Wilhelmina Agency. But
she recalls her move there two years ago, when no budget was
provided to help her find housing, unlike with other models. She
found herself living in a rodent-infested hotel for a time.
</P>
<P>
   At the Ford agency, Dakin says all the models, regardless of
size, are ``handled with kid gloves.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, requirements for plus-size models are comparable to
those of other models. They must be at least 5 feet 9 inches tall
and well-proportioned. (Most work out to stay toned.)
</P>
<P>
   In Kansas City, larger sizes such as 16 and 18 seem to be most
in demand. ``Julie encouraged me to gain weight,'' says Elizabeth
Smith of her agent.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, size 14 may be the most prevalent, but Lane
Bryant's Lippincott says the company uses most sizes in their
shows, and 14 to 16 for shoots because those are the sample sizes.
Mode tends to use models size 12, 14 and 16, says Nancy LeWinter,
publication director.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond size, all models should have ``an inviting personality,''
as Kim Hoffman calls it, or ``a certain energy,'' says LeWinter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-99 1104EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990629.0049 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 11:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3034 &Cx1f; kan-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-TORTE-KAN &LR;      06-29 1709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-TORTE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLUEPRINT FOR A FROZEN TORTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILL WENDHOLT SILVA  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   What do an ice cream torte and a skyscraper have in common?
</P>
<P>
   Blueprints.
</P>
<P>
   Engineers wouldn't dream of constructing a column of granite,
steel and glass without a plan to ensure its stability. Never mind
that there's a tower leaning 17 feet from the perpendicular over in
Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Kudos to the smart cookie who invented springform pans to hold
dense desserts built on fragile crumb crusts. With such a sturdy
base, even the noncook can construct a rather impressive torte
without fear of structural failure.
</P>
<P>
   So here's a blueprint for building your own frozen ice cream
torte: Take a cookie-crumb crust (the foundation), add scoops of
softened ice cream (the building blocks), drizzle with a gooey
dessert sauce (think mortar to cement the ``blocks'' together) and
garnish with a few sprinkles (the architectural details).
</P>
<P>
   The molded layers can be varied to suit your tastes. Don't like
coffee-flavored ice cream? Try pralines and cream ice cream
instead. Vary the type of crushed cookies in the crust, swirl
sauces with a flourish or go baroque with garnishes.
</P>
<P>
   Since discovering a recipe for Frozen Mocha Torte in Creme de
Colorado Cookbook by the Junior League of Denver, I have used it as
a springboard to other flavors and combinations. For instance, when
the mocha-flavored torte of the original recipe proved rather adult
for my 5-year-old son's birthday, I created a strawberry-vanilla
torte on an Oreo crust and sprinkled it with mini M&AMP;M's.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't already own a springform pan, they're fairly
inexpensive and sold at department stores and cookware stores. I
bought a set of 9-inch and 6-inch pans for $14.95.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to get fancy you can also pick up an ice cream
spade, a flat-ish ice cream scoop, to help smooth things along. I
found one at the supermarket for a few bucks.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from a cookie-crumb crust, which takes about 15 minutes to
assemble and bake, there's no heat involved. If this all seems just
a little too easy, feel free to make a stovetop dessert sauce from
scratch, although a store-bought ice cream sauce (not syrup) will
do nicely.
</P>
<P>
   Use the following lists of mix-and-match ingredients to build
the frozen torte of your dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Foundations
</P>
<P>
   Elinor Klivens, author of Bake and Freeze Chocolate Desserts
(Broadway), bakes these cookie crumb crusts at 325 degrees for 6
minutes in a 9-inch springform pan.
</P>
<P>
   Graham Cracker Crumb: 1 1/2 cups graham cracker crumbs, 3/4
teaspoon ground cinnamon, 5 tablespoons unsalted melted butter.
</P>
<P>
   Graham Cracker Crumb Crust With Nuts: 1 cup finely chopped nuts
(walnuts, pecans or toasted almonds), 1 cup plus 1 tablespoon
graham cracker crumbs, 1/2 teaspoon ground cinnamon, 5 tablespoons
unsalted melted butter.
</P>
<P>
   Graham Cracker or Chocolate Wafer Cookie Crumb Crust: 2 cups
chocolate wafer crumbs (9-ounce package), 6 tablespoons unsalted
melted butter.
</P>
<P>
   Graham Cracker or Chocolate Wafer Crumb Crust with Chocolate
Chips: 1 1/2 cups graham cracker or chocolate wafer cookie crumbs,
1 1/2 teaspoons ground cinnamon, 5 tablespoons unsalted melted
butter, 1/2 cup miniature semisweet chocolate chips.
</P>
<P>
   Oreo cookie crumb crust: 2 1/4 cups Oreo cookie crumbs with
filling (about 3 1/3 cups Oreos), 2 tablespoons unsalted melted
butter.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Adler, author of A Kansas City Christmas Cookbook (Two
Lane Press), bakes this one at 350 degrees for 12 minutes in an
8-inch springform pan.
</P>
<P>
   Macadamia nut crust: 1 1/2 cups all-purpose flour, 1/2 cup
melted butter, 1 cup sugar, 1/2 cup chopped macadamia nuts.
</P>
<P>
   (Note: Baked crumb crusts may be stored in the freezer for up to
1 month.)
</P>
<P>
   Mortar
</P>
<P>
   Whether you prefer storebought or homemade dessert sauces, heat
room temperature or chilled sauces for 5 to 10 seconds in the
microwave to help it drizzle better. Just be sure it's completely
cooled so it won't melt the ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   Amaretto Caramel Sauce: 1 cup sugar, 3/4 cup water, 1 teaspoon
vanilla extract, 1 cup heavy cream or condensed skim milk, 1/4 cup
amaretto.
</P>
<P>
   Combine sugar, water and vanilla in a heavy saucepan, and stir
over low heat to dissolve sugar. Increase heat to medium-high and
boil, without stirring, until mixture turns golden brown (about 5
to 10 minutes). Remove from heat and carefully whisk in cream.
Return to low heat and stir until mixture thickens (about 5
minutes). Remove from heat and stir in amaretto. Allow to cool.
Makes 2 1/2 cups. _ A Kansas City Christmas Cookbook by Karen Adler
and Jane Doyle Guthrie
</P>
<P>
   Scotch Butterscotch Sauce: 1 cup packed light brown sugar, 1/3
cup heavy cream, 3 tablespoons unsalted butter, 2 tablespoons dark
corn syrup, 2 tablespoons Scotch whisky, 1 teaspoon vanilla.
</P>
<P>
   In a medium saucepan, slowly bring the brown sugar, cream,
butter and corn syrup to a boil over medium heat, stirring
constantly to dissolve sugar. Boil gently, stirring often, until
the sauce thickens and coats the back of a spoon, 4 to 5 minutes.
Remove from the heat and stir in the Scotch and vanilla until
blended. Makes about 1 cup. Allow to cool. _ Short &AMP; Sweet
(Houghton Mifflin) by Melanie Barnard
</P>
<P>
   Hot Chocolate Drizzle: 1 1/2 cups light corn syrup, 1/3 cup
unsweetened cocoa powder, 1/4 cup water, pinch of salt, 1
tablespoon butter, 1 teaspoon vanilla extract.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the corn syrup, cocoa, water and salt in a 4-cup or
larger microwave-safe bowl. Microwave, uncovered, on high, for 3
minutes or until boiling. Remove from the microwave, add the butter
and vanilla, and stir until the butter melts and the mixture is
well blended. Allow to cool. _ Desperation Dinners! (Workman) by
Beverly Mills and Alicia Ross
</P>
<P>
   Pineapple-Apricot Sundae Sauce: 1 lemon, 1 jar (12 ounces)
apricot preserves, 1/3 cup light or dark brown sugar, firmly
packed, 1/3 cup unsweetened pineapple juice.
</P>
<P>
   Grate enough zest from the lemon to make 1 1/2 teaspoons.
Reserve the remaining lemon for another use. Combine the zest with
the remaining ingredients in a 4-cup or larger microwave-safe bowl.
Microwave 2 minutes, uncovered, on high. The preserves should be
melted and the mixture warm throughout. Remove from the microwave
and stir until the sugar is dissolved. Allow to cool. Keep
leftovers in the refrigerator. Makes about 2 cups. _ Desperation
Dinners! by Beverly Mills and Alicia Ross
</P>
<P>
   Hot Fudge Sauce: 6 ounces unsweetened chocolate, 4 tablespoons
butter, 2 cups sugar, 1 cup half-and-half, 14 ounces sweetened
condensed milk, 3 tablespoons brandy, bourbon, rum or favorite
liqueur (optional).
</P>
<P>
   In medium saucepan, melt chocolate and butter over low heat,
stirring constantly. Add sugar and half-and-half, and continue
cooking until thick. Gradually add condensed milk. Cook 20 minutes,
stirring occasionally. Stir in liqueur, if using. This keeps almost
indefinitely in the refrigerator. After it's cooled, you may need
to reheat for 30 seconds in the microwave or reheat on the stove
until pourable. Can freeze for up to 2 weeks before serving. Cover
with plastic wrap or aluminum foil. Makes 2 1/2 to 3 cups. _ Creme
de Colorado Cookbook by the Junior League of Denver
</P>
<P>
   Building blocks
</P>
<P>
   Chocolate ice cream
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry ice cream
</P>
<P>
   Vanilla ice cream
</P>
<P>
   Mint-Chocolate Chip ice cream
</P>
<P>
   Espresso Cream ice cream
</P>
<P>
   Chocolate-Chip Cookie Dough ice cream
</P>
<P>
   Peppermint ice cream
</P>
<P>
   Pineapple ice cream
</P>
<P>
   Details
</P>
<P>
   Mini M&AMP;M's and chocolate chips
</P>
<P>
   Peppermint candies
</P>
<P>
   Toffee bits
</P>
<P>
   Crushed candy bars
</P>
<P>
   Sliced bananas
</P>
<P>
   Fresh fruit slices
</P>
<P>
   Nuts
</P>
<P>
   Dream tortes
</P>
<P>
   Go ahead. Let your imagination run wild.
</P>
<P>
   - Try a gingersnap crust with layers of vanilla and pineapple
ice cream drizzled with Pineapple-Apricot sauce. Sprinkle with
slivered almonds or macadamia nuts.
</P>
<P>
   - Make a graham cracker crust. Top with two cheesecake-flavored
ice cream layers. Top with cherries.
</P>
<P>
   - An Oreo cookie crust is a wonderful showcase for layers of
chocolate and mint-chocolate chip ice cream. Top with curly
chocolate shavings.
</P>
<P>
   - A chocolate cookie crumb crust layered with chocolate and
banana ice cream, drizzled with amaretto caramel sauce and topped
with bananas sounds decadent.
</P>
<P>
   - Elinor Klivens' Bake and Freeze Chocolate Desserts has a
recipe for a Chocolate Peppermint Crunch Pie. It's built on a
chocolate or Oreo cookie crumb crust, then filled with a layer of
chocolate ice cream, another of peppermint ice cream and 1 cup of
coarsely crushed peppermint candy divided between the layers and
drizzled with chocolate sauce.
</P>
<P>
   - Haagen-Dazs makes a killer Macadamia Nut ice cream that would
taste great over a Macadamia Nut Crust.
</P>
<P>
   I stumbled on a recipe for Frozen Mocha Torte in Creme de
Colorado Cookbook by the Junior League of Denver. The editorial
note read: ``Absolutely scrumptious.''
</P>
<P>
   No need to be modest.
</P>
<P>
   Blueprint frozen mocha torte
</P>
<P>
   Makes 10 to 12 servings
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups chocolate wafer cookie crumbs
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons butter, melted
</P>
<P>
   3 cups chocolate ice cream
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup Hot Fudge Sauce, cooled, divided use (see Mortar
section)
</P>
<P>
   3 cups coffee ice cream
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces chocolate-coated toffee candy bars, coarsely crushed,
or 1/4 cup toffee bits
</P>
<P>
   Stir together cookie crumbs and butter. Lightly press onto
bottom of 9- or 10-inch springform pan. Bake at 350 degrees for 8
minutes or until lightly browned. Cool.
</P>
<P>
   Remove chocolate ice cream from refrigerator and allow to soften
to a spreadable consistency, about 20 to 30 minutes. Spread
chocolate ice cream in an even layer over cooled cookie crust;
drizzle evenly with 1/4 cup fudge sauce and freeze until firm.
</P>
<P>
   Remove coffee ice cream from refrigerator and allow to soften to
a spreadable consistency, about 20 to 30 minutes. Top ice cream
torte with a layer of coffee ice cream. Sprinkle evenly with
crushed candy and drizzle with remaining 1/4 cup fudge sauce. Cover
with plastic wrap and freeze until firm.
</P>
<P>
   To serve, unmold ring of springform pan and remove. Allow to sit
at room temperature for 10 minutes before using a sharp knife to
cut into wedges.
</P>
<P>
   Note: To make a 6-inch version, simply cut the entire recipe in
half.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-99 1105EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990629.0050 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 11:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3036 &Cx1f; kan-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-SILVA-KAN &LR;      06-29 0477
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-SILVA-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUST A TASTE COLUMN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILL WENDHOLT SILVA  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Can burning a little incense and lighting a few candles help
make chopping vegetables a meditative experience?
</P>
<P>
   If you've never thought about the karma of cooking, whether a
soup is yin or yang or about the feng shui, the ``life flow,'' of
your kitchen, you might dismiss all of this as so much New Age
speak.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, on the cusp of a new millennium, when so many of us are
dreaming of the Jetson-style kitchen of the future, there's a faint
yet audible mantra emanating from what I call spiritual cookbooks.
</P>
<P>
   The budding genre reveres the kitchen as a sort of holy
sanctuary. The act of cooking becomes an exercise in meditation and
astute eating is a recipe for salvation.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the sampling bearing quasi-mystical titles that have
landed on my desk in recent weeks:
</P>
<P>
   - The Sacred Kitchen (New World Library, $16.95), by Robert and
Jon Robertson. Its authors relied on sacred texts from throughout
the world to uncover a higher consciousness in the act of cooking
and eating.
</P>
<P>
   - The Tao of Food (A Godsfield Book, $24.95), by Richard Craze
and Roni Jay. Using the ancient Chinese principles now more than
3,000 years old, this system of thinking and eating is based on
common sense and simplicity.
</P>
<P>
   - A Simple Celebration: A Vegetarian Cookbook for Body, Mind and
Spirit (Harmony Books, $23), by Ginny Bell Bragg and David Simon
with a foreword by Deepak Chopra. Based on Ayurvedic health
practices, taste charts are used to help balance body types.
</P>
<P>
   - Healing Secrets of the Seasons (Morrow, $27), by Judith Benn
Hurley. An amalgam of ancient philosophies, Hurley emphasizes
listening to nature's rhythms to eat more healthfully.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999 trend forecasters tell us cooking is quickly becoming
more of a hobby and less of a necessity. No one need cook to
survive. But who knew it could be a way to self-improvement?
</P>
<P>
   The Sacred Kitchen, for instance, seeks to help cooks ``achieve
centeredness to free yourself from stress, to be mindful of the
moment to alleviate worry and to stay focused and peaceful while
you cook. It helps you `get into the act' of cooking and look
forward to dinnertime, not as another chore in your busy day, but
as a haven for relaxation and recharging.''
</P>
<P>
   On nights after work when I look into the jumbled depths of my
refrigerator with despair and try to fathom just what's for dinner,
I can only dream of that peaceful, easy feeling.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the act of cooking and eating is a daily ritual that should
nurture the body. And there are times when it can even touch the
soul.
</P>
<P>
   The late food writer M.F.K. Fisher once wrote: ``Any time we eat
it's holy. We should have ritual and ceremony, not just gobbling
down some food to keep alive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-99 1106EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990629.0051 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 11:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3046 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FULL-FIGURE-EXPLOSION     06-29 1408
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FULL-FIGURE-EXPLOSION-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASHION INJECTION FOR PLUS SIZES  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this special one-shot feature from W magazine _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ contact New York Times Syndicate Sales
Executive DEBRA WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!----------------------
 &HT;    THREE B&AMP;W PHOTOS are available ELECTRONICALLY by E-MAIL. Please
specify that you want the art when you order the article.
 &HT;    ----------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been filed into the ``a'' general
news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By ANNE D'INNOCENZIO 
 c.1999 Fairchild Publications  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There's a fashion explosion in the moderate and
better plus-size market, spurred by women in their 20s and early
30s who are demanding the same styles as their regular-size peers.
</P>
<P>
   Executives from firms such as Delta Burke, McNaughton Apparel,
Karen Kane and August Silk, which once played it safe with fashion
for the full-figured customer, are now coming out with such trendy
looks as capris, pants with cargo pockets and scoopnecks.
</P>
<P>
   The push began last year, but should be more dramatic for
fall/holiday.
</P>
<P>
   At the forefront of the movement is Lane Bryant, Limited's
750-store plus-size chain, which has been pushing bare looks for
several years. This spring, it has done well with capris, which hit
four inches below the knee, and pedal-pushers, five inches above
the ankle. The store has also done well with peasant blouses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took a gamble, and the (capri) looks did better than we
thought. It was a pleasant surprise,'' said Chris Hansen, vice
president of marketing and creative, adding that the cropped pants
sold out. ``It is a flattering look, something that she would not
have thought she could wear.''
</P>
<P>
   For fall, the chain will offer a wider version.
</P>
<P>
   Lane Bryant is also continuing to show its pants with cargo
treatments, which were unveiled in stores two years ago. She added
that the pockets are positioned on the hip.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the chain will offer vests in fleece, quilted nylon
and nylon stretch. There will also be jersey camisoles in nylon
stretch, merchandised with woven shirtings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in a fabulous fashion cycle, and there is a pent-up
demand among our customers for newness,'' she said, adding that
Lane Bryant is experiencing double-digit sales increases this
season over the year-ago period.
</P>
<P>
   Major better and moderate sportswear resources are following
suit.
</P>
<P>
   Take, for example, McNaughton Apparel, which over the past year
has made the color and print palette of its plus-size moderate
line, Maggie McNaughton, in sync with the fashion colors and prints
of its regular-size line.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, the plus-size customer wanted brights in the
tops. On the bottoms, they just wanted black or navy, and they
weren't willing to try wines or olives,'' said Lynn Fish, executive
vice president of design and merchandising at McNaughton Apparel.
``Now, they want softer colors such as pinks, soft yellows and
celadons. The fashion is being pushed by our younger customers, who
are in their 20s and 30s.''
</P>
<P>
   McNaughton is interpreting all the silhouettes for the plus-size
woman. The fall lineup includes double-layer skirts and hooded
zip-front deconstructed knit jackets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our plus-size customer likes hoods. She tends to like more
casual looks,'' said Fish.
</P>
<P>
   For spring 2000, the company is coming out with capris for the
first time _ for both the Norton McNaughton and the Maggie
McNaughton consumer. They will be in stretch twills and patterned
stretch.
</P>
<P>
   However, the firm will offer only clam-diggers, which offer more
leg exposure, for its Norton McNaughton customer.
</P>
<P>
   Fish added that for that same season, the company is also
interpreting the cropped drawstring sweater in plus sizes.
</P>
<P>
   Delta Burke, who designs a plus-size line that bears her name,
said the demand for more fashion has made creating her collection a
lot more fun. She added that ``the stores are coming around'' to
demanding sexier styles.
</P>
<P>
   Dillard's, she said, requested a line of teddies for fall.
</P>
<P>
   Burke's holiday lineup includes sweater sets in Lurex metallics,
which hit at the middle of the hip; capris, which are 24 inches _
an inch longer than the style's standard; trouser skirts and cargo
pants.
</P>
<P>
   Burke said that interpreting the cargo pants was a bit tricky.
Instead of putting the pocket on the side, which would have added
more bulk to the garment, she said she placed it on the front of
the pants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women want color and novelty fashion, and they want it at the
same time as the rest of the store,'' said Fern Bratten, designer
of a two-year-old plus-size line that bears her name.
</P>
<P>
   The line, which is in 400 doors, is a division of Kellwood's
David Dart Design Group.
</P>
<P>
   She said there is a ``younger spirit'' in the misses' plus-size
market. She believes that helping the fashion movement are such
plus-size personalities as actress Camryn Manheim of ``The
Practice'' and Rosie O'Donnell.
</P>
<P>
   While the bulk of Bratten's pants business is comprised of
pull-on elastic pants in garment-washed linen and Tencel, she is
offering one capri style, which hits midcalf, and cropped pants.
</P>
<P>
   The company will also continue to offer pants with cargo
pockets, which first hit the stores in May, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that stretch and capris are selling is proof that the
plus-size customer is taking more risks,'' said Bratten, who just
completed a 67-city tour in three months, visiting store accounts.
</P>
<P>
   She added, ``They are making peace with their size, and not
waiting to lose those 50 pounds.''
</P>
<P>
   For fall, Bratten is also shortening some of the jackets, to be
in sync with the trend to cropped looks.
</P>
<P>
   Becky Blair, vice president of sales at better-price sportswear
resource Karen Kane, admitted she wasn't prepared for the fashion
demands of the full-figured consumer when the company expanded into
large sizes this spring. Sure, the spring lineup, which offered a
combination of knit, Tencel and linen dressing, did well, but she
said the firm could have maximized the business even more.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were a bit too conservative,'' Blair acknowledged. ``We
thought that the customer wanted to be more covered.''
</P>
<P>
   The plus-size line, which was unveiled in 75 doors and was under
Karen Kane Sport, went too deep in black and navy, ignored capris,
which were offered in both its misses' and petite lines, and didn't
have any pink. It also did not offer stretch, and could have used
more hooded looks, Blair said.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem, she admitted, was that the company had
thought the plus-size line would appeal to an older group, women
from 35 to 55. However, company officials soon found out that it
also drew women in their early 20s to early 30s.
</P>
<P>
   ``There just seems to be a crop of young women who are demanding
something new,'' Blair said. ``They want the colors, the special
pieces.''
</P>
<P>
   For fall, Karen Kane is showing trendier looks such as stretch
jackets and is expanding plus sizes to its Lifestyle label, which
is more fashion-oriented than its Sport line. The plus-size line
will be expanded to 100 doors.
</P>
<P>
   For fall/holiday, only about 40 percent of the plus-size
collection will be in black and navy, compared with 60 percent this
spring.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Kane is also showing more embroidered tops, and item
T-shirts, Blair said, adding, ``The line was too group focused.''
</P>
<P>
   For fall, the collection will be in 100 doors. Wholesale volume
should be about $5 million in its first year, she said.
</P>
<P>
   August Silk, a better-price silk resource, which has long
offered plus sizes, is now out to ``maximize'' the business,
according to Jack Weinstock, chairman and chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We definitely plan to intensify the business,'' he said. ``We
had offered basics in the past. Now, we are offering more
fashion.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Anne D'Innocenzio is a reporter for Fairchild Publications.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (To purchase this special one-shot feature _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ contact New York Times Syndicate Sales Executive
DEBRA WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-99 1121EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990629.0052 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 11:21 </DATE_TIME>
