<DOCNO> NYT19990629.0059 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 11:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3054 &Cx1f; ttf-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FULL-FIGURE-EXPLOSION     06-29 1408
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FULL-FIGURE-EXPLOSION-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASHION INJECTION FOR PLUS SIZES  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this special one-shot feature from W magazine _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ contact New York Times Syndicate Sales
Executive DEBRA WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!----------------------
 &HT;    THREE B&AMP;W PHOTOS are available ELECTRONICALLY by E-MAIL. Please
specify that you want the art when you order the article.
 &HT;    ----------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been filed into the ``a'' general
news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By ANNE D'INNOCENZIO 
 c.1999 Fairchild Publications  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There's a fashion explosion in the moderate and
better plus-size market, spurred by women in their 20s and early
30s who are demanding the same styles as their regular-size peers.
</P>
<P>
   Executives from firms such as Delta Burke, McNaughton Apparel,
Karen Kane and August Silk, which once played it safe with fashion
for the full-figured customer, are now coming out with such trendy
looks as capris, pants with cargo pockets and scoopnecks.
</P>
<P>
   The push began last year, but should be more dramatic for
fall/holiday.
</P>
<P>
   At the forefront of the movement is Lane Bryant, Limited's
750-store plus-size chain, which has been pushing bare looks for
several years. This spring, it has done well with capris, which hit
four inches below the knee, and pedal-pushers, five inches above
the ankle. The store has also done well with peasant blouses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took a gamble, and the (capri) looks did better than we
thought. It was a pleasant surprise,'' said Chris Hansen, vice
president of marketing and creative, adding that the cropped pants
sold out. ``It is a flattering look, something that she would not
have thought she could wear.''
</P>
<P>
   For fall, the chain will offer a wider version.
</P>
<P>
   Lane Bryant is also continuing to show its pants with cargo
treatments, which were unveiled in stores two years ago. She added
that the pockets are positioned on the hip.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the chain will offer vests in fleece, quilted nylon
and nylon stretch. There will also be jersey camisoles in nylon
stretch, merchandised with woven shirtings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in a fabulous fashion cycle, and there is a pent-up
demand among our customers for newness,'' she said, adding that
Lane Bryant is experiencing double-digit sales increases this
season over the year-ago period.
</P>
<P>
   Major better and moderate sportswear resources are following
suit.
</P>
<P>
   Take, for example, McNaughton Apparel, which over the past year
has made the color and print palette of its plus-size moderate
line, Maggie McNaughton, in sync with the fashion colors and prints
of its regular-size line.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, the plus-size customer wanted brights in the
tops. On the bottoms, they just wanted black or navy, and they
weren't willing to try wines or olives,'' said Lynn Fish, executive
vice president of design and merchandising at McNaughton Apparel.
``Now, they want softer colors such as pinks, soft yellows and
celadons. The fashion is being pushed by our younger customers, who
are in their 20s and 30s.''
</P>
<P>
   McNaughton is interpreting all the silhouettes for the plus-size
woman. The fall lineup includes double-layer skirts and hooded
zip-front deconstructed knit jackets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our plus-size customer likes hoods. She tends to like more
casual looks,'' said Fish.
</P>
<P>
   For spring 2000, the company is coming out with capris for the
first time _ for both the Norton McNaughton and the Maggie
McNaughton consumer. They will be in stretch twills and patterned
stretch.
</P>
<P>
   However, the firm will offer only clam-diggers, which offer more
leg exposure, for its Norton McNaughton customer.
</P>
<P>
   Fish added that for that same season, the company is also
interpreting the cropped drawstring sweater in plus sizes.
</P>
<P>
   Delta Burke, who designs a plus-size line that bears her name,
said the demand for more fashion has made creating her collection a
lot more fun. She added that ``the stores are coming around'' to
demanding sexier styles.
</P>
<P>
   Dillard's, she said, requested a line of teddies for fall.
</P>
<P>
   Burke's holiday lineup includes sweater sets in Lurex metallics,
which hit at the middle of the hip; capris, which are 24 inches _
an inch longer than the style's standard; trouser skirts and cargo
pants.
</P>
<P>
   Burke said that interpreting the cargo pants was a bit tricky.
Instead of putting the pocket on the side, which would have added
more bulk to the garment, she said she placed it on the front of
the pants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women want color and novelty fashion, and they want it at the
same time as the rest of the store,'' said Fern Bratten, designer
of a two-year-old plus-size line that bears her name.
</P>
<P>
   The line, which is in 400 doors, is a division of Kellwood's
David Dart Design Group.
</P>
<P>
   She said there is a ``younger spirit'' in the misses' plus-size
market. She believes that helping the fashion movement are such
plus-size personalities as actress Camryn Manheim of ``The
Practice'' and Rosie O'Donnell.
</P>
<P>
   While the bulk of Bratten's pants business is comprised of
pull-on elastic pants in garment-washed linen and Tencel, she is
offering one capri style, which hits midcalf, and cropped pants.
</P>
<P>
   The company will also continue to offer pants with cargo
pockets, which first hit the stores in May, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that stretch and capris are selling is proof that the
plus-size customer is taking more risks,'' said Bratten, who just
completed a 67-city tour in three months, visiting store accounts.
</P>
<P>
   She added, ``They are making peace with their size, and not
waiting to lose those 50 pounds.''
</P>
<P>
   For fall, Bratten is also shortening some of the jackets, to be
in sync with the trend to cropped looks.
</P>
<P>
   Becky Blair, vice president of sales at better-price sportswear
resource Karen Kane, admitted she wasn't prepared for the fashion
demands of the full-figured consumer when the company expanded into
large sizes this spring. Sure, the spring lineup, which offered a
combination of knit, Tencel and linen dressing, did well, but she
said the firm could have maximized the business even more.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were a bit too conservative,'' Blair acknowledged. ``We
thought that the customer wanted to be more covered.''
</P>
<P>
   The plus-size line, which was unveiled in 75 doors and was under
Karen Kane Sport, went too deep in black and navy, ignored capris,
which were offered in both its misses' and petite lines, and didn't
have any pink. It also did not offer stretch, and could have used
more hooded looks, Blair said.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem, she admitted, was that the company had
thought the plus-size line would appeal to an older group, women
from 35 to 55. However, company officials soon found out that it
also drew women in their early 20s to early 30s.
</P>
<P>
   ``There just seems to be a crop of young women who are demanding
something new,'' Blair said. ``They want the colors, the special
pieces.''
</P>
<P>
   For fall, Karen Kane is showing trendier looks such as stretch
jackets and is expanding plus sizes to its Lifestyle label, which
is more fashion-oriented than its Sport line. The plus-size line
will be expanded to 100 doors.
</P>
<P>
   For fall/holiday, only about 40 percent of the plus-size
collection will be in black and navy, compared with 60 percent this
spring.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Kane is also showing more embroidered tops, and item
T-shirts, Blair said, adding, ``The line was too group focused.''
</P>
<P>
   For fall, the collection will be in 100 doors. Wholesale volume
should be about $5 million in its first year, she said.
</P>
<P>
   August Silk, a better-price silk resource, which has long
offered plus sizes, is now out to ``maximize'' the business,
according to Jack Weinstock, chairman and chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We definitely plan to intensify the business,'' he said. ``We
had offered basics in the past. Now, we are offering more
fashion.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Anne D'Innocenzio is a reporter for Fairchild Publications.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (To purchase this special one-shot feature _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ contact New York Times Syndicate Sales Executive
DEBRA WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
