<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Tuesday, June 29, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Wednesday.
If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-WILSON (San Diego) _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush appears to
be leaving one group behind as he tries to spread his message of
``compassionate conservative'' inclusiveness in California. So far,
the folks in Austin, Texas, have shunned most of the top political
strategists of former Gov. Pete Wilson. By ROBERT SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   PLASTIC-SURGERY (San Francisco) _ In the new century, doctors
will offer patients not only younger faces and trimmer torsos but
also fingers grown from cattle cells and organ parts built on
biodegradable scaffolds. That was the tantalizing possibility put
forth at an international conference here of nearly 2,000 plastic
surgeons. By ELIZABETH FERNANDEZ.
</P>
<P>
   STOLEN-TB-VIAL (San Francisco) _ Police are seeking the public's
help in finding a vial of live tuberculosis bacteria that was
stolen from the hotel room of a medical researcher attending a
tuberculosis conference here. By EMILY GURNON.
</P>
<P>
   MILLENNIUM-GENETICS (Houston) _ Custom ordering children may be
the ultimate shopping experience of the next millennium, like
ordering a sunroof or leather seats from a car dealer. One eminent
biologist describes a future in which parents engineer their
children to possess, say, the olfactory powers of dogs or the night
vision of owls. But even the tamest alterations promise to open a
Pandora's box of ethical questions. By TODD ACKERMAN. (For weekend
release, July 3 and 4. Photo and graphics available on NYT
database.)
</P>
<P>
   CANCER-SURVIVOR (Albany, N.Y.) _ Eight years after beating a
brain tumor, Philip Mucci finds that cancer no longer claims center
stage in his life. Mucci, 20, is part of the first big wave of
childhood cancer survivors to reach adulthood. He faces a future
full of unknowns from how childhood cancer survivors will age to
how radiation affects the body years after it is used. By CELINA
OTTAWAY.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-PROJECT (San Francisco) _ While many ex-prison inmates
get caught at new crimes, a woman here has started programs that
stop criminal behavior. They're called the Garden Project and the
Tree Corps, two programs designed to train and employ ex-offenders.
As sheriff of San Francisco, I can attest to their success. By
MICHAEL HENNESSEY.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-DROUGHT (Monclova, Mexico) _ Most of the farms around
here are desperately dry. The drought reveals how industrialization
and globalization are changing the face of Mexican agriculture.
International markets, pushed by trade pacts such as the North
American Free Trade Agreement, have stripped Mexican farmers of
much of the protection and price controls once provided by the
government. By ELIZABETH ALLEN. (For Sunday release. Photos
available on the Wieck database.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TEEN-INVESTING (San Francisco) _ Ginger Thomson, a former
investment banker and Harvard MBA who left the financial world
several years ago to raise her three kids here, has created a Web
site for teens to help them manage money, shop online and learn
about investments. It's called doughNET.com. By EDWARD IWATA.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-SOUTHPARK-PROFILE (Los Angeles) _ ``South Park'' creators
Trey Parker and Matt Stone tackle the film ratings system in
``South Park: Bigger, Longer &AMP; Uncut.'' The two always seem to
champion humor that pushes limits. The movie will be released
nationwide Wednesday. By BRUCE WESTBROOK.
</P>
<P>
   AMUSEMENT-PARKS (San Francisco) _ School's out, the summer heat
is creeping in, and the kids are bored. How about a day at the
amusement park? How does $141.32 sound? That's the average national
cost of taking the tykes to one, according to Amusement Business
magazine, a Nashville-based amusement industry weekly. By BOBBY
McGILL.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ In London, Prince William
doesn't smile brightly enough in the official photo of his uncle's
wedding, so the photographer takes William's grinning face from
another shot and morphs it onto the family portrait. In Madison,
Conn., a high school senior outrages his parents by shaving his
head just before the yearbook pictures are shot, so his folks get a
photo company to digitally restore the kid's longer hairstyle. This
increasingly common practice gives me the creeps. By STEPHANIE
SALTER.
</P>
