<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 12:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3124 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-SOUTHPARK-PROFIL     06-29 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-SOUTHPARK-PROFILE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVIE PASSES MUSTER, `SOUTH PARK' CREATORS SAY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BRUCE WESTBROOK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The ratings board of the Motion Picture
Association of America may be surprised by the final title of
``South Park: Bigger, Longer &AMP; Uncut,'' opening Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Board members demanded cuts when they first saw the animated
film about foul-mouthed third-graders, say creators Trey Parker and
Matt Stone, who co-wrote it and supplied many voices, with Parker
also directing.
</P>
<P>
   But their film is ``pretty much uncut,'' they said in an
interview here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   At first, the creators were upset with the MPAA's verdict. ``But
then we realized we could use it to our advantage,'' said Parker,
29.
</P>
<P>
   When told to cut a scene, he said, they made it ``five times
worse ... Then the MPAA came back and said, `OK, it's fine.' It was
totally arbitrary.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Their moral code is not the same as ours,'' said Stone, 27.
``In fact, it's not even consistent with themselves on a day-to-day
basis.''
</P>
<P>
   At least Parker and Stone are consistent. Ever since ``South
Park'' evolved from a short ``Christmas card'' video circulated in
Hollywood into a Comedy Central cable hit (currently on hiatus)
followed by millions, they've become champions of humor that pushes
limits.
</P>
<P>
   Their new movie continues that process with an uncanny
timeliness.
</P>
<P>
   In the real world, President Clinton has just complained about
kids seeing R-rated films.
</P>
<P>
   In the Colorado town of South Park, bratty Cartman and other
third-graders do just that, sneaking into a comedy filled with
gutter language.
</P>
<P>
   When the kids repeat such words at school, alarmed parents
launch a moral crusade against the country of the film's origins,
Canada.
</P>
<P>
   War is declared, America turns totalitarian and kids are
implanted with chips giving electrical shocks when they say ``bad''
words.
</P>
<P>
   Like those kids, ``South Park's'' creators feel like ``whipping
boys'' _ of the MPAA.
</P>
<P>
   They said the ratings board first ``pushed our buttons'' by
giving ``Orgazmo'' _ their absurdist comedy about porno filmmakers
_ an NC-17, a commercial death sentence. ``Orgazmo'' was
non-violent and had little nudity, just constant talk about sex.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have a studio behind us, and there wasn't anything
we could do about it,'' said Parker, who calls ``South Park'' ``way
more hardcore than ''Orgazmo,`` which was almost chaste. But
''South Park`` had Paramount behind it, and they were able to push
it through.''
</P>
<P>
   To underscore their contentions, Parker and Stone put war scenes
in ``South Park'' aping ``Saving Private Ryan,'' an R-rated film
that they felt should have been rated NC-17 for violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point is, in our film people think language is bad, but
violence and bloodshed are OK,'' Parker said. ``And of course, the
MPAA didn't say anything about the violence, either. It was just,
`Don't say this word,' but blowing people to shreds was fine.''
</P>
<P>
   The creators, who met while students at the University of
Colorado, also have been slammed by critics. ``Orgazmo'' was
roasted, as was their ribald sports film, ``BASEketball.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The reviews weren't saying they didn't like the movies so much
as they hated us,'' Parker said. ``They were so mean _ just
personally attacking us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gotten a lot of good press, too,'' Stone said. ``But
we've also seen people who laughed all through `Orgazmo' or
`BASEketball' and then give them bad reviews. They don't understand
laughter as a guilty pleasure.''
</P>
<P>
   Their series has come under fire for its use of crude language.
The film is even more profane. Parker and Stone _ like comedians
Lenny Bruce and George Carlin before them _ say that epithets ``are
just words.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No one's getting hurt by them,'' Parker said. ``In fact,
halfway through our movie, you're kind of numb to it all. The words
aren't for humor so much as to make a point.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not language that's made `South Park' successful,'' Stone
said. ``It's bizarre situations and characters people love.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the movie has the same crude style as the TV show, with
jumpy movements for characters who look like paper cutouts.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the 80-minute film cost $20 million. Four TV episodes
with the same total length would cost about $1.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, we took longer _ and Paramount had to pay all these
producers,'' Parker said with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, technical demands were greater, especially for
elaborate Broadway-style production numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted it to look like (the series), but we also did things
to say, `This is a movie,''' Parker said.
</P>
<P>
   As for ``South Park's'' future, Stone and Parker say its ratings
are still strong, though they've dropped from the highs of the
show's peak publicity last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're where we should be,'' Parker said. ``It's still one of
the highest rated shows on cable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We could get half the ratings we get now and it would still be
profitable for Comedy Central,'' Stone said.
</P>
<P>
   With all the furor over their cartoons, the creators are amused
that some who first branded the show as ``unimportant, trite and
stupid'' are blaming ``South Park'' for the ills of society and its
culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I guess we do have an effect then,'' Parker said.
``Which is it?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
