<HEADLINE>
PICTURES WORTH A THOUSAND LIES 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In London, Prince William doesn't smile brightly
enough in the official photo of his uncle's wedding, so the
photographer takes William's grinning face from another shot and
morphs it onto the family portrait for Prince Edward and Sophie
Rhys-Jones' nuptials.
</P>
<P>
   In Madison, Conn., a high school senior outrages his parents by
shaving his head just before the yearbook pictures are shot, so his
folks get a photo company to digitally restore the kid's longer
hairstyle for the yearbook.
</P>
<P>
   This increasingly common practice gives me the creeps: using a
computer to alter a photographic record of reality.
</P>
<P>
   After all, it's one thing for Hugh Hefner's minions to airbrush
to perfection every Playboy Playmate's bodacious ta-tas.
</P>
<P>
   But to put a smile where there was none?
</P>
<P>
   A crop of healthy brown hair where the reality was a 5 o'clock
shadow? Where will it stop? Will it stop?
</P>
<P>
   My favorite part of ``Wag the Dog'' was when the script called
for Hollywood computer wizards to transform a ditzy blonde model _
carrying a package of Tostitos _ into a terrified Albanian who was
fleeing bombs and clutching a white cat.
</P>
<P>
   But that was a cynical movie about cynical movie makers and
cynical politicians (redundant, I know). I hate to think that every
image in daily life will soon be suspect. Did it really happen that
way or did some unseen hand change history with a mouse and a
scanner?
</P>
<P>
   Reportedly, Prince William is a shy guy who isn't all that at
ease in front of a camera. To have him show up as the only Mr.
Sobersides in a smiley family wedding portrait seems to me a
faithful rendering of the way things are.
</P>
<P>
   In years to come, all the royals could have looked at Ed and
Sophie's wedding photo and sighed, ``Ah, just like William.''
</P>
<P>
   In next century's history books, scholars could have noted that
William displayed his customary solemnity.
</P>
<P>
   Now that peculiar, individual ``imperfection'' is gone.
</P>
<P>
   Same with Daniel Young's senior picture. For reasons important
to his teen-age self, Young got himself a buzzcut. He was making a
statement. His kids and grandkids could have looked at the yearbook
photo and asked him what the cut was all about. Or they could have
split a gut laughing at him. But the point is, Young's real-life
deed would have been recorded in the book.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in his preppy haircut, tie and white shirt, he looks
perfectly homogenous and devoid of statements.
</P>
<P>
   When I asked about all this, Kim Komenich, the Pulitzer
Prize-winning photographer for the San Francisco Examiner, told me
that altering photographic images ``has been around as long as
photography has.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether it was portrait photographers retouching a prom queen's
face to remove her acne and lightening the skin tone of
African-Americans or National Geographic moving the Great Pyramids
a few feet to the left, reality has always been flexible in
pictures.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference is, before, you had to be really good at the
alchemy,'' Komenich said. ``Because it was so difficult to do _ and
there was no un-do button _ only accomplished photographers did the
altering. Now you can buy a scanner for $99, and anybody can do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Like everything else that is generated by computers, I feel
certain that photo morphing will proceed unchecked. Put technology
into the hands of the masses and the masses will use it _
especially when it means you can place yourself on the bridge of
the Enterprise right next to Captain Picard.
</P>
<P>
   People like me, who grew up trusting photos, thinking of them as
snapshots of reality, soon will be looked upon as quaint or
laughably naive. Probably we already are.
</P>
<P>
   We come from an era in which one picture was worth a thousand
words. Now the exchange rate is not so good.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her e-mail address is
salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-99 1316EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
