u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-DRAFT-SECOND-BOS &LR;      06-29 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-DRAFT-SECOND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAN CELTICS GET UP TO SPEED AT 55? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- History tells us that at least one late second-rounder
taken in Wednesday's NBA draft will make it. Barring any deal, that
is where the Celtics pick _ 55th overall _ and it will be their one
crack at the Class of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Pitino may be disinclined to even think about making the
pick and who can blame him? He has 12 guaranteed contracts. He has
at least one free agent (Bruce Bowen) he might want to re-sign. If
the Celtics do choose, and there's no rule that says they have to,
Pitino may go with a familiar face (best Kentucky guy) or take a
project.
</P>
<P>
   Since the league expanded to 29 teams in 1995, making No. 55 a
second rounder, no player taken at that spot has done much. Do
these names ring a bell? _ Ryan Bowen, Mark Blount, Ronnie
Henderson, and Michael McDonald. Of the four, only McDonald has
even played in the league and that was a cameo in Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   However, in four of the last five years, at least one player
taken in the 50s has gone on to play in the league, the best being
Shandon Anderson, whom Utah took with the 54th pick in 1996. Others
include Lawrence Funderburke (51 in '94), Don Reid (58 in '96), and
Chris Crawford (51 in '97). No one taken in the 50's last year did
anything, although J.R. Henderson (56) did stick with the Grizzlies
as a 12th man/cheerleader/nobody else available.
</P>
<P>
   There is plenty of evidence to suggest that a second-round
choice is not a waste. You could put together a pretty competitive
team with former second rounders. Tiny Archibald and Maurice Cheeks
were second rounders, although Archibald went 19th overall. (Cheeks
went 36th.) The Celtics occasionally have come up big in the second
round with some of the better ones being Danny Ainge, K.C. Jones,
Kevin Stacom, Brad Lohaus, Jeff Judkins, and Dino Radja.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics don't expect much this time around; general manager
Chris Wallace said he hopes he's still awake when the time comes
for Boston to choose. But that's not to say Wallace isn't doing his
homework and isn't hoping that a player they have rated much higher
than 55 is there when their turn arises.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you are picking at the upper end of the draft, you have
to concern yourself with what a guy can't do. How can he fail? The
ramifications are so huge. And every year, two or three guys in the
top 10 are going to fail.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the second round, it's the reverse. You're looking for
positives, something you can hang your hat on. Is he an NBA
rebounder? Can he make a shot? Is there some aspect of his game
that is it an NBA level?''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace mentioned Manute Bol as an example. Bol went in the
second round in 1985 to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at him as a potential lottery or high pick and you
see no body, no offense, no experience. You look at him in the
second round and, hey, he's 7-7 and can block shots,'' Wallace
said.
</P>
<P>
   The greatest second-round draft had to be in 1986; it ended up
being better than the first. Among those taken include Dennis
Rodman, Mark Price, and Jeff Hornacek. Meanwhile, the first-round
casualties that year included Len Bias, Chris Washburn, William
Bedford, Kenny Walker, Roy Tarpley, Pearl Washington, and Walter
Berry.
</P>
<P>
   Second-round pickers look for the proverbial drifter, due to
``suspicious background'' or other potentially naughty stuff like
blowing off interviews or appointments. Nick Van Exel, thought to
be a top 15 pick in 1993, slipped to 37 in part because he missed
some workouts. Cliff Robinson had a so-so senior year and fell from
the first round to 36. (Who will ever forget the sad sight of
Robinson, alone, in the green room waiting to hear his name?)
</P>
<P>
   Europe used to be a fertile source for second rounders; Radja
and Toni Kukoc went in the second. Lately, players such as Dejan
Bodiroga, Zeljko Rebraca, and Bruno Sundov went in the second. But
if there's a decent European out there, he's going in the first
round; witness Predrag Stojakovic (Sacramento) and Zydrunas
Ilgauskus (Cleveland) in 1996 and Dirk Nowitzki (Dallas), Radoslav
Nesterovic (Minnesota), Mirsad Turkcan (Houston), and Vladimir
Stepania (Seattle) last year.
</P>
<P>
   This year, there are two European-weaned centers who may go in
the first round and definitely won't be around at 55: Aleksandar
Radojevic, a possible lottery pick, and French center Frederic
Weis.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's much more emphasis on scouting in Europe,'' Wallace
said. ``Plus, there have been changes in Europe that have had a
negative impact on the sport, mainly, the conflict in Yugoslavia.
Now, guys coming over here don't have the resumes and experience
that guys like Kukoc and Radja had.''
</P>
<P>
   If Pitino bothers, he may go with someone such as Heshimu Evans,
although he never officially coached the 6-foot-6-inch Kentucky
forward. Evans transferred from Manhattan and was a redshirt in
1996-97, Pitino's last season. Another possibility is Kentucky's
Wayne Turner, a point guard who does everything but shoot. He may
be gone by 55.
</P>
<P>
   So don't cancel your plans to wait for the Celtics' pick.
Chances are you haven't heard of him and he won't be around for
long. But there's always that small glimmer of hope. Few heard of
Anderson a couple years ago, and now he's a millionaire, a regular,
and an attractive free agent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-99 1317EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
