<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-LEAD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO NEIGHBORS FIGHT AN INDUSTRY'S POLLUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORREON, Mexico _ Dolores Guillen never expected to become a
political organizer, much less lead a crusade against the world's
largest silver mining plant, which sits just a few hundred yards
from her front door.
</P>
<P>
   But her small, white-brick house in this hot and dusty northern
Mexican city has become the nerve center for one of the country's
most dramatic battles against corporate environmental pollution.
</P>
<P>
   One by one during the past year, dozens of children in Guillen's
neighborhood _ including her 6- and 13-year-old sons _ have been
found to have harmful levels of lead in their blood, mostly caused
by particles that drifted from the sprawling plant that belongs to
Met-Mex Penoles, say government and health authorities here.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just a bunch of mothers, not organizers or a political
party,'' Guillen said recently as she sifted through a stack of
papers with the names and tests of children who have been diagnosed
with lead poisoning. ``But we're fighting two big monsters _ a big
business and our government.''
</P>
<P>
   The battle between the poor residents and their industrial
neighbor has marked a shift in the way once-lax government
authorities respond to such hazards.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, state and federal environmental prosecutors ordered
the company to cut its lead emissions by half and to take
responsibility for treating all affected children and relocating
more than 400 families. Officials say it is the first time a
company has been held liable for violations that predate Mexico's
environmental laws, which went into effect in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   The smelting plant has operated here for nearly a century,
processing minerals taken from the surrounding desert, which was
once a prehistoric sea floor. With more than 2,000 workers, most of
them from Torreon, Met-Mex Penoles is one of the city's largest and
most influential employers.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, the plant sat in an isolated parcel away from the
city's main residential and business areas. But as this city 300
miles from the Texas border grew, new neighborhoods sprouted just
outside the company's walls, dangerously close to mounds of
minerals that were often left uncovered and exposed to winds that
regularly swirl down from nearby mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Longtime residents say government officials back then did not
warn them about the risks of living so close to the plant. Nor did
authorities or company officials act after a study published in
1978 showed that strands of hair from children living near the
plant had unusually high levels of lead.
</P>
<P>
   The problem was essentially ignored until late last year, when
Alonso Garcia Vargas, a toxicologist at the University of Juarez in
the neighboring state of Durango, published an updated and more
complete study.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 394 children tested at schools near the plant, 98 of them
had lead levels in their blood above 25 micrograms per deciliter.
Most US health experts say anything above 10 micrograms of lead per
deciliter of blood is unhealthy. Others argue that anything above
35 micrograms could result in damage to a child's nervous system.
And a level of 80 or higher could result in convulsions or even
death.
</P>
<P>
   Also last fall, a local pediatrician, Manuel Velasco, began
reporting cases of high lead blood levels he found in several of
his patients to state health authorities. One child had a reading
of 80 micrograms per deciliter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a silent epidemic here,'' Velasco said. ``Many of
these kids looked healthy, but they were mentally slow or had
chronic internal problems. It will take as many as 20 years for
some of these children to recover if the lead is in their bones.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the United States, which began antilead campaigns in the
1970s, Mexico only recently has confronted the threats posed by
lead in the environment. It now sells unleaded gasoline and
encourages the sale of household paints without lead.
</P>
<P>
   Out of fear that government authorities might shut them down,
company officials have publicly accepted responsibility for the two
areas most affected by the plant's emissions, and they have agreed
to spend more than $34 million for the cleanup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lead is a product we produce, and we understand that it
creates problems,'' said Luis Rey Delgado Garcia, Met-Mex Penoles's
community relations director. ``But we must also remember that
Mexico didn't have regulations on lead until very recently.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of its agreement, Met-Mex Penoles has sent platoons of
workers _ wearing face masks and protective white suits _ into
neighborhood streets and homes to sweep away and vacuum the lead
dust.
</P>
<P>
   It has set up a mobile clinic in one neighborhood to conduct
more tests and to dispense vitamins and medicines for children, and
the company is paying the bills for more than two dozen children
who have been hospitalized. It also will pay to relocate hundreds
of families and tear down their contaminated homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a Titanic task,'' said Edmundo Mesta, a company
physician who is overseeing much of the outreach and treatment
projects. ``It took the United States 30 years to bring down its
lead levels, so we cannot just do this in one day.''
</P>
<P>
   But lead may not be the plant's only problem. A Dartmouth
University study released in April found that levels of two other
toxic contaminants, arsenic and cadmium, were also alarmingly high.
All three are also suspected carcinogens.
</P>
<P>
   Yet many residents here aren't satisfied. Two dozen families
have banded together to file a lawsuit against the company, but
their case is already running into trouble in Mexico's arcane legal
system.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have more than 1,000 environmental regulations, but the
laws are deficient,'' said Paolo Solano Tovar, a Mexico City
environmental lawyer. ``Active participants can't file a suit, and
if you do file a complaint, you're not allowed to seek other
remedies. These are technical flaws that need to be changed so that
people can stand up for their rights.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
