A3193 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUN-SHOWS-ART-2TAKES-     06-29 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUN-SHOWS-ART-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT GUN SHY 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: Two photos are being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STAN GROSSFELD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are more than 4,000 gun shows held in the United States
each year, predominately in the south and west. Most of them do not
welcome photojournalists. But Florida's largest gun show, held at
the Palm Beach County's South Florida Fairgrounds earlier this
month, invited Globe associate editor Stan Grossfeld to take
photos, and talk with vendors and customers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mary Cummings, licensed gun dealer &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q: Did you ever have to use a gun?
</P>
<P>
   A: I was a victim of an armed robbery in my business just west
of Palm Beach. I have a gun store and I was sitting in the store
with an off duty Palm Beach county sheriff's deputy. Two white
17-year-olds walked in the door. I was behind the counter and I had
the off-duty police officer sitting in front of me. They walked up
and put a gun to my head, one jumped the counter and they started
stealing guns.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing that ran through my mind was very simple: they
were not wearing masks, they made no attempt to cover their
identity, they were actually calling each other by their right
names _ there was no doubt in my mind that they had full intentions
of killing me.
</P>
<P>
   One went to leave, and the other one's in the back of the store
holding the gun on myself and the police officer. I reached over to
hit the panic button; I have a wireless remote that goes to the
police department . . . I turned around and this guy's got the
trigger just about half way pulled on the police officer. He had
full intentions of shooting the cop in the back of the head.
</P>
<P>
   I carry my own gun, a .38 revolver, on my side. And he didn't
happen to see it, and I was able to get the draw on him and I shot
him. I fired one round and it hit him. The bullet _ one in a
million odds _ passed through both main arteries of his heart and
he lived to tell about it.
</P>
<P>
   The sad thing was what happened afterwards; it took me a year
and a half of fighting, ranting, raving, and screaming bloody
murder to get this state to prosecute him.
</P>
<P>
   The one I shot was a straight A student. My own personal feeling
was that it was a gang initiation. They both came from two-parent
homes. Upper middle class. This was Ozzie and Harriet land. White
America.
</P>
<P>
   They tried to say he had a split personality. He thought he was
John Travolta from Pulp Fiction. They tried everything.
</P>
<P>
   They were sentenced to four years in the state pen and two years
probation. Of course, one of them only did a year and he's out. The
one that I shot is still in, 'til 2001. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q: Arent you worried about possible retribution?
</P>
<P>
   A: Every day of my life. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q: What do you do about it?
</P>
<P>
   A: Got a larger caliber gun. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q: How did it feel to pull the trigger?
</P>
<P>
   A: If it was me or some punk kid, sorry, kid loses. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q: Where did they get the gun used in the robbery?
</P>
<P>
   A: From the father, left it laying around the house. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q: How do you keep kids from playing with guns?
</P>
<P>
   A: That's the responsibility of parents. You don't go around
leaving Clorox and chemicals around the house, so why do it with
guns? Keep guns secure. Instead of a gun lock and hiding it and
saying don't touch it, try explaining that its not like you see on
TV where the bad guy gets shot and he's back next week. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q: Is there a way to stop straw sales (in which someone buys a gun
for another person)? &QL; 
 &QL; 
A: There's no way for a dealer to know (if someone is buying a gun
for someone else.) (And) if a suspect tries, and you refuse it, and
you stop it, the ATF does not enforce it . . .
</P>
<P>
   Go back and ask the government how many times they've prosecuted
people who've lied on this form (about who the gun was for). And
the answer is zero. Instead of making new laws, they need to
enforce the ones they got. &QL; 
 &QL; 
-------------------------------------------------------------- &QC; 
 &QL; 
Bill Page, a promoter known as the P.T. Barnum of gun shows. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q: What effect did the shootings in Littleton, Colorado have on
your gun show?
</P>
<P>
   A: Littleton? That tragedy out there hasn't really had anything
to do with our shows here in Florida. The Y2K thing, more people
are concerned about that. I think this Y2K scare has got everyone
crazy now. We have people spending alot of money. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q: There's a statistic that Clinton recently cited that at 46
percent of gun shows there's a convicted felon either buying or
selling guns. How do you feel about that?
</P>
<P>
   A: Less than 2 percent of guns used in crimes comes from gun
shows; that leaves 98 percent that comes from someplace else. We
have ATF (Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms Bureau) come around
checking and they found nothing wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The NRA is not the bad guys you think of. They are the backbone
of this country. They are the working middle and upper class of
this country.
</P>
<P>
   Look beyond the NRA. Crime is down in this country. The
president wants to take credit for it. We look at new statistics
that are coming out about concealed weapons permits; where states
have concealed weapons permits, crime is down. Because now we have
criminals who are afraid.
</P>
<P>
   We have another problem with children getting a hold of parents
guns when they go out. That's a major problem they want to put
locks on everything. Well 80 percent of the industry in handguns
(already) sends gunlocks on their guns when they're sent. So we're
already policing ourselves. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q: Why do you allow people with concealed gun permits to purchase
guns immediately?
</P>
<P>
   A: A concealed weapons permit allows you to buy firearms right
then and there because you've been thoroughly checked out,
fingerprints are on file. It's only good people. &QL; 
 &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
