<HEADLINE>
REAL QUIET BACK ON TRACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Imagine. A horse who wasn't good enough to win the Massachusetts
Handicap at Suffolk Downs won the $1 million Hollywood Gold Cup
Sunday. Has Suffolk become the hub of the racing universe?
</P>
<P>
   Well, not exactly. But it is true that Real Quiet, who finished
third as the 4-5 favorite behind Behrens and Running Stag in the
$600,000 MassCap, redeemed himself with an impressive score in the
Gold Cup. Real Quiet, who won the Kentucky Derby and Preakness last
year, received two big breaks in the Gold Cup. First, Old Trieste,
a potential monster who would have been favored, was scratched,
suffering from an abscessed foot. Second, Real Quiet, who was boxed
in around the turn and into the stretch, got running room late
along the rail.
</P>
<P>
   Jockeys will tell you that small fields can produce the toughest
trips because riders have the luxury of clocking all their
opponents. There were only four starters in the Gold Cup, and, sure
enough, Real Quiet was trapped in last behind dueling front-runners
Budroyale and Malek, and stalking Puerto Madero. Past the 16th-pole
Malek came out just enough to let Real Quiet loose, and he tallied
by a half-length at 9-10 ($3.80) in 1:59 3/5 for the 1 1/4 miles.
Budroyale, Malek, and Puerto Madero followed, in that order.
</P>
<P>
   ``I left myself with three options,'' said Bailey, who rode Real
Quiet. ``Go out, go in, go in between if the horses kind of split
on me. I think I prepared myself well, but you always have to have
some luck and a good horse.'' It was the second straight Gold Cup
victory for Bailey, who rode Skip Away last year, and fourth in the
last eight years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if my horse even saw Real Quiet,'' said Ted West,
who trains Budroyale, the longshot at 7-1. ``I was hoping they
wouldn't let him through, but Bailey found a way through there
somehow.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Baffert, trainer of Real Quiet, had a terrific weekend,
winning several major races at tracks around the country. The
``Silver Fox,'' who lost some luster with a bad Triple Crown season
and Real Quiet's flop in the MassCap, does not stay down for long.
Real Quiet did not like the deep, sandy track at Suffolk. A deep
track was the least of his worries at Hollywood, and, it turns out,
the 1 1/8 miles in the MassCap may have been too short for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he runs a mile and one-quarter, that's his distance,''
said Baffert. ``Any shorter, and he's going to have his little
problems. That's why he's not a win machine (20-6-5-6).''
</P>
<P>
   The victory moved Real Quiet into second place in the NTRA
Champions series with 22 points, behind Behrens, who has 28. Next
for Behrens is the Suburban at Belmont July 5. Real Quiet may go in
the Whitney at Saratoga Aug. 1, both series races. The decisive
meeting should come in the $1 million Pacific Classic at Del Mar
Aug. 29, the final race in the series and the event that decides
the bonus awards.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sweet 16 at Rock
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's $75,000 Rockingham Breeders' Cup has drawn 16
nominations, and the highweight, Mysterious Moll at 119 pounds, is
scheduled to compete.
</P>
<P>
   The contest, for fillies and mares at a mile and one-16th on the
turf, may also attract Cozy Blues, the second weight at 117, and
the top two turf mares based in New England, Nana's Toy and Sandy
Gator, both weighted at 115.
</P>
<P>
   A 4-year-old daughter of Bates Motel, Mysterious Moll is trained
by Del Caroll, and will be shipped in from New York to stay in the
barn of top local trainer John Botty. Sporting a lifetime record of
17-5-2-4, Mysterious Moll was most recently third to Cozy Blues in
the Just A Game Handicap at Belmont June 9.
</P>
<P>
   Cozy Blues, a 5-year-old daughter of Cure the Blues, is trained
by H. James Bond, who conditions Behrens. Bond is stabled at
Saratoga and likes to race at the New England tracks. Last year,
Bond took both the Rock Breeders' Cup and the Spicy Living with
Innovate. Cozy Blues has a lifetime record of 22-5-4-3, and
captured the Just A Game with a late charge from off the pace. The
field for the Rock Breeders' Cup will be drawn Friday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wonderland sets dates
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wonderland Park released its stakes schedule Monday, and the
$100,000 Wonderland Derby is set for Aug. 14. Derby trials will be
held July 26, July 31, Aug. 5, and Aug. 9. This will be the 65th
annual running of the Derby, contested over the 2,045 feet of the
Revere Course, with $60,000 going to the connections of the
greyhound who wins the final. The Grady Memorial Sprint, the other
major contest on the Wonderland slate, has been moved from June to
Oct. 9. Prelims for the 22d annual Grady, raced at the
five-16ths-of-a-mile sprint distance, will be conducted Sept. 20,
25, 30, and Oct. 4. The Grady carried a $75,000 purse last year,
but the purse for this year has yet to be determined. ``There was
kennel sickness around the country from late winter through the
spring,'' said Wonderland assistant general manager Ron Wohlen.
``We felt if we ran it in June, it would be too early, and then it
would back into the Derby. The next best route was to put it in the
fall and run it on Columbus Day weekend. We've had it in the fall
in the past.'' . . . One of Baffert's other big weekend scores came
when General Challenge took the $125,000 Affirmed Handicap at
Hollwood Park Saturday. As coupled in an entry with the filly
Excellent Meeting, General Challenge was the 9-2 Kentucky Derby
favorite, but he was crushed during the running and finished 11th.
The fact that he won his return engagement is a sign that he's
recovered from his unpleasant Derby experience. General Challenge,
who was ridden by David Flores, doffed the blinkers he had been
wearing, and came on from the back of a five-horse field to tally
by 2 lengths, defeating two nice foes, Desert Hero and Crowning
Storm.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
