<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-BOOKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACK TO PROVENCE? WHY NOT? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He's back.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Mayle has returned to his haven for grand times, good
food, and unforgettable characters. ``Encore Provence: New
Adventures in the South of France'' (Knopf, $23) is his sequel to
``Tojours Provence,'' which was the sequel to the book that started
it all, ``A Year in Provence.''
</P>
<P>
   ``With rose colored hindsight,'' he writes, ``the good times
become magical; the bad times fade and eventually disappear,
leaving only a seductive blur of sunlit days and the laughter of
friends. Was it really like that? Would it be like that again?
</P>
<P>
   ``There was, of course, only one way to find out.''
</P>
<P>
   So Mayle, a former ad executive, goes back to Provence after a
four-year absence to find . . . a gardener who grows black
tomatoes, an oversexed butcher with a secret, a perfume creator
with a highly educated nose, and plenty of other other Gallic
types, described with a mix of wit and respect. You'd expect food
to play a big part in this book, as it did in the others, and you'd
be right. From a memorable meal in a former gas station to a taste
of the best bouillabaisse to trips to the colorful weekly markets,
Mayle and the reader are in gastronomic heaven.
</P>
<P>
   So was it all he had hoped for, or had Provence changed 11 years
after his first book about the region? Let Mayle answer: ``Provence
is still beautiful. Vast areas of it are still wild and empty.
Peace and silence . . . are still available. The old men still play
their endless game of boules. The markets are as colorful and
abundant as ever. There is room to breathe, and the air is clean.''
</P>
<P>
   Most readers of ``Encore Provence,'' I suspect, will share his
delight.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mention movement by black people and many think of this
century's great migration from South to North or the last century's
forced migration from Africa to slaveholding states. But
African-Americans have traveled for other reasons, too _ adventure,
insight, and just pleasure _ and written about their experiences.
James Baldwin, for instance, went to Paris, and Langston Hughes
visited Mexico. ``A Stranger in the Village: Two Centuries of
African-American Travel Writing'' (Beacon Press, $25) is two
centuries worth of memoirs, book and diary excerpts, letters, and
lectures that show the breadth of such travel. A 19th-century
sailor tells about his trips to ``the ends of the world.'' A woman
``doctress'' describes the Panamanian frontier. Claude McKay shares
his observations on the newly formed Soviet Union. And, from
Nicaragua, Ntozake Shange ruminates on how Motown overcomes the
barriers of language and custom.
</P>
<P>
   In all there are nearly 50 pieces. Editors are Farah Jasmine
Griffith and Cheryl Fish, both English professors.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I've never considered Vermont a scary state. But ``Green
Mountains, Dark Tales'' by Joseph A. Citro (University Press of New
England, $19.95) shows that the state can serve up chills as well
as cheer. Citro turns up a stone-flinging poltergeist in Pownall, a
gallery of ghosts at Southern Vermont College, and cites the
historic Equinox in Vermont as the state's most haunted hotel.
There are more than 30 tales of the living and the dead from this
specialist on the occult in New England.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Guidebooks
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With their shiny silver covers and plethora of color photos, the
Knopf City Guides are decidely distinctive. The books offer
suggestions about where to go and what to do in nine major cities.
The Rome guide, for instance, tells 53 things you need to know,
giving information about 64 hotels, 92 restaurants, 38 nights out,
99 sights, 17 excursions, and 79 shops. Ten maps help you get to
those places. Other books in the series, to date, are Berlin,
Lisbon, London, Madrid, Milan, New York, Paris, and Rio de Janeiro.
The guides are $14.95 each.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Summer is a wonderful time for roaming New England. Accordingly,
the Countryman Press has published a second edition of ``Walks and
Rambles on Cape Cod and the Islands: A Nature Lover's Guide to 35
Trails'' ($14) by Ned Friary and Glenda Bendure, and a third
edition of ``Walks and Rambles in Rhode Island: 40 Trails for
Birders and Nature Lovers ($15.95) by Ken Weber. Both books have
the requisite maps, descriptions, and photos. Happy rambling.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And speaking of getting around, it never hurts to have a good,
up-to-date map to help you find where you're going in metropolitan
Boston. The spiral-bound ``Official Arrow Pocket Atlas: Metro
Boston'' (Langenscheidt Publishing, $9.95) offers large-scale,
color-shaded maps, with a list of places of interest and shopping
centers (they're not necessarily the same thing) for Boston and
nearly 30 nearby communities. There's also a Route 128 map.
</P>
<P>
   And if you're looking for full-size maps covering the entire
state, the Maine-based DeLorme mapping company has added the
``Massachusetts Atlas and Gazeteer'' ($16.95) to a series that now
covers all 50 states. In addition to routes, you'll find
information on historic sites, scenic drives, and camping, hunting,
and fishing sites.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Unless otherwise noted, guidebooks are paperbacks.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
