<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-CAROUSELS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTIQUE CAROUSELS ABOUND IN NEW ENGLAND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NATHAN COBB  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once upon a time in pre-PlayStation America, there were
thousands of wooden carousels. And there wasn't anything virtual
about their reality, which consisted of brightly painted animals,
gleaming brass poles, and lazy Sunday afternoons at the amusement
park.
</P>
<P>
   Today, fewer than 200 antique woodies remain in the nation, many
in various states of disrepair. But since the 1960s, carousels have
come to be viewed by many as true slices of Americana worthy of
preservation and restoration. A census published last year by the
National Carousel Association found there are seven old wooden
merry-go-rounds in Massachusetts that are open to the public. As
summer began this week, we climbed aboard three of them.
</P>
<P>
   The Paragon Carousel, 205 Nantasket Ave., Hull. 781-925-0472.
Open 10 a.m.-10 p.m. daily through Labor Day. $1.50 per ride.
</P>
<P>
   It's a cloudy weekday morning at Nantasket Beach, &UR;  &LR; just outside
of Boston, and only a few folks _ mostly mothers with small
children in tow, or is it the other way around? _ have shown up to
climb aboard the Paragon Carousel. James Hardwin, the
merry-go-round's restorer and sole full-time employee, is
undaunted. ``It's like `Field of Dreams,' '' he says. ``You open
the door and they do come.''
</P>
<P>
   Nineteen-year-old operator Matt Riccio clangs the carousel's
brass bell four times and sets the four-row behemoth in motion with
a slow pull on the vintage Western Electric trolley switch. The 66
hand-carved wooden horses and two Roman chariots begin their
three-minute sprint beneath 951 glittering white lights. ``I've
changed 'em all,'' Hardwin muses, looking up.
</P>
<P>
   Built in 1928 by the Philadelphia Toboggan Company (PTC), the
carousel spent most of its life only half a block away, at Paragon
Park, which closed in 1985. It is owned by The Friends of the
Paragon Carousel, whose 700 members are trying to preserve what
president Susan Fleck calls ``both an art treasure and an emotional
treasure.'' The task hasn't been easy. Fleck, a Hull native who
rode the carousel as a child, says the group recently restructured
its debt in order to ease its monetary pain.
</P>
<P>
   Despite being a work in progress _ 27 of the 66 horses have been
restored so far, and the 1920s Wurlitzer band organ is disconnected
_ the Paragon Carousel attracts about 100,000 riders per year,
according to Fleck. On this particular morning, one of them, a
small boy, is reluctant to leave and is tearfully clinging to his
brightly painted horse despite his mother's best efforts to pry him
loose. Watching, Hardwin smiles. ``Another satisfied customer,'' he
announces.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Fall River Carousel, 1 Central St. (Battleship Cove), Fall
River. 508-324-4300. Open 10 a.m.-6 p.m. daily, through Labor Day;
noon to 4 p.m. weekends only, Sept. 11 through Oct. 31. $1 per
ride.
</P>
<P>
   School groups bound up the rubber-clad staircase of Fall River's
ersatz Victorian carousel pavilion, but not everyone who comes here
is fresh from touring the USS Massachusetts next door. Last summer,
an elderly visitor stood on the sidelines, weeping. ``It was her
50th wedding anniversary,'' recalls co-manager Charlene Conway.
``She was remembering how her husband had proposed to her on one of
our chariots.''
</P>
<P>
   That would have been when this spectacular 48-horse carousel,
built by PTC in 1920, was the heartbeat of Lincoln Amusement Park
in North Dartmouth. Purchased at auction for $693,000 when the park
closed for good in 1986, the merry-go-round was meticulously
restored in Ohio before settling into the Fall River waterfront.
Like the Paragon Carousel, however, it has suffered financially.
Estimates that it would draw as many as 300,000 annual riders
proved optimistic. Today it is owned by the Fall River Development
Corp. and leased by Conway and her husband, Bob. Charlene Conway
says the carousel drew about 80,000 customers last year.
</P>
<P>
   Still, old amusement park rides don't get much more pristine
than this one. With even its massive center pole and heavy gears
part of its total restoration (although it does feature a new
electronic control system), the carousel gleams brightly in colors
that duplicate the originals. An antique band organ provides the
soundtrack, and the school kids climb atop palominos and dapples
that look like they just arrived from the factory. ``I rode on this
30 years ago,'' Charlene Conway says, ``and it never looked this
good.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Holyoke Merry-Go-Round, 221 Appleton St. (Heritage State
Park), Holyoke. 413-538-9838. Open 10:30 a.m.-4:30 p.m., Tuesdays
through Sundays, July 4 weekend through Labor Day. $1 per ride.
</P>
<P>
   All's quiet inside the yellow clapboard pavilion that houses the
Holyoke Merry-Go-Round. The colorful 14-ton unit operates only on
weekends until July 4, so weekday visitors must temporarily press
their faces to the windows. This downtime allows 23-year-old
operator Jason Charpentier an opportunity to explain the details of
the merry-go-round _ folks in Holyoke always call it a
merry-go-round, not a carousel _ to a visitor. He even has speed
figures: ``It travels 8.4 miles per hour on the outside, 4.7 on the
inside,'' he explains.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another carousel from PTC, this one was built in 1927. It
ran at Holyoke's Mountain Park until the trolley park, which opened
in 1895, closed 12 years ago. After the kind of fund-raising effort
that warms a community's heart _ kids selling cookies here, postal
employees running a bottle drive there _ the merry-go-round was
purchased for $850,000 by a local group known as the Friends of the
Holyoke Merry-Go-Round.
</P>
<P>
   It now draws 50,000 to 60,000 riders a year to 8.5-acre Heritage
Park in downtown Holyoke, which features another attraction you
don't encounter every day: the Volleyball Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   As is the case with the Paragon Carousel, the merry-go-round is
still being refurbished, in large part by local volunteers. It's no
small job bringing 56 scenic panels, 98 beveled mirrors, and one
very loud Artizan band organ back to life. And, of course, there
are the 48 prancing horses, many of which have yet to be restored
for the Playstation set. Says Charpentier: ``Kids come in here, and
they can't believe they're made of wood.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Other antique wooden carousels in Massachusetts are at Riverside
Park in Agawam (413-786-9300), Whalom Park in Lunenburg
(978-342-3707), Heritage Plantation in Sandwich (508-888-3300), and
the town of Oak Bluffs on Martha's Vineyard (508-693-9481 or
508-627-4440).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
