<HEADLINE>
200 ACTIVITIES IN BOSTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you haven't made plans for July 4, there's no better place
than Boston for one of the biggest and best celebrations anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Surrounding the July 4 festivities along the Charles River on
the Esplanade, where the Boston Pops will perform free before at
least 250,000, is the 18th annual Boston Harborfest. Harborfest
runs June 29 to July 5 and features more than 200 events including
a Chowderfest, children's day, walking tours, concerts,
Revolutionary Era historical reenactments, visits from US and
foreign naval ships and more. Thirty-five percent of the events are
free and the rest cost between $1 and $10. A new tradition will be
a Sunset Parade adjacent to the USS Constitution where a fife and
drum band and the US Navy Band will perform during the lowering of
the flag.
</P>
<P>
   For complete details on events, call 617-227-1528 or visit
www.bostonharborfest.com. General information on the city is
available by calling 888-BOSTON or by visiting www.bostonusa.com.
For the last 12 years, Harborfest has been named one of the Top 100
Events in North America by the American Bus Association.
</P>
<P>
   One Harborfest treat is the opportunity to experience history.
At the Old North Church (``one if by sea, two if by land'') you can
hear Paul Revere tell his story of the Revolution ($12 adult, $8
children) and also go behind the scenes of this famous church,
viewing the crypt and touring the famed bell tower ($8 adult, $6
children). For times and reservations, call 617-523-4848.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, there's nothing like joining the Pops on the
Esplanade for the July 4 concert, which this year features not only
Keith Lockhart conducting but the ``1812 Overture'' with the Boston
Symphony's Seiji Ozawa conducting. It's a grand salute to the
nation's birthday, complete with canons firing, church bells
ringing, and a massive fireworks display.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Film festival
</P>
<P>
   The second annual Maine International Film Festival, July 9-18,
will be held in Waterville, Maine, featuring more than 100 showings
of 40 films by top independent producers. The 22d Maine Student
Film and Video Festival will be held in conjunction with the film
festival. Filmmakers, screenwriters, and special guests will be on
hand at the screenings. For more information on the festivals, call
207-861-8138 or visit www.mint.net/movies/miff. For tickets, which
range from $7 for an individual ticket to $125 for a full festival
pass, call the Waterville Opera House box office at 207-873-7000.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Maritime Trail
</P>
<P>
   ``Boston by Sea: The Maritime Trail'' is a new free tour being
offered by the Boston History Collaborative. The 45-minute walking
tours Sunday through Wednesday will focus on topics ranging from
the role of codfish in Boston to historic events including the
American Revolution, the China trade, and the city's early role in
the slave trade and later in the Underground Railroad. Condensed
tours will be offered evenings Tuesdays and Wednesdays beginning
July 6. Tours leave from the Marriott Custom House and Legal Sea
Foods at Long Wharf at 1:30 p.m., and the evening tours begin at 7.
Tickets are free but reservations are a must. Call 617-574-5950 or
visit www.BostonBySea.org.
</P>
<P>
