<HEADLINE>
COAST, COUNTRY AND CHARM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's an area of some 150 square miles, embracing 33 communities
in southeastern Connecticut and coastal Rhode Island. And its
attractions include everything from 18th-century villages to
21st-century slot machines.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to Mystic Coast &AMP; Country, one of the most diverse and
delightful areas in the nation. As Donna M. Simpson, Mystic Coast &AMP;
Country executive director, put it in a telephone interview:
``There's so much to take in.'' So there is, and a lot of it has
undergone major improvements. Among attractions:
</P>
<P>
   --Mystic Seaport. The 19th century returns in this Mystic,
Conn., maritime museum, filled with ships and shops and sailors
singing chanteys. The Charles W. Morgan is a favorite ship to
visit. And a special project now underway is the construction of
the 129-foot schooner Amistad, using 19th-century techniques. An
exhibit nearby includes objects used in the Steven Spielberg film
``Amistad.''
</P>
<P>
   --Mystic Aquarium. Having undergone a $52 million expansion,
this impressive aquarium features 24 exhibits showcasing 6,000
specimens. More programs for youngsters have been added, and this
year there will be two major new exhibits. The Institute for
Exploration, headed by Robert Ballard, will zero in on deep-sea
exploration, including the ocean floor, which Simpson calls ``the
only uncharted territory we know of.'' The other will be an
outdoor, one-acre Alaskan Coast exhibit.
</P>
<P>
   --Foxwoods Resort Casino. This gambling and entertainment haven
in Ledyard, Conn., has doubled the size of its already huge casino
and added an 800-room tower, along with several upscale touches.
There are more than 5,500 slot machines and 370 table games. About
a mile away, the tribe that brought you the casino also brings you
the Mashantucket Pequot Museum &AMP; Research Center, a new, high-tech,
$193 million museum that takes visitors on a 20,000-year journey
through time, featuring sights, sounds, and smells that bring the
tribe's history to life.
</P>
<P>
   --Historic Ship Nautilus/Submarine Force Museum. Only in Groton,
Conn., can you tour the world's first nuclear submarine. Museum
exhibits, meanwhile, include a sub control room, operating
periscopes, and historical displays. A $4 million expansion is
scheduled to be completed this summer.
</P>
<P>
   There's much more: the Gillette Castle, the Essex Steam Train
and Riverboat Ride, the Mohegan Sun casino, the Mystic Factory
Outlets, the Stonington Vineyards, the pleasant beaches of Rhode
Island, good restaurants, fine theater, crafts, galleries, lots of
lodgings, and a raft of other attractions, most of them suitable
for all the family.
</P>
<P>
   And, as Simpson says, there are quaint communities with
white-frame churches, village greens, tumbling stone walls,
gardens, downtown shops, and historic homes, all of which give the
area its charm and character. Mystic Coast &AMP; Country, says Simpson,
``gives us a feeling of what we were and are in history.'' May the
new and the old always stay in proper balance.
</P>
<P>
   (For more information and a free copy of the Mystic Coast &AMP;
Country Vacation Planner, a special value Coast Card, and the new
Kids' Guide, call 800-MY-COAST. For an overview, visit
www.mycoast.com.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
And speaking of Mystic: We learn from the Mystic Aquarium that if
all the earth's oceans were to dry up, the leftover salt would
weigh 100 sextillion pounds. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Travel Trivia: You're standing next to Fred, who annoys you. So you
want to travel as far away from him as is possible. How many miles
away will you be when you reach your destination? (Answer at end of
column.)
</P>
<P>
   In a name: One of Britain's Channel Islands, Jersey, calls
itself ``The Cream of Holidays.'' (To see how rich that cream is,
call 800-617-3333 for a free set of Channel Islands guidebooks. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Today's loopy law: It's illegal to take a lion to the movies in
Baltimore. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Fascinating fact: The Hawaiian alphabet has a mere 12 letters: the
vowels a, e, i, o, u and the consonants h, k, l, m, n, p, and w.
(We thank Sal Chancholo of Medford.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Don't get sore: Dairl Johnson was a Navy fighter pilot who injured
his back in a training accident in an F-4 Phantom fighter jet. Now
he's CEO of Relax the Back, a company that, among other items,
sells travel products such as a self-inflating lower back support,
an inflatable U-shaped travel neck rest for sleeping on planes, a
compact massage unit, a travel-size support pillow, back support
belts, and an S-shaped ``back nobbler'' for reaching sore spots.
For a catalog, call 800-290-BACK. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Leave nothing: A Taiwan company makes dinnerware out of wheat, so
you can eat your plate. (With thanks to faithful contributor Mike
Schuster of Foxborough.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Ducky doings: One day, we hope soon, a new museum will rise in the
heart of Pennsylvania Dutch Country, devoted solely to Walt
Disney's famous fowl, Donald Fauntleroy Duck. Curator will be
Melissa Bernhart of Reading, Pa., who says the impact of Donald on
American culture cannot be underestimated. She herself has more
than 5,000 duck items to display, ranging from splendid statues to
collectible coffee cans. While you're waiting for the museum to
open, though, why not join her fan club, which publishes a
newsletter about the life and times of that mighty duck. For more
information, write to Donald Duck Fan Club, PO Box 13972, Reading,
PA 19612, call 610-396-9872, or e-mail
outerstationproj(at)juno.com. (Here's the legal stuff: The club is
in no way associated with the Walt Disney Co., which owns the
priceless copyright on Donald Duck.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Did you guess it? You will be 7,926 miles (the earth's diameter)
away.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send comments and questions to Travel Tidbits, Boston Globe,
Boston, MA 02107. Send e-mail to carpen(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
