<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3207 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-CAPETOWN-BOS &LR;      06-29 1116
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-CAPETOWN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WORLD IN ONE CITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINE TEMIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE TOWN _ It was my travel security blanket, a Liberty peacock
print shawl that I took everywhere, even wrapping myself in it to
sleep on planes. I lost it somewhere during a peripatetic evening
that started with drinks in the library at the Cape Grace Hotel,
then a drive to a nearby restaurant. During dinner, I noticed the
shawl was gone, and wrote it off as a sad loss. When I got back to
my room in the hotel, there it was, neatly folded at the foot of
the bed, thanks to some observant Cape Grace staff member.
</P>
<P>
   Much of what you hear about South Africa focuses on the alarming
crime rate, which recently forced Anne Paton, widow of Alan Paton,
who wrote ``Cry The Beloved Country,'' to announce that she was
moving to England because she couldn't handle being mugged and
hijacked any more. The crime is certainly there, although in two
lengthy visits to the country I've neither seen nor experienced
any. But there is also kindness, hospitality, and a desire to join
the community of nations after being cut off by apartheid for so
long.
</P>
<P>
   The strong desire to attract foreign tourists translates into
some superb places to stay, the Cape Grace being a case in point.
Opened in 1996, it is giving Cape Town's most renowned hotel, the
100-year- old Mount Nelson, a run for its money. The food at the
Cape Grace is sublime, the rooms luxuriously appointed in British
Colonial style. Lots of hotels have ``libraries'' that are actually
bars, but the Cape Grace's, in addition to being a civilized
setting for drinks, really is a library, extremely well-stocked
with books, many about South Africa. My favorite detail about this
hotel that gets the details right: Should you be mid-book when you
check out, you may take the tome with you, returning it in the
self-addressed mailer the hotel provides.
</P>
<P>
   The Cape Grace is on the Victoria &AMP; Alfred Waterfront, a great
shopping area boasting a huge South African craft market and a
world-class wine emporium, the Vaughan Johnson Wine Shop, which
specializes, naturally, in South Africa's stellar vintages. (They
ship.)
</P>
<P>
   The waterfront is also the point of embarkation for the short
boat ride to Robben Island, site of one of the world's most
notorious prisons, whose most famous occupant was Nelson Mandela.
The spartan buildings where prisoners once performed hard labor are
now a museum, as sobering in its way as Israel's Yad Vashem
memorial to the Holocaust or Senegal's Goree Island, the point from
which slaves were shipped to the New World. It was startling to
learn that my eloquent guide on Robben Island had been a prisoner
there from age 18-30, and, having missed out on formal higher
education, was a total autodidact. It was also startling to learn
that he was unpaid for his work as a guide: So strongly does he
feel about getting his message of forgiveness across that he works
for free. Sadly, his volunteer status may also be a result of South
Africa's high unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   South Africa's tourism slogan _ ``A World in One Country'' _
could be adapted to ``A World in One City'' and applied to Cape
Town. I spent an entire week at the Cape Grace, and felt I'd barely
begun to explore Cape Town and its environs. I visited the
historic, white-washed manor houses and vineyards a short drive
from the city, including Spier, Vergelegen, and Groot Constantia,
where the Dutch-influenced architecture suggests Amsterdam South. I
made the half-hour drive to the Grande Roche, which many consider
the finest hotel and the finest restaurant in all South Africa, a
circa 1700 wine estate with exquisite decor, its own tiny chapel
for weddings, and fabulous French food you can eat indoors or on a
terrace with lovely views.
</P>
<P>
   I made the obligatory pilgrimages to Table Mountain; to
Kirstenbosch, one of the world's greatest gardens; and out to the
wine routes, where you could spend forever visiting wineries that
vary from family-owned boutiques to high-tech, grand-scale
operations.
</P>
<P>
   These are the obvious stops. But there are unexpected gems: the
Jean Craig Pottery, for instance, near Stellenbosch, where ceramics
based on Xhosa, Zulu and Ndebele motifs can be had for about $3 per
pot. So chic have the bold geometric designs of the Ndebele become
of late that British Airways has commissioned twin Ndebele sisters,
Emmly and Martha Masanabo, to design patterns to emblazon on the
tails of BA jumbo jets.
</P>
<P>
   The South African art scene is as volatile as the rest of the
society, and ranges from the haunting wattle bark figurative
sculpture of a recluse named Jacques Dohnt to the stinging
political animation of William Kentridge, the most high-profile
South African artist on the international scene. Significantly, the
National Gallery in Cape Town puts contemporary South African art
front and center _ and relegates its 18th- and 19th-century
European canvases to galleries in the rear.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Driving East from Cape Town, I saw few flowers on the ``Garden
Route,'' which, in November, looked more like the bleakly beautiful
Yorkshire moors. But once I stopped in Plettenberg Bay, in the
heart of the Route, I found a new Eden. The gorgeous Plettenberg
Hotel, where I stayed, is filled with, and surrounded by, flowers.
Across the street, in someone's front yard, is an all-white ``moon
garden,'' starring Queen Anne's lace and white roses, with an array
of small white annuals in supporting roles. Just up the hill is a
reminder of South Africa's uneasy present _ St. Peter's Anglican
Church, an exquisite little stone chapel set in a garden abloom
with hibiscus, daisies, and agapanthus, the beds and borders in a
framework of stone arches and trellises. The wrought iron gates to
the church are locked, though, and a sad sign announces why. ``From
the year 1881, when this church was opened, until July of this year
(1998), the church has been kept open every day. However, following
a number of recent acts of theft and vandalism we have reluctantly
decided to keep the church closed.''
</P>
<P>
   My favorite Garden Route activity was also my riskiest moment in
South Africa _ and it had nothing to do with crime. Hiking with my
20-year-old son in the Robberg Nature and Marine Reserve, we opted
for the nine-kilometer (5 1/2-mile) trail, the longest of the three
suggested, without reading the fine print about ``high cliffs and
difficult rocky terrain dangerous to inexperienced hikers'' along
with ``freak waves and strong currents.'' Good thing Jon was
willing to slow down and drag his mother over those looming wet
rocks.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
