<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 13:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3209 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-CAPETOWN-2ND &LR;  &UR;      06-29 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-CAPETOWN-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 CAPE TOWN: ... wet rocks.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don't skip Durban. There are more obvious South African
destinations for tourists. You have to do Cape Town, one of the
world's most beautiful cities. You have to do Johannesburg, not
beautiful at all but valuable for experiences including Soweto, a
sprawling world unto itself. You have to do a game reserve, for a
wildlife experience unequaled anywhere else in Africa. (South
Africa offers more off-road and night game drives than you'll find
in East Africa, and you ride in open Land Rovers, as opposed to the
pop-top vehicles of other African safari experiences.)
</P>
<P>
   Durban is the most tropical city in South Africa, and its
beaches on the Indian Ocean make it a fun-in-the-sun place. But
it's much more. Its Indian population of 500,000 _ Indians first
came as indentured servants in the 19th century _ adds cultural
richness. Durban has many Indian restaurants _ I had a superb lunch
at the opulent Jaipur Palace, on a hill overlooking the city _ and
at the Victoria Street Market you can buy Indian brass, pottery,
and custom-mixed spices with names like ``delayed reaction,'' as
well as African crafts. You can even ride in a rickshaw: There are
about 20 licensed ones.
</P>
<P>
   The Botanic Gardens boast a splendid array of rare cycads; while
visiting the gardens, you pay an official ``car guard'' one or two
rand _ the current exchange is 16(CT) to a rand _ to protect your
car. Tourism Durban started the idea, to cut unemployment as well
as crime.
</P>
<P>
   Durban is also a cultural hub. I spent a happy afternoon
exploring the BAT Centre, a lively, four-year-old harborside
complex that supports local artists, writers, and musicians. Here
you'll find concerts, galleries, studios, and the Zansi Restaurant,
serving African food. The BAT Shop and the Bayside Gallery, both
part of the center, offer an excellent selection of indigenous arts
and crafts.
</P>
<P>
   If Durban's baroque City Hall looks slightly out of place in
Africa, it's because the design is recycled: It's precisely the
same plan used for the City Hall in Belfast. Durban's 1892 Old
Station Building is another architectural oddity: Its roof can
support 16 feet of snow. The London architects mistakenly sent
Toronto's station plan to Durban, and vice versa. Toronto's roof,
unable to support any snow at all, collapsed during its first
winter.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Johannesburg is a problem for tourists. You could almost skip
it, were it not so essential for taking the country's pulse. The
mere sight of the Carlton Hotel downtown is scary. A high-rise,
once the city's most elegant hostelrey, it is now closed because of
crime in the vicinity, its stairwells and elevators cemented so
squatters can't get to the upper floors.
</P>
<P>
   Like the city's posh art galleries and boutiques, its finest new
hotel, The Westcliff, is in the suburbs. A cascading series of
villas built into a hillside, like a Mediterranean village, The
Westcliff is secure and secluded and boasts a commanding view of
elephants in the Zoological Gardens below. The lavish rooms have
been decorated by South Africa's most famous interior designer,
Graham Viney.
</P>
<P>
   As for what to do in Johannesburg, don't miss the Market Theatre
complex downtown: It includes a theater, adventurous contemporary
art gallery, bars, and a fabulous, funky restaurant, Gramadoelas,
specializing in tribal African and Malaysian cuisine. Here you can
feast on crocodile and mopani worms.
</P>
<P>
   Soweto is definitely worth visiting, and there are now many
organized tours that are perfectly safe ways to see this sprawling
city of all economic levels, with its houses where celebrities
including Nelson and Winnie Mandela and Bishop Desmond Tutu either
once lived or still do. Containers donated by trucking firms have
been converted into art galleries here; in one, I saw photographs
of the 1976 Soweto Uprising by Peter Magubane, who spent 586 days
in solitary confinement for his efforts.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I'd taken South Africa's fabled Blue Train a few years ago, on
the 24-hour route from Johannesburg to Cape Town. It now leaves
from Pretoria because passengers were being accosted on the
platforms of the Johannesburg station.
</P>
<P>
   The train has recently been given a major facelift, and it's now
like traveling inside a jewelry box. Drawers and armoires in the
small but exquisite cabins are lined with padded gold silk;
tabletops are inlaid with leather; walls are panelled with wood
veneers in book-matched grains, and bordered with marquetry in a
pattern of dots _ blue, of course. The bathrooms _ each cabin now
has one, as opposed to the former shared accommodations _ are
miracles of space engineering, all fitted in sumptuous Italian
marble and gold. The murals in the dining car are the same scenes
you're looking at out the windows. There's one pit stop on the
trip, at Kimberley, to inspect the 3,600-foot hole that yielded 14
1/2 million carats of diamonds before the prospecting stopped.
Frankly, this mega-ditch is not one of the country's greatest
attractions, but if you're in the neighborhood anyway. . . .
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Train lunch is five courses; dinner, six. The food is
superb, complemented by the finest South African wines, all
included in the admittedly exorbitant price, which encourages you
to drink your money's worth. After doing so, you fall into a deep
sleep, awakening the next morning to a view of vineyards sheltered
by rugged mountains. In this country where flowers bloom in such
profusion, it's typical for each row of vines to be punctuated by a
rose bush at the end.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
