<HEADER>
A3211 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUN-SHOWS-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE-A     06-29 1547
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUN-SHOWS-2ND </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... good people.  Jim French, a member of Friends of the NRA, a fundraising branch of
the NRA. 
 
Q: Why is it that in Canada there are only a fraction of the deaths
caused by guns in the United States?
<TEXT>
<P>
   A: The primary reason is (because of) one segment of the
American society, which tends to be concentrated around the African
American community. If you take their statistics out . . . our
crime statistics are the same as Canada or even lower.
</P>
<P>
   We have segment causing an enormous amount of crime and getting
that under control would solve our so called crime problem &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q: How do you do that?
</P>
<P>
   A: We're creating a climate of immorality. Frankly it's a lack
of respect for the laws which have created a breakdown in the
structure of society of the whole. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q: Why do you need to be armed?
</P>
<P>
   A: We have a history of 160 years without a foreign invasion and
its easy to forget that it is possible to have tryranical
governments and foreign invasions. In this day and age, we sit now
as a superpower (and) the odds of being physically invaded are
pretty low. That doesn't stop an internal government from someday
arising that could be very dangerous. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q: Isn't the Second Amendment outdated? After all the British are
not coming.
</P>
<P>
   A: Locke and the others were set against tyranical government. I
mean, the Russians in '89 didn't throw the Americans out of Russia;
they threw their own government out. If we ever need to change
government in this country _ and we've been very fortunate that we
haven't had to take any extreme measures _ you want the means at
hand. You either trust the people or you trust a select group. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q: But aren't guns killing innocent children?
</P>
<P>
   A: The crime control statistics (define) kids as up to 21 . . .
Gangster rappers and turf war drive-bys, they call them kids being
shot. Well these are vicious criminals &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q: What are the police for?
</P>
<P>
   A: The police are an arm of government. They are not to defend
you from government, they are government. Ask about the police in
Germany in the 1930s; they became the problem they were not the
solution. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q: Is the government a problem now?
</P>
<P>
   A: Not at the moment, but I love history and there's no society
ever that been completely devoid of government over-stepping their
powers. The citizens better have guns if the police have guns. This
lesson's proven time and time again. &QL; 
 &QL; 
---------------------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Tressler, a firearms collector and father of 3-year-old
Gage. Tressler owns 173 firearms, from handguns to assault rifles. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q: Aren't you worried about Gage with so many firearms in the
house?
</P>
<P>
   A: No, because he knows already at three he's not suppossed to
touch them. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q: Do you have safety locks on them?
</P>
<P>
   A: No we don't have safety locks; never did when I was growing
up either. We never had any accidental shooting and my whole family
was involved in guns. We all had guns when I was growing up, and we
never had a desire to go to a high school and shoot everybody or
anything else. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q: Why did Littleton happen?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's not because of guns. It's the way parents bring up their
children. They don't teach them right from wrong. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q: Do you think TV and video games are glamorizing violence?
</P>
<P>
   A: Not really, cause look at the era I grew up in. Im 38.
Starsky and Hutch. Hawai Five Oh. Mannix. People got shot on those
shows all day long. We never had a problem. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q: What's the solution to the problem of guns and violence? A:
People need to take an interest in their children. Both parents
work too much. When I grew up my mom stayed home. They don't take
them to baseball games. They just give money and pawn them off on
someone else. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q: When were you introduced to guns?
</P>
<P>
   A: I've been hunting since I was a kid. I used to ride my bike
with a shotgun on my back and go dove and quail hunting. The
sheriff used to . . . go huntin with us. I was 12 years old. They
never said a thing. It was no big deal.
</P>
<P>
   If you buy a quality gun it will never decrease in value. It's
just like having a savings account. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ----------------------------------------- &QC; 
 &QL; 
Charlie Parrot, maker of the ``invisible holster,'' which is worn
under one's pants. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q: What's in your pants?
</P>
<P>
   A: A 1911 A1 (handgun) . . . That is a military semi-automatic
.45-caliber handgun, and if you've ever seen any war movie you've
probably seen it on the screen. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q: Where exactly is the gun concealed?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's a lower abdomen holster, and it goes around your hips,
right in your crotch. Its actually the best jock strap a male will
ever wear because it protects his privare part. If you kick me in
the groin right now you'd have one hell of a sore foot. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q: What do you think of gun control?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's just another way to take away some of our rights and
freedoms. It' guarenteed to do one thing: increase crime. Homicides
are going to go up. Murders are going to go up. Just look at every
gun control law that's ever been enacted.
</P>
<P>
   When you disarm law abiding citizens you give criminals an easy
work environment. They get braver, more confrontational. It's being
proven in Australia, where the homicide rate by handguns in
Queensland is up over 300 percent . . . background checks serve
only to deter law abiding citizens; they do nothing to deter
crime. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q: What do you think of waiting periods?
</P>
<P>
   A: The average length of time a revolver was used in a crime
after it was acquired was 7.2 years. Waiting periods don't do
anything except promote an increase in homicides and rapes, because
the victims can no longer get protection. The only thing that's
going to protect you from an armed criminal is a firearm, period. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q: But don't innocent people wind up getting killed?
</P>
<P>
   A: By criminals, not by law abiding gun owners. There's no
innocent people get killed by ordinary citizens. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q: What about accidental shootings? Kids playing with guns?
</P>
<P>
   A: Absolutely not. The number of accidental shootings by kids
grabbing guns is down to 200 to 300 per year. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q: Isn't one kid too many?
</P>
<P>
   A: One kid is too many, but whose life do you put more value on?
The over 2.5 million lives protected by firearms every year, less
300 to 400 kids. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q: Can I ask you a personal question? Aren't you woried you're
going to shoot your . . . off?
</P>
<P>
   A: No, because nothing including your own finger can even get
near the trigger when its in the holster. It's the safest way in
the world to carry a gun. Guaranteed. Even if the gun were to go
off the bullet would land between your feet. &QL; 
 &QL; 
-----------------------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Silverman, a collector of war relics and antique weapons. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q: Congress wants to make it illegal for you to sell guns. They say
you're a loophole and they want to close the loophole. What do you
think about that?
</P>
<P>
   A: What they want to do is make it illegal to sell a gun from
person to person, as opposed to going through a federally licensed
dealer. If (a customer) doesn't have a concealed gun permit, I have
to run it through a dealer. It won't bother me one way or the
other; it just costs the customer an extra $18. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q: You are not doing that now?
</P>
<P>
   A: No, because usually the stuff I have, I sell to other
dealers. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q: Do you think guns in the house gives you security?
</P>
<P>
   A: I feel a gun in the house is necessary. My wife is a liberal
and doesn't like guns. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q: Don't guns ultimately wind up being used in alot of domestic
disputes?
</P>
<P>
   A: If it's not a gun, it's a baseball bat or a knife or a frying
pans. Frying pans can kill, not as quick as a bullet, but just as
dead as a bullet. My wife knows if we have a fight I'm not going to
kill her.
</P>
<P>
   My whole life I only had to pull a gun once. I was trying to
pass on the road and (people in the car ahead) wouldn't let me
pass. I finally got around them, a stupid thing with young
teenagers. After I got to where I was going, they came out like
this (menacingly).
</P>
<P>
   They said `what's the idea of what you were doing?' I said `Did
you know that its illegal not to let somebody pass you when they
flash the lights?' They said, `Who made a stupid law like that.' I
said, `Why dont you ask the government?' . . . He started coming
for me. I pulled out a derringer and (he said) `Oh, he's got a
gun,' and they started running away. Fine. That pleased me no end.
I saved myself. They ran away and then after that I shook. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q: What would've happened if they kept coming?
</P>
<P>
   A: I don't know. It gets scary as hell. I hope I never have to
pull a gun on another person. I hope I never ever have to shoot a
person. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------- &QC; 
 &QL; 
Chris Bronahan, gun show customer. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q: How do you keep guns out of the hands of kids?
</P>
<P>
   A: A friend of mine had two kids, age five and six, and he
bought a rabbit so they could get used to it for two or three
weeks. Then he took a .22 out and shot the rabbit in front of the
children, and they were devasted _ absolutely devastated. The girl
was in tears and the boy was in tears. And he said, `Now this is
what's going to happen if you play with a gun and you shoot
somebody. They are dead.' To them it had such an effect, they never
wanted to touch a gun again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
