<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 13:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3215 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WALKING-GRANNY-BOS &LR;      06-29 1712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALKING-GRANNY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT 89, SHE'S OUT FOR A 3,000-MILE PROTEST TREK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MITCHELL ZUCKOFF  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   RANGER, Texas _ Nearing the end of her 1,240th-odd mile on her
walk across America, just after sidestepping a road-kill pancake,
Doris Haddock begins quoting Robert Frost. It seems prudent to
start worrying.
</P>
<P>
   Haddock is 89 and so is the temperature, and she is perspiring
freely as she makes her way along this moderately ugly stretch of
Texas highway with the goal of reforming federal campaign finance
laws. For a moment, her unusual purpose combines with her sudden
poetry recital to suggest a kindly old woman who has been too long
in the sun.
</P>
<P>
   But listen closely between the roar of trucks passing 4 feet to
the left, and her words, and maybe even her mission, begin to make
sense.
</P>
<P>
   The poem she is mumbling closes with Frost's message from a man
contemplating life's end: ``The woods are lovely, dark and deep,
but I have promises to keep. And miles to go before I sleep, and
miles to go before I sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   As she nears the end of her sixth month on the road, Doris
Haddock of Berlin, N.H., ``Granny D'' to her growing legion of
fans, has about 1,800 miles to go before she can rest. Only then
will she have completed her trek from California to Washington to
protest the failure by Congress to reduce the money-driven
influence of special interests and big business.
</P>
<P>
   It strikes some people as a curious cause to inspire a widowed
octogenarian with 11 great-grandchildren to rise well before dawn
to begin daily 10-mile excursions. But walk a few miles alongside
her _ she loves the company _ and there is no mistaking her clearly
articulated passion for prompting changes that she says will
restore faith and involvement in government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Democracy is drowning in a flood of money, and I've found
people _ when you ask them _ are pretty angry about that. They hate
the idea that big money has purchased their democracy out from
under them,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I think of the people who have given their lives for
democracy, and we're letting democracy go into the sewer, it's
disgusting.''
</P>
<P>
   The solution, she says, starts with passage of federal campaign
finance overhauls sponsored in the House by Representatives
Christopher Shays, a Connecticut Republican, and Martin T. Meehan,
a Lowell Democrat, and in the Senate by Republican John McCain of
Arizona, and Democrat Russell Feingold of Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   The House version, which passed last year and then died during a
Senate filibuster, would ban ``soft money'' contributions to
political parties, restrict late-breaking issue-advocacy ads that
target candidates, and tighten existing fund-raising rules.
Opponents say the changes would violate First Amendment freedoms by
unconstitutionally limiting political speech.
</P>
<P>
   Winning passage is a tall order for a woman barely 5 feet high
who walks with a pronounced forward-leaning stoop, as if she is
eager to reach the next mile marker or is about to fall on her
appealingly lined face.
</P>
<P>
   As she trudges on, weaving at times but never wavering, she
wears a wide-brimmed straw hat, a reflective vest, a T-shirt, khaki
pants, and jogging shoes with high-tech inner soles. It is her
second pair of shoes and her fourth hat since she began her walk
Jan. 1 in Pasadena, Calif. She hopes to arrive in Washington, D.C.,
on Jan. 24, 2000, her 90th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   On her shoulders is a backpack with a rubber bladder filled with
water, which she sips from a long blue straw. It is a safeguard
against dehydration, a bout of which landed her in the hospital for
four days in February.
</P>
<P>
   She carries a large yellow flag that reads: ``Granny D for
Campaign Finance Reform.'' When the wind is up the flag acts like a
sail, threatening to propel Haddock into traffic or down an
embankment, depending on which way it blows. The flag attracts
honks from drivers, some of whom presumably have learned about her
from the local newspapers and radio and television stations that
have chronicled her travels.
</P>
<P>
   Under her clothes she wears a corset with metal ribs. She has
arthritis in her back and hands, hearing aids in both ears,
dentures in her mouth, and the remnants of emphysema in her lungs
from 50 years of smoking, a habit she kicked in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other than that, I'm perfect,'' she says cheerfully.
</P>
<P>
   She is accompanied at all times by either her son Jim, who lives
next door to her in New Hampshire, or by one or two volunteers who
rotate on and off the road for short periods. They either walk
alongside her or drive behind her in a balky van plastered with
signs advertising Haddock's goal.
</P>
<P>
   On this day she is joined by two volunteers whose organizations
also are devoted to campaign finance reform: Jeanne Doogs, head of
the Reform Party in Texas, and Jeffrey Peters, founder of a New
Hampshire-based group called We The People that is dedicated to ``a
rebirth of democracy all across America.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps 100 people have accompanied her for various periods,
including a young man who insisted on burying all road kill he
happened past. Common Cause has sent several escorts, and she has
attracted activists from several organizations, including the
Reform Party, that she neither endorses nor shuns.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many disparate groups working on this, and if
they could get together they would be such a force. I have
absolutely no intention of belonging to them, but their primary
intent is campaign finance reform, and I'm happy as hell to have
them with me,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   For the past week, she also has been accompanied by a formerly
flea-infested, black-and-white mutt she adopted in Baird, Texas. It
has been dubbed DJ, for ``Doris Junior,'' and its sweet-natured
antics are a source of comfort and glee.
</P>
<P>
   Haddock was inspired to undertake her mission by a friend in New
Hampshire with whom she met regularly for exercise and political
discussions. In 1996, when Haddock complained about what she saw as
a link between low voter turnout and the influence of special
interests, her friend asked, ``Why don't you do something about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   After thinking about it awhile, Haddock began training. For nine
months last year she practiced with 10-mile walks, during which she
lost 20 pounds and became convinced she could go coast to coast.
Her family doubted her, though, and as recently as last Christmas _
a week before she began her trek _ several of her eight
grandchildren were making bets on how long she would last. None
thought she would get nearly this far.
</P>
<P>
   Although Haddock has always been politically active, little in
her past hinted at her current endeavor. She is a retired executive
secretary and lifelong activist who remembers casting her first
vote for Norman Thomas of the Socialist Party during one of his six
bids for the presidency. She has since become a Democrat. In the
1960s she helped lead a successful effort to stop nuclear blasting
in Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   As a young girl, she dreamed of becoming an actress and says she
completed three years at Emerson College toward that end, but left
school after eloping with her husband. He died in 1993 after 62
years of marriage.
</P>
<P>
   In a quiet moment, she says ``Granny D'' _ the cuddly old lady
walking for reform _ is actually a link to her old dreams of
acting. It is a role she is playing, a persona she has adopted that
belies her steely nature, because she thinks Granny D draws people
to the cause in a way Doris Haddock would not.
</P>
<P>
   When it is pointed out to her that an 89-year-old woman walking
cross-country is news no matter what she calls herself, Haddock
tilts her head upward and smiles, but says nothing.
</P>
<P>
   As she travels _ accepting donated meals, guest rooms in homes,
and hotel rooms paid for by supporters _ Haddock collects
signatures on a petition that reads: ``We the people of the United
States of America beseech our elected leaders to enact, with all
speed, campaign finance reform, eliminating `soft money' from
political campaigns.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she does not know how many names she has collected, but
proudly announces that she received 21,000 hits on her Web site
(www.grannyd.com) after she was mentioned on ``Good Morning
America.'' Though she has received a great deal of support, not
everyone likes her. One recent day after her walk, she approached
two women of her generation in a restaurant and asked them whether
they had signed her petition.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I haven't and I wouldn't want to,'' one said brusquely.
Haddock did not answer, but she acknowledged later that the
brushoff bothered her for several hours afterward.
</P>
<P>
   She gets a far better reception from local politicians who are
acutely aware _ as is Haddock _ that presenting her with a key to
the city (she has six at last count) or a written proclamation (too
many to count) is good for a photo on Page 1 of the local paper and
maybe a few seconds on the evening news.
</P>
<P>
   Haddock is also welcomed warmly at schools, where children seem
happiest when chanting her slogan: ``Go Granny Go!''
</P>
<P>
   As she walks, she sometimes admires the scenery, but her eyes
are usually trained on the ground. She dodges all sorts of debris,
from pieces of exploded tires to beer cans to various bits of dead
things. At one point, Haddock grabs a guest walker by the belt and
pulls him toward her. ``You definitely don't want to step on
that,'' she says, pointing at the unattached leg of a hoofed
animal, possibly a deer.
</P>
<P>
   She seems to ignore the ubiquitous billboards, advertising
everything from the Castle Arms Gun Shop to the Love's Rest Stop
about 50 miles down Interstate 20. But she comments on exit signs,
at one point marveling at Exit 361, leading to the towns of Strawn
and DeLeon. Thinking it a single town, she sings out, ``Strawn
DeLeon, what a lovely name for a town. I wonder how it got such a
name.'' When she is told they are two separate towns, she shrugs
and moves on.
</P>
<P>
   Haddock is certain that campaign finance laws will be
overhauled, though she doubts it will happen soon. ``It'll be
another 10 years before anything is accomplished,'' she says. And
no, she does not expect to live to see it happen: ``I'll be smiling
from the other side.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
