<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 13:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3216 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TELEPHONE-RAPIST-BOS &LR;      06-29 1386
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TELEPHONE-RAPIST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CON MAN LEAVES TRAIL OF ASSAULTS ACROSS THE NATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DANIEL VASQUEZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The calls began 17 years ago and haven't changed much since.
</P>
<P>
   They start with a muffled, barely intelligible voice that preys
on a woman's deepest fears about her family. They have ended in
dozens, perhaps hundreds, of rapes and sexual assaults across the
country.
</P>
<P>
   The victims are chosen randomly from the telephone book by
Richard Alan Minsky, a 56-year-old con artist and fugitive who is
wanted in Boston, Los Angeles, San Diego and elsewhere for rape,
sexual assault and extortion.
</P>
<P>
   While Minsky has scammed about $28,000 from victims in the past
six months, police say he hunts for sex.
</P>
<P>
   Minsky's crimes have landed him in prison in Massachusetts and
on a Georgia chain-gang for eight years, but today he's on the
loose and authorities are looking for him everywhere, knowing that
he favors his home state, as well as Florida and California.
</P>
<P>
   Police say Minsky, a balding chain-smoker who likes to be called
``Abe Lincoln,'' is a master manipulator, preying on the bonds a
woman has with a lover, husband, or child. He is on the Top 10 list
of fugitives issued by the Los Angeles Police Department and set to
be the subject of an upcoming episode of ``America's Most Wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's like a salesman with a perfected pitch,'' said William
Hartford, a Boston police detective who, along with his partner,
Paul Mahoney, arrested Minsky at the Copley Plaza Hotel in 1996 _
the only officers to catch him in the act of randomly calling
women, trying to lure them to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost like he's selling a product,'' Hartford said.
``He's successful at selling it, so he probably figures `Why change
the pitch?' ''
</P>
<P>
   When Hartford arrested him, Minsky was waiting for a victim from
Boston while using a bag of dimes to call more possible victims in
Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Minsky was convicted of indecent assault and battery and spent
two years in a Massachusetts penitentiary. He was released in June
1998, but failed to register as a sex offender and skipped
probation. Now Minsky faces a minimum of five years in prison for
parole violations.
</P>
<P>
   Police say Minsky fishes the phone book for victims, often
striking high-rent areas like Boston, Cambridge, San Diego and
Beverly Hills. He dials madly until he finds someone who will
believe him.
</P>
<P>
   He likes the early hours, and with the poise and push of a
clever telemarketer, Minsky tricks his victims into believing he is
an attorney trying to help a boyfriend or husband who has just fled
the scene of a vehicular homicide.
</P>
<P>
   The calls begin with a hushed, almost indecipherable, voice, and
when a victim blurts out a loved one's name in an attempt to find
out who is calling, Minsky pounces. He expertly changes voices, and
using the name he has just obtained, says he is a lawyer trying to
help that person.
</P>
<P>
   Minsky quickly convinces the women that sex, money or both can
be exchanged to pay off a malleable, lone witness.
</P>
<P>
   He cites state laws he is familiar with and mentions a mandatory
prison sentence. Minsky varies the con, sometimes pretending to be
a kidnapper holding a child at gunpoint.
</P>
<P>
   Minsky directs the victim to meet the made-up witness or
kidnapper at a hotel or airport, where Minsky himself will be
waiting, to make the so-called payoff.
</P>
<P>
   If Minsky likes the looks of the women he sees, he lures them to
a hotel room, police say. If not, he just walks away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm educated, I'm the vice president of a national sales
company. I'm no dummy, he caught me off guard,'' a 32-year-old
victim from the Miami area told the Globe recently. She is Minsky's
last known victim, one of the few who have provided police with a
template of Minsky's well-crafted scam.
</P>
<P>
   The first words she heard _ from Minsky, in a muffled voice
purporting to be her husband _ at 7:50 a.m. that Feb. 10 morning
were ``Honey, I'm in trouble.'' After she responded with her
husband's name, the voice changed to one evocative of a well-spoken
professional man _ supposedly, a lawyer offering her a chance to
pay off a witness to her husband's hit-and-run car accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was helping my husband,'' the woman said. ``The
man on the phone wanted to know what I was willing to do to help my
husband.''
</P>
<P>
   She agreed to meet the witness at the Miami airport with $5,000
in cash. Police say Minsky orders the victims to meet him fast,
before they can think clearly or call for help. In this case,
Minsky, while posing as the helpful attorney, insisted that the
woman practice her plea, saying out loud several times why her
husband couldn't afford to go to prison. She mentioned a new job
and their infant baby.
</P>
<P>
   Next, she was told to go to the arrival desk at United Airlines
and ask for ``Abe Lincoln.'' When she got there, Minsky was
waiting. Posing as the witness, he ordered her to drive to an
isolated area nearby where they could talk.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in a cheap black suit, scuffed leather loafers, and
thick eyeglasses, Minsky prattled for three hours and smoked a
dozen cigarettes, the woman recalled. He never made eye contact and
refused to talk about the made-up accident, instead chatting on
about having dogs and a girlfriend, all the while managing to touch
the victim's legs and chest. Sometimes he hugged and kissed her
head, reminding her that he ``needed to be convinced.''
</P>
<P>
   After the woman made it clear she would not have sex, Minsky
took the cash without counting it and asked to be dropped back at
the airport.
</P>
<P>
   The victim rushed home, tracked her husband by phone, realized
her mistake, and called the police. The case went unsolved until
recently, when police learned Minsky had committed similar crimes
in Los Angeles and had a past in Boston. She later identified his
photo.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was lucky. This guy was working on raping her, that's why
he wanted her to leave the airport,'' said Aventura, Fla., police
Detective Carlos Fernandez, who is handling the case.
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez said he obtained a photograph of Minsky from Boston
police, the agency with the most information about him, and the
victim immediately picked him out of a photo array. Florida will be
issuing an arrest warrant this week for Minsky.
</P>
<P>
   Minsky's scam is so polished, Fernandez said, ``He scares me.''
</P>
<P>
   Born in Brookline, Mass., Minsky has split his time between
Massachusetts and California for much of his adult life. Police say
he enjoys gambling and betting on horses; he particularly favors
several tracks in the Los Angeles area.
</P>
<P>
   He has little education, according to police, and his primary
work experience was as a part-time salesman for a brother-in-law
who owns a used car lot in a north-of-Boston suburb.
</P>
<P>
   His father, who once ran a produce business in Boston, has
retired to Florida and lives near Fort Lauderdale. When Minsky was
arrested in Boston in 1996, he listed an address near Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The earliest reported rape scams were in Southern California in
the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never forgotten this guy,'' said Los Angeles Police
Detective John Metcalf, who first came across Minsky as a detective
trainee in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   Metcalf linked Minsky to six attacks, but before Los Angeles
police could prosecute, Minsky was arrested in Georgia in 1983. He
was convicted of sodomy, sexual assault and extortion in Georgia
and Florida, and served an eight-year concurrent prison sentence in
Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   And since being released from Massachusetts last June, Minsky
has allegedly struck more than a half-dozen times in Los Angeles
and San Diego, said Metcalf.
</P>
<P>
   Metcalf said that Minsky relies on the belief most victims will
not call the police, afraid to tell authorities they willingly took
part in a scam, embarrassed about being raped or afraid their
husbands and family will not understand they were duped by a
smooth-talker who looks more like a snake charmer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my belief this guy has struck hundreds, maybe thousands,
of times. We only know about some of them,'' Metcalf said. ``This
guy is preying on the loyalty between between a mother and a
daughter, or a wife and husband. He knows the female is going to be
protective, he knows they're going to do whatever it takes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
