<DOCNO> NYT19990629.0123 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3217 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC-2TAK     06-29 0953
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVAR SERBS VENT ANGER AT MILOSEVIC
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KOSOVO POLJE, Yugoslavia _ At a 1987 rally, Slobodan Milosevic
bellowed from a balcony to the residents of this Serb industrial
town, ``No one should dare to beat you.''
</P>
<P>
   With those words, the Yugoslav leader donned the mantle of
protector of Kosovo's beleaguered minority Serbs and ignited the
ethnic hatred that would propel him into power and explode into one
war after another.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, in streets ravaged by Milosevic's hateful vision, a
funeral procession for a Serb _ beaten savagely with a hammer and
then shot to death by ethnic Albanians seeking revenge _ wound its
way beneath the same balcony where it all began.
</P>
<P>
   ``Milosevic made his promises to us, and now he has left us to
die,'' said Miodrag Stamenkovic, 66, as he stood by the simple
wooden casket that held his son Jovica, 41.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those words were all for his own political career, and it is
the people who are suffering and dying. We lost our beautiful
son,'' said Stamenkovic, brushing away tears. The son's body was
found Thursday in a pool of blood at the Pristina University cafe
where he worked.
</P>
<P>
   As the cycle of violence turns against the Serbs,
disillusionment with Milosevic's nationalist dreams seems to be
cresting. Each day Serbs in Kosovo, the southern province of what
is left of Yugoslavia, are turning against Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are wearing black because of him. Milosevic is now our
worst enemy,'' said Savka Martinovic, 70, shrouded in a black veil
as she made her way in the funeral procession Friday in a
wheelchair.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs' anger is reinforced by fear as the death toll mounts.
Serbian Orthodox Church officials allege that about 50 Serbs have
been killed in the two weeks since NATO ground troops moved into
Kosovo after a 78-day bombing campaign intended to halt the Serbs'
forced expulsion of ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   NATO is now accelerating deployment of peacekeeping forces to
reach a planned strength of 55,000 as soon as possible. The
alliance's leaders seem to believe that they must act quickly or
face the prospect of losing the peace after winning the war.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the streets of Kosovo Polje were lined with
frightened Serbs standing solemnly for Jovica Stamenkovic's funeral
procession. As they mourned a neighbor, they must also have feared
for their own lives, well aware that returning Kosovar Albanian
refugees were unleashing their anger on Serb neighbors throughout
the province, looting and burning homes and killing suspected
collaborators.
</P>
<P>
   Already, an estimated 75,000 of Kosovo's 125,000 Serbs have
fled. They had long been a minority of 10 percent of the province's
population, and their dwindling numbers dim any remaining hope of
maintaining a multiethnic Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But some, embittered and fearful, are staying, at least for now.
Mili Dimic, 35, with an AK-47 loaded with a 30-bullet clip lying on
a bed in his one-room home, looked out his window on the streets
last week. He had just lost his job at an electrical plant that was
once again operated by ethnic Albanian workers, who had been fired
under Milosevic's rule.
</P>
<P>
   Dimic said he will never leave, and he will kill anyone who
threatens him or his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Milosevic won't protect us, and NATO can't. We'll take care of
ourselves,'' said Dimic, adding that he had tossed in a trash heap
the framed photo of Milosevic that until two weeks ago hung on his
wall.
</P>
<P>
   All week long, the streets of Kosovo Polje crackled with
sporadic gunfire, and Serbian homes were set ablaze as ethnic
Albanians looted Serb homes and stores. NATO troops were a sparse
presence, with only an occasional tank rumbling down the street.
</P>
<P>
   It made no difference to the victims, but the scope of the
reflexive rage that ethnic Albanians unleashed on some of their
Serb neighbors was limited compared with the intense and systematic
campaign of violent expulsion that had been waged by Serb forces.
</P>
<P>
   The ethnic Albanians rationalize their current violence,
justifying it by saying that Serb civilians killed and raped their
loved ones and looted and burned their homes. They contend that
many Serb and Serbian gypsy civilians worked in concert with
murderous paramilitary units and police to carry out the ``ethnic
cleansing'' that forced 1 million refugees from their homes and
slaughtered an estimated 10,000 ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   But Stamenkovic was apparently an innocent victim, caught in the
wrong place at the wrong time. He served coffee at a Pristina
University cafe. The unknown assailants, who witnesses say were
ethnic Albanians, were believed to be targeting two prominent Serb
professors at the Serb-dominated university, which was once the
pride of ethnic Albanians before they were ousted from academic
positions under Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   The two professors were found bound and gagged and shot in the
head alongside the body of Stamenkovic. The message, it seemed, was
that ethnic Albanians will use force if necessary to take back
their jobs in everything, including academia.
</P>
<P>
   Inside a darkened home, a Kosovo Polje priest conducted the
funeral rites, the casket lit by a glow of mourners' candles. But
the priest was ordered by the church hierarchy not to attend the
burial in a nearby cemetery. The risk to his life was too great.
One priest was already missing, church officials said, after he was
seen being detained by the soldiers of the Kosovo Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-99 1340EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990629.0124 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3218 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC-2ND &LR;      06-29 1122
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 KOSOVO POLJE, Yugoslavia: ... Libertion Army.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The priests have reason to fear. Because Serb nationalism is
laden with religious symbolism, the KLA and the predominantly
Muslim Kosovar Albanians often see the Serbian Orthodox Church as
an ally of the Milosevic regime.
</P>
<P>
   That impression _ and the church hierarchy insists it is a false
one _ was solidified in 1989 when 1 million Serbs gathered at the
14th-century monastery in Gracanica to commemorate the 600th
anniversary of the Battle of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic presided on that day 10 years ago, standing
side-by-side with the Serbian Orthodox patriarch. Although his 1987
rally at Kosovo Polje had thrust him onto the national stage, it
was the 1989 rally that consolidated his power. Fired with Serb
nationalism, the crowd marched from the monastery to Gazimistan, a
sprawling farmland in the Lob River valley, and listened to the
words that unveiled Milosevic's ominous vision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Six centuries later we are again in battles and quarrels,''
Milosevic said. ``They are not armed battles, though such things
should not be excluded.''
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic was well aware that in the historic Battle of Kosovo
in 1389, when Serbs were defeated by the Turks and subjected to
some 500 years of Ottoman rule, has deep spiritual significance for
the Serbian Orthodox Church as well. It is seen as a noble defeat,
one that purified the souls of Serb soldiers as they fought for the
Serbian holy land. The date on which Serbs commemorate the battle,
June 28, is the day that a Serb nationalist chose in 1914 to
assassinate Austrian Archduke Ferdinand, triggering World War I.
</P>
<P>
   But as the traditional date of the battle approached last week,
there was little to commemorate.
</P>
<P>
   At the 1389 Pub one evening, Serb workmen were downing shots of
plum brandy. They hurled ugly insults at ethnic Albanians as
``thieves and whores,'' and the language grew louder and more
vulgar as more drinks were poured.
</P>
<P>
   On the wall was a huge mural depicting Serbian Czar Lazar _ who
chose to fight to his death rather than be conquered by the Turks.
The painting depicts the czar's last supper, mirroring the image of
Jesus Christ.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our history. This is who we are,'' said Petrovic
Stanica, part owner of the bar and the only one drinking a Coke.
``Milosevic wants to think he's Lazar. For a few years he had
support; now he is seen for what he is: a pawn of the world's
Mafia.'' Referring to President Clinton and British Prime Minister
Tony Blair, he continued, ``Your Clinton and your Blair are Mafia
kings.'' The 1389 Pub is just up the road from the historic
battlefield it celebrates, and there too is a monastery, where
Bishop Artemije Radosavljevic, bishop of the Serbian Orthodox
Diocese of Prizren, last week remembered Milosevic's 1989 speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``The speech frightened people, Serbs as well as Albanians. It
was the specter of a kind of nationalism that everyone knew meant
violence,'' he said in an interview. ``He used that day and its
symbolism for his own political purposes.
</P>
<P>
   But, he went on, ``there is no contact between Milosevic and the
Serbian Orthodox Church. When have you ever seen Milosevic in
church on a Sunday?''
</P>
<P>
   Now the Serbian Orthodox patriarch no longer stands beside
Milosevic. In a statement released just after NATO troops moved
into Kosovo, the church called for his resignation, making it the
most powerful institution to challenge Milosevic's hold on power.
</P>
<P>
   And there are signs that the disillusionment of Serbs in Kosovo
is spreading into Serbia proper. A recent poll showed that his
popularity had plummeted amid the ravages of NATO bombing. And the
Yugoslav Army has grown restive, blocking roads south of Belgrade
and demanding unpaid wages.
</P>
<P>
   Although there is widespread criticism that the church was too
late in challenging Milosevic, Artemije called that view unfair. He
said that the church had spoken out against Milosevic since 1992,
but had been ignored by the state-controlled media.
</P>
<P>
   But the bishop doesn't expect Milosevic, who stands charged as a
war criminal by an international tribunal in The Hague, to step
down any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the priests were arranging a funeral for four Serb
farmers, all in their 60s, who were found slaughtered, presumably
by ethnic Albanians, in the woods near their village. The men had
been castrated and their hearts cut out of their chests, Artemije
said, an account confirmed by family members and several priests.
</P>
<P>
   After the funeral, the procession of mourners from the four
victims' extended families, and most of the other residents of
their farming village, were too frightened to go home. Some 150 of
them camped inside the monastery's school.
</P>
<P>
   Among them was Voja Zvedkovic, 75, who huddled in fear with his
wife, Zorka, 65, in a classroom with children's drawings on the
walls and a model of a human heart encased in glass.
</P>
<P>
   Zvedkovic said KLA soldiers had kicked in his door in the middle
of the night, beat him badly, and forced him and his wife out of
their home. Tears streamed down over the black-and-blue half moons
under his eyes _ the result of the beating. His wife had a
reddish-blue bruise, the shape of a boot, from her left eye to her
neck. She said she had been kicked by a KLA soldier while she lay
on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look what has happened to us. Look what they did,'' said Voja.
``We have nowhere to go. We have no money.''
</P>
<P>
   But when they were asked about Milosevic and his campaign of
ethnic cleansing, the elderly villagers seemed too frightened to
criticize him. Even with evidence all around them of the horrors
that ethnic Albanian neighbors had suffered, they denied there had
been any atrocities. They insisted the killing and ransacking was
done by NATO, not Milosevic's forces.
</P>
<P>
   That sentiment remains common among Serbs who have only the
government-controlled media to rely on for their news.
</P>
<P>
   But when Stanko Shoranovic, 45, a manager of a petroleum
processing plant who holds advanced degrees in engineering, came to
the schoolhouse to pick up his elderly father, the contrast was
stark. Shoranovic can afford satellite television, and he had seen
the horror. But as he talked, the elderly villagers listened to him
silently and shook their heads in disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   Until two years ago, Shoranovic said, he actively supported
Milosevic, believing that his leadership would redress the
discrimination that he said Serbs suffered under Albanian political
leadership in Kosovo throughout the 1980s. But now, he said, he has
seen ``Milosevic's dirty war.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how Milosevic can live with himself,'' he said,
``not after what he has done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
