<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPTIMISM ON IRELAND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and k coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON &UR;  &LR; -- In Northern Ireland, the Perils of Pauline
character of the peace process is always dramatic, usually serious,
and occasionally dangerous _ as in right now.
</P>
<P>
   But it is also diverting from underlying trends that produce
most of the optimism that still surrounds the contentious
confusion.
</P>
<P>
   To an optimist conditioned by scores of events in the past five
years to look realistically past obstacles _ it is the politicians
in the six counties of the North that are the lagging indicators,
not the people.
</P>
<P>
   It is the people who have demonstrated and then voted for both
nonviolence and a settlement of outstanding political questions.
And it is the people whose religious leaders (most of them) and
economic activities (all of them) are creating a new environment
that will not tolerate a return to the madness of The Troubles that
began in such deadly earnest 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   And that is why the latest deadline _ Wednesday _ for political
progress _ imposed by British Prime Minister Tony Blair and his
Irish counterpart, Bertie Ahearn _ is less an ultimatum than a
marker. It is above all an expression by two of the governments
driving this process _ the third, thanks to President Clinton, is
the United States _ of an unwillingness to tolerate querulous
politics by the parties to last year's still-astonishing Good
Friday agreement, and to insist on implementation.
</P>
<P>
   That intolerance was expressed during a visit here last week by
Ireland's deputy prime minister, Mary Harney, the leader of the
junior party in Ahearn's coalition, the Progressive Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always envisaged there would be problems,'' she said in
between official appointments with Clintonites, ``but we cannot
contemplate failure.''
</P>
<P>
   Harney's portfolio in the Ahearn cabinet covers economic
affairs, which makes her an overseer of one of the genuine miracles
in the world today _ an economy that itself has evolved into a
powerful magnet for the North as well as a positive role model.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everyone can see what peace can produce, especially
when compared to the effects of 30 years of enormous damage to the
society in the North,'' she said. ``Since the ceasefire in 1994,
even the cross-border trade has been way, way up. The reaction in
the business community to continued progress would be extremely
positive, and many of their leaders are strongly encouraging the
politicians to go for it.''
</P>
<P>
   The core of the problem is not literally Unionist leader David
Trimble's insistence that Sinn Fein lean on its pals in the Irish
Republican Army to turn in some of their weapons and explosives in
advance of the deadline of next spring that was agreed to last
year; Trimble has insisted on some response to his liking as a
condition for agreeing to let the executive department of the new
government in the North be formed.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is the core of the problem Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams's
refusal to date to accommodate him.
</P>
<P>
   As Trimble has said, the core of the problem is diminished
confidence in the peace agreement within his divided community; and
as Adams has said somewhat less directly, the core of the problem
is an unwillingness to push disarmament ahead of schedule in the
absence of confidence that a new political day is in fact dawning.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's obviously needed is simultaneous movement on every
side,'' said Harney. ``All sides know what the words mean, but it's
not always the words themselves that matter. It's sometimes
important to go a bit beyond the words to honor the real spirit of
an agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Irish official involved in the process said that while
disarming _ they call it by the choice euphemism, decommissioning _
is not a precondition for the establishment of the power-sharing
executive, it is a commitment nonetheless for next May; and, in
that context, it is not unreasonable to push for things that will
establish confidence that the commitment will be kept.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, you could see the parties begin to move. Sinn Fein
was talking about formally declaring ``the war is over'' and not
just halted by a ceasefire. Trimble was talking about oral
commitments to disarm, not necessarily any actual turning in of
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   And, in addition to quietly encouraging Sinn Fein to take a step
toward the Unionists, the authorities in the North were banning a
major Protestant march this weekend from entering the Catholic part
of Drumcree, for years a flashpoint for violence.
</P>
<P>
   What all those moves share is a realization that the public
wants more progress, less intransigence, and no violence.
</P>
<P>
   We optimists believe the pols understand the message.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
