<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAPHIC-PLANES-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARTS AND AIRCRAFT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Take a look out the window of any airport terminal _ or a window
of an aircraft taxiing toward takeoff _ and you might see a plane
painted to look like a whale that contains a scene of Boston's
famous Swan Boats, or others painted to celebrate Nevada, Arizona,
or plain, old Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   In the highly competitive world of the airline industry,
carriers are looking for an edge. United Airlines earlier this year
finished painting all of its 460 planes in new colors; Delta is in
the midst of changing its look. And US Airways not only is changing
its colors for the third time in 10 years, it changed its name from
USAir to US Airways. Continental recently redid the outside of its
airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines must seem modern and cutting edge, so colors or print
type that were fashionable a decade ago can seem terribly passe,
industry specialists say. As a result an airline's colors _ what
the industry calls livery _ get changed frequently, and airline
executives hope that a message has been sent to business travelers,
vacationers _ even their employees.
</P>
<P>
   But the effort may not alter the bottom line, said Darryl
Jenkins, director of the Aviation Institute at George Washington
University.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never seen anybody, anywhere say that one airline made
more than another because of its livery,'' he said. ``You don't
want your airplanes to look like dogs, but you never see the
outside of an airplane when you are flying in one. The airline
business boils down to schedule and price.''
</P>
<P>
   Airlines are reluctant to divulge how much they spend on
changing livery. They say virtually all of the cost _ anywhere from
several hundred thousand dollars to a few million _ is in
commissioning the new design. Planes are painted during their
normal maintenance schedule _ no airline would take a plane out of
service simply to paint it. As a result, a complete changeover can
take several years.
</P>
<P>
   That, however, is not smart branding, said Audrey Duskey,
professor of marketing at Duquesne University.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think from the consumer's point of view, it is confusing,''
she said. ``Look at traditional images like Coca-Cola or Nike. They
don't change. As consumers, we like tradition and it surprises me
the airlines do this as much as they do. It is probably not a good
strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   While United, Delta, Continental, and US Airways are all going
with solid colors and clean lines, and each is trying to portray
international professionalism to the business traveler, other
carriers are taking a more eye-catching route.
</P>
<P>
   Consider British Airways. Two years ago, the airline scrapped
the Union Jack and royal crown painted on the tail of its planes
for more colorful, bold global images to reflect the airline's
worldwide route system.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was part of rebranding,'' said BA spokesman John Lampl.
``We are still British, the name will never change, but we fly to
167 destinations in over 80 countries. We wanted to reflect the
fact that we were appreciative of where we operate.''
</P>
<P>
   But BA's change caused a patriotic uproar in Merry Old England.
So halfway through the redesign, the airline decided to paint a
modified Union Jack on planes that had not yet received the wild
schemes designed by artists from around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Upstart Virgin Atlantic Airways this month unveiled a new livery
for its aircraft. The British flag is prominently featured on the
winglets and fuselages of its planes.
</P>
<P>
   Was it chance the rival airline, long a thorn in BA's side, saw
an opportunity to stick it to the big airline once again?
</P>
<P>
   ``There are coincidences in life, but this was not a
coincidence,'' said Virgin spokeswoman Elvi Taveras.
</P>
<P>
   Virgin has a history of using its fleet to convey all sorts of
messages. Many of its planes still have the message ``No Way BA
AA,'' a reference to the proposed alliance between British Airways
and American Airlines that failed to get off the ground. Virgin put
the political statement on its planes as it launched service to
Washington in an effort to get the Department of Transportation to
rule against the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Much more often, however, designs are tied to marketing rather
than politics. In 1989, after acquiring Piedmont and Pacific
Southwest Airlines, USAir changed its livery from a polished
aluminum fuselage with a red and orange stripe to a painted
fuselage with red, white and blue.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in 1996, the airline changed its livery and name again
because ``there was new management, and the airline was expanding
internationally, and we were upgrading our facilities,'' said Rita
Cuddihy, vice president of customer products and service planning
for US Airways.
</P>
<P>
   The first thing that had to be changed, said Cuddihy, was the
name. USAir sounded smaller than US Airlines or US Airways. The
former was the generic name for the domestic commercial aviation
industry, so the latter was chosen.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping US was a no-brainer, as was keeping red, white, and blue
_ although the blue became deeper and the underbelly of each plane
was painted gray, to ``get further into the business side to
reflect the pinstripe-suit formal side of life,'' said Cuddihy.
</P>
<P>
   The change involved some 1,600 separate items, from airplanes to
baggage trucks, from airport interior signage to corporate
stationery. And unifying everything, says Cuddihy, is the stylized
flag design painted on the tail of every plane, be it US Airways,
the US Airways Shuttle, or Metrojet.
</P>
<P>
   Other carriers aren't as consistent.
</P>
<P>
   Southwest Airlines's normal livery is gold, red, and orange,
with the colors extending the length of the fuselage and stripes
running up the tail. But seven of the airline's 292 Boeing 737s
have special paint jobs _ most of which cost more than the regular
livery.
</P>
<P>
   Three are painted to look like Shamu the killer whale, in a
marketing tie-in with Sea World. Others are painted as tributes to
Texas, Nevada, and Arizona. The plane the airline calls California
One has a giant bear (like the one on the state flag) painted on
the fuselage. And Triple Crown One is dedicated to Southwest
employees for the airline finishing with the best on-time arrival,
the best baggage handling, and the fewest customer complaints
registered with the Department of Transportation.
</P>
<P>
   The plane has the name of all 25,000 Southwest employees who
worked for the airline in 1996 on the luggage bins inside the
aircraft, said spokeswoman Kristie Kerr.
</P>
<P>
   ``People love to fly on the planes, especially Shamu,'' said
Kerr. In fact, people often request reservations on the specialty
planes _ something reservation agents have no control over.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, America West has some planes painted to represent
states the airline serves. It also has theme planes for the Phoenix
Suns basketball team and the Arizona Diamondbacks baseball club.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is Cape Air/Nantucket Airlines, with its
blue-and-white livery with either a seagull or Nantucket painted on
the tail of the Cessna 402s the airline uses.
</P>
<P>
   But among the fleet of 47 airplanes are three that president Dan
Wolf hopes do more than catch the eye. He hopes to instill an
appreciation for art.
</P>
<P>
   One plane, celebrating the airline's first route _ between
Boston and Provincetown _ is painted like a whale with scenes from
Boston and Provincetown. Designed and painted by Cape Cod artists,
the special planes cost much more than a normal paint job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very strongly that if you can get art out of galleries
and museums, it is an enriching thing,'' said Wolf.
</P>
<P>
   Another plane is designed to represent Nantucket's high school
sports teams. With new service to North Carolina's Outer Banks,
Cape Air plans to select an artist from that area to design and
paint the airplane. Future Cape Air planes may have scenes from
Martha's Vineyard and New Bedford.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Bond, co-chairman of New York advertising firm Kirshenbaum
Bond &AMP; Partners, thinks Cape Air is on the right track _ even if
the goal is less lofty than Wolf's desire to promote art.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something like that gives you the experience of a place before
you get there,'' said Bond. ``It says your vacation starts when you
step on the plane, not when you step off it.''
</P>
<P>
   Some might fret that airplanes with wild designs and special
themes are just a step away from flying billboards. But airlines
that sold ads on planes have not done so well.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado-based Western Pacific Airlines, a discount airline that
started operations in 1995, made a splash by turning its Boeing
737s into flying advertisements. One contract, for example, was
with Fox TV, and the plane was painted with cartoon characters from
``The Simpsons.'' But while Bart, Homer, and Marge are still
crowding the airwaves, their plane is not. The airline went
bankrupt in 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
