<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 13:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3223 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEVINGSTON-COLUMN-BOS     06-29 0608
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVINGSTON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAMBLING WITH PEOPLE'S LIVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN LEVINGSTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It came as little surprise when the doctor gave me the bad news.
For years I'd gone for the cheap laugh, the low blow, the wisecrack
_ always with little effect. Everybody told me that all those sick
jokes would catch up with me one day. So I half expected it when
the good doctor said: ``You have a diseased funny bone.'' He added
somberly: ``It looks fatal.''
</P>
<P>
   I knew I'd been a bit gauche at times but I just had to ask:
``Is it really . . . that bad?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mmm,'' he nodded. ``But I can offer you a glimmer of hope.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll do anything, doctor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a new procedure,'' he said. ``It's enormously risky.
But for a man as disturbingly sick as you, it's your only chance.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll do it. What is it?''
</P>
<P>
   ``A transplant.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A transplant?''
</P>
<P>
   ``We replace your funny bone with a healthy one. After months of
profound therapy, there's a chance you could surprise us with an
acceptable witticism or two.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And without the operation?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``You die.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's get started, doctor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something else,'' he said. ``The costs will be
astronomical. First you need to find a compatible donor. This will
require travel _ airfares, hotels, rental cars. Then there's the
procedure itself. Altogether we're looking at hundreds of thousands
of dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But of course my health insurance _''
</P>
<P>
   The doctor shook his head gravely. ``Transplants of the funny
bone. The insurance companies still consider them experimental.
They won't pay a penny.''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly I felt adrift. I was one of far too many patients who
find themselves engulfed in dark _ and uncomic _ desperation as
they try to scrounge money for a vital medical procedure.
</P>
<P>
   There's Susan Diaz who, the Wall Street Journal tells us, needs
a new intestine and is forced to hold yard sales and arts and
crafts auctions, and to place milk cartons in her local restaurants
seeking contributions from diners. She is still thousands of
dollars away from saving her own life.
</P>
<P>
   There are Robert and Amanda Sehee, who sell candy bars to fund a
bone-marrow transplant for their 22-month-old daughter. And JoEllen
Whitfield, who holds a raffle with donated gifts to pay for her
search for a bone-marrow donor.
</P>
<P>
   The health insurance system has failed them all. So too has the
government _ populated by oafs who, blinded by their
self-importance, have lost sight of the important issues. If there
is one thing a government in good faith ought to do it is to ensure
the health of its citizens.
</P>
<P>
   You won't catch me hawking candy bars or selling old
candlesticks on my front lawn. By the time I raised enough for my
new funny bone, the laughing would have long stopped. I have no
choice, really, but to take on the biggest gamble of my life. I've
sold everything I own, cashed in all of my certificates, bonds, and
baseball cards, and I'm converting the small lump of bills into
chips for the roulette table.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it's come to this.
</P>
<P>
   I'm placing the whole stack on 11 black. Whoosh. Round goes the
wheel, just like the fortunes of life, counter-clockwise, and
there's the tiny ivory ball spinning the opposite direction. If it
falls for me, I'm paid 35 to 1, and I live happily ever after with
a new and improved funny bone.
</P>
<P>
   Round and round. It's come to this _ one last shot.
</P>
<P>
   The wheel slows, the ball falls: It's 23 red.
</P>
<P>
   I lose. I die _ and it won't be funny.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Levingston can be reached at
dollarsnonsense(at)hotmail.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
