   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HEPATITIS-DRUG (Undated) _ Advocates for people with
hepatitis C announced that they have found a way for patients to
bypass a major drug company and purchase a medications at far below
the usual price. The medication is an antiviral drug, Ribavirin,
that works against hepatitis C only when it is combined with
another treatment, interferon. By Denise Grady. (700 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   COKE-EUROPE (Undated) _ As the crisis that caused the biggest
recall of Coca-Cola soft drinks unfolded this month, Coke
executives took several days to make the matter a high priority. An
apology to consumers came more than a week after the first
publicized reports of people falling ill. When Coke did respond, it
tried to diminish the reports of illness, and it was not until June
18 _ 10 days after the first schoolboy became dizzy and nauseated
after drinking a Coke _ that the company's top brass arrived in
Belgium. Coca-Cola will now have to work hard to restore the
Coca-Cola brand in Europe, which accounts for about 26 percent of
the company's profits. By Constance L. Hays.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SBC-AMERITECH (Washington) _ The FCC will announce its decision
on SBC's proposed $56 billion acquisition of Ameritech this
afternoon. By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-INTERNET (Hong Kong) _ Combining two of the decade's
hottest investment concepts _ China and the Internet _ in a single
stock offering, the China.com Corp. seeks to raise $56.3 million in
a listing on Nasdaq . It kicked off its road show for investors on
Tuesday. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   COMPAQ-ALTAVISTA (Undated) _ Compaq announces sale of Alta
Vista. By Saul Hansell.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-TRAVEL (Undated) _ The business travel column. By Jane
L. Levere.
</P>
<P>
   DEUTSCHEBANK-NEWMAN (Frankfurt, Germany) _ Frank Newman is
leaving Deutsche Bank less than a month after the takeover of
Bankers Trust, which he headed. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   LATIN-ECON (Buenos Aires, Argentina) _ Recent economic reports
suggest that Latin America's recovery may not be quite as strong as
many believe. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily Marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At midmorning, stocks were little changed.
The Dow Jones industrial average was up about 15 points, the S&AMP;P
500 up 1 point and the Nasdaq composite up 2 points. The 30-year
bond was yielding 6.08 percent. European markets were mixed, with
London down 1.46 percent, and Frankfurt up slightly. The Nikkei
closed up 0.98 percent and the Hang Seng fell 0.54 precent. By
Kenneth N. Gilpin.
</P>
