<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-FLORA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FREEDOM URGED FOR KOSOVO'S `MOTHER FLORA'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN ROUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For more than a decade, Flora Brovina peacefully, but openly,
protested Serbian atrocities against ethnic Albanian women and
children in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, friends and family say, she became too fearless.
</P>
<P>
   In April _ a month after NATO began airstrikes on Yugoslavia _
Serbian police arrested the woman whom Kosovar orphans
affectionately call ``Mother Flora.'' Brovina reportedly was
beaten, possibly tortured, and is partially paralyzed in a
Yugoslavian prison hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fear was never a part of her life,'' said Uranik Begu,
Brovina's son, who last saw his mother almost a year ago. ``That is
why she decided to stay and that is why she is paying with her
life.''
</P>
<P>
   The 21-year-old Dallas resident and other family members are
waging an international campaign to win Brovina's freedom. A
humanitarian who gave shelter to war orphans and wrote poetry books
that speak passionately about motherhood, suffering and love,
Brovina has become a symbol of ethnic Albanian resistance.
</P>
<P>
   Her case has drawn international attention from human rights
groups, including Amnesty International and the International
Committee of the Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. State Department is working with the Red Cross and the
United Nations to investigate claims of as many as 3,000 prisoners,
including Brovina, who were taken out of Kosovo before NATO
peacekeepers arrived, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   International support has been great, but more action is needed
to save Brovina's life, said Begu, who moved to Texas to attend
college.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's in a very bad state of health,'' he said. ``In the
United States, I would like a lot more women to raise their voices
because I'm sure she would do the same for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Begu said his mother is important to the peace process because
she could help women heal their psychological wounds without
seeking revenge.
</P>
<P>
   Brovina, 49, was in her apartment April 22 when eight men, some
masked, broke in, handcuffed her, forced her into a car and drove
away, according to Amnesty International.
</P>
<P>
   Prisoners freed after the war reported seeing Brovina in the
yard of the prison, said Vjosa Dobruna, a former co-worker of
Brovina's, in a telephone interview from Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was beaten and in very bad shape,'' said Dobruna, who
worked with Brovina for 10 years and has been her friend for 19.
``She was walking and other women were helping her walk around.''
</P>
<P>
   Brovina has been charged with ``joining in enemy duties,''
committing ``criminal acts endangering the territorial integrity''
of Yugoslavia and terrorism, the Los Angeles Times has reported.
She is also accused of making sweaters and masks, setting up a war
clinic and serving as the health minister for the Kosovo Liberation
Army, a separatist guerrilla group, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted, she could be sentenced to 10 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Brovina founded and has served as president of the Albanian
Women's League, a group that advocates emancipation for Albanian
women, since the early 1990s, Begu said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She would organize studies on culture and arts. But when the
war started, the objectives changed,'' Begu said. ``She organized
first-aid (classes), teaching women to heal wounds.''
</P>
<P>
   In January, Brovina was featured as one of Marie-Claire
magazine's Women of the World.
</P>
<P>
   In March 1998, Brovina organized a demonstration in which more
than 7,000 women, each carrying a loaf of bread, marched from
Pristina to Drenica to protest the killings that forced women to
flee their villages and hide in the mountains. The women marched
only 10 kilometers before they were stopped by police, Begu said.
</P>
<P>
   The message to the women was ``that they were not alone, that
they need bread,'' Begu said.
</P>
<P>
   Dobruna said she and Brovina were among several ethnic Albanian
doctors fired from the Central Daily Clinic for Children in
Pristina and replaced by Serbs 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But because Albanian women were denied health care, she and
Brovina continued to work for free, venturing into the mountains
and bringing women back to the clinics.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't have places to stay. They were there over a year,
even in minus-28-degree temperatures,'' she said. ``Women were
literally dying in the streets.''
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, Dobruna said, her friend refused to buckle.
</P>
<P>
   ``She'd say, `I'm doing what I'm doing to help people, so I
don't feel like I have to hide,' '' Dobruna said. ``We lived under
the violence all our lives. We very strangely, but very stupidly,
lost the fear.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
