<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-GALLERY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW NATIONAL MUSEUM GALLERY REPRISES PACIFIC WAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREDERICKSBURG, Texas _ Two Marines take a break on Guadalcanal;
a B-25 bomber sits ready on the deck of the USS Hornet. A Navy
Wildcat is scavenged for parts. Representations of war in the
Pacific are on display in a new venue.
</P>
<P>
   A few days after millions of TV viewers watched former President
George Bush celebrate his 75th birthday with a safe parachute
landing near Texas A&AMP;M University, hundreds of visitors gathered
around a grainy World War II film clip at the National Museum of
the Pacific War and watched a 20-year-old Bush being rescued from
the Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   His plane, a torpedo bomber, had been hit by enemy fire while on
a mission to knock out a Japanese communications center on a
Pacific island near Iwo Jima. Bush completed his mission before
parachuting to safety. He was picked up by the submarine USS
Finback. An officer on the sub filmed the rescue.
</P>
<P>
   The date was Sept. 2, 1944.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is very identifiable as a very young George Bush in that
film,'' said Helen McDonald, curator of exhibits and programs at
the Admiral Nimitz Historical Center, which houses the new $3
million National Museum of the Pacific War. The 23,000 square-foot
gallery in which the exhibits are displayed is called the George
Bush Gallery.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also have a piece of the rubber raft he was picked up in,''
she said. ``It was signed by him, and by other pilots who were
picked up by the Finback.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush was on hand for the gallery's dedication last week. Among
the visitors was a man who served on the Finback at the time of
Bush's rescue. The two didn't get a chance to meet.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was hustled off to other obligations, but he left a video
message for the thousands of visitors who are expected to see the
battle exhibits from World War II's Pacific theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``This museum is a gift to American citizens,'' Bush says in his
recorded welcoming speech, ``and a window reflecting the
foundations of our modern world.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush explains that he served under Adm. Chester Nimitz, the
Fredericksburg native for whom the complex is named. ``My family
was like millions of Americans, working tirelessly for the war
effort while waiting for the boys to come home.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly a thousand artifacts are on display in the Bush Gallery.
They range from the most simple _ Gen. Douglas MacArthur's corncob
pipe _ to an elaborate presentation of a miniature Japanese
submarine lurking off the shore of Pearl Harbor. The display takes
an entire room.
</P>
<P>
   ``That midget submarine, in that particular setting, is very
poignant and telling,'' McDonald said. ``It really sets the stage
for the rest of the exhibit. Pearl Harbor was so far away from
Japan, we really were an unsuspecting nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the exhibits are more personal. The museum considers the
acquisition of the goggles and flight helmet of Saburo Sakai
extremely important. Sakai, Japan's leading war ace with more than
60 downed planes to his credit, began building his reputation when
his squadron attacked Clark Field in the Philippines on the same
day that Pearl Harbor was attacked. During the U.S. landing on
Guadalcanal in 1942, Sakai was hit. Blinded in one eye, he flew his
Zero 560 miles back to home base while lapsing in and out of
consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   There is also the Medal of Honor posthumously awarded to Lt.
Cmdr. Howard Gilmore, who was on his submarine's conning tower when
the ship was hit. Badly wounded, he ordered ``Take her down,''
while he remained on deck. He was lost at sea, but the sub was
saved.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reception to the new gallery has been excellent,''
McDonald said. ``From the veterans, from their families, just the
general public, everyone really seems to be enjoying it.''
</P>
<P>
   The primary purpose, she said, is to reach a younger audience
and give them a better understanding of the contributions that were
made by the generation of World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ``That generation had a tremendous impact on us,'' she said,
``and they are fast leaving us. I talked to someone the other day
who said people of that generation are dying at a rate of about
1,500 a day. Soon, they'll be gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want this museum to keep their memories alive.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   INFO BOX: The National Museum of the Pacific War is the only
museum in the United States dedicated entirely to the Pacific
theater. It is part of the Admiral Nimitz Historical Center in
Fredericksburg and is under the Texas Parks and Wildlife
Department. For information, call (830) 997-8600.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
