<HEADER>
A3237 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOREA-BALLPLAYER-BOS &LR;      06-29 1371
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREA-BALLPLAYER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX CASTOFF FINDS FAME, STROKE IN SOUTH KOREA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL _ The fans are munching dried squid, guzzling potato
vodka, banging noisemakers and screaming like maniacs: ``Woo-ju!
Woo-ju! Woo-ju!'' Up at bat is ``Woo-ju,'' Korea's home-run hero,
otherwise known as . . . Tyrone Woods.
</P>
<P>
   If that doesn't sound like a Korean name, that's because it
isn't. Woods is a former Boston Red Sox minor league player who
kissed the Pawtucket, R.I., Triple A farm team goodbye in 1997 when
it became clear he wasn't going to make it to Fenway Park. He came
to South Korea for the first season that foreigners were allowed to
play in the Korean major league _ and said hello to fame, fortune,
and a whole new life.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, a man who spent a decade struggling in the minor
leagues at home surprised his new audience, his new managers and
himself by becoming the Mark McGwire of Korea _ breaking the home
run record, leading the league in runs batted in, and winning the
Most Valuable Player award. His picture graces the cover of local
sports sections almost daily, more often than the image of
Korean-born Red Sox pitcher Jin Ho Cho. (In Korea he is known as
Cho Jin Ho.)
</P>
<P>
   ``In the United States, whatever you do, it seems like it's not
enough . . . I was only a Triple A player and I was never given a
chance to go any farther,'' the 29-year-old first baseman reflected
after driving in the winning run in a game last week. ``This is
their major league, and to come and fit in right away is great.
It's everyone's dream to play in the major leagues.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods is an outsider who has become not just an insider, but a
national hero. That is no mean feat in Korea, a society that is
notoriously homogeneous, insular, and suspicious of foreigners.
Like Tom Selleck's character in the movie ``Mr. Baseball'' _ a
ballplayer who goes to Japan and must adapt to new customs _ Woods
has somehow bridged a cultural divide in a country where that gap
is pretty wide.
</P>
<P>
   Here, even the quintessential American sport of baseball has a
uniquely Korean flavor. Vendors don't hawk hot dogs or peanuts;
fans snack on squid jerky (dried, salted slabs of flattened squid),
hard-boiled eggs, sushi, and mint-green dumplings. The only beer
for sale is a low-alcohol variety that, Woods jokes, would take a
whole case to make an American tipsy. No matter; Korean fans prefer
``soju,'' a potent potato-based alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   But even that doesn't explain a ballpark atmosphere that is like
Yankee Stadium's famously rowdy bleachers _ only louder.
</P>
<P>
   The noise is thundering as fans beat together ``bangers,''
sausage-shaped plastic balloons decorated with team logos, going
wild over every base hit. A man in white satin pants, white leather
lace-up knee boots and a whistle leaps up and down on a platform to
fire up the fans. Two men in the official pep brigade bang maroon
drums that look like they came from a high school marching band.
But the biggest attraction for the mostly male, twenty-something
crowd may be the cheerleaders in white short-shorts and sneakers
who dance disco moves nonstop _ in the stands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tyrone is home run king!'' shouted Kim Eun Kuk, 30, a computer
engineer, pausing from banging his noisemaker.
</P>
<P>
   Woods appreciates the fans and the cheerleaders (``They're rowdy
the whole game''), but hasn't yet acquired a taste for dried squid
(``It's nasty'') or soju (``It's poison''). And he still thinks the
American custom of having the grounds crew manually rake the
infield in the seventh inning beats the mechanized Korean version _
a golf cart dragging a single rake behind it _ a sort of dirt
Zamboni. But those are superficial differences from playing ball
back home.
</P>
<P>
   Far more important are the social customs of conforming to group
behavior, observing formalities, respecting hierarchy, and keeping
out of trouble. A free spirit like former pro basketball star
Dennis Rodman wouldn't make it here. But Woods, a native of
Brooksville, Fla., and his wife, Cheryl, have managed so
successfully to behave in a ``Korean way'' that they have earned
the respect of their adopted compatriots.
</P>
<P>
   Ha Il Sung, the baseball commentator for Korean Broadcasting
Service, attributes Woods's popularity to his ``Asian style,'' no
less than his ballplaying skills: He never became a snob when he
got good; he is friends with other players; ``and his wife is like
a Korean wife _ she comes to every game to help motivate him; and
she is good with the other wives.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Koreans always have distance with foreigners,'' Ha said, ``but
Woods has really given us a good role model and example of a
foreigner.''
</P>
<P>
   Kim In Sik, the manager of Woods's team, the Doosan Bears, says
skill isn't the only key to success for foreigners playing in
Korea. Some former major league players, such as onetime Los
Angeles Dodger Mike Bush, have fizzled here. ``It's more . . . work
ethic and whether you can adjust to Korean lifestyle,'' Kim said.
</P>
<P>
   The acceptance issue, of course, cuts both ways. Kim admits his
Korean players were at first ``scared'' when they heard two
foreigners were joining Doosan last season. And Woods ``was not
only a foreigner, but a black person.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't know what to expect,'' Kim explained. ``Everyone
here has watched TV, but they hadn't met an African-American person
. . . They've seen gangster images, and he's nothing like that.
He's very good-looking, clean cut. They got along with him very
well and brought him into their family.''
</P>
<P>
   Koreans are sometimes accused of racism, not specifically
against blacks but against any non-Koreans. But Woods says he felt
more unspoken bias within the Red Sox organization than he ever has
here. He laughs at his nickname in some Korean papers _ ``the big
black bear'' _ explaining that it's because of his hulking build
and his team's mascot, and that it is intended affectionately in a
country that hasn't yet learned the meaning of ``politically
correct.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods hit 42 homers last year to break the Korean record _ far
short of McGwire's US record of 70. For one thing, the Korean
season is shorter than in the United States _ 126 games versus 162.
It is also true that pitching here is slower, hitting is weaker,
and fielding can be downright raggedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes we come out and play Triple A. Other times, we're
just bad,'' Woods admitted with a laugh. As of Monday night, Woods
was batting .310, with 20 homers and 65 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   The Korean league was founded in 1982 and has eight teams
sponsored by big corporations such as Doosan, the liquor
conglomerate that owns the Bears. The league has less money to
throw around than the US major leagues, but far more to spend than
the minors. Woods's salary last year jumped meteorically from the
$6,500 a month for six months he made in Pawtucket to over $130,000
a year. This season, his salary more than doubled, but Woods won't
reveal the precise figure in deference to management's wish to
avoid rivalry among players.
</P>
<P>
   After his spectacular season last year, his agent also told him
the Red Sox inquired about his returning to the minors. Woods said
he wasn't interested.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox have said Woods didn't have the stuff for the majors; he
says they spent two years ``telling me what I wanted to hear _ that
I had a great chance of making it. But it was basically lies,'' he
said with a laugh. ``They told me if someone goes down injured,
you'll be the first up. But people went down hurt all the time . .
. and I was waiting for a call that never came.''
</P>
<P>
   Demoralized by his experience with the Sox, Woods considered
becoming a firefighter. His move to Korea was a last-ditch try at
baseball, but it turned his life around. He has stayed partly for
the money, partly because he loves the country and his team, and
partly because he has become the star he never was at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It kind of makes me feel like Mo Vaughn or Ken Griffey,'' he
said, an electric smile lighting his face. ``The best thing is
feeling appreciated. No matter what you do, the fans and the front
office here are still behind you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
