<SLUG> BC-PLASTIC-SURGERY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTORS SEE BRIGHT FUTURE FOR PLASTIC SURGERY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ELIZABETH FERNANDEZ  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In the new century, the broadening terrain of
plastic surgery will offer patients not only younger faces and
trimmer torsos, but also fingers grown from cattle cells and organ
parts built on biodegradable scaffolds.
</P>
<P>
   That was the tantalizing possibility put forth Monday by doctors
meeting this week in San Francisco. Some 2,000 plastic surgeons
from around the globe are attending the 12th Congress of the
International Confederation for Plastic, Reconstructive and
Aesthetic Surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a tremendous increase in medical knowledge,''
said Dr. Ronald Iverson, former president of the American Society
of Plastic and Reconstructive Surgeons, which is hosting the forum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Physicians need to know how to assimilate this information,''
Iverson said. ``Every year, we think we've reached a new level of
technology. This meeting gives you wonderful exposure to what is
happening around the world, to an exchange of ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   Known to some as ``aesthetic correction,'' plastic surgery is a
flourishing industry, with baby boomers by the hundreds of
thousands clamoring annually for face lifts, fat transfers, tummy
tucks and other vanity procedures designed to rejuvenate sags and
bags or whittle unwanted weight. But the field, which of late has
been criticized for a spate of puzzling deaths tied to liposuction,
also encompasses reconstructive work, revising faces deformed by
cleft palates, salvaging severely burned limbs, and rebuilding
breasts lost to cancer.
</P>
<P>
   And in coming years it could do much more.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Noritaka Isogai, a hand and micro-surgeon from Japan,
unveiled slides showing a partial finger of sorts grown on the back
of a mouse. The specially engineered joint, built using three types
of cells from cattle, could be the precursor to widespread
production of human finger bones and joints, Isogai said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see a lot of children who have a congenital deformity and
are missing a finger,'' he said in an interview. ``At this point,
there is no way to reconstruct the finger except through a toe
transplant. There is no other solution. Since we can form a joint
(through tissue culturing), we can form a whole finger. This is my
dream.''
</P>
<P>
   Isogai transplanted bovine tissue onto polymer matrices that
were shaped like human finger bones. Then cartilage and tendon
cells from the shoulder of a calf were placed on that ``scaffold.''
</P>
<P>
   The structure was stitched together, then implanted under the
skin of a mouse. In 20 weeks, the tissue grew into the shape and
size of a human digit.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the relatively young field of tissue engineering
could someday be a tool for creating skin, bone, muscle, cartilage,
tendons and nerves, other surgeons said.
</P>
<P>
   Tissue engineering involves transplanting cells onto synthetic
forms where new tissue is generated. Some techniques are now being
tested on people.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an evolving concept and field of medicine,'' said Dr.
Michael Yaremchuk, a plastic surgeon with the Massachusetts General
Hospital who is also affiliated with the Plastic Surgery Research
Laboratory under the auspices of Harvard Medical School. ``There is
a limited amount of tissue. ... As plastic surgeons, we have to rob
Peter to pay Paul. Say the patient has a defect in his arm, the
idea is to take a little bit of tissue and grow it.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Yaremchuk said, liver cells could be grown to ``do
the job of the liver. ... Most is still experimental, you have to
take small steps, but the potential is enormous.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
