<HEADER>
A3248 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANCER-SURVIVOR-ART-H     06-29 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANCER-SURVIVOR-ART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANCER NO LONGER TAKES CENTER STAGE IN YOUNG MAN'S LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Photo available on Wieck database.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CELINA OTTAWAY  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ It's the room of a college kid come home for a
few days in between school and a summer job.
</P>
<P>
   A black Star Wars T-shirt sits on top of a pile of clothes to be
packed. Boxes clutter the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Mementos span the years geography wallpaper, action-figure toys
and a photograph of the class that will graduate from Brandeis
University in Waltham, Mass., next year. In the upper right corner
of the picture is Philip Mucci, his brown hair back in a ponytail
looking like the 20-year-old, biology major, ``X-Files'' fan,
I'm-not-sure-what-to-do-after-graduation college student that he
is.
</P>
<P>
   The picture doesn't say cancer survivor. Neither does the
handshake with which Mucci greets a visitor at the front door of
his family's home in Castleton, south of Albany.
</P>
<P>
   Eight years after beating a brain tumor, cancer no longer claims
center stage in Philip Mucci's life.
</P>
<P>
   Mucci is part of the first big wave of childhood cancer
survivors to reach adulthood. He faces a future full of unknowns
from how childhood cancer survivors will age to how radiation
affects the body years after it is used.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors don't know nearly as much about them as they do about
kids in their first years after cancer.
</P>
<P>
   A nationwide study of long-term childhood cancer survivors is
under way and may yield some answers. The researchers questioned
13,254 former patients who were treated between 1970 and 1986. They
collected detailed treatment histories, including the total amounts
of drugs the children had been given and what health issues the
survivors have faced since they finished treatment. It is clear
that for many survivors, cancer and the harsh therapies it took to
beat it exact a toll later in life.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Green, a childhood cancer specialist at the Roswell Park
Cancer Institute in Buffalo, has spent 20 years studying cancer
survivors and the effects of various cancer treatments.
</P>
<P>
   Many cancer therapies leave patients sterile, Green said, but
for both men and women who have remained fertile the resulting
pregnancies have largely been normal. Some women who've had
radiation to the pelvis have premature babies. And others who were
treated with certain chemotherapy drugs hit menopause 10 to 15
years early as their diminished egg supplies run out.
</P>
<P>
   Childhood cancer survivors who have been in remission for 15 or
more years are four to five times more likely to develop fatal
health problems than the rest of the population, Green said. The
higher mortality rates are mainly due to recurrences of the
original cancer, treatment-induced cancers and treatment-induced
heart diseases.
</P>
<P>
   The role of genetics in childhood cancer is a big unanswered
question, said Green.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing that is still unknown is whether the offspring are
at greater risk of developing childhood cancer,'' Green said.
``It'll probably be another two to three years before we have data
on cancer in offspring.''
</P>
<P>
   These days Mucci spends more time thinking about his new job at
a summer camp in Maryland than worrying about his odds.
</P>
<P>
   Mucci spent years staring cancer down. After he got healthy, he
returned to Albany Medical Center to work as an intern, spending a
lot of time with radiologists. He read his medical files something
he wouldn't recommend to everybody. It was hard to come face to
face with his own numbers, the high levels of radiation, the
changing odds of survival. But Mucci read on.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard reading all the technical terms that they were
using and reading that I might have died,'' he said. ``But if you
understand something, it is really hard to be afraid of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mucci went to college and majored in biology, thinking he would
go into cancer research. That has changed in the last year or so as
the urge to stare down the monster has given way to the desire to
get on with his life.
</P>
<P>
   Sometime during college, cancer loosened its grip on Mucci. He
started wearing his shoulder-length hair in a ponytail because he
likes the style even though you can now see the wide horizontal
scar, low on the back of his head, where hair no longer grows. He
recently had surgery to try and correct the damage radiation did to
his hearing.
</P>
<P>
   He has decided to hold off on fertility testing, leaving the
future to sort itself out.
</P>
<P>
   Ask him about whether he thinks about the cancer coming back and
Mucci looks you in the eye and with a little smile quotes dialogue
from ``The Empire Strikes Back.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like Yoda says,'' Mucci explains. ``Always in motion is
the future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
