 Tuesday, June 29, 1999    
 Editors      The Hearst News Service will file the following for
Wednesday. If you have questions, please call Susie McBee or Tim
Spence at 202-298-6920.    (Adds: HORMEL.)    (The ``HNS'' tag
appears in all sluglines.)   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PREVENTIVE-CARE (Washington) _ President Clinton's proposal to
overhaul Medicare includes a little noticed plan for Uncle Sam to
pay the entire cost of preventive health care measures such as
mammograms, prostate cancer screening and bone-mass measurements.
Clinton's chief economic adviser says the president opted for the
$3 billion-a-year expansion of benefits because he thinks it would
not only save lives but also cut long-term costs of treatment. By
STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   HORMEL (Washington) _ San Francisco gay rights advocate James C.
Hormel is scheduled to be sworn in as U.S. ambassador to Luxembourg
(at 4 p.m. EDT) as conservative groups protest outside the State
Department. Hormel will become the first openly gay U.S. envoy. By
JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   NUCLEAR-SAFETY (Washington) _ Congressional investigators say
the University of California should be fined for safety violations
at its Lawrence Livermore and Los Alamos nuclear weapons
laboratories. Violations included exposing workers to radioactivity
and having lax procedures for preventing nuclear accidents. By MARK
HELM.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush has the
same careless attitude toward the Constitution that his father did.
The governor has not only embraced a proposed constitutional
amendment to ban flag burning, as President George Bush did, but
also endorsed an outrageous House measure that would allow states
to permit posting the Ten Commandments in schools and other public
places. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
</TEXT>
