 PageExpress budget for the week of JUNE 28, 1999
<TEXT>
<P>
   PageExpress, a new service from The New York Times Syndicate,
consists of paginated pages built with content from Cox Newspapers
and The New York Times News Service. The pages are easy to retrieve
from a web site. You can use them just as they are or customize any
or all of the elements _ text, fonts, photos and graphics _ to suit
your needs.
</P>
<P>
   For more information on these pages, or to view a sample, use
your web browser to visit http://nytsyn.com/pageexpress.
</P>
<P>
   For the password to download and use the pages, call Bob Farnell
at The New York Times Syndicate: 800-972-3550 or e-mail him at
farnellb &LR; nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   Unless otherwise noted, pages are available after 2 p.m. Tue.,
June 29.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FOCUS (Available by 2 p.m., Fri., July 2) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS WILL INCLUDE SEVERAL PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS MONEY: As fireworks etch the skies with bright colors
for the last Independence Day of this century, the majestic dome of
the U.S. Capitol will look much as it did 99 years ago. But almost
everything else about Capitol Hill has changed in a century that
brought an explosion of staff, construction and bureaucracy _ not
to mention lobbyists _ to Congress. (Includes a large 4-column
information graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (Available by 2 p.m., Thu., July 1) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PAGE WILL INCLUDE SEVERAL PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE SET OF TODAY: ``Today,'' the first of the morning news
shows when it debuted in 1952, is amazingly dominant in the late
'90s. But it's not getting any easier. In September, ``Good Morning
America'' moves into its new studio overlooking Times Square, and
in November, CBS unwraps its new revamped show with Bryant Gumbel
as anchor and its own street-side studio on Central Park. (Includes
3-column color photo of ``Today'' star Katie Couric on the set.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: STAR FILE BRANDY: A Q&AMP;A with pop sensation Brandy.
(Includes 1-column color photo of Brandy.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: VIDEO REVIEWS: Reviews of ``Rushmore,'' ``The Thin Red
Line'' and ``Varsity Blues.'' (Includes 2-column color photo from
``Rushmore.'')
</P>
<P>
   WITH: CD REVIEWS: Reviews of the new releases from The
Pretenders, Test and a Graham Parsons tribute.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR (Available by 5 p.m., Thu., July 1) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PAGE WILL INCLUDE SEVERAL COLOR PHOTOS AND THREE COLOR
ILLUSTRATIONS.
</P>
<P>
   TOPIC: TBA.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: WINSTON CUP NOTES: Odds and ends package from Winston Cup
racing. (Includes two 6-pica color mugs of drivers.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: IN THE PITS: (Includes two thumbs-up, thumbs-down color
illustrations.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TRACK GRAPHIC: A 2-column color illustration of Daytona
International Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: WINSTON CUP STANDINGS
</P>
<P>
   WITH: BUSCH GRAND NATIONAL STANDINGS
</P>
<P>
   WITH: NEXT RACE BOX: A preview of Sunday's Pepsi 400 at Daytona
International Speedway, Daytona Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FOOD &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PAGE INCLUDES ONE COLOR ILLUSTRATION.
</P>
<P>
   TALE OF TWO KITCHENS: New York and Los Angeles may be the
temples of trendsetting cuisine, but the heart of American home
cooking lies in the heartland _ at the home of Betty Crocker and
Poppin' Fresh. (Includes 3-column color illustration of woman and
dough-boy working in the kitchen.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: FACT LIST: Items of interest about Betty Crocker and
Pillsbury.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: RECIPES: Country Style Ribs, Chocolate Goody Bars, Italian
Zuchini Crescent Pie and Country Apple Coffee Cake.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHEELS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PAGE INCLUDES FOUR COLOR PHOTOGRAPHS.
</P>
<P>
   1999 PORSCHE CARRERA CABRIOLET: The 1999 Porsche Carrera
Cabriolet offers a near-definitive testament to the notion that a
convertible sports car may not be the only way to go, but it's the
best. (Includes 4-column color photo of car's exterior and 2-column
color photo of car's interior and 1-column detail photo.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: AT A GLANCE: Fact box previewing the 1999 Porsche Carrera
Cabriolet.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: THE MECHANIC: If problems with contaminated
air-conditioning refrigerant go unchecked, they could become a
health issue. (Includes 1-column color photograph of columnist.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PERSONAL TECHNOLOGY &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PAGE INCLUDES THREE COLOR PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   SENIORS AND COMPUTERS: Attracted by the size of the market and
its potential _ the 65-to-74-year-old age group is the wealthiest
in America, according to census data _ computer makers and other
tech companies are making moves. (Includes one 4-column color photo
of elderly woman using the computer.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: INFO BOX: Facts on elderly using the computer. (Includes
18-pica color photo of woman holding a mouse.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TECH BRIEFS: With the Palm Pilot becoming increasingly
common place, there are scores of new software packages for this
handheld computer.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TECHNOBUDDY: When looking at the history of technology,
you'll find dozens of pioneering products that were important as
predictors of a basic change. In many cases, the products fell by
the wayside (Includes 1 column color sig of columnist.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: COMMENTARY: The Usenet forum was for owners of Chia pets,
those ceramic animals from mail-order TV. But who ended up on the
site was anybody's guess.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRAVEL &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PAGE INCLUDES THREE COLOR PHOTOGRAPHS AND ONE COLOR
ILLUSTRATION.
</P>
<P>
   MIAMI TOUR: Paul George started doing tours for friends in the
late 1970s. By 1983, he was doing it for University of Miami
students. He went ``public'' in 1985, aligned with the historical
association in 1988 and eventually spread out from downtown, doing
tours of places such as Miami Beach's Art Deco district and Coral
Gables. He's done tours of Fort Lauderdale since 1989. And he did
one tour along A1A from Deerfield Beach to Henry Flagler's
Whitehall mansion and museum on Palm Beach. He calls his tours ``a
painless and fascinating way'' to learn history. (Includes 3-column
color photo of Paul George directing a walking tour, 1-column color
photo of tourist enjoying walking tour.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TOUR SITES: A list of sites on the walking tour of Miami.
(Includes 2-column color graphic of tour sites.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TRAVEL BRIEFS: Passengers on United Airlines and US
Airways flights who are running late to the airport will have to
run a bit faster to make their flights under new policies designed
to have more planes arrive at their destinations on time.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: HOLOCAUST MUSEUM: On our last trip to Washington, D.C., my
husband and I visited the United States Holocaust Memorial Museum
and took our 12-year-old son. I'm glad we did, although I wish we
had taken him sooner. (Includes 2-column color photo of Aushwitz
death camp.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BOOKS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PAGE INCLUDES SEVEN COLOR PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   CREEPY-CRAWLIES: Funny how a picture book of dead, posed insects
can provoke reflection. But then you never know what to expect from
Barbara Norfleet. If you don't care for insects, her book ``The
Illusion of Orderly Progress'' will drive you buggy. (Includes
4-column color photo from book and 6-pica color photo of book
jacket.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: REVIEW: OUT FOR GOOD: Now, all these years later, when it
was least expected, Thomas Berger has produced a sequel to ``Little
Big Man.'' Although ``The Return of Little Big Man'' lacks the
scintillating surprise of the first one, this sequel is definitely
worth your time. (Includes 6-pica color photo of book jacket.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: COMIC DUO: Ben Stiller and Janeane Garofalo reveal depth
while turning the tables on the gurus of self-help. (Includes
2-column color photo of comics from the film ``Permanent
Midnight,'' and a 6-pica color photo of book jacket.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: STAHL'S CHANGING ROLES: In ``Reporting, Live,'' Lesley
Stahl recounts her journalism career. (Includes a 6-pica color
photo of book jacket.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: REDHUNTER: William F. Buckley takes a revisionist look at
McCarthyism in his new book. (Includes a 6-pica color photo of book
jacket.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: N.Y. TIMES BEST SELLERS LIST
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &AMP; HEALTH &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PAGE INCLUDES TWO COLOR PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   BALLOON THERAPY: The question was never if Lora Black would have
a hysterectomy, but when. Medication hadn't curbed the excessive
menstrual bleeding that had made her anemic and disrupted her life.
Her three older sisters had undergone hysterectomies. Now it was
her turn. But when could she take four to six weeks off to recover?
She chose summer but in the months before her operation, Black's
doctor told her about a new alternative to surgery that uses a
heated balloon to burn off the uterine lining _ the source of her
copious bleeding. It sounded good, but the word Black kept having
trouble with was ``new.'' (Includes 3-column color photo of patient
being instructed by doctor.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: BUG STUDY: Cellular biologists at the University of
Georgia are hoping to find a cure for Chagas' disease and other
parasitic infections that are major sources of plant, animal and
human illnesses and deaths. (Includes 2-column color photo of
researcher looking at microscopic organisms.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: PAIRING UP: There's more to couples getting together than
Cupid's arrow.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: SCIENCE COURT: Program aims to help courts in complicated
science matters.
</P>
</TEXT>
