<HEADER>
A3294 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STOLEN-TB-VIAL-HNS &LR;      06-29 0498
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STOLEN-TB-VIAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BURGLAR'S TAKE INCLUDES VIAL OF TUBERCULOSIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EMILY GURNON  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A vial of tuberculosis bacteria was stolen from
a medical researcher attending a tuberculosis conference here,
prompting the authorities to seek help in finding the missing
container while at the same time saying the public should not be
alarmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a general health hazard to the people of San
Francisco, but it can be a hazard to the person who has it now or
someone who might open it up,'' said Richard Lee of the San
Francisco Department of Public Health.
</P>
<P>
   The container was in a black Eddie Bauer-brand duffel bag stolen
from the hotel room of a researcher from the University of
California at Berkeley. The canister was in an inside pocket of the
bag, which also contained clothing and jewelry, leading the police
to conclude that the burglar was not out to get the bacteria, said
Capt. Ed Springer.
</P>
<P>
   The researcher had planned to exchange the vial with a fellow
researcher from the University of California at San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   The metal canister, marked with a ``biohazard'' label, is about
8 inches long and 3 to 4 inches wide, said Deputy Chief Rich Holder
of the San Francisco police. Inside that, enclosed in plastic
bubble wrap, is a 6-inch-long glass test tube containing gelatinous
material with a whitish substance _ the tuberculosis bacteria _
growing on top of it.
</P>
<P>
   One would have to breathe in the bacteria to become infected,
Lee said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone opened it, and if they got very close to it, they
could possibly contract tuberculosis,'' he said. Or someone could
come in contact with the bacteria if the vial broke.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone infected with the bacteria might show symptoms in a month
to a year, Lee said. TB attacks mainly the lungs, intestines, skin
and brain. Symptoms include a constant cough, difficulty breathing
and exhaustion.
</P>
<P>
   The police believe that whoever took the bag entered the room
from a side door for there were no signs of forced entry. Asked
whether a hotel staff person could have been involved, Holder
replied, ``That's something we'll look at.''
</P>
<P>
   Springer said police officers and security personnel at the
Cathedral Hill Hotel searched the building Monday, including all
garbage containers, trying to find the vial.
</P>
<P>
   ``The task here today is to make sure we find it before somebody
opens it up,'' Holder said.
</P>
<P>
   TB in the 1990s has returned as a significant health hazard
worldwide, in part because people with AIDS are particularly
susceptible to the disease. Also, strains of tuberculosis that are
resistant to front-line antibiotics are emerging around the world.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, TB was listed by the World Health Organization as the
world's most deadly transmittable disease.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, however, deaths from the disease worldwide dropped. TB
kills fewer than 1,000 people a year in the United States.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-99 1454EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
