<HEADER>
A3320 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEEN-INVESTIN-HNS &LR;      06-29 0645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEN-INVESTIN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW COMPANY OFFERS FINANCIAL ADVICE, SHOPPING FOR TEENS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDWARD IWATA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Ginger Thomson, who left the financial world
several years ago to raise her three children, has created a Web
site for teens to help them manage money, shop and learn about
investing.
</P>
<P>
   It's called doughNET.com.
</P>
<P>
   The site, doughNET.com, is both parent and teen friendly. The
site lets parents open on-line debit accounts for their children in
amounts such as $50 or $100.
</P>
<P>
   Teen-agers can shop on line for their favorite products,
including Urban Decay, a hip and edgy line of cosmetics; Alloy
Online, which sells clothes and accessories; and Shop.eonline.com,
which sells movie and television merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to create a free, safe environment for teens and
their families to learn about finance in the real world,'' said
Thomson, 42, doughNET's president and a former banker at Donaldson,
Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette Securities Corp.
</P>
<P>
   In an era when 10 percent of college students are saddled with
credit card debts of more than $7,000, Thomson hopes a little
education will go a long way.
</P>
<P>
   DoughNET and two similar on-line companies _ RocketCash
(www.rocketcash.com) and I Can Buy (www.icanbuy.com) hope to tap
the vast market of computer-literate youths.
</P>
<P>
   On the doughNET site, teens can learn about personal finance
through tips on how to play the stock market and links to on-line
brokerage companies and mutual funds. Later this year, doughNET
will offer on-line banking services.
</P>
<P>
   Recent articles and services appearing on the doughNET site
include a helpful primer on college loans, a story on career
planning and a calculator that estimates the car price a teen-ager
can afford.
</P>
<P>
   Teens also can donate to their favorite nonprofit causes,
including the Rainforest Alliance, the Humane Society and Youth
Service America.
</P>
<P>
   More than half of the nation's 31 million teen-agers regularly
use the Internet, according to Teenage Research Unlimited in
Northbrook, Ill. But will they shop on line until they drop? It may
take a while. Last year, only 1 percent of the $140 billion spent
by teen-agers was spent on line, according to Teen Research.
</P>
<P>
   DoughNET hopes to get its brand name out to youths with a
guerrilla marketing campaign launched recently.
</P>
<P>
   Thomson, who earned at master's degree in business
administration from Harvard University, founded doughNET last year
with her 48-year-old husband, Jon Hamren, who earned an MBA at
Stanford. Hamren is a veteran venture capitalist who has worked at
Gateway Partners, Cypress Funds and Sequoia Capital.
</P>
<P>
   Their idea was a hard sell to financiers at first, so the couple
spent $50,000 of their own cash last year to start the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone thought it was a great idea, but they wondered
whether we could really get it done,'' Hamren said. ``With all the
Internet commerce out there, could we get anybody's attention?''
</P>
<P>
   A few months ago, they persuaded Labrador Ventures in Redwood
City to pitch in $2 million in seed money in two rounds. Then, just
this month, two venture capital heavyweights _ Mayfield Fund in
Menlo Park and Maveron LLC in Seattle _ invested $7.3 million.
Mayfield has funded more than 300 high-tech companies, while
Maveron is owned by Starbucks Coffee Chairman Howard Schultz.
</P>
<P>
   Now, financiers are bullish on doughNET, which hopes to sign on
150,000 users and dozens of new merchants within 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   DoughNET predicts that each teen-ager will spend up to $700 a
year on on-line goods.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that doughNET has a significant opportunity to build
a brand that is relevant to teens and their families,'' said
Zachary Herlick, a partner at Maveron. ``It empowers teens to take
control of their financial lives.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
