<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 15:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3346 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-HELLMAN-BOS &LR;      06-29 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-HELLMAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN LIFE OVERSHADOWS ART 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN KOCH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
THE LIVES OF LILLIAN HELMAN 
Produced by: Julian Schlossberg 
Directed by: Phillip Schopper 
On: PBS 
Date: Wednesday, 9 p.m. 
 
DASHIELL HAMMETT. DETECTIVE. WRITER. 
Produced by: Margaret Smilow 
Directed by: Joshua Waletzky 
On: PBS 
Date: Wednesday, 10 p.m. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Think of Lillian Hellman and Dashiell Hammett, and what comes to
mind? The tumultuous relationship. Cigarettes dangling from their
mouths, iconically. Booze and more booze. Radical post-war
politics, the infamous Red-hunt and Hellman's timeless 1952 remark
to the House Committee on Un-American Activities: ``I cannot and
will not cut my conscience to fit this year's fashions.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, their lives overshadow their art, and perhaps for good
reason. The work of both prolific playwright Hellman and crime
novelist Hammett is decidedly dated _ although Hammett's stringent
prose in ``The Maltese Falcon'' and elsewhere resonates even now in
the best tough new crime fiction.
</P>
<P>
   So one would have hoped that, while capitalizing on a good
story, the makers of both ``Dashiell Hammett. Detective. Writer.''
and ``The Lives of Lillian Hellman'' would have made serious cases
for the quality of the writers' work. (The hour-long documentaries
air as part of the PBS ``American Masters'' series.)
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the somewhat more polished Hammett documentary at least
tries to evoke his prose, lets us hear a bit of it, and commends
its qualities in often rather clever phrases of its own. Thus, for
instance, smoky-voiced narrator Kathleen Turner refers to Hammett's
style as ``blue-collar language with white-collar trim.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hellman film, however, doesn't even take a stab at serious
literary biography, nor, except for its last few touching minutes,
does it show much flair as celebrity biography. For the most part,
it's a headlong recitation of titles of her plays and movies with
rapid-fire comments about their critical reception and box-office
grosses, and of lean biographical data. After ``The Children's
Hour'' opens to raves in 1934 and is followed by her profitable
bowlderized movie version, we learn that Hellman ``was rich and
famous while the rest of the country was starving.'' She then pens
another play, which fails, travels to Spain during the Spanish
civil war where she does broadcasts under fire, opens another play,
a hit this time, buys a farm in upstate New York, and suffers an
alcoholic depression.
</P>
<P>
   It all comes across as quite this telegraphic and disjointed,
and even the interesting talking heads involved _ friends Norman
Mailer and Jules Feiffer, intimate Peter Feibleman _ are often
edited in such a way as to make the least of their potentially
lively and valuable anecdotes.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps worst of all (not counting Eli Wallach's
irritatingly mannered narration) is the lack of thoughtful
attention in ``The Lives of Lillian Hellman'' to her complex but
central relationship with Hammett. We hear about it, of course, but
the information is, like so much of this documentary, hurried and
colorless. There is, at least, a legible account of Hellman's
bitter legal action against Mary McCarthy, who publicly called her
a liar, and provocative clips from interviews with Hellman herself.
In one, she describes her later years with Hammett when both were
battered by booze, Hammett nearing death, but Hellman with several
cat's lives left in her resilient little frame. ``It's a very hard
relationship to explain because once the so-called physicality is
gone, usually people break up. We had almost the opposite
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   One is left, finally, with a sense that her notorious toughness
was matched by a capacity for fierce devotion and a never
diminished hunger for life.
</P>
<P>
   But to better appreciate their tattered and oddly devoted love,
see the Hammett hour, which weaves their lives and work into far
more interesting patterns. Hammett's success, if relatively brief,
was stunning, and some of his creations, notably the novel ``The
Thin Man,'' drew imaginatively on his experience with Hellman. When
his own writing failed for good, Hammett functioned as kind of a
muse for Hellman. And ``Dashiell Hammet'' nicely develops his
improbably selfless role as the playwright's mentor. He gave her
the idea and background research for her reputation-securing play,
``The Children's Hour,'' and served as a mercilessly honest and
helpful editor.
</P>
<P>
   With the valuable input of at least three Hammett biographers,
who are given time to shape their interesting ideas about him, the
film makes a case for Hammett's deceptive cultural importance. Of
particular interest is Joan Mellen's claim that Hollywood's durable
ideal of masculinity _ tall, sexy, silent, smart, and heroic but
childlike men _ was modeled on Hammett himself and his fictional
creations.
</P>
<P>
   Hellman and Hammett are such provocative, intriguing characters
that almost anything reasonably accurate and literate about them is
worth a look _ as these documentaries are, especially the Hammett.
Curiously, however, a recent A&AMP;E television movie called ``Dash and
Lilly,'' based on their 30-year relationship but not a strictly
factual account of their lives, is superior to both of these
nonfiction films. It seems more true to the emotional turbulence of
their affair, and skillfully evokes Hammett's role in Hellman's
creative life. Hellman, whom virtually everyone agreed resorted to
creative deceptions if not outright lies in her own popular
memoirs, might have appreciated the irony.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-99 1527EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990629.0153 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 15:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3361 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEEN-MAGS-950(2TAKES)     06-29 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEN-MAGS-950(2TAKES)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TODAY'S TEEN MAGAZINES MAY BE SENDING MIXED MESSAGES TO GIRLS
</HEADLINE>
 
(Accompanied by BC-TEEN-MAGS-RACK, BC-TEEN-MAGS-GLANCE) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LIZ STEVENS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On its July cover, YM asks its girl readers to rate their
``Sweetie-Snagging Style.'' Teen magazine enthuses over ``Stars'
Hair Secrets.'' And Twist promises its audience ``The Truth About
Boobs.''
</P>
<P>
   The three B's: boys, beauty and body. Is that all girls think
about these days? Uh, I don't THINK so. And yet the covers of their
favorite magazines are plastered with Day-Glo headlines trumpeting
all three almost exclusively.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates for girls have become increasingly vocal about what
they assert are damaging messages perpetuated by magazines for
pre-teen and teen-age girls _ that rail thin is the only acceptable
body type and that a girl's worth is based on how she looks and how
well she attracts boys.
</P>
<P>
   These educators, parents and psychologists have appeared on
television, undertaken research, even started their own magazines
for girls.
</P>
<P>
   But as their concerns have grown, so has the market for teen
publications that stress the three B's. This week's debut of
CosmoGIRL! _ a spinoff of the racy women's magazine _ is unlikely
to appease the critics.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message that is given (in girls' magazines) is so far
afield from the reality of what today's girls look like and what
the variety of their interests happen to be,'' said Whitney
Ransome, co-executive director for the National Coalition of Girls
Schools. ``This is such a narrow view of teen girls, and that's
what bothers us.''
</P>
<P>
   Girls' magazines closely parallel women's magazines in content
and advertising. They focus primarily on fashion and beauty. They
talk a lot about men and boys. The models in the ads and the
layouts are almost universally skinny.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the magazines do tackle topics like sexuality and health
in a straightforward, honest manner, but often the written messages
about body image and physical appearance contradict the magazine's
visual content, says Teresa Thompson, a professor of communications
at the University of Dayton.
</P>
<P>
   This past winter, Thompson's class on women and communication
analyzed the content of 90 issues of various teen magazines. The
students, Thompson reports, found ``token'' remarks encouraging
girls to accept their body shapes, ``a nod to empowerment''
outweighed by the emphasis on getting a guy, and ``an occasional
comment'' about eating disorders juxtaposed with ads full of
waiflike models.
</P>
<P>
   This last criticism is especially significant: A recent Brigham
Young University study concluded that media images of women
perpetuate eating disorders in girls, though the images aren't the
sole cause of the disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``To these young women who are at risk, some of these beauty and
fashion magazines can be as dangerous as giving a beer to an
alcoholic,'' researcher Steven Thomsen noted.
</P>
<P>
   Magazines are far from the only medium girls look at, but a 1997
study by Children Now found that 24 percent of 10- to 17-year-olds
read fashion magazines ``very often.'' The report examined the four
top teen magazines in the fall of 1996 and discovered that 35
percent of the articles focused on dating; only 12 percent looked
at school or careers. Thirty seven percent of the articles dealt
with appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a fashion and beauty magazine, and in a fashion and
beauty magazine you show clothes and makeup,'' said Roberta Caploe,
executive editor of Seventeen magazine. Fourteen million girls read
the publication each month partly because they aspire to be
fashionable, and ``I don't think there's anything wrong with
that,'' Caploe said. ``The magazine is only reflecting what's going
on in society.''
</P>
<P>
   Seventeen debuted in 1944 and has survived by changing. It used
to have a monthly feature devoted to wedding planning, and its
articles coached girls on the ladylike way to exit a car.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, last month's issue included an essay by Jamie Byrd,
who wrote about her father James Byrd's racially motivated murder
in Jasper, and the Sex and Body column answered the question, ``Can
you get AIDS from oral sex?''
</P>
<P>
   In January 1998, the magazine began using plus-size models (size
10 and up) in its regular fashion spreads. (Other girls magazines
such as Girl and Jump do the same.)
</P>
<P>
   MORE &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the competition really puts a lot of emphasis on
getting a guy,'' Caploe said, ``but we feel other things are
equally important in a young woman's life: friends, school, having
a sense of the world at large.''
</P>
<P>
   Seventeen and its competitors regularly tackle serious issues:
international refugee crises, AIDS and date rape, for instance. The
magazines also encourage girls to read, notes Robert Butterworth,
the child psychologist behind Teen magazine's Ask a Guy column.
</P>
<P>
   Some magazine content, he says, may even help teens from various
backgrounds better understand one another. Plus, ``they're getting
stuff (about sex and relationships) their parents might not be
talking to them about.'' Butterworth further emphasizes that his
columns never suggest that girls take a back seat to boys.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the most recent issue of Teen is a virtual hunk fest,
filled with photos of boy bands and features like ``What's His Love
Style?'' ``Who's That Babe?'' and ``Dumped? How to Deal.'' The June
Seventeen cover announces ``Guywatch: Meet them, schmooze them,
snag them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think girls need accurate information,'' said Nancy Gruver,
publisher of New Moon: The Magazine for Girls and Their Dreams.
``But if that one piece of valuable information is couched in 180
pages of sexual innuendo about `What do boys find sexy?' that's
where I have the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, when her twin daughters were 11 years old, Gruver
created New Moon, an ad-free magazine run by girls. An editorial
board of 17 8- to 14-year-olds chooses cover art, picks stories and
decides which letters to the editor to publish.
</P>
<P>
   The bimonthly based in Duluth is far from flashy, but its goal
is to promote empowerment through intellectual and creative
pursuits.
</P>
<P>
   ``My passion is to help girls tell the world who they are,''
Gruver said, ``instead of letting (the culture) tell girls the way
they should be.''
</P>
<P>
   Ransome believes it would be unfair to girls _ who have
legitimate interests in their appearance during adolescence _ and
unrealistic for parents to pry teen magazines out of their
daughters' hands.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, she says, talk with girls about the publications
they're reading.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we need to become savvy media analysts and know how to
look at these stories as well as the pictures and be able to
critique them on a reality meter,'' said Ransome, who encourages
girls to ``take issue'' with how they are portrayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Write letters to the editor, start your own campaign,'' she
added. It will take more than a handful of complaints from parents
and educators, Ransome said, to persuade publishers to change their
recipe for success.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
