<DOCNO> NYT19990629.0156 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 15:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3364 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEEN-MAGS-RACK-TEX     06-29 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEN-MAGS-RACK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A ROUNDUP OF WHAT TEEN MAGAZINES ARE ON THE RACKS
</HEADLINE>
 
(Accompanies BC-TEEN-MAGS, BC-TEEN-MAGS-GLANCE) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LIZ STEVENS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   CosmoGIRL!
</P>
<P>
   No cleavage on the cover! Cosmopolitan has curbed its infamously
titillating tone for this new spinoff. Heavier on the topic of boys
than Seventeen, with lots more star-gazing, too (celebrity
romances, style, makeup, a fold-out calendar with their birthdays).
A brief article explains why having a boyfriend isn't that
important; another tells the story of a model who recovered from
anorexia nervosa.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our message, through advice, inspiration and scoop is that our
reader can be all that she desires to be,'' says Atoosa Rubenstein,
the mag's 27-year-old editor, in the press kit. ``This is what
distinguishes CosmoGIRL! from other teen-age titles.''
</P>
<P>
   Hmmm. Doesn't look all that different to us. But then again,
we're not 14.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Girl
</P>
<P>
   A girl-centered style magazine that features full-figured models
in almost all fashion spreads. A story about hair removal ends with
a bold ``Reality Check!'' reminding girls that body hair is
``completely natural and normal.'' Debuted in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Girls' Life
</P>
<P>
   A down-to-earth mag for younger girls with very little celebrity
fawning and an entire page devoted to books. The June/July issue's
Last Laugh feature is a hysterical roundup of ``Deep Thoughts from
Supermodels.'' Debuted in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Honey
</P>
<P>
   A stylish and sophisticated magazine aimed at college-age
African-American women. Heavy on fashion and relationships, with
several substantive articles, including one on female genital
mutilation. Debuted in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Jump
</P>
<P>
   This month's issue features a refreshing four-page swimsuit
spread with all ``plus size'' (meaning size 10 and up) girls.
Heavier on boys, makeup and celebs than Girls' Life and Girl.
Debuted in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   LatinGirl
</P>
<P>
   With departments like Mi Barrio, in which girls write about
their lives, this new mag has some meat on it. There's moderate
concentration on boys, more on fashion and beauty, a books page and
heavy focus on Hispanic pop culture. Debuted in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   MXG (MoxieGirl)
</P>
<P>
   A sly combo of catalog and magazine in which every item pictured
can be ordered through a toll-free number run at the bottom of each
page. Light on the ``boyz'' stuff, with a story in the latest issue
about plus-size model Mia Tyler. Debuted in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   New Moon
</P>
<P>
   Edited by a staff of 8- to 14-year-olds. Accepts no advertising,
and most graphics are illustrations. The May/June issue has stories
about the Japanese art of shodo and an interview with
African-American filmmaker Julie Dash. Debuted in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Seventeen
</P>
<P>
   The grande dame of teen magazines has added plus-size models to
some fashion spreads, offers fiction and often stories that tackle
weighty issues. Heavy on fashion, with a moderate amount of
boy-centered material and straight talk about sex. Debuted in 1944.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Teen
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Girl, Teen's hair-removal headline tells girls ``you
can't be carefree unless your skin is smoothly hair-free.'' Loads
about boys in the July issue, along with a story on teen-age
abductions (and how to stay safe). Debuted in 1957.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Teen People
</P>
<P>
   Ever heard of something called People magazine? Swap Whitney
Houston for Britney Spears, and you've got Teen People. Debuted in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Twist
</P>
<P>
   Ninety-eight pages of celebrity gossip, hunky boys, romance
advice, pop culture and fashion. A graphic asking ``Is he
summer-fling material?'' tells girls to ``dis'' a guy if ``he
drives his parents' minivan.'' Debuted in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   YM (Young &AMP; Modern)
</P>
<P>
   This month's quiz asks ``Do you have a sexy personality?'' and
the Babe Watch section checks out ``Surfer Studs.'' That's balanced
with results from the love and marriage poll and a feature on a
girl born with a facial deformity. Debuted in 1940 as Calling All
Girls, changed to YM in 1966 (which stood for Young Miss until
1989).
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
