<DOCNO> NYT19990629.0157 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 15:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3369 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRENCH-DISCO-TEX     06-29 0973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRENCH-DISCO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SACRE BLEU! AMERICANS DISCOVER DISCO `MUSIQUE'
</HEADLINE>
 
(Accompanied by BC-FRENCH-DISCO-GLANCE, BC-FRENCH-DISCO-PRIMER) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MALCOLM MAYHEW 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It started with a breath of fresh Air.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, a French duo called Air released one of 1998's most
critically acclaimed CDs, ``Moon Safari,'' a techno-meets-lounge
effort that, critics wrote, was a refreshing change of pace from
typical pop music.
</P>
<P>
   Music listeners seemed to think so, too: The disc wound up
selling more than a half-million copies _ and that was on this side
of the shore.
</P>
<P>
   Echoing what happened when Nirvana was unearthed in Seattle, the
discovery of Air has drawn a degree of attention to France's
dance-music scene, which has been bubbling since the mid-'90s.
</P>
<P>
   But now, thanks to Air's success, and a recent Billboard
charting of French duo Les Nubians, French dance acts are garnering
attention from wider audiences. Is France the next Seattle? In its
own unique way, it already is _ and has been for awhile.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where some of the most exciting electronic music is
being made right now,'' says Booth Beckett, a manager at Dallas'
Core Records, an independent record shop that specializes in dance
music. ``America is known for dance music, but the French stuff has
been on a different level. Some of it is just phenomenal.''
</P>
<P>
   Beckett says that although Air and Les Nubians _ a rhythm and
blues-flavored duo whose debut, ``Princesses Nubiennes,'' recently
cracked Billboard's 200 chart _ have grabbed the attention, the
real stars of France's dance-music scene are a circle of artists
who merge '70s funk with '90s grooves for a formula they like to
call ``French disco.''
</P>
<P>
   The forefathers of this sound: Daft Punk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Daft Punk is one of the main reasons (French acts) are getting
all this exposure,'' Beckett says, commenting on a recent Spin
magazine article on French groups and MTV offshoot M2's playing of
French bands' videos. ``They were one of the first (groups) to dig
up old funk riffs. They laid the groundwork for a lot of what's
going on over there today.''
</P>
<P>
   Daft Punk is a two-man operation made up of Guy-Manuel de
Homem-Christo and Thomas Bangalter. They are as popular as they are
low-key: They shy away from interviews but perform to sell-out
crowds in their homeland. Their bestselling CD, ``Homework,'' has
sold more than a million copies but was made on a modest budget _
and in their homes. During photo shoots, they wear disguises.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's because they don't want to sell out,'' Beckett says.
``They don't want to be known. That's the cool thing about them _
they're getting more and more popular with mainstream music fans,
but people in the underground still like them, because they've kept
their integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   Other groups that have followed Daft Punk's lead include
Stardust (actually a Daft Punk offshoot), Cassius, DJ Cam, Kid
Loco, La Funk Mob and Motorbass. French record labels _ many of
which, such as Source and Roulette, are owned or partially owned by
artists _ sell their records by the ton.
</P>
<P>
   One of the few labels on this side of the globe to distribute
records by French disco acts is Astralwerks, also home to techno
heroes the Chemical Brothers and Fatboy Slim.
</P>
<P>
   It's too bad, Astralwerks' Dan Cohen says, that more U.S. labels
aren't releasing efforts by these groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are bands in France that are selling tons of records
that never get released in America,'' says Cohen, the label's
national director of publicity.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's understandable,'' he says. ``French music hasn't had
the best reputation. There wasn't much that people were going nuts
about until (these artists) came along. But now a lot of big U.S.
producers are into it, and that's helped get their music translated
in America. It also legitimizes them before they even take a step
on these shores.''
</P>
<P>
   Astralwerks has played a major role in exposing French disco
artists to U.S. audiences. Astralwerks compilations, such as
``Source Material'' and ``Respect Is Burning,'' featured tracks by
French artists that eventually made it to U.S. dance clubs and
dance-music airwaves.
</P>
<P>
   One of the label's most significant releases has been a recent
one: ``1999,'' the latest CD by Cassius, a supergroup made up of
members of other French groups (and no, ``1999'' is not a Prince
cover). ``They're pretty much `It' right now,'' Cohen says.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason Cassius is so popular is that fans of this
genre of music recognize the names of the other acts that Cassius
members are involved in: La Funk Mob and Motorbass.
</P>
<P>
   ``It works a lot like hip-hop does over here,'' Cohen says.
``The names of the band members are recognizable, so it's gonna
sell well.''
</P>
<P>
   Like America's hip-hop scene, the people involved in it support
one another, performing on and/or producing each other's records.
That's one difference between France's dance music scene and
America's.
</P>
<P>
   ``In America, as far as dance music goes, everyone competes,''
says Beckett. ``In France, they work with each other. This is the
first time France has been recognized for putting out quality
music, so everyone's supporting each other.''
</P>
<P>
   But there's more to new French music than French disco, says
Celia Faussart, half of the sister duo Les Nubians (the other
sister: Helene). Celia says that although she supports French
disco, she'd hate for it to get singled out and overshadow France's
music scene as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   ``Behind America, France is the second-biggest country for
hip-hop,'' she said in a recent phone interview. ``There's a
hip-hop scene, rock and world music scene. It's not just dance
music. We have a great pop scene here.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
