</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRENCH-DISCO-GLANCE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIVE KEY DISCS FROM FRENCH DISCO ARTISTS:
</HEADLINE>
 
(Accompanies BC-FRENCH-DISCO, BC-FRENCH-DISCO-PRIMER) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MALCOLM MAYHEW 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   1. DAFT PUNK, ``Homework'': Three years old, this wonderfully
mesmerizing disc _ full of hypnotic dance grooves and funky samples
_ still sounds as fresh as it did in 1996, when French disco was
just taking off. This record helped lay the groundwork for what
French dance music is today.
</P>
<P>
   2. CASSIUS, ``1999'': This is what French dance music is today.
Cassius is sort of like French disco's Garbage: It's made up of two
producers, Hubert Blanc-Francard and Philippe Zdar, who, like the
rhythm section of Garbage, decided to start their own band.
``1999'' is a wildly varied culmination of the different genres
Zdar and Francard have toyed with, from hip-hop to funk to house.
</P>
<P>
   3. AIR, ``Moon Safari'': Although not exactly dance music,
``Moon Safari'' is groove-driven, with an ambient, loungey
undertone. Good chill-out music.
</P>
<P>
   4. VARIOUS ARTISTS, ``Respect Is Burning Vol. 2'': If you want a
broad taste of French disco, go here. The second volume of
Astralwerks' now hard-to-find ``Respect Is Burning'' compilation
features tracks by Stardust, Deejay Punk-Roc, Francesco Grant and
several others.
</P>
<P>
   5. VARIOUS ARTISTS, ``Source Material'': French label Source has
been chronicling French disco for several years now; this
collection of tracks from artists like Phoenix, Sebastien Tellier
and Ernest Saint Laurent, among others, is a good place to start.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
