<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 16:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3385 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MASTER-CHEF-NYT &LR;      06-29 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASTER-CHEF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A STANDARD OF THE AMERICAN SHORE GETS CITIFIED 
</HEADLINE>
  This is the sixth of eight columns by Thomas Keller, the chef and
owner of the French Laundry in Yountville, Calif. His collaborator
is Michael Ruhlman. 
(jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every summer, Mom took us to visit my aunt and uncle, who owned
a tavern in Gambrills, Md. There, we ate soft-shell crab
sandwiches: blue crabs just after they had molted, fried and served
on two slices of bread with lettuce, tomato and tartar sauce. I
still love the multi-flavored, textural experience of a soft-shell
crab sandwich _ the crispy shell, the meaty interior and the
flavorful mustard, tomalley and roe.
</P>
<P>
   I wanted to serve a version of the sandwich in the restaurant,
and the trick was how to reinterpret this great rustic classic as
something appropriate for people expecting to eat highly refined,
French-inspired food.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out to be easy. Instead of white bread, I use a round
of toasted brioche, rich and delicious. Tomato confit _ wedges of
slowly roasted tomato transformed into intense bursts of flavor _
takes the place of the sliced raw tomato. Arugula is the lettuce,
though any sharp Asian green or cress will provide a peppery
counterpoint to the sweet crab.
</P>
<P>
   The sauce is still a tartar sauce, but one that is made with
hard yolks, cornichons and shallots, and refined by a tiny dice of
colorful vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   I trim the crab to make its shape a little more elegant and
proportionate to the brioche round. And I always check the quality
of the crab; the shell should be no more resistant than silk
(though if the shell is hard it can be removed and discarded).
</P>
<P>
   And that's all there is to it _ the soft-shell crab sandwich
with tartar sauce, lettuce and tomato, as haute cuisine.
</P>
<P>
   CHESAPEAKE BAY SOFT-SHELL CRAB SANDWICH
</P>
<P>
   Time: 50 minutes
</P>
<P>
   2{ teaspoons finely diced ( 1/16 inch) carrots
</P>
<P>
   2{ teaspoons finely diced ( 1/16 inch) turnips
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon finely diced ( 1/16 inch) dark green leek greens
</P>
<P>
   2 hard-boiled egg yolks
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons hot chicken broth or water
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons liquid from bottled cornichons
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   { cup canola oil, plus more for frying
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons minced cornichons
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced shallot
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced parsley
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon capers
</P>
<P>
   6 soft-shell crabs, cleaned and trimmed of legs except for claws
</P>
<P>
   All-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   Clarified butter for sauteing crabs (optional)
</P>
<P>
   6 brioche rounds, 2\ inches in diameter and \ inch thick,
lightly toasted
</P>
<P>
   6 pieces tomato confit, at room temperature (recipe follows)
</P>
<P>
   \ cup baby arugula, or thinly shredded arugula leaves.
</P>
<P>
   1. Prepare sauce: Fill a medium saucepan half full of water;
bring to a boil. Prepare an ice bath by filling a large mixing bowl
with water and ice. In a small strainer, combine carrots, turnips
and leeks. Submerge strainer in the boiling water about 10 seconds,
then plunge into the ice bath a few seconds. Drain vegetables on
paper towels. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   2. In the container of a blender, combine egg yolks, broth,
cornichon liquid and mustard. With machine running, slowly drizzle
in { cup canola oil to emulsify. Transfer to a small bowl, and add
blanched vegetables, cornichons, shallot, parsley and salt and
pepper to taste. Refrigerate up to 2 days; bring to room
temperature before serving.
</P>
<P>
   3. Prepare capers: Pat dry with paper towels. In a very small
saucepan over medium-low heat, heat about 2 inches canola oil to
250 degrees. Add the capers, and fry slowly until the bubbles stop
forming around them and they are dry and crunchy, 12 to 15 minutes.
Drain capers on paper towels. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   4. Prepare crabs: Cut off the two large claws from each body,
and reserve. Using scissors, trim the sides of each body for a
smooth edge. In a large mixing bowl, combine about 1 cup flour with
salt and pepper to taste. Dredge crab bodies and claws in flour,
shaking off excess.
</P>
<P>
   5. In a large skillet over medium heat, add clarified butter or
canola oil to a depth of [ inch. Place crab bodies shell side down
in the skillet, and adjust heat so crabs sizzle but the butter or
oil does not pop. Saute crab bodies until they are golden brown and
crusty, 2 to 3 minutes. Turn bodies, and add claws. Turn the claws
after about 1 minute. Cook about 2 more minutes. Remove crabs, and
drain on paper towels.
</P>
<P>
   6. To serve, place a spoonful of sauce in the center of each of
six serving plates. Center a brioche round on the sauce, and top it
with a crab body. Place a piece of tomato confit on top of each
body, folded if necessary, and finish with a stack of baby arugula.
Sprinkle each dish with fried capers. Serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   TOMATO CONFIT
</P>
<P>
   Time: 2\ hours
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   6 whole ripe tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   Extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Fresh thyme sprigs.
</P>
<P>
   1. Fill a medium saucepan half full of lightly salted water, and
bring to a boil. Prepare an ice bath by filling a large mixing bowl
with ice and water. Cut and discard cores from tomatoes, and cut a
shallow ``X'' through the skin on the bottom of each. Drop tomatoes
into boiling water for a few seconds, then transfer to ice bath.
Peel tomatoes and cut into quarters through the stem, or if large
cut into 6 pieces. Remove remaining pulp or seeds to leave a smooth
tomato petal.
</P>
<P>
   2. Preheat oven to 250 degrees. Cover a baking sheet with
aluminum foil. Drizzle foil with olive oil, and lightly sprinkle
with salt and pepper. Place tomato petals with the insides facing
down on the foil, and drizzle with more oil. Salt and pepper tops
of tomatoes, and top each with a small sprig of thyme.
</P>
<P>
   3. Bake until tomatoes have partially dried, but retain some
juices, 1{ to 2 hours. Discard thyme. Cover; can be refrigerated
until ready to use. Bring to room temperature before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 24 pieces.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
