<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990629.0163 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 16:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3387 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WINE-TALK-NYT &LR;      06-29 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN FRANCE, A RUMBLE IS HEARD: `VIVE GALLO' 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By FRANK J. PRIAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ For an American winemaker, France is the belly of the
beast, a virtually impenetrable market. From Bordeaux to Burgundy,
from Champagne to Beaujolais, American wines are about as popular
as some new strain of vine-eating bug.
</P>
<P>
   But you wouldn't learn that by talking with Michael Novy, a
breezy, 32-year-old Chicagoan charged with nothing less than
establishing the wines of Ernest and Julio Gallo in France. While
his reception often has been about as warm as that accorded the
Americans who stormed the Normandy beaches 55 years ago, Novy is
confident that he, and the giant California winery he represents,
will prevail.
</P>
<P>
   Gallo has had considerable success in the rest of Europe. After
little more than a year in Germany, its 1998 sales there were a
million cases. Gallo wines also have a modest presence in Belgium,
the Netherlands and Scandinavia. And its sales in Great Britain
last year came to some two million cases.
</P>
<P>
   The most popular Gallo labels overseas are Turning Leaf and the
Ernest &AMP; Julio Gallo Wine Cellars. In European markets, Gallo
advertising emphasizes the Gallo family heritage, tapping into the
Old World respect for family ties and for elders.
</P>
<P>
   In France, striving for a youthful image, the company focuses
its advertising on Gina and Matt Gallo, Julio Gallo's
grandchildren, the third generation in the business.
</P>
<P>
   Novy and his team set up shop in France just a year ago in
Boulogne-Billancourt, just outside Paris, after studying the market
for quite some time. ``We were really surprised,'' he said. ``We'd
been lead to believe that the French were unalterably opposed to
non-French wine. What we discovered was that about 10 percent of
all French wine drinkers would like to try something else.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he was targeting the 25-to-40-year-old consumer with
disposable income, a yen for travel and a taste for American movies
in English. Turned away by some of the major French wine
distributors, Gallo got a more encouraging response from
supermarket chains like Auchan, Casino and Carrefour.
</P>
<P>
   Not too many years ago, poor vintages and wines from marginal
regions were dismissed by Frenchmen as ``supermarket wines.'' Now,
some of the most prestigious winemakers, including famous Bordeaux
chateaus and small Burgundy estates, are not unhappy seeing their
labels on supermarket shelves. Which has not always made things
easier for Novy and Gallo. Some supermarkets have ordered him to
remove his wines after only a few days on display because they
weren't selling.
</P>
<P>
   Novy said Gallo's immediate goals were modest. Fewer than 2,000
cases were sold in France last year, and he hopes to sell about
5,000 cases in 1999. Not much for a company that produces some 75
million cases of wine and spirits a year. But Novy is undeterred.
``It will take us 5 to 10 years'' to see a return on investment, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Gallo may be the best-known American winemaker trying to open up
the French market, but there are others. American wine exports last
year totaled about $530 million, most of it to Canada. Exports to
France totaled only about $8 million.
</P>
<P>
   If France is a particularly tough market to crack, the reason
has more to do with economics than chauvinism. Even though the
French drink more wine than anyone else _ more than 16 gallons a
person a year, compared with just under 2 gallons a person in the
United States, according to Impact, a trade publication _ wine
consumption in France has fallen steadily since the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   Recent figures show that more than half of all French adults
drink no wine at all. Each year millions of gallons of surplus
French wine are converted to alcohol and burned.
</P>
<P>
   The rare Bordeaux wines that sell for astronomical prices and
make headlines account for only 2 percent of Bordeaux's production;
the amount of expensive Burgundy, compared with France's total
output, is even smaller.
</P>
<P>
   A powerful, resourceful competitor like Gallo is understandably
viewed with alarm. Not by Chateau Lafite-Rothschild, perhaps, but
by dozens of major producers of average table wines.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, the French image of American wine could change
rapidly. Since a now-historic blind tasting in Paris in 1976, when
French experts preferred some relatively unknown California wines
to some of the most famous Bordeaux, French winemakers have had
considerable respect for American wines.
</P>
<P>
   Young French winemakers regularly apprentice at California
wineries, and it's no secret that many prominent Bordeaux wine
producers now make their wines in the less tannic, earlier-maturing
California style. Many other winemakers, particularly in the south
of France, have adopted the American practice of identifying wines
by their grapes, rather than by the place from which they come.
</P>
<P>
   In commenting on Gallo's initial moves into the French market,
the newspaper Le Monde noted that Gallo, the largest winery in the
world, has a long-standing relationship with Wal-Mart, the largest
retailer in the world, and that the two were working together in
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart recently acquired Asda Group PLC, Britain's
third-largest supermarket chain, which can only strengthen Gallo's
position there. Wal-Mart has as yet no position in France, but the
moves in Germany and Britain leave little doubt that Gallo intends
to be a major participant in the wine business in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are here for the long term,'' Novy said, and it's evident
that Gallo has the means to be patient. The company had an
estimated $1.2 billion in sales in 1998, which, Le Monde noted, is
a little more than was sold by the entire Bordeaux wine exporting
business. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
