A3392 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-WILSON-HNS &LR;      06-29 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-WILSON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR NOW, BUSH SKIRTS SOME GOP OFFICIALS IN CALIFORNIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ The presidential campaign of Gov. George W. Bush
appears to be keeping its distance from former California Gov. Pete
Wilson and some of his key strategists as the Texan tries to spread
his message of inclusiveness in California.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, the state's most successful Republican in recent years,
was dubbed a compassionate conservative years before Bush. He won
four straight elections in a state dominated by Democrats and he
knows how to squeeze cash out of the tightest wallets. Most of the
state's most astute GOP political strategists are intimately
connected to Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   But the former governor and his inner circle carry unwieldy
baggage. Wilson was a major supporter of Proposition 187, the
anti-illegal immigrant ballot initiative blamed for scaring away
Hispanic voters from the Republican Party and hurting the 1998
gubernatorial campaign of former California Attorney General Dan
Lungren.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see how it would do Bush any good to be publicly seen
hanging around with Wilson,'' said Mark Petracca, chairman of the
political science department at the University of California at
Irvine. ``Bush's hope to win the presidency _ and this is already
showing in the opinion polls _ rests on his ability to attract a
key minority group of voters to eat into the base support of the
Democratic Party. One key group is certainly Latinos.''
</P>
<P>
   Leslie Goodman, Bush's California adviser who worked in Wilson's
communications office for three years, rejects the notion that the
former governor or his people are being excluded from the campaign,
saying the people who want to help offer ``an embarrassment of
riches.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about going back to the Nixon days, the Reagan
days, the Deukmejian days, to the Wilson days and the Lungren
campaign, all of whom we hope to be part of a massive campaign,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is trying to smooth the Republican Party's hard edges by
defining himself as a compassionate conservative without distancing
himself too far from the GOP's powerful right wing.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson has had no visible role in Bush's campaign, although
campaign sources say Wilson may eventually be named an honorary
co-chairman. Wilson hasn't even decided whether he'll endorse Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this juncture, there are a number of presidential
candidates who have either met personally or spoken with (Wilson)
on the phone seeking his support and advice on the state,'' said
Wilson spokesman Sean Walsh. ``The governor has not decided to
endorse any specific candidate, but there are a couple who have
impressed him greatly.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson handed over the governor's office to Democrat Gray Davis
in January after serving two terms. Wilson's tough position on
illegal immigration is blamed for alienating Hispanic voters in the
state.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Bush has spent five years as governor courting
Hispanics. He traveled to Mexico frequently, and won nearly half
the Hispanic vote in his re-election last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There needs to be a message that speaks to the values that the
Hispanic community can understand,'' Bush said after arriving
Monday night in San Diego. ``I've done a good job in Texas in
reaching out to the Hispanic community. I intend to do the same
thing here.''
</P>
<P>
   Some political observers believe that it would harm Bush to shun
the former California governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why Governor Bush wouldn't be reaching out more
aggressively to Wilson and to the people around him, but it would
be a very smart thing to,'' said Dan Schnur, a former Wilson
spokesman who recently took a job with another Republican
presidential candidate, Sen. John McCain of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Goodman, other former Wilson officials have joined the
front-running Bush campaign. Bush has brought aboard Eloise
Anderson, Wilson's social services director, and Ann Veneman,
Wilson's secretary for food and agriculture, to his statewide
leadership team. Another California co-chair is Gerald Parsky, a
Wilson appointee to the University of California regents.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson spoke to Bush to discuss California politics after Wilson
decided not to enter the presidential race earlier this year. Some
of Wilson's chief advisers have been informally contacted by the
Bush campaign. And Wilson's closest confidant, former chief of
staff Bob White, is helping raise money for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   But some top members of the Wilson team haven't yet moved to the
Bush camp. They include Schnur and Wilson's husband-and-wife
communications team, Kim and Sean Walsh.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign so far has avoided Lungren's advisers.
</P>
<P>
   Goodman said the campaign had received more requests than they
could handle from people wanting to work for them, and ``one of the
things this campaign is not doing right now is paying for expensive
consultants.''
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Jim Brulte, a Republican from Rancho Cucamonga and a
Bush supporter, said: ``If you know anything about George W. Bush,
and his style and his campaigning, he is inclusive by nature.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
