<HEADER>
A3405 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRESERVE-BOOK-REVIEW-     06-29 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRESERVE-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESERVING THE BEST OF EACH SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By FLORENCE FABRICANT    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let's face it: Great-Grandma would not recognize home canning
today. For most of us, it's not driven by the need to fill the
pantry before the onset of winter (or a fear of Y2K problems), nor
is it much of a money-saver.
</P>
<P>
   Preserving and pickling have largely become recreational
activities: to put up a few jars of homemade strawberry jam or
peach preserves when these fruits are at their peak, to be able to
serve our own bread-and-butter pickles to friends and family and to
know exactly what ingredients go into what we eat. This approach to
canning inspired Anne Gardon, who lives on a farm in Quebec, to
write ``Preserving for All Seasons'' (Firefly Books, $24.95,
paper). She also took the book's stunning photographs.
</P>
<P>
   In the introduction, she explains that she used to spend all
summer canning and preserving, but now she is more relaxed,
preparing jams, pickles, sauces, chutneys, herb mixes and the like
with seasonal produce throughout the year. ``I eat my preserves
within a few weeks or a few months, instead of keeping them for
later,'' she writes, which makes preserving less of a chore.
</P>
<P>
   Most of her recipes are for smaller quantities than in many home
canning guides, so you can make preserves without having your
kitchen look like a subsidiary of Smucker's. And though Ms. Gardon
packs her jams, pickles and sauces in sterilized jars, she usually
refrigerates or freezes them, making processing them in a boiling
water bath or pressure-canner unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   The book touches on the safety factor, but not in the kind of
detail you find in the heavy-duty home-canning books, or the
manuals published by the Agriculture Department or the canning-jar
companies. To be on the safe side, a less-experienced canner should
plan to refrigerate the pickles, preserves and chutneys.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Ms. Gardon's recipes contain enough acid (vinegar) or
sugar to make spoilage unlikely. The results can be refrigerated
and used in a relatively short time, within about three months,
further minimizing any risk. Ms. Gardon recommends freezing some
jams and condiments, like a chutney, but doesn't say for how long;
I think six months would be the limit.
</P>
<P>
   But I was surprised that the recipes for seasoned oils, which
are low-acid and not processed, did not specify refrigerating them.
(At minimum, they can spoil if they are not. At room temperature,
oil flavored with some seasonings, like fresh garlic, can provide a
breeding ground for toxins.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Preserving for All Seasons'' offers some good tips, like
selecting citrus fruits with thick skins for the most tender
candied peels, and not discarding the seeds from fresh hot chilies,
as most recipes require, but saving, drying and grinding them for
later use as a seasoning.
</P>
<P>
   APRICOT AND HONEY COMPOTE
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``Preserving for All Seasons'' Time: 1 hour
</P>
<P>
   2 cups fresh apricot puree (about 1{ pounds pitted fresh
apricots)
</P>
<P>
   1 cup honey.
</P>
<P>
   1. Combine ingredients in heavy saucepan and bring slowly to a
boil. Reduce heat and simmer until thick, stirring frequently,
about 35 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   2. Ladle into sterilized canning jars and seal. Store in
refrigerator up to 3 months.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 2 cups.
</P>
<P>
   ALMOND-PEACH JAM  &QL; 
Adapted from ``Preserving for All Seasons'' Time: 45 minutes
</P>
<P>
   6 medium-large ripe pitted peaches, in chunks (about 4 cups)
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon pure almond extract.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Combine ingredients in heavy saucepan and bring slowly to a
boil. Reduce heat and simmer until thick, about 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   2. Ladle into sterilized canning jars and seal. Store in
refrigerator up to 3 months.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 3 cups.
</P>
<P>
   CURRIED SLICED PICKLES
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``Preserving for All Seasons'' Time: 30 minutes,
plus brining
</P>
<P>
   3 pounds Kirby cucumbers
</P>
<P>
   { cup pickling salt or kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon curry powder, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 cups cider vinegar
</P>
<P>
   2{ cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon mustard seeds
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon celery seeds.
</P>
<P>
   1. Wash cucumbers and slice \-inch thick. Place in a large
stainless-steel bowl. Dissolve salt in 8 cups cold water, pour over
slices and let stand 5 hours.
</P>
<P>
   2. Rinse under cold water and drain.
</P>
<P>
   3. Combine remaining ingredients in a large saucepan and bring
to a boil. Add more curry powder if desired. Add cucumber slices,
return to a boil and remove from heat. Pack slices in hot,
sterilized canning jars, cover with cooking liquid and seal. Store
in refrigerator up to 3 months.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 pints.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
