<HEADLINE>
RICH, BUT WITHOUT A PRICE TO MATCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Danzante Sangiovese 1997, Le Marche, Italy. About $10.
</P>
<P>
   It's about time we all got a break, and here it is: a really
delicious Italian wine, widely distributed and at a great price.
This is yet another fruitful result of the combined talents of the
Robert Mondavi Winery in California and the Frescobaldi family in
Tuscany. This one, from the point of view of the average wine
buyer, really makes sense.
</P>
<P>
   The sangiovese grape is usually associated with Tuscany and
Chianti wine, of which it is the chief component. But good
sangiovese can be found all over north and central Italy.
</P>
<P>
   The Marches, the coast region east of Tuscany and Umbria,
produces excellent wines from the grape, and this is one of them.
It's a rich wine with lots of fruit, and it's ready to drink now.
Danzante, by the way, is Italian for dancing. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
