A3421 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT &LR;      06-29 0423
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEETS FOR SKEPTICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MARK BITTMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Commercial canners probably don't want you to know this, but
beets can be eaten raw, and they're delicious. They're not as
approachable as an apple, but my suspicion is that even beet-haters
will like them raw in this salad. Uncooked beets are less sweet and
earthy than they are when boiled or roasted.
</P>
<P>
   To eat a beet raw, you have to peel it and shred it. The first
step is easiest with a regular vegetable peeler. I do the second
with the metal blade of a food processor, pulsing the machine on
and off until the beets are finely cut. You could use the shredding
blade, but it isn't any easier or better. Or you could use a manual
grater, but only if you're interested in an upper-body workout.
</P>
<P>
   Beets are messy, so this is a job best done near the sink, where
utensils can be washed quickly. Wear an apron or previously stained
clothing. After the peeling and grating, this wonderful salad can
be thrown together in about five minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Because of their sweetness, raw beets really should be tossed
with a very sharp dressing, one that you might otherwise consider
too strong. More vinegar than oil is unusual for a vinaigrette, but
each time I made this salad I changed the ratio. I began with 2
parts oil to 1 part vinegar and ended up with 2 parts vinegar to 1
part oil. I also use more mustard and shallots than usual.
</P>
<P>
   Dill is a traditional partner for beets, and it won't do any
harm here. But stronger herbs are better, like a few leaves of
tarragon or rosemary, or a good handful of chopped parsley.
</P>
<P>
   If you just can't resist cooking beets, once they're shredded,
they can be quickly sauteed in butter or oil. They become
completely tender in less than 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   RAW BEET SALAD &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1 pound beets
</P>
<P>
   1 large shallot
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons Dijon mustard, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons sherry vinegar or other good strong vinegar
</P>
<P>
   Minced parsley, dill, chervil, rosemary or tarragon.
</P>
<P>
   1. Peel the beets and the shallot. Combine them in the bowl of a
food processor fitted with the metal blade, and pulse carefully
until the beets are shredded; do not puree. (Or grate the beets by
hand and mince the shallots; combine.) Scrape into a bowl.
</P>
<P>
   2. Toss with the salt, pepper, mustard, oil and vinegar. Taste,
and adjust seasoning. Toss in the herbs, and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-99 1635EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
