<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEST-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WILD, WILD WEST': GADGETS, BOND GIRLS AND MEN IN CHAPS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By JANET MASLIN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The latest inevitability to hit the movie screen has its
blockbuster credentials firmly in place: Will Smith, July 4th
weekend, ``Men in Black'' director, swell gadgets, huge Erector set
toy spider, chart-bound hip-hop title song behind the closing
credits. Not to mention cheesecake (Salma Hayek in a corset),
comical cross-dressing (Kevin Kline in a corset) and enough
schoolboy double-entendres to bring out the 11-year-old in the most
circumspect sage.
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, the collective effect of this Pavlovian bonanza is
bound to be a hot-weather, opening-weekend stampede in the
direction of ``Wild Wild West.'' But this is another big, lavish
movie with no there there. Ruled by increasingly ghoulish special
effects, it leaves reality so far behind that its storytelling
would be arbitrary even by comic-book standards, and its characters
share no common ground or emotional connection. It cares far more
about herding audiences into theaters than about what they hear or
see.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wild Wild West'' is hard to categorize, a quality not to be
confused with originality. It begins on a James Bond note despite
its post-Civil War time period, then segues into contraption-heavy
science fiction and ultimately a ``Godzilla''-style battle with a
mechanical monster. Into this same blender are thrown a maimed
Confederate villain with Nazi stylistic flourishes, elaborately
antiquated railroad scenes and enough crafty, kiddie-minded
pratfalls to make one wonder whether the film really had to begin
with a whorehouse sequence. All in all, acid indigestion for the
soul.
</P>
<P>
   In the quaint old days of ``Hudson Hawk'' and ``Howard the
Duck,'' the film that senselessly grafted together such a
smorgasbord of styles was a fluke. Now, amid a wave of uncommonly
slapdash summer movies, the stylistic grab bag looks like the
status quo, and the movie that actually makes sense is the freak
occurrence. As ``Wild Wild West'' begins, it's clear that there's
no danger this latest film directed by Barry Sonnenfeld will fall
into the latter category.
</P>
<P>
   With his acerbic ``Addams Family'' comedies, the Elmore Leonard
edge in ``Get Shorty'' and the deadpan alien humor of ``Men in
Black,'' Sonnenfeld could anchor his own merrily perverse pop style
to something sturdier than the material he has here. This time, in
a film loosely based on a television show of no great staying
power, he's more apt to drift. Without the winning presence of
Smith, whose knowing, newly hunky presence here is the film's
greatest asset, ``Wild Wild West'' would look even flimsier. But
the star's wit and swagger do a lot to deflect attention from the
film's sputtering. And they make it all the more regrettable that
``Wild Wild West'' doesn't make better use of its vast budget and
acting talent.
</P>
<P>
   Handsomely outfitted as a dandy, Smith plays James West, a
government agent in the days of the Ulysses S. Grant
administration. And Kevin Kline, in addition to impersonating
President Grant, plays West's odd-couple colleague, a master
inventor named Artemus Gordon. When West turns up on the roof of
Gordon's private train car, for instance, there is a gizmo to
catapult him into an armchair so that Gordon can say: ``How nice of
you to drop in!'' In a screenplay that has four credited authors
but no particular story, there are a lot more hoary Bondian puns
and winks where that came from.
</P>
<P>
   In a typically good-looking (the film was shot by Michael
Ballhaus) but dopey opening section, West and Gordon meet in a
brothel where both are trying to trap a minor villain, Gen.
``Bloodbath'' McGrath (Ted Levine), whose grotesque ear trumpet
sets the tone for much of what will follow. Then, after a visit to
the White House, where sheep are seen grazing on the lawn, the film
offers a little history lesson as it heads with President Grant to
Promontory Point, Utah, for the joining of the trans-continental
railroad. Since within the film there is also a science project
straining to get out, the story's various railway escapades work in
a few physics demonstrations, as when West and Gordon find
themselves with powerful magnets attached to their necks. The
magnets plus a cornfield chase make for a nice, jokey action
sequence that has nothing much to do with the rest of the movie.
</P>
<P>
   But it does show off the handiwork of Dr. Arliss Loveless,
played by Kenneth Branagh in a steam-powered wheelchair and a
goatee any heavy-metal band would envy. There's no point to
wondering where Dr. Loveless lost the lower half of his body, why
he made plans for outsmarting the President and how his minions
managed to coax Ms. Hayak's Rita Escobar into a bedroom cage
surrounded by bondage equipment; these are just the sorts of things
that ``Wild Wild West'' takes for granted. Besides, Branagh's madly
villainous Confederate ranting (``way-all'' for ``well'') and
spider fetish are stupefying enough to dispel questions.
</P>
<P>
   Even with Kline as a charmingly suave comic foil, Ms. Hayek to
raise the film's temperature, and other good but weirdly utilized
players on hand (Bai Ling, who had a serious leading role in ``Red
Corner,'' is reduced to smirky Dragon Lady moves as an Asian
character called East), ``Wild Wild West'' trades especially
heavily on Smith's considerable appeal. Many barbed references to
slavery have been worked into the dialogue, and he delivers them
with winning acerbity. His abilities as a tough but jokey action
hero and ladies' man at least mean at least there's something worth
remembering when the film is over.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: ``Wild Wild West'' is rated PG. It includes sexual
situations, sexual references, jokey but deadly violence and many
snickery double-entendres.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Barry Sonnenfeld; written by S.S. Wilson, Brent
Maddock, Jeffrey Price and Peter S. Seaman, based on a story by Jim
Thomas and John Thomas; director of photography, Michael Ballhaus;
edited by Jim Miller; music by Elmer Bernstein; production
designer, Bo Welch; produced by Jon Peters and Sonnenfeld; released
by Warner Brothers. Running time: 107 minutes. This film is rated
PG.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Will Smith (James T. West), Kevin Kline (Artemus Gordon),
Kenneth Branagh (Dr. Arliss Loveless), Salma Hayek (Rita Escobar),
Ted Levine (McGrath), Bai Ling (Miss East), Frederique Van Der Wal
(Amazonia), Musetta Vander (Munitia) and Sofia Eng (Miss
Lippenreider).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-99 1637EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990629.0170 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 16:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3434 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERNET-POLLING30-CO     06-29 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-POLLING30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL POLLING FACES PITFALLS IN CYBERSPACE
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ ``OK Internet Brigade, let's get out there and
stand strong for Pat!'' That's the rallying cry on Pat Buchanan's
Web site, which urges his supporters to ``hit the on-line polls and
register your vote for PJB.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't view it as skewing the numbers, just getting out the
vote,'' said Bob Adams, a spokesman for the Republican presidential
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   But could such partisan efforts skewer bold plans to make the
Internet a major source of political polls for the 2000 elections?
</P>
<P>
   Already, one leading market research firm has announced plans to
measure next year's political races on the Internet, including
battles for the White House, Congress and governorships. Such
plans, however, are deeply troubling to other survey professionals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Political polling on the Internet has absolutely no
validity,'' said Andrew Kohut, director of the widely respected Pew
Research Center. ``It's a giant leap backwards because it allows
the squeaky wheels to have a greater say. Responsible people
shouldn't be doing this.''
</P>
<P>
   Pew recently compared its polling data with the results of
survey responses to the same questions posed on America Online.
More than half the people in the online survey disapproved of the
job President Clinton was doing. But two-thirds of those surveyed
by Pew on the phone approved.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping polls accurate as the industry moves into the Internet
age is even more of a challenge than the one posed by the last
technological leap, from door-to-door polling to telephones, which
occurred a generation ago.
</P>
<P>
   In telephone polls, numbers are dialed at random. The results
are then weighted to accurately represent the national voting
population or a regional grouping. By contrast, Web pollsters must
deal with a self-selected group of volunteer respondents.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, it's clear that cyberspace dwellers are different
from the nation as a whole. One indicator is that, according to a
Georgia Tech survey released last month, the average annual income
of Web users is $57,300 _ more than $20,000 higher than the median
income of U.S. households.
</P>
<P>
   Such criticism has not deterred Gordon Black, the chief
executive officer and founder of Harris Interactive. That's the new
name the venerable Harris market research firm adopted Tuesday,
when it announced a major reorganization.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1960s, as a graduate student at Stanford, Black
recalls being barred by his teachers from using telephone surveys
because they were deemed unreliable. Now, he suggests, the same
prejudices plague the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Simply stated,'' Black said, ``the Internet is faster, cheaper
and more versatile than traditional mail, door-to-door and
telephony research methods. In fact, half of Harris Interactive's
watershed research during the past year are studies that could not
have been accomplished without the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, using an Internet database of just 1 million, the
Harris Poll Online accurately predicted 21 of 22 U.S. elections for
governor and senator in 16 states. By contrast, on average,
telephone polling units missed five of the 22 contests.
</P>
<P>
   By the fall of 2000, Harris plans to expand its database of
Internet users from the current 3.5 million people to as many as 10
million. With the expanded database, Harris says it will be able to
accurately discern trends among ever smaller segments of the
population.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's strictly an empirical thing,'' said Jon Siegel, who
directs Harris' political efforts. ``It either works or it doesn't
work. We're going to be as honest about our methods and our results
as a newborn baby.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically,'' Siegel added, ``it's a technology that's ready to
roll. If the Wright Brothers had waited, somebody else would have
flown first. Is what we've got a 747? No it's not. But I can assure
you that it will fly.''
</P>
<P>
   Some members of the American Association for Public Opinion
Research are not persuaded that Internet political polling is ready
for prime time. The group, meeting last week in Orlando, weighed
whether it should adopt a new survey rating system that would
require interviewers to tell the public and the media what
standards are being used to elicit results.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't overstate the concern that people who practice
polling have about this,'' said Nancy Belden, a Washington-based
pollster who organized the Orlando discussion. ``It is more urgent
because of the proliferation of Internet polling.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-99 1639EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990629.0171 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 16:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3436 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BARBECUE-SAUCES-NYT &LR;      06-29 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARBECUE-SAUCES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR THE BARBECUE, A KALEIDOSCOPE OF SAUCES  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN RAICHLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Not everyone sees red as the color of barbecue sauce.
Just as barbecue is defined as pork in some states and beef in
others, the liquid used for basting and flavoring can vary from
region to region. And ketchup is not at all as common as one may
think.
</P>
<P>
   The vinegar-based sauces of North Carolina are well known. But
in South Carolina and parts of Georgia, barbecue sauce is often
yellow-brown, based on mustard, not ketchup. In northern Alabama,
you can find white barbecue sauce, made from mayonnaise. And in my
hometown, Miami, we're partial to an amber blend of fried garlic
and citrus juice that goes by the name of mojo.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina's vinegar sauce may well be the original American
barbecue sauce, according to Bob Garner's ``North Carolina
Barbecue'' (John F. Blair, 1996). The book says that Virginians and
North Carolinians in the 18th and 19th centuries sauced their
barbecue with a tangy mixture of vinegar, red pepper, salt and
oyster juice. He speculates that the vinegar may have been chosen
for its ability to mask the gamy taste that meat must have had in
the age before refrigeration.
</P>
<P>
   The mustard sauce found farther south _ sweet and tangy _ can be
varied infinitely. The basic ingredients are mustard (preferably
that cheap lurid yellow ball park variety, but sometimes two or
three classier kinds), vinegar and some sort of sweetener, like
honey, molasses, brown sugar or cane syrup or a combination. Local
cooks change the vinegar, sweetener and mustard to put their own
imprint on the sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Jack McDavid, the owner of Jack's Firehouse in Philadelphia and
the consulting chef and a partner in Red's Backwoods BBQ, a
restaurant chain primarily in the South, created a mustard sauce
that gets its kick from jalapeno peppers and its silken sweetness
from corn syrup.
</P>
<P>
   At the other extreme is the piquant white barbecue sauce served
with chicken in northern Alabama. ``My grandfather came up with the
recipe in 1925,'' said Don McLemore, the third-generation owner of
Big Bob Gibson's restaurants in Decatur, Ala. No self-respecting
pit master would disclose the exact formula for his sauce, but
McLemore says that the main ingredients are vinegar, mayonnaise and
black pepper.
</P>
<P>
   It sounds weird, and it is in fact weird. But sometimes weird is
best when it comes to barbecue. One taste of Big Bob's chicken,
smoked to a mahogany color and then tossed with the creamy but
peppery white sauce, made me a believer. My own contribution to the
recipe was a spoonful of prepared horseradish for more bite.
</P>
<P>
   As for the mojo (pronounced MO-ho), it owes its aromatic profile
to that triumvirate of Cuban seasonings: garlic, cumin and oregano.
The garlic is fried to the color of amber to intensify its flavor
without making it bitter. The traditional souring agent for mojo is
the juice of the naranja agria, the sour orange, which is available
in many Hispanic markets. You can approximate it by combining fresh
lime and grapefruit juices.
</P>
<P>
   It's classically Latin, but you'll be surprised by the
electrifying effect mojo has on grilled food of all ethnic
persuasions.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH CAROLINA-STYLE MUSTARD SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   } cup distilled white vinegar
</P>
<P>
   { cup beef or chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   { cup finely chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   { cup seeded minced jalapeno chilies
</P>
<P>
   { cup yellow mustard or Dijon-style mustard
</P>
<P>
   \ cup honey mustard or brown deli-style mustard
</P>
<P>
   \ cup light corn syrup (or to taste)
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons molasses
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon black pepper
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   \ teaspoon cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   1. Combine all ingredients in saucepan, and bring to boil.
Reduce heat, and simmer until thick and richly flavored, about 10
minutes, stirring occasionally. Taste for seasoning, adding
additional salt or corn syrup as desired. This sauce goes great
with just about anything.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 3 cups
</P>
<P>
   MOJO DE AJO (CUBAN CITRUS-GARLIC BARBECUE SAUCE)
</P>
<P>
   Time: 10 minutes, plus 30 minutes for cooling
</P>
<P>
   { cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   8 large cloves garlic, thinly sliced crosswise
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup fresh sour orange juice (or { cup fresh lime juice and 3
tablespoons fresh grapefruit juice)
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup water
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon ground oregano
</P>
<P>
   1{ teaspoons salt, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons chopped fresh cilantro or flat-leaf parsley
</P>
<P>
   1. Heat olive oil in deep saucepan over medium heat. Add garlic,
and cook until fragrant and pale golden brown. Do not let brown too
much, or else garlic will become bitter.
</P>
<P>
   2. Stir in sour orange juice (or lime juice and grapefruit
juice), water, cumin, oregano, salt and pepper. Stand back, because
the sauce may spatter. Bring to rolling boil. Correct the
seasoning, adding more salt and pepper, if needed. Let cool to room
temperature, and then stir in cilantro or parsley. Store in bottle
or jar with tight-fitting lid; shake well before serving. Serve
with grilled pork, chicken, seafood and vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 1{ cups
</P>
<P>
   ALABAMA WHITE BARBECUE SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1 cup mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   10 tablespoons distilled white vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1{ tablespoons prepared white horseradish (optional)
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1. Combine all ingredients in mixing bowl, and whisk until
smooth. Serve with barbecued chicken, or as a dip for grilled
vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 1} cups
</P>
