<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 16:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3437 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERNET-POLLING30-CO     06-29 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-POLLING30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL POLLING FACES PITFALLS IN CYBERSPACE
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ ``OK Internet Brigade, let's get out there and
stand strong for Pat!'' That's the rallying cry on Pat Buchanan's
Web site, which urges his supporters to ``hit the on-line polls and
register your vote for PJB.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't view it as skewing the numbers, just getting out the
vote,'' said Bob Adams, a spokesman for the Republican presidential
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   But could such partisan efforts skewer bold plans to make the
Internet a major source of political polls for the 2000 elections?
</P>
<P>
   Already, one leading market research firm has announced plans to
measure next year's political races on the Internet, including
battles for the White House, Congress and governorships. Such
plans, however, are deeply troubling to other survey professionals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Political polling on the Internet has absolutely no
validity,'' said Andrew Kohut, director of the widely respected Pew
Research Center. ``It's a giant leap backwards because it allows
the squeaky wheels to have a greater say. Responsible people
shouldn't be doing this.''
</P>
<P>
   Pew recently compared its polling data with the results of
survey responses to the same questions posed on America Online.
More than half the people in the online survey disapproved of the
job President Clinton was doing. But two-thirds of those surveyed
by Pew on the phone approved.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping polls accurate as the industry moves into the Internet
age is even more of a challenge than the one posed by the last
technological leap, from door-to-door polling to telephones, which
occurred a generation ago.
</P>
<P>
   In telephone polls, numbers are dialed at random. The results
are then weighted to accurately represent the national voting
population or a regional grouping. By contrast, Web pollsters must
deal with a self-selected group of volunteer respondents.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, it's clear that cyberspace dwellers are different
from the nation as a whole. One indicator is that, according to a
Georgia Tech survey released last month, the average annual income
of Web users is $57,300 _ more than $20,000 higher than the median
income of U.S. households.
</P>
<P>
   Such criticism has not deterred Gordon Black, the chief
executive officer and founder of Harris Interactive. That's the new
name the venerable Harris market research firm adopted Tuesday,
when it announced a major reorganization.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1960s, as a graduate student at Stanford, Black
recalls being barred by his teachers from using telephone surveys
because they were deemed unreliable. Now, he suggests, the same
prejudices plague the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Simply stated,'' Black said, ``the Internet is faster, cheaper
and more versatile than traditional mail, door-to-door and
telephony research methods. In fact, half of Harris Interactive's
watershed research during the past year are studies that could not
have been accomplished without the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, using an Internet database of just 1 million, the
Harris Poll Online accurately predicted 21 of 22 U.S. elections for
governor and senator in 16 states. By contrast, on average,
telephone polling units missed five of the 22 contests.
</P>
<P>
   By the fall of 2000, Harris plans to expand its database of
Internet users from the current 3.5 million people to as many as 10
million. With the expanded database, Harris says it will be able to
accurately discern trends among ever smaller segments of the
population.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's strictly an empirical thing,'' said Jon Siegel, who
directs Harris' political efforts. ``It either works or it doesn't
work. We're going to be as honest about our methods and our results
as a newborn baby.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically,'' Siegel added, ``it's a technology that's ready to
roll. If the Wright Brothers had waited, somebody else would have
flown first. Is what we've got a 747? No it's not. But I can assure
you that it will fly.''
</P>
<P>
   Some members of the American Association for Public Opinion
Research are not persuaded that Internet political polling is ready
for prime time. The group, meeting last week in Orlando, weighed
whether it should adopt a new survey rating system that would
require interviewers to tell the public and the media what
standards are being used to elicit results.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't overstate the concern that people who practice
polling have about this,'' said Nancy Belden, a Washington-based
pollster who organized the Orlando discussion. ``It is more urgent
because of the proliferation of Internet polling.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
