<HEADER>
A3441 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DUNCAN-CIVIL-COLUMN     06-29 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DUNCAN-CIVIL-COLUMN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Decal is a sign of the times
 &HT;    By Todd C. Duncan
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The other day, as I was waiting for the traffic light to turn
green at one of downtown Atlanta's busiest intersections, I noticed
an emblem of how far our society has moved away from civility.
</P>
<P>
   Posted on the rear window of a stealthy-looking black Chevy
pickup was the white outline of the cartoon character Calvin _ of
``Calvin and Hobbes'' fame _ urinating on a Ford logo.
</P>
<P>
   I had seen these decals before, but in this climate of school
shootings, sex scandals, dragging deaths and police torture cases,
the tiny cartoon suddenly represents something more.
</P>
<P>
   It's one thing for adult devotees of one brand of automobile to
circulate Xerox copies and e-mails with this expression of
automotive superiority, but to publicly display such crudeness is
simply repugnant.
</P>
<P>
   As I drove alongside the truck, I spied the occupants. The
driver was a man, probably in his late 30s. His passengers were a
woman about the same age and a young boy playing with one of those
toy robots that transform into another machine or animal. All had
smiles on their faces.
</P>
<P>
   I'll assume they are hard-working, well-meaning folks. I'll even
bet they describe themselves as ``average Americans.'' That's what
is so troubling about the sporting of the decal.
</P>
<P>
   The notion that ``average Americans'' don't find urinating
anywhere _ except before a commode _ distasteful is clear
indication that we have lost the way to civilization.
</P>
<P>
   If we were to talk to the adults in that truck, I believe they
would agree that American values have taken a turn for the worse _
accelerated by ineffective schools, the disintegration of the
family, the irrelevance of spirituality, and the violence portrayed
on television, in movies, music and video games.
</P>
<P>
   They are correct on those points, but more importantly, they've
missed the obvious.
</P>
<P>
   We teach our children with our actions and who and what we
surround ourselves with.
</P>
<P>
   The message they are sending with their decal works hand in hand
with the over-pumped silver screen idol blowing away dozens of
``bad guys'' to move us away from basic decency. Each desensitizes
us.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from being distasteful, the decal displays a level of
blind intolerance. Intolerance for what is different or for a
different way of thinking or living.
</P>
<P>
   It really isn't a far stretch in these times for someone to
replace that car brand logo with the logo of the type of music they
despise, the sports team they dislike or the political party they
vote against. I noticed a bumper sticker the other day with the
same Calvin figure standing over seven yellow-stained letters,
C-L-I-N-T-O-N.
</P>
<P>
   A politician now, but how about a religion tomorrow? A race? The
exchange is not that difficult to foresee.
</P>
<P>
   This by no way means that people who enjoy this decal are going
to raise the next Timothy McVeighs or neo-Nazis. However, it does
point out that we are not thinking about the meaning of the banners
we're flying.
</P>
<P>
   The message the decal sends to others, especially children: ``If
you don't like something, you have the OK to urinate on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Is that a family value? Is that message better than off-color
rap or speed metal lyrics? How did this decal get to be funny or
cute and acceptable for public display?
</P>
<P>
   This society accepts many forms of destructive behavior. Just
watch the ``Jerry Springer Show'' for two minutes. It's hard to
tell who is more obscene; the male guest who's having an affair
with his fiancee's lesbian grandmother or the audience members who
cheer the guests' stream of profane tirades and physical assaults.
</P>
<P>
   For the even more absurd, look at all of the children in this
country walking around wearing T-shirts with their favorite
engorged, living cartoon characters _ pro wrestlers. There is a pro
wrestling character whose persona is that of a street pimp. He
calls the scantily clad women that follow him his ``hoes.'' How
does a character like that make it to a television screen viewed by
children? What is the wrestling or TV executive thinking about when
they give their permission to create such nonsense? What sponsor
believes it's OK to advertise around a segment featuring a pimp and
his whores? How can any parent let their children watch such
displays.
</P>
<P>
   While seeking civility, we should not forget that freedom of
thought and speech is the key to our democracy's survival. One does
have the right _ with some limitations _ to crude expression.
However, individuals, families and communities also have the right
not to accept it. Acting civilized should not be inconsistent with
being a good American. A good person. ``Keeping it real'' does not
mean ``keeping it vile.''
</P>
<P>
   It seems we've lost our basic starting points. Say ``please''
and ``thank you.'' ``Don't curse in public.'' ``Be respectful to
our elders.'' ``Treat others the way you want to be treated.''
</P>
<P>
   Common decency used to be common.
</P>
<P>
   Todd C. Duncan is an editor with Cox News Service in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
