<HEADER>
A3443 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PARK-FILM-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      06-29 1190
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARK-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SOUTH PARK`: MAKING A POINT WITH SMUT AND LAUGHS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ask any self-respecting third-grade boy what is the funniest
thing in the whole wide world, and he might tell you (in different
words, of course) that it is the nether region of the human body.
In its spontaneous and sometimes noisy release of noxious fumes,
which turn out to be (gasp! chortle!) flammable, the posterior
operates according to its own natural laws. These laws are
diametrically opposed to the orderly rules laid down by grade
school principals and soccer moms who are constantly nagging you to
stand in line, wash behind your ears and smell nice for granny. But
as any third grader will tell you, chaos can erupt from below at
any moment to throw a pall over the nicest little tea party.
</P>
<P>
   The rock-bottom reality of third-grade humor versus adult
sanctimony is the source of many of the laughs in ``South Park:
Bigger, Longer and Uncut,'' the very funny, extremely obscene movie
spinoff from the popular animated Comedy Central series. With
eerily perfect timing, ``South Park'' addresses the current
national debate about the Motion Picture Association of America's
movie ratings and President Clinton's call for exhibitors to
enforce them vigorously. In an early scene a group of chirpy
round-faced tykes in the Rocky Mountain town of South Park pay a
homeless man to take them to a movie starring a Canadian duo who
spew nothing but high-velocity profanity with an anal slant.
</P>
<P>
   Proudly flaunting their new, scatological vocabulary, the boys
shock the community with sophisticated language that they don't
fully comprehend but enjoy slinging around. Emergency meetings are
held, and Sheila Broflovski, the bossy mother of Kyle, one of the
corrupted third graders, leads a hysterically vindictive anti-smut
campaign that grows into a national movement. Sheila blames Canada
for all the ills of the world. Diplomatic insults fly, and (in a
grand gesture borrowed from the 1995 movie ``Canadian Bacon'') the
United States declares war on Canada.
</P>
<P>
   In the movie's sharpest satirical twist, Cartman, one of the
boys, is subjected to a behavior-modification experiment
(reminiscent of ``A Clockwork Orange'') and implanted with a V-chip
that delivers a severe electric shock every time a naughty word
escapes his mouth. In an amusingly subversive twist, the mechanism
eventually becomes a potent weapon of war.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the boys' pal Kenny (who in the series is regularly
killed off only to be resurrected) dies in an accident that begins
with a flaming ignition of his own body gas and winds up in that
ultimate nether world, the one ruled by Satan. The Devil seems to
be having romantic problems. Having succumbed to the charms of
Saddam Hussein (portrayed as a smiling photograph attached to a
tiny cut-out figure), who has died and gone to hell, he has become
the Iraqi dictator's pining love slave. The Devil is shown poring
over ``Saddam Is From Mars, Satan's From Venus'' for tips on how to
improve their communication. But their troubled idyll is
interrupted by the war above ground, which Satan realizes is his
opportunity to put in an appearance and take over the planet.
Armageddon is suddenly at hand.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest difference between the movie and the television
series is that along with everything else, the film is a
Disney-style (or anti-Disney, if you will) musical with 15 songs.
These poke fun at everything from Rodgers and Hammerstein (the
icky, cheery opener, ``Mountain Town,'' and the ``Do Re Mi''-like
``It's Easy, Mmmkay'' about learning to replace obscenities with
nice words) to ``Les Miserables'' (``La Resistance'') to Mariah
Carey-style inspirational ballads (``Up There''). Most of the songs
were written by Trey Parker (who created the ``South Park'' series
with Matt Stone) and the film composer Marc Shaiman. Several are
staged as splashy chorus-line production numbers. While none are
classics, they underline the movie's cheeky attitude toward
grown-up authority.
</P>
<P>
   Not to become ponderous (after all, it's only a movie), but the
``South Park'' phenomenon cannily zeroes in on some essential
contradictions of American popular culture. In its cheerfully
smutty way it wants to clear the air of pompous, hypocritical
rhetoric about protecting children from basic if unpleasant
realities. Beneath the hilarity, the movie is a scathing social
parable in which desperate, paranoid grown-ups who long for an
impossibly sanitized environment go collectively crazy to the point
that they're willing to bring on World War III. And what are they
so afraid of? Just some dumb off- color humor about bodily
functions.
</P>
<P>
   One key to ``South Park's'' humor is its lack of political
smugness. In spoofing such stereotypes as a bossy Jewish mother
(Mrs. Broflovski), a campy gay man (Big Gay Al) and a black man who
is a repository of sexual knowledge (the grade school chef, spoken
by Isaac Hayes), the satire extends to everybody.
</P>
<P>
   As jolly as it is, the humor in ``South Park'' isn't as acute as
in the television series' best moments. Nothing in the film matches
the force of an episode in which the third graders are taken on a
hunting trip by adults who instantly revert to atavistic macho
insanity, getting drunk and shooting at everything that moves. And
in an effort to bring in as many characters as possible from
different ``South Park'' episodes, the movie also goes on tangents.
Some of its jokes (like a song devoted to the skater Brian Boitano)
will mystify those unfamiliar with the series.
</P>
<P>
   When all is said and done, ``South Park'' has a very simple,
self-justifying moral. As much as the movie touches on the
socialization process and a conservative society's fears and
prejudices about the human body and sex, it is really about mass
entertainment, censorship and freedom of speech. Its argument is
distilled in a single short speech pointing out that movies allow
almost unlimited violence while remaining petrified of anything
reeking of smut. The mere existence of ``South Park,'' which
received an R rating after a struggle to avoid NC-17, suggests that
it is winning its argument.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: ``South Park'' (whose R rating requires viewers under 17
to be accompanied by a parent or adult guardian) has reams of
profanity, not all of it intelligible because much of it is spoken
so quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Trey Parker; written by Parker, Matt Stone and Pam
Brady; director of animation, Eric Stough; edited by John Venzon;
music and lyrics by Parker, with score and additional music by Marc
Shaiman; produced by Parker and Stone; released by Paramount
Pictures. Running time: 88 minutes. This film is rated R. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WITH THE VOICES OF: Trey Parker, Matt Stone and Mary Kay Bergman
(Cartman, Kenny, Kyle and Stan), Isaac Hayes (Chef), Jesse Howell,
Anthony Cross-Thomas and Francesca Clifford (Ike), George Clooney
(Dr. Gouache), Brent Spiner (Conan O'Brien), Minnie Driver (Brooke
Shields), Dave Foley (the Baldwin Brothers), Eric Idle (Dr.
Vosknocker) and Mike Judge (Kenny's Goodbye).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
