<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 16:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3447 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LUCY-BOOK-REVIEW-NYTR     06-29 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUCY-BOOK-REVIEW-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN AUTHOR HAS A BALL WITH `LUCY' 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JAY HANDELMAN   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARASOTA, Fla. _ I know I'm not alone in saying that I'm a big
fan of ``I Love Lucy,'' arguably television's greatest situation
comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Even repeated viewings of Lucy Ricardo's shenanigans do little
to dim the humor. I've read a few books about the show, most of
them serious looks at the hard work and creativity that went into
TV history.
</P>
<P>
   At last, there's a book that tells the story with a sense of
humor, ``Laughs, Luck ... and Lucy,'' by Jess Oppenheimer, the
show's creator and head writer. Oppenheimer died in 1988 before he
completed his memoirs, which provided a life-changing opportunity
for his son, Gregg.
</P>
<P>
   The younger Oppenheimer gave up his legal career when he signed
the contract for the ``Lucy'' book and started rummaging through
his father's files to piece together notes and letters into a book.
</P>
<P>
   The book has just been published in paperback by Syracuse
University Press.
</P>
<P>
   While working on the book, Oppenheimer collected hundreds of his
father's scripts for Jack Benny, ``Lucy,'' ``Baby Snooks,''
starring Fanny Brice, and the ``My Favorite Husband'' radio series
that led to ``I Love Lucy.''
</P>
<P>
   He learned a few things about his father in the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing I learned, which was not a real surprise, is that
his sense of humor really helped him cope with all the hurdles that
were thrown at him.'' Jess Oppenheimer had double vision as a
child, which caused all sorts of social problems. But his
awkwardness led him to develop his natural wit and humor as he
figured that making people laugh could also make him popular.
</P>
<P>
   Though Gregg Oppenheimer said he inherited his father's sense of
humor, he never turned to television comedy (aside from a brief
stint working on a Debbie Reynolds series in the 1960s). ``I had a
blast and thought that this is what I want to do, but Dad said I
had to go to college and find something to do where I can earn some
money.''
</P>
<P>
   Gregg Oppenheimer had a clear purpose with the book _ to make
people laugh. ``I've read a lot of `Lucy' books and most were
serious,'' he said in a telephone interview. ``It seemed strange
that all the stuff about the person who has given more laughter to
the world than practically anyone in history is so depressing. I
thought it would be nice to let people read about her and laugh.''
</P>
<P>
   So the book mixes the serious with the funny, as it relates the
evolution of turning radio's ``My Favorite Husband'' into ``I Love
Lucy.'' Actually, you can hear it, too, because the book includes a
compact disc with clips from both shows.
</P>
<P>
   One track features a restaurant scene from ``Husband'' that is
virtually identical to a scene later heard on ``I Love Lucy.'' Even
the waiter (played by Frank Nelson) is the same.
</P>
<P>
   On another track, you can hear Ball's ``Husband'' character
acting like a racetrack tout to sell a used dress, while a similar
style has Lucy Ricardo selling excess meat in a butcher shop.
</P>
<P>
   To further the multimedia theme, Oppenheimer also has created a
lively Web site (www.lucylibrary.com) that features stories, sound
and video clips, biographies and a book excerpt.
</P>
<P>
   The show was an instant success when it premiered in 1951, but
it almost ended before it became the classic it now is. Lucille
Ball became pregnant, and no other series had ever dealt with such
a happy problem. Remember, this was in the era when married people
on TV slept in separate beds, and the word ``pregnant'' was not
allowed.
</P>
<P>
   But those episodes are now embedded in our minds, and no other
series since has dealt with the farcical realities related to
pregnancy without touching on something that Oppenheimer and his
writing staff had already done.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the most accessible shows ever done,'' Gregg
Oppenheimer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I Love Lucy'' runs nightly on Nick at Nite, and you can expect
big things in 2001, the 50th anniversary of the show's birth.
Oppenheimer is putting together a collection of
never-before-published ``Lucy'' scripts.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to be that sophisticated to watch, yet they
didn't write down to the audience,'' said Oppenheimer. ``They took
simple concepts and executed them very elegantly. The visuals are
hilarious, but the writing builds them up.''
</P>
<P>
   Oppenheimer said his favorite episode was the Emmy-nominated
``L.A. at Last'' when the Ricardos and Mertzes arrive in Los
Angeles and Lucy, Ethel and Fred visit the Brown Derby restaurant
and run into William Holden.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Brown Derby scene is just a beautiful acting scene. She
makes it look so simple and I know she spent days practicing. She
didn't do any of this stuff naturally. Dad would say that if you
came to rehearsals, you'd think get rid of the redhead, she's
terrible. But after several days of wrestling with the script, she
owned it.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why we still love Lucy.
</P>
<P>
   (Jay Handelman is the television critic for the Herald-Tribune
in Sarasota, Fla., which is part of the New York Times Regional
Newspaper Group. This article was distributed by the New York Times
News Service.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
