<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990629.0176 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 16:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3454 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INFANT-DEATHS-COX     06-29 1418
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INFANT-DEATHS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Infant deaths: 'You can't describe what this is like'
 &HT;    (EDS: WITH PHOTOS. Call CoxNet at 800-950-3739 if you have any
problems. MOVING IN (a) GENERAL NEWS and (l) LIFESTYLE categories.)
 &HT;    By Anntoinette Moore
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONGVIEW, Texas _ It's called ``Babyland'' but there are no
aisles of cute baby clothes or nursery furniture.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, a row of plaques mark tiny graves decorated with
flowers and favorite toys at the Chapelwood Memorial Gardens in
Bowie County, Northeast Texas.
</P>
<P>
   One of the plaques reads, ``Our beloved little man, Anthony D.
Zimmerman, July 24, 1998-Feb. 17, 1999, Now I lay me down to
sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Zimmerman can't forget the day his 6-month-old son died.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went to bed about 9 or 10 p.m. He went right to sleep,
laying in my arms. He woke up at 4 a.m., and I gave him his
pacifier and I sang him back to sleep,'' Zimmerman said.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony's 2-year-old sister, Katelyn, woke up at 6 a.m., and
Zimmerman gave her a bottle.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when I woke up with my son in my arms. He was clinging
to me and looking at me,'' but he wasn't breathing, said Zimmerman,
22.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman called 911. The Bowie County sheriff's office and an
ambulance from St. Michael Hospital in Texarkana responded. When
Anthony arrived at the hospital, ``they said he was gone,''
Zimmerman said.
</P>
<P>
   Local law enforcement officers and a Child Protective Services
investigator examined the circumstances of Anthony's death, and his
body was autopsied.
</P>
<P>
   CPS is a division of the Texas Department of Protective and
Regulatory Services.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of Anthony's death still is unknown, but investigators
found no evidence of child abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman and his wife, Tina, 18, are just one of the more than
2,000 couples who suffer the loss of a child younger than
1-year-old each year in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   CPS staff and local committees are examining the circumstances
surrounding child deaths across the state to see if they can be
prevented.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony had been hospitalized for RSV _ respiratory syncytial
virus _ and had been out of the hospital for just four days when he
died, Zimmerman said.
</P>
<P>
   Longview pediatrician Dr. Karen Roberts said RSV is the most
common respiratory virus in children and often causes them to be
hospitalized. It usually occurs from December through February.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can make the kids have the appearance of (sudden infant
death syndrome, or SIDS). In very small infants, it can just make
them quit breathing,'' Roberts said. Children with RSV are treated
as if they had asthma, and no RSV vaccine is available.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts is a member of the Texas Child Fatality Review Team that
covers the 23 counties that make up CPS' Region 4. Other members
include a CPS worker, police chief, district attorney, retired law
enforcement officer and former CPS worker. The committee meets
about four times a year to review the circumstances of all child
deaths in Region 4, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The committee asks, ``Can we pick out something that anyone did,
that could have been improved upon and might have saved that baby's
life,'' Roberts said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if a child drowns, the committee examines the
police report and autopsy records to see if the drowning could have
been prevented, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They found that the frequency of child death by drowning
decreases by about 60 percent when you put a fence up,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The committee also has talked about ways ``to get the word out
to people saying don't shake your baby,'' Roberts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times we sit around and say, 'if only,' and this
allows me to help change that 'if only,' `` Roberts said. ``It's a
chance to make the world a little bit better, a little safer for
kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman and his wife, who now live in a mobile home park in
the Bowie County town of Hooks, were willing to talk about
Anthony's death because they want to prevent others.
</P>
<P>
   When Anthony died, all four Zimmermans were sleeping in an adult
bed in a camper, Zimmerman said.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony usually slept in his own bed, but occasionally he did
sleep with his parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept him on my arm, 'cause I could feel him when he turned.
I'm a light sleeper,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Zimmerman cautioned parents about sleeping with their
babies in a large adult bed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a hard sleeper, I'd put him in a baby bed, that's
what I'd do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kip Wright is the CPS specialist who investigated Anthony's
death.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's mandated that we investigate any deaths of children 6
years old and under who didn't die in a motor vehicle accident or
who didn't have an ongoing illness,'' said Wright, who also looks
into reports of child abuse by school employees throughout Region
4.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'm looking for is, could the death have been prevented
and was the child abused,'' he said. If there are other children in
the home, they receive physical exams to make sure they are not
being abused.
</P>
<P>
   ``If abuse or neglect is ruled out and there's no risk to the
surviving children, we close the case out. ... I generally have a
pretty good idea if abuse or neglect occurred within the first
couple of days of the investigation,'' Wright said.
</P>
<P>
   He has worked for CPS for six years but investigated his first
child death in January. Since then, Wright has investigated five
deaths, all of children 1-year-old or younger.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't describe what this is like. The first dead baby I
saw looked like my son. You become very protective (of your
children), and you watch out for everything,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these deaths have involved ``high-risk kids and young
parents,'' Wright said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Anthony's death, one child died of SIDS, one suffocated,
one strangled on a Venetian blind cord, and one overdosed on
medication, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something that's just common sense. When you have young
children, you put your medication up because children will put
things in their mouth,'' Wright said.
</P>
<P>
   Other common-sense precautions: don't leave your children in
locked vehicles in the summer, don't shake your baby, no matter
what, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wright reports his findings to the area fatality review team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talk about what could have been done to prevent (the
death). That helps me learn what to look for when investigating
these cases. It also makes sure I haven't missed anything,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   CPS may refer parents who have lost a child to support services,
such as counseling or parenting classes, Wright said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hard investigations are the ones I've had recently, the
SIDS death. We don't want to leave it that we don't know what
happened, why your child died,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Janece Keetch, statewide coordinator for child fatality review
teams, said the teams have been able to educate communities about
how to reduce child deaths.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many infants die because they are not in safe beds or cribs.
We really encourage that parents not sleep with their children or
that they do that safely, so that a child is not accidentally
suffocated,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Other infants drown because they are left unattended in a
bathtub, Keetch said.
</P>
<P>
   Many drownings take place when a group of adults supervise a
group of children around water because one child is overlooked, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You really need to have one-to-one assigned supervision. It
takes a very short time, like two minutes, for a child to drown,''
Keetch said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need specific data to target prevention efforts. Did the
child drown in a pool or in a mop bucket?'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can make a lot of assumptions about child deaths, but
unless we have the hard data, our assumptions many times are going
to be wrong,'' Keetch said.
</P>
<P>
   CPS community initiatives specialist Linda Cunningham said the
majority of child deaths are caused by accidents or suffocation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents unknowingly put their children in dangerous
situations,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman said parents need to ``make sure they spend as much
time with their kids as they can, because you can't ever tell what
happens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seeing a little baby just born and knowing our little son, 6
months old, is gone. ... just tears me up,'' said Zimmerman, who
works at a cafeteria.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took off work a couple of days ago. I went over to his grave
and just sat there. It's hard, very hard,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Anntoinette Moore writes for the Longview News-Journal,
Longview, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
