<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3497 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-PROJECT-HNS &LR;      06-29 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-PROJECT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DIRT ON STOPPING CRIME: GARDEN PROJECT 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL HENNESSEY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ More than 2 million adults are incarcerated in
the United States _ one out of every 150 residents. With rare
exceptions, they have one thing in common: They all get out. Most
of them come out no better off than when they went in.
</P>
<P>
   Most have no practical plans for making it in the real world.
</P>
<P>
   Most, with little education and few skills, resort to the
underground economy, commit new crimes and are soon rearrested.
</P>
<P>
   What if someone came up with an idea that could end this cycle?
You would think that governments and sociologists would be
clamoring to fund, study and replicate such an amazing idea.
</P>
<P>
   That someone does exist. Her programs have stopped criminal
behavior in hundreds of former criminals. As sheriff of San
Francisco, I can attest to their success.
</P>
<P>
   Cathrine Sneed is the idea person behind the Garden Project and
the Tree Corps, two programs designed to train and employ
ex-offenders. She is also the program manager, the fund-raiser, the
inspirational speaker and the person who makes these programs work.
</P>
<P>
   A recidivism study printed in American Jails magazine reported
that while 55 percent of offenders released from the county jail
were rearrested within one year, only 27 percent of the 390 Garden
Project participants were rearrested within four years of their
release.
</P>
<P>
   Just what is the secret of Sneed's success? She teaches work
skills, requires former outlaws to move back into the framework of
a lawful society (get a driver's license and bank account, take
adult education classes) and urges them toward the self-respect and
self-sufficiency that employment brings.
</P>
<P>
   It takes more than good intentions to break back into the
mainstream of society.
</P>
<P>
   This is where the genius of Cathrine Sneed enters the picture.
</P>
<P>
   We all know that having a legitimate income is the key to a
lawful life. But who is going to give a break to an untested
ex-con?
</P>
<P>
   In the Garden Project and the Tree Corps, Sneed takes offenders
fresh out of jail, puts them to work, mentors them until they learn
how to work, and then helps them find a job elsewhere in the job
market. In Sneed's programs, they learn the joys of gainful labor
and the advantages of not having to run from the cops.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, it is our community that benefits from this
transformation. As these hundreds of Garden Project and Tree Corps
graduates reject the criminal life, thousands of crimes never
happen, government resources are no longer used to incarcerate and
feed them, and new taxpaying employees are created.
</P>
<P>
   Produce from the Garden Project's organic vegetable garden is
sold at farmers' markets and to local businesses. Some produce is
donated to local soup kitchens, the very place that people getting
out of jail often count on for their meals.
</P>
<P>
   Garden Project participants learn not only how to work but also
the real meaning of work: the feeling of success when a job is
finished; the sense of pride one gets when someone compliments the
product; the satisfaction of being able to tell your family what
you did today; the comfort of having a source of income for the
essentials of living.
</P>
<P>
   The Tree Corps is an advanced work program for ex-offenders,
funded through a street beautification bond program that mandates
the city of San Francisco to maintain and increase trees along
public streets.
</P>
<P>
   This is a full-time, hard-labor job _ digging out dead tree
stumps, tamping soil and hefting trees into newly dug holes. In the
eight years that the Tree Corps has been in existence, its members
have planted and cared for more than 7,500 new trees in San
Francisco, often in the poorer neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Tree Corps participants move on to other full-time
employment, bringing with them a record of hard work and pride in
accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the Garden Project nor the Tree Corps can operate
without support. Innovation and community support have been the
keys to success so far.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco Sheriff's Department pays Sneed's salary and
rents an eight-acre plot of land to her non-profit group for $1 a
year. Several business owners on the Garden Project's advisory
board have purchased produce and hired graduates.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, every year it is a struggle for Sneed to find funds.
</P>
<P>
   As a non-profit organization, the Garden Project is always
looking for foundation support, contributions from businesses or
citizens and new employment avenues for graduates.
</P>
<P>
   Now that you know someone has a key to stopping crime, maybe you
know someone else who wants to be part of this remarkable project.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Michael Hennessey has been San Francisco sheriff since 1980.
Write to Cathrine Sneed c/o the Garden Project, Pier 28, San
Francisco, CA 94105.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
