A3518 &Cx1f; paxxx
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-COUNSEL-PA     06-29 0422
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-COUNSEL-PA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        SPECTER CALLS FOR INDEPENDENCE IN INDEPENDENT COUNSEL
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Tiffany Lynch  
 &HT;    c. 1999 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, June 29 -- Pennsylvania Sen. Arlen Specter and other
members of the Senate said they are concerned that a new policy
will make the office of Independent Counsel less independent.
</P>
<P>
   A Department of Justice measure puts the independent counsel
under the guidance of the Attorney General -- an office that could
be the subject of an investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Specter said the chain of command created an ``irreconcilable
conflict-of-interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Specter and three other senators spoke out against the DOJ
proposal Tuesday and introduced an alternative. The legislation,
called the Independent Counsel Reform Act of 1999, would limit the
power of the independent counsel and hold the investigator to the
same regulations as other federal prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   The current independent counsel system, created in the aftermath
of Watergate, allows the Attorney General to call on an individual
to investigate and prosecute crimes by up to 200 officials,
including the President. It will expire on July 1.
</P>
<P>
   Under the current process, the independent counsel is
independent of the Attorney General and the Department of Justice.
But under new Department of Justice regulations, the Attorney
General has the power to remove special counsels and veto their
actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that the rule of law is indispensable and you can't
have a rule of law if the individual is investigating himself or
the person in charge of him has an irreconcilable
conflict-of-interst,'' Specter said.
</P>
<P>
   Specter said he would also like to see Congress use its power to
change the DOJ rule. He said he will work on trying to revise the
DOJ plan, in addition to pushing his own legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Specter's measure would reign in the power of the independent
counsel. It would limit the possible subjects of investigations to
the President, Vice President, the Cabinet and the President's
chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
   The measure would hold investigations to a two year period,
unless a special court approves additional time for the inquiry. An
independent counsel wouldn't be able to expand the investigation
from the original purpose. It would also prevent investigators with
a conflict of interest from launching a case.
</P>
<P>
   Specter said the need for tighter control over the independent
counsel was because of the liberty and expansion past prosecutors
such as Kenneth Starr have taken with investigations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-99 1721EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
