<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-HELLMAN-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`AMERICAN MASTERS': HELLMAN AND HAMMETT, STURM UND DRANG 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although the biographies of Lillian Hellman and Dashiell
Hammett, carried in tandem on Wednesday night's American Masters
series, are linked by romance and politics, fame and hard knocks,
they are studies in contrast.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lives of Lillian Hellman'' is a very public document,
while ``Dashiell Hammett. Detective. Writer'' is as private and as
elusive as the Continental Op, Hammett's famous fictional
detective. The Hammett biography is mainly about the writer's work,
with helpings of the movie version of his novel ``The Maltese
Falcon''; the Hellman biography is less about her writing than
about her contentious personality.
</P>
<P>
   ``The detective is an anonymous character,'' a Hammett scholar
says. ``He has, as it were, no individuality. His individuality is
simply what he does.'' Hammett was similarly shy on personal
details. The program's narrator says that he ``almost seems to have
willfully covered the traces of his own life.''
</P>
<P>
   Hellman was 11 years younger than Hammett. When they met in
Hollywood, he was at the peak of his fame as a best-selling writer
of mysteries, notably ``The Thin Man''; she had not yet begun to
write. Soon, in a strange sort of transference, he bequeathed his
talent to her, beginning with the idea for her first play, ``The
Children's Hour.''
</P>
<P>
   A critic, Joan Mellen, says that the history of literature
``would be hard pressed to find another example of a man who so
selflessly helped a woman to achieve the most out of her, I would
say, somewhat limited gifts. She was smart, she was clever, but she
wasn't a natural, and he was a natural. And he gave her everything
that he had.''
</P>
<P>
   Their life together, beginning in the 1930s on Hardscrabble
Farm, combined left-wing politics and random affairs, heavy
drinking and chain smoking. As his career faded, hers took off.
``These Three,'' her 1936 movie adaptation of ``The Children's
Hour,'' was a hit. The narrator reports, ``Lillian was now rich and
famous while the rest of the country was starving.''
</P>
<P>
   Politics and playwriting merged. She went to Spain on behalf of
the Loyalist cause and wrote ``The Little Foxes,'' a memoir of
growing up, and then ``Watch on the Rhine,'' an anti-Fascist play.
She won the gratitude of the Russians with ``The North Star,'' a
pro-Soviet movie that one critic likened to a bowl of borscht.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1940s she joined the presidential campaign for Henry
Wallace's third party and helped organize the Communist-influenced
Waldorf Peace Conference. Around this time, during the
Communist-hunting era, Hammett was sentenced to six months in jail
and Hellman, refusing to ``cut my conscience to fit this year's
fashions,'' would not answer questions from the House Committee on
Un-American Activities. She was blacklisted by the movies, but her
1960 play, ``Toys in the Attic,'' was a hit; a few months later, in
1961, Hammett died.
</P>
<P>
   Hellman took up with another writer, who was many years her
junior, and set out on a series of best-selling biographies that
blended fact and fiction. When the novelist Mary McCarthy called
her a liar, Hellman sued. As Norman Mailer commented, ``Lillian was
not someone who was anchored to the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Afflicted by glaucoma, emphysema and strokes, Hellman battled
death as she had battled in the causes to which she gave her life.
A friend, the writer Richard Poirier, reports that as she lay dying
she said, ``I was fun, wasn't I?'' Many disagreed, but another
friend said at her funeral, ``She was awful and she was worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAN MASTERS: The Lives of Lillian Hellman
</P>
<P>
   PBS, Wednesday night, 9 p.m.)
</P>
<P>
   Susan Lacy, executive producer; Julian Schlossberg, producer;
Phillip Schopper, director. A co-production of WNET in New York and
Castle Hill Productions. Jac Venza, director of cultural and arts
programs at WNET.
</P>
<P>
   Dashiell Hammett. Detective. Writer.
</P>
<P>
   PBS, Wednesday night, 10 p.m.)
</P>
<P>
   Susan Lacy, executive producer; Margaret Smilow, producer;
Joshua Waletzky, director. A co-production of WNET in New York and
Alternate Current. Jac Venza, director of cultural and arts
programs at WNET.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-99 1721EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
