<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, June 30, 1999, sent to computer graphics clients of The
New York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Numerous locations across the Northeast and Middle Atlantic
States received abundant rainfall Tuesday as an arriving cold front
sparked thundershowers by lifting warm, humid air. The southern
portion of this front will become stationary Wednesday from the
Carolinas to southern Oklahoma. Many places near the front will
have showers and thunderstorms again, with larger clusters of
storms along the Carolina Coast, in the lower Mississippi Valley
and the southern Plains.
</P>
<P>
   A region of low pressure in extreme northern Minnesota will
bring showers and clouds to portions of the western Great Lakes.
Behind this system, cool and dry and air will filter to the south
across the northern Plains. Meanwhile, sunny skies are likely over
much of interior New England as high pressure moves into the
region.
</P>
<P>
   Showers and low clouds are likely near the coast in the Pacific
Northwest as a jet stream disturbance at 18,000 feet moves onshore.
The jet stream over the Northwest is unusually fast-moving for this
time of year, allowing numerous disturbances to continually
approach the coastline. This will keep cool, damp weather anchored
in this region.
</P>
<P>
   Scattered showers are likely in Florida, especially in the
northern parts of the peninsula, as a weak disturbance promotes
thunderstorms. Much of the Southwest and Central Valley of
California will remain very hot and dry, with temperatures reaching
triple digits in lower elevations. Some locations from southwest
Texas to southern Arizona, however, will have isolated
thunderstorms during the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Focus: Heat Wave &LR;
</P>
<P>
   An official heat wave was declared on Monday along the Northeast
Seaboard as temperatures from New York City to Boston climbed to 90
degrees or more for the third consecutive day. Reaching 90 degrees
for three consecutive days or more was proposed as a universal
criterion for a heat wave in 1900. But such a rigid criterion does
not take into account normal conditions in certain regions. For
example, the average daily high in Dallas reaches 90 on June 6 and
stays at 90 or above until September 12. Applying this definition
of a heat wave at Dallas ignores the city's `normal' summer heat.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
