<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3538 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-BOS &LR;      06-29 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURIER TOUGHS OUT BRITISH ONSLAUGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ They've tried firing their two deadliest weapons at
him, baking him, dehydrating him, sticking needles in him,
squeezing him on line calls _ in his opinion, anyway _ and
drenching him. And still the English can't get rid of Jim Courier.
</P>
<P>
   The Ugliest American in these parts has been on a reign of
terror spanning two months, and while the natives applaud his
resiliency, they'd really rather bid him good riddance.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, they're close, but they've been there before and they know
how comfortable he is on the precipice.
</P>
<P>
   Courier's two-fisted performance remained on hold Tuesday, as
did all the action at Wimbledon, inundated by rain and forced to
suspend play without a ball being struck. The postponement was
announced at approximately 6:30 p.m., some eight hours after the
grounds opened to approximately 30,000 fans who brought their
brollies but never got their jollies. For only the 30th time in the
113-year history of The Championships, there was not one stroke of
competition, and while the patrons received refunds,
concessionaires hit the jackpot on strawberries and cream,
champagne and Pimms, and souvenir seat cushions.
</P>
<P>
   And Courier lived on. The Grudge Match against Tim Henman _ who
was hoping to avenge the 3-2 first-round Davis Cup loss the United
States, principally Courier, inflicted on the Brits at Birmingham
in April _ remained where it had the night before when play
initially was suspended. Henman leads in sets, 2-1, and has a 4-3,
30-15 advantage in the fourth. Potentially, he's within two games
of victory, and he hoped to complete the job Tuesday. But the
closest he and Courier came to combat was standing around for three
minutes at Centre Court before rain shooed them back into the
players' locker room and the tarpaulins and tents were brought back
out. They'll try again Wednesday, but Henman and his countrymen
know better than to sleep easy on the advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Courier became the scourge of the Empire when he outlasted first
top-ranked Brit Henman, 7-6, 2-6, 7-6, 6-7, 7-5, and then, in the
deciding match, No. 2 Rusedski, 6-4, 6-7, 6-3, 1-6, 8-6.
</P>
<P>
   That signaled two things: Those attending the US-Australia
quarterfinal July 16-18 at Longwood should make late dinner
reservations when Courier plays; and his career is back on an
upswing.
</P>
<P>
   Ranked No. 1 in the world the last time he advanced past the
second round at Wimbledon, 1992, Courier seemed to be washed up
this year at 28, as illustrated by his No. 62 ranking.
</P>
<P>
   But the Cup apparently was his elixir, and he has continued his
Rasputin impersonation here. A straight-set first-round breeze past
another unfortunate Brit, Barry Cowan, was an anomaly. Then
Courier, who came here with a vicious head cold, reverted to his
favorite style: long, grueling, and chock full of adversity.
</P>
<P>
   Spaniard Carlos Moya was supposed to take care of him for the
hosts, but Courier outsweated him, 6-3, 3-6, 7-6 (8-6), 5-7, 6-3,
on Centre Court. He surely was dead against Dutchman Sjeng Schalken
in the third round Friday, dropping the first two sets in stifling
heat. But he flat out refused to surrender, scrambled back to tie
the match, then won the protracted fifth-set duel, 13-11.
</P>
<P>
   After spending 4 hours 27 minutes dodging bullets, Courier
required intravenous treatment and was transported to a hospital.
But no sooner was the needle out of his arm than he was out of the
emergency room, and he returned to Wimbledon Saturday for a belated
press conference full of vim and vitriol. Having suffered severe
cramps before he received treatment the day before, he berated All
England Club officials for the absence of IVs on the premises.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the only tournament _ only country _ that we play in
where this is the case, from what our trainers tell us,'' said
Courier. ``I'd heard this before from other players. They'd run
into the same brick wall of conservatism. I'm sure there are
different medical aspects here in this country, but you know,
top-level athletes should be above all that stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   He spoke of his affection for hostile crowds _ the more
boisterous, the better. ``I've always been told or always heard
that I shouldn't do this or I couldn't do that,'' he said, ``and so
I'm used to those kind of naysayers, so to speak, so maybe that's
why I respond to that.''
</P>
<P>
   He agreed that the past few weeks have rejuvenated him, restored
his juices more than any IV could. ``I think it's a new experience
for me,'' said Courier. ``I feel much older, much wiser. That's
probably a myth.''
</P>
<P>
   Henman hopes to turn Courier's British domination into one, and
Wednesday, like Monday, he'll be backed by a capacity house of
13,813 who will scream his name at every pause, flaunt the Union
Jack, and savor every Courier misadventure.
</P>
<P>
   And if that doesn't work, they always can unleash pestilence and
famine. They've tried just about everything else against Courier.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
