<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTHING SHORT ABOUT BUNNY AUSTIN'S MEMORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COULSTON, England _ Bunny Austin focuses his alert and kindly
blue-green eyes on the TV screen, and then looks out the window.
Same picture: rain. Lots of it. Not much of a day for the fair
ladies in their Wimbledon finery.
</P>
<P>
   Prof. Henry Higgins had it wrong. Since he and Eliza Doolittle
were Londoners, he should have phrased it: The rain's a pain that
falls mainly on a plain called Wimbledon _ and has nothing to do
with Spain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, it rained in my day, too,'' smiles Henry Wilfred ``Bunny''
Austin, a sartorial benefactor who ought to be remembered in the
prayers of every male tennis player. ``But I'm sorry when it rains
during Wimbledon because it's such a delight for me on the TV. I
can't get out anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Bunny Austin, who will be 93 in August, is the answer to a
couple of trivia questions. Who was the last Englishman to grace
the Wimbledon final? And who emancipated men's knees by amputating
his pant legs to introduce shorts on the international circuit?
</P>
<P>
   Before Bunny's revolutionary tailoring, long white flannel
trousers were the encumbering but accepted costume. ``I acknowledge
that I'm best known for that. But not very happy about it because I
was quite a good player.''
</P>
<P>
   No doubt about that. Austin, cultivated, genial and sharp, has
been pretty much immobilized by a fall three years ago, and largely
forgotten. Sitting in his pleasant room in a retirement home
located in a bucolic sector of Surrey, he is most proud of the
framed document on the wall among sunny prints of Utrillo and Van
Gogh. It's his certificate of admission to a pantheon, the
International Tennis Hall of Fame at Newport, R.I.
</P>
<P>
   Wimbledon finalist in 1932 and 1938, French finalist in 1937, he
was a world top 10 resident 11 straight years from 1928, No. 2 in
1931 and 1938. Moreover, ``The most rewarding part of my career was
Davis Cup _ going to Paris to take it away from the French in 1933
and holding it until 1937.''
</P>
<P>
   Austin was a player, all right, but one who has lived in a
couple of shadows: the shorts breakthrough, and teammate Fred
Perry, the greatest of all Limeys, the last of their Wimbledon
champs, 1934-35-36.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it took two of us to win those four Davis Cups. Fred
couldn't do it alone,'' Bunny points out correctly. ``But he
usually got the credit.'' Yet Austin does hold the British singles
record in Davis Cup: 36-12.
</P>
<P>
   Don Budge, the 6-1, 6-0, 6-3, victor over Austin in 1938,
remembers him as ``a beautiful strokemaker, steady groundstrokes
and good volleys. Quick on his feet. He really played well that day
despite the score.''
</P>
<P>
   Austin nods. ``Don's nice to say that. I thought I hit the ball
all right, but at that time he was unplayable. The best I ever
faced. Don could have played with anyone today. I feel our great
players could have, but most players today are much better, and I
enjoy watching them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't have imagined, though, in 1938 that I would be the
last Englishman in the final. All those years ago. Roger Taylor, a
semifinalist in 1973, should have won, but I've almost given up
hope. I'd like to see (Tim) Henman go all the way this year, but I
admire what (Jim) Courier did against us in the Davis Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   Austin was unlucky to reach finals that linked him with
juggernauts: Ellsworth Vines in 1932, then Budge, the original
Grand Slammer for whom Bunny represented the third side of that
quintessential quadrilateral.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vines?'' he laughs about the 6-4, 6-2, 6-0, defeat. ``As
unplayable as Budge that day. He had 30 aces in 12 service games,
and some of them I never saw.''
</P>
<P>
   Bunny, who bears a schoolboy nickname _ ``I think it was my
protruding front teeth that gave me a sort of rabbit look'' _
feels, ``My best tennis was in Davis Cup. The finale of 1934, over
the US, when I beat Sidney Wood and Frank Shields. He was Brooke
Shields's grandfather, a great bon vivant, who once sailed to the
States by accident after the French. Frank was attending a
going-away party on a liner at Cherbourg, forgot to get off and
thus missed Wimbledon. The champagne must have been very good.''
</P>
<P>
   The inspiration for shorts hit him ``in New England, either
Boston or Newport, 1932. It was ghastly hot. Flannels soaked with
sweat meant you carried an awful lot of weight between knee and
shoe. I'd played soccer in school, so why not shorts for tennis. It
made sense. I bought a pair in New York in 1932 and used them at
Forest Hills. The next year I wore them here, on Centre Court, and
thought there'd be a fuss. But no one cared.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nor did they when my sister, Joan, was a bit daring in 1931,
the first woman to play on Centre without stockings.''
</P>
<P>
   Bunny likes Anna Kournikova's attire and is sure his sister
would, too. ``I've seen it all. I remember seeing the champion,
Mrs. Lambert Chambers, in dresses to the ground, and the women
sometimes bleeding from the stays in their whalebone corsets.
Suzanne Lenglen came along and changed all that in 1919 with her
short skirts. She was absolutely hypnotic. Beautiful body. Moved
beautifully. I couldn't take my eyes off her.''
</P>
<P>
   A concierge in Monte Carlo couldn't take his eyes off Bunny, and
tried to be helpful. ``It was in my early days of shorts. I left
the hotel for the courts with a topcoat over mine. The man seemed
embarrassed, but he worriedly said, `Mr Austin, excuse me, but I
think you've forgotten your trousers.' I thanked him and
explained.''
</P>
<P>
   Bunny has forgotten little, and his Hall of Fame membership
assures that he'll be remembered.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
