<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3551 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-SOCCER-0630-CO     06-29 0481
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-SOCCER-0630-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FREE KICKS: ETHNIC ALBANIANS RETURN TO SOCCER STADIUM
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (s) Sports categories.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ One of the defenders for the Pristina
soccer club might move a little slowly this year. He's coming off
the disabled list from a shrapnel wound from his time in the Kosovo
Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   But, 27-year-old Hysni Gjinovci(CQ) felt good kicking a ball
around Tuesday while his teammates jogged.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the second greatest day for me. The first was the
liberation, this is second,'' Gjinovci said. ``This is my love. I
love soccer.''
</P>
<P>
   Made possible by the withdrawal of Serb troops and the
protection of NATO peacekeepers, ethnic Albanians re-entered the
Pristina stadium as players for the first time in nearly 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   The soccer practice was a sign, two weeks after NATO entered
this war-shattered province, that aspects of normality are slowly
returning to its provincial capital. Street lights are beginning to
work, a few restaurants have opened and, according to British
military police, the number of murders is steadily dropping.
</P>
<P>
   Starting in 1989, when Serbia removed the autonomous status of
the province of Kosovo, official soccer teams were purged of ethnic
Albanian players and coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Albanian players were not allowed to play in the 40,000 seat
stadium. They formed their own parallel leagues and tried to play
in small villages and fields, often being made to stop by Serb
police.
</P>
<P>
   Albanian leaders of the local soccer teams wanted to show that
they, too, are getting back to business. They held a mid-day
exhibition in front of about 60 pleased fans.
</P>
<P>
   The field was a little shaggy and the players rusty. They played
a half-field scrimmage only.
</P>
<P>
   Beneath the stands, the locker rooms still showed the creepy
signs of occupation by Serb troops, who ran a campaign of
atrocities during the NATO bombing of Yugoslavia. Two empty
ammunition crates sat on a training table, blood stained the seats
by the lockers.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, the players held a moment of silence for the many
ethnic Albanians killed _ several players are still missing and at
least one is known murdered. Then they turned to applaud their 60
fans and popped open champagne.
</P>
<P>
   Beqir Aliu was president of the Pristina team until 1989. He was
repeatedly arrested by Serbs as he tried to organize black-market
games. His brother, a soccer player, was killed by Serb troops
during the NATO air war.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the happiest day of my life. This is the only moment
that I have forgotten about my brother,'' said the 48-year-old Aliu
as he watched the team take the field. ``I promised I would restart
... Sports brings people together.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
