<HEADER>
A3553 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GAYS-SCHOOLS30-COX     06-29 0503
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAYS-SCHOOLS30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Becoming educated about gay issues
 &HT;    By Lyle V. Harris
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Early on in the documentary ``It's Elementary: Talking About Gay
Issues in School,'' a curly-haired fourth-grader sums up his
feelings about homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how their life is, they're gay. So what?'' he says with
the kind of moral certitude only a 9-year-old can muster. Then,
without missing a beat, he raises a more pressing issue with his
teacher: ``Can I go to the bathroom now?''
</P>
<P>
   With a chipper earnestness and a bare-bones premise, ``It's
Elementary'' profiles a half-dozen schools around the country that
are incorporating lessons about gay life into their curriculums.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to teach diversity and tolerance, the schools invite
speakers into their classrooms, hold weeklong celebrations and have
teachers lead students in candid discussions.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, not everyone's pleased. The Christian Coalition of
Georgia petitioned WPBA president Milton Clipper and Gov. Roy
Barnes to cancel the broadcast, saying it ``promotes a lifestyle
that is unhealthy and in direct contradiction to the traditional
family model.''
</P>
<P>
   The station's decision to air the program would seem courageous
under different circumstances. But this isn't ``Tales From the
City,'' the 1994 miniseries that featured gay and straight sex that
got sister station WGTV in hot water with conservative critics.
</P>
<P>
   For one, there is no explicit sex talk. When a curious middle
schooler asks a guest speaker ``how do you guys do it?'' he
politely tells her he's not allowed to discuss his sex life.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not here to recruit you,'' he tells her. ``We are not
here to make you gay or lesbian.''
</P>
<P>
   They are, however, trying to make the students think. At times
it seems to be working.
</P>
<P>
   It's evident as a group of fourth-graders listens to Disney's
``The Lion King'' theme song and are surprised that the pop idol
who sings it, Elton John, is gay. There's also the unmistakable
flash of insight as a group of second graders discover a schoolmate
has two mothers at home, not a mom and a dad.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad such moments are few. Once you get over the built-in
shock of children discussing homosexuality in school, there's not
much else here to keep it interesting.
</P>
<P>
   It feels somewhat lopsided. Producers Helen S. Cohen and Debra
Chasnoff open the program with canned footage of a senator from New
Hampshire criticizing the homosexual curriculum as ``filth,'' and
there are later clips of irate parents protesting in New York. Both
images have a tacked-on look.
</P>
<P>
   What saves ``It's Elementary'' are the students; hopeful, smart,
precocious, funny kids who are learning how to handle a reality
some of their parents still have a hard time talking about.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Elementary: Talking About Gay Issues in School''
</P>
<P>
   9 p.m. WPBA
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   Lyle V. Harris writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
