<HEADER>
A3554 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-COMMERCIALS30-COX     06-29 0411
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-COMMERCIALS30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Greatest Commercials' not enough of good thing
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Billing a special as the ``50 Greatest Commercials of All Time''
and then limiting it only to American ads is like listing the 50
best soccer players of all time and only counting Americans. It's
beyond narrow-minded, bordering on ignorant.
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to be a world traveler to know that many of the
most creative (and outrageous) TV commercials are devised for
consumers in Great Britain, Japan and Australia. Heck, British beer
commercials alone rival the best of what America has produced.
</P>
<P>
   But we love our lists, so TV Guide polled 37 (American)
advertising executives as to what they thought were the best.
Although the criteria are never explained, it's hard to argue with
their top choice: Apple's famous ``1984'' ad, which ran only once,
during the 1984 Super Bowl. It was both fabulously produced
(directed by Ridley Scott, with an anti-Orwell, smashing-Big
Brother theme) and very effective: the Macintosh personal computer
it introduced flew off the shelves.
</P>
<P>
   Also ranking high: two classic Volkswagen ads from the '60s (the
funeral procession and the guy who drives the snowplow),
Alka-Seltzer's ``spicy meatballs'' and Federal Express'
fast-talking guy.
</P>
<P>
   Besides its self-imposed limitations, what's most frustrating is
that there isn't one single ad that's presented in its entirety
without interruption. So we see Clara Peller bellowing ``Where's
the beef?'' and the little dog saying ``Yo quiero Taco Bell,'' as
tiny snippets. But what else could they have done to fit 50
commercials (plus the commercials that support the show about
commercials) into a half-hour?
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who cares about TV commercials _ how they work, why the
good ones are so good _ might check out ``The 100 Best TV
Commercials'' (Times Books, $29.95), a new book independent of the
TV Guide list and TVLand special. International in scope and with
better analysis (it also ends up ranking ``1984'' as the best
commercial ever), the only thing missing from the book is the
ability to watch Michael Jordan and Larry Bird do their ``nothing
but net'' bit for McDonald's.
</P>
<P>
   ``TVLand Presents the 50 Greatest Commercials of All Time''
</P>
<P>
   8 tonight on TVLand.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C-
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
