 UPDATE &HT;    UPDATE
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Wednesday, June 30,
1999.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eds: Adds: SC-VIDEO-POKER, GA-MEDICARE
</P>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-CALIFORNIA _ SAN DIEGO, Calif. _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush
begins a three-day campaign trip in California with a fundraiser in
San Diego and a speech at the fairgrounds. (Herman, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   w/BUSH-CALIF-FACTS _ SAN DIEGO, Calif. _ Facts about the
Califonria. (Herman, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   GORE _ MIAMI _ Vice President Al Gore attends the first
constitutional convention of UNITE. (Crowley, Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN _ With a decision not to participate in the Iowa straw
poll in August, Sen. John McCain (R-Ariz.) is pinning his
presidential hopes on strong showings in New Hampshire and South
Carolina. McCain has virtually divided his campaign time between
the two states, and he returns to New Hampshire today to open a
fresh assault on the nation's campaign finance laws. Defying the
conventional wisdom that campaign finance reform is an issue that
won't sell with Republican voters, McCain will blame Republicans
and the Democrats for supporting a system that allows special
interests to write laws, riddle the tax code with loopholes and
lard up the budget with pork barrel spending. (Foskett, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 25.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-POLLING _ WASHINGTON _ A look at a new plan to conduct
2000 election polling via the Internet. Some see this is a
milestone development for polling, comparable to switching from
face-to-face interviews to telephones. (Shepard, Cox News Service).
22.
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
</P>
<P>
   HISPANICS-GEORGIA _ ATLANTA _ Gov. Roy Barnes announces an
effort to get Hispanic Georgians to register to vote _ an
initiative that could very well assist the governor's choice in
next year's presidential campaign, Vice President Al Gore.
Three-fourths of new Hispanic voters tend to register and vote
Democratic. Regardless, in Georgia and elsewhere, they are a key
bloc in the 2000 elections. At the same time, Barnes is seeking to
elevate Hispanics' status in state politics by appointing a group
to recommend legislation next year to boost Hispanic interests.
(Judd, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (a) general news and (p) politics categories.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE _ WASHINGTON _ President Clinton unveils the
long-awaited details of his plan to reform Medicare. (Lipman, Cox
News Service). 30.
</P>
<P>
   w/GA-MEDICARE _ ATLANTA _ Far from the pharmacy on Peachtree
Street, President Clinton unveiled plans for Medicare to include a
prescription drug benefit that could help many of the 870,000
Georgia seniors like Foster who depend on Medicare. Two out of
three state seniors now have some coverage for drugs, but the
remaining third _ many of them middle class and rural residents _
are shelling out as much as hundreds of dollars each month without
any discounts. With short profiles of two seniors (one will save
$300 a month under the Clinton plan; the other a mere $20). (Lore,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BLACK-FARMERS _ WASHINGTON _ The National Black Farmers
Association sets a 3 p.m. EDT protest at the Agriculture Department
over delays in implementing the settlement of its class action
lawsuit alleging USDA bias. (Hill, Cox News Service). 10.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   INS-RAILKILLER_ As the FBI continues to hunt for suspected
serial killer Rafael Resendez-Ramirez, the INS is being showered
with questions about how Border Patrol agents let him slip through
their fingers. The answer, according to INS sources, is that no one
was looking for him, and their computerized identification system,
dubbed IDENT, didn't include a red flag to alert agents when
Resendez- Ramirez's fingerprints were scanned after his June 2
apprehension. The IDENT system, according to agents, is set up to
tell them how many times an immigrant has been detained, not to
give them the criminal history of everyone they catch _ it is not
linked to national crime networks like NCIC. Still, a California
agent says the suspected killer's prior deportations should have
caused agents to probe deeper into his past. (Harmon, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   INFANT-DEATHS _ LONGVIEW, Texas _ More than 2,000 couples suffer
the loss of a child younger than 1-year-old each year in Texas.
Child Protective Service staff members and local committees are
examining the circumstances surrounding child deaths across the
state to see if they can be prevented. (Moore, Longview News
Journal). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Attention Texas editors.
</P>
<P>
   SC-VIDEO-POKER _ The South Carolina legislature is expected
today to approve a ballot question that would require elimination
of or regulation of video poker across the state. As one of the few
states without any such regulation, South Carolina now has the
dubious distinction of having more video poker machines than any
other state in the country, including Las Vegas. (Manuel, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SOCCER _ PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ Ten years after being
from their playing in their home stadium, Kosovar Albanian soccer
players are returning. Like baseball is to Americans, soccer is to
Albanians. Developing. (Kaplow, Cox News Service). 12.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (i) International and (s) Sports categories.
</P>
