<DOCNO> NYT19990629.0200 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3570 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KITCHEN-WARES-ART-NYT     06-29 1200
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KITCHEN-WARES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIZZLING, AND SPUTTERING, AND NO CHARCOAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is addressed to the hibachi haters of the world, which is
to say everyone who finds crude little charcoal grills so dirty,
slow and inconvenient in countless other ways that they can wreck
any holiday weekend.
</P>
<P>
   There is an alternative: miniature gas grills. They are,
relatively speaking, pristine. By comparison with their charcoal
brethren, they are nearly effort free. But by definition, they are
also less powerful than a full-size gas grill; even a small
charcoal grill can get hotter. Can you actually grill well on them?
And how do the different brands compare?
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that while there are a great number of the little
charcoal versions, there are really only two miniature gas models
available: the Coleman Powermax Grill Stove and the Weber
Go-Anywhere Gas Grill. To test them, I borrowed a neighbor's patio
for an afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Both grills are a cinch to set up. The Coleman opens like a
suitcase, and has wings attached to the lid, which prop up and act
as wind guards. Gas canisters, which must be purchased specifically
for this grill, simply screw into the back and it's ready to go.
</P>
<P>
   The Weber requires a little assembly. It is more like a standard
grill, raised off the ground and fitted with a lid and a wooden
handle. It takes small propane canisters, which can be purchased in
hardware stores.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings up the issue of grilling in New York City. It is
illegal to bring gas canisters that are heavier than one pound into
a building in the city. (Both of these grills use canisters that
weigh less than a pound.) Grills must also be placed at least 10
feet away from any combustible surface and you must have either a
hose connected to a water source or a 16-quart pail of water
nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Though the little Weber has an automatic starter, I had to light
it by hand. It seemed to be getting very hot, very quickly.
</P>
<P>
   After heating the grill on high for 15 minutes, I laid down my
first experiment: spicy poultry sausages. Nothing happened. I
checked the heat. It was indeed as high as it would go. I bent down
closer to the grilling surface. If I listened very, very carefully
I could hear a faint sputtering, a suggestion of cooking. There was
no smoke.
</P>
<P>
   While the sausages warmed, I moved on to skewered scallops. I
brushed some with olive oil and wrapped others in bacon. When I
laid them on the grill, I heard my first sizzle. Fat, I realized,
was essential to getting anything resembling a grill-like sear.
Without it, this was just going to be an outdoor toaster oven.
</P>
<P>
   I set the lid on top of the grill, and soon there was more
sizzling and a ribbon of smoke. As the bacon cooked, it dripped fat
and scallop juice onto what is called a flavorizer bar _ a vented
cover over the gas flame invented to replace lava rocks. When the
fat and juice hit the flavorizer bar, they immediately cook off,
circulating aroma and smoke inside the grill. I was getting
somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The scallops wrapped in bacon cooked best, browning lightly on
the edges, and the sausages eventually cooked through but never
developed the deep grill marks and blistering I wanted.
</P>
<P>
   Slabs of Vidalia onion brushed with oil browned on the edges and
softened slowly _ a pleasant effect not easily achieved with a hot
grill.
</P>
<P>
   Burgers made of ground chuck roast, not a terribly lean cut,
dripped and sizzled, as did lamb chops brushed with olive oil. But
with the lid down and the searing slow, the lamb chops cooked too
slowly. They browned on the outside but cooked through further than
I would have liked.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: The grill worked. Kind of. With rigging, the food
browned. But it was underwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   I called the Weber-Stephen Products Co., the maker of the grill,
to see what it thought of the performance. Unfortunately, it seems,
it has limited ambition for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like comparing a grape to a full-blown piece of fruit,''
Betty Hughes, the company's director of consumer affairs, said of
the miniature grill relative to the larger backyard grills.
``There's just no comparison.''
</P>
<P>
   My hopes for the Coleman Powermax Grill Stove, which appeared
more a camping convenience than a serious cook's appliance, had
diminished.
</P>
<P>
   I heated the grill to high and placed a fat round slice of onion
on top. Within a minute, it had dark, distinct grill stripes on it.
I actually needed to turn the heat (italics)down!(end italics)
</P>
<P>
   There is no flavorizer bar in the Coleman grill. The grill rack
is closer to the heating element and the base than the Weber, so
any drippings cook on the base, sending up wafts of smoke and
flavor to the food cooking above.
</P>
<P>
   There is also temperature variation on the grill. It is cooler
on the perimeter and hotter in the center, so when grilling the
onions for instance, I first browned them on the center, then moved
them to the exterior to finish cooking.
</P>
<P>
   The Coleman also has an extra feature: a gas burner. If you're
camping, this is great for any number of tasks: boiling water,
cooking hot cereal, heating canned soups. It is also helpful for
terrace grilling. You can heat a sauce or keep a marinade warm
while you grill meats.
</P>
<P>
   The sausages were next. Their casings blistered and colored, and
the meat heated through in just a few minutes. The grill striped
the scallops without drying them out or overcooking them. There is
no lid for the grill and it does not need one.
</P>
<P>
   But the real proof that this grill could do its job as well as
any miniature charcoal stove was when I cooked the burgers and lamb
chops. They crackled and sizzled the moment they touched down on
the grill. The burgers gained deep mahogany marks on both sides and
were perfectly pink in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   The fat on the edges of the lamb chop warped and curled under
the heat, and the chops crisped beautifully on the outside while
staying rare on the interior.
</P>
<P>
   Grills are designed to sear food. And as these two grills made
clear, some sear food better than others. Both grills run on 10,000
British thermal units.
</P>
<P>
   BTUs, however, do not measure the efficiency of a particular
grill, or how quickly it sears food.
</P>
<P>
   That is where design comes in. On the Weber, the heat source is
farther from the grilling surface than on the Coleman, making it
more difficult to get it as hot as it needs to be. The Coleman has
another advantage: the base under the gas source is close to it and
angled upward so that heat is reflected in the direction of the
grilling surface, increasing its efficiency even more.
</P>
<P>
   And that makes the difference between outdoor grilling and
outdoor toasting.
</P>
<P>
   The Coleman Powermax Grill Stove is $139.99 at Paragon Athletic
Goods Corp., 867 Broadway (18th Street); (212) 255-8036. Coleman
Powermax Fuel is $4.50 for 6 ounces and $5.50 for 10.6 ounces.
</P>
<P>
   The Weber Go-Anywhere Grill is $54.98 at Zabar's, 2245 Broadway
(80th Street); (212) 787-2000. Propane fuel is available at
hardware stores. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
