NYT-06-29-99 1755EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990629.0201 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3579 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAZZ-FESTIVAL-2TAKES-     06-29 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAZZ-FESTIVAL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: LESS WOULD BE MORE _ JAZZ FESTIVAL BLUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BEN RATLIFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Where there is jazz, there are inflated expectations.
Jazz is patriotism, American genius, our home-grown cultural
aristocracy. People who really love jazz routinely misunderstand
the scale of its popularity; they wonder why the pride of American
culture doesn't have a large audience.
</P>
<P>
   One result of this attitude, in the case of New York's two big
summer jazz festivals, Bell Atlantic Jazz and JVC Jazz, is that
``jazz'' _ the construct, the marketing word, the mystique _ is too
expensive to be supported by the music itself. The jazz needs to be
supported by other forms of music that share its audience (a
tradition of jazz festivals since the late 1960s) and by nostalgia,
which is more problematic. Nostalgia never fails to sell tickets
but usually results in lackluster shows.
</P>
<P>
   That is why I'll remember the 1999 Bell Atlantic festival
principally for a rock show by the Japanese band the Boredoms and
the JVC festival mostly for the nonjazz concerts by the Brazilian
performers Carlinhos Brown (two-thirds full) and Caetano Veloso
(sold out) that closed it last week. And that seems strange.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1988, the two jazz festivals _ the mainstream, big-ticket
JVC and the more alternative, scrappy Bell Atlantic (previously
Texaco and Heineken) _ have gone through various phases of working
together and standing in opposition. The business story may be of
little interest to jazz fans; what's important is that the
festivals once offered different strengths. But now, with not quite
more concerts than ever but still a whopping number (38 at JVC this
year, 120 at Bell Atlantic), both are suffering from a lack of
identity.
</P>
<P>
   The Bell Atlantic festival, which is produced by Knit Media and
therefore uses the Knitting Factory as its flagship performance
space, had a very representative time at the club from June 3 to
13: it was basically a sampling of the normal run of events there
throughout the year (with exceptions _ a rare reunion of members of
Ronald Shannon Jackson's Decoding Society, a series of Berlin-based
groups with no American reputation, a night of Charlie Haden duets,
a night of Dave Douglas bands).
</P>
<P>
   In its defense, programming based on the normal musical life of
the city, the bricks and mortar of the scene, feels honest, and it
answers the need to represent the state of the music. But in
practice, a schedule that swamps a few special attractions with the
ordinary fails to distinguish festival time from nonfestival time _
except that ticket prices double and audiovisual equipment captures
the music for Internet downloading.
</P>
<P>
   This is all to the good for those who have the proper Bell
Atlantic high-speed Internet connections and are in remote cities
and don't get to hear a lot of live music. But computer stuff
aside, we are physically in New York, yes? (On the plus side,
sponsorship by a telecommunications giant also led to a series of
music seminars for high school students on the Web, and at the
festival's Web site, www.jazfest.com, one can also custom design a
CD of live material from the festival.)
</P>
<P>
   For bigger events, Bell Atlantic Jazz used other spaces: Town
Hall for Grover Washington Jr. (booked partly as a corporate event
for Bell Atlantic brass), Roseland for the neo-swing band Big Bad
Voodoo Daddy (expensive tickets, expensive to produce, and it
didn't sell out), and the South Street Seaport Atrium for a
combination of rock and jazz shows.
</P>
<P>
   One has to admire Knit Media's simple achievement of booking
some great-to-interesting-to-loony noncommercial acts at the
Seaport Atrium, a major stage at a major festival. They included
the reunion of the free jazz group the New York Art Quartet (June
13), and the Boredoms _ who played one of the most purposeful and
mysterious performances (June 9) I've ever witnessed. To its great
credit, the festival did mix the two perceived camps of jazz _
tradition and the vanguard. But it did so without conceptual
muscle; since the downtown esthetic is about mixing and matching,
more attention should be drawn to how easily these supposedly
opposite teams can share stages and audiences.
</P>
<P>
   But back to the South Street Seaport Atrium: if it were one of
the wonders of the world, perhaps concertgoers wouldn't have minded
paying $20 to $30 to go there for bad sound. It does have a
pleasant deck overlooking the East River. Inside, however, it's a
mall, and experiencing concerts there was every bit as dispiriting
as going to hear art music at a food court (with a loud sports bar
one floor below). The planning and execution of individual nights
there also left much to be desired. For a night of female singers
on June 11, promoters seemed to expect that a middle-aged,
mainstream-jazz crowd would sit through five acts until after 1
a.m. in an unappealing place. The Skatalites concert on June 10
started almost two hours late and an electronic music night on June
4 had lost most of its crowd by 3 a.m., after interminable waits
between sets. This was not just a lack of creature comforts; it was
punishment.
</P>
<P>
   I think I would even give up comfort for better programming,
though. Where were the special lineups of past years, with groups
from Amsterdam, Chicago and elsewhere that we've heard about but
don't often get to see? And where were the experimental jazz groups
that have generated buzz, like Peter Broetzmann's Tentet (it played
in Quebec the week before Bell Atlantic started), the quintet led
by the MacArthur grant recipient Ken Vandermark (it played at
Tonic, in Manhattan, a week after Bell Atlantic ended) and the big
band led by pianist Guillermo Klein (he lives in New York), for
three examples?
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   One word: tributes. Homages to fallen idols suffused the JVC
jazz festival this year, as they did last year; almost a third of
its 38 concerts were homages to figures of jazz's past.
</P>
<P>
   In classical music, there's the concept of the premiere, an
enticement for any concertgoer who wants to stay current; it
narrows the focus of attention to a  &UR; thing &LR; , a new work. Jazz
musicians, of course, deal with the very fluid matter of group
improvisation, which at its best results in a changing experience
from night to night; they don't often come up with new long-form
compositions. So the jazz version of the thing-centered big event
has become the tribute concert.
</P>
<P>
   Compare JVC '99 to JVC '89, when only two of the 38 shows were
tributes. Look at who was still alive and playing in that festival:
Joe Williams, Art Blakey, Ella Fitzgerald, Dizzy Gillespie, Gerry
Mulligan, Mel Torme, Don Pullen. Sure, one didn't need so many
tributes then. But on the other hand, is jazz not still freshly
made? Are people under 45, the not particularly nostalgic, just not
buying tickets? Jazz needs some new popular figures, it's true, but
shouldn't we be scaling down if necessary in order to move on?
</P>
<P>
   Some tributes this year came off well: Cassandra Wilson's homage
to Miles Davis, which she has been developing for years, and Ken
Peplowski's program of Benny Goodman big-band music, with which he
has previously toured. But tributes in general are frustrating.
It's difficult for any band to capture the essence of a beloved
composer, and the spectacle of soloists' filing onstage one after
another to grab one's attention becomes wearying. Newly
commissioned arrangements of old music would be wonderful, but
unless you're talking about a group that's part of an institution _
the Carnegie Hall Jazz Band, say _ it's hard to make that happen.
</P>
<P>
   Tucked into the festival _ with smaller audiences _ were some of
the best working bands and musicians in jazz: Dave Holland's
quintet, Greg Osby's quartet, solo piano performances by Brad
Mehldau and Gonzalo Rubalcaba. Working bands tend to provide great
nights of music, whatever the theme or rubric; they need to be
programmed as much as possible, as opposed to ad hoc supergroups.
</P>
<P>
   The appearance of James Moody in two consecutive concerts _ as a
guest with Dave Brubeck on June 20 and playing the ``Charlie Parker
With Strings'' material the following night _ almost but not quite
constituted a thread: one more night of his terrific playing,
perhaps with a young saxophonist like Mark Turner (they made a
little-heard record together two years ago), and it might have
drawn some welcome attention to Moody and to the festival.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately it's hard for a critic to get a consensus reading on
either festival, because there weren't many surprises; with the
dust cleared, there's strangely little to talk about, and it
resists falling into perspective.
</P>
<P>
   There are some possible solutions to the nebulous character of
the festivals. One _ especially for Bell Atlantic _ is to put more
thought and more money into fewer concerts. The other _ especially
for JVC _ is to scale down. There's no need to abandon Carnegie or
Avery Fisher for the few artists who attract large audiences, like
Oscar Peterson and Cassandra Wilson. But JVC could start using more
small halls, clubs and outdoor spaces (how about some actual
festivity?) for smart, well-programmed bills; a result might be to
give the festival a sense of more deliberate planning, a curator's
touch rather than an opportunistic, whoever's-available feel.
</P>
<P>
   Both festivals desperately need to develop themes and threads
that provide personality. (Montreal's jazz festival does this with
its ``Invitation'' series, runs of three or four consecutive nights
spotlighting the same musician in a different context. It's an idea
worth stealing.)
</P>
<P>
   As far as I could tell, fewer critics than usual attended the
shows this year. Perhaps it's only the critics who have been there
and done that, not the New York jazz audiences. But based on the
excitement stirred up by other, smartly programmed, not exactly
competing summer festivals this summer _ the Vision Festival,
Tonic's New Music Festival and Central Park Summerstage _ I'm not
so sure. Everybody likes a fresh idea presented in the right size.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-99 1801EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990629.0203 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3582 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ICE-CREAM-ART-2TAKES-     06-29 1278
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ICE-CREAM-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEYOND PRIMARY COLORS: BOLD NEW ICE CREAMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By RICK MARIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The heat is making people do weird things to ice
cream. Crazy things. Flavors like bay leaf, oatmeal, Serrano chili,
Sichuan peppercorn, honey-blossom water with dates.
</P>
<P>
   Curry.
</P>
<P>
   Happens every summer now. Chefs and their pastry pros get an
urge to start throwing everything but the busboy into their creme
anglaise: root vegetables, herbs, Belgian beer. And New York diners
keep pushing them further by actually eating the stuff.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, the special ice creams and sorbets at Avenue
include that old standby white pepper, along with tomato cumin,
roasted beet, cucumber, garden mint, Tahitian vanilla steeped in
bourbon and, during the garlic festival in August, garlic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like cloyingly sweet things,'' said Scott Campbell,
Avenue's co-owner, chef and resident ice cream maker. No kidding.
Campbell trained as a saucier, and that's how he thinks of his
savory-sweet confections. ``The interesting thing about ice cream
is it's a sauce,'' he said, ``a sauce that's frozen and then
served.'' His garlic ice cream has some sauces in it, too (Tabasco
and Worcestershire), and is served with steak tartare, though one
customer ordered an entire bowl of the stuff for dessert ``and
survived,'' Campbell said.
</P>
<P>
   More ice cream is consumed in July than in any other month, and
most of it is still vanilla, according to the International Ice
Cream Association in Washington. In much of the country, that means
towering sugar cones dribbling over small hands, pints of Ben &AMP;
Jerry's devoured in binges of guilt and heartbreak, and more
business for the place with the 31 flavors.
</P>
<P>
   But here in New York, we'll be comparing notes on the corn ice
cream at Mesa Grill versus Bolivar's purple corn. Which, discerning
palettes want to know, tastes less like a can of niblets?
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Harley Brachman, the pastry chef at Mesa Grill and Bolo,
is an exuberant defender of his Southwestern inventions. ``Corn in
half the world is used as a dessert,'' he said. Serrano chili and
jalapeno also have what Brachman calls a ``historical background.''
The Aztecs put hot peppers in chocolate, he said. He puts them in
ice cream _ a startling marriage with a potent aftertaste you
either love or want to rename Brachman's Revenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to combine gooey and creamy and crunchy and creamy,''
he said, employing the technical terminology of his trade. He's
doing cactus pear at Mesa Grill and, at its Spanish-inspired sister
restaurant, Bolo, he's got a fig and a honey quince ice made with a
quince paste called membrillo often taken at breakfast in Spain.
</P>
<P>
   Cross-branding is the buzzword in the retail ice cream world:
mixtures involving Breyer's ice cream plus Oreo cookies or Chips
Ahoy. Similarly catchy hybrids seem to be cropping up, at a more
rarefied level, in New York restaurants, except they call them
``infusions.''
</P>
<P>
   Vegetables are big in the new infusions, and so are herbs like
basil and spices like bay leaf. The beet sorbet at Aquavit is
swirled with vanilla yogurt and served with a chocolate ganache
cake _ ``a really old classic mix,'' said Kristen Murray, the
restaurant's former pastry chef. Ms. Murray was also responsible
for a balsamic apple concoction, as well as a curry zabaglione and
curry apple sorbet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just thought it would be fun to try a curry,'' Ms. Murray
said. ``It's very fragrant.'' That isn't all. It tastes like, well,
curry. As if that weren't enough on its own, it shares the plate
with a poached peach tart in almond cream, pistachio pesto, lemon
coconut sorbet and grenadine tapioca. ``It's a very intense dish,''
she said. ``You kind of stand back and go, `My Lord!'''
</P>
<P>
   Shock value does play a part in the mania for bizarrely flavored
ice creams. These weird frozen experiments are another way for
pastry chefs, many of whom now crave recognition as much as their
bosses, to get noticed. At the Local, you might be offered a lime
and rosemary creation, modestly presented on an artist's palette.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel offers a mint risotto, a raspberry hibiscus and a
verbena, but they are as far as Thomas Haas, the pastry chef, is
willing to go. ``I'm not superconservative, but I strongly believe
in classics,'' Haas said. ``You can twist them a little, but don't
overtwist them.'' He distances himself from the relentless quest
for novelty at other restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people want to make themselves a little more interesting
through this,'' he said. ``They want to make a name for themselves.
But it's like with the fusion cooking, it often turns into
confusion cooking.''
</P>
<P>
   But something about ice cream makes even otherwise sane pastry
chefs go a little nutty. Part of it is what the customers will
tolerate. As Brachman observed, ``People won't go that far out on a
weird cake, but if it's ice cream they'll try anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Debra Racicot said when she started making oatmeal ice cream at
Aquavit, ``A lot of people were a little bit weirded out by it at
first, but it flew.'' When Ms. Racicot moved to Picholine as pastry
chef last month, she took her oatmeal recipe with her.
</P>
<P>
   The other reason chefs go wild on ice cream is that they can.
Ms. Murray, who replaced Ms. Racicot at Aquavit, pointed out that
``because the base is so simple, you can do so many infusions that
are visually appealing and flavorful.''
</P>
<P>
   Even easier _ and possibly cheaper _ they can be ordered up as
custom flavors from a specialty maker like Ciao Bella. F.W. Pearce,
one of Ciao Bella's co-owners, said his company used to get one
special request a week from New York chefs. Now, he said, there are
as many as 10 a week, often multiple requests from single
restaurants. Bond Street wants its wasabi root, Cafe Bari its
honey-blossom water with dates. Beer-based demands have been
pouring in from Heartland, Belgo and Markt.
</P>
<P>
   Beer is big: Even places that aren't Belgian or brew pubs are
flavoring ice cream with a boozy kick. Monkey Bar has a Sierra
Nevada Pale Ale ice cream, Bayard a cherry lambic sorbet.
</P>
<P>
   Ciao Bella charges restaurants $3 to $5 more for a five-gallon
tub of custom ice cream or sorbet. A tub of one of the company's
100 existing flavors goes for $24 to $27, sorbets $24 to $34.
``We're able to get a premium because the restaurants have so much
room in their pricing,'' Pearce said. Room is a polite way of
saying they can charge $5 to $10 for a scoop when it's only costing
them 50 cents to $1, with minimal labor.
</P>
<P>
   A sweet racket, the ice cream trade. Its history is a little
vague. No inventor or specific date of origin is known, though
Alexander the Great is said to have enjoyed snow and ice flavored
with honey and nectar and Catherine de' Medici introduced a kind of
proto-gelato to the French court when she married Henry II. Long
before Howard Johnson's 28 flavors, Baskin-Robbins' 31 and Ben &AMP;
Jerry's Chubby Hubby, the 19th-century New York restaurant
Delmonico's served its society clientele novelty ice creams:
asparagus and pumpernickel rye.
</P>
<P>
   H.L. Mencken once denounced ice cream for ``leading the younger
generation from the straight and narrow path of spinach.'' But
Mencken could not have anticipated Avenue's garden mint flavor,
which gets its green color from an ingredient not mentioned on the
menu.
</P>
<P>
   Spinach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some things,'' said Avenue's Campbell, ``are better not
known.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   PINK-GRAPEFRUIT MUSTARD SEED SORBET
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Tabla
</P>
<P>
   Time: 15 minutes, plus freezing
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons red mustard seeds (see note)
</P>
<P>
   1 quart freshly squeezed pink grapefruit juice
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons light corn syrup.
</P>
<P>
   1. In a small pan over low heat, gently toast mustard seeds
until aromatic. Allow to cool.
</P>
<P>
   2. In a medium bowl, combine juice, sugar and corn syrup. Mix
until dissolved. Stir in the mustard seeds.
</P>
<P>
   3. Transfer to an ice cream machine and freeze according to
manufacturer's instructions.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: About 1 quart.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Red mustard seeds are sold at Foods of India, 121
Lexington Ave. (28th Street), (212) 683-4419. Brown, black or
yellow seeds may be used.
</P>
<P>
   OATMEAL ICE CREAM
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Picholine
</P>
<P>
   Time: 45 minutes, plus cooling and freezing
</P>
<P>
   2 cups heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   2 cups milk
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 cup light corn syrup
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup steel-cut whole grain oatmeal
</P>
<P>
   10 egg yolks.
</P>
<P>
   1. Place heavy cream, milk, 1/2 cup sugar and the corn syrup in
a medium-size pot. Bring to a boil, stir in oatmeal and turn off
heat. Allow to steep for 10 minutes. (For stronger oatmeal flavor,
steep longer.) Strain into a pot. Discard solids.
</P>
<P>
   2. Place egg yolks in a large bowl, and whisk in the remaining
1/2 cup sugar. Reheat cream mixture. When it comes to a boil,
slowly add it to the egg yolks, whisking constantly.
</P>
<P>
   3. Pour mixture into a new pot, and heat slowly, stirring
constantly, until it thickens to the point where it will coat the
back of a spoon. Pour immediately into a stainless steel bowl set
over ice. Let cool thoroughly, continuing to stir.
</P>
<P>
   4. Transfer to an ice cream machine, and prepare according to
manufacturer's instructions.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: about 1 quart.
</P>
<P>
   BALSAMIC APPLE SORBET
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Aquavit
</P>
<P>
   Time: 15 minutes, plus overnight to drain yogurt, and freezing
</P>
<P>
   1 quart plain yogurt
</P>
<P>
   1 cup fresh apple juice
</P>
<P>
   1 cup balsamic vinegar
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   Juice of one lime
</P>
<P>
   Pinch sea salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup buttermilk.
</P>
<P>
   1. Line a fine strainer with cheesecloth. Pour yogurt into
strainer, set over a bowl and drain overnight or at least 8 hours.
</P>
<P>
   2. In a medium-size pot, bring apple juice to a boil. Add
balsamic vinegar, and boil until it is reduced by half. Reduce
heat, and add sugar, lime juice and a pinch of salt. Simmer for 2
minutes, remove from heat and let cool.
</P>
<P>
   3. In a large bowl, combine drained yogurt and buttermilk. Whisk
until blended.
</P>
<P>
   4. Pour cooled balsamic liquid into yogurt mixture, and whisk
until thoroughly blended.
</P>
<P>
   5. Transfer to ice cream machine, and freeze according to
manufacturer's instructions.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: about 1 quart.
</P>
<P>
   MANGO SORBET WITH PINK PEPPERCORNS
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Ciao Bella
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes plus freezing
</P>
<P>
   7 or 8 very ripe mangoes
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons whole pink peppercorns.
</P>
<P>
   1. Peel and slice mangoes. Puree until smooth in a food
processor.
</P>
<P>
   2. Combine mango puree, 2 cups water, sugar, lemon juice and
peppercorns. Place in an ice cream machine, and freeze according to
manufacturer's instructions.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: about 1 1/2 quarts.
</P>
<P>
   BASIL SORBET
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Cena
</P>
<P>
   Time: 45 minutes, plus cooling and freezing
</P>
<P>
   2 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 Granny Smith apples, peeled, cored and diced
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 cups diced fresh pineapple
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound fresh basil leaves (1 cup packed tight)
</P>
<P>
   1 cup freshly squeezed lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup pineapple juice.
</P>
<P>
   1. In a medium-size pot, bring 3 cups water and the sugar to a
boil. Add apples and pineapple; simmer for 2 minutes. Add 2/3 cup
basil leaves, cover pot and turn off heat. Let sit for 15 minutes.
Add remaining basil leaves. Blend thoroughly in a blender, and
strain through a fine-mesh strainer into a medium-size stainless
steel bowl. Let cool.
</P>
<P>
   2. In a small bowl, combine lemon and pineapple juices. Add
juice mixture to the cooled basil and fruit mixture. Mix well.
</P>
<P>
   3. Transfer to an ice cream maker, and freeze according to
manufacturer's instructions.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: about 1 quart.
</P>
<P>
   MINTED RISOTTO ICE CREAM
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Daniel
</P>
<P>
   Time: 90 minutes, plus cooling and freezing
</P>
<P>
   For the ice cream base:
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4cups whole milk
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   1 vanilla bean, split lengthwise, seeds scraped loose
</P>
<P>
   20 large fresh mint leaves
</P>
<P>
   6 large egg yolks
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   For the risotto:
</P>
<P>
   2 cups whole milk
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   Finely grated zest of 1 Meyer (or 1/2 regular) lemon
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup arborio rice
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of salt.
</P>
<P>
   1. Make the ice cream base: In a medium pot, combine the milk,
cream and vanilla bean pod and seeds. Bring to a boil. Remove from
heat, stir in the mint leaves and cover. Let rest 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   2. Meanwhile, in a medium bowl, whisk together the egg yolks and
sugar until pale. Set a stainless steel bowl into a larger bowl
filled halfway with ice water. Keep close at hand.
</P>
<P>
   3. Strain the milk mixture into a clean saucepan and bring back
to a boil. Gradually pour half the hot liquid over the yolks,
whisking to combine. Return entire mixture to pan, and cook over
medium heat, stirring constantly with a wooden spoon. When mixture
thickens slightly (it should lightly coat the back of the spoon)
and the bubbles on top are the same color as the liquid underneath,
strain into the chilled bowl and cool to room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   4. While ice cream base is cooling, prepare the risotto. Pour
the milk into a small saucepan, add the sugar and lemon zest and
bring to a boil. Remove from heat, cover and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   5. In a medium pot, combine rice with 1 cup cold water in a
medium pot. Add salt, and bring to a boil. Lower heat to a simmer,
and cook, stirring occasionally, until nearly all the water
evaporates. Begin to add the warm lemony milk, 1/4 cup at a time,
stirring constantly over medium heat. Wait until most of the liquid
is absorbed before adding another 1/4 cup milk. Keep cooking and
stirring until all the liquid has been added and the rice is tender
but a bit soupy. Combine with the ice cream base, and cool
completely. Cover with plastic wrap, and refrigerate until
completely chilled.
</P>
<P>
   6. Freeze in an ice cream machine according to the
manufacturer's instructions. Cover in plastic wrap, and place in
the freezer for 1 to 2 hours before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 1 quart.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to creating ice creams and sorbets, chefs'
imaginations know no bounds. But for starters, here are 47 flavors
being served in the New York area this summer.
</P>
