A3595 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-EGYPT-305&AMP;ADD-     06-29 0498
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-EGYPT-305&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUBARAK SHARES OPTIMISTIC U.S. VIEW OF INCOMING ISRAELI
GOVERNMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak on Tuesday hailed
the imminent changeover of government in Israel as a ``new dawn''
in the Middle East, a remark that reflects the view of the Clinton
administration as it prepares to step up its campaign for a
comprehensive peace between Israel and all of its Arab neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   In accepting an honorary degree here ahead of a White House
meeting this week with President Clinton, the Egyptian leader said
the victory by the Israeli Labor Party and Prime Minister-elect
Ehud Barak in the May election ``holds the promise of better days
for the people of Israel and Palestine.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The road ahead is long and the obstacles are many,'' Mubarak
said in accepting the degree at George Washington University. ``But
we have seen the birth of a new dawn.''
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials described the meeting Thursday between
Clinton and Mubarak as the start of a intensive effort by the
United States to take advantage of a burst of good feeling in the
Arab world resulting from Barak's victory over Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu, widely seen by Arab leaders as an implacable
enemy of the peace effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president wants to consult with President Mubarak on how
we can together help to push the peace process forward on all
fronts, with the objective of achieving a comprehensive peace,''
said Martin Indyk, assistant secretary of state for Near Eastern
affairs.
</P>
<P>
   He said at a State Department news conference that the United
States hoped that there would be a warming of relations between
Israel and Egypt, which were severely strained during Netanyahu's
tenure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do think it's important, as the peace process moves
forward, which we expect it will in the near future, that Egypt
take steps to broaden and deepen its relationship with Israel,''
Indyk said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Administration officials say they are eager to hear from
Mubarak's views on the intentions of Syrian President Hafez Assad,
who has offered tantalizing hints in recent days that he is ready
to renew peace negotiations with Israel as a result of Barak's
victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've received messages,'' Indyk said. ``We've had our own
dialogue with President Assad over the past six months which lead
us to believe that he is keen to engage with the new government in
the hopes of achieving a comprehensive peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Indyk said the United States was pleased by a recent interview
widely reprinted in Arab newspapers in which Assad praised Barak as
a strong and honest leader who seems interested in peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Assad has not been one to praise the Israeli
leadership as honest and sincere and committed to peace,'' he said.
``I think that is an indication of his desire to engage with Prime
Minister-elect Barak.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
