<SLUG> BC-AMUSEMENT-PARKS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAYING FOR AMUSEMENT PARK MAY BE NO LAUGHING MATTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BOBBY McGILL  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   School's out, the summer heat is creeping in, and the kids are
bored. If you don't find some way to entertain them, they're gonna
drive you nuts.
</P>
<P>
   How about a day at the amusement park? How does $141.32 sound?
</P>
<P>
   That's the average national cost of taking the tykes to the
amusement park for the day, according to a report released Monday
by Amusement Business magazine, a Nashville, Tenn.-based amusement
industry weekly.
</P>
<P>
   If it's any consolation, the study did find the national average
is $1.58 lower than it was last year.
</P>
<P>
   Compiled yearly, the study tracks the prices of 25 theme parks
across America by assembling what is known as a family price index.
</P>
<P>
   The index calculates the average national cost of the following
amusement park purchases: admission for two adults and two
children, parking, two hot dogs, two hamburgers, four orders of
French fries, four small soft drinks and two child-sized souvenir
T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   Most parks reported an increase in admission prices, but they
were offset by decreases in children's prices and souvenir
T-shirts, according to the survey.
</P>
<P>
   This was the first decline in average overall daily cost in the
five years that the report has been done.
</P>
<P>
   The three most expensive parks, according to survey are:
</P>
<P>
   _ Universal Studios Orlando, at $225.50 per day
</P>
<P>
   _ Busch Gardens Tampa Bay at $206.50
</P>
<P>
   _ Universal Studios in Universal City, Calif., $199.50.
</P>
<P>
   The least expensive was Nellie Bly park in Brooklyn, costing $65
for a family of four.
</P>
<P>
   According to Jeff Jouett, spokesman for Six Flags' Marine World
Africa USA in Vallejo, Calif., parents would do well to stuff the
kids full of food before they go inside any theme park's gates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real variable is going to be how many times you eat and
how much you eat,'' Jouett said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, according to the report, the average price of a hot dog
and a hamburger increased 14 cents to $2.46 and $2.99,
respectively. An order of fries will cost you 13 cents more this
year and a soft drink an added 8 cents.
</P>
<P>
   If you're looking for any new amusement parks to open up in your
area, don't get your hopes up, said Neil Begley, senior analyst
with Moody's Investor Services in New York. He said consolidation
in the regional theme park industry _ including Six Flags' merger
with Marine World Africa USA in October 1998 _ should keep the
industry steady for a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say that it's stable now with the consolidation that has
gone on,'' Begley said. ``I think that it is less likely that you
are going to have much groundbreaking.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-99 1810EDT &QL; 
