u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-NYT &LR;      06-29 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAIN CANCELS ALL WIMBLEDON COMPETITION 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By ROBIN FINN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ After a glitch-free opening week that
whittled the men's and women's singles fields down to 16 contenders
each, Wimbledon wore rain like a second skin Tuesday. Not a single
ball was struck in competition, the first total shutdown at the All
England Club since 1997, when the first Thursday and Friday were
submerged.
</P>
<P>
   Steady drizzle kept the courts beneath tarpaulins for all but
the few mid-afternoon moments that featured the protagonists from
Monday's cliffhangers. Most notable of these was the the tense
Center Court contest between Britain's favorite son, Tim Henman,
and the U.S. Davis Cup squad's favorite pit bull, Jim Courier, who
marched through the mist to trade warm-up shots only to be driven
back inside for good. Their score stood just the way it had when
the harbinger of Tuesday's inclement weather terminated play on
Monday evening: Henman led 4-6, 7-5, 7-5, 4-3 with Courier to serve
in the fourth set.
</P>
<P>
   And over on Court One, an impatient seven-time champion Steffi
Graf, 6-2, 4-2 ahead of 16-year-old qualifier Kim Clijsters, the
youngest player in the tournament, remained two games from her
anticipated quarterfinal berth.
</P>
<P>
   While the 6th-seeded Henman and Courier had the resolution of
their quarterfinal aspirations postponed for another sleepless
night, Andre Agassi, safely through to that round, celebrated his
rainy off-day in a low key way.
</P>
<P>
   No fan of putting in overtime on bumpy, slippery, unreliable
grass courts, the 4th-seeded Agassi, who did much of his practicing
for his 1992 Grand Slam title here indoors on hardcourts,
designated a half hour Tuesday to an indoor practice session. Then,
Agassi and his coach, Brad Gilbert, settled down in front of the
television in the player's rental manse and watched Pancho
Gonzalez, Agassi's former brother-in-law, and Charlie Pasarell mix
it up in a Wimbledon classic, the longest men's match in the
tournament's history.
</P>
<P>
   The 22-24, 1-6, 16-14, 6-3, 11-9 epic comeback by Gonzalez took
five hours 12 minutes and, said Gilbert, provided a lengthy
distraction Tuesday when there was little else for Agassi to occupy
himself with _ except thoughts of his quarterfinal here against
Brazil's Gustavo Kuerten. Both players share a French Open
pedigree, with Kuerten the 1997 champion and Agassi the reigning
titleholder.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just right where he wants to be, in the thick of things
in the second week,'' said Gilbert, whose charge became the first
man since Rod Laver to acquire all four slam titles with his
victory at Roland Garros. Fittingly, the protean 29-year-old
Agassi, whose appearance over the years has vacillated as wildly as
his results, became the first man to win the slams on three
different surfaces. When Laver, Don Budge, Fred Perry, and Roy
Emerson compiled their Grand Slams, the majors were confined to
grass and clay.
</P>
<P>
   At Paris, Agassi was committed to rebounding from the failure of
his marriage to Brooke Shields, which ended in April, by winning
the only slam title he'd failed to master. Here at Wimbledon, he's
determined to become the first player since Bjorn Borg to make the
direct, and difficult, segue from a French Open championship on
clay to a Wimbledon crown on grass four weeks later.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would say I feel as good as my game,'' said Agassi, still
basking in his French triumph and his completed Grand Slam
collection. ``It has sunk in as deep as I'm capable of
comprehending. I can only imagine that I won't ever quite have an
appreciation for what it means to live my life knowing what's it's
like to win all of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to win more, finish the year at No.1,'' said Agassi,
who finished 1997 ranked 122nd and hadn't won a Grand Slam title
since commandeering the Australian Open on his first visit in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi's Wimbledon philosophy is similar to that of the
five-time champion Pete Sampras, who believes the second serve and
the return are the pivotal shots on this surface, where cavalcades
of aces from sharpshooters like Greg Rusedski and Goran Ivanisevic
are as predictable as the rain delays.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the most important shot in grass court tennis is the
second serve,'' said Agassi, who puts ``hold games,'' not aces, at
a premium. ``I'm not surprised that I can have enough in the rest
of the departments of my game to overcome a big server.''
</P>
<P>
   Agassi's next opponent, Kuerten, is more durable than dangerous,
and Agassi predicted their first-ever grass clash will be an
``interesting'' encounter, especially since Kuerten leads their
rivalry, 2-1. Kuerten all but predicted an Agassi victory.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have a chance, but he's playing wonderful, and I'm sure he's
the favorite,'' said Kuerten, whose previous Wimbledon campaigns
ended in two first round round losses. ``Nobody expects me to go to
the quarterfinal; it's going to be a lot of fun. Hopefully he don't
hit too hard and he let me play and enjoy it a little, too.''
</P>
<P>
   But Agassi, on a mission to remain on a Grand Slam roll, isn't
planning to be very charitable. ``I'm shooting for an important
goal,'' said Agassi.
</P>
<P>
   He allowed as to how his support will swing in Sampras'
direction only if he finds himself dismissed before the final
round. ``I'd love to see him accomplish six Wimbledons if I happen
to lose here,'' said Agassi about his contemporary's much-heralded
bid to tie Emerson's all-time slam record of 12 by capturing a
third straight title here.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
