</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLANECRASH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Two die in morning airplane crash
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Firefighter Matt Driver got within a yard of the
burning plane. Through the smoke he could see small movements, and
under the roar of traffic from the expressway and the crackle of
flames he could hear a voice murmuring ``Help me, help me.''
</P>
<P>
   Then the fire reached another fuel cell and roared up in his
face. He could no longer see the plane, he could hear no more cries
and he had to retreat.
</P>
<P>
   Driver and Mike Roberts, both Atlanta firefighters who were on
their way to work when they saw a twin-engine plane go down beside
I-20 Tuesday morning, along with an unidentified citizen with a
fire extinguisher, made an heroic effort to rescue the two men
aboard but were driven back by the fire.
</P>
<P>
   One of the victims was identified as Robert Dodson, 29, of
Memphis, Tenn. The Fulton County Medical Examiner's office said
Dodson died from blunt trauma. Pathologists were awaiting dental
records before positively identifying the second victim.
</P>
<P>
   All eastbound lanes of I-20 heading toward Atlanta were shut
down for about an hour Tuesday morning, and it was well past rush
hour before all lanes were reopened. Traffic was backed up for
miles to the west.
</P>
<P>
   Experts from the National Transportation Safety Board were
investigating the crash.
</P>
<P>
   The Beechcraft Baron 58, owned by Paragon Air Express in
Nashville, Tenn., was making its daily Nashville-Atlanta-Mobile,
Ala. run to deliver checks to and from banks in those cities when
it took off from Fulton County Airport shortly after 6 a.m. It
immediately ran into mechanical difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said the pilot of the six-passenger plane radioed
the tower that he was turning back. They said he did not indicate
what kind of problem the plane was experiencing.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said the plane was ``sputtering.''
</P>
<P>
   Alan Joyce, a Delta Air Lines employee, was driving down I-20 en
route to work when the plane crossed over the interstate in front
of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had taken off and was going at a fair rate of speed, and he
seemed to me to be having a hard time getting it up,'' Joyce said.
``It looked like he was trying to do a sharp turn to get back to
the airport.''
</P>
<P>
   Joyce lost sight of the plane as it crossed over trees along the
south side of the interstate. ``When it crossed over the trees, it
seemed to be sideslipping or banking real hard. I was waiting to
see him come up above the trees on the other side and the next
thing was a big cloud of black smoke.''
</P>
<P>
   Driver and Roberts, who arrived on the scene at virtually the
same time but in separate cars, said the plane banked sharply to
the right, avoiding the industrial area south of the freeway, and
turned back northward toward the airport. But instead of righting
itself, the plane continued to roll to the right until it was
upside down, and then plunged straight into a narrow strip of
hardwood trees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It pretty much went straight down,'' Fulton County Fire Capt.
Terry Coursey said.
</P>
<P>
   He said firefighters got the first call at 6:29, reached the
scene seven minutes later but took almost half an hour to beat down
the flames because hoses had to be carried down the long, steep
bank into the woods and then have foam canisters attached to them
to fight the aircraft fuel fire.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts said that as he and Driver dashed down the embankment,
``We yelled out to see if there were any survivors. We heard
somebody moaning, but then there was a big explosion. There was
nothing we could do. There was too much fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Driver said six or seven other people rushed down the slope, one
of them carrying a fire extinguisher. ``The guy with the fire
extinguisher did a good job,'' he said, ``but then it flashed up on
us and we had to bail out.''
</P>
<P>
   The man with the fire extinguisher apparently drove away without
identifying himself.
</P>
<P>
   Fulton firefighters brought a small bulldozer to the crash scene
to plow a path about 50 yards through the trees to the remains of
the plane, which were burned to an unidentifiable mass. Papers
thrown from the plane on impact littered the slope around it.
</P>
<P>
   The bodies of the two victims were brought out shortly before 11
a.m., and investigators from the Federal Aviation Administration
and the NTSB took over the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Powell, the lead investigator for the NTSB, said they would
have to rely heavily on information from witnesses, but ``you'd be
surprised'' what can be learned from wreckage burned even as badly
as the Beechcraft.
</P>
<P>
   He said he would have a preliminary report ready on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Warner writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga. Mike Morris, Bill Montgomery and Gary Hendricks
contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
