<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHPARK-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUT OF FOUL MOUTHS OF BABES COMES CLEVER PARODY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
OUR RATING: 3 stars 
By FRED SHUSTER 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _The ``South Park'' movie blasts other adult-themed
cartoon features out of the water, and it isn't just because it
shows Saddam Hussein and Satan having trouble in their
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, it's tasteless, childish and utterly obscene. And yes,
those familiar animated tykes Cartman, Stan, Kenny and the rest get
to talk far dirtier than they do on the popular Comedy Central
series that spawned them two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But ``South Park: Bigger, Longer &AMP; Uncut'' is also a clever and
highly topical parody of post-Columbine kid-culture paranoia that
has theater owners promising to police customers while electronics
companies scramble to place program-blocking chips in TV sets.
</P>
<P>
   It's tempting to say ``South Park'' creators Trey Parker and
Matt Stone got lucky with this very funny and fast-paced script,
which jumps from a military attack on the Baldwin brothers to the
murder of Bill Gates to the devil and Hussein as gay lovers
plotting to take over the world.
</P>
<P>
   The crudely animated picture opens with a big production number
_ there are several hilarious musical interludes here _ in which
South Park's population celebrates its redneck mountain town.
However, life isn't all burgers and beer _ a foul-mouthed and
flatulent Canadian duo called Terrence and Philip are undermining
the kids, teaching them naughty words and dirty songs by way of a
hit movie that's just hit town.
</P>
<P>
   But South Park's third-graders aren't supposed to be seeing the
movie _ it's R-rated, just like ``Bigger, Longer &AMP; Uncut'' itself.
</P>
<P>
   How to get around the problem? Easy _ Cartman and the gang
bribes a homeless guy to buy them tickets.
</P>
<P>
   When the tykes come home spouting Terrence and Philip's
profanity, parents and teachers launch a crusade against Canada.
War is declared, and one of the kids is implanted with a chip
giving electrical shocks when he says bad words.
</P>
<P>
   Is ``Bigger, Longer &AMP; Uncut'' ripped from today's headlines?
Partly so, it seems.
</P>
<P>
   At the very least it's the ``Citizen Kane'' of
construction-paper cut-out animation. Every penny of the film's
$14.50 budget is up there on the screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bigger, Longer'' is raunchy, outrageous entertainment for
adults, thanks to those perfectly realized musical numbers and an
approach that holds nothing sacred and everyone and everything _
from Winona Ryder to the military _ up for good-natured lowbrow
ridicule.
</P>
<P>
   But like the Terrence and Philip movie, ``South Park: Bigger,
Longer &AMP; Uncut'' is definitely not for kids. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
