A3607 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JUNIOR-MISS30-COX     06-29 0437
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUNIOR-MISS30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    America's Junior Miss, every parents dream
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Lee
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Sarah Jane Everman of Kennesaw (Ga.), is not only the
new America's Junior Miss, she's every parent's dream.
</P>
<P>
   The win on Monday is just the latest honor for Everman, 18, who
graduated this summer from Pebblebrook High School with a major in
dance and minors in vocal and drama. From best actress in the 1998
state one-act play competition (as Ariel in ``The Tempest'') to
slots in the Governor's Honors program and the National Honor
Society, her resume bulges with overachievement. She's a member of
Mount Paran Church of God and has taped public service
announcements against drunken driving.
</P>
<P>
   Today, she's off to Myrtle Beach, S.C., for an appearance on
TNN's ``Crook and Chase Show.'' After the 3 p.m. show, she'll head
to New York for another round of media schmooze fests, then back to
Atlanta by Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm running on about three hours sleep but I'm pretty
excited,'' she said Tuesday from Mobile.
</P>
<P>
   Everman was chosen from eight finalists. Her parents, John
Everman of Houston and Linda Everman of Kennesaw, watched from the
audience with her sister and two dozen other supporters, including
several Pebblebrook faculty members. TNN will air the competition
at 9 p.m. Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Between her wins in the local, state and national competitions,
Everman has picked up $57,000 in scholarship money for the
University of Cincinnati, where she will study musical theater
starting this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Earl Reece, director of Pebblebrook's performing arts school,
describes Everman as a talented young woman with a strong faith
who's been a role model for younger students. Between classes and
play rehearsals, she routinely put in 12-hour days in high school.
In the past four years, she appeared in every play except one that
the school produced.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have much of a social life,'' Everman said. ``It's
pretty much I just see my friends at school every day, then
rehearsals.''
</P>
<P>
   As for dating, she said laughing, ``that's for later.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, she wants to concentrate on starting college and a year
of appearances for Junior Miss. Everman, who enrolled at
Pebblebrook because of her interest in dance, soon expanded her
scope to singing and drama. She hopes for a career in live theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once I did a show I realized that's where I was comfortable,''
she said. ``I think I've been blessed.''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Lee writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
