<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3610 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEDDING-DRESS-NYTR &LR;      06-29 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEDDING-DRESS-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LONG, HARD SEARCH FOR THE RIGHT WEDDING DRESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JODY KLEINBERG   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA ROSA, Calif. _ Six months ago, I did something really
foolish.
</P>
<P>
   I told my mom I would love to buy my wedding dress with her.
</P>
<P>
   I thought it would be fun, an old-fashioned mother-daughter
ritual that would help us bond.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that we aren't close. We are. But we haven't always
been.
</P>
<P>
   I figured shopping for the dress would help solidify our ``new
relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   I also thought it would clarify what I did and did not want the
wedding to be.
</P>
<P>
   Simple, not flashy. Intimate, not grandiose. Modern, not
traditional.
</P>
<P>
   Theoretically, my plan was brilliant.
</P>
<P>
   Realistically, it was a nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   We were in Los Angeles, where I grew up. My mom had planned the
day and had booked three appointments at different boutiques.
(Appointments, she explained to me, are crucial because bridal
salons only service one client at a time.)
</P>
<P>
   Our 10 a.m. stop was the largest and most expensive on the list.
Everything in the store sparkled. Bouquets of white flowers bloomed
on the counters and reflected in mirrors that were behind, next to,
and in front of me. And of course, there were rows and rows of long
white dresses.
</P>
<P>
   The moment we walked in, two middle-aged women bustled up and
asked my name. When they realized I was their appointment, they
lurched into action.
</P>
<P>
   First, they circled me. Then they started making strange
clicking noises with their tongues. Finally, they began to coo and
to repeat, as if it was a mantra, that I would be a
``bee-oo-tee-ful'' bride.
</P>
<P>
   It was almost comical. Almost, because they were serious. And,
because I had no escape.
</P>
<P>
   My mother's smile told me I had to stay.
</P>
<P>
   So, I took a deep breath and let the women go to work.
</P>
<P>
   They began by walking me through the store, holding out dresses
and asking my opinion. Not that it mattered. I hated almost
everything, but I still ended up with a bedroom-sized dressing room
full of gowns.
</P>
<P>
   They led me into it gleefully. A floor-to-ceiling mirror in the
dressing room permitted me to see myself from all angles. Perfect.
</P>
<P>
   I stood politely waiting for them to leave so I could begin.
But, they just stood there smiling.
</P>
<P>
   Then it hit me. They were staying.
</P>
<P>
   I looked at my mother in horror.
</P>
<P>
   The women poo-pooed my muttering about shyness and insisted that
only they knew how to put the gowns on properly. Their presence was
essential, they said. Pivotal to my success as a bride.
</P>
<P>
   I looked at my mom and she shrugged, but didn't offer me an out.
Slowly, I undressed and stood still while they zipped, buttoned,
tucked and clipped.
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes, I was transformed.
</P>
<P>
   No more jeans and unmatched socks.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, I was a perfect vision in white.
</P>
<P>
   A snowflake.
</P>
<P>
   A cream puff with a tiny middle.
</P>
<P>
   My mother's eyes filled with tears.
</P>
<P>
   The women bubbled over. At one point, they got so effusive I had
to order them to pipe down or get out.
</P>
<P>
   They eyed each other quizzically. The princess, they seemed to
say, was part ogre.
</P>
<P>
   I couldn't help myself. I felt like an idiot. And I had a
million angles to prove it.
</P>
<P>
   But my mother was beaming.
</P>
<P>
   And my father, she said, would be thrilled if he saw me in such
a dress.
</P>
<P>
   I stopped for a moment and considered this.
</P>
<P>
   Was it really so bad?
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't what I wanted. In fact, it was the opposite. But
couldn't I live with it if it made them so happy?
</P>
<P>
   I looked back at my mom. For a moment, I could see nothing else.
It was just me and her and all those years and disappointments in
between.
</P>
<P>
   I hadn't been the perfect daughter. At times, I hadn't even been
a good one. I was rebellious and had spent more time away from home
than in it.
</P>
<P>
   But maybe, if I could do this one thing right, none of that
would matter. For once, I would be everything they wanted.
</P>
<P>
   I thought about this as we walked out of the shop. I considered
it as I stood in another store, with yet another set of women
clucking and clicking around me.
</P>
<P>
   I carried it with me on the plane home, on my way to work each
day and home each night. It started to bother me that I was
spending so much time worrying about something as silly as a dress.
</P>
<P>
   But, somehow it had become bigger than just silk or lace. It was
my childhood, my adult life and the conflict between the little
girl I had been and the woman I had become.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, it was my mom who helped me solve the problem. She
did it by telling me a story about her wedding.
</P>
<P>
   She was younger than me _ just out of college. She and my father
had been high school sweethearts and both families were eager for
them to marry.
</P>
<P>
   Like me, my mother was the only girl in her family. That meant
her wedding was more than just a personal celebration. It was a
family event.
</P>
<P>
   Her mother, my grandmother, was a perfectionist who planned
everything meticulously. She envisioned begonias in the aisle,
bite-sized chocolates on the tables and strolling violins during
dinner. And, she wanted my mother to wear a tailored silk dress
with a schoolgirl bow in the front, a long train on the back and a
pill box hat.
</P>
<P>
   My mother wore the dress. But she never liked it. Especially not
the hat.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, her dislike was so deep that 30 years later, she
refused to let me CONSIDER wearing her dress.
</P>
<P>
   No, she said. She didn't want to see the dress again. And, she
wanted me to love what I wore.
</P>
<P>
   That's when we both realized that I couldn't wear the dress from
the shop. It wasn't me.
</P>
<P>
   It was a wonderful moment. Worth all the strain of the past
months. Well, almost.
</P>
<P>
   For a brief second, we traded places. I saw her as a young
bride; she understood me as an independent woman.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, our epiphany did nothing to solve my dress
problem.
</P>
<P>
   It just sent me back to the stores.
</P>
<P>
   Shopping took me months, but eventually I found a dress I love,
a fitted gown of ivory silk and organza.
</P>
<P>
   The dress won't be ready until a few weeks before the wedding.
That means I won't have to think about it _ or worry about my
family's reaction _ for a while.
</P>
<P>
   Still, finding it has allowed me to relax.
</P>
<P>
   And, it's given me and my mom time to focus on what's really
important.
</P>
<P>
   Like whether I should wear a veil.
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
