</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PREVENTIVE-CARE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S MEDICARE OVERALL OFFERS FREE PREVENTIVE PROCEDURES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 (EDs: CHANGES headline, substituting the word free for no cost(  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton's proposed overhaul of Medicare
Tuesday includes a provision long sought by health care advocates _
a plan for Uncle Sam to pay the entire cost of diagnostic tests
designed to prevent serious illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   The tests, such as mammograms, colorectal cancer screening and
bone-density measurements, were part of the administration's 1993
massive health care plan overseen by First Lady Hillary Rodham
Clinton. They would be offered to the 39 million elderly and
disabled Americans currently covered by the Medicare program.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, addressing administration officials and members of
Congress in the East Room of the White House, said his plan would
``create a much better match between the benefits of modern science
and the benefits offered by Medicare.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the diagnostic procedures that can detect diseases early
did not even exist in 1965 when Medicare was created, Clinton
noted. Preventive screening ``if done in time, can save lives,
improve the quality of life and cut health-care costs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton added: ``It makes no sense for Medicare to put up
roadblocks to these screenings and then turn around and pick up the
hospital bills that screenings might have avoided. No senior should
ever have to hesitate, as many do today, to get the preventive care
they need.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's proposal would eliminate the 20 percent co-payments
Medicare recipients now pay for many of the screening procedures
and waive the $100 deductible for those diagnostic tests.
</P>
<P>
   The expanded benefits build on changes pressed by the White
House and adopted by the Republican Congress in 1997. These changes
provided partial Medicare reimbursement for many of the same
preventive care procedures rather than reimbursement only for
doctor-ordered diagnostic tests.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Sperling, Clinton's chief economic adviser and an architect
of the new plan, said the president's expanded preventive care
benefits would cost an estimated $3 billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   The effort reflects ``the consensus in the health care community
and basically just common-sense _ that we should be doing
everything possible to encourage preventative care that saves our
government money over time and, more importantly, saves families
the heartbreak of more serious illnesses over time,'' Sperling
explained.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal also includes a nationwide education program to
promote health awareness among Americans over age 50.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's comprehensive health care plan failed in 1994
after encountering massive opposition from the health care
industry.
</P>
<P>
   The president's latest plan, including first-ever partial
coverage for drug prescriptions, would be paid for over a 10-year
period from an estimated $72 billion in savings from cost-cutting
changes within Medicare, $11 billion in new levies on beneficiaries
and $45.5 billion from the federal budget surplus, Sperling said.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond 10 years, costs would be borne by revenues from the
Medicare payroll tax and general revenue from the U.S. Treasury.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the Health Care Financing Administration said
Clinton's proposal would eliminate all cost-sharing by patients for
approved preventive health care procedures, leaving the entire cost
_ up to the ``Medicare approved amount'' _ to be paid by the
federal government.
</P>
<P>
   The preventive health care procedures that would qualify for
cost-free coverage include:
</P>
<P>
   _ Annual mammograms for women over age 40.
</P>
<P>
   _ Pap smears, pelvic exams and clinical breast exams for women
every three years, with annual coverage for women who have had an
abnormal Pap smear in the previous three years.
</P>
<P>
   _ Diabetes self-testing procedures, including blood glucose
monitors and testing strips for all diabetics, who would receive
free training in outpatient facilities on how to administer the
tests.
</P>
<P>
   _ Colorectal cancer screening for Medicare beneficiaries age 50
and older, including a fecal occult blood test every 12 months and
screening by scoping with a flexible tube once every 48 months. The
proposal also would cover colonoscopy procedures once every 24
months for Medicare beneficiaries at high risk for colorectal
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bone-density measurement.
</P>
<P>
   _ Prostate cancer screening, with annual digital exams and blood
tests for a protein that is present when the prostate is diseased.
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 and via E-mail
at stewart(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
