<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3615 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNN-COX     06-29 0477
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CNN to launch pricey ad campaign aimed at boomer marketBy
Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ CNN USA will launch a $25 million ad campaign on
Thursday, the largest in the news channel's history.
</P>
<P>
   In another first, the campaign will extend simultaneously across
television, newspapers and the Internet. The campaign's promotional
theme line is ``You are what you know.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is CNN's largest campaign by a long shot,'' says Steve
Korn, vice chairman and chief operating officer of the
Atlanta-based CNN News Group, a unit of Time Warner.
</P>
<P>
   To help kick off the campaign, CNN announced Tuesday a
replacement for longtime anchor Lou Dobbs, who left his popular
Moneyline Newshour show last month. Dobbs is being replaced by two
current CNN news people, Stuart Varney and Willow Bay.
</P>
<P>
   A long time in the planning, the ad campaign comes as CNN faces
increasing competition that has cluttered a cable TV news niche it
once had to itself.
</P>
<P>
   Today, CNN and its sister news channels compete against MSNBC,
Fox News and financial channel CNBC and ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   CNN remains by far the leading news channel on cable TV. It saw,
for example, a 25 percent jump in its average daily household
viewership during the past three months.
</P>
<P>
   And parent Time Warner wants to ensure CNN stays the leader _
especially among the channel's core audience of affluent baby
boomers.
</P>
<P>
   The ad campaign is really part two of a larger strategy underway
for the past 18 months. First came an effort to raise the quality,
in terms of both appearance and content, of CNN.
</P>
<P>
   CNN recruited former ABC News executive RicK Kaplan as the
president of CNN USA. Kaplan began new shows such as Newstand and
hired new anchors.
</P>
<P>
   Now CNN wants to promote these changes in the ad campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're focusing the campaign on those people who remain our
vital core audience,'' says Korn. That audience is people age 35-54
with incomes of $50,000 or more.
</P>
<P>
   To appeal to this group, the CNN campaign will feature
successful baby boomers from all walks of life. Among those
appearing in ads will be New York Yankee's pitcher Roger Clemens,
Amazon.com founder Jeff Bezos, and Richard Branson, founder of
Virgin Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   CNN will roll out its campaign in three stages. The first, which
begins Thursday, will feature financial program Moneyline Newshour.
</P>
<P>
   The second phase of the campaign will begin in mid-July and
feature Larry King Live. And phase three, which will begin in late
August, will feature the Newstand news magazine show.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign will run at least through the end of the year, says
Korn. At that time CNN will decide whether to continue it.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Haddad writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
