<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3623 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOP-COMMERCIALS-LADN     06-29 0333
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOP-COMMERCIALS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV SPECIAL DEVOTED TO ALL-TIME GREATEST COMMERCIALS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
By MARLA MATZER 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ I have a confession: I love TV Land. Give me a
25-year-old episode of ``All in the Family'' over the latest
installment of ``Friends'' any day. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; But I used to love it more. When the channel, an offshoot of
Nickelodeon's Nick at Nite, first began in 1996, it had no
advertisers. Instead, it showed old commercials. Dubbed
``retro-mercials,'' these were as popular as the channel's
programming.
</P>
<P>
   A big part of TV Land's charm came from the feeling of having
hijacked a time machine back several decades. While some of these
older shows had continued to run in syndication, they'd often been
cut to fit more commercials in _ new, loud, charmless commercials
that broke up the nostalgic vibe.
</P>
<P>
   All good things must end, and now TV Land's commercials are
mostly of the current variety. A cable channel, after all, has to
make money either by charging you or charging advertisers to reach
you. Unfortunately, TV Land missed an opportunity with its
first-ever original production, ``TV Land Presents the Greatest
Commercials of All Time,'' to re-create the time warp of its early
days.
</P>
<P>
   This half-hour special, based on TV Guide's current cover story
picking the 50 greatest commercials, is too short and choppy to do
its subject justice. I kept hoping they'd show a commercial all the
way through, but the only one they show in its entirety is the
``1984'' commercial for the Apple Macintosh.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the show is disjointed montages of old commercials
interspersed with commentary from ad executives and (snore)
journalists. A framing story pairing fast-talking Fed Ex spokesman
Frank Moschitta and ``Joe Isuzu'' David Leisure is clever ... the
first time around. Then it, too, starts to feel like an intrusion
on what we really want to see _ the commercials themselves. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-99 1832EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
