<TEXT>
<P>
   (pr) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Wednesday, June 30. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News Service
Night Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   SBC-AMERITECH (Washington) _ Federal regulators say they are
prepared to approve a merger between SBC Communications and
Ameritech Corp. This would create the nation's largest local
telephone company on terms that will both require the new company
to open its enormous market and move aggressively into 30 new
cities. By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-LAWSUITS (Washington) _ Infuriating many Democrats, Congress
and the White House agree on legislation that will put restraints
on lawsuits arising from Year 2000 computer problems. By David E.
Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE-CLINTON (Washington) _ Promising better Medicare
benefits to match scientific advances, President Clinton proposes
free preventive health services plus a $1,000-a-year prescription
drug benefit for older and disabled Americans _ at the cost of a
monthly $24 premium. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   With MEDICARE-PRIMER and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   COUNSEL-LAW (Washington) _ Corruption investigations against
high government officials will change significantly on Wednesday at
midnight with the expiration of the Ethics in Government Act, the
law that gave the country Whitewater prosecutor Kenneth Starr and
19 other independent counsels in the last two decades. By David
Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SERBS (Cacak, Yugoslavia) _ In the first major
anti-government demonstration since NATO stopped bombing
Yugoslavia, about 10,000 people pack into the central square of
this war-damaged manufacturing city to demand the resignation of
President Slobodan Milosevic. By Blaine Harden. 1,300 words.
</P>
<P>
   CONTRACEPTION-INSURE (Boston) _ Viagra has a political side
effect. Around the county, more than half a dozen state
legislatures have recently passed laws requiring insurers who cover
prescription drugs like Viagra to cover contraceptives as well. By
Carey Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   Reefer:
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-OCALAN (Istanbul, Turkey) _ A Turkish security court
sentences the Kurdish rebel leader, Abdullah Ocalan, to death for
his 15-year campaign against the Turkish army. Because of the
violence that followed Ocalan's arrest in February, the sentence
set off security concerns. But there were no reports of violent
reaction. By Stephen Kinzer. 1,500 words.
</P>
</TEXT>
