<HEADER>
A3629 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOODWARDS-CHARGED-BOS     06-29 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOODWARDS-CHARGED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AU PAIR'S PARENTS CHARGED IN FUNDS CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN AND ELLEN O'BRIEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The parents of former British au pair Louise Woodward,
who was convicted of killing a Newton, Mass., baby in 1997, were
formally charged by police in England Monday with bilking their
daughter's defense fund of at least $15,000.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Cheshire police in England said Tuesday that
Gary and Susan Woodward face counts of theft and false accounting.
The couple allegedly defrauded their daughter's defense fund of
about $15,000 for room and board that they had received for free
from Elaine Whitfield Sharp, the Marblehead, Mass., lawyer who was
formerly part of Louise Woodward's defense team. They allegedly
doctored an invoice as evidence of the payment, police charge.
</P>
<P>
   The Woodwards have denied the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   During their daughter's murder trial, money flowed to the family
from around the world from people who believed Woodward should not
be held responsible for the death of Matthew Eappen, the
8-month-old who lapsed into unconsciousness while in her care.
</P>
<P>
   Woodward was found guilty of second-degree murder by a jury, but
that conviction was reduced by Judge Hiller B. Zobel to
manslaughter. Zobel sentenced her to the time she had already
served in jail and she was released. She went home to Britain after
the Massachusetts Supreme Judical Court upheld Zobel's decision.
</P>
<P>
   Following Woodward's manslaughter conviction, the defense fund
grew, with donations meant to pay for an appeal that might clear
her name.
</P>
<P>
   Sean Sexton, the Liverpool lawyer who represents Susan Woodward,
did not return phone calls seeking comment Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But the Associated Press reported that he had said that Susan
Woodward ``vigorously denies the allegations which have been made
against her and her husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is heartily sick of the vicious lies and poisonous gossip
which have been directed against her and her family and looks
forward to the opportunity of setting the record straight when this
matter comes to court,'' Sexton said.
</P>
<P>
   Whitfield Sharp has repeatedly said that she did not charge the
Woodwards room and board.
</P>
<P>
   Reached at her Marblehead law office Tuesday, Whitfield Sharp
threatened to sue the Woodwards' attorneys for libel if they
continue to point the finger at her.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they think that attacking me is a good defense, they're in
trouble,'' Whitfield Sharp said. ``It's a sad day when all they
come up with is `Elaine Whitfield Sharp is crazy.'
</P>
<P>
   ``They are lawyers,'' she said. ``But they are certainly not
immune from being sued.''
</P>
<P>
   Jean Jones, the woman who founded the defense fund in the
Woodwards' hometown of Elton, England, but who fell out with the
Woodwards over the fraud allegations, said she learned of the
charges ``with great sadness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like everyone else. Very sad,'' Jones said in a
telephone interview. ``They've been charged. If it's proved, it's
proved. If it's not, it's not.''
</P>
<P>
   The investigation was carried out by both Cheshire police and
the FBI. The Woodwards were arrested for questioning by Cheshire
police on May 6. On Monday, they were formally charged and then
released on bail pending their appearance in Chester magistrate's
court July 26.
</P>
<P>
   The Woodwards have split up in the aftermath of their daughter's
trial. Reflecting on the seemingly endless saga Tuesday, Whitfield
Sharp said she hopes the public will separate the alleged criminal
acts of Louise Woodward's parents from the charges made against
their daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Whitfield Sharp said she remains among those who believe there
was enough reasonable doubt to acquit the teenager.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not saying she was innocent,'' Whitfield Sharp said. ``I
am saying the evidence did not support a conviction. Those are
completely separate things.''
</P>
<P>
   In Britain, meanwhile, the Rev. Ken W. Davey, the British
minister who was chairman of the defense fund, said he heard about
the charges but declined comment Tuesday ``because the case is
sub &UR;  &LR; judice,'' using the legal term that limits public discussion
of pending legal cases in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Davey ruefully noted that had similar discretion been followed
in Louise Woodward's case, reporters probably wouldn't be calling
him seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Woodward's supporters contend she was convicted, in part,
because of negative pre-trial publicity in the United States. Such
coverage is tightly controlled in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(This story was reported by Kevin Cullen in London and by Ellen
O'Brien in Boston.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-99 1834EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
