<HEADLINE>
TV NOTES: TWO FOR THE `MONEYLINE' 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also TV-FAMILY-GUY) 
(bl) 
 By LAWRIE MIFFLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Moving quickly to fill the gap left when Lou Dobbs resigned
three weeks ago, CNN on Tuesday named new co-anchors for
``Moneyline News Hour,'' the early-evening business news program
that Dobbs created and anchored for 19 years. One newcomer is an
old hand at financial news, Stuart Varney; the other is Willow Bay,
the co-anchor of two CNN prime-time programs, ``CNN and Fortune''
and ``CNN and Entertainment Weekly.''
</P>
<P>
   Varney, like Dobbs, joined CNN at its inception, and worked
there covering financial news for 18 years before taking the past
year off for what he called a sabbatical.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a spectacular opportunity,'' Varney said Tuesday by
telephone from Derby, England, where he was visiting his mother.
``Lou created the premier financial news program, and I would just
like to follow in those footsteps.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bay, who will continue on the two prime-time shows as well,
said doing ``Moneyline'' was another step in her professional
evolution. ``The work I've been doing at `CNN-Fortune' is covering
business,'' she said, ``and what I've been doing for
`CNN-Entertainment Weekly' is focusing on the entertainment
industry as a business, the business of moviemaking or the business
of Broadway.''
</P>
<P>
   CNN felt pressure to move fast because its main financial news
competitor, CNBC, immediately pumped resources into its ``Business
Center'' program, expanding it from 30 minutes to fill the same
hour from 6:30 to 7:30 p.m. as ``Moneyline''; shifting its
best-known anchors, Ron Insana and Sue Herera, there, and spending
lavishly on promotion.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the first week of those changes, brought a 13 percent
ratings gain for ``Business Center,'' to an average of 238,000
households, still trailing the 293,000 homes ``Moneyline'' reached
that week.
</P>
<P>
   Another CNN competitor could well make the 10 p.m. time slot
more competitive in the fall, if Tuesday's second-quarter Nielsen
numbers for cable networks are any indication. Since Paula Zahn
took over as anchor of Fox News Channel's 7 p.m. news in March,
that broadcast has more than doubled its ratings (to an average of
167,000 households).
</P>
<P>
   Last week Fox News Channel president Roger Ailes named Ms. Zahn
anchor of a new 10 p.m. news magazine.
</P>
<P>
   That hour had been an interview show, with Catherine Crier as
host; Ms. Crier left last week to join Court TV. Ailes wants to
make it a hard-news program, more like ABC News' ``Nightline,'' and
cited Ms. Zahn's experience at CBS News as a reason. The new show
will start in August.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
