<HEADLINE>
DISARMAMENT REPORT SEEN AS KEY TO RESOLVING STALEMATE IN BELFAST 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland _ Negotiators on Tuesday turned their
hopes of meeting an imminent deadline for resolving the impasse
threatening the Northern Ireland peace agreement to a long-awaited
report on whether paramilitary organizations are willing to disarm.
</P>
<P>
   The report has been prepared by retired Gen. John de Chastelain
of Canada, the head of an international disarmament commission set
up by the accord, and a key part is based on answers to a
questionnaire he put to the groups asking how committed they were
to turning in their arms.
</P>
<P>
   The guerrilla organizations' insistence on maintaining their
arsenals has stalled the vital next step in the peace accord _ the
transfer of power from the British government to the new Northern
Ireland Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   The Ulster Unionists, the biggest party in the legislature, are
refusing to let Sinn Fein, the political wing of the Irish
Republican Army, take its seats in the Assembly's executive cabinet
without a move to disarm by the IRA.
</P>
<P>
   A deadline of midnight Wednesday has been set by British Prime
Minister Tony Blair, who, with his Irish counterpart, Bertie Ahern,
has been in Belfast since Monday jointly conducting the final talks
as the two of them did in April 1998 before the signing of the
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   A similar declaration of a firm deadline during those talks
served to focus frustratingly inconclusive negotiations and produce
an agreement, and that was Blair's purpose this time in setting the
June 30 date. July 1 is also the day that the new legislatures in
Scotland and Wales assume their powers, making it a fitting
historical moment for the Northern Ireland Assembly to do the same.
</P>
<P>
   Blair said that the deadline was ``absolute'' and that he had
``no plan B'' if the deadline expired with no decision. The
strategy seemed to be having a positive effect as representatives
of the parties to the accord spoke to reporters gathered outside
the Stormont Castle Buildings Tuesday evening with little of the
fatalism that has characterized their comments in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence that the de Chastelain document was becoming the
vehicle for a resolution emerged after the two prime ministers held
a lunch meeting with the Canadian and then said delivery of the
report, scheduled for Tuesday afternoon, was being postponed until
Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The delay was seen as a way of gaining time to incorporate
critical negotiating points into the document. A spokesman for
Blair explained that there was ``business being done here by the
prime ministers that is relevant to what the general is doing.''
</P>
<P>
   The report is expected to outline the timetable for paramilitary
disarming or decommissioning, as it is called here, leading up to
the deadline of May 2000 envisaged in the peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   This aspect of the report took on added significance this week
when David Trimble, leader of the Ulster Unionists and the first
minister of the Northern Ireland Assembly, suggested that a
statement by Sinn Fein committing the IRA to disarm by that date
could satisfy his party's demand and allow the creation of the
power-sharing cabinet to go forward.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble's comment raised the hope that he might drop his ``no
guns, no government'' insistence that there must be actual
disarmament before Sinn Fein could enter the executive cabinet in
exchange for an enforceable IRA disarmament pledge. Blair has
already put forward the notion, intended to reassure the Unionists,
that Sinn Fein's participation in the government would forcibly end
if the IRA failed to disarm in the allotted time.
</P>
<P>
   The de Chastelain report and the role it might play in
reconciling the Catholic and Protestant sides emerged at a moment
when all other efforts seemed to have failed and the despairing
possibility loomed that the carefully calibrated and much hailed
agreement designed to end three decades of sectarian violence might
be in danger of collapsing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anyone can underestimate the formidable
difficulties we face,'' Blair said at the outset of the second day
of talks, ``but we've been here before, we've done it before and we
can do it again.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Tensions were on the rise in the province after a decision on
Monday by the government-appointed Parades Commission to ban the
annual march from Drumcree Church through a Catholic neighborhood
in Portadown and the linking of bomb material captured by Irish
police in a truck headed for Northern Ireland to the IRA.
</P>
<P>
   The IRA connection to the confiscated explosives became known
when the two men arrested in the case asked to be admitted to the
wing of the Irish jail housing members of the guerrilla group.
Unionist politicians in Belfast argued unsuccessfully that the
episode constituted a violation of the IRA's commitment to a
cease-fire that underpinned Sinn Fein's participation in the peace
effort and should result in expulsion of the party.
</P>
<P>
   In Portadown, Royal Ulster Constabulary police were putting up
barricades and digging trenches at the rural parish that has been
the scene of violent confrontations each July the last five years,
and leaders of the Orange Order, which sponsors the march,
scheduled daily parades in the town leading up to this weekend's
showdown.
</P>
<P>
   They also prepared to welcome an estimated 150 Orangemen and
victims of IRA violence who are crossing the province this week in
a ``long march'' of solidarity with the Orangemen of Portadown.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Ian Paisley, the militant Protestant political figure,
said Blair had assured him Tuesday, however, that he was still
trying to find a way to settle the Drumcree standoff. David Jones,
the spokesman for the Portadown Orangemen, said his people might
now abandon their longtime refusal to meet with the residents of
the protesting Catholic Garvaghy Road neighborhood if it would
enable the men to parade this Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
