<HEADLINE>
THE BUSH BOGGLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Like father, like son.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush obviously learned important political
lessons from his father, the former president. One thing he could
not learn, however, is reverence for the Constitution's First
Amendment because his father didn't have any.
</P>
<P>
   Neither man is willing to leave its magnificent message alone.
</P>
<P>
   While in the White House, George Bush supported a constitutional
amendment to criminalize the burning of the U.S. flag, a
pseudo-patriotic attack upon the great document's protection of
freedom of speech.
</P>
<P>
   It was a political low to which the president of the United
States, leader of the free world, should never have stooped. He was
campaigning for reelection at the time, but that is no excuse.
</P>
<P>
   Flag-burning is neither widespread nor a threat to the dignity
of either Old Glory or the republic. And the Supreme Court held
long ago that symbolic gestures are the equivalent of speech and
are therefore protected from government repression.
</P>
<P>
   But pandering politicians keep insisting they know better. The
nutty House of Representatives voted recently for the third time to
ban flag burning.
</P>
<P>
   And guess what? It was applauded by the president's son, who
pro
</P>
</TEXT>
