<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990629.0240 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3639 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-29 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BUSH BOGGLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Like father, like son.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush obviously learned important political
lessons from his father, the former president. One thing he could
not learn, however, is reverence for the Constitution's First
Amendment because his father didn't have any.
</P>
<P>
   Neither man is willing to leave its magnificent message alone.
</P>
<P>
   While in the White House, George Bush supported a constitutional
amendment to criminalize the burning of the U.S. flag, a
pseudo-patriotic attack upon the great document's protection of
freedom of speech.
</P>
<P>
   It was a political low to which the president of the United
States, leader of the free world, should never have stooped. He was
campaigning for reelection at the time, but that is no excuse.
</P>
<P>
   Flag-burning is neither widespread nor a threat to the dignity
of either Old Glory or the republic. And the Supreme Court held
long ago that symbolic gestures are the equivalent of speech and
are therefore protected from government repression.
</P>
<P>
   But pandering politicians keep insisting they know better. The
nutty House of Representatives voted recently for the third time to
ban flag burning.
</P>
<P>
   And guess what? It was applauded by the president's son, who
promptly told a New Hampshire questioner that he supported the
move. He is in mid-campaign, too, and it is still no excuse.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, the Bushes and the House may never have to face the
consequences of their constitutional ignorance. The Senate has
never approved the flag-burning foolishness and is still two votes
short of doing so.
</P>
<P>
   But the Texas governor went on to reinforce his careless
constitutional attitude with a second stupidity during his initial
campaign swing. Incredibly, he endorsed another recent House
measure that trashes the First Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   This one would allow states to permit the display of the Ten
Commandments in schools and other public facilities. It's supposed
to be voluntary, but if you believe that, I have this genuine
diamond ring I'd like to sell you.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he had no problem at all with hanging those religious
rules of behavior in public places.
</P>
<P>
   The Constitution protects freedom of religion by forbidding
government establishment of an official faith and erecting a
barrier between church doctrine and state action traditionally
honored by the courts. Twenty years ago the Supreme Court struck
down a Kentucky law requiring the posting of the Commandments in
public schools.
</P>
<P>
   The Commandments come in many versions _ as does religious faith
itself. Posting one version over another means the state has
authorized one over the other.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, covering public walls with biblical injunctions is
not going to stop one brainless kid with a bazooka from mowing down
his classmates.
</P>
<P>
   God is not a sound bite to be thrust forward for temporary
political gain. Prodded by self-appointed religious purists, the
House went berserk after the Littleton, Colo., high school shooting
over the Ten Commandments as a way of appearing concerned about
cultural violence without dealing with the problem of easy access
to guns.
</P>
<P>
   But why did Governor Bush fall for this hypocritical exercise?
</P>
<P>
   He stands with the Republican Party on the sensitive subject of
gun control. He doesn't want any new laws that might inconvenience
the sellers and buyers of the weapons of death. He recently signed
a new Texas measure that prohibited city lawsuits against
gunmakers.
</P>
<P>
   But he stayed largely on the sidelines during the congressional
debate over the gun issue. It wasn't his fight. He was wearing his
home-boy Texas blinders at the time.
</P>
<P>
   His overall goal is to move to the philosophical center,
sticking to basic right-wing positions but framing them in vague
ways that seem low-key and reasonable. Eventually, he will have to
say more on gun control and everything else.
</P>
<P>
   Joining the anti-First Amendment brigade, however, puts Bush in
a dangerous category of legislators who believe their judgment is
superior to that of the timeless principles of the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Bush sides with a crowd that believes Congress has the right to
push the religious and free speech views of its majority on other
free citizens who may think differently. He sides with zealots and
ignorant opportunists who hide behind patriotism and religion to
promote a selfish agenda of getting re-elected.
</P>
<P>
   This is not where a responsible presidential candidate should
stand. The First Amendment is too important to our basic freedoms
to be so cavalierly trod upon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
