<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUCLEAR-SAFETY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT CALLS FOR FINES AGAINST UNIVERSITY OF CALIFORNIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The University of California system should not be
protected by federal law from paying fines for safety violations at
the two nuclear weapons laboratories it runs, congressional
investigators said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In a report released during a congressional hearing into safety
conditions at America's nuclear laboratories, the General
Accounting Office called for changing the law that blocks the
Energy Department, which owns the labs, from forcing the university
system to pay.
</P>
<P>
   Under the 1996 law, called the Price-Anderson Act, the Energy
Department is allowed to cite both for-profit and nonprofit
organizations, such as universities, that contract to do research
in its labs. However, the nonprofit organizations are not required
to pay fines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forcing the nonprofits to pay these fines would do a lot to
bringing more accountability to the system,'' GAO investigator Gary
L. Jones told the House Commerce Committee's oversight and
investigation panel.
</P>
<P>
   The law was enacted to protect universities from having to pay
fines using money from their public endowments.
</P>
<P>
   According to David Michaels, assistant secretary for
environment, safety and health at the Energy Department, the
agency's primary form of punishment is issuing public notices of a
lab's safety violations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, by getting the word out about violations, we
believe the labs have a great incentive to fix the problem,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Several members of Congress and the GAO disagreed, saying the
law needed more teeth.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not working,'' said Rep. Ron Klink, D-Pa., who called
UC's handling of the two laboratories ``careless.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1996, nonprofit contractors have been fined but not forced
to pay $605,000. Of these fines assessed on nonprofit
organizations, the UC labs accounted for $425,000, or 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The UC system was cited for:
</P>
<P>
   _ Failing to implement a plan to protect workers and the public
from radiation after a fire and explosion involving radioactive
material occurred at the Los Alamos facility in New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   _ Turning off or modifying without consent monitors that alert
workers to radiation exposure at the Lawrence Livermore lab in
California.
</P>
<P>
   _ Exposing workers at Lawrence Livermore to radiation levels
that exceeded safety limits because lab officials failed to
implement radiation protection requirements.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO report noted that the violations were not
life-threatening. The GAO is the investigative arm of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Van Ness, senior vice president of the UC system, said
enforcing the fines was unnecessary and that public notice of
violations was enough to ensure that labs meet safety requirements.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our reputation is our single most important asset,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Van Ness said that the possibility of losing future contracts
with the Energy Department ensured a ``commitment to excellence''
by nonprofit organizations. ``The potential loss of the contract is
much more significant than any fine that would be assessed,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   However, during questioning by the subcommittee chairman, Rep.
Fred Upton, R-Mich., Van Ness acknowledged that the University of
California has never had to compete for its Livermore and Los
Alamos contracts and likely will not in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Energy Department owns the Livermore and Los Alamos
facilities, the university runs all of the labs' operations.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for House Commerce Committee Chairman Thomas J.
Bliley Jr., R-Va., said the representative was concerned about the
GAO report and that he would look at changing the law. The Commerce
Committee oversees the Price-Anderson Act.
</P>
<P>
   ``As it is now, the nonprofits have very little
accountability,'' the spokesman, Eric Wohlschlegel, said.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or by e-mail at
mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
