<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWISS-HOLOCAUST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN BEGINS TO TELL NAZI VICTIMS HOW TO GET COMPENSATED BY
SWISS BANKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ELIZABETH OLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ A campaign began Tuesday to inform victims of Nazi
persecution how to claim compensation from a $1.25 billion fund set
up by two Swiss banks.
</P>
<P>
   People can apply even if they or their relatives never had a
Swiss account. A full-page advertisement ordered by a U.S. court is
being published in 500 newspapers and magazines in 40 countries. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Toll-free numbers and a Web site in seven languages, including
Yiddish, have been set up, said the World Jewish Congress, which,
with a panel of lawyers, oversees the effort. The eligible victims
or targets include Jews, Gypsies, Jehovah's Witnesses, homosexuals
and the handicapped.
</P>
<P>
   The ad has a coupon that can be mailed for more information.
Applications, which are not in the ad, are at
www.swissbankclaims.com. The site lists toll-free numbers for many
countries. In the United States, it is (888) 635-5483. Claims have
to be filed by Oct. 22.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign began with news conferences in New York, Tel Aviv
and other cities. The plan, approved by Judge Edward Korman of U.S.
District Court in Brooklyn, lists these categories of claimants: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ People with rights to assets, including bank accounts or
investment funds, deposited in Switzerland before May 9, 1945.
</P>
<P>
   _ People who had valuables, including art or similar assets that
the Nazis looted or removed.
</P>
<P>
   _ People forced into slave labor for companies that may have
deposited the revenues gained from that labor in Swiss companies.
</P>
<P>
   _ People who fled the Nazis but were turned away at Swiss
borders or, after having entered, were mistreated.
</P>
<P>
   _ People forced into slave labor at a site anywhere that a Swiss
company, bank or government agency owned or controlled.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement, reached in August, provided that the United Bank
of Switzerland and Credit Suisse pay the first installment of $250
million to an escrow account this year. Three additional
installments start this year. The distribution of the money could
begin late next year, said Elan Steinberg, executive director of
the World Jewish Congress.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-99 1849EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
