<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ESCAPEE-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS AUTHORITIES NAB ESCAPED TEXAS KILLER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PATTY REINERT 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Escaped murderer Clifford Jones, who spent two nights nearly
naked in the East Texas woods after fleeing one of the state's most
secure prisons, was found in a tree Tuesday and surrendered, prison
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We caught our guy,'' said prison spokesman Larry Fitzgerald.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who fled the Estelle prison unit shortly after noon
Sunday, was spotted by a guard at 1:25 p.m. Tuesday about 2 1/2
miles from the prison northeast of Huntsville. The escapee, who
scrambled up a tree as officers closed in, was asked to come down
and give himself up, which he did, Fitzgerald said.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, at first thought to be hiding out in the woods naked, was
wearing his white prison-issue boxer shorts when he was captured.
He appeared to be suffering from dehydration and mosquito bites,
and asked for food and water, which he was given when he was
returned to the prison, Fitzgerald said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Considering where's he's been, he's in good condition,''
Fitzgerald said. ``He wasn't a walking welt,'' he added, referring
to earlier indications that the inmate had climbed a poison
ivy-infested oak tree Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, 33, was serving a 26-year sentence _ 20 years for killing
a Dallas man and attempting to kill a police officer, and six for
assaulting a prison guard. He now faces charges for escape and will
be transferred to another prison unit for medical treatment,
Fitzgerald said.
</P>
<P>
   Allan Polunsky, chairman of the Texas Board of Criminal Justice,
meanwhile, ordered an internal investigation of Jones' escape from
the 2-year-old prison, which was built as a prototype for prisons
housing some of the state's most dangerous offenders. Already,
prison officials have modified plans for four more prisons under
construction to take into account flaws that allowed Jones to
escape. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; On Sunday, as Jones was being led from his cell to a caged
recreation area, he slipped out of his handcuffs and shoved a guard
out of the way before climbing a 25-foot fence and squeezing
through an 8- to 10-inch gap between the top of the fence and the
roof.
</P>
<P>
   After scaling a second fence and a camera tower, he vaulted over
the razor wire atop the prison's outer fence. A perimeter guard in
a van fired two shots at Jones, but missed.
</P>
<P>
   Security cameras recorded Jones shedding his shoes and stripping
off his prison uniform about 100 yards from the prison before
running into the woods. Search dogs followed Jones' trail to an oak
tree covered in poison ivy vines, where officials believe the
killer spent the night.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday and Monday, as crews worked to shore up security at
Estelle, welding additional fencing to fill the gap through which
Jones escaped and adding razor wire to the camera towers, about 300
searchers used dogs, boats and helicopters to hunt for Jones.
</P>
<P>
   They had few leads until about 3 a.m. Tuesday, when a helicopter
equipped with heat sensors detected the prisoner in chest-deep
water near the prison. The helicopter was running low on fuel and
wasn't able to land because of the wooded and swampy terrain,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once the helicopter spotted him, we redoubled our efforts in
that area and were closing in when a guard saw him,'' Fitzgerald
said. ``He was found in the area where we were searching all the
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones was the first inmate to escape from a Texas prison this
year. Last Thanksgiving, seven condemned killers escaped death row
at the nearby Ellis I unit. One of them, Martin Gurule, cleared the
prison's outer fences, but was found dead in a creek near the
prison after a massive weeklong manhunt. An autopsy showed that he
had drowned shortly after his escape.
</P>
<P>
   Prison board member Mac Stringfellow of San Antonio, who will
lead the investigation into Jones' escape, also investigated
Gurule's break-out. In that case, investigators concluded that
negligence by prison employees was to blame. The prison warden was
demoted and his two assistants were reassigned to other prisons,
while at least three guards were disciplined.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
