<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Wednesday, June 30 and thereafter. For questions about stories,
contact Jeremy Bagott at the Daily News, (818) 713-3702.
</P>
<P>
   MYLES-VERDICT (Los Angeles) _ Two men who robbed and shot a
North Hills woman as she picked up her daughter from Bible study
classes were convicted of murder in a crime that shocked the San
Fernando Valley. Laurie Myles's 9-year-old son tried to save his
mother's life, as she bled to death. Now 15, he said the conviction
is bittersweet justice. ``The only thing I could do is smile _ it's
over,'' said Joshua Myles. ``I have my mom's heart in me. She was a
really great person.'' By Jesse Hiestand. (Will move in the ``n''
California news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CAR-RING (Los Angeles) _ A business owned by NBA player Latrell
Sprewell and a Chatsworth resident were swept up into an
investigation of cars and trucks stolen in Mexico and smuggled to
the United States. The ring is a twist on the reverse phenomenon:
cars stolen here and shipped out of the country. In some cases, DMV
employees are involved in the ring as they receive kickbacks to
issue new titles on the stolen vehicles. Sprewell is not accused of
a crime. By Lisa Van Proyen. (Will move in the ``n'' California,
``a'' national and ``s'' sports news file.)
</P>
<P>
   LA-HOOKERS (Los Angeles) _ Jody ``Babydoll'' Gibson appears in
court to plead not guilty to nine pimping charges, on allegations
that she ran a prostitution ring that catered to the rich and
famous from the San Fernando Valley to Europe. By Phillip Browne.
(Will move in the ``n'' California and ``a'' national news file.)
</P>
<P>
   LA-POST-PRODUCTION (Los Angeles) _ Post-production entertainment
work in Los Angeles County amounts to nearly $7 billion annually
and carries a bright outlook, a survey to be released Wednesday
shows. The sector amounts to nearly one third of the economic
activity generated by the the entertainment industry, according to
the study. By Dave McNary. (Will move in the ``f'' financial and
``n'' California news file.)
</P>
<P>
   HOWS-MARKET (Los Angeles) _ It's official. With the opening
today of a second supermarket, this time in the Los Angeles suburb
of Santa Clarita, a group of former Hughes Family Markets
executives has bucked market trends and introduced a brand-new
grocery chain: HOWS Markets. By Jason Takenouchi. (Will move in the
``f'' financial news file.)
</P>
