<HEADER>
A3659 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-SERBS-2TAKES(T     06-29 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-SERBS-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
10,000 SERB PROTESTERS DEMAND RESIGNATION OF MILOSEVIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (rm) 
 By BLAINE HARDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CACAK, Yugoslavia _ In the first major anti-government
demonstration since NATO stopped bombing Yugoslavia, about 10,000
people packed into the central square of this war-damaged
manufacturing city Tuesday to demand the resignation of President
Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   A parade of speakers said that Milosevic, by committing robbery
and murder in Kosovo in the name of the Serb people, has shamed
Serbia in the eyes of the world, ruined the economy and tried to
cover up his failures by a campaign of lies in the state-owned
media.
</P>
<P>
   In this city where several large factories were destroyed by
American bombs that killed five civilians, not a single speaker
blamed the United States for devastation that will likely take
decades to recover from. Instead, the speakers accused Milosevic of
``evil'' that provoked attacks from Serbia's traditional allies in
the West.
</P>
<P>
   ``This government has shamed us in front of ourselves, in front
of God and in front of the whole world,'' said Milan Protic, a
history professor from Belgrade and a leader of the Alliance for
Change, an umbrella group of opposition parties that organized the
rally.
</P>
<P>
   Vladan Babic, coordinator of what the Alliance for Change says
will be a series of rallies across Serbia in coming weeks, told the
crowd that the point of the demonstration was to send a simple
message to Milosevic: ``Go away! Go to Cuba and study Stalinism
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Cacak is one of the few cities in Serbia where the opposition is
in complete control of the city government. The rally's organizers
said they did not yet plan any demonstrations in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Three months of daily rallies in Belgrade in the winter of
1996-97 brought huge crowds into the streets demanding that
Milosevic resign. But due in part to in-fighting among opposition
leaders, the demonstrations fizzled out.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Just as Tuesday's demonstration began, a loud explosion went off
in a far corner of the central square. The crowd was stunned into
silence by the blast, but it hurt no one. A device used in war
games to imitate the sound of artillery reportedly caused the
explosion. It was not clear who planted it.
</P>
<P>
   After demonstrators saw that nobody was hurt, the rally resumed
and they joined in shouting, ``Red Bandits, Red Bandits,'' a
familiar reference to Milosevic and his government.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The state of war imposed here during NATO's 11-week bombing
campaign ended last weekend, but the Serbian government has not
lifted its ban on public gatherings. The city of Cacak decided to
go ahead with the rally despite being told by Serbian police that
it was illegal, said Dusan Dzinkovic, the vice-mayor.
</P>
<P>
   On roads leading into this town of about 80,000, Serbian police
stopped a number of buses and cars, some from Belgrade carrying
opposition party leaders, as well as foreign and local journalists.
A few foreign reporters said they were turned back.
</P>
<P>
   During the rally, Vuk Obradovic, an opposition leader, thanked
the Yugoslav Army for the local soldiers who he said picked up
demonstrators and brought them to the rally after police had
stopped busloads of opposition activists outside town.
</P>
<P>
   Army reservists have blocked roads and bridges in several towns
in central Serbia in the past week, protesting that they have not
been paid during the war. It was not clear, though, if these
reservists were the ones who helped bring demonstrators to town.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``Thanks to our army for enabling people to break through the
police barricades on some roads and come to join us. They are with
us and we are with them and they know it,'' said Obradovic, a
former Army general who resigned in 1992 to protest the conduct of
Serbia's war against Croatia.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav army has had a rocky relationship with Milosevic
over the years, marked by frequent purges and grumbling about
declining living standards, as the Serbian leader has shifted money
to the Serbian police.
</P>
<P>
   A Serbian police officer on the outside of town said after the
rally that he and his fellow officers had stopped no one from going
into Cacak and accused the speakers at the rally of spreading false
information.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers of the rally said it was the first of what they hoped
will be about 20 to 25 demonstrations across Serbia in the next
five weeks. Only then, they said, will they go to Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the police harassing us, it is easier to organize
locally,'' Protic said. ``Belgrade should come as the
culmination.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The opposition crushed the ruling Socialist Party in elections
in Cacak in 1996, taking control of all but eight seats in the
70-member town council. The already high anti-Milosevic temperature
of Cacak soared during Serbia's war with NATO. The city's popular
mayor, Velimir Ilic, complained publicly that the Yugoslav Army had
caused the death of four civilians in the town by parking its tanks
near private houses. They were hit by NATO bombs aimed at the
tanks.
</P>
<P>
   After Ilic's complaints found their way onto Radio Free Europe,
military police tried to arrest him on May 19 and he went into
hiding. Ilic used Tuesday's rally as a coming out party, and his
appearance on stage ignited the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today I am the happiest person in the world because I am with
you again,'' he said. ``But I could cry because of what this
government has done to this country.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor challenged the Serbian government to arrest him now,
saying that he would no longer hide from authorities.
</P>
<P>
   The rally was as notable, though, for who did not speak. Vuk
Draskovic, the charismatic leader of the largest opposition party
in Serbia, had refused to join the opposition alliance. He says the
time is not yet ripe to take to the streets to demand that
Milosevic leave power.
</P>
<P>
   At a press conference in Belgrade, Draskovic said Tuesday that
he hoped to pressure change in the Milosevic regime without
disruptive demonstrations and sniffed that, in any case, there is
no viable opposition movement in Serbia without his Serbian Renewal
Movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it wasn't for journalists no one would have any knowledge
neither of the alliance nor of their rallies,'' he said. ``The
alliance groups small parties with no influence, and everything
they organize will substantiate that fact.''
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic's dismissive remarks were the only mention of
Tuesday's demonstration that appeared in the evening on state
television, which is controlled by Milosevic.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   On a wiltingly hot afternoon in Cacak's town square,
expectations were low that demonstrations alone could force
Milosevic to step down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no hope that this rally will change anything,'' said
Vladimir Lukic, 25, who is soon to graduate with an engineering
decree from a Cacak college whose windows were blown out this
spring by NATO bombs. ``These demonstrations have happened before
and they didn't change anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Lukic said he came out to shout for Milosevic's
resignation ``because this is the worst country in Europe. I am
sick and tired of this regime.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he blamed the United States or the countries of Western
Europe for the bombing that in April closed his college, Lukic
said, ``No. This is not the will of the American people, it is the
consequence of the crimes that have been going on in this country
for 10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Lukic, a towering young man with a gold ring in his left
earlobe, said that he is hoping to escape Serbia next year. He said
that his widowed mother, who teaches in the local high school, has
not been paid for four months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no future and I plan to go to the USA, if I can,'' he
said. ``I will even go to Cleveland. I hear in films that it is the
ugliest city town in America, but I will even go there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
