<SLUG> BC-CAMBODIA-PRISON-ART-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR THE GHOSTS OF TUOL SLENG, NO COMFORT IN THE ARREST OF A
TORTURER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(gm) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia _ The ghosts seem to think this old
schoolhouse belongs to them, thumping and moaning, crying out for
help, offering themselves for sex, turning themselves into white
cats.
</P>
<P>
   People who work here say the ghosts are the restless souls of
victims of the Khmer Rouge, and their forms are as varied as the
imaginations of the people who describe them.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, these people say, the ghosts have become newly agitated.
Their master is back: the buck-toothed schoolteacher nicknamed Duch
who turned the Tuol Sleng high school building into the most
efficient and terrifying torture chamber of the Khmer Rouge years.
</P>
<P>
   Having run a prison that dispatched at least 14,000 people to
their deaths from 1975 to 1979, Duch (pronounced dook) escaped with
other ousted Khmer Rouge leaders into Cambodia's western jungles,
where he converted to Christianity and returned to his old role as
a teacher.
</P>
<P>
   In May he was discovered and arrested, and has admitted ordering
torture and killings. Now he awaits trial in a military cell _ far
more commodious than the brick-walled pens of Tuol Sleng _ just 300
yards down a muddy, rutted lane.
</P>
<P>
   He would know the prison well if he returned. It has hardly
changed since he fled in January 1979 after executing the last
half-dozen prisoners, still shackled to their metal cots in bare
interrogation rooms. The bodies are gone, but the cots and shackles
remain. Dried blood still blackens the cracks of the tile floors
beneath them.
</P>
<P>
   Tuol Sleng prison has been preserved unrestored as a museum
since the Khmer Rouge fled a Vietnamese invasion after a Cambodian
reign of terror in which at least a million died. Its windows are
broken and its bars are rusting, surrounded with weeds and refuse,
filled with the twittering of tiny birds.
</P>
<P>
   The walls of its ground-floor rooms are a montage of hundreds of
portraits of prisoners who were greeted with the flash of a camera
when they arrived and, if they survived their torture, were trucked
to a killing field when they left.
</P>
<P>
   Twice a year, monks visit to chant Buddhist exorcisms to calm
the ghosts. But for the 40 guides and custodians who provide
security by sleeping here in rotating shifts of 10, the nights
still seem haunted.
</P>
<P>
   Keo Lundi constantly hears a thumping, like that of someone
jumping down from a wall, but every time he leaves his cot to
investigate, he finds nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Lach Kalyan saw a spectral white cat as she swept the back
rooms, growing larger every time she glanced at it until she threw
down her broom in terror and fled.
</P>
<P>
   Lor Chandara once made the mistake of sleeping in a doorway that
was apparently a passage for invisible prowlers and ended up
wrestling with something as insubstantial as the darkness.
</P>
<P>
   One security guard, Keo Lundi said, was tormented night after
night by the image of a young woman who offered herself, unwanted,
at the edge of his cot. But when he kicked at her, he encountered
only the flimsiness of his mosquito net.
</P>
<P>
   Workers say another guard died of a heart attack here after
sharing a communal dream of ghosts with three companions.
</P>
<P>
   It was only a little while ago that a worker was startled, in
broad daylight, by screams for help coming from the back of the
building, several museum guides said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounded like a real person being beaten or killed,'' said
Keo Lundi, who ran to investigate. ``I'd never heard a sound like
that. We looked and looked, but there was nobody there. So we think
it was a ghost, come to take revenge now that Duch is back.''
</P>
<P>
   The image of Duch _ whose real name is Kang Kek Ieu _ is
everywhere in the small, dark upstairs room where Mrs. Lach Kalyan,
44, works alone as the custodian of the Tuol Sleng archive.
</P>
<P>
   On the walls, in glass-fronted cabinets and scattered on a
tabletop, fraying and fading together, are portraits of the chief
Khmer Rouge killers intermingled with the vacant and frightened
faces of their victims.
</P>
<P>
   Reach into a pile of pictures on the table and pull out a
smiling photograph of Pol Pot, the Khmer Rouge leader, who died
last year. Or instead it may be the stunned image of a young man
seeming to ask, as many of the prisoners did when they arrived,
``Where am I?''
</P>
<P>
   In one cabinet is a reproduction of Duch's rules of conduct for
interrogations, written in chalk on a blackboard with the
starchiness of a strict schoolmaster:
</P>
<P>
   ``Answer exactly what you are asked. Never try to dodge the
question.
</P>
<P>
   ``Answer immediately without taking even a moment to consider.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do not scream when you are beaten or electrocuted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do nothing. Sit still and wait for my orders. If there is no
order, keep quiet. When I give you a command, obey immediately
without protest.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Late afternoons are the worst here among the archives, Mrs. Lach
Kal-yan said, when the building has fallen quiet, the sky begins to
darken and the images around her almost seem to come to life.
</P>
<P>
   ``One day I was here and the clouds got very black,'' she said.
``The wind started blowing and the windows were shaking. I was
alone. The clouds got darker and darker, and the room got darker
and darker, just like an American ghost movie. I ran downstairs and
ran home. Even you would have been scared if you were here, I
think.''
</P>
<P>
   Out on the grounds, though, where the guides sometimes play
volleyball near an outdoor torture rack, the ghosts retreat.
</P>
<P>
   A busload of tourists from Taiwan, together with their
Vietnamese girlfriends, files out past a cluster of one-legged
beggars. A vendor sells soft drinks and postcards. The air is
pungent with the smell of frying garlic.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly a man runs past wearing only shorts and jogging shoes.
It is Lor Chandara, who left his job as a guide here eight years
ago, on his daily run through the grounds of Tuol Sleng.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, it's not strange,'' he said, when asked about his choice
of running track. ``I live nearby and it's convenient to come here.
And it's really good, I tell you, jogging. If I don't jog for one
day I feel ill. Plus it lowers the cholesterol.''
</P>
</TEXT>
