<HEADLINE>
NASDAQ, S&AMP;P 500 APPROACH RECORD HIGHS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stocks staged another broad advance Tuesday as the
NASDAQ composite index and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index
moved close to their record highs.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the solid gains, traders said the increase in prices
appeared to have more to do with technical adjustments to
portfolios than a shift in investor sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   The main market gauges have been under pressure for weeks as
high valuations and the threat of a series of interest rate
increases by the Federal Reserve have combined to sow seeds of
uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed governors began two days of meetings Tuesday and will
announce the outcome Wednesday afternoon. The central bank is
widely expected to raise rates by one-quarter of a percentage
point.
</P>
<P>
   One school of thought holds that with few signs of inflation,
the Fed will need to raise interest rates only once this year. But
there is a real possibility that this could be the first in a
series of moves. At the end of last week, many had expected trading
activity would remain light and convictionless until the Fed
revealed its intentions.
</P>
<P>
   That did not happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's counterintuitive,'' said Bob Gasser, head of U.S. equity
trading at J.P. Morgan Securities. ``With valuations where they are
and on the eve of what could be more than one increase in interest
rates by the Fed, I don't understand'' the recent rise in prices.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average rose for the third consecutive
session Tuesday, gaining 160.20 points, or 1.5 percent, to
10,815.35.
</P>
<P>
   Chevron, which was raised to a ``buy'' by analysts at Donaldson,
Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette, United Technologies and General Electric, led
the blue-chip index higher.
</P>
<P>
   Broader market averages also did well.
</P>
<P>
   The S&AMP;P 500 surged 20.10 points, or 1.5 percent, to 1,351.45,
16.11 points below its high, reached on May 13. NASDAQ gained
39.67, or 1.5 percent, to 2,642.11. The index is now just 9.94
points below its high on April 26.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller-company stocks continued what has been a strong
quarter-long rally. The Russell 2000 index gained 5.47 points, or
1.2 percent, to 454.08.
</P>
<P>
   Trading volume was much higher than recent sessions.
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange, 820 million shares changed
hands. Volume on the NASDAQ market was 952 million shares.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Gasser and other traders said much of the activity
centered on the reconstruction of various market indexes, including
the S&AMP;P 500 and the Russell 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Airtouch Communications, which has been acquired by Vodaphone
and will be leaving the S&AMP;P 500 index Wednesday, and Best Buy,
which is replacing it, were heavily traded stocks. Airtouch fell 3
1/2, to 107 1/2. Best Buy rose 3, to 65 11/16.
</P>
<P>
   And some 350 issues, including many Internet stocks, have seen
their market capitalizations expand to the point where they no
longer qualify to be included in the Russell 2000 index. They will
be replaced by others whose market capitalization falls within a
$1.4 billion ceiling and a $180 million floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spent a lot of time with Airtouch and Best Buy,'' Gasser
said. ``All told, I spent about 90 percent of my time on these
index reconfigurations.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Clark, head of U.S. stock trading at Credit Suisse First
Boston, said, ``At the end of the day you could see the rebalancing
taking place.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But you don't want to be a hero,'' at this juncture, he added.
``What you really want to see is what the Fed does, and how the
market reacts to early second-quarter earnings reports. The next
couple of weeks will be very important.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there were some fundamental reasons for optimism.
</P>
<P>
   A series of positive announcements from Asian countries,
including Japan and South Korea, helped to bolster stocks of
companies that do a lot of business in the region, like United
Technologies, General Electric, Applied Materials and Intel.
</P>
<P>
   United Technologies, which derived about 17 percent of its sales
from Asia last year, gained 3 3/4, to 68 15/16. General Electric
rose 3 1/2, to 109 11/16.
</P>
<P>
   Applied Materials, the world's leading semiconductor equipment
maker, said its sales in Southeast Asia might double this year. The
stock rose 2 3/4, to 69 1/8. And Intel gained 2 1/4, to 59 1/4.
</P>
<P>
   Drug stocks, which have been the worst performing group this
quarter, regained some ground Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Pfizer rose 3 13/16, to 104 7/8. Warner-Lambert shot up 4 3/8,
to 67 1/8. And Merck gained 1 7/16, to 71 1/2.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
