<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 19:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3675 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-DRAFT-ODOM-BOS &LR;      06-29 1643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-DRAFT-ODOM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEAT'S ON FOR ODOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KINGSTON, R.I. _ For about 30 minutes, steady bouncing of
basketballs and quick-stop squeaking of athletic shoes could be
heard on the opposite side of the University of Rhode Island's
Tootell East Gym. Then it gave way to footsteps heading toward the
door, which flung open after being shoved by an angry,
sweat-drenched 19-year-old who had spent the previous half-hour
trying to impress NBA scouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``They picked a great gym,'' shouted URI sophomore Lamar Odom,
reaching for a nearby empty trash can to hold open the door so
fresh air could enter the gym _ which had no open windows and no
air conditioning. After a few failed attempts, he lowered his head
and returned inside to brace the elements again.
</P>
<P>
   You have to feel for Lamar Odom. Many facets of his life have
been all too similar to the pressure cooker he worked out in Monday
night, and too often his need to break away for fresh air
outweighed his willingness to withstand and endure.
</P>
<P>
   Though he has played just one season of college basketball, Odom
is the most talented prospect in the NBA draft. At 6 feet 10
inches, he can play all five positions. He is a text-book perimeter
shooter but thinks pass first. He sees the floor well, can create
off the dribble, and has a quick, fluid first step.
</P>
<P>
   On the court, he handles pressure with the composure of a
seasoned veteran: In his first collegiate game, he scored on a
finger roll with 5.7 seconds left to lift URI past Texas Christian.
In his penultimate game, he scored on a 25-foot 3-pointer at the
buzzer to beat Temple in the Atlantic 10 tournament final, giving
URI its first conference title.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it's safe to say that the four teams present for the
workout (Toronto, Los Angeles Clippers, Miami, and Chicago) did not
sit through the suffocating air to check out Odom's skills.
</P>
<P>
   They wanted to hear his side of the story _ why, after
committing to the NBA draft and signing with an agent, did Odom
skip a Bulls workout and fail to show up at the predraft camp?
</P>
<P>
   Or, as Bulls assistant coach Frank Hamblen put it, ``I just
wanted to know if there really was a Lamar Odom.''
</P>
<P>
   The Queens, N.Y., resident said he didn't shoot well in the
workout and added, ``I'm looking forward to (the draft), but
hopefully I didn't take myself out of the top five.'' It was his
first meeting with assembled media since May 17, when he announced
he was forgoing his last two seasons of college eligibility to
enter the NBA draft.
</P>
<P>
   Odom is concerned about his stock with NBA scouts because
``everything that has been going on has been so crazy. But I'm a
fighter. I wanted to come back because it's a crazy business and at
19 years old, you have to be ready for everything. It caught me a
little bit off guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the business part of it, for a 19 year old, someone who
doesn't really have anyone close to him, a father figure who can be
there and that really knows everything that's happening, all of
this I had to take care of myself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It caught me off guard, and I just love the innocence of
college basketball, and with Jerry (DeGregorio) being the head
coach, (URI) is a great place to play. It made it hard to sleep at
night.''
</P>
<P>
   Odom is still a gem in the eyes of scouts. Chicago has the first
overall pick, Los Angeles fourth and Toronto fifth, respectively,
and it is doubtful they would have ventured to Kingston two days
before the draft if they weren't interested in Odom.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's Washington Post reported that Toronto and the
Washington Wizards (seventh pick) were exploring swapping picks,
enabling the Wizards to possibly select Odom or Miami of Ohio star
Wally Szczerbiak. DeGregorio, who has also served as Odom's mentor
and advisor, said he has been besieged with calls from agents,
scouts, marketing firms, management groups, and trading card
companies.
</P>
<P>
   But that is not to say Odom's indecision hasn't bothered some.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very frustrating in the evaluation process,'' said
Hamblen, ``because you also want to deal with someone on a personal
basis. I know that we are not the only franchise that's
disappointed. For whatever reason, there have been a lot of broken
commitments.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Problem is, the recent wavering came at a time when Odom had
appeared to be shedding that reputation. It began to take root when
he left Christ the King High School in Queens after his sophomore
season and attended Redemption Christian Academy in Troy, N.Y.,
then left there for St. Thomas Aquinas in Milford, Conn., where
DeGregorio once coached.
</P>
<P>
   Odom signed a national letter of intent to attend Nevada-Las
Vegas, then was released from the letter after a Sports Illustrated
article questioned the validity of his entrance exam scores. He
opted to try and earn a scholarship at URI as a nonmatriculating
student his first year but left a few times that year while
attempting to make the grade, including once during final exams.
</P>
<P>
   Odom finished his one-year career at URI as one of the school's
most celebrated players. He averaged 17.6 points and 9.4 rebounds
per game, and was named A-10 rookie of the year.
</P>
<P>
   When Odom declared himself eligible for the draft, he said he
would not sign with an agent before the draft, and he added that he
could not foresee anything that would make him change his mind and
return to URI. Asked that day about his wavering in the past, Odom
said that was indicative of growing pains and added, ``I'm a man
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Odom did, however, go on to sign with New York-based agent Jeff
Klein. But following a workout with the Vancouver Grizzlies, he
decided he wasn't ready for the NBA lifestyle after all. Klein
ultimately resigned as Odom's agent.
</P>
<P>
   Odom's change of heart came a day after DeGregorio indicated
that Odom was not pulling out of the draft and was merely seeking
new representation.
</P>
<P>
   Underclassmen who sign with agents forfeit their eligibility.
URI officials initially offered to help Odom prepare a long-shot
appeal with the NCAA, but then changed their minds, stating that
the facts surrounding the situation didn't warrant going forward.
</P>
<P>
   The saddest part about Odom's tale is that it often leads people
to draw the wrong conclusions; he is actually a very bright,
approachable individual.
</P>
<P>
   But even Odom knows he needs to work on his decision- making: In
the past, when the going got tough and he left, Odom was always
able to return to another chance. Now he knows that some actions
are irreversible. Perhaps he found out just in time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave it a shot and it didn't work,'' said Odom about trying
to return to school. He added he harbors no ill feelings toward URI
for changing its mind. ``As soon as they told me I couldn't come
back, I got over it.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about changing his mind about signing with an agent, Odom
said if he had to do it all over again, he would not have done so,
but would have sought legal counsel instead. Moreover, he said he
still would have explored going to the NBA. He said difficulties
with people around him led him to renege on attending the predraft
camp. ``That was when I decided to return to Jerry.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I just would have kept my options open. Me signing with an
agent killed my chances of coming back,'' Odom added. ``But I'm
happy to be an NBA player. This is what I've always wanted, what
I've always dreamed about.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DeGregorio said he repeatedly has been asked if he was surprised
Odom wanted to come back. ``And my comments are that I would have
been surprised if he didn't come back,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very safe place for him. He likes it here. He likes
being with his friends, the college lifestyle, and the social
aspects of it. He loves his teammates and he's very close with his
coaching staff. I think once he looked out and viewed what was out
there in terms of that lifestyle he just realized that, `Maybe I
could wait another year.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Todd Bozeman said that when he was coaching at California, he
had three players leave early _ Jason Kidd, Shareef Abdur-Rahim,
and Lamond Murray. He said Abdur-Rahim, who wanted to leave solely
to take care of his family, changed his mind then changed it again,
and was drafted by Vancouver as the third overall pick.
</P>
<P>
   But Bozeman said that Odom's indecision is not unique to college
basketball because players usually want to showcase their skills
immediately upon leaving school.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why you're out there, basically,'' said Bozeman. ``I
think there is a maturity factor there. I think he probably wanted
to crawl back into the cocoon of college basketball, and there's
nothing wrong with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he is pursuing new representation, Odom said, ``I'm
trying. But it's no great hurry. I've been in contact with Billy
Hunter, and I think he will wind up handling some of my work. It's
a new age with a player where you don't need an agent the first
couple of years. Everything is set in stone.''
</P>
<P>
   After working out, Odom was swarmed for autographs by several
youngsters who were at URI attending the US Scholar- Athlete Games.
At one point, a girl tapped on the shoulder of an onlooker, pointed
to Odom and said, ``You see that guy right there? He's going to be
famous someday.''
</P>
<P>
   If he can duplicate his collegiate exploits at the pro level,
and improve his decision-making skills, Odom likely will be. Still,
to hear him talk, he would still put it on hold for a chance to
play four years of college basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he had any advice for young players who will face a
similar decision, Odom quickly fired back, ``Stay for four years of
college,'' he said. ``You will make it much easier. You will learn
so much. Four years of college is the best thing I think anybody
can do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
