<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3678 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CMGI-ALTAVISTA-BOS &LR;      06-29 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CMGI-ALTAVISTA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CMGI BUYS MOST OF COMPAQ'S ALTAVISTA IN $2.3B DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In its largest deal yet to build its Internet holdings, CMGI
Inc. will buy most of Compaq Computer Corp.'s AltaVista search
engine in a deal worth about $2.3 billion, mostly in stock.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement announced Tuesday will give Compaq, the
Houston-based computer maker, control of about 16 percent of CMGI
and a seat on the Internet venture company's board as its largest
outside investor.
</P>
<P>
   In return, CMGI will gain control of 83 percent of AltaVista and
the task of turning the lagging search service into a full-fledged
Internet portal site.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, rumored for a week, ends some uncertainty about
Compaq's Internet strategy and marks a maturation of CMGI, whose
shares rose 13 percent after the agreement was announced.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, most of CMGI's market valuation of $10.5 billion
relates to small investments it once made in start-up companies
that later blossomed, including Lycos Inc. and GeoCities.
</P>
<P>
   Now CMGI is looking to capitalize on users who visit the
plethora of chat, news, and retail-service sites it operates or in
which it holds stakes. AltaVista could make an ideal platform for
links to services such as the Raging Bull financial news site or
the Furniture.com shopping service, said CMGI chairman and chief
executive David Wetherell.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to have the broadest reach on the Internet,''
Wetherell said.
</P>
<P>
   He and Compaq declined to discuss specific financial terms of
their agreement, but Wetherell said the additional revenue from
AltaVista would roughly double CMGI's current operating revenue of
about $160 million. Each company will also spend about $50 million
to bolster advertising for AltaVista, he said, compared to the
roughly $1 million Compaq has spent on branding so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the agreement, CMGI will also take control of
related AltaVista business units such as Shopping.com, and will
issue a $220 million three-year note to Compaq.
</P>
<P>
   For Compaq, the deal finally clarifies its intentions toward
AltaVista, which has stagnated since the computer maker acquired it
along with the rest of Digital Equipment Corp. in January 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Digital once touted AltaVista's speed, but under Compaq's
stewardship AltaVista has failed to keep up with competitors
including Lycos and Yahoo Inc., which have added new services and
transformed themselves from search tools into full-fledged portal
sites. In May, AltaVista attracted 10.6 million visitors, compared
with 31 million for Yahoo, according to Media Metrix Inc. in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq said earlier this year it might sell public shares of
AltaVista, and as recently as Monday AltaVista was rolling out new
services it said would make it more competitive. But Tuesday,
Compaq's chairman and acting chief executive Benjamin Rosen said
CMGI might map out a better future for AltaVista, and that his
company hopes to capitalize on CMGI's diverse holdings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found it made more sense to have a share of (CMGI's) broad
portfolio rather than 100 percent of one property,'' Rosen said in
a conference call with analysts and reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually the companies might sell public shares in AltaVista,
but for now the unit and its 475 employees will remain in Palo
Alto, Calif., under the direction of Rod Schrock, a Compaq veteran
named to head the company earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   AltaVista's problems had drawn many skeptics, and people
familiar with the company said before striking its deal with CMGI,
Compaq had also held talks with other parties including Yahoo,
Lycos, and Time-Warner Inc. (All declined official comment.)
</P>
<P>
   The deal also muddies the outlook for CMGI's relationship with
Waltham-based Lycos, an AltaVista competitor in which CMGI still
holds a 20 percent stake. Lycos once seemed a natural partner for
some of CMGI's services, but Wetherell and Lycos chief executive
Bob Davis fell out earlier this year over a different merger
proposed by Lycos.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, analysts were generally positive about the
CMGI-Compaq deal and suggested it would position the Andover firm
to consolidate traffic among its various properties and affiliates.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (Compaq) are selling it to people who can actually create
some value out of it,'' said First Albany Corp. analyst Ullas Naik.
``CMGI has reached a certain level in its growth curve where they
needed a major deal like this one,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Said Hambrecht &AMP; Quist analyst Paul Noglows, ``Strategically it
makes sense, since one of the things that CMGI has always been
about is drawing traffic and funneling through all sorts of
different services.''
</P>
<P>
   The agreement implied a total value of $2.7 billion for
AltaVista. Assuming total revenue of about $160 million, CMGI is
paying about 14 times earnings for its stake _ in line with the
valuations of other Internet stocks, Noglows said.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts also noted that by taking on the task of operating
AltaVista, the deal will help CMGI avoid a regulatory
classification as an investment company. Among other things, that
would require its shareholders to pay higher taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Share in CMGI, based in Andover, Mass., rose 12 5/8 to close at
110 5/16 in Nasdaq trading. Shares in Compaq rose 1 1/16 to 23 3/8
in New York Stock Exchange trading.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
