<SLUG> BC-CELLULARONE-CHARGES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELLULAR ONE DUMPS PLAN TO CHARGE FOR UNANSWERED CALLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MOHL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After being deluged with angry calls from customers, Cellular
One has pulled the plug on a plan to begin charging for calls 15
seconds after the send button is hit, even if no one answers the
phone.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which had planned to implement the new billing
procedure Thursday, said it would continue its existing policy of
billing customers after 30 seconds have elapsed. That's the
equivalent of about six rings; 15 seconds would have allowed only
three rings. Other cellular phone companies begin charging only if
a connection is made.
</P>
<P>
   In a three-sentence statement, the company said it reversed
itself after ``evaluating our pricing and product plans to ensure
we're meeting our customers' needs.''
</P>
<P>
   But customers and sources inside the company said the about-face
occurred only because of a loud chorus of customer complaints. The
company had notified customers of the planned change in April, but
most did not become aware of it until a Boston Globe story on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Several called the Globe to complain. John R. Fisher of Walpole
was so incensed that he said he planned to drop Cellular One when
his contract expires in November. Another caller, who asked not to
be identified, said he wanted to cancel his contract immediately
but couldn't because a penalty clause would have kicked in. The
caller said other cellular phone companies allow you to opt out
with no penalty if the company changes terms of the contract.
</P>
<P>
   Cellular One, a subsidiary of SBC Communications of San Antonio,
defended the 15-second billing approach last week by saying its
network is utilized whenever a call is initiated. Because Cellular
One bills in one-minute increments, the 15-second policy would have
meant calls that ring longer would have carried at least a
one-minute charge, from 10 cents to 52 cents, depending on the
customer's calling plan. If the caller had free minutes, they would
start being deducted after 15 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   SBC operates cellular firms under various names in many parts of
the United States, including much of Texas, Connecticut,
Washington, D.C., and Chicago. But SBC chose to move to 15-second
billing only in the Boston market, which stretches from southern
New Hampshire to Rhode Island. It declined to say why.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen A. Greyser, a marketing and communications professor at
Harvard Business School, said the company's change of heart will
probably minimize the damage. ``I would characterize their initial
decision as an unwise, arguably stupid, decision,'' Greyser said.
``Rescinding it is better than making the original decision and
sticking with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lowenstein, senior vice president at the Yankee Group
consulting firm in Boston, said he was astounded Cellular One was
moving to charge customers for calls after 15 seconds when the
trend in the industry is to give away more for less.
</P>
<P>
   John Palmer, executive director of marketing for Bell Atlantic
Mobile, said he suspected that rival Cellular One must have heard a
lot of static from its customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In today's hypercompetitive wireless industry, no one has to
tolerate any type of unnecessary charge that they think is
unfair,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
