<SLUG> BC-SOUTHPARK-RATING-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SOUTH PARK' CREATORS FOUGHT FOR R RATING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The makers of the ``South Park'' movie don't deny
that the outrageous cartoon comedy deserves its R rating. They do
say, however, that the battles to bring the foul-mouthed little
film to the screen didn't have to be so, well, animated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't call them skirmishes. It was more a constant
battle,'' said Trey Parker, who with partner Matt Stone created the
``South Park'' series on Comedy Central and made the new movie,
``South Park: Bigger, Longer &AMP; Uncut.''
</P>
<P>
   It took months of negotiations between the film's creators and
the Motion Picture Association of America (MPAA) before the movie
ratings board granted ``South Park'' an R, meaning anyone under 17
must be accompanied by a parent or guardian.
</P>
<P>
   The board had initially insisted on the NC-17 rating, which
means no one under 17 may be admitted.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would've been the kiss of death, and we knew it,'' Parker
said. ``We got a series of notes describing what the MPAA objected
to. And it started with this certain scene we couldn't believe they
wanted us to cut. So, just because we were angry and just because
we could, we made it 10 times worse and five times longer and
resubmitted it to make them watch it again.
</P>
<P>
   ``And they came back going, `OK, that's better.' We learned
every time they told us to take something out, we'd replace it with
something much, much worse and much funnier.''
</P>
<P>
   The filmmakers said the MPAA first annoyed them by giving
``Orgazmo'' _ their comedy about porno films _ an NC-17, the mark
of death commercially.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that time, we didn't have a studio behind us, and there
wasn't anything we could do,'' says Parker, who dubbed ``Bigger,
Longer &AMP; Uncut'' much edgier than their earlier film. ``I mean, the
board didn't even give us notes telling us what they objected to.''
</P>
<P>
   But the $20 million ``South Park'' movie had Paramount Pictures
muscle behind it, and this time the filmmakers got notes _ lots of
them.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't cartoon violence but sexual content that upset the
board. For example, at one point in the process, the MPAA
complained of a scene where ``South Park's'' cartoon kids surf for
porn on the Internet and come across a particularly nasty Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, we took that out and had them find something far worse,''
Parker, 29, explained. ``The board accidentally made the film
better. But my goal in life is to take that thing (the MPAA) down,
because it's so arbitrary and wrong. They target bad language but
don't care about violence.''
</P>
<P>
   MPAA president Jack Valenti defended the board from assertions
that it cares more about screen sex than violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to generate publicity for your movie, what do you
do? You trash the ratings system,'' Valenti told The New York
Times. ``The ratings are not designed to please motion picture
studios or producers or raters. They're designed to give advance
cautionary warnings to parents. And that's the only audience we
care about.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Parker and Stone _ who had final cut _ say some of the
jokes the MPAA ruled too dirty for the multiplex have been recycled
for TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``The movie board is more strict than the TV people,'' Stone,
27, said. ``But it wasn't like we started out with `Who can we
offend, and how can we do it?' It's a musical _ an R-rated,
animated musical.''
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, ``South Park: Bigger, Longer &AMP; Uncut'' mirrors
current events. In a pivotal scene, the animated tykes sneak into
an R-rated movie, go home and begin repeating all the filthy
language they've heard in the film, sparking a political firestorm
that eventually leads to war with Canada.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, one of the kids is implanted with a ``V-chip''
that gives him an electronic shock every time he utters a bad word.
Ironically, the movie opens today, one day before new TV sets go on
sale equipped with a parent-comforting V-chip designed to block
objectionable programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``South Park's'' creators acknowledge many of their most loyal
fans are under 18 and admit some of those youngsters will see the
80-minute film regardless of the rating and despite the promises of
theater chains to check identification when selling tickets to
teens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our fans will see it one way or the other, and I hope other
people will, too,'' Stone said.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Kay Bergman, the voice of Mrs. Cartman, Sheila Broflovski
and Mrs. McCormick in ``South Park: Bigger, Longer &AMP; Uncut,'' says
the film clearly deserves its R rating.
</P>
<P>
   ``I dearly hope parents are going to be cautious about this film
and not bring young children to see it, because it's very raw, and
we do a lot of things that we can't do on TV,'' she said. ``People
don't always understand that `South Park' is not for kids just
because it's animated and children are the main characters. It's
designed for an older audience. That's why it's on TV late at
night, as it should be.''
</P>
<P>
   For their part, Parker and Stone insist the message of the
comedy is ``question authority'' while pointing out there's
probably worse language heard in most high school cafeterias than
in their film.
</P>
<P>
   ``Still, we're expecting controversy,'' Parker said. ``We wrote
the script a year ago, and it's just ironic that the spotlight has
been on some of these issues. If anything, it makes the film more
poignant.''
</P>
<P>
   The Columbine High School slayings in Littleton, Colo., hit
Parker and Stone close to home, since Stone grew up in the state,
and Parker was born there. Stone's parents still live in Littleton,
and the filmmaker says he took his SAT's in the high school's
cafeteria.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could have happened anywhere,'' he said. ``We were as
shocked and saddened as everyone else about what happened.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-99 1937EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
