u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TURKEY-OCALAN-525(2TA     06-29 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-OCALAN-525(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REBEL KURDISH LEADER SENTENCED TO DIE BY TURKISH COURT 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ A Turkish security court on Tuesday sentenced
the Kurdish rebel leader, Abdullah Ocalan, to death for his 15-year
campaign against the Turkish army.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the violence that followed Ocalan's arrest in
February, the sentence set off concerns for security around the
country and beyond. But there were no reports of violent reaction
either in Turkey, where the police were on high alert, or
elsewhere. Kurds staged peaceful protests in Bonn, Moscow, the
Hague, Paris and other European cities. Others scuffled with police
in Rome and Nicosia, Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign governments, including the United States, appealed for
calm and urged Turkey not to carry out the sentence. Ocalan's rebel
group said it had no plans to order retaliation for the verdict
because the Turkish state ``still has the power to amend this.''
The Kurds in southeast Turkey began their armed struggle for an
independent state 15 years ago, rebelling against Turkey's attempts
to suppress their language and culture. Both sides have been
accused of atrocities during the war.
</P>
<P>
   The chief of the three-judge panel that pronounced the sentence,
Turgut Okyay, said Ocalan's fighters had ``murdered thousands of
innocent people, among them babies, children, women and the
elderly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ocalan and the organization he ruled carried out terrorist
actions aimed at dividing the state,'' Okyay said. ``His activities
constitute a serious, immediate and great danger to the country.''
</P>
<P>
   During his trial on the prison island of Imrali, Ocalan
confessed his responsibility for killings but said he had changed
his views and was now ready to make peace. He said that if his life
is spared and the government grants greater cultural freedom to
Kurds, he would ask his followers to give up their guerrilla
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But he also warned that if he is hanged the conflict would grow.
He said 5,000 of his followers were ready to stage suicide attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not accept this charge of treason,'' he said in a brief
statement before the sentencing. ``I believe I have struggled for
the unity of this land and for a free life.''
</P>
<P>
   Ocalan, 50, showed no reaction as he was sentenced. Relatives of
Turkish war victims who were in the courtroom, together with their
lawyers, whooped for joy and began singing the national anthem.
Ocalan rose to his feet, smiled wanly, shambled out of the glass
booth in which he has been seated throughout the trial and left the
courtroom through an adjacent door.
</P>
<P>
   Conviction of treason carries a mandatory death sentence in
Turkey, so the verdict was widely expected. A long appeals process
may lie ahead.
</P>
<P>
   The case will automatically go to a higher court for review, and
if the sentence is upheld there, both Parliament and President
Suleyman Demirel must approve it if it is to be carried out.
Military commanders may be able to influence the final decision.
</P>
<P>
   Ocalan is also expected to appeal to the European Court of Human
Rights, whose jurisdiction Turkey has accepted in the past. Such
appeals can take a year or longer.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The political wing of Ocalan's party, the Kurdistan Workers
Party, or PKK, issued a statement in Vienna after the verdict
saying that party leaders would ``look at this new development from
all sides, discuss it, and then implement the strategy and actions
as soon as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The PKK has regarded this process as illegitimate from the
beginning,'' the statement said. ``With this ruling, the Turkish
side has ignored the call by the Kurdish side for a peaceful
settlement of the war and an end to the bloodshed.''
</P>
<P>
   Turkish leaders say that the PKK has served as a tool for
foreign powers seeking to divide Turkey. They have repeatedly
refused to consider its cease-fire proposals.
</P>
<P>
   In southeastern Turkey, however, many Kurds openly express
admiration for Ocalan and his movement. They complain about their
region's low level of economic development and what they perceive
as the government's refusal to recognize their ethnic rights. These
sentiments helped Ocalan's build his movement into one of the
world's most potent guerrilla forces.
</P>
<P>
   They have achieved some victories. When the Kurds took up arms
against the Turks, their language was banned on the streets, their
music was not allowed to be played and Kurdish-language education
was forbidden. Today, Kurdish conversation and music can be heard
but the language is still not taught.
</P>
<P>
   During his trial Ocalan acknowledged that his fighters have
carried out all the attacks they were accused of and described some
of their activities as ``the mistakes of people with a peasant
mentality.''
</P>
<P>
   Foreign governments and human rights advocates say that Turkish
security forces have burned several thousand villages, tortured
Kurds in detention centers, and supported death squads that killed
many suspected Kurdish nationalists.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of last year, Demirel said that since the armed
conflict began in 1984, it had cost the lives of 5,302 civilians,
5,555 soldiers and security officers, and 23,638 PKK members.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
