<HEADLINE>
BOSTON FINANCIER, EVERCORE BUY INSERT FIRM FOR $1.9B 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Boston financier Thomas H. Lee and Evercore Capital Partners
announced Tuesday a $1.9 billion buyout of the nation's largest
printer of newspaper advertising inserts, New York-based Big Flower
Holdings Inc. Lee will reportedly take 60 percent of the company.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street uncertainty about the deal led Big Flower shares to
plunge nearly 4 points to 31 9/16. Standard &AMP; Poor's indicated it
might slash Big Flower's credit ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Big Flower was founded in 1992 by current chairman Theodore
Ammon, a former Kohlberg Kravis Roberts takeover specialist. It
provides what it calls highly targeted advertising and promotional
products and services to 3,000 customers, such as newspaper inserts
aimed at high-income communities and direct mail campaigns. It
reported revenue of $1.8 billion for the year ended March 31.
</P>
<P>
   Terms of the deal were not disclosed. Bloomberg Business News,
citing a person familiar with the transaction, said when the deal
is complete, Thomas H. Lee Co. will own about 60 percent of the
company and Evercore 15 percent. The deal includes $900 million to
buy outstanding stock and assumption and refinancing of $955
million in debt, Bloomberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Under proposed terms, Big Flower shareholders would get $30 cash
per share and $5.25 worth of preferred stock accruing 10 percent
annual dividends. Ammon's management team will continue to run the
company and own a substantial fraction of shares.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas H. Lee Co., which manages $5 billion, said Big Flower has
``an outstanding management team and great market positions'' with
big growth potential.
</P>
<P>
   The deal needs shareholder approval at a meeting set for
September or October. Tuesday's annual meeting was canceled.
</P>
<P>
   Lee's recent deals include taking large stakes in Patriot
American Hospitality Inc., Eye Care Centers of America, battery
maker Rayovac, Safelite Glass, Fisher Scientific International, and
Experian Information Solutions. Evercore is headed by former US
deputy treasury secretary Roger Altman. Last month it paid $850
million for the publisher of the National Enquirer and Star
supermarket tabloids.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 1.4 million shares of Big Flower changed hands in New
York Stock Exchange trading Tuesday, six times recent daily volume.
Big Flower announced in April it was considering a sale or other
strategic transaction.
</P>
<P>
   The deal led rating agency Standard &AMP; Poor's to put several Big
Flower corporate credit ratings on ``credit watch with negative
implications.'' More information about the structure and rationale
for the deal is expected in Securities and Exchange Commission
filings this week.
</P>
<P>
   Chase Securities, Deutsche Bank, Bank of America and Bear,
Stearns &AMP; Co. are committing financing for the deal, Big Flower
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-99 1937EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990629.0262 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3687 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TURKEY-OCALAN-2NDTAKE     06-29 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-OCALAN-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 ISTANBUL: PKK members.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the days after Ocalan's capture last February in Kenya, where
he had been living under the protection of Greek diplomats, Kurds
in Turkey and in many European cities erupted in violent anger.
After the death sentence was pronounced on Tuesday, Germany's
interior minister, Otto Schily, urged the 2 million Kurds living
there to ``remain calm and not to get swept up in ill-conceived
actions.''
</P>
<P>
   Comments by American officials reflected a combination sympathy
for the Turks and concern about their treatment of Ocalan. The
White House spokesman, Joe Lockhart, called Ocalan ``an
international terrorist who should be brought to justice.''
</P>
<P>
   James P. Rubin, the State Department spokesman, said the United
States was concerned about ``the initial nine days of incommunicado
detention imposed on Mr. Ocalan and the limited access of Ocalan's
lawyers to private consultations with their client and to written
material included in the prosecution case.''
</P>
<P>
   European governments strongly urged that the death sentence not
be carried out. Prime Minister Massimo d'Alema of Italy, which
denied Ocalan asylum, warned Turkey against ``distancing itself
from Europe'' and said: ``One cannot even think of carrying out
this sentence.'' President Vaclav Havel of the Czech Republic also
said he opposed executing Ocalan.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Russian Foreign Ministry said avoiding
execution would show Turkey's adherence to ``high principles of
humanity.'' A French government spokeswoman said a commutation
``would be in keeping with Turkey's European calling.''
</P>
<P>
   The Council of Europe, which is dedicated to promoting democracy
and human rights on the continent, said none of its 41 member
states had executed a prisoner in the last two years, and called
upon Turkey, which is a member, to extend the unofficial moratorium
on executions that has been in force here since 1984.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now there seem to be real opportunities to bring an end to the
terrorist actions in the southeast part of Turkey and to establish
peace,'' the council said in a statement. ``These opportunities
must not be missed.''
</P>
<P>
   The council said Ocalan had been given a fair trial, but the
private human rights group Amnesty International disagreed, saying
the trial ``violated both national law and international
standards.'' The chief human rights officer of the United Nations,
Mary Robinson, said ``lack of due process'' made the verdict
``particularly disquieting.''
</P>
<P>
   Public opinion in Turkey still seems heavily favorable to
carrying out the death sentence. It is shaped in part by relatives
of Turkish war victims, hundreds of whom cheered wildly and hugged
each other on the docks of Mudanya, near Ocalan's island prison,
when the verdict was announced.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit opposes the death penalty on
principle, but his main coalition partner, Devlet Bahceli, whose
party includes many militant nationalists, has said he will do all
he can to assure Ocalan's execution.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days various intellectuals, including some close to
the government, have been urging that Ocalan's life be spared. A
former Turkish ambassador to the United States, Sukru Elekdag, said
Turkey should use this ``historic opportunity'' to end the war by
commuting the death sentence and recognizing ``Kurdish identity.''
</P>
<P>
   One prominent newspaper columnist wrote: ``Let us not hang him
because he will then be a symbol; because Turkey will then be
isolated; because a democratic country does not act with vengeance;
because terror will then never end; and because Turkey, to remain
part of the democratic world, must realize that Kurds are living on
their soil and respect their demand to protect their identity.''
</P>
<P>
   But Yilidrim Akbulut, the speaker of the Parliament, reflected
what may be the view of many government leaders. ``This was
definitely the necessary punishment,'' Akbulut told reporters soon
after the verdict was announced. ``Those who practice terror must
pay the price.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
