<HEADLINE>
GILLETTE SUES RIVAL OVER RAZOR PATENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Gillette Co. is suing a small rival for infringing on
its patents used to make its Mach3 razor, less than a week after an
inventor and a local engineering firm made similar claims against
Gillette.
</P>
<P>
   Four days after claiming that lawsuit was baseless, Gillette
disclosed Tuesday it filed a federal lawsuit of its own three weeks
ago against American Safety Razor Co. of Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   ASR, as the company is known, asserted that Gillette's suit is
without merit.
</P>
<P>
   If Gillette can successfully persuade the court that ASR's new
three-bladed Tri-Flexxx infringes on some of its Mach3 patents, ASR
might have to pull the Tri-Flexxx off the market and redesign it,
Gillette said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are surprised that Gillette would sue us over these
matters,'' countered ASR president Jim Murphy. ``ASR strongly
believes that the products cited in Gillette's filing do not
infringe on the intellectual property rights of Gillette.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides infringing on its patents, Gillette's lawsuit asserts
that ASR has made misleading comparisons to the Mach3 in its
Tri-Flexxx advertising and that the packaging of Tri-Flexxx is so
similar to Mach3's as to confuse consumers.
</P>
<P>
   When it debuted last year, Mach3 was billed as the world's first
three-bladed razor; Gillette said it has invested more than $1
billion in Mach3's development and marketing launch.
</P>
<P>
   Tri-Flexxx seems poised to be positioned as a low-cost
alternative to Mach3. A four-pack of Mach3 razor cartridges has a
suggested retail price of about $6.50.
</P>
<P>
   ASR makes razors retailers such as Wal-Mart Stores Inc. sell
under their own brand names. Retailers set their own prices, which
are lower than those of the national brands.
</P>
<P>
   Given the difficulties Gillette has faced in selling its
products in such ailing economies as Russia and Brazil, sustaining
Mach3's early success is vital.
</P>
<P>
   ASR would seem like a gnat nipping at Gillette. ASR had $297
million in 1998 sales. Gillette razor sales were $3.03 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``ASR has not been able to garner a 1 percent share of the
worldwide blade market, but still we must defend our intellectual
property rights,'' said Gillette spokesman Eric Kraus. ``If we
don't, any competitor could violate them.''
</P>
<P>
   Because it is the ``market leader'' in many product categories,
Gillette has often been a target of rivals who seek to improperly
copy its success, or of rivals who use their ads to disparage
Gillette products, Kraus said; in many cases, Gillette responds to
such challenges with ``aggressive'' legal action.
</P>
<P>
   This is the fourth time in two decades Gillette has taken legal
action against ASR; the earlier cases were resolved in Gillette's
favor, according to Kraus.
</P>
<P>
   In unrelated news, Gillette said it recently informed the 263
employees who work at its Duracell World Technology Center in
Needham, a Boston suburb, that most will be offered transfers to
Duracell's divisional headquarters in Bethel, Conn. Plans call for
the transfers to take place 9 to 12 months from now.
</P>
<P>
   Some Gillette employees now working in Gillette's Boston plant
will later be transferred to Needham, as will some workers at a
Maryland facility slated to close.
</P>
<P>
   The moves are part of a reorganization plan announced last fall
that envisioned cutting 4,700 jobs, or about 11 percent of
Gillette's worldwide work force, over an 18-month period.
</P>
<P>
   Not all those offered transfers to or from Needham may take
them. As a result, Gillette declined to say what the Needham head
count might be after transfers are completed next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-99 1939EDT &QL; 
