<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUNDRAISING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH IN FUND-RAISING LEAD AS BRADLEY KEEPS UP WITH GORE
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By DON VAN NATTA Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush has accumulated at least
$20 million in just four months, raising more money, more quickly,
than any presidential candidate in history. But the most surprising
early windfall has gone to former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey,
who has raised more than $11 million to close the money gap with
Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Buoyed by three days of receptions in California this week that
will net $4.2 million, Bush has amassed more money than all his
Republican opponents combined. Bush's early success, another sign
of how expensive the 2000 election will be, also establishes him as
the leader in the money race over Gore, the front-runner for the
Democratic nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Since April 1, Bush outraised Gore by nearly a 2-1 ratio. By the
close of the second quarter on June 30, Gore will have raised
between $18.2 million and $18.5 million this year, his aides said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that our success in these first two quarters
demonstrates the broad and strong support the vice president enjoys
across the country,'' said Marla Romash, deputy chairman of the
Gore campaign.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Bradley, the only Democrat challenging Gore,
has raised enough money to have the resources to remain the
alternative to the vice president through many of the early
primaries in 2000, aides said Tuesday. Bradley had a strong second
quarter, raising about $7 million in the last three months and more
than $11 million this year, supporters said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of interest in his candidacy,'' said Eric
Hauser, a spokesman for Bradley's campaign, ``and a lot of people
from different backgrounds have made it clear they want to be
supportive.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Bradley's surprise showing, Ms. Romash, the Gore deputy
chairman, said: ``I would suggest that there is a more valuable
comparison to be made in terms of how much support each candidate
is getting in voters. Democrats are supporting Al Gore, in some
polls, by a 3-to-1 margin.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the presidential election is more than 16 months away,
the current dash for checks of $1,000 or less is even more
important this year because most of the important primaries will
occur in the first few months of 2000. Because the first straw
ballot will not occur until August in Iowa, party leaders closely
scrutinize the fund-raising totals as evidence of each candidate's
ability to attract support and meet the high costs of running a
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the candidates intend to release their second-quarter
totals on Wednesday, but they do not have to file their quarterly
reports with the Federal Election Commission until July 15. Some
campaigns were putting out low estimates about their fund-raising
totals so far, hoping, like corporations' modest quarterly profit
estimates, that the actual numbers will be seen as having exceeded
expectations. For example, aides to Bush would say only that he had
raised ``at least $20 million,'' even though several supporters
said privately that the campaign had raised substantially more than
that.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the final tally, Bush's record-shattering pace is
remarkable because he did not personally begin to raise money until
June 12 in Iowa, about two weeks after the Texas legislative
session ended and midway through the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one expected that we would do this well,'' said Dave
Beckweth, a spokesman for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Bush's success is due to the prowess of a fund-raising
clique named ``the Pioneers,'' a group of more than 150 Republicans
who pledged to raise $100,000 each. On Monday, in Austin, a
thank-you reception was held for 90 Pioneers who have already met
their goal. In Texas alone, the Bush campaign has raised $11
million, one supporter said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's fund-raising skill has hampered the ability of most other
Republican contenders to raise money. Most candidates have reduced
their expectations, hoping now to merely outraise the rest of the
field.
</P>
<P>
   Of the remaining candidates, Sen. John McCain of Arizona
finished second in the money race among Republicans with a total of
$4.1 million. McCain raised $2.5 million in this quarter, aides
said. McCain also transferred $2 million from his Senate campaign
treasury to his presidential effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``Outside of Bush, we have raised nearly double what anyone else
has raised,'' said Howard Opinsky, the spokesman for McCain. ``We
continue to meet our fund-raising expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dole, the former American Red Cross president, has had
a disappointing start, but she raised $2 million in the second
quarter, her supporters said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are having a respectable second quarter and we expect to be
competitive with the rest of the pack,'' said Ari Fleischer, a
spokesman for the Dole campaign. ``While other candidates are at
risk of taking their last gasps of air, we're going to find an
auxiliary oxygen tank.''
</P>
<P>
   The publisher Steve Forbes had his best fund-raising quarter
ever in the last three months. Forbes, who spent $37.5 million of
his own money in 1996, is expected to raise a total of $2.5 million
in the second quarter, his supporters said. Forbes had a
fund-raising dinner in Manhattan that raised $1.2 million alone,
his aides said.
</P>
<P>
   Former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander, who had to make cutbacks
in staff to meet payroll, has raised about $2.2 million this year.
``We've reorganized our campaign,'' said Bryan Kennedy, Alexander's
political director. ``We're meeting our financial goals. We're
meeting our political goals. And we'll have enough money to be
fully competitive in the early states.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Vice President Dan Quayle raised approximately $1 million
in the second quarter, giving him a total of about $3 million for
the year. But that result is disappointing; Quayle's supporters had
predicted in February that he would raise $3 million by April 1.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
