<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-BRADLEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY TROLLS FOR DEMOCRATIC SUPPORT IN NEW HAMPSHRIE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILL ZUCKMAN AND TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.H. _ Reminiscing about piano lessons, the French horn
and trumpet playing, Bill Bradley brought his unconventional
campaign for president here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, he also picked up an endorsement from Mark
Fernald, one of the 13 Democratic state senators, and from 13 of
the 154 Democratic House members. (Vice President Al Gore, by
contrast, has been endorsed by 10 Democratic senators and a
majority of the House Democratic caucus supports him.) Later, at a
dinner in Boston Tuesday night, Bradley raised about $200,000.
</P>
<P>
   As he seeks the nation's highest office, the former New Jersey
senator and New York Knicks basketball player is visiting people
and groups that he says do good work, listening to their stories,
and telling a few of his own. He says he won't begin issuing policy
proposals until the fall.
</P>
<P>
   At the Concord Community Music School, Bradley almost forgot to
tell the room full of activists that he was running for president.
Instead, he seemed to get lost remembering the days when his mother
forced him to take piano lessons in the third, fourth, and fifth
grades.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother insisted on it,'' he said. But one Christmas,
Bradley said, there was an envelope under the tree. In it, his
mother wrote him a note. ``It said, you no longer have to take
piano,'' said Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Bradley said he now has a fantasy of taking up the
piano again when he is 78, ``or maybe a little older.'' He said
that after a couple years of practice, he would like to open a
piano bar and play for customers.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said he also used to play the trumpet, until the band
leader urged him to switch to the French horn because there were
too many trumpet players in the band.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just here today to salute the music school for everything
you do,'' Bradley said. ``By the way, I'm running for president of
the United States. That's why I'm here.''
</P>
<P>
   In response to a question from the audience, Bradley said that
if elected, he would increase funding for the National Endowment
for the Arts to support music schools and other artistic endeavors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Creativity lifts the human spirit and let's it soar,'' Bradley
said. ``More people ought to have that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
