<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON   Editors note: The San Francisco Chronicle rounds up the best of
the unusual for home and garden in this regular feature, Off the
Wall. 
 
 
 OFF THE WALL: Old Glory Gets New Treatment in the Bathroom  
   
 By Terry Nagel  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Betsy Ross never dreamed her patriotic sewing
project would wind up like this: A German company has embedded the
American flag pattern in a glass sink.
<TEXT>
<P>
   In honor of the opening of its first U.S. store, AquaDreams has
introduced the ``Stars and Stripes'' sink, retailing for $13,000 _
``$1,000 per colony!'' the press release says.
</P>
<P>
   The shimmering red, white and blud sink was created at the
company's German workshop using glass fusion. During the process,
metal oxides creating the pattern are infused into glass under
intense heat.
</P>
<P>
   Aqua Dreams offers other glass-fusion sinks, including a $4,000
small ``Tiger Eye'' sink with brownish sparkles and little pearls
to a $16,000 double sink called ``Wasserschatzi'' (``water
treasure'' in German) that mingles colors of the Caribbean Sea.
</P>
<P>
   The sink designers also fuse flower designs, rainbows and
corporate logos into basins. They work with more than 30 jewel
tones.
</P>
<P>
   With talk lately of amending the U.S. Constitution to protect
the flag, does it dishonor Old Glory to mold its likeness into a
sink?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not at all,'' says Nadia Soncksen, U.S. manager of AquaDreams.
She recalls thousands of designers and customers walked by the sink
at a trade show in Las Vegas and ``they thought it was so original
and beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   As the ultimate test, she adds, ``even some Republicans liked
it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
WHERE TO FIND IT
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AquaDreams Ltd. &LR; , 8606-A Melrose Ave., Los Angeles, Calif.
90069; toll-free (877) 818-9000. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
