<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOTSTUFF-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 Editors note: Psst! Read the latest? If not, you haven't
read  HotStuff, the San Francisco Chronicle's weekly roundup of
great 
 new home-and-garden items and places to visit. This week, we'll 
 tell you where to get a special prayer fountain and unusual 
 ceramics from Italy.   Handmade Prayer Fountains Send a Wish for Kindness  
   
 OAKLAND, Calif. _  Maura Singer Williams was director of an AIDS
hospice in San Francisco two years ago when the budget was slashed,
eliminating a fountain that was planned for the new courtyard.
Since she was an experienced sculptor, she says, ``I thought I
would make one for them.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   She created a fountain that helps others appreciate the practice
of Buddhist mindfulness, using water the way that Tibetan prayer
flags use wind.
</P>
<P>
   A prayer of loving kindness is inscribed on a spiral of copper
tubing; as water comes out the end of the tube, it hugs the bottom
of the spiral and flows back down into a rock-filled bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The fountain was such a hit that Singer Williams teamed up with
a friend, Amy Hutto, to make smaller versions suitable for homes.
Their Oakland-based company, Egg Universe, offers 15-inch-high
fountains made out of cast concrete in earth tones of antique amber
and fern green. Custom colors also are available. The fountains
cost $360 each and can go indoors or outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   The prayer printed on the copper spiral was derived from
Buddhist teachings. It says, ``May all beings be well and happy.
May all beings be harmonious and peaceful. May all have the light,
the way out of suffering, the way home. May we each share our
bright, wondrous nature for the benefit of all beings.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea, says Singer Williams, is ``to generate a loving
kindness prayer within your own heart, then send that out to
others.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Egg Universe, Oakland; (510) 652-5213. Web site: &LR; 
www.egguniverse.com
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_ Terry Nagel
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; San Francisco Store Sells Unusual Ceramics From Italy &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; Many travelers find themselves overwhelmed by the
beautiful ceramics they encounter in Italy, and end up shipping
home caseloads of vibrantly colored plates and pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   But with new stores specializing in Italian ceramics opening in
the Bay Area, it's no longer necessary to go abroad for the pieces
you once looked at longingly in Siena or Urbino.
</P>
<P>
   One such store is Pesaresi Ceramics, which opens July 2 in San
Francisco's Crocker Galleria. The store features ceramics from four
regions of Italy: Tuscany, Marche, Umbria and Sicily. Among the
items you'll find are wrought-iron garden furniture with tile tops,
urns painted with pastoral scenes, and tableware in modern
geometric and fruit patterns.
</P>
<P>
   Prices range from $20 for a mug to $8,000 for a  &LR; vaso di &LR; 
 &LR; farmacia, &LR;  a large decorative canister that was once used to store
medicine in pharmacies. A snake-handled vase, made in the 1880s by
Molaroni in Pesaro, Italy, is an example of the type of merchandise
available at Pesaresi Ceramics.
</P>
<P>
   Store owner Alessandra Taboni hails from Marche, a region known
for artistic ceramics since the Renaissance. Some of the store's
best pieces come from Castel Durante, near Taboni's hometown of
Pesaro, and boast a prestigious DOC  &LR; (denominizioni &LR;   &LR; d'origine
controllata) &LR;  label. This designation is awarded by the Italian
government to certify that products are made in a particular area
and in the time-honored tradition.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Pesaresi Ceramics, Crocker Galleria, 50 Post St. (near &LR; 
 &LR; Montgomery Street), San Francisco; (415) 362-4570. Open from 10 &LR; 
 &LR; a.m. to 6 p.m. Monday through Friday and from 10 a.m. to 5 p.m. &LR; 
 &LR; Saturday. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_ Tara Duggan
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 1 of HOT STUF (99938 ) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
