<HEADER>
A3708 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEARN-TOMATO-SFCHRON &LR;      06-29 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEARN-TOMATO-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Every other week, The Chronicle features ``Learning
to Cook'' by Marion Cunningham, a cooking teacher and cookbook
author best known for her revisions of the Fannie Farmer cookbooks.
This column is intended for novices in the kitchen.    LEARNING TO COOK: Tomatoes Make Life Simple  
   
 By Marion Cunningham 
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Spaghetti with fresh tomato sauce is one of those
easy-to-make dishes that is always welcome for dinner. And the
sauce couldn't be easier than when the tomatoes bake in the oven.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Baking brings out the sweetness in the tomatoes, and enhances
their flavor even when they're not at their prime. The tomatoes get
extra appeal with the flavors of parsley, garlic and olive oil, the
classic Italian seasoning trio.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, when they're in the oven, the tomatoes cook unattended;
you don't need to be hovering with wooden spoon in hand. Use the
time instead to prepare a simple salad to serve alongside.
</P>
<P>
   My Italian aunt used to finish a simple spaghetti supper with a
chilled glass of cocoa topped with a scoop of vanilla ice cream. If
you feel lazy and don't want to heat up your kitchen, serve Aunt
Frances' Cocoa Dessert.
</P>
<P>
   Bay Area cooking teacher, is the author of ``Learning to Cook,''
``Cooking With Children,'' ``The Fannie Farmer Cookbook'' and ``The
Breakfast Book,'' among others.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR; MARIETTA'S SPAGHETTI
</P>
<P>
   Note: From ``Learning to Cook With Marion Cunningham'' (Knopf,
1999).
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   12 Roma or plum tomatoes (about 13/4 pounds)
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   3 garlic cloves
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch parsley
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 pound dried spaghetti
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch fresh basil
</P>
<P>
   Instructions: Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Preparing the tomatoes:  &LR; Cut the tomatoes in half lengthwise
and place them cut side up in a 9 x 13-inch baking dish. Season
lightly with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Preparing the garlic, parsley and olive oil:  &LR; Peel and finely
chop the garlic.
</P>
<P>
   Wash the parsley and pat dry; remove and discard the stems.
Finely chop the leaves and set aside 1/2 cup. Put any remaining
parsley in a covered dish and place in the refrigerator for later
use.
</P>
<P>
   Mix together the garlic, half of the parsley and 2 tablespoons
of the olive oil in a small bowl. Using a spoon or your fingers,
pat the garlic mixture on the tomatoes and drizzle on 2 tablespoons
olive oil.
</P>
<P>
   Bake uncovered for 45 minutes. The tomatoes should be mushy; if
not, bake for another 10 minutes and test again.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Cooking the spaghetti:  &LR; About 20 minutes before the tomatoes
are done, pour about 4 quarts of water into a 6-quart pot. Stir in
the 1 tablespoon salt and bring to a boil over high heat. When the
water reaches a full boil, add the spaghetti and stir. After about
12 minutes, start testing the strands of pasta every minute or so
until the spaghetti feels tender but still firm.
</P>
<P>
   Dump the water and the noodles into a colander set in the sink.
Let the spaghetti drain.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Finishing the pasta:  &LR; Melt the butter in a small pot over
medium heat.
</P>
<P>
   Chop the basil leaves into small pieces (you will need 1/2 cup).
</P>
<P>
   In a large serving bowl, mix together the remaining parsely and
olive oil, the melted butter and the basil. Add the drained
spaghetti and the baked tomatoes. Toss together well and serve
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 756 calories, &LR;   &LR; 17 g protein, 96 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 35 g fat (7 g saturated), 16 mg cholesterol, 71 mg
sodium, 3 g &LR;   &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; AUNT FRANCES' COCOA DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup cocoa
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup hot water
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   4 cups (1 quart) milk
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   Vanilla ice cream
</P>
<P>
   Instructions: &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; Mix the cocoa, sugar, water and salt in a 11/2-quart saucepan. Put
the pan on the stove and turn the heat to medium-low. Don't leave
the stove for any reason until you finish making this. Stir
steadily, but slowly, until the mixture boils. Cook, stirring
constantly, for 2 minutes. Stir in the milk. Cook until the milk is
warm (stick your finger in to test it). When the milk is warm,
remove from heat and add the vanilla.
</P>
<P>
   Let cool, then cover and refrigerate until you are ready to
serve.
</P>
<P>
   Pour into glasses, filling them about 3/4 full, and add a scoop
of vanilla ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   Yields about 1 quart.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER CUP: &LR;   &LR; 263 calories, &LR;   &LR; 9 g protein, 39 g carbohydrate, 9 g &LR; 
 &LR; fat (6 g saturated), 33 mg cholesterol, 255 mg sodium, 1 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-99 1948EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990629.0272 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3710 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SECRET-PORK-SFCHRON &LR;      06-29 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SECRET-PORK-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The Chronicle offers readers the recipe
for an outstanding dish at a Bay Area restaurant, plus the chef's
secrets for making it a success. Tips and recipe follow.   SECRETS OF SUCCESS: Pork Pairs Well With Blue Cheese  
   
 By Michael Bauer  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Most people think of fruit when they think of
pork, but the fact that this pork tenderloin dish doesn't is what
makes it so exciting. The sauce is made with tangy blue cheese,
which actually pairs with the meat to make it all the more sweet.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first time I ran across this dish was at Antica, the
charming neighborhood Italian restaurant at the corner of Polk and
Union streets.
</P>
<P>
   At Antica, chef Ruggero Gadaldi has created a menu that reads
like the offerings of most other Italian restaurants but tastes
worlds apart. His lamb shanks are some of the best in the city. And
one of the best desserts is the Coppa Antica, a blend of pastry
cream, whipped cream and crisp meringue.
</P>
<P>
   While the restaurant is small, it's developed a Bay Area
following because of its food, first-rate service and charming
interior that features warm wood accents and an ebony stained
floor.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Antica Trattoria, 2400 Polk St. (at Union Street), San &LR; 
 &LR; Francisco; (415) 928-5797. Open for dinner Tuesday- &LR;   &LR; Sunday. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
SECRETS OF SUCCESS
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The marinade. &LR;  Allowing the pork to steep in a slightly sweet
marinade intensifies the flavor of the meat, creating a more
dramatic contrast to the tangy blue cheese sauce.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; The blue cheese sauce. &LR;  While most chefs add fruit to pork, this
sauce sets up an electrifying contrast to the sweet marinated meat.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
GRILLED PORK MEDALLIONS WITH BLUE CHEESE &AMP; POLENTA
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; Ingredients: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; The Marinade
</P>
<P>
   1 quart water
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup pickling spices
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup cider vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   1 carrot
</P>
<P>
   1 celery stalk
</P>
<P>
   1/2 onion, peeled and chopped
</P>
<P>
   The Pork
</P>
<P>
   3 whole pork tenderloins, about 1 pound each
</P>
<P>
   6 bamboo skewers
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   The Polenta
</P>
<P>
   6 cups water
</P>
<P>
   11/2 teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups instant cornmeal
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons grated Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   The Garnish
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces pancetta, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon butter
</P>
<P>
   The Sauce
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   3 ounces Blue Castello cheese or Italian Dolcelatte Gorgonzola
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; For the marinade:  &LR; Bring the water to a boil in a large
nonreactive saucepan. Add the sugar, pickling spices, vinegar,
salt, carrot, celery and onion. Simmer for 20 minutes. Remove from
heat and let cool to room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   When marinade is ready, cut each pork tenderloin into 10
medallions. Thread 5 medallions on each skewer. Place the skewers
in a shallow nonreactive container and pour in the marinade. Cover
and refrigerate for at least 4 hours or overnight.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To make the polenta:  &LR; Bring the water and salt to a boil in a
large pot. Add the cornmeal in a slow stream, whisking constantly.
When the water returns to a boil, reduce heat and cook for 5 to 10
minutes, stirring frequently. To finish, stir in the butter and
Parmesan.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The garnish:  &LR; Cut the pancetta slices into small pieces. Melt
the butter in a small pan over low heat. Add the pancetta and saute
until it turns golden brown. Remove to paper towels to drain.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To make the sauce: &LR;  Pour the cream into a small saucepan and
simmer until slightly thickened. Crumble in the cheese, stirring
until it melts. Strain if desired.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To grill the pork:  &LR; Remove the skewers of pork from the
marinade and pat dry. Season with salt and pepper and brush with
olive oil. Grill the pork to medium doneness (or broil for 10
minutes, turning at the halfway point).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To assemble:  &LR; For each serving, place a large spoonful of
polenta to one side of a heated dinner plate. Ladle some of the
sauce on the other half of the plate. Remove the pork medallions
from 1 skewer and arrange over the sauce. Sprinkle pancetta over
the pork and polenta.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 589 calories, &LR;   &LR; 48 g protein, 28 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 30 g fat (14 g saturated), 176 mg cholesterol,
1,100 mg sodium, &LR;   &LR; 2 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
