<HEADLINE>
&HT;       
  
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
Editors Note: Bay Area Classics profiles food-related businesses
more than a half-century old. &HT;     
 BAY AREA CLASSICS: Andronico's Maintains Culture of a Family 
 Business While Business Booms  By Karola Saekel  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; Some memorials are hewn in stone, august and cold.
Others are less forbidding _ redwood trees planted in the memory of
a loved one, songs, endowments to charity.
<P>
   John Andronico's memorial is the grocery company he guided from
the Depression-era, mom-and-pop store founded by his Greek
immigrant parents, Frank and Eva, to the upscale Bay Area grocery
chain that boasts eight dynamic stores.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the expansion, the store most dear to John Andronico was
his parents' original grocery on Solano Avenue in North Berkeley,
where he would walk from nearby Thousand Oaks School as a young
boy. A complete remodel of the that store is just about finished.
</P>
<P>
   Since John Andronico's death in March, his son, Bill, is at the
helm, serving as president and CEO of the privately held company
and overseeing the completion of the ninth store in the chain, set
to open in Danville later this summer. While co-founder Frank has
also passed away, his wife (and Bill's mother), Eva, still chairs
the board.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the business is expanding today, not all previous
expansions were successful. Ventures into Richmond, Alameda and
Oakland in the 1940s were short-lived, and Hayward and Pleasant
Hill stores were eventually sold or leased to other grocery
companies in the '70s and '80s.
</P>
<P>
   The current expansion started when the company acquired and
remodeled two moribund Co-Op stores in Berkeley in the late '80s.
In the same period, the Andronicos put their family name on the
markets, a change from the stores' original name of Park and Shop.
</P>
<P>
   Andronico's hasn't looked back since. Bill Andronico says that
transforming the old Solano Avenue store while simultaneously
completing the Danville store, the company's most ambitious
project, was a lot to tackle at once. Unlike other branches that
moved into existing buildings, the Danville store is being built
from the ground up. But the family decided to give Solano its face
lift in honor of John.
</P>
<P>
   Bill says his dad would be delighted with the very '90s changes
_ an in-store bakery with artisan breads and a sushi station among
them _ and the fact that the changes are being carried out without
closing the store for even a day.
</P>
<P>
   Attention to customers' expectations is the key not only to
survival but to the success of a family-run business such as his,
says the entrepreneurial grocer. His stores' success seemingly
flies in the face of trends. Industry studies, he says, predict
that by the year 2001, 50 percent of America's grocery business
will be handled by just five large chains.
</P>
<P>
   However, there are pockets in the country that buck the trend,
and the Bay Area is one of them. As chains get bigger and more
impersonal, he believes, some consumers will continue to seek out
stores that are not only upscale but are also personal.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how much the business grows, says Andronico, ``We must
never lose sight of our style. We must maintain the culture of a
family business'' _ even if that family has grown from the handful
of clerks who assisted Eva and Frank Andronico in 1929 to 800
employees in 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
