<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The San Francisco Chronicle's panel of
professional tasters tries a different product available in
supermarkets.   TASTER'S CHOICE: Turkey Takes Top Honors Among the Un-Hot Dogs  
   
 By Robin Davis  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  For a Fourth of July barbecue, many people will
throw hot dogs on the grill. Those looking for a healthier
alternative to beef and pork franks turn to poultry hot dogs, most
of which are lower in fat.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today's panel tasted 11 brands of poultry hot dogs, some made
solely of turkey or chicken, others a combination. Some
manufacturers make both a chicken and a turkey hot dog. In one case
the turkey hot dog outscored its same-brand chicken cousin by 10
points, while another manufacturer's two franks differed in score
by only two points.
</P>
<P>
   The hot dogs differed significantly in price and in fat content.
The least expensive was $1.59 for one pound (eight hot dogs) while
the priciest was $3.89 for 12 ounces (six hot dogs). Fat ranged
from five to 12 grams per serving.
</P>
<P>
   Uncured, nitrite-free hot dogs were not popular. None of the
four tasted scored high enough to rate.
</P>
<P>
   Top honors went to &UR; Foster Farms &LR;   &UR; turkey franks  &LR; (one pound,
$2.29 at many supermarkets). Three panelists especially liked the
texture, one describing it as ``best of show.'' Another taster
thought it was a bit salty, but still liked the overall flavor.
Four would buy it; one might.
</P>
<P>
   Second place went to &UR; Safeway jumbo turkey franks  &LR; (one pound,
$1.69). One panelist described the flavor as smoky and ``adult.''
Four would buy it; one might.
</P>
<P>
   Third place was a tie between  &UR; Foster Farms chicken franks  &LR; (one
pound, $2.29 at many supermarkets) and  &UR; Zacky Farms chicken &LR; 
 &UR; franks &LR;  (one pound, $2.19 at Andronico's).
</P>
<P>
   Three panelists thought the Foster Farms chicken frank most
resembled regular beef or pork hot dogs, but two others found the
texture too smooth and soft. Three would buy it; two might.
</P>
<P>
   One panelist described the Zacky Farms chicken frank as an
``awesome balance of flavors,'' but another thought it tasted
overly smoky and disliked the soft texture. Four would buy it; one
would not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Zacky Farms turkey franks &LR;  (one pound, $2.19 at Andronico's)
came in fifth, scoring just two points lower than Zacky Farms
chicken hot dog. Two panelists thought it was too smoky, but two
others liked the balance of flavors. One panelist detected an odd
metallic flavor. Three would buy it; two might.
</P>
<P>
   Jennie-O jumbo turkey franks, Louis Rich original franks,
Diestel uncured turkey franks, Applegate Farms uncured turkey hot
dogs, Rocky uncured chicken hot dogs and Applegate Farms uncured
chicken hot dogs scored too low to rate.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Panelists were Dan Bowe, associate culinary director, Center for
Culinary Development; John P. Carroll, cookbook author; Patricia
Hart, dietitian and consultant; Donna Katzl, chef-owner, Cafe For
All Seasons, San Francisco; and Kirk Webber, chef-owner, Cafe Kati,
San Francisco. All products are tasted blind.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
