r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POTATO-SFCHRON &LR;      06-29 2288
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POTATO-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
Editors Note: Package includes main story and recipes.  Spud Fest '99: Red, white and blue salads get you through the 
 Fourth in style  
   
   
 By Robin Davis 
 &HT;     c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; Potatoes are such humble little things, oddly
shaped, strangely colored. But they star in American cuisine, and
perhaps nowhere more than in potato salad. And let's face it _
potato salad is as much a part of Fourth of July as are fireworks.
<P>
   Even though most food historians believe that the potato salad
originated in Germany, it's potato salad Americans crave on
Independence Day.
</P>
<P>
   But which potato salad? There are almost as many recipes for the
``classic'' version as there are cooks. Some people insist on
mayonnaise-based dressings while others think vinaigrettes work
well. Some home chefs wouldn't dream of using starchy potatoes;
others think these varieties absorb the dressing better. And then
there's the debate as to whether to add the dressing when the
potatoes are hot or cold.
</P>
<P>
   There aren't any ``right'' answers to these questions; it's all
a matter of personal preference. The following recipes are some of
my favorites and use a variety of potatoes, dressings and
techniques. You can create your own signature dishes if you keep
the following in mind:
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; Know the difference between starchy, waxy and new potatoes. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Starchy potatoes, like russets or white rose, will fall apart
more readily. On the other hand, they tend to absorb dressings
better.
</P>
<P>
   Waxy potatoes, like red-skinned or white-skinned, don't fall
apart as easily, but also don't absorb as much dressing.
</P>
<P>
   New potatoes, which are just young potatoes of any variety, are
best suited for potato salads because they're small enough to be
cooked whole and retain their shape after being cooked and cut.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; Know your cooking techniques. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Boiling potatoes in salted water adds some flavor to the spuds,
but tends to turn the skins an anemic gray color. Steaming keeps
some of the color of the skins, but doesn't let the salt get into
the potato during cooking.
</P>
<P>
   Some chefs like to roast potatoes for their salads, but the
flavor of cold roast potatoes can be problematic.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; Choose accompanying ingredients for texture, color and accenting &LR; 
 &UR; flavors.  &LR; Celery is a natural because it adds crunch. But asparagus
also adds a crisp element along with color and a unique flavor.
Consider other ingredients like bell peppers, pickles or cheese.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; Finally, get creative with your dressing. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   If you're using mayonnaise, add a splash of vinegar or citrus
juice to cut the richness, then add herbs or spices like thyme,
rosemary, fresh mint or curry powder.
</P>
<P>
   With vinaigrettes, you can be even more creative with
ingredients like roasted garlic, fresh herbs, citrus juices or
peels.
</P>
<P>
   Whether you follow these recipes, use them as guidelines or make
your own creation, don't pass up this all-American opportunity to
stage your own spud fest this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN RECIPES) &QL; 
 &QL; 
POTATO SALAD WITH ASPARAGUS AND PESTO VINAIGRETTE
</P>
<P>
   Note: This salad is sophisticated enough for a summer dinner
party, but so delicious it's wonderful at a family picnic, too. Try
to serve this one as soon as it's been made because the pesto will
discolor when exposed to air. Alternately, assemble all the parts
and refrigerate separately (press plastic wrap directly onto the
surface of the pesto), then throw them together when you're ready
to serve.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound asparagus, trimmed, cut into 2-inch lengths
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds red-skinned potatoes (about 6 large), cut into
1/2-inch-thick slices
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves, peeled
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup (packed) basil leaves
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup (packed) Italian parsley leaves
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup toasted walnuts
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup freshly grated Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Blanch the asparagus in a large pot of boiling salted water
until bright green and just tender, about 3 minutes. Using a
slotted spoon, transfer the asparagus to a bowl of cold water.
Drain.
</P>
<P>
   Add the potatoes to the boiling water. Return to a boil. Cook
until just tender, about 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, finely chop the garlic in a food processor. Add the
basil, parsley, walnuts and lemon juice and process until finely
chopped. With the processor running, gradually add the oil and
process until mixture is emulsified. Stir in the cheese. Season to
taste with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Drain the potatoes. Run under cold water until cool. Drain well.
</P>
<P>
   Toss the asparagus with 2 tablespoons pesto. Arrange in the
center of a platter. Toss the potatoes with the remaining pesto.
Arrange around the asparagus.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 340 calories, &LR;   &LR; 6 g protein, 31 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 22 g fat (3 g saturated), 3 mg cholesterol, 75 mg sodium, 4 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; HORSERADISH-DILL POTATO SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Note: Use the tiniest red-skinned potatoes you can find for this
salad. If you can only find larger ones, halve or quarter them.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   Dressing
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sour cream
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons creamy horseradish
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon white wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped fresh dill
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Salad
</P>
<P>
   1 pound small white- or yellow-skinned potatoes
</P>
<P>
   1 pound small red-skinned potatoes
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup thinly sliced green onions (white and green parts)
</P>
<P>
   Instructions: &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; For the dressing:  &LR; Whisk together the sour cream, horseradish and
vinegar in a small bowl until smooth. Stir in the dill. Season to
taste with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; For the salad:  &LR; Cook the potatoes in a large pot of boiling
salted water until tender. Drain and cool.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the potatoes, green onions and dressing in a large bowl.
Toss to coat.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 170 calories, &LR;   &LR; 4 g protein, 30 g carbohydrate,
4 &LR;   &LR; g fat (3 g saturated), 9 mg cholesterol, 26 mg sodium, 3 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR; GERMAN-STYLE POTATO SALAD WITH YUKON GOLDS
</P>
<P>
   Note: This vinegary salad should be served warm, and goes
especially well with grilled sausages.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds Yukon Gold potatoes (about 6 medium), cut into 2-inch
pieces
</P>
<P>
   6 bacon slices, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 large red onion, sliced
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons cider vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon dry mustard
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup canned low-salt chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup chopped dill pickles
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Chopped fresh parsley
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Place the potatoes in a large pot of salted water. Bring to a
boil. Cook until tender, about 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, cook the bacon in a heavy large skillet until crisp.
Transfer to paper towels to drain.
</P>
<P>
   Discard all but 3 tablespoons drippings from the skillet. Heat
the drippings over medium-high heat. Add the onion and saute until
tender, about 5 minutes. Carefully add 3 tablespoons vinegar
(mixture may splatter), the mustard and sugar and stir until
mustard dissolves. Add the broth and reduce by half.
</P>
<P>
   Drain the potatoes. Transfer to a large bowl. Sprinkle with the
remaining 1 tablespoon vinegar. Add the pickles, reserved bacon and
warm dressing and gently toss to coat. Season to taste with salt
and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Sprinkle with parsley and serve warm.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 175 calories, &LR;   &LR; 6 g protein, 32 g carbohydrate,
4 &LR;   &LR; g fat (1 g saturated), 5 mg cholesterol, 173 mg sodium, 3 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; CLASSIC AMERICAN POTATO SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Note: Perfect for any Fourth of July gathering, this salad also
may be made up to a day ahead and kept in the refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   3 pounds red-skinned potatoes (about 9 large)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons buttermilk
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon distilled white vinegar
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons chopped fresh parsley
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon celery seed
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup minced sweet onion (such as Vidalia)
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup thinly sliced celery
</P>
<P>
   3 hard-cooked eggs, peeled and chopped
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Cook the potatoes in a large pot of boiling salted water until
just tender. Drain. Cool. Cut into 2-inch pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Whisk the mayonnaise, buttermilk, vinegar, 2 tablespoons of the
parsley, the celery seed and sugar in a small bowl to blend.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer the potatoes to a large bowl; add the onion, celery and
eggs. Add the dressing and toss to coat. Season to taste with salt
and pepper. Sprinkle with the remaining 2 tablespoons parsley.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 365 calories, &LR;   &LR; 9 g protein, 45 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 18 g fat (3 g saturated), 115 mg cholesterol, 172 mg sodium, 5 &LR;   &LR; g
fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; LIGHT AMERICAN POTATO SALAD
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; Note: For those watching their waistlines, this is as delicious as
the classic potato salad, but not quite as high in fat.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   3 pounds red-skinned potatoes (about 9 medium)
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup light mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup nonfat plain yogurt
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons low-fat buttermilk
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon distilled white vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup chopped fresh parsley
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon celery seed
</P>
<P>
   1 cup thinly sliced celery
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup minced sweet onion (such as Vidalia)
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients: &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; Cook the potatoes in a large pot of boiling salted water until
just tender. Drain. Cool. Cut into 2-inch pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Whisk together the mayonnaise, yogurt, buttermilk, vinegar, 2
tablespoons of the parsley and the celery seed.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the potatoes, celery and onion in a large bowl. Add the
dressing and toss to coat. Season with salt and pepper. Sprinkle
with the remaining 2 tablespoons parsley.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 225 calories, &LR;   &LR; 6 g protein, 46 g carbohydrate,
2 &LR;   &LR; g fat (0 saturated), 3 mg cholesterol, 99 mg sodium, 5 g
fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR; CURRIED POTATO SALAD WITH PEAS
</P>
<P>
   Note: This salad, with its Indian notes, is interesting and
colorful. Serve it alongside grilled chicken sandwiches.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 pound unshelled fresh peas
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   3 pounds small white creamer potatoes, quartered
</P>
<P>
   1 cup nonfat plain yogurt
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon white wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon curry powder
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons chopped mint leaves
</P>
<P>
   1 small red onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Instructions: &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; Shell the peas; discard pods. Cook the peas in a small pot of
boiling salted water until tender; it will take from 10 to 30
minutes depending on the maturity of the peas. Drain. Cool.
</P>
<P>
   Steam the potatoes until just tender, about 15 minutes. Cool.
</P>
<P>
   Whisk together the yogurt, vinegar, curry powder and cayenne.
Stir in 2 tablespoons of the mint. Season with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the peas, potatoes and onion in a large bowl. Add the
dressing and toss to coat. Sprinkle with the remaining 1 tablespoon
mint.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 230 calories, &LR;   &LR; 8 g protein, 50 g carbohydrate,
1 &LR;   &LR; g fat (0 saturated), 1 mg cholesterol, 45 mg sodium, 6 g
fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
SWEET POTATO AND SPINACH SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Note: This salad should be served as soon as the dressing goes
on, otherwise the spinach will become limp. But all of the
components _ cooking the potatoes, making the dressing _ may be
done several hours in advance.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds sweet potatoes (about 2 large), peeled, cut into 1-inch
pieces
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons cider vinegar
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   11/2 tablespoons honey
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon mustard seed
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces baby spinach, stemmed
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces smoked ham, cut into 1/2-inch cubes
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Steam the potatoes on a rack in a large pot of boiling water
until tender. Cool.
</P>
<P>
   Whisk together the vinegar, mustard and honey in a small bowl.
Stir in the mustard seed. Gradually whisk in the oil until the
mixture is completely emulsified. Season with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Toss the spinach with 2 tablespoons of the dressing. Arrange on
a platter. Toss the potatoes and ham with the remaining dressing
and arrange over the spinach.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 350 calories, &LR;   &LR; 6 g protein, 38 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 20 g fat (3 g saturated), 9 mg cholesterol, 396 mg sodium, 4 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR; PURPLE POTATO SALAD WITH GORGONZOLA
</P>
<P>
   Note: The striking color of the potatoes makes this salad the
focus of any picnic table. Tossing the still-warm potatoes with
vinaigrette intensifies the complex flavors.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   11/2 tablespoons fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup minced shallots
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped fresh thyme
</P>
<P>
   11/2 teaspoons chopped fresh rosemary
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon grated lemon peel
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   3 pounds purple potatoes, halved or quartered
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup crumbled Gorgonzola cheese
</P>
<P>
   3 cups mixed baby greens
</P>
<P>
   Chopped chives for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Instructions: &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; Whisk the mustard and lemon juice in a small bowl until smooth.
Stir in the shallots, thyme, rosemary and lemon peel. Gradually
whisk in the oil until the dressing is completely emulsified.
Season with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Cook the potatoes in a large pot of boiling salted water until
just tender. Drain. Transfer to a large bowl. Pour half of the
dressing over the potatoes and gently toss. Set aside until cool,
tossing occasionally.
</P>
<P>
   Add the Gorgonzola and the remaining dressing to the potatoes.
Toss gently.
</P>
<P>
   Arrange the greens on a large platter. Top with the potato salad
and sprinkle with chives.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 400 calories, &LR;   &LR; 8 g protein, 44 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 23 g fat (5 g saturated), 11 mg cholesterol, 309 mg sodium, 5 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
