<HEADER>
A3718 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SC-VIDEO-POKER-COX     06-29 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SC-VIDEO-POKER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    South Carolina assembly in special session for 'video poker
mess'
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Star Lanes in Greenville, S.C., had a snack bar,
lounge and 32 lanes of bowling. But it wasn't enough _ until the
eight video poker machines came in.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about money,'' said general manager Ernest Pyles.
``It's just another way to raise revenue.''
</P>
<P>
   And it's not just in bowling alleys. The machines are as common
as tourists at Hilton Head and can be found in gas stations, hair
salons, restaurants and hotels.
</P>
<P>
   About the only one not getting a cut of the $2.5 billion-a-year
industry is the state government.
</P>
<P>
   Ordered into special session by Gov. Jim Hodges, who vowed
during his fall campaign to clean up the ``video poker mess'' left
by his predecessor, the South Carolina General Assembly is on the
verge of putting on the November ballot a referendum that would let
voters decide whether to regulate the controversial industry _ or
kill it altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Hodges rose from limited notoriety last year and upset incumbent
David Beasley after the challenger received millions from gambling
interests, which also bankroll several state legislators.
</P>
<P>
   Last year before the National Gambling Impact Study Commission,
Columbia psychiatrist Frank Quinn testified that 36,000 video poker
machines in South Carolina made gambling more accessible than in
Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   Quinn said gambling companies in The Palmetto State represent
the same kind of threat the fictional heartless banker Henry Potter
did to his hometown in ``It's a Wonderful Life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The relevance of the special session long-term is whether
we're going to be living in Pottersville or not,'' Quinn said. ``It
appears they've bought our legislature and our governor.''
</P>
<P>
   Each year, South Carolina sells video poker licenses for $2,000
a pop. That generates more than $60 million for the general fund,
but it's the only direct return to state coffers.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the regulation debate has centered on taxing video poker
proceeds as high as 25 percent. A machine returns an average of
$87,000 a year in gross receipts and $25,000 in annual profit,
based on industry reporting to the state.
</P>
<P>
   If video poker became an indispensable part of state funding, it
would be hard for legislators to ban the games.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot at stake financially,'' said Bill Moore, a
political scientist at the College of Charleston.
</P>
<P>
   If voters don't eliminate video poker in November, players will
be able to win a maximum of $500 a hand, compared to the current
$125 allowed during a 24-hour sitting.
</P>
<P>
   The old law attempted to keep the betting to a low-stakes form
of entertainment. With the higher amount, losers are more tempted
to wipe out their losses with a big win, Quinn said.
</P>
<P>
   He said that's the crux of the entire debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that could be controlled, then all the other issues would
flow from there,'' Quinn said.
</P>
<P>
   Pyles, the bowling alley manager, said limiting jackpots would
discourage players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why play $600 if your incentive to win is only $500,'' said
Pyles, whose typical players are women who come in after work.
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina has 7,600 gambling sites compared to 2,400 in
Nevada, Quinn said. As he testified before the gambling commission,
Quinn said video poker creates a ``cannibalistic economic loop,''
with in-state residents constituting the primary players. Job
creation is limited to minimum wage employment.
</P>
<P>
   ``No money is invested in capital development,'' Quinn said.
``There is no $2 billion Bellagio (casino) in South Carolina but we
literally have doublewides in cornfields'' that house video poker
machines.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Democrat-controlled state Senate passed a
referendum that would have let voters decide on state-imposed
regulations. But the GOP-led House failed to deliver the two-thirds
vote it needed to send the measure to this fall's ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Several members of the Legislative Black Caucus refused to vote,
protesting Hodges' refusal to fund economic measures that would
have benefited their constituents.
</P>
<P>
   ``There seems to be some strong sentiment that we should use
this as a vehicle to get the attention of the leadership in support
of what we want,'' said Rep. Leon Howard, a Democrat from Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   Marlon Manuel writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
