<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
These are the stories The San Francisco Chronicle Food section
plans to move Tuesday, June 29, on the New York Times News Service
wire. Questions? Please call Lesli Neilson at 415-777-6044. &HT;     SAN FRANCISCO _  Potatoes  _ Spudfest '99: Potatoes are such humble
little things, oddly shaped, strangely colored. But they star in
American cuisine, and perhaps nowhere more than in potato salad.
And let's face it _ potato salad is as much a part of Fourth of
July as are fireworks. With recipes. &HT;     By Robin Davis  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
SAN FRANCISCO _  &UR; SECRETS-Pork  &LR; _ This isn't your typical pork
tenderloin dish. The sauce is made with tangy blue cheese, which
actually pairs with the meat to make it all the more sweet.
<P>
   This is the latest installment of the regular column describing
what makes a Bay Area restaurant's dish a success. We'll tell how
to make it.
</P>
<P>
   With recipe, chef's secrets for success.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By Michael Bauer &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
SAN FRANCISCO _  &UR; TASTE-Hot Dogs  &LR; _ This week, The Chronicle's panel
of professional tasters rates poultry hot dogs. &QL; 
 &UR; By Robin Davis &QL;  &LR; 
