<DOCNO> NYT19990629.0281 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3720 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOMASH-DOMASH_SFCHRON     06-29 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOMASH-DOMASH </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 ONLINE INVESTING/HARRY DOMASH  &HT;     Taking In-Depth Look at a Mutal Fund 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
SECOND OF TWO PARTS.
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
In my latest column, we used Morningstar's Quicktake report to do
an initial analysis of a mutual fund. We found out whether the fund
was load or no-load and used Morningstar's return, risk and overall
ratings to determine whether the fund's track record warranted
further investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Let's assume we've found a fund worth a further look. We'll use
Morningstar to analyze the fund in depth.
</P>
<P>
   Log on to Morningstar ( &LR; www.morningstar.net &LR; ) and type the
fund's symbol into the data-entry box to bring up the Quicktake
report, then click Risk &AMP; Return on the Quicktake menu.
</P>
<P>
   You'll see the fund's total return for one-, three-, five-and
10-year periods, along with shorter-term statistics.
</P>
<P>
   What I find especially useful is the fund's return compared with
the Standard and Poor's 500 index for each period. I don't pay much
attention to the one-year performance, but I do look for funds that
consistently outperformed the S&AMP;P over the longer periods.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Largest Holdings
</P>
<P>
   Click on Portfolio in the Quicktake menu to display the fund's
10 largest holdings. Spend some time here. You can learn a lot
about the fund and its potential future performance by looking
carefully at the portfolio. If you've selected one of the recent
top-performing funds, you'll probably see most of the following
stocks in the portfolio: America Online, Dell Computer, Lucent
Technologies, Pfizer, Merck and Microsoft. All great companies, but
consider:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_These stocks all appreciated enormously during the past year and
are selling at high valuations. Do you think they will continue to
appreciate at a similar rate in the future? There's no right or
wrong answer to this question. If you say yes, continue with your
evaluation, otherwise go on to another fund.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
_Check the funds you currently own. Do they have the same companies
in their portfolios? If so, you're not diversifying by buying
another fund with similar holdings.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
_What industries are represented by the top 10 holdings? Say a fund
owns several bank stocks, and you think that rising interest rates
will hurt bank earnings in the coming months. A different fund owns
oil companies, and you think the recovery in Asia will increase
demand for oil and push prices and profits up. Your analysis of the
industry sectors would lead you to favor the second fund over the
first.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
_A fund may hold companies you don't want to own. For instance,
several funds have large holdings of Philip Morris, which you'd
want to avoid if you don't want to own tobacco companies.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR; Watch Out for Turnover
</P>
<P>
   Check the turnover percentage shown below the top 10 holdings.
Turnover measures a fund's trading activity. A turnover of 100
percent means the fund, on average, replaces its entire portfolio
every year.
</P>
<P>
   When a fund sells stock at a profit, it incurs a capital gain.
Mutual funds must distribute to shareholders most of their realized
capital gains that are not offset by realized losses by the end of
each year. These gains are taxable to shareholders. The more a fund
trades, the more taxes are likely to accrue.
</P>
<P>
   (Note: If your fund is in an IRA or other tax-sheltered account,
you won't pay taxes until you withdraw the money.)
</P>
<P>
   Turnover also tells you something about a fund manager's trading
style. High turnover indicates a short-term-oriented manager. Low
turnover indicates a buy-and-hold style. The average turnover for
U.S. equity funds is around 90 percent. I look for funds with less
than 50 percent annual turnover.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR; Fund Expenses
</P>
<P>
   Select Nuts &AMP; Bolts from the Quicktake menu and then click on
Fees &AMP; Expenses.
</P>
<P>
   The expense ratio includes all expenses incurred to run the
fund, from paying the manager's salary to the electric bill. The
expense ratio is deducted from a fund's investment returns before
you get paid.
</P>
<P>
   Consider two funds with exactly the same stock holdings. Both
funds' portfolios increased in value by 25 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   But Fund A's expense ratio was 0.5 percent, and Fund B's expense
ratio was 2 percent. Fund A's shareholders received a 24.5 percent
return while Fund B's shareholders received only 23 percent.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR; Price/Earnings Ratio
</P>
<P>
   The final data we'll look at in Morningstar is the average
price/ earnings ratio of stocks in the portfolio. A company's P/E
is its stock price divided by its annual earnings per share.
</P>
<P>
   A mutual fund's P/E is the weighted average P/E ratio of
companies in the portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   You can find the fund's P/E by selecting Portfolio from the
Quicktake menu and then selecting Stylebox basics.
</P>
<P>
   I've found a fund's P/E to be an important factor in determining
future performance. General equity funds with portfolio P/E ratios
above 30, on average, underperform the market, especially in weak
markets.
</P>
<P>
   This restriction does not apply to funds specializing in
specific industries such as health care, technology, etc. Specialty
funds almost always have above-market portfolio valuations.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR; Manager info
</P>
<P>
   A fund's performance depends, in part, on the the skill of the
manager. But what if the manager changes?
</P>
<P>
   A different site, Fund Alarm ( &LR; www.fundalarm.com &LR; ) keeps track
of management changes and gives you its opinion on the change's
impact.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
