<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UCLABS-PENALTIES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 GAO WANTS LAB SAFETY PENALTIES AGAINST UNIVERSITY OF CALIFORNIA  &HT;     By TANYA SCHEVITZ 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Congress' investigative arm says in a report to be released
Tuesday that the University of California should be fined for
safety violations at Lawrence Livermore and Los Alamos nuclear
weapons laboratories.
</P>
<P>
   In a report being released to a House subcommittee, the General
Accounting Office found a range of violations at the labs,
including exposing workers to radioactivity and lax procedures for
preventing nuclear accidents.
</P>
<P>
   The report criticizes the Energy Department for not following
through with proposed safety rules and calls for strengthening the
nuclear safety enforcement program. Among its recommendations is
fining nonprofit contractors like the University of California for
safety violations.
</P>
<P>
   The report will be the focus of a hearing Tuesday by the House
Commerce Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, Congress enacted legislation permitting the Energy
Department to impose penalties on contractors. Since enforcement
began in 1996, it has assessed more than $1.8 million on its
contractors for 33 safety violations.
</P>
<P>
   But UC and other nonprofit contractors have been exempt from
penalties, partly out of concern about putting public assets at
risk. Since 1996, nonprofit contractors have been exempt from
$605,000 in fines.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; No Accountability
</P>
<P>
   In the report, the GAO argues that eliminating the exemption
could be a valuable tool to hold UC and other nonprofit contractors
responsible for safety violations.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have these contracts, and they really have no
accountability,'' agreed Eric Wohlschlegel,cq  &LR;  a spokesman for the
House Commerce Committee. ``UC is one of the most serious
violators, and they are exempt from any penalties.''
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Energy found in March 1998 that workers at the
Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory in Livermore were exposed to
radiation that exceeded limits because of poor safety procedures.
In July 1998, the lab was found to have repeatedly violated
precautions designed to prevent uncontrolled nuclear reactions.
</P>
<P>
   The fines assessed but uncollected for the two incidents totaled
$313,125.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Los Alamos National Laboratory in New Mexico was
cited for lax monitoring of radiological contamination and not
taking adequate corrective actions. UC, which manages the lab, was
exempt from a $112,500 fine.
</P>
<P>
   The Energy Department wants to continue the exemption and has
even recommended that it be expanded to nonprofit subcontractors
and suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Nelson, UC's director of contracts management, said he had
not seen the report and could not comment on its recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously we are interested in maintaining the highest level
of safety we can at our operations,'' he said. ``But we don't think
anything has changed since 1988 in terms of why nonprofits were
exempted.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the report points out that when the exemption was first
allowed, nonprofit contractors did not receive fees above their
reimbursable costs, and now they do.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1993 the University of California has received $14 million
of its $25 million annual fee as a reward for good performance.
Currently $10 million to $12 million is reinvested in the
laboratory for research.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO report comes as the University of California and the
Energy Department are under fire for security breaches at the labs
that allowed China to obtain highly classified nuclear technology.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
