A3722 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-CONSERVATIVE-SFC     06-29 1829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CONSERVATIVE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH SPEAKS SOFTLY, GOVERNS TOUGH
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By MARC SANDALOW 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  Austin, Texas _ Listen to George W. Bush talk about compassion,
inclusion and diversity on the campaign trail, and one might be
uncertain of his political leanings.
<P>
   Take a look at his record as governor, and the confusion ends.
</P>
<P>
   In 41/2 years as governor of Texas, the son of the former
president has established himself as a bedrock conservative. He is
a solid Republican who has advanced the party's core agenda,
frustrated liberals and civil libertarians, and overseen the demise
of the Texas Democratic Party. Most Americans know little about the
man who, according to virtually every public opinion poll, is the
overwhelming favorite to be the GOP nominee for president.
</P>
<P>
   Although he is regarded as the most powerful Texas governor in a
generation, he is a political novice who says he was more
interested in becoming the next Willie Mays than following in his
father's footsteps. He lacks the hard edge of fellow Texans Tom
DeLay and Dick Armey, two prominent House Republicans who are
almost always at the heart of Washington's partisan battles, but he
has a resume that will disappoint few conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's record as governor shows him to be many things: a skilled
communicator who makes friends of his political opponents; a
strong-willed executive who seizes every opportunity to advance his
agenda; a unifier who reaches out to Latino voters; a moral
crusader who speaks of the existence of God and urges abstinence as
an alternative to abortion; a down-to-earth Westerner with a love
for baseball and a history of women, drink and chewing tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   This week, as he barnstorms through California in his maiden
trip to the West as a presidential candidate, he will sell himself
in much simpler terms _ as a likable conservative, comfortable in
his own skin and confident of his ability to lead.
</P>
<P>
   And on that, everyone can agree. With his preference for
compromise rather than confrontation, his self-deprecating humor
and disarming smile, Bush has been able to bridge the partisan gap
in the state capital of Austin in ways that would be unthinkable in
Sacramento or Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been a very good meeter and greeter,'' said Molly Beth
Malcolm, executive director of the Texas Democratic Party. ``If all
we're looking for is a guy with a nice smile and a good handshake,
he's a very good candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   As for his record, Democrats are far less complimentary.
</P>
<P>
   He is pro-business, pro-guns, pro-death penalty, anti-tax,
anti-abortion, anti-affirmative action and has been criticized by
environmentalists, labor leaders and advocates for the poor.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's conservative ideology was reflected in the four campaign
priorities of his 1994 bid to unseat then-Gov. Ann Richards: an
overhaul of the juvenile justice system, improvement of public
schools, a reduction in welfare benefits and tort reform. By the
end of his first year in office, all four had been accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   Tough new penalties were instituted for juveniles, and the
capacity at detention centers was tripled. The practice of
promoting school-children to the next grade regardless of their
accomplishments was ended. Local school districts were given more
authority, and test scores are up. Welfare payments were limited to
two years. Caps were placed on punitive damages, as businesses
cheered the less-litigious climate.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knew what he wanted to accomplish. He laid out an agenda,
and got it done,'' said Tony Garza, a longtime Bush associate who
is now the state's elected railroad commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   The 52-year-old Bush is only the second Texas Republican elected
governor since Reconstruction. But Texas _ which is emerging as one
of the most Republican states in the nation _ has responded
enthusiastically to Bush, re-electing him in November with 69
percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``There hasn't been a governor in Texas who has been such a
force since John Connally,'' said Lt. Gov. Rick Perry, recalling
the Democratic icon from the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas economy has boomed during Bush's tenure, allowing Bush
to cut property taxes by $3 billion. The state _ like California _
has become a mecca for the high-tech industry and trade with Mexico
and other Latin American countries.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Bush deserves credit for the state's strong economy is a
matter of debate. Much like Republicans who say that President
Clinton is not responsible for the nation's strong economy,
Democrats in Texas downplay Bush's role in their state's growth.
Sure he cut taxes, they say, but so did more than half of the
governors in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush record on social issues has been subject to harsher
attack. Civil libertarians complain that the state's justice system
is stacked against defendants and call it a national laughingstock.
Welfare payments are among the lowest in the country. Consumer
groups complain that the tort law overhaul is too pro-business.
</P>
<P>
   The National Abortion Rights Action League has identified 16
pieces of legislation signed by Bush that they consider grave
threats to a woman's right to an abortion. The measures range from
a requirement that doctors notify parents 48 hours before
performing an abortion on a minor to a prohibition on spending
state money on clinics that offer abortion services.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists blamed Bush this spring for dooming a measure
that would have required air polluters to comply with air quality
standards by September 2001. Bush favored voluntary, rather than
mandatory, standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor has been largely absent on environmental issues
this (legislative) session,'' said Ken Kramer, director for the
Sierra Club in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   On guns, Bush affirmed Texans' fondness for firearms in 1995
when he signed a law to permit residents to carry concealed
weapons. Earlier this month, he signed a bill to make it more
difficult to sue gun manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   Bush ``does not believe the manufacturer of a legal product
should be responsible for the criminal misuse of that product,''
spokeswoman Linda Edwards said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is an unapologetic supporter of the death penalty, a stance
that is a political strength in a state that has executed more
inmates in the past two decades than any other. Recently, a
convicted Canadian killer was executed in Texas, prompting a group
of Canadian journalists to ask Bush what he would tell their
countrymen who think of Texas as a remnant of the Wild West.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're Canadian and you come to our state, don't murder
anybody,'' Bush responded.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has made his mark, even though the governor of Texas is a
constitutionally weak position, with no cabinet, no power to make
judicial appointments and no legislative function other than the
authority to veto bills.
</P>
<P>
   He was quick to grasp the need to win friends among Democrats,
who had majorities in both the Texas House and Senate when he came
to office in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   During his first days, Bush went straight to the offices of
Texas legislators of both parties. He talked; he laughed; he won
many of them over.
</P>
<P>
   ``People like him. People want to like him. He uses that in a
very disciplined, very effective way,'' said Perry, who as
lieutenant governor would become governor if Bush moved on to the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   Although many Democrats remain fiercely opposed to Bush's
policies, he is well liked. Some have crossed party lines to become
his allies. When longtime Democratic leader Bob Bullock died
earlier this month, Bush delivered the eulogy as Bullock had
requested. When Bush hosted 2,000 donors in Washington last week,
Robert Junell, a powerful Democratic member of the Texas House,
introduced him.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is rarely involved in partisan fights. He is not dogmatic,
nor is he beyond giving credit to political opponents. When he
signed a education reform bill in 1995, he did it in the district
of Texas House Democrat Paul Sadler.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican Party has soared in Texas during Bush's rise. Ten
years ago, of the 29 cq &LR; positions elected statewide, only two were
held by Republicans. Today, all 29 are held by Republicans. Much of
the turn reflects the decline of the Democrats throughout the
South, as conservatives who shunned the GOP since Reconstruction
began to abandon the Democrats. Others give Bush his due.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would not be as strong in Texas today without this strong,
charismatic guy at the top,'' said Perry, who formerly was a
Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has sidestepped the dangers encountered by California
Republicans. For example, although Texas shares some of
California's problems with illegal immigrants, Bush was careful not
to make enemies while California Republicans have been virtually
abandoned by Latino voters ever since Gov. Pete Wilson championed
Proposition 187 in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spent a considerable amount of political capital in the
border communities, trying to woo the Latino population, which
comprises about a third of Texas. He has appointed scores of
Latinos to state positions. He frequently visits the border and has
brushed up on his Spanish, becoming conversational.
</P>
<P>
   ``Juntos Podemos'' read a huge banner over his inauguration
parade, beside an English translation: ``Together We Can.''
</P>
<P>
   Five governors of nearby Mexican states attended Bush's swearing
in, and while Republicans like Dan Lungren in California were
receiving just 20 percent of the Latino vote, Bush received more
than 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats charge Bush with opportunism and say that his
attention to Latinos has been little more than tokenism. Bush spent
$4 million _ about one-fifth of his entire campaign budget _ on the
relatively small El Paso market.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was setting himself up to run for President of the United
States,'' said Malcolm.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats also charge Bush with taking credit for policies that
are theirs. In his presidential stump speech, he talks about giving
a $3,000 raise to teachers. The raise was part of a Democratic bill
that some Democrats say he fought against. He also talks about
expanding health care to children, though as governor he fought for
a much more modest proposals.
</P>
<P>
   ``For those of us who sit in Texas and watch, it's very hard for
us to stomach,'' Malcolm said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has no guiding principles. The one thing he believes in is
that he should be _ and will be _ elected president.''
</P>
<P>
   One way to get a sense of what Bush stands for is to hear him
deliver a commencement address, something he does numerous times
each spring. Much of it could come only from a conservative _ the
discussion of the existence of God, of the need for personal
responsibility, of the moral emptiness of the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest applause _ and for many the most memorable line
_ is something that cannot be so easily labeled.
</P>
<P>
   Without fail, Bush tells graduating seniors to remember:
```Baseball should always be played outdoors, on grass, with wooden
bats.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
