u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-CALIFORNIA-HNS &LR;      06-29 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CALIFORNIA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH COURTS TINSELTOWN, HISPANIC VOTERS IN CALIFORNIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA TOLLEY  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush, preparing for the
political version of a Hollywood screen test, partially blamed the
television and film industry Tuesday for violence among young
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a correlation between violence in movies and
youth violence, but I also think there's a correlation between
violence and drug use and alcohol abuse and lack of parental
love,'' said Bush, who was scheduled to attend a small, exclusive
reception and fund-raiser with entertainment industry
representatives that was expected to net $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I meet with the movie people I'm not going to single them
out,'' Bush told reporters earlier Tuesday. ``I'm going to say:
`We're all responsible for ushering in the responsibility era.
We've all got to play a part.'''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, on his first visit to California since he began his
presidential campaign, also sought to portray himself as a
Republican candidate who can attract a range of voters from such
Democratic strongholds as the Hispanic community to the high-tech
world of Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore and his Democratic rival, former New
Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley, have been campaigning hard in the state,
which is viewed as a must-win for the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Bush hopes to increase his campaign donations from California to
$4.2 million for the campaign finance reporting period that ends
Wednesday. His campaign reportedly will announce he has raised
about $23 million since early March _ an amount that dwarfs those
of his GOP rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is trying to make inroads with Hispanics in California,
where a voter-approved ballot initiative seeks to deny medical and
education benefits to illegal immigrants. That initiative,
Proposition 187, was supported by former Gov. Pete Wilson, a
Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who received nearly half the Hispanic vote in his
re-election in November, opposes the California initiative.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm asking for the (Hispanic) vote. And I'm talking about a
message that is inclusive and an education system that refuses to
leave people behind, an education system that measures and gives
parents more options when there is a failure,'' said Bush, who
sprinkled his remarks with Spanish throughout the day of
campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   As for Proposition 209, the California ballot measure that ended
affirmative-action programs in state hiring, contracting and
university admissions, Bush said he supported ``the spirit of no
quotas and no preferences.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I do know, though, that quotas won't work when it comes to
meeting certain social obligations such as encouraging capitalism
to be spread all around the country,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who brands himself a ``compassionate conservative,'' was
to be the star attraction at a reception hosted by Terry Semel,
chairman and co-chief executive officer of Warner Bros. and Warner
Bros. Music Group and a long-time supporter of Democrats, including
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Semel went to the Texas capital earlier this year with a group
of Californians to attend a Bush luncheon at the Governor's
Mansion. After that visit, Semel offered to host a private
reception at his Bel Air home for Bush, according to campaign
spokeswoman Karen Hughes.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood traditionally favors Democratic candidates, and GOP
candidates such as Dan Quayle win points among conservatives for
blaming the television and film industry for violence and other
social problems.
</P>
<P>
   Bush had only mild criticism for the entertainment industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope Hollywood lauds responsible behavior and responsible
decisions and responsible actions,'' he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, violence can beget violence. But people behave
violently for all kinds of reasons,'' he said. ``But the whole
point I'm going to make with the movie folks is that all of us, all
of us, need to work together to change the culture. One industry
alone doesn't bear all the brunt.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At stops in La Jolla, Del Mar and Irvine, Bush sounded familiar
campaign themes of personal responsibility, local control of
schools, rebuilding the military and reducing marginal taxes, but
he avoided mentioning abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Yet small groups of abortion-rights protesters were on hand
outside the hotels where he gave speeches in La Jolla and Irvine.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Hayes-Raitt, the National Abortion Reproductive Rights
Action League's southern California director, called Bush ``the
most anti-choice governor in the nation'' for signing a bill last
month that requires doctors to notify parents before performing an
abortion on a teen-ager.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush said he will do everything in his power to restrict
abortion, and so far he has. What will he do as president?''
Hayes-Raitt said.
</P>
<P>
   In California, the always-controversial issue has proved
problematic in recent years for statewide candidates who oppose
abortion rights, according to political observers.
</P>
<P>
   If Bush becomes the GOP nominee, California Democrats are likely
to exploit Bush's position _ he opposes abortion except in cases of
rape, incest and to protect the mother's life.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been campaigning around the country as a moderate on this
issue, and clearly he isn't,'' Hayes-Raitt said.
</P>
<P>
   While protesters waved signs outside events, the crowds inside
cheered his arrival.
</P>
<P>
   At a fair in Del Mar, Bush received a rock star's welcome as he
worked his way through a crowd of several hundred people shaking
hands, posing for pictures and signing autographs. Many people
chanted ``Viva Bush!''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to disappoint you, but it's not worth that
much,'' he told one youth who sought his autograph.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Scott Delmas asked Bush: ``Will you please bring
integrity back to the White House?''
</P>
<P>
   After Bush moved on, Delmas identified himself as a registered
Democrat leaning toward support the Texas governor next year. He
said integrity transcended all other issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he brings integrity, he will make decisions based on
that,'' Delmas said.
</P>
<P>
   Inside a 4-H tent, Bush mixed with participants who were showing
their lambs. As he left the tent, he said he could sense excitement
about his candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are hungry for something. I hope I'm the person to give
it to them,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
