<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIO-BIO </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 FDA Says Approved Drugs Are Not Without Risk  &HT;     By Tom Abate 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
When it comes to pharmaceutical drugs, Americans should understand
that safe doesn't mean risk-free, Food and Drug Administration
Commissioner Jane Henney told biotech industry executives yesterday
in Berkeley.
<P>
   Henney, who heads the agency charged with testing drugs for
safety and efficacy, made her remarks in answer to a question at a
daylong industry gathering at the University of California at
Berkeley's Haas School of Business.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA has drawn heat lately after some newly approved drugs
turned out to have harmful or deadly side effects even after going
through the lengthy FDA approval process. Henney told the audience
of roughly 200 industry executives that her agency needs to do a
better job of explaining that ``there is and always will be an
element of risk'' that new drugs will have unanticipated side
effects or will be improperly used or prescribed.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we say we do safety tests, we understand safety is a
risk-benefit equation,'' Henney said. ``People have translated that
into `safe,' meaning no risk, and that's not the concept we want to
get across.''
</P>
<P>
   Henney, who took over as head of the FDA in November, is the
first woman to hold that post. She devoted most of her hourlong
appearance to assuring industry executives that the FDA will
continue looking for ways to speed up the process of reviewing drug
candidates without giving short shrift to safety tests.
</P>
<P>
   She said one way the agency will try to accomplish this
balancing act is by beefing up its in-house scientific research.
For example, she said, FDA researchers have begun looking at the
risks involved in modifying animal organs, like livers or hearts,
for transplant into humans, a field called xenotransplantation.
Henney said FDA researchers are looking at whether animal organs
might carry viruses that could infect humans.
</P>
<P>
   After she left the stage, Henney answered questions about
genetically modified foods. Environmentalists, among others,
criticize current  &LR; FDA rules that assume genetically modified foods
are safe and require no FDA approval, unless the company making the
modified food reports that it could cause some allergy or other
risk.
</P>
<P>
   Critics distrust this self-policing policy, but Henney said ``by
and large the system has worked well'' and she sees no need for
change at the current time.
</P>
<P>
   Henney's policy-oriented remarks were a departure from the
financial focus of the conference, which took the form of a series
of executive panel discussions. With the biotech sector in a long
slump on Wall Street, financial gloom characterized the panel
discussions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There isn't enough money out there,'' said Vaughn Kailian,
chief executive of COR Therapeutics. ``With 1,300 biotech
companies, we're going to have to be laying people off whether
consciously or unconsciously, by starving them (the companies)
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the many issues facing biotech executives is how to deal
with the retail investors who hold a majority of the shares in many
early stage biotech firms.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Eastman, chief executive of Geron Corp. in Menlo Park, said
more than 70 percent of his firm's stock is held by small
investors. Geron repeatedly has garnered national headlines for
scientific breakthroughs, like discovering a protein that seems to
rejuvenate cells. Such news has sent its stock soaring, only to
tumble quickly as investors realize how many years can elapse
between discovery and product.
</P>
<P>
   Joking that Geron's stock chart ``looks like the Himalayas,''
Eastman said biotech executives must walk the line between creating
excitement for the scientific potential of their work and stressing
how long it takes to turn ideas into profits.
</P>
<P>
   Kailian, jumping in as moderator, encapsulated the challenge of
communicating such risks to lay investors with this hypothetical
pitch: ``Give me your 5,000 bucks, and you have a 2 percent chance
of seeing this turn into a product.''
</P>
<P>
   The conference, which was organized by the Nasdaq exchange, ends
today with a luncheon address by David Lawrence, chief executive of
Kaiser Foundation Health Plan, who will talk about how HMOs are
struggling to pay for new products coming out of the biomedical
industry.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
