<SLUG> BC-MONEYBAG-MONEYBAG </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONEYBAG/ARTHUR M. LOUIS 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   Helping Your Children Invest 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: My 13-year-old daughter has $1,500 she would like to invest in a
mutual fund. Can you recommend any well-managed funds that would
let her open an account with this amount?
</P>
<P>
   A: There are few, if any, funds _ well managed or not _ that
will open a standard account for your daughter. Typically, they
want an investor &UR;  &LR; to start with an initial investment of at least
$2,000, notes John Collins, a spokesman for the Investment Company
Institute.
</P>
<P>
   So, why not be a sport and give your daughter at least $500 more
to invest? (Because she is under age 18, it will have to be a
custodial account, with you or your wife _ or both _ placing the
trade orders.)
</P>
<P>
   Another possibility would be to have her transfer her money to
an Individual Retirement Account. Practically all mutual funds
impose much lower limits on initial investments made through IRAs.
With $1,500 in an IRA, your daughter will be able to open an
account with just about any fund she chooses. (Again, in the case
of your daughter or any other minor, we are talking about a
custodial IRA account.)
</P>
<P>
   The catch is that she may not be eligible to contribute $1,500
to an IRA. She can do so only if her earned income for the year is
going to be at least that much. Does she make $1,500 per year from
baby-sitting, lawn mowing or lemonade sales?
</P>
<P>
   I would rather not recommend a specific mutual fund _ or any
other security.
</P>
<P>
   However, anyone interested in mutual-fund investments should at
least take a look at the funds that track the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index. These index funds have outperformed the vast majority of
managed funds year after year, yet they charge much lower
management fees than most other funds.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Depreciation Rules
</P>
<P>
   Q: In a recent column, you answered a question about how to
depreciate a computer bought for personal use and later transferred
to a newly created sole proprietorship. I was shocked that you told
this poor guy he had to depreciate the computer over five years
when, in fact, he can depreciate up to $18,500 worth of equipment
in the first year of ownership under Section 179 of the tax code.
Someone should tell him this because as a startup proprietor, he
will need all the tax breaks he can get.
</P>
<P>
   A: What you say is correct only if the computer was converted
from personal to business use in the same year it was purchased. If
it wasn't, then it indeed will have to be depreciated over a
five-year period, says Internal Revenue Service spokesman Jesse
Weller.
</P>
<P>
   Section 179 allows you to depreciate equipment in a single year
provided that it is the same year you placed it in service. The
ceiling was $18,500 for the 1998 tax year, but it moved up to
$19,000 this year. Next year, it increases to $20,000, and in 2001
and 2002, it will be $24,000. It tops out at $25,000 in 2003.
(Those figures could change; there has been talk in Congress about
accelerating the increases or permitting even greater limits.)
</P>
<P>
   The asset you depreciate under Section 179 must be used at least
50 percent of the time for business. If it is mainly for personal
use _ in the case of a computer, for example, if you spend endless
hours every day palavering in chat rooms _ then it doesn't qualify
for Section 179 depreciation.
</P>
<P>
   If the equipment is used for business 60 percent of the time,
for example, it qualifies for first-year depreciation _ but only 60
percent of the price can be depreciated.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
All Is Wells
</P>
<P>
   Q: I recently got a notice from Wells Fargo informing me that my
credit card account is being transferred, effective July 1, from
Wells Fargo Bank (Arizona) to an affiliated bank, Norwest (Nevada).
The notice also states that the account will be governed and
interpreted in accordance with Nevada law. How does this affect me?
Will I lose any rights under Nevada law?
</P>
<P>
   A: Wells Fargo spokesman Lance Berg says you won't lose any
rights. ``From the customer's standpoint, there will be no change
whatsoever,'' he says, ``except for a change in the address where
they send their bill payments.''
</P>
<P>
   Berg particularly stressed that there will be no change in the
fees or interest rates on your account.
</P>
<P>
   Moving accounts from Arizona to Nevada is part of a Wells plan
to consolidate certain operations, Berg notes. ``The reference to
Nevada law refers to how we are required to operate under the laws
of that state. It is strictly an internal thing.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
