u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCCAIN-COX     06-29 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    McCain takes risk with fund-raising stance
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ While the George W. Bush bandwagon rolls through
all the major primary states, Sen. John McCain (R-Ariz.) is
focusing his presidential campaign on two states where he hopes his
wartime record and maverick politics will play well.
</P>
<P>
   Since the first of the year, McCain has divided his campaigning
almost exclusively between New Hampshire and South Carolina,
deciding not to risk a test vote in the Iowa straw poll in August.
</P>
<P>
   McCain returns to New Hampshire again today to open a fresh
assault on the nation's campaign finance laws, defying the
conventional wisdom that campaign finance reform is an issue that
won't sell with Republican primary voters.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of the speech coincides with the close of the year's
second quarter fund-raising cycle. Like some of his rivals, McCain
has been making a last-minute effort to court contributors. He
e-mailed subscribers to his Web site this week and asked them to
make contributions over the Internet before the June 30 reporting
deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Today's speech in Bedford, N.H., is pure McCain: patriotic, bold
and full of heart. In an advanced transcript of his remarks, the
Arizona Republican accuses President Clinton of turning the Lincoln
bedroom into a ``Motel 6'' in return for large donations of soft
money. But McCain also blames soft money for corrupting his own
party, noting that pork-barrel spending in Congress has
``dramatically'' increased since Republicans took control in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to reform government,'' McCain said Tuesday. ``I want
to reform the tax business. I want to reform education. I want to
reform the military. All of that is made dreadfully more difficult
when you have a system that allows special interests to dominate
the legislative process over the average citizen.''
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts doubt that McCain can make much headway with a
cause that many Republican voters believe is a non-issue. ``His
campaign will go nowhere if it is based on the attractiveness'' of
campaign finance reform or tobacco legislation, McCain's other
national issue, said GOP pollster Whit Ayres. ``His campaign is
based fundamentally on his story, which is a compelling story.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain believes that his outspokenness on campaign finance
reform and other issues will gradually distinguish him from the
rest of the GOP field, including Bush. McCain was the most forceful
of the presidential contenders on the subject of Kosovo, and he
almost never shies away from making direct answers to controversial
subjects.
</P>
<P>
   But outspokenness also comes at a price. McCain has been one of
the loudest critics of the ethanol program, a federal program that
costs taxpayers $600 million a year but is popular among many
Midwestern corn farmers. McCain's campaign acknowledges that the
candidate's views on ethanol could hurt him among Iowa voters, for
example.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's strong views on tobacco could also hurt among some
voters in South Carolina, said Rep. Mark Sanford (R-S.C.), who is
supporting the candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Campaign finance won't hurt him,'' said Sanford. ``Tobacco
will. I've heard people say they can't support him because of his
stance on tobacco.''
</P>
<P>
   In several of his eight visits to South Carolina this year,
McCain has addressed the tobacco issue head on with tobacco
farmers, explaining that his proposal to levy new fees on
cigarettes to finance a federal campaign to reduce teen smoking
included $3 billion in subsidies to help tobacco farmers shift into
other crops.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are very satisfied with that,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   Following the nation's first primary in New Hampshire, McCain is
counting on South Carolina to give him the momentum he will need to
stay competitive with Bush in California and the large primaries
that quickly follow.
</P>
<P>
   The Palmetto State would seem a natural fit for McCain, a
decorated Vietnam pilot who survived five years of confinement and
torture at the hands of the North Vietnamese. South Carolina has
the highest per capita concentration of veterans of any state, not
to mention a large garrison of active-duty personnel.
</P>
<P>
   ``South Carolina is crucial to John McCain,'' said Rep. Lindsey
Graham (R-S.C.), who is supporting McCain. ``If you have not gained
momentum by South Carolina, you are in trouble. His stand is in
South Carolina.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the endorsement of 18 local legislators, McCain conceded
that he has a ``huge, long way to go'' in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has been to South Carolina only once as a candidate, but he
leads the field of other Republicans, according to the most recent
in-state poll.
</P>
<P>
   Bush got more than 55 percent of the support of hard-core GOP
primary voters, followed by Elizabeth Dole with 14 percent, former
Vice President Dan Quayle with 6 percent and McCain with 5 percent,
according to a poll released in May by Clemson University.
</P>
<P>
   Clemson political scientist James D. Woodard, who authored the
poll, said he had expected McCain do well because the poll was
taken in April, when Kosovo and McCain were in the news. Instead,
the poll numbers confirmed the surge Bush has gotten almost
everywhere, Woodard said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The simple fact is that (McCain) is not electrifying people
the way he needs to to win,'' Woodard said. ``I've never seen the
kind of enthusiasm for a candidate before he ran that I have seen
for Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Foskett writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
