<HEADER>
A3731 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOME-HOME_SFCHRON &LR;      06-29 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-HOME </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Will Rate Hike Cool Hot Housing Market?  &HT;     By Arthur M. Louis 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
An expected jump in interest rates this week isn't likely to cool
off the red-hot Bay Area housing market, at least not this summer.
<P>
   Mortgage lenders and homebuyers seem to already have anticipated
that the Federal Reserve will increase interest rates at its
monthly meeting today and tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Lenders already have boosted mortgage rates, with no noticeable
impact on Bay Area home prices or demand.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the steep rise in home prices _ the median price hit a
record $301,000 in May _ the median mortgage payment is still
smaller than it was nine years ago because interest rates are
lower, noted John Karevoll, an analyst with Acxiom Dataquick.
</P>
<P>
   Based on May's 6.9 percent interest rate, homebuyers who made a
20 percent down payment on a median-priced home would be paying
$1,587 per month on their mortgage.
</P>
<P>
   That is $241 per month less than the all-time high: a $1,828
mortgage payment on a median-priced house in March 1990. At that
time, the median-priced house cost only $251,000, but mortgage
rates stood at 10.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   At current home-price levels, the old record for monthly
mortgage payments would be surpassed if mortgage rates were to rise
as high as 8.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   That's not likely to happen unless inflation takes an
unexpectedly sharp upward turn _ something the Fed hopes to head
off at its meeting starting today.
</P>
<P>
   Most experts expect the Fed to raise the federal funds rate by
0.25 percentage points right away, while a minority expects an
immediate 0.5 percentage point increase.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Schlossberg, an economist with Wells Capital Management,
thinks rates might increase by as much as 0.75 percentage points in
multiple stages before year's end.
</P>
<P>
   However, because Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan has
been warning repeatedly about inflationary dangers in the hot U.S.
economy, mortgage rates have already risen.
</P>
<P>
   As of last week, the average rate in the Bay Area for a 30-year,
fixed-rate ``conforming'' loan (for less than $240,000) was 7.5
percent _ up 0.6 percentage points from 6.9 percent in May.
</P>
<P>
   Mortgage rates could continue to rise if inflation seems likely
to surge. But at the moment, that doesn't seem likely, Schlossberg
says.
</P>
<P>
   Prices are unlikely to dip _ although the rate of increase could
slow somewhat from the strong pace of recent months.
</P>
<P>
   ``The amount of money people seem to be willing to pay for Bay
Area housing is nowhere near what we know to be the limits,'' says
Karevoll. ``We could have a rise in interest rates of a couple of
percent before we reach the stretched-thin financial situation we
saw during the 1988-90 housing boom.''
</P>
<P>
   Historical data gathered by Acxiom Dataquick confirms that big
mortgage-rate gains don't necessarily push down home prices.
</P>
<P>
   When the average mortgage rate shot up to 9.1 percent from 6.7
between October 1993 and November 1994, the median Bay Area home
price actually rose slightly _ from $223,000 to $224,000.
</P>
<P>
   During another big rate rise _ from 6.9 percent in February 1996
to 8.1 percent in September 1996 _ prices rose substantially, from
$224,000 to $236,000.
</P>
<P>
   The experts don't expect huge interest rate increases in the
current low-inflation environment.
</P>
<P>
   Inflation, as measured by the Consumer Price Index, has been
running at a modest 2 percent annual rate or less in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fed tightening is just an insurance policy,'' Schlossberg
observes.
</P>
<P>
   While he considers the insurance advisable, Schlossberg adds:
``I don't see the need for big interest-rate increases. The
restraining influences on inflation are still in place: excess
capacity worldwide, the strong dollar (which holds down commodity
prices), continued corporate restructuring to improve efficiency,
and the investment in efficiency-raising high technology.''  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Leslie Appleton-Young, chief economist with the California
Association of Realtors, says upticks in mortgage rates normally
stimulate demand at first, with prospective homebuyers rushing out
in a panic to buy before rates go higher still. But this hasn't
happened with the latest uptick, she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talk to brokers throughout the state on a regular basis,
and only one or two have reported any stimulatory effect from
rising rates.''
</P>
<P>
   She concludes that panic hasn't set in because ``by historical
standards, mortgages are still affordable.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
