<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3733 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEB-WEB_SFCHRON &LR;      06-29 1317
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEB-WEB </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   Internet Mortgage, Credit Card Firms Trying to Cash In on Online 
 Success 
 &HT;     By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
OK, you joined the crowds online to trade stock. But are you ready
to take out a credit card or get a mortgage on the Internet?
<P>
   Karen Murphy and John Lee were. The Mountain View couple got a
loan from iOwn.com, a 3-year-old Web-based mortgage broker, to buy
a $310,000 house in North Berkeley, a purchase that closed last
week.
</P>
<P>
   Their verdict? They say Web surfing got them a super rate: a
7.25 percent fixed-rate loan for $248,000 that converts to an
adjustable loan after five years, with 1 percent of the loan amount
rebated at the close of escrow.
</P>
<P>
   But the lender they found through iOwn, First Nationwide
Mortgage, peppered them with last-minute questions and demands,
causing them to miss the financing deadline in their purchase
contract. Fortunately, the seller agreed to give them more time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty nerve-racking,'' said Lee, a 31-year-old
Microsoft marketing director, about his mortgage. ``I feel
confident I got the best possible rate, and iOwn has a great
dedication to customer service. But they're still working out the
kinks.''
</P>
<P>
   That about sums up the current state of online borrowing.
Internet-only companies such as iOwn and credit card purveyor
NextCard say the Web offers great prices, broad selection and
unbeatable convenience.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can literally customize the terms for you,'' said NextCard
chief executive Jeremy Lent.
</P>
<P>
   And online mortgage companies offer rate-comparison software
that lets borrowers find the best loans available on the market
with the features they want.
</P>
<P>
   But electronic-commerce experts say the Web falls flat handling
complicated transactions in which human beings, not computers, make
the final decisions.
</P>
<P>
   A mortgage is an example of a loan that has to be individually
underwritten for each customer. Those are tougher to complete
online.
</P>
<P>
   ``Credit products go from simple to very complex,'' said Jay
Norman, a Chicago electronic-commerce specialist with the
consulting firm PricewaterhouseCoopers. ``It's the less-complex
loans that best fit the Web.''
</P>
<P>
   Credit card applications are simple because a few pieces of data
about employment, residence and income are all that's needed to
make a decision. NextCard says it grants approvals within seconds.
</P>
<P>
   But mortgages require property appraisals, title searches and
proof of insurance. Applications often end up on the desks of human
underwriters who can stop the process in its tracks.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean homebuyers shouldn't shop for mortgages or
other complicated loans online. They simply should know that ``no
matter what they do on the Web, there are still people pushing
paper behind the scenes,'' Norman said.
</P>
<P>
   Today, online lending still represents a minuscule proportion of
the total credit market.
</P>
<P>
   Forrester Research, a Boston consulting firm, recently estimated
that just 1 percent of the $2 trillion in consumer credit extended
this year will be lent via the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Compare that with stock brokerages, in which one-third of all
retail trades now take place online.
</P>
<P>
   But things are about to change. ``The online credit market is
poised to take off,'' forecasts Forrester analyst James Punishill.
</P>
<P>
   Major-league lenders, including Countrywide Credit, the nation's
No.2 mortgage company, and First USA, the second-ranking credit
card issuer, are making big bets on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, a flock of well-financed startup companies are
building all-Internet businesses to reach borrowers in virtually
every lending niche, including specialty areas such as auto loans.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the fastest-growing new companies are based in the Bay
Area, including San Francisco's NextCard, the largest all-Internet
credit card issuer; iOwn, also based in the city; and Dublin's
E-Loan, the largest Web-based mortgage company.
</P>
<P>
   By 2003, Forrester predicts that nearly 10 percent of mortgages,
more than 16 percent of credit card loans and more than 25 percent
of student loans will be made over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Web-based lending has been slower to take off than the brokerage
business because consumers haven't seen offers they can't resist.
The rock-bottom commissions for trading stock online can run as low
as $5 compared with 10 or 20 times as much for trading off line.
</P>
<P>
   ``The value proposition isn't as clear and compelling,'' said
Punishill.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, online mortgages generally are cheaper than traditional
loans though the benefits are not as immediately apparent. That's
because the savings are in the origination fees, not the loan terms
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   IOwn charges a $400 processing fee plus 0.5 percent of the loan
amount, and E-Loan levies a single fee of 0.5 to 0.75 percent of
the loan. That compares with fees as high as 1.5 percent of the
loan from traditional mortgage brokers. The companies charge less
because they assign staff loan specialists to each customer and
don't use commissioned brokers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've taken the loan agent out of the process and substituted
salaried employees,'' said E-Loan President Janina Pawlowski.
</P>
<P>
   That strength also can be a weakness.
</P>
<P>
   Templeton Co.'s Linda Wolan, the real estate agent used by
Murphy and Lee, said she didn't have the same clout with iOwn that
she might have had with one of her regular mortgage brokers. When
things went awry, she couldn't intervene the way she ordinarily
might.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have the control I normally do,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, iOwn said it's trying to avoid such pitfalls by
automating underwriting tasks. For example, it now orders and
receives appraisals electronically.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're working to streamline the process and eliminate as many
of those variables as possible,'' said Charles Reed, iOwn vice
president of lending services.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast with mortgage brokers like iOwn, E-Loan makes most
of its mortgages itself. When it is the lender, it can avoid the
kinds of glitches that often crop up with third-party mortgage
companies. It sells its loans to Fannie Mae, the intermediary that
buys retail mortgages and repackages them for sale to investors.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, E-Loan makes more money when it lends money itself
than when it brokers a mortgage. But the company says its
loan-selection software finds the best rate for customers whether
it's an E-Loan product or a loan from another company.
</P>
<P>
   Online credit cards don't offer clear savings. Though NextCard
says i offers lower rates, a consumer probably can find a company
offering better terms among the thousands of card issuers in the
market.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's clearly not the same value'' as in an online mortgage,
said Punishill.
</P>
<P>
   What a company like NextCard provides is an unmatched ability
for a customer to tinker with terms and features and then get
instant approval on an application.
</P>
<P>
   NextCard, for example, lets applicants choose from a variety of
rewards programs and adjusts interest rates depending on sizes of
balances transferred from other card issuers. It even lets some
customers put photographs on the front of their cards.
</P>
<P>
   ``What some people put on their card is their pet,'' said Lent,
the CEO.
</P>
<P>
   But beware. NextCard has tight standards. It prefers applicants
with solid credit records and large balances outstanding on their
cards. Only about one in four members of the public meet the
company's underwriting criteria, Lent said.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Lachut, a 24-year-old software marketing specialist in
Pittsburgh, was one of those who made the cut. He took out a
NextCard Visa last year and was so impressed that he bought 100
shares of the company's stock.
</P>
<P>
   The application ``took about two minutes,'' Lachut recalled.
``Plus, I don't get an outstanding amount of junk mail from them.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-99 2001EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990629.0293 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3737 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HISPANIC-GEORGIA-COX     06-29 1005
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HISPANIC-GEORGIA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia governor campaigns for Hispanic citizenship
 &HT;    By Alan Judd
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When Maritza Soto Keen tried to register new voters at
a predominantly Hispanic flea market in DeKalb County last year,
she quickly learned she was going about her task all wrong. Rather
than asking Hispanics whether they were registered voters, she
said, ``the question should be, `Are you a United States citizen?'
''
</P>
<P>
   ``If they take that step to become a citizen,'' said Keen,
executive director of metro Atlanta's Latin American Association,
``they will take that next step to exercise their responsibility
and privilege to register to vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Roy Barnes wants to make sure they do.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday Barnes threw his support behind a campaign supported
by Keen's organization and others to increase voter registration
among the state's Hispanic residents, the fastest-growing ethnic
group in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he called on federal officials to speed
citizenship applications so more Hispanics and other immigrants
will become eligible to add their names to the voting rolls.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can no longer be denied that the faces of our economy and
our people are changing,'' Barnes said during a news conference to
announce the registration drive, adding that he plans to ``educate
and actively recruit'' Hispanic voters before next year's
elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``Voting,'' he said he will tell them, ``is the voice that
really counts.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor's blessing of the privately funded registration
effort reflects the fact that Hispanics have an importance _ and an
illusiveness _ that is increasingly attracting attention from
political figures across the ideological spectrum. Among others,
presidential candidates such as Democratic Vice President Al Gore
and Texas Gov. George W. Bush, a Republican, are aggressively
courting Hispanic voters, even as officials try to determine just
how many of them there are.
</P>
<P>
   In Georgia, state officials not only don't know how many
Hispanics are currently registered to vote, they can't say
definitively how many Hispanics reside in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia voter registration forms ask applicants to declare their
race _ white, black or ``other'' _ but do not allow potential
voters to describe themselves as being of Hispanic ancestry or as
belonging to any other ethnic group. Among states with large
Hispanic populations, Florida takes a similar approach, while
election laws in two others _ California and Texas _ don't call for
collecting any racial or ethnic information from voters.
</P>
<P>
   Hispanics ``generally fall under the `other' category,'' said
Kara Jones, a spokeswoman for Georgia Secretary of State Cathy Cox,
the state's chief elections officer. About 2 percent of Georgia's
3.5 million registered voters have checked ``other.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Hispanics are estimated to comprise about 5 percent of
all voters nationally, their presence has barely been noticed in
Georgia elections. When the Voter News Service, a research company
supported by news organizations, interviewed voters leaving Georgia
polls last fall, less than 1 percent said they were of Hispanic
descent.
</P>
<P>
   The Hispanic turnout may or may not have been proportionate to
the state's Hispanic population.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Census Bureau estimates that 207,053 people of Hispanic
origin live in Georgia _ not quite 3 percent of the state's 7.5
million residents.
</P>
<P>
   But in endorsing the voter-registration drive, Barnes cited a
significantly higher Hispanic population figure _ 475,000 _ that
came from a recent report to the state Board of Regents.
Researchers at Georgia State University counted the number of
Hispanic children enrolled in the state's public schools and
extrapolated the larger figure.
</P>
<P>
   Whichever number is correct, Georgia is believed to have nearly
twice as many Hispanic residents now than it did in 1990, and the
number is expected to double again within a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Bachtel, a demographer at the University of Georgia,
disputed projections, cited by Barnes, that Hispanics may soon
become the state's largest minority group. Noting that African
Americans make up 29 percent of the population, far more than
Hispanics would account for even if their numbers doubled again,
Bachtel said: ``Georgia is a traditional black-white state. I don't
foresee the day where the Hispanic population is a dominant
population group.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes _ who hopes an accurate census count next year will give
Georgia another seat in Congress _ said the Hispanics' rapid
population growth is why he has recently paid so much attention to
their concerns; in addition to endorsing the voter drive, he also
has appointed a panel of Hispanic leaders to recommend legislation
addressing issues affecting their community.
</P>
<P>
   He denied Tuesday that his interest in Hispanic affairs was
related to his support of Gore, and said it had not been prompted
by either Gore's campaign or the Democratic National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   But he added: ``I don't think I'm registering a band of
Republicans. Even if I were, I would still be in favor of
registering.''
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts aren't so sure. Larry Sabato, a political
scientist at the University of Virginia, described Barnes' action
Tuesday as ``a dead giveaway'' that Democrats are worried about
retaining the Hispanic votes they can normally count on.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is happening all over the country with both sides,''
Sabato said. ``Everyone recognizes that Hispanics are a critical
swing bloc in the electorate.''
</P>
<P>
   Hispanics recognize their political importance, too, said Sora
Chavez McFarlane, executive director of the Georgia Hispanic Voter
Registration Campaign. The campaign, she said, will ensure that
``every single one in Georgia who's Hispanic is going to be
registered to vote. We're going to count.''
</P>
<P>
   Alan Judd writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
