<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3738 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUDGET-SURPLUS-NYT &LR;      06-29 1087
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-SURPLUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RISES IN PRODUCTIVITY AND PERFORMANCE LED TO HIGHER SURPLUS
ESTIMATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also MEDICARE-CLINTON) 
(sw) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON and MICHAEL M. WEINSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Where did the Clinton administration find $1
trillion?
</P>
<P>
   The White House's new analysis of the federal budget _ which
shows a windfall of more than $1 trillion in the next 15 years on
top of the previously anticipated $4.9 trillion cumulative surplus
in that period _ is built on good things happening deep in the
economy and in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians do not much care where the surplus is coming from,
only in how much they have to play with. With the Congressional
Budget Office set to release its own updated projections on
Thursday, Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, who is chairman of the House
Ways and Means Committee, said on Tuesday that he expects to
increase the size of the proposed Republican tax cut to take
account of any new money that become available.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of the $775 billion, 10-year tax cut that Republicans
had planned, they may now shoot for a tax cut of $1 trillion or
even more, Archer said. In suggesting that Republicans would seek
an even bigger tax cut, Archer and other Republican leaders set out
a hard-line strategy for dealing with the White House, which wants
to hold down the size of any tax cut and instead put the bulk of
the surplus into Social Security, Medicare and new spending
programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we should say, `Oh, goodie! We have more
money''' to spend, Sen. Trent Lott of Mississippi, the majority
leader, told reporters on Capitol Hill. Rather, Lott said, the
extra money ``makes it a lot easier and more justifiable'' for
Congress to pass a tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   But the partisan battle would not be possible if the government
did not find itself awash in good fiscal news, albeit, news
predicated on optimistic assumptions and educated guesswork about
where the economy is heading. None of the developments driving the
growth of the surplus are by themselves terribly surprising or even
new. Taken together, though, they are sufficient to create
breathtaking flows of money into the government's coffers and
reshape the political debate over the nation's priorities.
</P>
<P>
   The debate in Washington over arcane budget matters is so
intense, said Rudolph G. Penner, a former director of the
Congressional Budget Office, because ``adjustments that are small
to professional economists can have immense political importance.''
</P>
<P>
   Even tiny changes, multiplied by the world's largest economy,
make big differences over the years. The most important of them
include an increase in the administration's estimate of growth in
productivity, or how much each worker can produce in a given period
of time. When productivity improves, so does the economy's ability
to expand without inflation _ and therefore to generate a steady
increase in tax revenues.
</P>
<P>
   The degree to which the economy is enjoying a permanent increase
in productivity growth is part of a broader debate over whether the
economy has entered a new era in which massive investments in
technology have made businesses and workers much more efficient.
Administration officials said they were not endorsing the new era
concept, but simply reflecting the reality that the economy has
been performing better than its previous estimates predicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a constant tension in these economic forecasts to be
prudent and realistic at the same time,'' said Jacob J. Lew, the
White House budget director. ``If we put out numbers that
underestimate economic trends, they wouldn't be credible. On the
other hand, we went to great lengths not to overstate the economy's
potential.''
</P>
<P>
   In its new analysis, the administration estimated that
productivity growth would be 1.6 percent annually through 2002, up
from 1.3 percent in the analysis it prepared in February. Over the
longer run, it estimated that productivity growth would slow
somewhat, to 1.4 percent annually, a figure that is still higher
than its previous long-range estimate of 1.3 percent annually.
</P>
<P>
   The improved productivity outlook _ plus the economy's extremely
strong performance for the past several quarters _ underpinned an
increase in the administration's growth estimates. From this year
through 2004, the administration is now estimating that the economy
will expand by an annual average of 2.5 percent, up from 2.2
percent in the administration's last budget analysis in February.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the economy is already bigger at this point than the
administration had predicted. Merely applying the old projected
growth rates to the new higher levels of revenue and income would
produce a large part of the additional surplus.
</P>
<P>
   In real life terms, stronger growth means more people are
working, earning bigger paychecks _ and paying more taxes. The
experience of the last few years shows how strong growth has
translated into the beginnings of the revenue cascade that the
administration now anticipates.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the surge in revenues is coming from individual income
taxes. For next year, for example, the administration now expects
individual tax receipts to total $921 billion, up more than $21
billion since the February estimate. Corporate income tax receipts
are expected to come in somewhat lower than previously anticipated,
reflecting slower profit growth.
</P>
<P>
   A portion of the growth in individual income tax receipts stems
directly or indirectly from the long bull market on Wall Street.
Individuals are reaping substantial capital gains, and more and
more people are being compensated with stock or in ways that
reflect the performance of their employer's shares.
</P>
<P>
   The effect of the rising stock market can be seen clearly in
receipts from inheritance taxes levied on estates, many of which
contain big holdings of stocks and bonds that have appreciated in
value tremendously in recent years. The administration estimated
that estate and gift tax revenue next year would be $31.4 billion,
up from $27 billion in its February estimate.
</P>
<P>
   Can anyone count on the new budget projections? Not really.
Economists cannot project federal revenues and spending a few years
out _ much less 15 years hence _ with any precision.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the administration and the Congressional Budget Office
can claim that their assumptions and projections are reasonable,
which may be as good as it gets for the purpose of policy decisions
whose implications play out over decades.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-99 2004EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
