<DOCNO> NYT19990629.0297 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3743 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDICARE-CLINTON-ART-     06-29 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-CLINTON-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON OUTLINES PLAN TO OVERHAUL MEDICARE AND ADD DRUG COVERAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: An expanded, 1,400 word version of this story is scheduled
to move by 9 p.m. ET; see also BUDGET-SURPLUS) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rm) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Following through on a promise to preserve Medicare
for the aging baby boom generation, President Clinton on Tuesday
proposed fundamental changes in the program to make it more like
private health insurance and to add coverage of prescription drugs,
a benefit long sought by the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   His proposal, one of the biggest domestic policy initiatives of
the last three decades, would help keep Medicare solvent until
2027, the White House said.
</P>
<P>
   The president who rode into office with a promise to guarantee
health insurance for all said he was hoping to close his
administration by enhancing the giant health program for the
elderly and the disabled. The number of Americans 65 and older is
expected to double in 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials acknowledged a potential contradiction
in their efforts to shore up Medicare while creating a costly new
benefit. The savings from structural changes in the program,
including greater competition and prudent purchasing techniques,
would be dwarfed by a huge infusion of cash from the federal
treasury: $374 billion in the next 10 years, and a total of $794
billion from 2000 to 2014.
</P>
<P>
   The economic context for Clinton's proposal could hardly be
better. A vibrant economy has generated a windfall of federal
revenue. The White House said this week that it foresaw surpluses
totaling nearly $3 trillion over the next decade. One in eight of
those dollars would go to shore up Medicare under the president's
plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a nation bursting with prosperity, no senior should have to
choose between buying food and buying medicine,'' Clinton told a
bipartisan audience at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Under his plan, drug coverage would be voluntary, but the
administration said it would be such a good bargain that almost
everybody would take it. In 2002, the first year of the proposal,
each person would pay a premium of $24 a month _ $288 a year _ for
drug coverage. Medicare would cover half of a person's drug costs,
up to a limit of $1,000 on the first $2,000 of drug expenses. The
premium would rise to $44 a month in 2008, and the government would
pay a maximum of $2,500, or half of drug expenses up to $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a drug benefit our seniors can afford, at a price
America can afford,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Some lawmakers said the fast-growing budget surplus improved the
prospects for passage of a major Medicare overhaul. But beneath the
inklings of bipartisanship Tuesday, the old suspicions lingered.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans in Congress reacted cautiously. They did not reject
Clinton's proposals out of hand, saying they, too, wanted to
restructure Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Lobbyists for the elderly said enactment of a Medicare drug
benefit prior to next year's elections was a long shot. But they
rejoiced that Clinton had put the issue high on the nation's
agenda.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton would offer drug coverage to all 39 million
Medicare beneficiaries, Republicans said Congress should start by
helping the 15.5 million who do not have such coverage.
</P>
<P>
   In a joint statement, the speaker of the House, Dennis Hastert,
and the Senate Republican leader, Trent Lott, said, ``We should be
careful not to force those who already have prescription drug
coverage to accept a government-run plan that costs more and
provides fewer choices.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he would ``bring to the traditional Medicare
program the best practices from the private sector,'' allowing the
government to use its immense purchasing power to bargain with
suppliers of medical goods and services. He also proposed changes
to encourage price competition among health maintenance
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   HMOs and other forms of managed care dominate the commercial
health insurance market, but have attracted only 16 percent of
Medicare beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   In proposing coverage of prescription drugs and improved
coverage of preventive health care services, Clinton said he was
trying to modernize Medicare. ``Nobody would devise a Medicare
program today, if we were starting all over, without including a
prescription drug benefit,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Under Clinton's plan, beneficiaries would pay extra premiums
totaling $110 billion over the next 10 years, and the government
would put up $118 billion.
</P>
<P>
   People with low incomes (under $17,000 a year for a couple)
would not have to pay premiums or the beneficiary's share of the
drug costs.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Gail E. Shearer, a health policy expert at Consumers Union,
said, ``The proposed drug benefit offers consumers good value _ far
better than they can now get in the Medigap market,'' which offers
private insurance to supplement Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   The White House estimates that the new drug benefit would cost
the Treasury $21.8 billion a year in 2009, and it anticipates that
the costs then would be growing about 11 percent a year _ much less
than the increases in drug spending reported recently by private
health plans. This disparity will inevitably raise questions about
whether the administration has underestimated the long-term cost of
its proposal, as the government has done with other Medicare
benefits in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Some elements of Clinton's plan had been disclosed in recent
weeks, but there were a few surprises Tuesday. For example, he
proposed to eliminate all co-payments, deductibles and other
charges that beneficiaries pay for preventive services covered by
Medicare. These services include screening for osteoporosis and for
breast, colon and prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also called for a study to see if Medicare should cover
services to help people quit smoking.
</P>
<P>
   However, the president also proposed to make beneficiaries pay
20 percent of the cost of laboratory services, for which they now
pay little or nothing.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he asked Congress to increase the deductible amount
that Medicare beneficiaries pay for doctors' services and
outpatient hospital visits. The deductible has been fixed by law at
$100 a year since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Under Clinton's proposal, the deductible would be automatically
increased each year to reflect increases in consumer prices. In
other words, it would be indexed for inflation, as measured by the
Consumer Price Index.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
