<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-ARMY-HOLDUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO CITY ROBBERS KILL 2 AS THEY STEAL MILITARY PAYROLL 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SAM DILLON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ In one of the most brazen criminal attacks in
memory here, armed robbers on Tuesday ambushed elite soldiers of
the Presidential Guard two blocks from Ernesto Zedillo's
presidential residence, stealing a $50,000 military payroll and
killing an army colonel and a lieutenant.
</P>
<P>
   The midday attack appeared certain to increase the perception
that criminal violence is out of control at a moment when
politicians from all three main parties are converting crime into a
central campaign issue in state and national races.
</P>
<P>
   Gangland-style killings have become increasingly routine in
Mexico City. But the Mexican army is widely feared, and anti-crime
experts said street crimes that focused on military officers were
extremely rare.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo was not in danger. He was at a meeting of Latin American
leaders in Rio de Janeiro.
</P>
<P>
   The six gunmen, described by witnesses as extremely young,
perhaps teen-agers, drove two vehicles in front and behind the
soldiers' sedan as it stopped at a red light on an busy boulevard
that runs through a middle-class neighborhood adjoining Los Pinos
presidential compound.
</P>
<P>
   Running to the windows of the soldiers' car, the assailants
reportedly fired at least 26 shots into the sedan.
</P>
<P>
   ``They started to shoot, and the soldiers in the white car
closed their eyes,'' said Adrian Kauffman, a student who saw the
shooting.
</P>
<P>
   The robbers seized an attache cash that was apparently filled
with cash and fled the scene unscathed in their two vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's pretty bold,'' said Daniel Bell, general manager of
Kroll-O'Gara de Mexico, a security business. ``I've not heard of
attacks on military officers like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Robberies of payroll deliveries, however, are occurring at
``epidemic rates,'' Bell said.
</P>
<P>
   With so many robberies, many companies are switching payroll
systems to direct electronic transfers to employees' bank accounts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
