<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3760 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS &LR;      06-29 1383
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
10,000 IN BELGRADE PROTEST MILOSEVIC REGIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX TODOROVIC AND JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE _ Defying police roadblocks, a small bomb and the full
weight of Slobodan Milosevic's security apparatus, at least 10,000
people toop part Tuesday in Yugoslavia's first antigovernment rally
since 1997, demanding the removal of the man who led Yugoslavia to
war against NATO.
</P>
<P>
   ``One man is responsible for this tragedy!'' said Vuk Obradovic,
a former general in the Yugoslav Army and leader of the Christian
Democratic party. ``He's responsible for these 10 years of
suffering and a destroyed economy.''
</P>
<P>
   US officials and Balkan experts agreed that the rally, ignored
by state-controlled Yugoslav television, reflected increasing
discontent with the Yugoslav president. US Defense Secretary
William Cohen said in Washington that he expected rising criticism
``in the wake of people understanding they have lost their jobs,
they have lost members of their family, they have been isolated
politically and their economy is going to take years to repair as a
result of his actions.''
</P>
<P>
   As police turned back hundreds of cars headed toward the central
Serbian town of Cacak _ whose mayor had gone into hiding after
publicly criticizing Milosevic _ hundreds more vehicles threaded
through back roads, and people from nearby villages walked to the
town. Many speakers arrived a day early, anticipating that
Milosevic's government, which has not lifted its ban on public
gatherings, would try to thwart the protest.
</P>
<P>
   Just after the rally began, a bomb exploded in a parking lot,
leaving a sizable crater and shattering the windshield of a Yugo.
The crowd, shouting ``Red Bandits!'' _ a reference to Milosevic's
communist and socialist ruling coalition _ buckled and began to
flee, but the rally's first speaker, Milan Kandic, urged everyone
to stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told us not to be afraid,'' said 18-year-old Visnja, a
student in Cacak. ``Everyone understood how important it was that
we not run. Anyway, what's one small bomb after everything we've
been through.''
</P>
<P>
   Some chanted ``Red Bandits!'' after the explosion, in a
reference to the communist and socialist ruling parties.
</P>
<P>
   One by one, the speakers addressed the crowd and spoke with a
singular voice, saying Yugoslavia must remove Milosevic to move
forward. They called for fair elections as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a government of traitors. They're in conflict with the
Serbian Orthodox Church, Montenegro and the world,'' said Zoran
Zivkovic, the mayor of southern Serbian town of Nis.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Cohen told reporters that it was ``too early to
tell'' whether the public protests would weaken Milosevic, but he
believed that the demonstrations would continue, and grow, against
the Yugoslav leader.
</P>
<P>
   Eric D. Gordy, a Clark University sociologist and author of
``The Culture of Power in Serbia,'' said the demonstration may
indicate broad popular dissent against Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did it at a time when the regime still banned protests,
and specifically banned this one and set up roadblocks. I think
that also you have to think about the political environment
there,'' Gordy said. ``It's really hard for people to imagine that
they can achieve anything by protesting, because this regime has
destroyed everything in the past year. The fact that anybody would
show up at all is pretty major.''
</P>
<P>
   Organizers of the event chose to hold the rally without the
government's approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``We advise the government to stop using the police against the
people as that never saved one dictatorship,'' said a statement
from the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   There were two minutes of silence; one for those killed in the
war, another for the removal of Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   The last speaker, Cacak's popular mayor Velimir Ilic, emerged
from several weeks of hiding to address the crowd. Demonstrators
adoringly chanted ``Veljo! Veljo! Veljo'' _ his nickname _ as he
moved toward the microphone.
</P>
<P>
   Ilic fled Cacak during the war after the police tried to arrest
him for his anti-government statements. Ilic's voice trembled as he
spoke of his ordeal. He said monks in the mountain village of
Brezovici sheltered him while he hid from the police.
</P>
<P>
   ``The elder of the monastery told me not to carry a gun, but a
cross,'' said Ilic. ``I came back only with God's help.
</P>
<P>
   His speech sent a wave of emotion through the crowd. To wild
cheering, Ilic concluded: ``We want a new Serbia!''
</P>
<P>
   The rally was organized by the Alliance for Change, a coalition
of opposition groups who are calling on Milosevic to step down and
for fair elections. The Alliance plans to hold such demonstrations
all summer across Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal of the Alliance is to allow citizens to articulate
their rage in a positive manner,'' said Vladan Batic, the
Alliance's coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   The police roadblocks show that the Milosevic's well-paid police
force is prepared to carry out orders and may take additional
measures to prevent such demonstrations. The Alliance is determined
to hold its gatherings in the face of a government crackdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``We absolutely have to encourage young people to become
involved in the future of this country. Nobody can change the
government but us,'' said Obradovic, the Christian Democrat leader.
</P>
<P>
   Batic said that the Alliance would boycott unfair elections.
Without reform of election laws, the alliance promised to hold
parallel opposition elections instead that would establish a second
government.
</P>
<P>
   Since martial law was lifted last week, criticism of Milosevic
in the press has gained a steady momentum. A parade of Serbian
intellectual and cultural figures have called for his removal, as
well as the Serbian Orthodox Church.
</P>
<P>
   But the powerful nationwide television station, Radio Television
Serbia, still ignores any unflattering news about the government.
Even Studio B, the Belgrade television station controlled by the
Serbian Renewal Movement, Serbia's largest opposition party,
mentioned the Cacak rally only in passing.
</P>
<P>
   In Kosovo, the commander of the international peacekeeping force
said that more guerrilla fighters in the province had turned in
their weapons. Lt. Gen. Mike Jackson said he was ``broadly
satisfied'' that the disarmament of the Kosovo Liberation Army was
proceeding according to plan.
</P>
<P>
   But Cohen said Tuesday that NATO forces must continue to move
quickly into Kosovo to prevent firefights between Serb
paramilitaries and ethnic Albanian fighters. There was special
concern that some Serb fighters had remained behind and, in a
reversal of roles with the ethnic Albanian separatists, would try
to play the role of guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   ``What will be important is for us to accelerate _ to the extent
possible _ the arrival of the full KFOR force,'' said Defense
Secretary William S. Cohen, referring to Kosovo Force peacekeepers.
About 14,000 peacekeepers are now in Kosovo, and Cohen said more
than 25,000 should be in the province in two weeks. Ultimately, the
force will number 50,000.
</P>
<P>
   The full US contingent of 7,000 soldiers is expected to be in
Kosovo in about two weeks, said Army Lieutenant General Michael
McDuffie of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.
</P>
<P>
   The 1st Infantry Division soldiers are moving from Germany into
Kosovo. The Navy warship Bob Hope arrived Tuesday at the Greek port
of Thessaloniki carrying Army tanks, howitzers and other equipment
for the soldiers. A second US warship, the Soderman, is due in the
Greek port Saturday, McDuffie said.
</P>
<P>
   The movement of American troops into Kosovo has been fairly easy
because there was less damage to roads and bridges than expected,
he said. Another unexpected find: there have not been huge numbers
of ethnic Albanians found in mountain or forest hideouts throughout
Kosovo, McDuffie said. US intelligence reports had estimated that
up to 500,000 people were living in desperate conditions with
little or no shelter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really have not found any large number of'' internally
displaced persons, he said, adding only that intelligence reports
and information from the United Nations had turned out to be
incorrect.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Todorovic reported from Yugoslavia; Donnelly reported from
Washington.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
