<HEADER>
A3761 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-AKERS-COX     06-29 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-AKERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Akers rations her energy and adjusts to a new role for the U.S.
team
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   No Women's World Cup Barbie dolls bear Michelle Akers' likeness,
and no clever commercials feature her as a glamorous soccer star.
</P>
<P>
   On a U.S. team basking in the limelight of newfound sports
celebrity during the Women's World Cup, Akers does not personify
any of it.
</P>
<P>
   But the 33-year-old defensive midfielder _ kept together with
the help of daily intravenous injections, a less stressful role on
the field and an abiding religious faith, as she nears the end of a
glorious 14-year career _ helped create what is swirling around her
and her teammates.
</P>
<P>
   Akers, 5 feet 10 with bushy blonde hair, a craggy face and
occasional slowness of step, is aware of the ``warhorse''
description that follows her. She even uses the term when talking
about herself. But for a woman who lives with chronic fatigue
syndrome and has endured no fewer than a dozen knee operations, she
insists that she never has felt better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel pretty good right now,'' she said. ``The only job I
have is to play. Day to day, I have a handle on it.''
</P>
<P>
   While Mia Hamm, Julie Foudy, Kristine Lilly, Brandi Chastain and
others make the media rounds, Akers spends time in the training
room, replenishing her body with nutrients, or by herself at the
team hotel, bundling up energy for the next practice session or
game.
</P>
<P>
   Akers has been well-rested the past week, scoring a goal and
playing the first half in a 7-1 romp over Nigeria and sitting out
Sunday's 3-0 win over North Korea. Her physical ability could prove
to be critical for Thursday's quarterfinal with Germany in
Landover, Md., in what could be the most rugged encounter for the
Americans. And that's what has kept her value high after being
switched from a primary role as a powerful scorer for the 1996
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know that in every game she's going to leave everything
she has on the field,'' Foudy said. ``That's what you love about
her, that's what you love about playing next to her. We have to
have her out there.''
</P>
<P>
   After starring for the U.S. team in the first Women's World Cup
in 1991, where she scored 10 goals, Akers became the heart, soul
and persona of women's soccer. She grew to be a prominent sports
figure in Sweden, where she played professionally for three
seasons. Her goal last week was the 103rd of her career, putting
her fifth on the all-time international list, a feat lost among the
clamor over Hamm, who recently took over the lead with 111.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michelle may not be getting the commercials, but when you're
looking for someone to point to as where this all started, she was
the pioneer,'' said Bill Barker, the University of Georgia women's
soccer coach, who coached Akers at Central Florida in the
mid-1980s. ``For some reason, she's been chosen to be the player
who stepped up for women's soccer when a lot of people weren't
paying much attention at all.''
</P>
<P>
   When she returned to Sweden with the U.S. team for the 1995
World Cup, however, her abundance of energy was gone. She couldn't
force herself off the sofa after what were becoming longer and more
frequent naps, and it took her hours to cook, do laundry, run
errands. When a series of different diets didn't work, Akers, on
the verge of desperation, went to a doctor.
</P>
<P>
   Norway ousted the Americans in the semifinals, as Akers tried
gamely to recover from a broken bone she suffered near her eye
earlier in the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought my playing career was over,'' Akers said. ``I just
couldn't do anything, on or off the field. It looked like it was
over.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the diagnosis was in, the crazy diets stopped. Painstaking
detail to nutrition, exercise and outside activities were hard for
Akers to accept at first, but they have prolonged her career.
</P>
<P>
   While teammates were parading around the Sanford Stadium field
in July 1996, draped in the American flag and accepting their
Olympic gold medals, Akers was in the locker room hooked up to an
IV. She missed most of 1997 recovering from the Olympics and
plunged into a vocal role as a born-again Christian, finding it
impossible to separate her needs for physical and spiritual
sustenance.
</P>
<P>
   ``When everything's been ripped out of your life, you become
very introspective,'' she said. ``I saw that God needs to be the
primary focus in my life and the foundation of who I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Akers has hinted that next summer's Olympics probably will bring
down the curtain on her career, but she is savoring every moment
while strictly observing the habits that have gotten her this far.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been years of paying attention to very minute details and
then stepping out on the field and seeing what's there,'' she said.
``That's the part you never really know about from day to day, but
I think I'm holding up pretty well.''
</P>
<P>
   Wendy Parker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
