<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3762 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDICARE30-COX     06-29 1089
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON MODERNIZES MEDICARE
 &HT;    980&AMP;add. With Medicareglance30.
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON - President Clinton offered a plan Tuesday to
modernize the 1960s-era Medicare program by including a
prescription drug benefit and increased competition among managed
care plans.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans in Congress immediately criticized the plan for not
providing enough protection against catastrophic medical expenses
and offering lavish coverage for the wealthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a nation bursting with prosperity, no senior should have to
choose between buying food and buying medicine,'' Clinton said,
unveiling his plan before a packed audience in the White House East
Room.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's plan would give the 38 million elderly and disabled
Medicare beneficiaries the option of having the government
subsidize half of their drug costs up to $1,000 beginning in 2002
and $5,000 when fully implemented by 2008. The government's maximum
payment then would be $2,500 per person.
</P>
<P>
   The plan would impose a $24 a month premium for the voluntary
Medicare Part D drug program. The premium would rise to $44 by
2008. The drug benefit would cost the federal government $118
billion over 10 years, much of which the administration expects
would be offset by reduced spending on hospitals and other
treatment because seniors were receiving proper medication.
</P>
<P>
   Elderly with incomes below 135 percent of the poverty line -
currently $11,000 for individuals, 17,000 for couples - would not
have to pay the drug premium.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a drug benefit our seniors can afford at a price
America can afford,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Other facets of the plan include increased competition among
managed care plans to cover a core set of benefits, elimination of
deductibles and copayments for Medicare-approved preventive care
services such as cancer screenings, and extension of the provisions
of the 1997 Balanced Budget Act which reduce payments to providers
such as hospitals and HMOs. The provisions are scheduled to expire
in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   ``The plan is credible, sensible and fiscally responsible. It
will secure the health of Medicare while improving the health of
our seniors,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's announcement fulfilled Clinton's promise last March to
offer his own Medicare reform plan after the Bipartisan Medicare
Reform Commission fell one vote short of getting the 11 votes
needed to issue a recommendation to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The commission's leaders, Sen. John Breaux, D-La., and Rep. Bill
Thomas, R-Calif., attended the White House announcement and later
said they saw Clinton's plan as a positive development - although
both were critical of numerous provisions.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's proposal does little to change Medicare's basic
structure, but with an infusion of the projected federal surplus,
it gives the program a sound fiscal future well into the next
century.
</P>
<P>
   Without changes, Medicare Part A , which pays for hospital
charges out of the payroll tax, is expected to be depleted by 2015.
Clinton's plan would take 15 percent of the surplus, nearly $800
billion over the next 15 years, and shift it into the Part A trust
fund, extending its life until 2027.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, after years of failing to provide a drug benefit
because it was considered too expensive, the fight now is likely to
be over how rather than whether to provide a prescription drug
benefit.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton wants to make it available to all Medicare
beneficiaries, but only cover a portion of the costs. Republicans
want to make it available to fewer beneficiaries, but provide
catastrophic coverage to those with extraordinarily high bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody would devise a Medicare program today, if we were
starting all over, without including a prescription drug benefit,''
Clinton said. ``We all know that these prescription drugs both save
lives and improve the quality of life, yet Medicare currently lacks
a drug benefit.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, the chairman of the House Ways and Means subcommittee on
health, which has jurisdiction over the Medicare program, said
Republicans are committed to providing drug coverage for seniors,
but in a different manner than Clinton's plan.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than giving all seniors 50 percent coverage, Thomas and
other Republicans want full drug coverage for low-income seniors
and a cap on the maximum expense beneficiaries would have to pay.
The level of the cap has not been determined.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans also oppose giving the same drug benefit to all
elderly regardless of income.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should somebody that has a $100,000 income get a federal
subsidy for prescription drugs?'' said Senate Majority Leader Trent
Lott, R-Miss.
</P>
<P>
   Florida senators split along party lines over Clinton's
proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Democrat Bob Graham hailed the drug plan and Clinton's effort to
expand coverage for preventive care screenings - a proposal similar
to one Graham made earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Medicare won't be relevant in the 21st century if we don't
cover the treatments that physicians use and patients require,''
Graham said.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Connie Mack said he was concerned Clinton's drug
proposal would result in many elderly dropping their retiree drug
benefits or supplemental Medigap policies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taxpayers will be forced to cover prescription drug costs for
those who can afford it, which is not fair,'' Mack said. ``We
should start by providing prescription drug coverage to the
approximately one-third of the Medicare population who cannot
afford it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Optional trim
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's proposal was hailed by some senior groups as a
positive starting point, but there were reservations about the
level of benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going in the right direction by creating a universal
benefit and not just a poverty benefit,'' for prescription drugs,
said Daniel Schulder, legislative director for the National Council
of Senior Citizens, a group that has a liberal orientation.
</P>
<P>
   But Schulder said his organization would like to see the
government subsidize a higher portion of the prescription costs
than the 50 percent proposed by Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Corry, federal affairs director for AARP, the nation's
largest senior organization, said ``whether we get it done this
year or next year, this is a step forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Corry said his members would have to ``chew on it a little'' to
determine whether they would support the plan with the level of
benefits Clinton proposed.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
