<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBC-ALBERT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARV ALBERT RETURNING TO NBC 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Marv Albert returned to NBC Sports Tuesday to call
National Basketball Association games nearly two years after a
trial filled with embarrassing details about his sex life led the
renowned announcer to plead guilty to a misdemeanor count of
assault and battery. NBC discharged him on the day he entered his
plea.
</P>
<P>
   The three-year NBC contract represents Albert's fourth job, one
year after he had been jobless. He calls NBA games on TNT cable for
Turner Sports and Knick games on WFAN Radio, and is host for the
``SportsDesk'' news program on the MSG Network. Turner had to
approve his NBC hiring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back a year or a year and a half ago, I thought I'd be
working, but I never took it for granted that all this would fall
into place,'' Albert said. ``There was always a distant hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Albert's salary from his four jobs will be between $2 million
and $2.5 million annually, about what it was when NBC dismissed him
and he was forced to resign from MSG.
</P>
<P>
   His rehiring at NBC does not mean a return to the No. 1
play-by-play slot, which will continue to be manned by Bob Costas.
</P>
<P>
   NBC's interest in Albert came amid his negotiations to join Fox
Sports for National Football League games. Three weeks ago, Dick
Ebersol, the chairman of NBC Sports, called Albert's agent upon
reading of the progress of the Albert-Fox talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized I'd better act immediately or I wouldn't be able to
do this for three or four years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He knew, but did not react, to being told in early May about the
Fox talks by Arthur Kaminsky, Albert's agent. A month later,
sensing that Fox could beat him, Ebersol called to negotiate a deal
with Albert. Ed Goren, the co-executive producer of Fox Sports,
said: ``I had to be a realist. You can't compete against what NBC
offered. You don't even want to.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaminsky said: ``We would have been happy to make the Fox deal.
We were making progress. Once it was clear NBC would make Marv an
offer for the NBA and the Olympics, it was much more alluring
considering what Marv does.''
</P>
<P>
   Albert will also call boxing for NBC at the 2000 Summer Olympics
in Sydney, Australia, and ice hockey for the 2002 Winter Games in
Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   NBC's decision to rehire Albert was made easier because there
has been little adverse advertiser reaction to his hiring by MSG
and Turner.
</P>
<P>
   Ebersol's desire to bring Albert back is in contrast to the
announcer's rapid dismissal in September 1997, on the day he
pleaded guilty to biting a former girlfriend during a hotel
encounter earlier that year.
</P>
<P>
   Albert assured Ebersol that he was innocent and would not plead
guilty, and when the announcer entered the plea, NBC dismissed him.
While not saying Albert would never again work at NBC _ Ebersol
said he would consider it if Albert fixed his life _ a return
seemed unlikely. ``We did what we felt we had to do,'' Ebersol
said. ``And Marv has done what he had to do in the meantime.''
</P>
<P>
   Albert completed a year of psychiatric treatment, which resulted
in the expunging of his criminal record in Arlington County, Va.,
where he was tried.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understood what had to be done and never felt `they did this
to me,''' said Albert, regarding his dismissal by NBC. ``I'm just
thrilled to be back.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
