<HEADER>
A3767 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKO-MARV-ALBERT-COX     06-29 0398
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKO-MARV-ALBERT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NBC pre-empts Fox, rehires Albert for NBA
 &HT;    By Prentis Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Marv Albert's comeback has come full circle.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, NBC announced that Albert has rejoined the network.
Athough he will not get his old job as the lead NBA play-by-play
announcer, Albert will work regional and playoff NBA telecasts for
NBC, along with boxing at the 2000 Sydney Olympics and hockey at
the 2002 Salt Lake City Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just walking back into the building was a wonderful feeling,
although the security guard did stop me,'' said Albert, who signed
a multiyear deal. ``It's hard to make a judgment on the word
'redemption.' It's better to look ahead than to look back, and
everything has gone in the right direction in the last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Albert, who spent 20 years with NBC, was fired by the network
after he was convicted of misdemeanor assault in 1997. He pleaded
guilty to charges of biting a woman during a sexual encounter in a
Virginia hotel room. He was out of broadcasting until New York's
Madison Square Garden Network re-hired him in 1998. Albert then
branched out to national cable when Turner added him to its NBA
roster.
</P>
<P>
   NBC Sports and Olympics chairman Dick Ebersol thanked Turner and
MSG for their roles in Albert's comeback and for giving their
permission to sign him. But Ebersol also said that Albert's
negotiations with Fox, which wanted him for the NFL, actually set
the wheels in motion three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was reading in the papers about the talks going on with Fox,
and that said to me the time had come to move, or the oportunity to
get Marv back would be three or four years away,'' Ebersol said.
``We did what we had to do (in 1997), but Marv has been a great
friend for a long time''
</P>
<P>
   Albert, whose duties with MSG and Turner remain the same, said
he was enticed by doing the NFL on Fox, but the lure of the NBA,
the Olympics and ultimately returning to NBC was too great.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dick and most people at NBC have been very supportive, and I
understand what had to be done,'' Albert said. ``But I didn't take
the attitude they did this to me. . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   Ebersol said Albert's NBA partner has not been
determined.Prentis Rogers writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
