</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CALIF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH MOVES TOWARD THE CENTER ON IMMIGRATION AND QUOTAS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LA JOLLA, Calif. _ George W. Bush plunged into the most populous
state Tuesday for the first time as a presidential candidate and
immediately cast himself as more temperate than most Republican
leaders here and in Washington on two emotionally charged ballot
measures that have roiled his party: immigration and affirmative
action.
</P>
<P>
   Bush distanced himself from a proposition that passed in this
state in 1994 that prohibits public services to illegal immigrants.
And he refused to endorse a proposition approved by this state's
voters in 1996 that outlawed affirmative action in the state for
hiring, employment, the education system and contracts.
</P>
<P>
   The remarks by the Texas governor marked a striking departure
for a Republican presidential candidate because both measures were
championed by the last Republican who was elected governor of
California, Pete Wilson. Bush's stand is also at odds with the
dominant position of the congressional wing of the Republican
Party. And it differs from the position of most of Bush's rivals
for the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   His comments in response to questions from reporters were the
most vivid demonstration thus far of how Bush is so confident of
his support that he has embarked on a general election strategy to
attract as broad a swath of voters as possible. With his more
moderate positions on affirmative action and immigration, Bush is
seeking to appeal to minorities and independent voters in a general
election.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's comments are all the more notable because he is setting
the tone for the Republican competition. He is swamping his
opponents in the polls here and nationwide and on this trip he has
been showered with donations and greeted by packed gatherings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wouldn't have had a 187 in my state,'' Bush said of
Proposition 187, the initiative on immigration that curtailed the
rights of illegal immigrants to public services like schools.
</P>
<P>
   Asked at a stop here whether he would have supported the
measure, Bush sidestepped the question but made his qualms clear:
``I said when it first came out I was against the spirit of 187 for
my state. I felt like every child ought to be educated regardless
of the status of his parents. I don't know what's happened in
California, but I do know that quotas won't work when it comes to
certain social obligations such as encouraging capitalism to be
spread all around the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also sounded a moderate tone in refusing to stand behind
the measure on affirmative action, Proposition 209. ``I support the
spirit of no quotas, no preferences,'' he said, ``but what's
important to say is not what you're against _ what you're for. I'm
for increasing the pool of applicants and opening the door so that
more people are eligible to go to the university systems.''
</P>
<P>
   On the first of three days of appearances up and down this state
_ the king of electoral votes with 54 _ Bush acted like he was
already running a general election: He made no mention of his
Republican rivals. He played up his success in Texas at appealing
to Hispanic voters. And he cast himself as an inclusive candidate
who would not be tugged to the right.
</P>
<P>
   It was no accident that one of Bush's stops Tuesday was at the
Plaza de Mexico, a Latino area at the Del Mar Fair near here. He
worked his way through hundreds of people, many of who greeted him
with ``Viva Bush'' chants. Pointedly, Bush delivered some of his
remarks in Spanish, in which he is fluent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I intend to win California in a general election,'' Bush
repeated again and again to the Republican faithful. ``I intend to
become the next president of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to name one Republican who was a threat to Bush in
California, state Sen. Jim Brulte, a Bush supporter, was stumped.
``Expectations,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's play-to-November strategy may not be risky in the primary
here because it may draw moderate Republicans, many of whom
defected and helped elect a Democrat, Gray Davis, last year.
</P>
<P>
   Besides putting forth more moderate positions, Bush made a play
for the Hollywood elite, who are traditionally more supportive of
Democrats and have been courted assiduously by Vice President Al
Gore. Terry Semel, the chairman of Warner Brothers and a prominent
supporter of Democrats, Tuesday held a reception for Bush at his
home in exclusive Bel Air.
</P>
<P>
   Appealing to entertainment executives who believe that President
Clinton and Gore unfairly fault Hollywood for violence, Bush said:
``All of us need to work together to change the culture. One
industry alone does not bear all the brunt.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush will again delve into Gore's territory on Thursday, when
his campaign holds fund-raising events in Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   And, Bush vowed, this is only the beginning. Pledging to
concentrate his energies in this battleground state, Bush has told
supporters that he has the luxury to focus here because he is well
positioned in two other states with huge electoral prizes: In Texas
he is the favorite son and in Florida his brother, Jeb, is
governor.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   At event after event in California, Bush was welcomed by
ebullient crowds _ as well as by expectations among many
Republicans that he can rescue their party in this state from
turmoil. No Republican has won California in a general election
since Bush's father, George Bush, won in 1988. And with the
election last year of Davis, Republicans lost control of the
governorship for the first time since 1982.
</P>
<P>
   George Gorton, who was a longtime top aide to Wilson but is
neutral in the presidential race, marveled at the outpouring for
Bush at a breakfast here Tuesday morning. ``This is the closest
thing to a legitimate draft I've ever seen in my life,'' Gorton
said. ``There are people here who are both from the right and from
the left of the party _ people you don't see in the same place.''
</P>
<P>
   At a breakfast Tuesday morning in San Diego, Gerald L. Parsky,
chairman of the Bush campaign in California, declared in his
introduction, ``Never again will you have speculation about how
aggressively Republicans should fight in California.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In random interviews at Bush's events Tuesday, many Republican
said they were not troubled by the governor's distancing himself
from the immigration and affirmative action measures that were
supported by most Republicans in California.
</P>
<P>
   John Hensley, a lawyer from Irvine, said he disagreed with Bush
on the two ballot initiatives but still expected to support him.
``It's nice to see a guy with a family and a proven track record,''
he said. ``That forgives a lot of sins. He's a good guy too, which
has a lot to do with it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Democratic officials in the state said they believed Bush
was most vulnerable for his stand against abortion and his refusal
to press for stronger gun control laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush is out of step with most Americans on gun safety, and he
is out of step with California,'' Roy Romer, the general chairman
of the Democratic Party, said in Washington on Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
