A3770 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEB-WEB_SFCHRON &LR;      06-29 0400
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEB-WEB </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   Internet Mortgage, Credit Card Firms Trying to Cash In on Online 
 Success 
 &HT;     By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; OK, you joined the crowds online to trade stock. But are you ready
to take out a credit card or get a mortgage on the Internet?
<P>
   Karen Murphy and John Lee were. The Mountain View couple got a
loan from iOwn.com, a 3-year-old Web-based mortgage broker, to buy
a $310,000 house in North Berkeley, a purchase that closed last
week.
</P>
<P>
   Their verdict? They say Web surfing got them a super rate: a
7.25 percent fixed-rate loan for $248,000 that converts to an
adjustable loan after five years, with 1 percent of the loan amount
rebated at the close of escrow.
</P>
<P>
   But the lender they found through iOwn, First Nationwide
Mortgage, peppered them with last-minute questions and demands,
causing them to miss the financing deadline in their purchase
contract. Fortunately, the seller agreed to give them more time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty nerve-racking,'' said Lee, a 31-year-old
Microsoft marketing director, about his mortgage. ``I feel
confident I got the best possible rate, and iOwn has a great
dedication to customer service. But they're still working out the
kinks.''
</P>
<P>
   That about sums up the current state of online borrowing.
Internet-only companies such as iOwn and credit card purveyor
NextCard say the Web offers great prices, broad selection and
unbeatable convenience.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can literally customize the terms for you,'' said NextCard
chief executive Jeremy Lent.
</P>
<P>
   And online mortgage companies offer rate-comparison software
that lets borrowers find the best loans available on the market
with the features they want.
</P>
<P>
   But electronic-commerce experts say the Web falls flat handling
complicated transactions in which human beings, not computers, make
the final decisions.
</P>
<P>
   A mortgage is an example of a loan that has to be individually
underwritten for each customer. Those are tougher to complete
online.
</P>
<P>
   ``Credit products go from simple to very complex,'' said Jay
Norman, a Chicago electronic-commerce specialist with the
consulting firm PricewaterhouseCoopers. ``It's the less-complex
loans that best fit the Web.''
</P>
<P>
   Credit card applications are simple because a few pieces of data
about employment, residence and income are all that's needed to
make a decision. NextCard says it grants approv
</P>
</TEXT>
