A3771 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SERIAL-KILLER-IMMIGRA     06-29 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SERIAL-KILLER-IMMIGRANTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME HISPANICS COMPLAIN THAT MANHUNT FOCUSING ON ANY MAN `WHO LOOKS
LIKE A MEXICAN' 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Ill., Ky., Texas) 
(Eds.: Graphic available on NYT database) 
(Eds.: A tilde needed over n in Zuniga) 
 
By JO ANN ZUNIGA 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Exterminator Francisco Bermea was on a recent call
when he noticed a sheriff's patrol car drive slowly by.
</P>
<P>
   The deputy had a wanted flier in her hands and was comparing
Bermea's face to the photo of accused serial killer Rafael
Resendez-Ramirez. It's a photograph familiar to most people who
have picked up a newspaper or watched a TV news program during the
last couple of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took off my glasses so the deputy could get a better look
and I said, `It's not me,''' said Bermea, a 35-year-old Mexican
native who lives in Houston but often drives his pest control truck
to outlying towns for work. ``She laughed and drove away.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand,'' said Bermea, who also is local coordinator of
the Association for Residency and Citizenship of America. ``They're
doing their job.''
</P>
<P>
   Others are not so understanding.
</P>
<P>
   Resendez-Ramirez, a Mexican national linked to at least eight
slayings in Illinois, Kentucky and Texas, is on the FBI's Ten Most
Wanted list. As the manhunt grows, some Hispanics are complaining
that any man ``who looks like a Mexican'' is considered a suspect.
</P>
<P>
   ``We as Hispanics are stereotyped anyway,'' said Maria Jimenez,
local director of another immigrants' rights group, the American
Friends Service Committee. ``So with thousands of calls coming from
all over the country, law enforcement and others need to be
cautious while engaging in a search. They need to make sure they're
individualizing their search instead of generalizing a whole
population.''
</P>
<P>
   Fernando Garcia, coordinator in El Paso of the Immigration Law
Enforcement Project, said the phenomenon is most intense along the
border.
</P>
<P>
   ``The climate is that the sheriff's deputies and Border Patrol
are stopping almost everyone if they look like a Mexican,'' Garcia
said. ``People are getting arrested for just walking on the
(railroad) tracks. It's getting out of hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia fears the search for Resendez-Ramirez could hurt Hispanic
immigrants in the long run.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here on the border, it's almost normal to be detained,'' he
said. ``But we are worried that the government will use this for
political gains to make tougher immigration laws or argue again for
troops on the border.''
</P>
<P>
   A Marine Corp patrol, deployed during an anti-drug surveillance
operation in 1997, shot and killed an 18-year-old goat herder in
West Texas. The use of Marines on anti-drug operations along the
border was later suspended, and the troops were withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
   Immigration and law enforcement officials say they are being
careful to protect the rights of innocent people. But they vow an
aggressive search, noting that the suspect is accused of
particularly vicious crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Union Pacific Railroad Co. police are teaming up with the FBI,
the U.S. Border Patrol and other law enforcement agencies in the
search for Resendez-Ramirez. The victims were all killed in homes
near railroad tracks, and the suspect is believed to travel the
country by hopping on and off freight trains. Most of the victims
were bludgeoned to death, and most of the women were sexually
assaulted. Fingerprints and other physical evidence point to
Resendez-Ramirez, police say.
</P>
<P>
   Union Pacific police are inspecting trains and yards along
routes in 23 states, looking for people who illegally ride the
rails. They are stopping trains whenever they get a tip, said
company spokesman John Bromley.
</P>
<P>
   ``We stop an average of 10 to 12 trains a day,'' Bromley said
from Union Pacific's Omaha, Neb., headquarters. ``We have had 14
such incidents in the last 24 hours on reports of trespassers on
the yard or rail.''
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, agents walk alongside the trains with dogs
sniffing each car. If a dog signals that something is wrong, the
agents will open a car and search it.
</P>
<P>
   Union Pacific police removed about 97,000 trespassers from rail
property last year, Bromley said. Half of those were illegal
immigrants, he said, mostly Hispanic males.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a zero tolerance for trespassers even before this
search,'' he said. ``But before, we would just order them to leave
the property. Now we're taking more time to identify them.''
</P>
<P>
   Railroad police for Fort Worth, Texas-based Burlington Northern
Santa Fe Corp. also are working with the Border Patrol to search
trains. Spokesman Richard Russack said the FBI has requested that
company to remain on the lookout for the suspect.
</P>
<P>
   In Houston, FBI spokesman Rolando Moss said there were no new
developments in the case, adding that the multi-agency task force
searching for Resendez-Ramirez continues to follow up on some of
the many leads it receives each day.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
