<HEADER>
A3776 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-MARKETPLACE-NYT     06-29 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: BY ANY OTHER NAME, COULD CHINA.COM BE SO CONFIDENT? 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ In the helium-filled world of Internet investing, a
lot can ride on a new company's name. When that name is China.com,
you might reasonably assume its stock would float on gossamer
wings.
</P>
<P>
   After all, China.com Corp. combines two of the decade's hottest
investment concepts _ China and the Internet _ in a single stock
offering. While both have lost a bit of their luster among
investors in recent weeks, China.com seems convinced that putting
them together will prove irresistible.
</P>
<P>
   The company, based in Hong Kong, plans to raise $56.3 million
through an initial public offering on the NASDAQ stock market in
two weeks. It began its road show for investors, at a lavish lunch
in Hong Kong on Tuesday, with a familiar mixture of intoxicating
predictions and fuzzy details.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe we have presented one of the most exciting
investment opportunities in Asia,'' said Peter Yip, the vice
chairman and chief executive of China.com. ``No other company has
our integrated approach.''
</P>
<P>
   Yip noted that the number of Internet users in China was
projected to rise from 2.4 million in 1998 to 16.1 million in 2003,
a compound annual growth rate of 46 percent. As the first public
company to tap that vast market, Yip believes, China.com will be
one of the cyberheavyweights of Asia.
</P>
<P>
   It is a tantalizing prospect _ one that lured America Online to
buy 10 percent of China.com for $25 million earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at China.com's investment bank, Lehman Brothers, said
the offering was already oversubscribed. And analysts predicted
that China.com would take off like a rocket after the shares begin
trading.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company has a great name,'' said Kaushik Shridharani, a
media analyst at Salomon Smith Barney in Hong Kong. ``That will
drive investor enthusiasm for the stock, because most investors
don't delve into the details.''
</P>
<P>
   The details in China.com's case are eye-opening. Despite its
all-encompassing name, China.com does most of its business in Hong
Kong, where it operates an Internet portal service called
hongkong.com, an Internet advertising service and a Web design and
consulting business.
</P>
<P>
   China.com's Hong Kong portal _ and a similar one on Taiwan _
offer a menu of services, from English- and Chinese-language news
and information to e-mail, search engines and message boards.
</P>
<P>
   The company does operate a portal called china.com, which is
aimed at users in mainland China, but technology executives said it
generated little traffic. In a recent ranking of Web sites
conducted by the Chinese government, it placed 17th, behind
destinations like Sinanet and Sohu.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given all the PR they've created, they really should be
generating more traffic,'' said Hanson Cheah, the executive
director of Asia Tech Ventures, a venture capital firm here that
specializes in Internet companies.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Farrall, an expert on the Internet in China who runs a
consulting firm in New York, said: ``China.com has never been a
factor in the Internet business in China. It doesn't register on
the radar screen.''
</P>
<P>
   China.com said Tuesday that it had 400,000 registered users of
its three main portals. The company said it recorded 1 million
``page views'' a day, and would double that by year's end.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, China.com chief operating officer Peter
Hamilton acknowledged that the number of users ``doesn't satisfy
our internal objectives.'' But he added, ``We're satisfied with the
growth rate.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton said the company's critics were placing too much
emphasis on its relatively low traffic. He said the company could
expand its reach through its regional advertising service, 24/7,
which places ads on Web sites in 11 Asian and Pacific Rim
countries, from Japan to Australia.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you build a business based solely on China, you're going to
have a long and hungry wait for ad revenue,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Like most fledgling Internet companies, China.com has never made
money. In 1998, it reported losses of $11 million on revenue of
$3.4 million. More than three-quarters of its sales come from its
Web consulting business. And China.com said it would not turn a
profit until 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its meager revenues, China.com has been able to attract
an impressive array of U.S. technology companies as partners. They
include Netscape Communications, Bay Networks, Sun Microsystems,
Pointcast, and most recently, America Online. But the critics note
that most of these partnerships have fizzled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have any of China.com's ventures become real businesses?''
Cheah asked. ``As far as I can tell, none.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps China.com's most sensitive relationship is with Xinhua,
China's official news agency. Xinhua is one of the original
investors and still owns a 13.6 percent stake. In addition to
supplying China.com with mainland news, Xinhua edits news from
Reuters and Agence France-Presse that is distributed on the
company's Chinese site _ deleting references to Taiwan and Tibet.
</P>
<P>
   Yip said it was an honor to work with Xinhua, adding, ``As we
all know, the Internet business in China is highly regulated.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the questions about its business, China.com has a couple
of probable advantages.
</P>
<P>
   It is the first China-focused Internet company to go public, and
it is doing so at a time when analysts say investors in the United
States are becoming jaded by the constant stream of Silicon Valley
start-ups.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, it is entering the market at a time when other
high-profile Chinese companies are stepping out. China National
Petroleum Corp., the country's biggest oil company, and China
Unicom, a rival to the dominant China Telecom , are both planning
major share offerings.
</P>
<P>
   With potential investors overflowing a hotel ballroom in Hong
Kong, the buzz surrounding China.com was unmistakable. Shridharani
said such interest was bound to result in disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   ``To the extent that expectations are shaped by what's going on
in the States, investors are going to be disappointed,'' he said.
``This company is going to grow fast, but not on a scale that will
excite investors.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
