<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3779 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-TREASURY-SCANDAL-B     06-29 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-TREASURY-SCANDAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE SEE EARLY LINK BETWEEN SUSPECTS IN TREASURY THEFTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHEN KURKJIAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Less than a year after he was promoted to deputy
Treasurer, Robert Foley approached the manager of the state's
Unpaid Check Fund with a scheme to loot millions of dollars from
the fund, according to a State Police affidavit released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next six years, conspiring with two businessmen and
their own wives, Foley and John F. Trischitta allegedly stole
nearly $10 million in checks intended for companies that were owed
money by the state.
</P>
<P>
   According to the affidavit released in Boston Municipal Court,
Foley and Trischitta, both of whom were arrested in the theft last
February, were able to carry out what is alleged to be the largest
theft of state money in the Commonwealth's history without raising
the suspicions of supervisors and auditors inside the office of
State Treasurer Joseph Malone.
</P>
<P>
   Foley even cashed more than $179,000 in stolen checks at the
Treasurer's office, according to the affidavit, which was based for
the most part on the testimony of Trischitta, who is cooperating
with the investigation by Attorney General Thomas Reilly's office.
</P>
<P>
   What emerges from the affidavit is an insider's portrait how
Trischitta, who started his state career as a driver for Treasurer
Robert Q. Crane, and Foley, an ambitious, political appointee of
Malone's who juggled private work on state time, were able to treat
the fund as their own personal bank account.
</P>
<P>
   Trischitta agreed to cooperate with investigators on the second
day he was questioned by Reilly's investigators about the missing
money. In exchange for Trischitta's cooperation, Reilly's office
has agreed to recommend that he be sentenced to no more than five
years and a day in state prison. Theft by a state employee from the
state's treasury, the statute under which Trischitta and Foley
would be charged, carries a maximum sentence of life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Although the thefts from the state Treasury exploded into public
view in mid-February with the arrest of Trischitta and then Foley,
the affidavit provides the first detailed description of how the
two men allegedly hatched their scheme, pulled off the series of
the thefts and then worked to cover them up.
</P>
<P>
   The affidavit discloses for the first time that the two men
worked together and involved their wives in the scheme. To split up
some of the stolen money with an heir finder who was part of the
alleged scheme, Trischitta's wife and Foley's now-former wife, were
falsely listed as working for the heir finder's firm and issued
payroll checks to cover their husbands' share of the take.
</P>
<P>
   It is not known if Reilly's office -- which had no comment on
Tuesday's release of the affidavit -- is considering prosecuting
the two women.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that Trischitta had no past criminal record and that he
was cooperating in the investigation, Judith Lindahl, Trischitta's
lawyer, said that Reilly's recommended sentence was not lenient.
Gary L. Meyers, Foley's lawyer, had no comment on the allegations
in the affidavit.
</P>
<P>
   No charges are currently pending against either Foley or
Trischitta or two heir finders, Martin Robbins of Danvers and
Thomas Ciliberto, of Warwick, R.I., who have been implicated in the
scheme.
</P>
<P>
   All four were charged in Boston Municipal Court in February and
March with various counts of theft and bribery brought by Reilly's
office. However, Reilly last month asked that the charges be
dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   Saying that his investigators had found a woeful lack of
documents in the Unpaid Check Fund to build a paper trail, Reilly
said more time was needed to unravel the complicated dealings and
determine if more money had been stolen and if others were
involved.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly recently told reporters that he is confident that the
Suffolk County grand jury, which is taking testimony in the case,
will return indictments. The affidavit provides some basis for
Reilly's confidence.
</P>
<P>
   According to the affidavit, Trischitta told investigators that
he and Foley devised the scheme to plunder the Unpaid Check Fund in
late 1992 or early 1993 shortly after Foley was promoted as Deputy
Treasurer, overseeing cash management for the entire state
Treasury. The fund contained millions of dollars in checks issued
by the state to private firms that for a variety of reasons were
never received or went uncashed.
</P>
<P>
   Trischitta said that Foley first proposed that Trischitta leave
his position as the fund's manager and open up an heir finder's
firm, which would notify companies of the unclaimed checks and --
for a healthy fee -- work to get the money to them. However,
Trischitta said he turned down Foley's offer because he didn't want
to lose the health insurance and pension benefits that came with
his state job.
</P>
<P>
   A short time later, Trischitta said, Foley came to him with
another offer. He wanted him to approve a claim -- which Foley
acknowledged was phony -- to issue a series of checks amounting to
$1.6 million to DeMatteo Construction Co. of Braintree.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Trischitta said Foley told him the money would be split
up, with each of them getting $200,000 and ``connected people''
getting the lion's share of the money, $1.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the phony claim, Foley told Trischitta, ``We take
this to our grave.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the fund was filled with a hundreds of checks, most
amounting to less than a thousand dollars, Trischitta said Foley
told him not to put any checks for more than $5,000 on the lists
given to heir finders.
</P>
<P>
   Those larger checks were provided solely to Ciliberto, a close
friend of Foley's partner in an accounting firm, who operated an
heir finder business between 1993-1997, according to the affidavit.
</P>
<P>
   Trischitta said he routinely approved the claims filed with
Ciliberto's firm, The Reinke Group, and in return he and Foley
recived 50 percent of the profits. To cover up their involvement in
the scheme, Trischitta's wife and Foley's wife were listed as
employees of Reinke.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993 alone, Trischitta said, his wife received about $79,000
in checks from Reinke. In the following years, he estimated she
received about $50,000 a year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
