<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3780 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Y2K-LAWSUITS-ART-2TAK     06-29 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-LAWSUITS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BREAKING WITH PARTY, CLINTON TO APPROVE LIMITS ON YEAR 2000
COMPUTER LAWSUITS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(rm) 
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Infuriating many Democrats, the White House on
Tuesday reached a basic agreement with Republicans in Congress on
legislation to limit lawsuits arising from Year 2000 computer
breakdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders said that all the main points had been
settled and that they hoped Congress would clear the measure for
the president's signature this week. The White House agreed that
only technical language remained to be worked out.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, aggressively promoted by business interests and
the computer industry and opposed by trial lawyers and consumer
groups, generally follows the lines of the bill approved by the
Senate two weeks ago. Most Democrats voted against that bill, and
President Clinton promised at the time to veto it.
</P>
<P>
   A White House spokesman said some relatively minor changes
enabled the president to approve the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   As described by lawmakers from both parties, it would set a
ceiling on punitive damages against small companies, give all
companies a grace period to fix breakdowns before they could be
sued, sharply limit class-action suits involving many plaintiffs
and protect wealthy companies against being held responsible for
computer failures caused by poorer ones.
</P>
<P>
   Many angry Democrats in the Senate and House said the White
House had encouraged them to cast a politically risky vote for the
bill and then sold them out.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a closed-door deal that will hurt consumers,'' said
Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt. ``Maybe we can dare hope that this will
be the last case of triangulation of the 20th century.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Triangulation'' is a term coined by Dick Morris, President
Clinton's former political adviser, to mean that the president
should not stand with Democrats or Republicans but at points above
or between them. Democrats use it nowadays to express their
irritation when Clinton does not follow the party line.
</P>
<P>
   What is called the Y2K problem results from the longtime
reliance of computer programs on only the last two digits of a
year. When confronted by 00, some computers, software and
electronically controlled machinery that have not been updated
might misinterpret it as 1900 rather than 2000, substitute another
year or simply freeze.
</P>
<P>
   These are the main aspects of the legislation:
</P>
<P>
   _ Companies with fewer than 50 employees could not be assessed
more than $250,000 in punitive damages.
</P>
<P>
   _ All companies would be given 90 days to fix a problem from the
time they were notified before they could be sued.
</P>
<P>
   _ No more than 100 plaintiffs could be involved in a
class-action suit, and no more than $10 million in damages could be
sought.
</P>
<P>
   _ Class-action suits would be diverted from state courts to
federal courts, making them more expensive and burdensome for
plaintiffs.
</P>
<P>
   _ All companies responsible for a computer failure would share
the legal liability, and large, wealthy companies could not be
forced to pay damages beyond their proportional responsibility in
cases in which less affluent or bankrupt businesses are also at
fault.
</P>
<P>
   The central purpose of the measure is to prevent frivolous
lawsuits. But critics said there were insufficient protections for
consumers who suffered financial loss because of computer failures.
</P>
<P>
   A White House spokesman said President Clinton's main interest
was that the measure was confined to Year 2000 computer problems
and did not involve general tort reform.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the spokesman said small changes involving class
action suits and the proportional liability provisions convinced
the president that the bill was worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., was instrumental in working out
the deal. Insurance companies in Connecticut are especially
interested in limiting lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Business interests were gleeful. Thomas Donohue, president of
the U.S. Chamber of Commerce, which made the legislation its top
lobbying priority of the year, called it ``a watershed achievement
for business and the American economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Jasinowski, president of the National Association of
Manufacturers, said ``a potential global technology crisis'' had
been avoided.
</P>
<P>
   But groups representing consumers were critical. When computer
problems develop, ``the public is going to be very angry, and small
businesses are going to be the most affected,'' said Joan
Claybrook, president of Public Citizen.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Complicating the work on the bill all year has been the desire
of both parties to win the political and financial support of
wealthy individuals and companies in the computer industry.
</P>
<P>
   A Republican strategist in Congress said his party was not
willing to give much in the negotiations because the president was
over a barrel. If he vetoed the bill, it would have hurt Vice
President Al Gore specifically and Democrats generally in their
quest for support in Silicon Valley. By accepting the agreement, in
this view, the president gave Republicans what they wanted.
</P>
<P>
   A Democratic strategist added another element. He said Vice
President Gore, as he begins his campaign for the presidency, was
eager to rid himself of the taint of financial support from trial
lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   The conflict between trial lawyers, who are among Democrats'
biggest campaign contributors, and business interests, which are
the Republicans' biggest donors, has been a thread running through
legislative battles for the last several years. Among other issues,
it has arisen on product liability legislation, antismoking
measures and bills to regulate managed-care health plans.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic strategist said that for Gore, the money from the
trial lawyers was probably not worth the criticism he faced for
taking funds from an unpopular source. But that may not be the
case, the strategist said, for Democrats in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   In a careful statement Tuesday, Mark Mandell, president of the
Association of Trial Lawyers of America, said, ``It is positive
that this unique response to a unique situation will be law for
only three years and that the legal rights of anyone who suffers a
physical injury are preserved.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
