<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICHAEL HOOKER, PRESIDENT OF UMASS, 1992-95; AT 53 
</HEADLINE>
   (Attn.: N.C.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE ZERNIKE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Michael Hooker, who set a bold vision for reform as
president of the University of Massachusetts but left the task
early to head his beloved alma mater, the University of North
Carolina-Chapel Hill, died Tuesday. He was 53.
</P>
<P>
   Considered a rising star from his earliest days _ the first in
his family to go to college, a college president at age 37 _ Hooker
was diagnosed with non-Hodgkins lymphoma in January.
</P>
<P>
   He took a two-month leave from his job as chancellor at Chapel
Hill this spring to undergo experimental treatment at the National
Institutes of Health. He had returned, working from home, earlier
this month.
</P>
<P>
   He chaired, by conference call, a meeting of his cabinet Monday
morning, and worked into the evening, before being admitted to the
University Hospital, where he died just before 2 a.m. Tuesday from
complications related to the cancer.
</P>
<P>
   In three years as chancellor of the nation's oldest public
university, Hooker had become both an agent of change and a beloved
figure _ one friend recalled Chapel Hill students hoisting him up
and passing him through the crowds at a basketball game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just radiated personal energy and intellectual energy, he
drew people along in his wake,'' said Daniel Taylor, the former
head of the UMass trustees, who led the search committee that chose
Hooker unanimously as its president in 1992. ``He was a very
important figure in the history of the university.''
</P>
<P>
   In three years at UMass, Hooker was credited with securing more
state funding for the university and combining the five campuses
into one system. He set an ambitious five-year plan to make the
system ``world class'' by 2000, demanding that each campus compare
itself to its peers nationwide, and strive to meet higher
standards. Many of the things his plan called for _ eliminating
undersubscribed programs, raising admissions standards _ set the
foundation for the elevation of the university's reputation under
its new leader, former Senate President William M. Bulger.
</P>
<P>
   The son of a Virginia coal miner, Hooker was raised from a young
age to appreciate the value of an education. His parents decided
early they would have only one child, so they could afford to make
him the family's first college graduate.
</P>
<P>
   He earned his doctorate at UMass-Amherst. As a teacher of
philosophy at Harvard in the mid-1970s, Hooker once said he used to
watch President Derek Bok and dream of becoming a college
president. He did so at 37, becoming president of Bennington
College just in time to rescue it from financial disaster. Two
years later, Esquire magazine featured him in a story on the ``Best
of the New Generation.'' Later, at the University of
Maryland-Baltimore County, Hooker was credited with bringing more
and better-qualified minority students on campus, and smoothing
racial tensions.
</P>
<P>
   Hooker believed in, and spoke eloquently about, the need to
stress the original purpose of public, so-called Land Grant
universities, which the federal government created to make sure the
citizens of each state could not only be educated, but serve the
needs of the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Universities have a reputation more deserved than we want to
admit for being self-righteously arrogant and disdainful of the
outside world,'' he told a Globe columnist in 1993, a year into his
term. ``But the world has changed. We have to wallow in the muck of
human problems without the luxury of standing aside and smugly
criticizing others for not solving problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Bulger said Tuesday, ``Michael Hooker recognized that the first
responsibility of a university is that of education, and the
community would be repaid for its investment through the service
performed by individuals in their subsequent lives and careers. He
served this community well and will be greatly missed by all of us
who knew him personally.''
</P>
<P>
   Professors and administrators criticized Hooker for leaving
UMass early, just three months after he announced his five-year
improvement plan, and three years into his term. He had promised to
stay 10 years. In a state where private colleges had long had a
lock on academic prestige, Hooker admitted it had been harder than
he realized to increase what he called ``public affection'' for
UMass. It would take Bulger, with well-developed social, business,
and political connections, to attract the money and support for the
public university.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, though, Hooker explained the move as a sort of
homecoming. As a child, his parents had taken him on tours of
campuses, with UNC one of their earliest stops.
</P>
<P>
   He adopted as the motto for the system, ``For the People,'' and
toured all of North Carolina's 100 counties to remind citizens of
the contributions UNC made to the community, emphasizing that what
had become known as an elitist university really did belong to the
taxpayers who fund it.
</P>
<P>
   An early believer of the importance of technology in higher
education, Hooker developed a program, partly funded by private
companies, that will ensure that each freshman has a laptop
computer by this fall. Nationally, he served on several panels on
technology in education, as well as one to enlist college students
in the effort to get elementary school students reading by third
grade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Years from now, when we look back, what will be routine for
everybody, he thought of five years ago,'' said Mary Anne Marsh, a
Democratic political consultant in Massachusetts, who worked with
Hooker here and in North Carolina. ``He was light years ahead of
his time, and he died long before his time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael Hooker brought a remarkable level of energy and a
compelling vision to this campus over the past four years,'' said
UNC-Chapel Hill Provost Dick Richardson. ``Chapel Hill has been
forever changed by the agenda that Michael placed before all of us.
He was a wonderful harbinger of the new millennium. We will all be
challenged by what he wanted this place, which he loved so much, to
become.''
</P>
<P>
   Hooker met Carmen Buell, a state legislator from Greenfield, at
a UMass basketball game in 1993, and married her in 1995 with a
reception at the Mullins Center at Amherst.
</P>
<P>
   He leaves his wife, of Chapel Hill; his daughter, Alexandra
Hooker, of Baltimore; his mother, Christine Hooker, of Roanoke,
Va.; and his wife's daughters, Jennifer and Cyndi Buell, both of
Charlotte.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
