<HEADLINE>
HORMEL SWORN IN AS NATION'S FIRST OPENLY GAY AMBASSADOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ San Francisco gay rights advocate James C. Hormel
was sworn in Tuesday as U.S. ambassador to Luxembourg by Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright, who told more than 300 wellwishers,
``This is one of those glorious days when the nice guy finishes
first.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright said Hormel's installation was intended to send a
message that ``neither race nor creed nor sexual orientation is
relevant to the selection of an ambassador to the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   She said Hormel ``never lost his sense of humor, dignity and
graciousness'' while he was under attack by Senate conservatives
who blocked his nomination for 18 months because he is gay. Senate
Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss. _ who compared homosexuality
with alcoholism, kleptomania and sex addiction _ refused to bring
the matter up for a vote.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, President Clinton on June 4 announced he was giving
Hormel a recess appointment while Congress was not in session.
</P>
<P>
   Hormel, 66, who became America's first openly gay ambassador, is
an heir to the Hormel meatpacking fortune and is a former dean of
the University of Chicago Law School.
</P>
<P>
   Tanned and wearing a navy suit, red tie and white shirt, Hormel
took the oath of office on his father's Bible, swearing he would
``support and defend the Constitution of the United States against
all enemies foreign and domestic.'' The Bible was held by his
partner, Timothy Wu, 36, a San Francisco fundraiser.
</P>
<P>
   The ceremony was held on a platform in the State Department's
main reception room, which has eight large crystal chandeliers and
tall gilded columns.
</P>
<P>
   After more than two minutes of applause, Hormel praised
President Clinton for appointing him. He also thanked his five
children, who stood to one side of the stage, and Wu, who will
become a White House fellow this fall. Hormel said of Wu, ``His
wisdom and resilience enabled both of us to endure
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-99 2027EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
