<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HORMEL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HORMEL SWORN IN AS NATION'S FIRST OPENLY GAY AMBASSADOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ San Francisco gay rights advocate James C. Hormel
was sworn in Tuesday as U.S. ambassador to Luxembourg by Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright, who told more than 300 wellwishers,
``This is one of those glorious days when the nice guy finishes
first.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright said Hormel's installation was intended to send a
message that ``neither race nor creed nor sexual orientation is
relevant to the selection of an ambassador to the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   She said Hormel ``never lost his sense of humor, dignity and
graciousness'' while he was under attack by Senate conservatives
who blocked his nomination for 18 months because he is gay. Senate
Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss. _ who compared homosexuality
with alcoholism, kleptomania and sex addiction _ refused to bring
the matter up for a vote.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, President Clinton on June 4 announced he was giving
Hormel a recess appointment while Congress was not in session.
</P>
<P>
   Hormel, 66, who became America's first openly gay ambassador, is
an heir to the Hormel meatpacking fortune and is a former dean of
the University of Chicago Law School.
</P>
<P>
   Tanned and wearing a navy suit, red tie and white shirt, Hormel
took the oath of office on his father's Bible, swearing he would
``support and defend the Constitution of the United States against
all enemies foreign and domestic.'' The Bible was held by his
partner, Timothy Wu, 36, a San Francisco fundraiser.
</P>
<P>
   The ceremony was held on a platform in the State Department's
main reception room, which has eight large crystal chandeliers and
tall gilded columns.
</P>
<P>
   After more than two minutes of applause, Hormel praised
President Clinton for appointing him. He also thanked his five
children, who stood to one side of the stage, and Wu, who will
become a White House fellow this fall. Hormel said of Wu, ``His
wisdom and resilience enabled both of us to endure this challenging
time.''
</P>
<P>
   The new envoy added that thousands of letters of support had
encouraged him to ``stay the course.'' His favorite, he said, came
from a 93-year-old grandmother who said she had prayed she would
live long enough to see him sworn in.
</P>
<P>
   Another speaker was Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., a longtime
friend of Hormel. She said, ``Somewhere along the line we have to
stand up for what we believe is right. This one was right.'' She
then kissed Hormel on both cheeks and blinked back a tear.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., who also spoke, said, ``Bigotry
based on sexual orientation is wrong anywhere, anytime and any
place.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Hormel shook hands and chatted with hundreds of his
supporters in a receiving line. He said he plans to leave for
Luxembourg within a month. Wu, who stood with Hormel, said he and
Hormel ``always had faith that this was going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Nancy Pelosi, D-Calif., called Hormel ``a special person''
and added, ``He's been an ambassador all his life.''
</P>
<P>
   Hormel's former wife, Alice Turner, who also attended the
ceremony, said the whole family had felt ``under attack.'' She said
the experience ``has been very powerful'' for their five children.
``They've been there for him. This has been a family cause.''
</P>
<P>
   Hormel's daughter, Sarah Hormel of Charlottesville, Va., said it
has been ``kind of hard knowing that there are 10 websites''
attacking her father for his homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   But she added, ``My father deserves this more than anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Another guest, San Francisco Treasurer Susan Leal said the
Senate had put Hormel ``through hell.''
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco Supervisor Mark Leno added that he hopes Hormel's
appointment will usher in a new chapter of tolerance. ``The hateful
derision directed at Jim for 18 months was inexcusable,'' Leno
said.
</P>
<P>
   Alvin Baum, a San Francisco psychotherapist, said he thought
Hormel's appointment will help to dispel prejudices of homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   Hormel was twice was named to U.S. delegations to the United
Nations before being nominated as ambassador to Luxembourg, a tiny
country with 425,000 people that is 97 percent Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   The job of ambassador to Luxembourg, a place unfamiliar to most
Americans, became famous briefly when it was held from 1949 to 1953
by a wealthy woman named Perle Mesta. Her adventures as the
``hostess with the mostest'' became the basis for ``Call Me
Madam,'' an Irving Berlin Broadway musical starring Ethel Merman.
</P>
<P>
   About a half dozen protesters appeared at the main entrance of
the State Department as Hormel was being sworn in. They displayed
copies of what they said was pedophilia and pornography from a wing
of San Francisco's main public library that Hormel supported with a
$500,000 gift.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is unfit to be ambassador,'' said Andrea Sheldon, executive
director of the Traditional Values Coalition, a Christian group, in
an interview. ``He has been the major financier of the homosexual
movement.''
</P>
<P>
   ``His library may be the community standard in San Francisco,
but he does not represent the values and beliefs of the American
people at large,'' Sheldon said.
</P>
<P>
   Wendy Wright, spokeswoman for Concerned Women for America, a
conservative religious advocacy group, said Clinton's appointment
of Hormel was ``an end run around the Constitution.'' Hormel, she
said, ``is seen as a leader of a group that opposes laws and
viewpoints that support traditional families and morals.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
