<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: NANNY'S PARENTS CHARGED
</P>
<P>
   The parents of Louise Woodward, the English nanny convicted of
manslaughter in the death of an infant in Boston in 1997, have been
charged by the police with theft from the trust fund set up to pay
for their daughter's defense. Sue Woodward, 42, and Gary Woodward,
43, who are separated, were charged with fraud. Their lawyer, Neil
Cobley, said they were accused of forging expense claims from their
time in the U.S. during the trial. ``The charges are vigorously
denied,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   VATICAN: POPE'S MIDEAST `YEARNING'
</P>
<P>
   Pope John Paul II said he had a ``strong yearning'' to visit
holy sites in the Middle East next year, but he omitted the names
of cities, including Ur, in Iraq, Mount Sinai in Egypt, and
Nazareth, Bethlehem and Jerusalem, that were included in his
prepared text. The Vatican did not explain why the pope left out
specific places. But negotiations with Israeli officials over a
planned stop in Jerusalem have long been problematic.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: GUN LICENSE RECALL
</P>
<P>
   The Interior Ministry acknowledged that it had illegally issued
``some 20 to 30'' gun licenses to TV stars and others who were
falsely identified as government officials. The ministry said it
had ordered the licenses retrieved, but refused to identify those
who received them or explain why they were given out. The
irregularities came under scrutiny with the recent gangland murder
of Francisco Stanley, an entertainer in whose clothing authorities
found an illegal gun license and a bag of cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   CHINA: 2 DISSIDENTS SEIZED
</P>
<P>
   The police arrested two of Beijing's most active dissidents,
seizing documents and a computer from their homes, a human rights
group said. The arrested men, Gao Hongming and Zha Jianguo, are
supporters of the outlawed China Democracy Party. Since early May
China has at least temporarily detained more than 190 dissidents
and 30 remain in custody, according to the Information Center of
Human Rights and Democratic Movement in China, based in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA: MUSLIMS SLAIN
</P>
<P>
   At least 18 Muslim villagers were murdered by gunmen in two
incidents in the Poonch district of the state of Jammu and Kashmir,
the police said. While authorities said the deaths appear to be the
work of rival groups of Kashmiri separatists, one militant
organization accused security forces of striking at the relatives
of its members.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA: ENVOY REPORTED BEATEN
</P>
<P>
   Government officials in New Delhi said one of their diplomatic
employees in Islamabad had been pulled from his car and beaten by
Pakistani ``intelligence operatives.'' The reported attack occurred
just a day after India ordered the expulsion of a Pakistani
diplomat accused of spying.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: COALITION NEARING
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister-elect Ehud Barak moved closer toward finalizing
his coalition government, signing a deal as expected with the
ultra-Orthodox United Torah Judaism and moving toward signing a
deal with the Center Party. United Torah Judaism will not accept a
ministry in the government; the Center Party's leader, Yitzhak
Mordechai, is expected to be the transportation minister.
Negotiations with the ultra-Orthodox Shas Party were continuing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
