<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PREVENTIVE-CARE (Washington) _ President Clinton's proposed
overhaul of Medicare includes a provision long sought by health
care advocates _ a plan for Uncle Sam to pay the entire cost of
diagnostic tests designed to prevent serious illnesses. The tests,
such as mammograms, colorectal cancer screening and bone-density
measurements, were part of the administration's 1993 health care
plan overseen by First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton. By STEWART M.
POWELL. (2ndld-writethru filed.)
</P>
<P>
   HORMEL (Washington) _ San Francisco gay rights advocate James C.
Hormel is scheduled to be sworn in as U.S. ambassador to Luxembourg
as conservative groups protest outside the State Department. Hormel
will become the first openly gay U.S. envoy. By JUDY HOLLAND.
(Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   NUCLEAR-SAFETY (Washington) _ Congressional investigators say
the University of California should be fined for safety violations
at its Lawrence Livermore and Los Alamos nuclear weapons
laboratories. Violations included exposing workers to radioactivity
and having lax procedures for preventing nuclear accidents. By MARK
HELM. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-2000 (Los Angeles) _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush begins his
California campaign and fund-raising swing with a reception in a
town rarely graced by Republican presidential candidates:
Hollywood. Terry Semel, the co-chairman of Warner Bros. and a
longtime Democratic fund-raiser, is hosting an event for Bush. By
R.G. RATCLIFFE.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-CALIFORNIA (Los Angeles) _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush
campaigns for the Hispanic vote on his maiden trip to California as
the early front-runner for the Republican presidential nomination.
By LAURA TOLLEY. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SERIAL-KILLER-IMMIGRANTS (Houston) _ With a nationwide manhunt
for suspected serial killer Rafael Resendez-Ramirez under way, some
Hispanics are complaining that any man ``who looks like a Mexican''
is considered a suspect. Fernando Garcia, coordinator in El Paso of
the Immigration Law Enforcement Project, said the phenomenon is
most intense along the U.S.-Mexican border. By JOANN ZUNIGA.
(Graphic available on NYT database.)
</P>
<P>
   ESCAPEE-TEXAS (Undated) _ Convicted killer Clifford Jones, who
spent two nights nearly naked in the East Texas woods after fleeing
one of the state's most secure prisons, surrenders to Texas
authorities about 2 1/2 miles from the prison northeast of
Huntsville. By PATTY REINERT. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush has the
same careless attitude toward the Constitution that his father did.
The governor has not only embraced a proposed constitutional
amendment to ban flag burning, as President George Bush did, but
also endorsed an outrageous House measure that would allow states
to permit posting the Ten Commandments in schools and other public
places. By MARIANNE MEANS. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BKN-DREAM (Houston) _ From a basketball standpoint, it makes
sense for the Houston Rockets to trade Hakeem Olajuwon. But from a
public-relations view, it could be a nightmare. And that is exactly
what is holding the Rockets back from finalizing the deal to unload
their franchise center. By JONATHAN FEIGEN.
</P>
<P>
   With: BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN
</P>
<P>
   BKN-NBA-DRAFT (Undated) _ Advance on the NBA Draft, focusing on
whether Elton Brand will be the top pick by the Chicago Bulls. By
MICHAEL MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-ASTROS (Houston) _ The Houston Astros try to snap their
longest losing streak of the season at the Astrodome as they open a
three-game series against Mark McGwire and the St. Louis Cardinals.
By CARLTON THOMPSON.
</P>
