<HEADER>
A3795 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MINDSPRING30-COX     06-29 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINDSPRING30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MindSpring, Covad expand collaboration on high-speed lines
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ MindSpring Enterprises and Covad Communications are
expected today to announce an expansion of their deal to jointly
provide high-speed lines _ the route customers increasingly use to
reach the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement extends an alliance that the two have already
formed to deliver the rapid connections known as digital subscriber
lines or DSL.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based MindSpring last week touched off speculation about
a possible merger or major acquisition when it announced it was in
talks toward some kind of business ``combination.'' Since then,
MindSpring has kept mum.
</P>
<P>
   With today's announcement, the company reaffirmed its stated
goal to continue growing as access to Internet moves away from the
dial-up modems that the vast majority of customers now use. The
previous pact called for Santa Clara-based Covad to provide
symmetric DSL _ SDSL _ that MindSpring's new business unit could
sell to companies in Atlanta, Texas and California.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the two companies are poised to announce a version for
consumers in California and Texas known as ADSL _ for assymetric
DSL (digital subscriber line). In that version, the most rapid
transmission of data is in the direction of the customer. In SDSL,
the speeds of transmission are equal.
</P>
<P>
   California accounts for nearly 13 percent of MindSpring's 1.2
million subscribers, many of them having arrived with the company's
purchase of Netcom. Texas represents only about 3.8 percent of
MindSpring's customers. Georgia, where MindSpring was born,
represents its largest customer block with about 17 percent of its
total.
</P>
<P>
   DSL seems to be the turf on which much of the potentially
lucrative battle for the high-speed customer will be fought.
</P>
<P>
   Provided by various phone companies, the technology's greatest
advantage is the ability to run on copper phone lines like those
already installed to most American homes. DSL also offers a
connection that is always on, so users can avoid the sometimes
uncertain nuisance of dialing up a link. On the other hand, the
technology doesn't work on some old lines and homes that are too
far from a switching office.
</P>
<P>
   Unavailability is only a temporary obstacle, said Jim Anderson,
MindSpring director of product management for fast access. ``It
will be a damper on those who can't get it right away, but just
because you can't get it right now doesn't mean you can't get it in
six months or nine months.''
</P>
<P>
   Cable modems offer their own set of strengths and weaknesses as
cable companies steadily trot them out.
</P>
<P>
   As it happens, MindSpring is playing both sides of the street.
</P>
<P>
   The company has a pact with Knology, a sister company also born
with cash from ITC Holdings, to deliver Net access via cable
modems, but Knology's reach is relatively limited. Besides, many
analysts believe there is a good chance both DSL and cable modems
will have their measure of success.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Covad is a young _ albeit ambitious _ company that also
has limited reach. For MindSpring's first DSL deal, made on its
home turf in Atlanta, the company partnered with BellSouth.
</P>
<P>
   None of these deals is exclusive, so BellSouth sells its DSL
service to MindSpring and other Internet service providers, as well
as marketing it to customers of BellSouth.net.
</P>
<P>
   As the incumbent phone company, BellSouth can ideally offer a
direct line to millions of customers. But the company is all too
aware of ADSL's limitations and can hear the thundering sound of
AT&AMP;T as its cable units upgrade to cable modems.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth plans to install devices that can double the reach of
ADSL. Moreover, BellSouth plans to offer a variation known as
G-Lite in 30 markets by year's end, said spokeswoman Sue Holub.
</P>
<P>
   The new version should make installation possible without a
technician's visit to a customer's home.
</P>
<P>
   Michael E. Kanell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
