<HEADER>
A3797 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLAROID-Y2K-BOS &LR;      06-29 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLAROID-Y2K-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLAROID TO DROP ADS LAMPOONING Y2K BUG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HEATHER KAMINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Polaroid Corp., buckling under pressure from the American
Bankers Association, will pull television advertisements that poke
fun at the Y2K bug, after the ABA said it did not get the joke.
</P>
<P>
   The ads suggest that some banks may not be prepared to handle
the computer glitch, the ABA said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took their comments seriously,'' said Polaroid spokeswoman
Nancy Childs Tuesday. The commercial, she said, was meant as a
``light-hearted spoof'' geared toward a younger audience.
</P>
<P>
   The Cambridge, Mass. company hoped the humorous ads would
``re-invigorate'' Polaroid's image by promoting its PopShots
product to ``hipper'' customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not want to add to the (Y2K) anxiety or suggest that ABA
is not ready to handle the problem,'' Childs said.
</P>
<P>
   The advertisement depicts a man taking a Polaroid photo of an
ATM screen showing his bank balance just seconds before the new
year. He then takes a second photo of his balance after the clock
strikes midnight, the machine malfunctions, and his account
increases by millions.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year the ABA sent similar letters to Kia Motors
America concerning another ad that depicted a line of panicked
consumers waiting to withdraw cash from a financial institution.
Kia refused to pull the ad.
</P>
<P>
   The ABA is defending the letters, saying that the commercials
counteract the $10 billion and millions of man hours the banking
industry has spent to ensure it will be business as usual as the
``People are anxious about Y2K already,'' said ABA spokesman John
Hall. ``We feel people are best served with responsible information
about Y2K prepardness rather than making light of an industry's
readiness.''
</P>
<P>
   The Y2K bug is a computer problem that could cause some
comuters, as the the new year begins, to read the digits as 1900
instead of 2000, threatening the operations of computer systems,
banks, hospitals, and other industries.
</P>
<P>
   Whether public perceptions have been shaped more by science
fiction than scientific study, industry experts on both sides of
the debate agree that customer perception is just as crucial as the
eventual reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overreaction by the public is one of our greatest risks and
could create a self-fulfilling prophecy despite systems being
ready,'' said Jack Gribben, spokesman for the President's Council
on Y2K Conversion.
</P>
<P>
   ``If 200 million Americans decide to do anything at the same
time, whether it is filling their gas tanks or it is with the
banks, the systems are not going to be able to handle that,''
Gribben said.
</P>
<P>
   And if the problem turns out to be more drastic than making fun
of the bug now could turn out to be a great disservice to the
public later, said Deutsche Bank economist Edward Yardeni, who has
been an outspoken critic of the government's Y2K progress.
</P>
<P>
   Banks aren't the only ones who face pressure to avoid depicting
panic. Earlier this year Warner Bros. canceled plans for a film
titled ``Y2K,'' a move its producers believe was due to public
pressure against depicting a worst-case scenario.
</P>
<P>
   The movie was to star Chris O'Donnell as a computer programmer
who discovered a Y2K-related glitch could leave US security systems
vulnerable to terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   But the movie ``had a happy ending,'' said producer Bing
Howenstein, who said it was developed with input from Yardeni and
software consultant Peter de Jager, two industry figures well-known
for their criticism that the government isn't disclosing enough
specific information to allay fears. ``It's like they don't even
want to talk about'' dramatic Y2K scenarios, Howenstein said.
</P>
<P>
   ABA critics charge that if dispersing correct information is
what the ABA is concerned about then why are federal agencies
refusing to release the specifics on just which banks are lagging
in their preparations.
</P>
<P>
   Federal laws mandate that banks and regulators not release
examination data, but many say if this data was public, Y2K fears
would disipate, allowing Polaroid and Kia ads to be taken as a
joke.
</P>
<P>
   Although 98 percent of banks have received the highest grade on
examinations of their preparedness, it is not publicly know which
banks make up the 2 percent that are not quite ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just which banks are these? How many thousands of customers do
they have, and how many dollars of deposits do they control?,''
asks Richard Torrenzano, an industry consultant and former
spokesman for the New York Stock Exchange. ``I want to know now. I
do not want to gamble with my money, even though the odds are ...
in my favor.''
</P>
<P>
   Regulators at the Federal Reserve and other agencies defend
their decision not to disclose ratings given to individual banks,
saying that could lead consumers to panic and withdraw all their
funds, assuring bank closures. Instead, regulators have only cited
a handful of the worst-performing banks and ordered a few shut down
altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Torrenzano argues that if public confidence in the financial
system needs to be bolstered than regulators need to lead the
industry in communication.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the government wants to avoid erratic behavior by the
public, it should disclose its Y2K examinations by issuing its
`seal of approval' to satisfactory banks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Ross Kerber of the Globe staff contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
