<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-DISCRIM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coke ruling coming in July
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The federal judge overseeing the race discrimination
case against Coca-Cola will decide soon after a hearing next month
whether to grant the company's motion to prevent the case from
becoming a class-action lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   During a telephone conference with attorneys, U.S. District
Judge Richard Story said he will hear arguments July 15 on
Coca-Cola's motion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may well rule at the hearing,'' Story said Friday, according
to a transcript of the hearing. ``If I don't, I will rule within
one or two days after it.''
</P>
<P>
   If Story rules for Coca-Cola, it will reduce the size of the
case from potentially 1,500 salaried African-American employees in
the United States to the four named plaintiffs in the lawsuit. The
plaintiffs allege companywide discrimination in pay, promotions,
performance evaluations and terminations.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola strongly denies the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Lamar Mixson, one of the plaintiffs' attorneys, expressed
confidence Story will dismiss Coca-Cola's request.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would be very surprised if he granted the motion,'' Mixson
said. ``He would be saying it is impossible to have a class action
under any set of circumstances. I don't believe that's the law. We
don't have any discovery yet; we don't know what the facts are. How
can he decide the issue without the facts?''
</P>
<P>
   But Coca-Cola believes the suit is inappropriate for
class-action treatment because of the wide variety of individual
circumstances that would have to be considered. The company argued
that the only common thread is the race of the potential
plaintiffs.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Story is grappling with a request to require
Coca-Cola to produce a witness who will give pretrial testimony
about the company's employee database and records.
</P>
<P>
   In a court motion filed last week, plaintiffs' lawyers informed
Story they had received an anonymous letter accusing Coca-Cola of
destroying documents. The unsigned, June 14 letter to plaintiffs'
attorney Cyrus Mehri in Washington said that since Memorial Day,
the company had set up a document destruction room that has
``copiers, printers and shredders.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter said the room was located next to the company's Human
Resources Department and has a 24-hour operation, with security
surveillance. ``Good luck with your efforts,'' the letter
concluded.
</P>
<P>
   In their motion filed last week, the plaintiffs said the
``whistle-blower's allegations'' give rise to the need to obtain
testimony immediately from a Coca-Cola official who can discuss the
records maintained by the company.
</P>
<P>
   Mixson said the plaintiffs will ask the company about the
anonymous allegations when Coca-Cola officials give pretrial
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola spokesman Rob Baskin said the letter's accusations are
baseless.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not maintaining a document destruction room,'' Baskin
said. ``We do have a room we use to collect data and prepare a
database that we will be sharing with the plaintiffs and using as
part of our defense. ... But it contains no shredders and no data
is being destroyed.''
</P>
<P>
   During Friday's hearing, Story appeared to discount the
accusations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't put much stock in anything that someone hasn't seen,
first of all,'' the judge said. ``Secondly, I did receive the
response from Coke in which they have explained this room, and
what's taking place there, and it's at least consistent with what
should be happening on the defense end of the case.''
</P>
<P>
   He explained that the company should be in the process of
collecting and organizing personnel records and documents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coke needs to keep moving and get this information together to
get it over to the plaintiffs,'' Story said.
</P>
<P>
   William Clineburg, a Coca-Cola attorney, said the company will
produce to plaintiffs by Thursday its active employee database,
which dates back to Jan. 1, 1996. The company also is trying to
activate an older database so it can provide court-ordered employee
personnel information dating back to Jan. 1, 1993, Clineburg said.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Rankin writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
