A3803 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MP3-COX     06-29 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MP3-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Music industry embraces Net
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Downloadable music files, also known as MP3 or Liquid
Audio, are the hottest Internet craze and, companies like
Amazon.com and Atlanta-based Cox Interactive Media are betting, one
of the Web's biggest revenue generators looking to the 21st
century.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest stumbling block to date has been the recording
industry, which has maintained that Web downloads are one of the
biggest sources of music piracy.
</P>
<P>
   The set of proposed standards announced this week by a recording
industry coalition called the Secure Digital Music Initiative _
which includes record labels, hardware manufacturers and technology
companies _ should help the recording studios feel more
comfortable. That could open a profitable new channel for music
marketers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is a huge new distribution opportunity for music
artists,'' added Peter Winter, president of Cox Interactive Media,
which just bought a 10 percent stake in MP3.com. ``The recording
industry establishment seems to want to take that opportunity away.
But, like rock and roll, the Internet will never die.''
</P>
<P>
   While the standards, which will require encryption of any new
music on the Web to keep it from being played on new devices, won't
stop copyright violations of existing music, they should be able to
control piracy of future recordings that reach the Web as MP3
files.
</P>
<P>
   The record companies have realized that the past is past, said
Leonardo Chiariglione, a Telecom Italia SpA researcher who
coordinated the development of MP3 and was recruited to oversee the
development of the security standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is virtually no means to protect past content already
out on the Web. This way, future content will be screened,''
Chiariglione told The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   The new security guidelines the SDMI wants would make digital
music players used to download and play back digital MP3 files,
such as Diamond Multimedia Systems Inc.'s Rio, incompatible with
any music pirated from the Web.
</P>
<P>
   The next generation of music players will be able to tell
pirated songs from newly manufactured music recordings and refuse
playback.
</P>
<P>
   It's assumed that newly manufactured CDs will include some kind
of watermark to allow this operation.
</P>
<P>
   However, files downloaded from all CDs manufactured to date will
still play on these playback devices, whether or not they are
pirated.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is to have the standards in place before the holiday
shopping season. Forrester Research estimates that 1 million of the
palm-sized players will be sold this year.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Web sites that distribute music downloads such as
MP3.com, which has been a vocal critic of the recording industry's
position on digital music downloads, say the standards seem to be
designed to protect the record companies not artists or consumers.
(Cox Interactive Media, which owns a stake in MP3.com, is owned by
Cox Enterprises, parent company of Cox News Service.)
</P>
<P>
   ``What's interesting to us is that the two most important
constituencies in the music industry _ the artists and the
customers _ were not included in SDMI's development,'' said Michael
Robertson, founder and chief executive officer of MP3.com. ``The
recording industry is looking out for their own interest and
ignoring the interest of the artists and customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Jupiter Communications analyst Lucas Graves agrees with Winter
and says that the SDMI's proposal indicates the recording
industry's grudging acceptance that MP3 technology isn't going to
go away and that it is willing to work with Web sites and artists
going forward as long as interests aren't compromised by the new
technology.
</P>
<P>
   As the proposal now stands, artists and record companies can
choose whether to encode their materials.
</P>
<P>
   Users of Rio players currently on the market will be able to
download and playback any MP3 files they want, legal or otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``The record company knows the stuff is out there,'' Graves
says. ``They are trying to protect what happens on the demand side,
which is what consumers do with a download after they get it. These
standards will offer a set of tools for the supply side (sites like
MP3.com) to make sure the music is being paid for and people aren't
downloading the music and then sharing it with five, 50 or 500
friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Frances Katz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
