A3805 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-VISITATION-BOS &LR;      06-29 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-VISITATION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DECISION EXPANDS ROLE OF NONTRADITIONAL FAMILY IN SOCIETY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SACHA PFEIFFER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- In a groundbreaking ruling that expands parental
rights for gay men and lesbians, the state's highest court said
Tuesday that a lesbian who helped raise her partner's biological
son had been a ``de facto'' parent, entitling her to visitation
rights after the couple split up.
</P>
<P>
   The decision, coming a week after the Supreme Judicial Court
ruled that an aunt was entitled to visit a child she had helped
raise, expands the legal notion of parenting, acknowledging the
place of nontraditional families in modern life.
</P>
<P>
   ``The recognition of de facto parents is in accord with notions
of the modern family,'' Justice Ruth Abrams wrote for the
four-member majority.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is to be expected that children of nontraditional families,
like other children, form parent relationships with both parents,
whether those parents are legal or de facto.''
</P>
<P>
   The 16-page ruling was praised by gay and lesbian advocacy
groups and assailed by defenders of the traditional family as well
as a minority of the court, which warned that it could open the
door to same-sex marriages in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really a watershed decision recognizing the existence
of gay and lesbian families and the importance of ensuring the
continued relationship between, in this case, the non-biological
parent and the child,'' said Jennifer Levi, an attorney for
Boston-based Gay and Lesbian Advocates and Defenders.
</P>
<P>
   But the head of the Catholic Action League of Massachusetts said
the ruling threatens families.
</P>
<P>
   ``Centuries of experience have taught us that the best way to
nourish and nurture a child is through a two-parent family made up
of a man and woman, husband and wife,'' said C.J. Doyle, the
group's executive director. ``Anything that weakens the traditional
family harms society.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice Charles Fried, in a stinging, 14-page dissent, said the
ruling amounted to a ``denigration of parental rights'' and an
``unwarranted judicial intrusion into family relations.''
</P>
<P>
   Calling the subject of same-sex marriages ``difficult,
controversial, and important,'' Fried _ who steps down from the
court Wednesday to return to Harvard Law School _ also wrote that
the ruling ``is a clear step in granting legal force to such
unions. But if that is what the court intends, it should say so
directly.'' Fried was joined by Justice Neil Lynch in the dissent.
</P>
<P>
   The case that prompted Tuesday's ruling involves a lesbian
couple from Martha's Vineyard who had a monogamous relationship for
13 years, during which they decided to have a child through
artificial insemination. The ruling does not refer to the couple by
name.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, while the couple was living in Maryland, one of the two
women became pregnant. When the child, a son, was born in February
1995, the woman's partner acted as her birthing coach.
</P>
<P>
   The couple sent out birth announcements naming both as parents,
and the child's last name consisted of both women's last names. The
boy tells people he has two mothers, one he calls ``mommy'' and one
he calls ``mama.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the child was born, and again afterward, the two women
signed a ``coparenting agreement'' that expressed their intent to
raise the boy together. The agreement also stated that, should the
women separate, both would retain parental status.
</P>
<P>
   After the couple broke up in May 1998, eight months after moving
to Massachusetts, the boy's biological mother denied her partner
access to the child. The partner then filed a complaint seeking
visitation rights, as well as the right to adopt the child and
assume joint custody.
</P>
<P>
   After a hearing, a Dukes County Probate and Family Court judge
ordered temporary visitation, pending trial, between the plaintiff
and the boy, citing the so-called ``best interest of the child''
standard.
</P>
<P>
   The boy's biological mother appealed the probate court's
decision to the SJC, which Tuesday backed the lower court's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Several family law specialists and other legal experts said the
high court's ruling raises complex questions, such as whether
stepparents and foster parents are entitled to visitation rights,
and whether ``de facto parents'' have a financial obligation to
children and partners.
</P>
<P>
   Elaine Epstein, one of two Boston attorneys representing the
biological mother, called Tuesday's decision ``an end-run around
the Legislature'' and warned that it could ``open a Pandora's box
of potential litigants.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Owen Todd, Epstein's law partner, agreed: ``My biggest
worry is that this could throw open the courts' doors to
boyfriends, girlfriends, day-care providers, and anyone else who
had a role in a child's life and now wants visitation.''
</P>
<P>
   But other legal analysts said similar cases are likely to come
under careful scrutiny by courts in an effort to determine whether
a person who has no blood relation to a child qualifies as that
child's ``de facto parent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-99 2040EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
