<SLUG> BC-BUSH-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH MEETS WITH HOLLYWOOD EXECUTIVES, MOVIE STARS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush used his status Tuesday
as one of the hottest summer trends since Jedi knights and Austin
Powers to do a meeting with a key Democratic financial group of
Hollywood executives and movie stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hollywood likes what's cool, so you can understand why they
are looking away from (Vice President) Al Gore,'' said David
Horowitz, a Bush friend in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush has got charisma. He's hot. He's got star
quality, and that's what this town relates to,'' Horowitz said.
</P>
<P>
   In the lowest-profile event of his three-day California tour,
Bush met privately with about 60 people at the Bel Air home of
Terry Semel, co-chairman of Warner Bros. and Warner Music Group.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the guests were movie executives, and many, like Semel,
have been major contributors to the Democratic Party, President
Clinton and Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting was not meant to raise money for Bush, but to let
him meet Hollywood people who have been turned off by the Clinton
administration's criticism and decision to study the links between
movie violence and youth violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can no longer ignore the well-documented connections
between violence in the media and the effects it has on children's
behavior,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Official Hollywood, which has raised large amounts of campaign
cash for Clinton and the Democratic Party, was shocked by Clinton's
actions. Gore, the front-runner for the Democratic nomination, is
suffering for it.
</P>
<P>
   Several major executives, including Disney's Michael Eisner, are
supporting Democrat Bill Bradley. And Semel was opening the door
for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Bush described his meeting at Semel's house as an opportunity to
get to know people in the movie industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I meet with the movie people today, I'm not going to
single them out,'' Bush said. ``I'm going to talk in terms ... that
we are all responsible for ushering in the responsibility era.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he believes it is important to understand that youth
violence is not caused just by violent movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a correlation between violence in movies and youth
violence, but I also think there is a correlation between violence
and drug use and alcohol abuse and lack of parental love,'' Bush
said. ``There's a lot of reasons why we have violence in our
society.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush indicated he does not like ``pure violence for violence
sake,'' but added that he also believes ``adult movies are for
adults.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope Hollywood lauds responsible behavior and responsible
decisions and responsible actions,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   The relationship between the industry and Republicans has been
uneasy through most of this decade.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1996 elections, people in the entertainment industry
gave $442,075 to Clinton's re-election campaign and $166,070 to the
campaign of Republican challenger Bob Dole.
</P>
<P>
   Former Vice President Dan Quayle, a GOP presidential contender
this year, accused the entertainment industry of contributing to
the nation's moral decay through the portrayal of fictional
television character Murphy Brown's unwed motherhood.
</P>
<P>
   And during the 1996 election cycle, Dole singled out Time
Warner, of which Semel's company is a subsidiary, for promoting
violence against police in its gangsta rap recordings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to ask the executives of Time Warner a
question,'' Dole said in a 1995 speech. ``Is this what you intended
to accomplish with your careers? You have sold your souls, but must
you debase our nation and threaten our children as well?''
</P>
<P>
   The Hollywood focus on violence also has been under attack in
the courts. Time Warner faces lawsuits that claim the movies
``Natural Born Killers'' and ``The Basketball Diaries'' caused
copycat teen killings. Semel was involved in the final cuts of
``Natural Born Killers.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has visited with entertainment moguls before, but only the
conservative ones. In April, he spoke to Horowitz's Center for the
Study of Popular Culture, ostensibly about the Texas film industry,
but the speech was laden with talk about personal responsibility
and individual freedoms.
</P>
<P>
   Horowitz said Bush has a chance to break the barriers between
Hollywood and Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton-Gore have launched this attack on Hollywood,''
Horowitz said. ``They (Hollywood insiders) fear Republicans are
going to be worse. But when they discover that Bush is not their
darkest fears, they are going to come over.''
</P>
<P>
   Horowitz said Bush's ``compassionate conservative'' campaign to
bring prosperity to ``people left behind'' will appeal to
Hollywood. But Horowitz said no one should expect an immediate
stampede to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you are going to find people jumping at the
beginning of a campaign,'' Horowitz said. ``We're at the stage
where this is a look-see.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Makinson of the Center for Responsive Politics said he was
surprised by Hollywood's courting of Bush, but added: ``It's hard
for me to imagine a single issue (such as youth violence) that
would drive a wedge between Hollywood and Democrats.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides his meeting with the Hollywood executives, Bush spoke at
fund-raisers in San Diego, Irvine and Los Angeles as part of his
effort to raise $4.2 million in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also had what was promoted as a Hispanic voter outreach
event at the Plaza de Mexico at the Del Mar Fair. However, the
event was held before the fair was open to the public, and Bush's
invited crowd of about 100 people apparently contained few
Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   The National Abortion Rights Action League also had a small
crowd of protesters outside of each of Bush's fund-raising events.
</P>
<P>
   NARAL Southern California Director Kelly Hayes-Raitt said the
group wants to tell Californians that Bush is ``the most
anti-choice governor in the nation.'' But Hayes-Raitt said that
Bush's relatively moderate comments on abortion rights are signs
that he is ``equivocating'' after the defeats of Republican
anti-abortion candidates in U.S. Senate and governor's races in
California last year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
