<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3812 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UNCLE-SAM-ART-$ADV04-     06-29 1174
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNCLE-SAM-ART-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THAT FAMILY FIGURE WATCHING OVER US IS NOT BIG BROTHER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Mass.)  (af) 
 Sarah Bayliss is an associate editor of Artnews magazine.  
 By SARAH BAYLISS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Contrary to popular belief, Uncle Sam wasn't born on the Fourth
of July but on Sept. 13, 1766, in Arlington, Mass. And he had many
guises before James Montgomery Flagg painted a stern, white-haired
man proclaiming, ungrammatically, ``I want YOU for U.S. Army.''
</P>
<P>
   Uncle Sam's namesake was Samuel Wilson, a meat packer who
settled in Troy, N.Y., and supplied food to American troops during
the War of 1812.
</P>
<P>
   According to legend _ and to an eyewitness report published in
The New-York Gazette and General Advertiser in 1830 _ a workman
joked that the letters ``U.S.'' on Wilson's shipping crates stood
for ``Uncle Sam'' Wilson. The anecdote spread and led to the
patriotic symbol now reproduced in political cartoons,
advertisements, posters and fine art.
</P>
<P>
   Images of Uncle Sam, including portrayals by Currier &AMP; Ives,
Thomas Nast, Charles Dana Gibson and Andy Warhol, can be seen in
``Uncle Sam: The Face of a Nation,'' at the New-York Historical
Society in Manhattan through Aug. 21.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, Samuel Wilson's life had little to do with Uncle Sam,
except that he was a tall, enterprising Yankee. As he evolved into
a star-spangled icon, Uncle Sam surpassed Lady Liberty, Columbia,
Yankee Doodle and Brother Jonathan as the most popular
personification of America.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, he has endorsed American products from Liberty Bonds
to cleaning powder to Ex-Lax. Star-spangled hats can be found on
old Grateful Dead albums, and Allen Ginsberg wore one in 1966 for a
Central Park peace rally. Today, the red, white and blue top hat
pops up as a screen icon for Turbotax, the popular software used to
calculate income-tax returns.
</P>
<P>
   In the 19th century, Uncle Sam represented rural, down-home
America _ most of the country _ in contrast to Britain's portly
mascot, John Bull. In some cartoons, Uncle Sam and his shabby
alter-ego, Brother Jonathan, were interchangeable. More often,
though, Uncle Sam represented the federal government and Brother
Jonathan the common man.
</P>
<P>
   ``Uncle Sam Sick with La Grippe,'' an 1836 cartoon by Edward
Williams Clay, finds him wearing a flaglike robe, weakened by a
financial crisis. A humble Brother Jonathan appears outside a
window, greeting the doctor.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Nast, the political cartoonist whose comic inventions
included the Democratic donkey and the Republican elephant, is
credited with popularizing Uncle Sam's goatee. In Nast's ``Uncle
Sam's Thanksgiving Dinner'' (1869), the avuncular host presides
over a banquet table of guests symbolizing different nations,
including stereotypes of Chinese, Spanish and Irish families.
</P>
<P>
   If some early portrayals of Uncle Sam now seem racially
insensitive _ many show the lanky patriarch attended by crude
caricatures of African- and Asian-Americans _ he carried great
authority during times of national crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lady Liberty came to be associated with the single topic of
immigration,'' says Grady Turner, co-curator of the New-York
Historical Society show. ``She doesn't rally you to patriotism
going into war. Uncle Sam is a warrior figure.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that is why Flagg chose him for his now-famous World War
I recruitment image, created for a 1916 cover of Leslie's
Illustrated Weekly Newspaper and reprinted the next year on
posters.
</P>
<P>
   With some four million copies distributed during World War I and
more than one million during World War II, it was the most famous,
and most parodied, American poster of all time.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Uncle Sam's severe patriotism is too old-fashioned for
the Army's ``Be all that you can be'' campaign (though he does
appear, saluting, on a new 33-cent stamp). ``Uncle Sam is a
historical keepsake,'' says Douglas Smith, a public affairs
representative for Army recruitment. ``We don't want to portray
ourselves as a World War I or World War II recruiting agency. The
modern concept of the Army is that you serve your country and your
service comes with benefits back to you.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also likely that Uncle Sam's Yankee heritage doesn't hold
sway with current American racial demographics. ``A nation that
sees itself as diverse can't rally behind an old white man from the
Northeast,'' says Turner.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not, but it can parody and adapt him for a variety of
purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1960s, Uncle Sam has championed causes from the
discriminatory to the ridiculous. ``Uncle Sam has become the symbol
of radicalism and counter-culture movements,'' says Elena Millie,
the curator of the poster collection at the Library of Congress and
of a 1994 Uncle Sam poster show.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people see him, they say: `Oh. What's he doing for us
now?''' In spoofs of Flagg's picture, Uncle Sam has endorsed the Ku
Klux Klan, civil rights and the admission of homosexuals to the
military. A 1968 poster supporting Pope Paul VI's ban on birth
control among Roman Catholics featured Uncle Sam admonishing
Americans against taking the Pill.
</P>
<P>
   Ben and Jerry's 1994 search for a chief executive officer for
their ice cream company had him saying, ``We want you to be our
C.E.O.''
</P>
<P>
   Uncle Sam's survival probably rests on the fact that any fringe
group can claim him as a spokesman. ``Uncle Sam can mean everything
to everybody _ he can have great power,'' says Mike Darnall, the
author, with the illustrator Alex Ross, of the graphic novel
``Uncle Sam,'' published by DC Comics earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   In the book, a tattered and confused Uncle Sam wanders through
time in a dank American landscape, at one point getting into a
fistfight with his own double. ``I like to think that there was a
certain civility in a country represented by gentle old Uncle
Sam,'' says Darnall. ``But we're living in a world where senators
call the president a scumbag. If Uncle Sam existed today, he would
cover his ears in shock.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner notes that many children arrive at the New-York
Historical Society show without knowing who Uncle Sam is. ``He led
to his own decline,'' Turner says, ``by being a stereotype and
consorting with other stereotypes.''
</P>
<P>
   Uncle Sam's future is still bright in some regions. Since 1961,
Troy, N.Y., has been the official home of Uncle Sam, declared so by
a 1961 bill pushed through Congress by Sens. Jacob K. Javits and
Kenneth Keating of New York, to the consternation of some
modern-day Arlington residents who want to revive interest in
Samuel Wilson's birthplace.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 13 is Uncle Sam Day in Troy, and Fred Polnisch, a local
Uncle Sam impersonator, is busy keeping Samuel Wilson's story
alive. Crowds love to hear about Uncle Sam Wilson, he says, almost
as much as they like his star-spangled shoelaces.
</P>
<P>
   And if they don't know a lot about American history, they do
have one strong association with Uncle Sam. ``Some people ask me
why I'm taking all their money for taxes,'' says Polnisch. ``I tell
them to write to their congressmen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
