<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3814 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-HEPATITIS-DRUG-NY     06-29 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-HEPATITIS-DRUG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVOCACY GROUP FINDS NEW WAY FOR PATIENTS TO OBTAIN EXPENSIVE
DRUG 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By DENISE GRADY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Advocates for people with hepatitis C have found a way for
patients to bypass a major drug company and purchase an expensive
medication, Ribavirin, at far below the usual price.
</P>
<P>
   Starting on July 9, when the patent on Ribavirin for use against
hepatitis C expires, patients will be able to order the drug from a
pharmacy in Pittsburgh, according to the Hepatitis C Action &AMP;
Advocacy Coalition, a patients' group based in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The new strategy, which seems to have taken both the Food and
Drug Administration and the drug industry by surprise, is carefully
constructed to navigate the nation's drug approval and patent laws.
It involves an overseas manufacturer, a U.S. importer and the
drugstore in Pittsburgh known as a ``compounding pharmacy,'' where
pharmacists will hand-pack imported Ribavirin powder into capsules
to fill individual prescriptions.
</P>
<P>
   FDA officials said on Tuesday that they were looking into the
plan, but would probably not try to stop it unless it was
determined to be unsafe. The officials said that compounding
pharmacies fall into a gray zone of regulation, an area in which
the agency is struggling to develop rules to cover a growing and
rapidly changing field.
</P>
<P>
   Like old-fashioned drugstores, the pharmacies prepare drug
mixtures and doses that differ from what is commercially available.
They are not permitted to copy commercially available products, but
may make versions of them that vary one or more ingredients
according to a doctor's prescription for a patient, who may, for
example, be sensitive or allergic to a substance that is normally
included.
</P>
<P>
   The drug now at issue, Ribavirin, is approved to treat hepatitis
C only in combination with another drug, Intron A. Alone, Ribavirin
has no effect on the disease. Although the combination appears to
eliminate the virus in only 40 percent to 45 percent of patients,
it is the best treatment developed so far for the disease, which
kills 10,000 Americans year and is the leading cause of liver
transplants. About 4 million people in the United States are
thought to be infected. The virus is spread mainly by contaminated
needles and other exposure to infected blood.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the only way that patients can buy Ribavirin is as
part of a combination product, Rebetron, sold only by the
Schering-Plough Corp. of Madison, N.J. Rebetron includes Ribavirin
and Intron A, a brand of interferon made exclusively by
Schering-Plough. Patients take it for six months or a year, with a
year of treatment costing $15,600 to $17,300, or $1,300 to $1,440
per month.
</P>
<P>
   When Rebetron was approved in June 1998, it was hailed as a
major advance, because it worked far better than the previous
treatment, interferon alone. But some patients' enthusiasm withered
when they found out that Schering-Plough had ``bundled'' the two
drugs into a kit and would not sell them separately.
</P>
<P>
   In the year since its approval, 293,000 prescriptions for
Rebetron have been filled, earning $214 million for
Schering-Plough, according to IMS Health, a health care information
company based in Plymouth Meeting, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   The bundling of Rebetron provoked bitterness because three other
companies besides Schering-Plough also make interferon, and some
patients who had trouble tolerating the side effects of Intron A
wanted to try their luck combining Ribavirin with one of the other
brands.
</P>
<P>
   Now, starting on July 9, patients will be able to buy Ribavirin
alone for $225 a month, from Fisher's Specialty Pharmacy Services,
in Pittsburgh. That price is about 80 percent less than what
Schering-Plough's version costs, based on subtracting the price of
Intron A from the price of Rebetron.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a corner drugstore, basically,'' said Betty Stein, a
pharmacist and owner of the business along with two other
pharmacists, Jeff Fisher and Donald Kerrish. ``We have checked into
this. We are not doing it on a whim. Every avenue is on the up and
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Stein said that she and her colleagues would not manufacture
the Ribavirin themselves, but would purchase the powder from
another company and pack it into capsules by hand, according to
each patient's prescription. She declined to name the company, but
said it was a U.S. importer that bought the drug from an overseas
manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Ribavirin is imported, Ms. Stein said, it is
pure and carries the USP label, which stands for U.S. Pharmacopeia
and means that the product has been approved by that agency for
dispensing in this country.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Stein said it will be legal to sell Ribavirin in this manner
on July 9 because Schering-Plough's patent on using it for
hepatitis C will expire the day before. Although the company still
has an agreement that bars U.S. competitors from marketing generic
forms of the drug that agreement does not apply to pharmacies like
Fisher's, which do not manufacture the drug but merely put it into
capsules.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Schering-Plough said that the company was
investigating the matter, but that so far, it appeared to be legal.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Stein said that her staff would be standing by at the store
on July 9, waiting to fill orders. ``We'll be up late,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
