s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POSSIBLE-CUBE-ALBUM-$     06-29 0601
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POSSIBLE-CUBE-ALBUM-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A JAZZ-ROCK FUSION WITHOUT THE GHOST OF MILES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 4) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ADAM SHATZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The German critic Walter Benjamin, in his famous essay on
Proust, observed that all distinguished works of art ``found a
genre or dissolve one.'' The Chicago Underground Trio's new record,
``Possible Cube,'' does both: it's an act of creative destruction.
</P>
<P>
   This graceful collage of free jazz and art rock has refreshingly
little in common with the electric jazz of Miles Davis, whose ghost
tends to hover over such experiments. Instead of looking to funk
for inspiration, the trio delves into the ethereal textures of
modern electronica.
</P>
<P>
   And the astonishing thing is that the record doesn't sound like
an experiment. Where most jazz-rock fusions feel awkwardly
hyphenated, this one is naturally hybrid.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago Underground Trio is Rob Mazurek on cornet,
electronics and vibes; Chad Taylor on percussion and vibes, and
Noel Kupersmith on bass and vibes. The ensemble grew out of the
Windy City's fertile new music scene, which has lately given birth
to such ``post-rock'' bands as Tortoise and Sam Prekop's Sea and
the Cake.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago milieu comprises young, artistic musicians who feel
comfortable dipping into genres as various as avant-garde jazz,
electronica, mope rock, samba, lounge music and minimalism. Unlike
some of their New York peers, they recognize that genre-mixing
needn't be ostentatious, or tongue-in-cheek.
</P>
<P>
   Close enough in sensibility to constitute a movement, these
Chicagoans all seem to play in each other's bands. Mazurek, who
plays on Tortoise's ``TNT,'' leads an acid-jazz outfit called
Isotope 217 with three members of that band, one of whom, Jeff
Parker, plays guitar and organ on a few tracks of ``Possible
Cube.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor and Mazurek, who also record as the Chicago Underground
Duo, can be heard to lovely effect on Sam Prekop's eponymous record
and on ``Hoffman Estates,'' an evocative new recording by the
guitarists Loren Mazzacane-Connors and Alan Licht.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most jazz records today, ``Possible Cube'' is an album
rather than a grab-bag of tunes. Superbly produced by Bundy K.
Brown, formerly of Tortoise, ``Possible Cube'' moves cinematically
from long, free-form pieces to bagatelle-like interludes of 30
seconds to two minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The cover art is no less striking. Fashionably blurred in the
manner of a Gerhard Richter painting, it's a photograph of the
musicians in vintage clothes, sitting in the corner of a dimly lit
room and resembling nothing so much as an indie rock band. The
genre of music is left purposely vague: there's no clue to what
kind of ``underground'' this is.
</P>
<P>
   The music on ``Possible Cube'' is quiet, understated _ and
startling. Improvising over austere ostinatos, the trio specializes
in subtle, timbral contrasts, particularly between the vibraphone
and the cornet. (Their use of vibes and marimbas owes as much to
Tortoise as it does to, say, the Modern Jazz Quartet.)
</P>
<P>
   Mazurek, who until recently was a traditional hard-bop player,
recalls Don Cherry in his spare, fragile phrasing and in his
preference for migratory structures; the track ``Nude Anthem''
seems to pay homage to ``Nu Awake,'' a composition on Cherry's 1966
recording ``Where Is Brooklyn?''
</P>
<P>
   And yet the trio's music is never frenetic: it is lapidary in
its precision. With painterly splashes of organ and electronics, it
casts a nocturnal, spectral glow. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE CHICAGO UNDERGROUND TRIO: `POSSIBLE CUBE' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Delmark, CD, DE-511.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
