<SLUG> BC-BKN-DRAFT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BULLS IN CONTROL IN '99 NBA DRAFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is what it's like in the 1999 NBA Draft. Picture some
diplomatic conference on world harmony whose outcome depended on
what North Korea was going to do. Now you have a pretty good idea
of what the rest of the NBA is dealing with because ubersleuth
Jerry Krause of the Chicago Bulls is sittin' on No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Words like ``blackmail'' and ``extortion'' have been mentioned
in conjunction with the Bulls, who, like everyone else, are
disenchanted with the talent level of this year's crop. Krause is
trying to trade the pick for players/picks and probably will keep
trying Wednesday. A couple of rumors have involved the Celtics and
Ron Mercer.
</P>
<P>
   Krause also is notorious for keeping people guessing. Most Bulls
watchers were certain that he was going to take Joe Wolf of North
Carolina with the 10th pick in 1987. Krause decided to take Horace
Grant instead. (Wolf went 13th to the Clippers.) Not a bad move,
huh?
</P>
<P>
   As of late Tuesday, most people had Duke's Elton Brand penciled
into the Bulls' slot if they keep the pick. The other possibility
is dynamic Maryland guard Steve Francis, who also could be taken as
part of a trade. (If Vancouver selects Francis, you can be certain
something's up.)
</P>
<P>
   The status of Lamar Odom also was of keen interest on the eve of
the draft. He was thought to have righted the ship a bit after
sliding out of the top spot, which, on talent alone, he probably
merits. He may not go in the top three and that would leave the
Clippers at No. 4 as one possibility. Another would be Minnesota at
No. 6.
</P>
<P>
   Odom held a workout Monday night at Rhode Island for a handful
of teams, one of which was Miami. The Heat pick 25th, so their
presence indicates that Pat Riley may be working the phones trying
to get the Grizzlies' No. 2 pick, which is, as they say, available.
</P>
<P>
   So, too, is No. 1. Krause may wind up alienating 28 colleagues
before this is over. He is determined to rebuild the Bulls and
equally determined to squeeze everything he can out of the pick.
The Raptors would love to trade with their eye on Francis, but are
loathe to give up Tracy McGrady, a Krause favorite. (So, too, is
Mercer, who has been mentioned in a three-way with the Bulls and
Raptors.) Cleveland also has two lottery picks (8, 11) and might
package that with a player (Derek Anderson?) to try and move up.
They want Wally Szczerbiak, however, the senior sharpshooter from
Miami of Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   There also were rumors Tuesday that Indiana was shopping Mark
Jackson and was talking to Phoenix about a deal for Tom Gugliotta
(for Jalen Rose and Antonio Davis). The Pacers draft 26th, not an
opportune spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people say the draft stops at seven. Others say it stops
at 12, and some others say it stops at 18,'' said Indiana general
manager David Kahn. ``Anyway you look at it, it doesn't look good
for us guys in the 20s.''
</P>
<P>
   Toward that end, the Rockets sent out a memo Tuesday telling
teams that their pick, 22d overall, was available for just about
anything. The Rockets and Raptors reportedly had a deal involving
the estimable Hakeem Olajuwon, but Toronto GM Glen Grunwald was
quick to shoot it down. The Raptors would have surrendered two
picks and two players for the aging Olajuwon, not a wise move.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta goes into the draft with four first rounders, but
reportedly has agreed to send two of them to the Warriors for John
Starks. Golden State would then be poised to make a run at Mitch
Richmond. Utah has three first rounders, the best of which is 19th.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
