<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3819 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-MEDICARE-BOS &LR;      06-29 1292
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MEDICARE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON MEDICARE PLAN TARGETS PRESCRIPTION DRUG COSTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER AND RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With time slipping away for new legislative
accomplishments, President Clinton Tuesday offered a plan to shore
up the shaky finances of Medicare, imposing more cutbacks on
financially strapped hospitals and giving seniors several new
benefits, including partial coverage for the cost of prescription
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The drug benefit would be the most significant expansion of
Medicare since its inception in 1965, when pharmaceuticals were
much less costly and less central to medical care.
</P>
<P>
   Under Clinton's drug proposal, which would start in 2002 if
approved by Congress, seniors and the disabled would be charged $24
a month, or $288 a year, for insurance to cover half of their first
$2,000 in drug costs, or up to $1,000 in annual reimbursements.
</P>
<P>
   When fully in place in 2008, beneficiaries would pay $44 a
month, or $528 annually, for Medicare to cover half of their first
$5,000 in drug purchases, or up to $2,500 in annual reimbursements.
The program would be voluntary, and the government would waive or
share the premium for low-income people.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also would end all existing co-payments and deductibles
for preventive care already offered by Medicare, such as screening
tests for osteoporosis and for breast, colon, cervical and prostate
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The plan also aims to add 12 years to the financial health of
Medicare, assuring solvency until 2027. The money would come from
lower payments to health care providers and insurers _ who
complained loudly about the plan Tuesday _ and from future federal
budget surpluses.
</P>
<P>
   The Medicare plan comes just as the White House and the
Republican-led Congress head into what could be the last major
budget negotations of Clinton's presidency. Clinton has 18 months
left to serve, but he has already noted that the 2000 elections
will make compromises on sensitive issues, such as Medicare, more
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare is part of a larger debate over how to spend massive
budget surpluses that the White House believes will reach $5.9
trillion over the next 15 years, assuming there is no prolonged
economic recession and that lawmakers do not pass large, new
spending plans.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton wants to devote $794 billion of the expected surpluses
to Medicare, an even larger amount to Social Security, and smaller
sums to favored social programs, defense and a tax incentive for
low- and moderate-income workers to save for retirement.
Republicans also talk about shoring up Medicare, Social Security
and defense, but a large tax cut is likely to be the centerpiece of
their agenda, possibly as much as $778 billion over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a thousand ways to spend the surplus, all of them
arguably attractive, but none more important than first
guaranteeing our existing obligation to secure quality health care
for our seniors,'' Clinton said in a White House speech to unveil
his Medicare proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Republican lawmakers said some sort of drug coverage was a good
idea, but many also said the president was less interested in
fixing Medicare than in winning votes from seniors for Democratic
candidates next year. They said Clinton was wrong to offer new
benefits to wealthier seniors, while Medicare is already stressed
by the current benefit package.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's more likely a politically driven benefit structure than
a benefit structure directed at the problem,'' said Senator Judd
Gregg, Republican of New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Several major sectors of the health care industry also opposed
the plan, including hospitals and health insurers. Many of them are
posting financial losses they blame on steep Medicare cutbacks
approved in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's plan would impose ``additional devastating cuts'' on
hospitals, said Andrew Dreyfus, executive vice president of the
Massachusetts Hospital Association. ``They would hurt. They would
affect every floor in every hospital in Massachusetts.''
</P>
<P>
   Outright support for the president's proposal was scarce.
Senator Edward M. Kennedy called it ``the right prescription,'' but
Senator John F. Kerry, while generally supportive, warned that it
would cut too much from hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare, the nation's second-largest domestic program after
Social Security, offers health insurance to 34 million seniors and
5 million disabled Americans. Beneficiaries already pay a $45.50
monthly premium to cover doctor's office visits.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics said the drug proposal offered too much help to
certain seniors, and others said it offered too little to the poor.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Phil Gramm, Republican of Texas, said Clinton ignored
the fact that two-thirds of seniors already have drug coverage,
mainly through their former employers. Clinton would ``impose more
tax burden on young working families'' to pay for insurance many
people already have _ an idea that ``makes absolutely no sense
economically.''
</P>
<P>
   A relatively small proportion of elders _ only 4 percent,
according to the administration, but up to 20 percent in some
studies _ have medication costs above $2,000 a year, and several
experts said Clinton should do more for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``For people at the low end of the income strata, the Clinton
plan helps, but it doesn't help enough,'' said Thomas Smedden,
director of a Pennsylvania pharmacy assistance program that enrolls
250,000 low-income elders.
</P>
<P>
   ``A beneficiary with an income of $12,000 and pharmacy costs of
$4,900, which is not unusual, would get only $1,000 from the
Clinton plan, leaving $325 a month in out-of-pocket costs,'' said
Steven Soumerai of Harvard Medical School. ``They can't possibly
afford their medicines, which is basically unfair.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the prescription drug benefit would cost $118
billion over 10 years. To cover these new costs, as well as to ward
off the projected insolvency of the Medicare program by 12 years,
he proposed:
</P>
<P>
   -- Directing $794 billion in future budget surpluses to Medicare
over 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   -- Requiring beneficiaries to pay 20 percent of the cost of lab
services, and raising the $100 ``Part B'' deductible for physician
and outpatient services each year to keep pace with inflation. This
would save $11 billion over 10 years, the White House said.
</P>
<P>
   -- Obtaining bulk discounts on goods and services. Instead of
paying all doctors a flat fee to treat a disease or perform
surgery, for example, Medicare would seek volume discounts from a
small number of doctors. This would save $25 billion over 10 years,
the White House said.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Vladeck, Clinton's former Medicare and Medicaid chief, who
is now director of the Institute for Medicare Practice at Mount
Sinai Medical School in New York, said the cost-savings were
plausible.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know it will save money,'' Vladeck said. ``There has been
demonstrated experience. With coronary bypass surgery you can save
10 to 15 percent and get better results.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Cutting payments to health care providers by $31.5 billion
over 10 years. More than half the cuts would come from payments to
hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   -- Encouraging private insurers to compete with Medicare. The
White House said managed care insurers could provide plans
identical to Medicare, but at a lower cost, saving the government
$8 billion over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Ignani, president of the American Association of Health
Plans, said Clinton should fix an existing system that encourages
managed care companies to offer Medicare plans. She said Clinton's
plan included too many restraints on managed care companies that
want to offer plans to seniors.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Zitner reported from Washington, Knox from Boston.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-99 2054EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
