<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-HMOS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE DEAL ON HMO DEBATE BREAKS LOGJAM 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After more than a week of intense partisan feuding
that plunged the Senate into utter paralysis, Republicans and
Democrats reached an agreement Tuesday on how and when to consider
legislation to give patients new guarantees from their health
insurance plans.
</P>
<P>
   The decision cleared the way for the Senate to pass several
spending bills held captive by the logjam, and it set the stage for
four full days of debate and votes in mid-July on an issue that
promises to be every bit as contentious as new restrictions on
firearms were.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real fireworks are going to be  &UR; after  &LR; the Fourth of
July,'' said Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., just after the deal
was struck.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy's subtly triumphant voice indicated the sense among
Democrats that they had engineered a victory like the one they
claimed on gun control _ that is, once again forcing Senate
Republicans to tackle a politically charged topic before they
necessarily wanted to, and at greater length.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans had said for days that they were willing to find
some kind of accommodation. Democrats, they insisted, were
deliberately resisting a reasonable deal because they were more
interested in staging political tirades than actually getting
anything done.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a farce,'' Lott had said on the Senate floor late
Monday. ``But it's not a happy one. It's a sad one.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Republicans made more concessions to Democrats than
they were initially prepared to. The compromise was forced on them
by the fact that Democrats had employed parliamentary tactics to
keep the Senate in an indefinite state of suspended animation,
beginning last Tuesday, and had vowed to continue doing so until
Republicans agreed to imminent consideration of new guarantees for
patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Senate,'' Lott said late Tuesday, ``you have to be
prepared to deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, the Senate will begin to debate and vote on
what has come to be known as the patients' bill of rights _ a set
of new regulations and requirements for health insurance plans _ on
July 12, the first day that the lawmakers return from a week-long
recess.
</P>
<P>
   Consideration of the bill would last four days, with a time
limit for each amendment. Democrats believe they will have enough
time to introduce most or all of the 20 amendments they want.
</P>
<P>
   From the start of the stalemate, Democrats had been pressing for
an assurance that they would be able to do that, but Republicans
had been unwilling to provide one. The deal the parties ultimately
struck essentially creates a likelihood _ but not a guarantee _
that the Democrats will get to make all the points that they want
to.
</P>
<P>
   Although the House passed legislation defining new rights for
patients within their health insurance plans last year, Republicans
in the Senate voted not to bring it to the floor.
</P>
<P>
   What will come to the Senate floor on July 12 is a Republican
bill that was approved by a Senate committee, in a strict
party-line vote, in March.
</P>
<P>
   The bill is aimed in particular at patients enrolled in health
maintenance organizations and other forms of managed care, and it
would give them new rights like an external appeals process
whenever an insurer denies treatment.
</P>
<P>
   But significant portions of the Republican proposal affect only
about 48 million Americans in plans not regulated by the states. A
rival Democratic proposal, whose principal sponsors include Kennedy
and Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle of South Dakota, affects
about triple that number of Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, the Democratic proposal puts significantly more
control in the hands of patients and doctors _ an emphasis that
Republicans say is untenably costly _ and removes the tall hurdles
that currently prevent most patients from suing their health
insurance plans for botched treatment decisions.
</P>
<P>
   In pressing Republicans for a sustained, wide-ranging debate,
Democrats sought the ability to offer various pieces of their
proposal as amendments to analogous portions of the Republican
plan.
</P>
<P>
   They said that while most Republicans would stick with their
party in simple, broad votes on the overall Republican vs.
Democratic plans, many Republicans would be reluctant to cast
repeated no votes on portions of the Democratic plan that seemed
more sympathetic to patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great victory for 160 million Americans who today
are demanding that Congress act,'' Daschle said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
