<SLUG> BC-FILM-WEST-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WILD, WILD WEST' ESSENTIALLY A CARTOON, OFFERING NO INVOLVEMENT
WITH CHARACTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The one thing you can say with some certainty about
Barry Sonnenfeld's incorrigibly silly and juvenile big-screen
version of the '60s TV show, ``The Wild Wild West,'' is that it's
amazingly faithful to its source.
</P>
<P>
   As he did with his ``Addams Family'' TV-to-film translation,
Sonnenfeld has massively blown up the premise and added a layer of
sexual innuendo to every scene, but he resolutely retains the
original's style and sensibility.
</P>
<P>
   And this is something of a surprise, since the film's title has
lost the article, its main character has undergone a race change,
and its MTV spots seem to promise Hollywood's first rap western.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not, however, this fidelity will translate into the
kind of summer blockbuster the film needs to be to recoup its $100
million investment is another matter.
</P>
<P>
   Even in its own time, the show had very limited appeal.In our
time, it has had such limited rerun exposure that the 13-year-old
male audience at which the movie is so obviously aimed will have no
identification with it.
</P>
<P>
   Since its star, Will Smith, is the the only aspect of the movie
that links it to its target audience, the whole project is a huge
test of his stardom. If it flops, it's likely to seriously diminish
Smith's lightning career momentum. But if it works, he'll finally
emerge as the Tom Cruise-level superstar he's been threatening to
be since ``Independence Day.''
</P>
<P>
   Set just after the Civil War, the film tells the story of how
U.S. Secret Service agents-to-be James West (Will Smith) and
Artemus Gordon (Kevin Kline) team up for the first of many times to
save the nation from some super-villain.
</P>
<P>
   This first enemy is a renegade scientist (Kenneth Branagh) who
has kidnapped the world's leading scientists, and forced them to
make him a super weapon: a tanklike military machine that looks
like a gigantic spider and moves like some ``Star Wars''
contraption.
</P>
<P>
   After several encounters back East, the action moves to Utah,
where, in what seems an hourlong climax, the boys battle the
villain in a desperate effort to save the life of kidnapped
President U.S. Grant (also played by Kline).
</P>
<P>
   Sound familiar?
</P>
<P>
   If it does, it may be because virtually every element of the
plot appeared, at one time or another, in the old series, which ran
from 1965 to 1970 and began as a deliberately campy western spoof
of the James Bond films.
</P>
<P>
   Devotees of the show will enjoy the deja vu, as well as the
elaborate and imaginative design and look of the film, which uses
computer animation to take the old Rube Goldberg gadgetry of the
series to undreamed of heights of mechanical delirium.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, the stars shine. Both are noticeably shaky
through the first act, but settle into the roles and develop a
workable buddy chemistry that's helped by Branagh's delightfully
hammy turn as their cackling nemesis.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's problem is that it's a cartoon, offering no
emotional involvement with its characters and no dramatic
imperative. (Seriously, folks, does anyone really care what happens
to the most corrupt president in U.S. history?)
</P>
<P>
   And since there's no real menace or threat, the endless
cliffhanger situations inevitably become tedious and boring (there
were several walk-outs in my row at the Seattle preview).
</P>
<P>
   Some of the writing and situations, of course, are witty and
clever, but never hugely so, and the six credited writers never
give Sonnenfeld the kind of distinctive comic style he managed in
the ``Addams'' movies and ``Men in Black.''
</P>
<P>
   In a curious way, the film is reminiscent of last summer's
remake, also by Warner Bros., of a '60s television show, ``The
Avengers.'' Like that film, it's overblown and immensely loyal to a
premise that's had its day, but not much else.
</P>
<P>
   Wild Wild West. Directed by Barry Sonnenfeld. Written by S.S.
Wilson &AMP; Brent Maddock, Jeffrey Price &AMP; Peter S. Seaman, Jim Thomas
&AMP; John Thomas. Cast: Will Smith, Kevin Kline, Kenneth Branagh,
Salma Hayek. 114 minutes. Rated PG-13 for sexual references.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
