<SLUG> BC-BKN-DRAFT-TIDBITS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FEW TRIVIAL DRAFT PURSUITS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Everything you wanted to know about the NBA Draft, but were too
busy having a life to even consider:
</P>
<P>
   The first center expected to be selected is 7-foot-3 Serbian
Aleksandar Radojevic, who just finished his second season at Butler
County (Kan.) Junior College. Radojevic, 22, had signed a letter of
intent to play at Ohio State, but was busted by the NCAA for
accepting cash to make an on-court appearance in Yugoslavia. If you
must have a game and a name for the sake of comparison, think of
finesse-oriented center Zydrunas Ilgauskas of the Cleveland
Cavaliers. If you've never heard of Ilgauskas, it means you took a
wrong turn at the horse-racing page.
</P>
<P>
   Two prospects escaped from high school this month and waded into
the 1999 draft pool. Jonathan Bender (6-11) of Picayune Memorial
High in Picayune Miss, should be selected in the top five. Leon
Smith (6-9) of Martin Luther King High in Chicago, figures to be
second-round material.
</P>
<P>
   The alumni list of players who hopped from high school to the
NBA: Darryl ``Chocolate Thunder'' Dawkins and Bill ``Poodles''
Willoughby (1975); Kevin ``Da Kid'' Garnett (1995); Kobe ``Jumping
Bean'' Bryant and Jermaine ``Tip-Dunk'' O'Neal (1996); Tracy
``Vince Carter's Cousin'' McGrady (1997); Al ``Well-Rested''
Harrington, Rashard ``The 6-10 Guard'' Lewis and Korleone ``An
Offer I Should Have Refused'' Young (1998).
</P>
<P>
   Eight teams do not have first-round picks today. Sitting out the
first 29 selections (barring trade) will be Detroit, Milwaukee, New
Jersey, Portland, Philadelphia, Dallas, Sacramento and Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Southern California's contribution to the '99 draft includes
UCLA point guard Baron Davis, supposedly in Charlotte's crosshairs
with the third overall pick, and Utah point guard Andre Miller, the
Verbum Dei product who also will be chosen in the lottery. Stanford
point guard Arthur Lee (North Hollywood), Pepperdine's Jelani
Gardner, a 6-6 guard from St. John Bosco, and Arizona State forward
Michael Batiste (Long Beach) are candidates for second-round
selection.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of Round 2, wouldn't you like to see a list of current
NBA regulars who were chosen after Round 1? Of course you would.
The second-round honors list is as follows: Former Dominguez High
standout Cedric Ceballos, Nick Van Exel, Shandon Anderson, Ike
Austin, P.J. Brown, Howard Eisley, Matt Geiger, Steve Kerr, Toni
Kukoc, Long Beach State's Byron Russell, Bobby Phills and Grant
Long.
</P>
<P>
   Second-rounders currently starring as wrestlers: Dennis Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   No list of draft minutiae is complete without tossing the names
of a few ``sleeper'' prospects against the wall. This year's
sleepers (players who have enough talent to avoid being put to
sleep) include: Dion Glover (Georgia Tech), Antwain Smith (St.
Paul's, a Division II school in Virginia), Radojevic, 7-1 Frederic
Weis (Limoges of France) and Jason Miskiri (George Mason). Glover,
who finished the 1998 season as one of the nation's top freshmen,
injured his knee on the first day of practice last season, and
hasn't played since. He won't be cleared to begin working out until
August, but the powerful, 6-5 shooting guard still may be snapped
up in the middle of the first round.
</P>
<P>
   Devean George is a sleeper with his own category. George, a 6-7
forward from Augsburg (Minn.) College, is expected to go in the
second round, and would be the first Div. III player selected since
Golden State picked Lamont Strother of Virginia's Christopher
Newman College in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Our sleeper list for the Y2K Draft may include Chinese sensation
Yao Ming, an 18-year-old who was this close to slipping into the
1999 draft. Ming turned the heads of high school bird dogs a year
ago at the Nike Camp. Another year of seasoning with the Shanghai
Sharks, and the nimble, 7-5 Ming may be good to go. DePaul's
Quentin Richardson, a 6-6 sophomore-to-be, is another goodie who's
taking at least one an extra year before cutting his NBA teeth.
</P>
<P>
   But the kid now tweaking the interest of NBA scouts is Ajou Ajou
Deng of UConn. Deng, a 190-pound lightning bolt who's almost 7-feet
tall, is described by outgoing Huskies star Richard Hamilton as
``absolutely awesome.'' UConn coach Jim Calhoun, who has coached
both players, refers to Deng as a taller version of the late Reggie
Lewis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
