<SLUG> BC-BORIS-GODUNOV-OPERA-2TAKES-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW FOCUS FOR MUSSORGSKY WITH `BORIS' AS LENS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 4) 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 Joseph Horowitz is the author of ``Wagner Nights'' and ``The
Post-Classical Predicament,'' among other books.  
 By JOSEPH HOROWITZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The most famous image of Modest Mussorgsky _ and one of the most
gripping of all 19th-century Russian paintings _ is Ilya Repin's
portrait of 1881: with its red nose, swollen eyes and sweaty,
unkempt hair, the countenance of dissolute genius.
</P>
<P>
   And Mussorgsky is indeed remembered as a kind of inspired
dilettante, whose insufficient formal training (his musical
education was unsystematic) and undisciplined personal habits (he
drank destructively) were offset by the Tolstoyan sweep and
Dostoyevskian acuity of his musical canvases.
</P>
<P>
   For decades after Mussorgsky's death, his stark orchestral and
keyboard textures were filled in by other hands. In particular, his
opera ``Boris Godunov'' was commonly heard as revised by
Rimsky-Korsakov, with its idiosyncracies of orchestration,
structure and musical speech smoothed away.
</P>
<P>
   Repin's indelible portrait was painted in a ward of alcoholics
one day before his friend Mussorgsky died; it depicts a state of
terminal dissipation. A more representative rendering would evoke
qualities of intellectual distinction and lucid craftsmanship we
have yet to integrate into our picture of the composer.
</P>
<P>
   True, ``Boris'' is today given without Rimsky's Technicolor
``improvements.'' And ``Pictures at an Exhibition'' is played by
pianists exactly as Mussorgsky wrote it: its octaves and tremolos
seem the more truthful for being naked. To portray Mussorgsky
fully, however, would require a full reconsideration of his
signature masterpiece.
</P>
<P>
   Mussorgsky wrote ``Boris Godunov'' twice. The first version,
composed at white heat in 1868 and 1869 to a libretto adapted from
Pushkin, comprises seven tableaux organized into four acts and
lasts barely two hours. It was submitted to the directorate of the
Imperial Theaters in 1871. The directors were impressed but asked
for changes, including a substantial female role.
</P>
<P>
   A second ``Boris,'' completed in 1872, consists of a prologue
and four acts and lasts almost three hours. An entire Polish act
was inserted, with a love duet, a ballet and a sultry princess (all
missing before). Elsewhere, Mussorgsky made abridgments and
additions. ``Boris'' was now accepted for performance. But further
alterations, by the conductor Eduard Napravnik, ensued. Rimsky's
popular edition appeared in 1896.
</P>
<P>
   Today, at the Metropolitan Opera and elsewhere, ``Boris'' is
often performed with Mussorgsky's original vocal and instrumental
parts. But what we usually (at the Met, always) hear is a
conflation of 1869 and 1872. This results in a panoramic ``Boris''
longer than either version Mussorgsky composed: an abundance of
marvels but, arguably, not a finished product. Rarely (at the Met,
never) is the original 1869 version revisited.
</P>
<P>
   This further stage in rediscovering Mussorgsky is more than
imminent. The most memorable ``Boris'' of my experience was the
unrevised 1869 opera as presented three years ago in St. Petersburg
by the Kirov Opera under the musical direction of Valery Gergiev.
And the Kirov and Gergiev have now recorded both versions of
``Boris'' side by side in a five-CD set from Philips.
</P>
<P>
   As given without intermission in St. Petersburg in 1996, ``Boris
Godunov'' unfolded with relentless immediacy, a single fatalistic
trajectory beginning with Boris' coronation and ending with his
death. Not only was the double tragedy of the guilty, guilt-ridden
Czar and his duped and abused subjects _ a timeless statement of
Russian political culture _ agonizingly realized; Mussorgsky was
also revealed as a startlingly laconic musical dramatist.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the handling of Grigory, pretender to the throne. In
1872, he is a recurrent presence, onstage for nearly an hour in
four different scenes. As a lover, he woos the Polish Princess
Marina. As a leader of men, he rouses peasant discontent in the
Kromy Forest. In short, he is the opera's tenor.
</P>
<P>
   In 1869, Grigory is onstage for less than half an hour: only in
the two scenes of Act II (both retained in 1872). A fledgling monk,
he learns that the Czarevitch Dmitri, murdered by Boris, was
precisely his own age, and (we infer) conceives the notion of
impersonating Dmitri and seizing power. In flight to Lithuania, he
stops at an inn, from which he is chased by the police. He leaps
out a window _ and disappears from the opera.
</P>
<P>
   Is this loose and sloppy dramaturgy? In fact, at the moment of
Grigory's early exit, we already know everything we need to know
about him; his lengthy appearances in Poland and the Kromy woods
add nothing to the initial portrait Mussorgsky has drawn with a few
deft strokes. The same economy shapes the entire 1869 score.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In the pivotal scene in the Czar's apartments, Boris' monologue
_ his tortured confession _ has not yet acquired an elaborate prop:
the 1872 clock with chiming tritones that dramatize his anguish.
His exchange with the devious Shuisky is not yet embellished with
rhetorical ejaculations of mistrust. The horror of it all is
unrelieved by the 1872 animal ditties sung by the Czar's son and
his nurse.
</P>
<P>
   What emerges is a series of punishing vignettes, as ruthless for
their concision as for their grim import. The usual introductions
and transitions are curtailed or omitted. No wonder the directors
asked for revisions: this was a work decades ahead of its time.
</P>
<P>
   As it happened, the revisions they obtained were exemplary _ not
an expeditious patch job but a painstaking reconsideration of shape
and structure. Mussorgsky turned his compressed musical drama into
a grandly expansive Romantic opera.
</P>
<P>
   For Grigory and Marina, he composed some of his most lyrically
impassioned music and used it to create a complex ``love'' scene
riddled with suspicion and self-interest. For the Kromy Forest
finale (which in effect took the place of the taut confrontation
outside St. Basil's Church between Boris and a clairvoyant
simpleton), he created a widescreen pageant of peasants eternally
feckless and abused. In the scenes he retained, he gave the women
fresh tunes to sing and (straying far from Pushkin) transformed
declamatory musical speeches into something closer to songs.
</P>
<P>
   All the same, it is idle to deny that the scissors and paste are
sometimes visible. The leisurely dramatic rhythm of the Polish act
risks seeming sluggish in juxtaposition with the scenes altered
least. The expanded female roles _ the nurse, the Czar's children,
the Innkeeper _ add colorful padding, not vital substance.
</P>
<P>
   For all its stirring amplitude, the 1872 ``Boris'' is more
conventionally operatic. Imagine ``Pictures at an Exhibition'' _
like the 1869 ``Boris,'' a trajectory of epigrams _ cushioned and
expanded.
</P>
<P>
   From Richard Taruskin's invaluable book ``Mussorgsky: Eight
Essays and an Epilogue,'' one learns that there exists a critical
tradition favoring the 1869 ``Boris Godunov.'' Reviewing a 1928
Leningrad production of the 1869 ``Boris,'' the pre-eminent Soviet
musicologist, Boris Asayev, called it ``more integrated, more
profound, more complete and more penetrating than any of the
revisions, including those of the author himself.'' Among other
writers to follow suit was Gerald Abraham, a leading English
scholar of Russian music.
</P>
<P>
   Taruskin himself prefers the 1872 ``Boris'' as an ``authentic
masterpiece.'' Whether or not he underrates the earlier version,
one outcome of his painstaking documentation and analysis of
Mussorgsky's revisions is a fresh understanding of the composer.
The recomposition of ``Boris Godunov,'' he demonstrates, was not a
capitulation to philistine objections, leaving confusion in its
wake, but a professional job, sophisticated and thorough. As a
summary image, Taruskin's Mussorgsky is much more valid than
Repin's.
</P>
<P>
   Here's hoping that the Met's next ``Boris,'' scheduled for 2003,
is vintage 1869. Better yet, why not boldly juxtapose both versions
in the same season, as Philips has done on CD? A single cast and
production would do.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
