<HEADER>
A3840 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-S.C.-GAMBLE-NYT &LR;      06-29 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-S.C.-GAMBLE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTH CAROLINA AGAIN FAILS TO REIN IN VIDEO POKER
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. _ The video poker industry here is the largest in
the country, with 34,000 gambling machines blinking and beeping in
virtually every town in South Carolina. Its growth has exploded
because of an absence of any serious regulation, but once again
Tuesday, the state Legislature failed to agree on a method of
bringing it under control.
</P>
<P>
   Twice now Gov. Jim Hodges has called the Legislature into
special session in hopes that it will approve a referendum giving
voters a choice: either ban the gambling machines, or put them
under a regulatory system that would impose steep new taxes and
curb the growth of the casino-style machine emporiums that have
become ubiquitous.
</P>
<P>
   But for a variety of reasons, the House failed to pass the
governor's bill, falling five votes short of a two-thirds majority.
It was the sixth time the House had voted it down, and some members
believed that attempts at regulation and taxation had finally died.
But Hodges vowed to press on.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took 12 years to get into this mess, and it might take more
than a day to get out of it,'' he said after Tuesday night's vote.
</P>
<P>
   The ``mess'' he referred to is the stunning growth of electronic
gambling in a state that never consciously approved it. In the
1970s, the legislature agreed to let pinball machine owners pay a
small amount of money to winners. But when electronic video games
became popular a few years later, owners exploited the pinball
loophole and began attracting gamblers to electronic versions of
poker and blackjack, with payouts in the hundreds of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   After a series of court rulings that the machines did not
violate the anti-lottery provision of the state Constitution, the
industry grew tremendously, with only minor attempts at regulation.
Owners were making so much money, and contributing so much of it to
political campaigns of legislators, that proponents of regulation
could never produce agreement on real limits.
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina's 34,000 machines dwarf those of any other state,
including Nevada, the closest state in terms of numbers, with
17,922 machines outside of casinos.
</P>
<P>
   The machines blare their electronic jingles from gas stations
and convenience stores throughout South Carolina, and in dark
corners of restaurants and bars in virtually every town. Although
state law forbids more than five machines per establishment,
operators have easily sidestepped that rule by declaring each room
in a building a separate corporation, with its own door and
electric meter. This has led to the proliferation of casino-like
buildings with hundreds of the machines, each with the dark and
faintly illicit atmosphere of the old adult parlors of Times
Square.
</P>
<P>
   Players sit mesmerized in front of the screens, feeding $10 and
$20 bills into the slots as they bet on games of five-card stud,
blackjack, and keno. The state theoretically prohibits winning more
than $120 a day, but the law is rarely enforced, and many machines
advertise jackpots of several thousand dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The report issued last week by the National Gambling Impact
Study Commission said the machines have become so addictive they
are known as the ``crack cocaine'' of gambling. It notes
disapprovingly that there is no age limit to play the machines in
South Carolina, although winners must be 21 to collect money from
the cashier.
</P>
<P>
   The report says that the industry in South Carolina took in $2.5
billion last year, and paid out $1.8 billion to winners, while
paying the state only $60 million in licensing fees. That
relatively small tax revenue, along with the moral objections of
many legislators, is one of the reasons the referendum bill has
recently gained momentum in the State House.
</P>
<P>
   If Tuesday's bill had passed and voters chose not to ban the
machines, the industry would have had to pay the state 25 percent
of its net income, no one under age 21 would have been allowed to
play, and large casino-style operations would have been banned.
But, in a concession to the industry, the $125 daily ceiling on
payouts to winners would have been increased to $500.
</P>
<P>
   That has led many gambling opponents to charge that the bill is
only a mild form of regulation that would do little to curb the
industry or reduce the addictive nature of the game that often
drains the paychecks of lower income families. Some of those
opponents aligned with industry supporters Tuesday to vote down the
referendum bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you were making billions of dollars a year, and you
suddenly had to pay a quarter of that in taxes, would you go out of
business?'' asked state Rep. Bob Sheheen, a Democrat from Camden
who was formerly House speaker and is a bitter opponent of
gambling. ``I don't think so. All this is going to do is bring more
money to the state government, which will spend it all on enough
pork to choke the state of South Carolina.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The compromise has been pushed by Hodges, a one-time opponent of
gambling who switched sides during his election campaign last year
and accepted about $3 million _ half his campaign treasury _ from
video poker interests. His predecessor, David Beasley, called video
poker a ``cancer'' on the state and sought to ban it outright;
Hodges has said the voters should decide.
</P>
<P>
   Many supporters of the referendum were clearly angered by the
bill's surprise failure, particularly after legislative leaders had
predicted it would pass. Some black legislators apparently voted
against it because they believed not enough attention had been paid
to community development bills they had favored; some Republicans
seemed to be motivated by a desire to embarrass Hodges, a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Terry E. Haskins, the speaker pro tem of the House and a
Republican who strongly favored the referendum, said he was tired
of the constant attempts at voting, even though he considers the
machines ``evil.'' He questioned how many more times the governor
could call the legislature back for special sessions if it keeps
voting no.
</P>
<P>
   But some anti-gambling legislators said there may be another way
to rein in the gambling machines. A federal judge recently ordered
the state to begin enforcing the $125-a-day limit on winnings, and
industry officials have said a ceiling that low might drive away
customers who dream of many more digits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
