<HEADER>
A3841 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRANK-O'HARA-ART-2TAK     06-29 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANK-O'HARA-ART-2TAKES-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN ARTISTS AND WRITERS SHARED THE SCENE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 4) 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 Deborah Solomon is the author, most recently, of ``Utopia Parkway:
The Life and Work of Joseph Cornell.''  
 By DEBORAH SOLOMON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When did all the fun go out of the art scene? American art may
be alive and kicking, but no one can pretend there's a scene
surrounding it. We're in an age when artists, critics and curators
conduct themselves like harried lawyers, socializing not in
downtown dives but over midtown business lunches.
</P>
<P>
   They go to bed and wake up at normal hours. They have to get to
work on time. They are professionals _ and, truth be told, they
make me nostalgic for Frank O'Hara, the legendary poet who doubled
as an art critic, a museum curator and an all-purpose symbol of
bohemia's final moments in New York.
</P>
<P>
   O'Hara easily qualifies as the American poet who had the largest
number of painter friends. To hear his name is to instantly
envisage street corners in Greenwich Village, dusty book shops
along Fourth Avenue and the Cedar Tavern in its smoke-filled heyday
_ images from an era when the worlds of art and poetry were still
entwined.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to say when, exactly, that era ended. But I'd put it
somewhere around the early Sunday morning in July 1966 when O'Hara,
age 40, was hit by a jeep on the beach on Fire Island, N.Y.
Speaking at the funeral a few days later, the artist Larry Rivers
told the mourners: ``Frank O'Hara was my best friend. There are at
least 60 people in New York who thought Frank O'Hara was their best
friend.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Hara proved that friendship is an art form all its own, as a
new exhibition reminds us. The show, ``In Memory of My Feelings:
Frank O'Hara and American Art,'' opens next Sunday at the Museum of
Contemporary Art in Los Angeles and remains on view through Nov.
14.
</P>
<P>
   An appealingly sentimental affair, it rounds up some 100-odd
works by 25 members of the O'Hara gang _ from canonical Abstract
Expressionists (Willem de Kooning, Franz Kline, Philip Guston) to
underrated figurative painters (Fairfield Porter, Alice Neel, John
Button) to celebrated Pop Art pioneers (Jasper Johns, Claes
Oldenburg) to at least one essential eccentric (Joe Brainard, who
took his cue from comic strips before giving up art to devote
himself full-time to reading Victorian novels).
</P>
<P>
   O'Hara's lasting, cultish appeal goes beyond his accomplishments
as a poet. He was no less inspired as a personality. Thin and
animated, with light blue eyes and a broken nose, he talked
nonstop, survived on six hours of sleep a night and smoked three
packs of Camels a day.
</P>
<P>
   He was famously careless with his poems, shoving them into his
coat pockets or shelving them alongside his groceries. For all his
literary distinction, he didn't carry himself like a great poet; he
was free of the bruising egotism that so often characterizes
creative personalities. Funny, generous and always interested, ``he
became your friend in about six seconds,'' as the painter Jane
Freilicher has said. ``It was instant intimacy.''
</P>
<P>
   That helps explain how O'Hara became an adored figure among a
group of hard-drinking, malcontented artists. Ad Reinhardt once
said of the Cedar Tavern, ``We go there to meet the people we hate
most, the other painters.'' O'Hara, by contrast, seemed to have a
crush on almost everyone. He wrote poems in tribute to his
artist-friends and reviewed their shows (favorably) for Artnews
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Arriving in New York in 1951, he took a job selling postcards at
the Museum of Modern Art, where he ended up as a high-ranked
curator. His zealous promotion of the work of his friends and
lovers today might be called a conflict of interest, but, in the
'50s, contemporary art was worth so little money, there was no
opportunity for improper gain.
</P>
<P>
   As a champion of avant-garde artists, O'Hara was admirably
eclectic (and unsexist), an anomaly in an age when other writers
were bullishly taking sides. The leading critics of the '50s tended
to behave like campaign managers determined to get their candidates
into office.
</P>
<P>
   Clement Greenberg led the Pollock camp, while Harold Rosenberg
stood squarely behind de Kooning. It did not seem to occur to them
that in art, unlike government, there can be two kings, or 20
kings.
</P>
<P>
   O'Hara, however, was aware of this. He was aware that the world
is not a small place and can accommodate artists of different and
even opposing styles. Did he have perfect taste? He made the
question seem irrelevant. Instead of a good eye, he prided himself
on his welcoming heart.
</P>
<P>
   This doesn't mean he loved every new painting he saw. His basic
allegiance was to the unslick, opulently emotive art of the '50s,
to 10th Street as opposed to Madison Avenue. Tellingly, he did not
care for Warhol, describing him as ``chi-chi'' and ``walleyed.''
</P>
<P>
   Warhol once tried to score points with O'Hara by giving him a
painting of Marilyn Monroe as a gift. O'Hara stuck it in his
closet.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, O'Hara belongs to the New York School of poetry; the
best way to sum up his style is to say that his poems provide
sustained fun. They have a casual, colloquial tone, and they
elevate the least likely subjects _ gossip, phone numbers,
wisecracks from his friends _ into the stuff of art.
</P>
<P>
   He had no interest in musing on traditional poetic themes like
nature and the sublime. ``I can't even enjoy a blade of grass
unless I know there's a subway handy,'' he noted wryly in one poem.
</P>
<P>
   His love life was busy and complicated, as we know from Brad
Gooch's engaging biography, ``City Poet: The Life and Times of
Frank O'Hara,'' which appeared in 1993. Though openly gay, O'Hara
was drawn to men who were straight, ``or almost straight,'' as the
poet John Ashbery once said. He nurtured a long, futile passion for
Larry Rivers, whom he once compared to ``a demented telephone.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody knew whether they wanted it in the library, the
kitchen, or the toilet, but it was electric,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The anecdotes go on and on, and after a while they can have a
strangely alcohol-like effect, blurring our vision and inducing a
sloppy, unexamined nostalgia for the lost past. On the other hand,
if the '50s have been sentimentalized to the hilt, O'Hara deserves
the fuss; the fabled artistic camaraderie of that era was in no
small part his own creation.
</P>
<P>
   He probably spent more time in artists' studios than any writer
of his age, asking little of his friends other than the chance to
loiter by their easels. There is no explaining the quality of his
devotion to artists, but here is one theory:
</P>
<P>
   A poet's desk is a chaste place with a typewriter, a stack of
white paper and perhaps an unabridged Oxford dictionary. Poets do
not entertain at their desks. An artist's studio, by contrast, is a
social place. Visitors get to look at art, catch up on news, sip
wine, listen to music and, in O'Hara's case, anyway, take off their
clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Rivers painted a full-length portrait of O'Hara in which
he appears stark naked except for a pair of army boots. Then again,
in Alex Katz's five-foot-tall wood cutout (1959-60), O'Hara wears a
jacket and tie, hands stiffly at his sides, a tense, remote
presence save for his bouncy widow's peak.
</P>
<P>
   O'Hara posed more often than George Washington, and the
resulting portraits can be found in ``In Memory of My Feelings,''
which was organized by Russell Ferguson and takes its title from a
poem O'Hara started on his 30th birthday, leaving a sheet rolled in
his typewriter and returning to it over four days.
</P>
<P>
   Besides portraits, the show will feature photographs of O'Hara,
illustrated volumes of his poetry, collages on which he
collaborated and, for the most part, artworks that evoke his
presence indirectly, like Jasper Johns' poignantly empty,
grayed-over masterwork, ``In Memory of My Feelings _ Frank
O'Hara.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the paintings in the show are memorable mainly for their
documentary interest, including Elaine de Kooning's clunky, quite
garish portrait of O'Hara, which reminds us, for better and worse,
that he never let esthetic standards stand in the way of
friendship.
</P>
<P>
   O'Hara belongs to the tradition of the poet art critic, which
goes back to 1845, when Charles Baudelaire began reviewing the
Salon exhibitions in Paris. These days, there is very little
overlap between artists and literary people, which is distressing
to anyone who cares about art and literature.
</P>
<P>
   Our culture is beset by a division of labor. Poets write poems,
artists make art and when they meet it is likely to be at some arts
awards ceremony sponsored by the government.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to suggest that O'Hara ranks as one of the great art
critics. While Baudelaire's criticism today commands at least as
much interest as his poems, O'Hara's criticism is hardly read at
all. His reviews for Artnews and Kulchur magazine were surprisingly
unremarkable; and though he wrote the first monograph on Jackson
Pollock (in 1957), he all but buried the artist beneath a mound of
hyperbolic, rhapsodic prose.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, perhaps only an imperfect critic can be a perfect
friend to artists, as O'Hara surely was. ``I am the least difficult
of men,'' he once wrote. ``All I want is boundless love.'' He
conducted his career in a spirit of infatuation _ and that is why
he is interesting.
</P>
<P>
   The downtown scene wasn't merely a life style for him, an excuse
to have a martini for breakfast (as he was fond of doing). More
important, downtown was a creative upland, a place where people
were caught in a shared sense of artistic adventure.
</P>
<P>
   O'Hara deserves to be remembered for something that is now
practically defunct: the conviction that art and life can be
joyously mixed, and that a visit from a friend can amount to its
own small masterpiece.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
