<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-PARK-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SOUTHPARK: UNCUT,' REVELS IN BEING IRREVERENT, RUDE AND GROSS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ OK, I admit at first I was just laughing at the sheer
gutsiness of ``South Park'' creators Trey Parker and Matt Stone.
But after 10 minutes, I was laughing at the script.
</P>
<P>
   Because these guys didn't bother to skip targeting any sacred
cows in ``South Park: Bigger, Longer &AMP; Uncut.'' It's the big screen
debut _ definitely uncut _ of the groundbreaking adult animated TV
show that chronicles the adventures of a group of scatologically
obsessed third-graders who live in a peaceful place called South
Park.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the film is more irreverent, rude, gross and obvious
than the original, and it gloriously revels in the freedom to be
all of the above and more.
</P>
<P>
   There's something to offend every faction in the film _ no one
is excused from skewering: not Germans, Christians, Satan, Jews,
African Americans, gays, the military, Saddam Hussein, bad Andrew
Lloyd Webber-type musicals, the Baldwin brothers and especially not
our neighbor to the north, Canada.
</P>
<P>
   It all begins when best buddies Stan, Kyle, Cartman and Kenny
pay a homeless guy $10 to buy tickets for the R-rated movie,
``Asses of Fire,'' which stars the Canadian comedy team Terence and
Phillip. But the duo's fart jokes and nasty lyrics have made them
an easy target for the adults' wrath as well.
</P>
<P>
   And later, when the boys can't stop swearing, their parents,
fearing these sweet little darlings have been corrupted, start a
censorship campaign against the film. It erupts into global warfare
with the elders, the president, the military, Satan and Saddam
Hussein _ as well as Stan, Kyle, Cartman and Kenny _ struggling for
control of the world. The boys must become resistance fighters to
save their idols, the Earth and more importantly, South Park,
against the evils of a closed mind.
</P>
<P>
   It seems weirdly prophetic that ``South Park'' should deal with
issues and concerns about censorship and taking responsibility for
one's own actions is even more bizarre in the ragings against
Hollywood movies that followed the killings in Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   But Parker and Stone _ joined by co-writer Pam Brady _ had the
insight to answer the questions, not just ask them. Communication
is the key, they tell us, and communication begins at home.
</P>
<P>
   And though the more politically correct will want to be
righteously offended at the on-screen antics and certifiable bad
taste slapping us in the face, there's just enough truth and bite
in the script to mollify those concerns. Besides, everyone at the
preview screening I attended was so interactive _ and vocal _ that
it might just be safer to cast off all the adult robes and revel in
an unmitigated display of third-grade toilet humor.
</P>
<P>
   South Park: Bigger, Longer &AMP; Uncut. Directed by Trey Parker.
Written by Parker, Matt Stone, Pam Brady. Paramount Pictures. 80
minutes. Rated R for language, adult situations.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
