<HEADER>
A3846 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMTRAK-ART-NYT &LR;      06-29 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMTRAK-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMTRAK UNVEILS TRAIN OF THE FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Amtrak unveiled its hope for the future on Tuesday,
the fastest train on the continent, which will begin running late
this year from here to New York and Boston. The railroad is
attempting to create a demand nationwide for reliable, fast and
luxurious trains among travelers who will pay a hefty ticket price
to avoid driving or flying.
</P>
<P>
   The train, called the Acela Express, (pronounced ah-SELL-ah)
will run from New York to Boston in 3 hours 8 minutes, down from 4
hours 47 minutes, giving Amtrak its first real crack at the
business-travel market between those cities. The railroad will
double the number of daily seats between those cities, to 8,000,
and almost double the number of trains, from 18 to 34, adding its
first ``premium'' trains to the route.
</P>
<P>
   The high-speed train would not look out of place pulling up to a
space station, its sleek gray front topped with a bulbous black
cab.
</P>
<P>
   The Acela Express will travel between New York and Washington in
2 hours 43 minutes _ 16 minutes faster than the Metroliner's time.
The railroad is betting that that small improvement, when combined
with creature comforts, will still be enough to draw additional
passengers. The number of ``premium,'' seats, now known as
Metroliner service, will rise to 11,400 from 9,900 now.
</P>
<P>
   And the old Metroliner cars are to be refurbished to serve
travelers paying lower fares on slightly slower trains.
</P>
<P>
   The new cars will tilt by up to 4.7 degrees, leaning into the
turn as the train goes around curves, making passengers more
comfortable. And with amenities like electrical outlets for laptop
computers at each seat, modern bathrooms with diaper-changing
stations and beer on tap in the cafe cars, the railroad thinks it
can charge a one-way fare of $140 on the New York to Washington
route, about $25 dollars more than it does now for Metroliner
service but still about $60 less than the walk-up fare at the air
shuttle.
</P>
<P>
   The New York-Boston fare will be about $130, according to the
railroad, for the first premium service on that route. Seats on
ordinary trains cost $69 now. Acela Express trains are all
reserved, like the Metroliner.
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak is acting more like an airline, discussing corporate
discounts and considering a railroad equivalent of frequent flier
plans.
</P>
<P>
   But along with revitalizing service in the Northeast, Amtrak
said it can create a national market for high-speed rail.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to have congressmen and senators saying, `New
York's got that, why can't I have it?''' said Gov. Tommy G.
Thompson of Wisconsin, chairman of Amtrak's board. ``This is the
synergism that's going to open it up.'' Thompson said the Midwest
and California were prime candidates for high-speed corridors.
</P>
<P>
   After a ceremony to show off the train, at a new repair shop
just north of Union Station here, Jolene M. Molitoris, the federal
railroad administrator, spread her arms wide and hugged the
locomotive's blunt gray snout. She said that new locomotives, using
jet engines or flywheels, could provide high-speed service in
places where electrification is not practical.
</P>
<P>
   When talk turns to high-speed trains, said Scott Leonard,
assistant director of the National Association of Railroad
Passengers, ``I always felt if we could get something like Acela up
and running in the United States, and it was seen to be attractive
and useful, that other regions in the country would notice and say
to themselves, today, why can't we have it?''
</P>
<P>
   The railroad is renaming its service ``Acela'' all over the
Northeast, and as far south as Virginia: including from Buffalo
through Albany to New York, from Harrisburg to Philadelphia, and
from Newport News, Va., to Washington. Acela is a word Amtrak
invented by combining ``acceleration'' and ``excellence.''
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak is also retraining on-board personnel and improving
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, the cab resembles an airplane cockpit. Flat panel
computer displays have replaced traditional dials, and at the touch
of a button the engineer can call up page after page of data.
Beneath the engineer's perch, 10 feet over the rails, are giant
A.C. motors, which are more reliable and efficient than the D.C.
models that have been used in locomotives for decades.
</P>
<P>
   The cab has everything from intermittent windshield wipers to an
electronic security system. Like an automatic teller machine, the
locomotive can be operated only with a magnetically coded card and
a security code entered on a key pad. A fax machine behind the
engineer can deliver messages from dispatchers.
</P>
<P>
   The passenger cars, more brightly decorated than the 30-year-old
Metroliners, have closed overhead bins. Conductors will take
payments by credit cards and print out tickets using portable
computers, like the ones at rental car lots.
</P>
<P>
   The new train's top speed is 150 miles an hour, up from 125 mph
on the Metroliner, saving 10 minutes between New York and Boston.
</P>
<P>
   But the Acela Express speeds up more quickly than the
Metroliner, especially when it exceeds 90 mph, for a savings of 5
minutes; electrifying the track beyond New Haven saves 10 minutes,
and reconfiguring the track in the New Haven area to allow higher
speeds will saves another 10 minutes, Amtrak says. Changes in the
tracks in Queens, the Bronx and New Rochelle will save another 7
minutes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
