<HEADLINE>
GMS CAN SET MEAN SMOKESCREENS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the second coming of Pinocchio included a tour of duty as an
NBA general manager, he'd grow a nose that could handle a dozen
loitering crows.
</P>
<P>
   But intentional misinformation is just part of the job.
</P>
<P>
   Don't despair. The truth is still out there, we just can't see
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you hear or read about some general manager saying he
absolutely loves a certain player,'' offers one NBA executive,
``you can bet he's going to take someone else.''
</P>
<P>
   So, imperiled by the conspicuous bullets of subterfuge, we will
attempt to issue our forecast for the first round of tonight's 1999
NBA Draft.
</P>
<P>
   You can try this at home; just don't make any wagers.
</P>
<P>
   An example:
</P>
<P>
   Bob Bass, general manager of the Charlotte Hornets, has
announced he will use the third pick to select Baron Davis,
assuming the UCLA point guard still is available.
</P>
<P>
   That's good to know. It also may be Bass bait.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Krause, general manager of the Chicago Bulls, will author
the draft's course by making the first pick, unless his pre-draft
salesmanship leads to an offer another GM can't laugh off.
</P>
<P>
   Gentlemen, start your polygraphs.
</P>
<P>
   1. Chicago
</P>
<P>
   Needs: A time machine, or any player who can score points,
defend, rebound and do all three with enough flair to keep the
corporate rascals filling up on those United Center luxury suites.
</P>
<P>
   Names: Maryland combo guard Steve Francis (6-2); Duke power
forward Elton Brand (6-8); or a three-headed Bleth from the planet
Koo-Koo-Roo (7-9, 7-8, 7-10) with a tremendous ``up'' side.
</P>
<P>
   2. Vancouver
</P>
<P>
   Needs: Power forward, dietician for center Bryant ``Big Tummy''
Reeves.
</P>
<P>
   Names: The Grizzlies could deal the pick to a Francis-seeking
team if Brand is gone; or bite the bullet and draft dazed and
confusing Rhode Island talent hog Lamar Odom (6-11).
</P>
<P>
   3. Charlotte
</P>
<P>
   Needs: Point guard, bald-headed owner six championship rings
</P>
<P>
   Names: Davis, if the word of Bass can be trusted; or Francis, if
he inexplicably drops this far.
</P>
<P>
   4. Clippers
</P>
<P>
   Needs: Point guard, shooting guard, Barbara Eden
</P>
<P>
   Names: Davis, if Bass is full of it; Odom, if they choose to
roll the dice on potential greatness; Wally Szczerbiak (6-7), if
they want 15,000 female season-ticket holders; UConn shooting guard
Richard Hamilton (6-6), if they want someone to provide points and
funny quotes; high schooler Jonathan Bender (6-11), if Coach Chris
Ford has slipped out for coffee when the pick is made.
</P>
<P>
   5. Toronto
</P>
<P>
   Needs: Point guard, shot-blocker, film stock for Vince Carter
highlight reels
</P>
<P>
   Names: Trade up for Francis; or stockpile prodigies by adding
the freakishly talented Bender
</P>
<P>
   6. Minnesota
</P>
<P>
   Needs: Shooting guard, small forward, possible point guard
replacement for free agent Terrell Brandon.
</P>
<P>
   Names: Szczerbiak; Bender; or Hamilton
</P>
<P>
   7. Washington
</P>
<P>
   Needs: Center, small forward
</P>
<P>
   Names: Serb Aleksandar Radojevic (7-3) may be the most-talented
center by a mile, but it could be too early for him here; Hamilton,
in case free agent Mitch Richmond moves on; Duke freshman escapee
Corey Maggette (6-6)
</P>
<P>
   8. Cleveland
</P>
<P>
   Needs: Coach, small forward, backup point guard
</P>
<P>
   Names: Itching to trade up for Szczerbiak, but may settle for
Arizona's Jason Terry (6-1)
</P>
<P>
   9. Phoenix
</P>
<P>
   Needs: Shooting guard, center
</P>
<P>
   Names: Can Hamilton stick around this long?; falling Maggette
</P>
<P>
   10. Golden State
</P>
<P>
   Need: Point guard
</P>
<P>
   Names: Utah's Andre Miller (6-2); or Terry
</P>
<P>
   11. Cleveland:
</P>
<P>
   Need: Small forward
</P>
<P>
   Name: Georgia gunner Jumaine Jones (6-7)
</P>
<P>
   12. Toronto
</P>
<P>
   Need: Point guard
</P>
<P>
   Name: Duke score-a-few-points guard William Avery (6-1)
</P>
<P>
   13. Seattle
</P>
<P>
   Needs: Small forward, shooting guard, center
</P>
<P>
   Names: Ron Artest (6-6) from St. John's; or power forward
insurance from TCU scoring machine Lee Nailon (6-8)
</P>
<P>
   LOTTERY OVER, THIS COULD GET UGLIER
</P>
<P>
   14. Minnesota
</P>
<P>
   Need: A center still might be nice
</P>
<P>
   Name: Radojevic
</P>
<P>
   15. New York
</P>
<P>
   Needs: Point guard, heir to center Patrick Ewing
</P>
