<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIGBOARD-SEC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NYSE AGREES TO MONITOR FLOOR TRADERS MORE CAREFULLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By SHARON R. KING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York Stock Exchange has agreed to a
settlement with the Securities and Exchange Commission, which found
that the exchange did not adequately monitor independent floor
brokers who illegally profited from trades, the commission
announced on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement is the first involving regulatory problems at the
Big Board, the nation's largest stock market, and raises questions
about the integrity of the exchange at a time when individuals have
sizable investment and retirement stakes in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the agreement, the exchange promised to
improve its surveillance of floor brokers by increasing its
regulatory staff, to review its rules and regulatory procedures and
to put in an electronic order tracking system to monitor trading
activity.
</P>
<P>
   The exchange did not admit or deny any wrongdoing, and no fines
or censure will be imposed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This action underscores that self-regulatory organizations,
such as the New York Stock Exchange, must vigilantly enforce the
federal securities laws and their own rules,'' said Richard H.
Walker, the commission's director of enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   While the settlement ends the commission's actions against the
exchange itself, securities regulators and federal prosecutors are
continuing to investigate the extent of illegal trading by brokers
who work on the floor of the exchange, and additional cases could
be announced soon, said Carmen J. Lawrence, the commission's
Northeast regional director.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the exchange will continue its own investigation
into the issue, said Richard A. Grasso, chairman and chief
executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our commitment is to assure fairness and honestly in the
market,'' Grasso said. ``We have zero tolerance for any member who
does not fully comply with the NYSE and the SEC rules and
regulations.''
</P>
<P>
   Primarily, the SEC contended that for extended periods between
1993 and 1998, including the period of 1995 to 1997, the exchange
failed to monitor routinely independent floor brokers' activities.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the exchange failed to supervise profit-sharing
plans and other performance-based compensation for independent
floor brokers, the commission said.
</P>
<P>
   The charges stemmed from a federal case last year charging that
a group of rogue brokers operating from the exchange floor made
more than $11 million in illegal trading profits.
</P>
<P>
   In February 1998, the U.S. attorney's office in Manhattan filed
charges against eight brokers, including an official at the New
York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Executives of the Oakford Corp., a now-defunct trading firm that
was not a Big Board member firm, set up accounts for traders at the
firm, who entered orders at their own discretion and falsified
trading tickets so it appeared that the tickets came from the firm.
Then, the traders split profits from the activity with the company,
the commission said.
</P>
<P>
   That type of trading violates both federal law and New York
Stock Exchange rules.
</P>
<P>
   In May, two Oakford co-owners and four stock traders who worked
on the floor of the exchange pleaded guilty to felony charges of
illegal stock trading. Previously, five other brokers and one clerk
pleaded guilty to similar charges. Charges against another broker,
John R. D'Alession, also a floor official at the exchange, were
dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, however, the case hit a snag because prosecutors said
they could not prove how much the defendants profited from the
trading.
</P>
<P>
   Also, defendants have contended that illegal trading was
widespread on the floor of the exchange and that the exchange began
enforcing rules only after the U.S. attorney filed the case.
Because the practice is widespread, the defandants contend, they
should not be prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
   Independent floor brokers take orders from brokerage firms whose
floor employees may be busy and from firms that may not have any of
their own people on the floor. These brokers deliver the buy or
sell orders to the specialists who function like auctioneers in
individual stocks. The brokers are supposed to try to get the best
price for their clients.
</P>
<P>
   Because working at the exchange gives floor brokers an advantage
over others, they are not allowed to trade for their own accounts
unless they comply with special rules and receive especially close
supervision.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. attorney's office has said that at least 64 floor
brokers may have participated in illegal transactions.
</P>
<P>
   A securities industry lawyer said the steps taken could only
improve the exchange, which has prided itself in the past on being
one of the country's best run and regulated exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   ``At a time when the latest electronic and computing procedures
are being used in the trading areas, it brings some of those
procedures and systems into the regulatory area,'' said Lewis
Lowenfels, a prominent New York securities lawyer and former
governor of the American Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The Big Board, relying on a task force it set up last year, has
already been working on many of the improvements that are part of
the settlement. An electronic trading system with automatic time
stamped entries will be put into effect next year. Computer
software to detect and analyze trading anomalies should be ready by
the end of the year. Several additional rules governing trading
records and member accounts await SEC approval.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
