<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHONE MERGER APPROVED SUBJECT TO UNUSUAL RULES
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials tentatively approved the $72 billion
acquisition of Ameritech by SBC Communications provided that the
new company not only open its market to competition but also offer
local telephone service in 30 cities outside its existing region.
Officials said the unusual regulatory approach for approving the
acquisition was intended to drive down phone bills by encouraging
competition in markets that have been dominated by one phone
company. SBC and Ameritech executives said that regulators would
impose stiff financial penalties if the new company failed to offer
residential and business telephone service.
</P>
<P>
   AGREEMENT NEAR ON YEAR 2000 SUITS
</P>
<P>
   The White House and Republicans in Congress have agreed on
legislation to limit lawsuits arising from Year 2000 computer
breakdowns. The president is expected to sign the measure this
week.
</P>
<P>
   ENERGY EAST SEEN IN DEAL FOR CTG
</P>
<P>
   In a move signaling further consolidation in a deregulated
utility industry, Energy East is expected to announce that it is
buying CTG Resources of Hartford, the holding company for
Connecticut Natural Gas, for about $355 million in stock and cash,
people close to the talks said. Shares of CTG Resources rose
$1.625, to $35.625.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA.COM LINKS HOT CONCEPTS
</P>
<P>
   China.com combines two of the decade's hottest investment
concepts _ China and the Internet _ in a single stock offering.
While both have lost some luster among investors in recent weeks,
China.com seems convinced that putting them together will prove
irresistible. The company, based in Hong Kong, plans to raise $56.3
million through an initial public offering on Nasdaq.
</P>
<P>
   BANKERS TRUST CHAIRMAN RESIGNS
</P>
<P>
   Frank Newman resigned as chairman of Bankers Trust, apparently
isolated and powerless after Deutsche Bank acquired his company for
$10 billion.
</P>
<P>
   NASDAQ AND S&AMP;P 500 NEAR HIGHS
</P>
<P>
   Stocks staged a broad advance as the Nasdaq composite index and
the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index moved close to their record
highs. The S.&AMP;P. 500 surged 20.10 points, to 1,351.45, and Nasdaq
gained 39.67 points, to 2,642.11. The Dow Jones industrial average
rose 160.20 points, to 10,815.35.
</P>
<P>
   SUMMIT MEETING ENDS WITHOUT DEAL
</P>
<P>
   The first summit meeting of Latin American and European nations
ended with leaders of the world's second- and third-largest trading
blocs unable to agree on a timetable or an agenda for talks for a
free-trade pact.
</P>
<P>
   CMGI TO BUY A STAKE IN ALTA VISTA
</P>
<P>
   CMGI, the Internet venture capital company, will buy a majority
stake in Compaq Computer's Alta Vista Internet search engine
business for $2.03 billion in stock.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETING EXECUTIVE FOR THOMPSON
</P>
<P>
   J. Walter Thompson is naming a high-profile executive to a new
post with duties that include marketing the agency itself. Mary
Baglivo, 41, left, who unexpectedly announced last month that she
would resign as chief executive at Euro RSCG Tatham in Chicago for
personal reasons and return with her family to the East Coast, will
join Thompson, effective Sept. 1, as executive vice president and
chief marketing officer-U.S.A.
</P>
<P>
   CONSUMER CONFIDENCE INDEX RISES
</P>
<P>
   Consumer confidence rose in June to the highest level in more
than three decades. The Conference Board's index of consumer
confidence rose to 138.4 from 137.7 in May.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
