<HEADER>
A3870 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-CALIFORNIA-COX     06-29 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CALIFORNIA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    George W. Bush opened his California campaign Tuesday
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Gov. George W. Bush opened his California campaign
Tuesday by mingling with the usual ballrooms full of well-heeled
Republicans and taking his campaign to Hispanic and Hollywood
crowds that don't often line up with the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   Day one of the three-day campaign swing included fund-raising
events in San Diego, Irvine and Los Angeles, where he is expected
to collect a total of almost $3 million. It also included a
high-profile stop at a Hispanic venue at a local fair and a private
meeting with entertainment industry executives.
</P>
<P>
   The closed-door event with Hollywood types was at the Bel Air
home of Terry Semel, co-chairman of Warner Bros. and a longtime
supporter of Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Semel, who has given more than $100,000 to Democrats in recent
years, gave $1,000 to Vice President Al Gore, the frontrunner for
the Democratic nomination.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday night, Semel was listed as a chairman for Bush's Los
Angeles fund-raiser, a dinner expected to bring in $2 million as
Bush moves toward the end of a record-setting six-month
fund-raising period that has produced more than $20 million and
left other GOP contenders gasping for cash.
</P>
<P>
   Consistent with his effort to be a candidate veering toward the
middle, Bush refused to join the Hollywood bashing rekindled by
recent school shootings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is a correlation between violence in movies and
youth violence,'' Bush said in San Diego. ``But I also think there
is a correlation between violence and drug use and alcohol abuse
and lack of parental love. There's a lot of reasons why we have
violence in our society. And when we meet with the movie people,
I'm not going to single them out.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said Semel came to Austin recently and asked him to meet
with Hollywood executives during the California campaign swing. The
Bush-Semel connection has been a major buzz in Hollywood in recent
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent newspaper column, Susan Estrich, a former top aide
in Democrat Michael Dukakis' unsuccessful 1988 presidential
campaign, said, ``Mr. Bush is being hosted by one of Hollywood's
most respected studio heads, a Democrat, at a reception of the top
tier of the Hollywood elite, almost every one of them a Democrat.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, something is going on,'' Estrich concluded.
</P>
<P>
   What's going on, according to California Democrats, is a
Republican presidential candidate attempting to make voters forget
what he stands for on some issues. Bush opposes abortion rights.
Every senator California has sent to Washington since Roe vs. Wade
has backed a woman's right to choose abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``As Bush gets ready to visit the most pro-choice state, I
thought it would be of interest to read Bush's most recent
statements relating to his 100 percent opposition to Roe V. Wade,''
Bob Mulholland, an adviser to the California Democratic Party, said
in a memo recounting Bush's comments on the landmark case that
legalized abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Several abortion rights protesters picketed Bush events in San
Diego and Irvine on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to collecting money, Bush took a small step toward
his strategy of luring Hispanics to the GOP column.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American dream is important for all,'' he said in Spanish
to supporters at the Plaza de Mexico at the Del Mar Fair in San
Diego.
</P>
<P>
   But in Washington, the Democratic National Committee offered up
a view of what it said is Bush's ``anti-Hispanic failure to support
recent hate-crime legislation and the fact that only 8 percent of
his appointees have been Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   ``California's Hispanic families care about a good education,
strong economy and keeping their families safe. Bush sides with the
extreme Republicans in Congress who would threaten our
prosperity,'' said U.S. Rep. Loretta Sanchez of California, a
co-chair of the Democratic National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   After the Del Mar Fair, . Bush distanced himself from two
California ballot initiatives _ one that ended affirmative action
and another that ended welfare and education services for illegal
immigrants _ that have driven Hispanics away from the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he opposed the effort that barred illegal immigrants'
children from public schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like every child ought to be educated regardless of the
status of their parents,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush danced a bit when asked about affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   ``I support the spirit of no quotas, no preferences,'' he said,
trumpeting a Texas program aimed at ``increasing the pool of
applicants'' for state university slots by guaranteeing admission
to students who finish in the top 10 percent of their class.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Canales, a business owner in nearby Vista, said Bush's
message will sell well among California Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   ``He speaks Spanish better than I do,'' Canales said.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Herman writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
