A3871 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-REDS-TICKETS-COX     06-29 0529
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-REDS-TICKETS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reds rule the Central, but tickets abound
 &HT;    By Sam Borden
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ There are plenty of good seats still available on
the Cincinnati Reds' bandwagon _ more than you might expect.
</P>
<P>
   After the Reds capped off an improbable seven-game sweep of the
Arizona Diamondbacks and the Houston Astros on the road, many
expected the new first-place team in the National League Central
division to return home to a party. But the atmosphere at last
night's game against Arizona wasn't exactly like Fat Tuesday on
Bourbon Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``This city is a tough crowd,'' said Scott Goodridge, who
traveled to Cinergy Field from Hebron, Ky. ``People aren't used to
these guys doing so well. If they're going this good in a month
then maybe people will get swept up in it.''
</P>
<P>
   With their stirring run away from home the Reds have earned the
moniker ``The Big Road Machine,'' reminding longtime fans of the
Big Red Machine which won back-to-back World Series in 1975 and
'76. For those who have been sitting in the stands for that long
however, there are some noticeable differences.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Big Red Machine was far ahead of these players, but it was
different to be a fan then too,'' said Dayton's Dan Ekberg. ``Back
then the environment was alive. The cheering was loud and everyone
knew exactly what was going on. Now, the people just aren't backing
them like they used to do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're fair-weather fans,'' added Ekberg's wife, Shirley.
</P>
<P>
   But even the fairest-weather supporter couldn't ask for much
sunnier skies. The Reds have won nine of their last 11 games and 27
of their last 50. They have edged percentage points in front of
Houston for first place in the Central, and will face the Astros in
a four-game series this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``People like to come out and watch a winner,'' said Reds
managing executive John Allen. ``This team reminds me a lot of the
(World Series champion) 1990 team, with young guys who aren't as
experienced. All the national media attention lately has spiked
(the attendance) a little bit lately.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Allen reported that advance sales were up ``about 10
percent'' for last night's game, but walk-up purchases seemed
sparse. At 4 p.m. yesterday only about 16,000 seats had been sold.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is nothing compared to what it used to be like,'' said
off-duty Cincinnati police officer John Brehm. Brehm was working
security near the West ticket officeTuesday, as he has been for the
Reds since the end of the 1990 season. ``It used to be a 45-minute
wait to get to the front of the line, but now there's no wait at
all.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there might be a hint of a fever spreading through the
downtown area. Last night's attendence appeared to be in the
neighborhood of 20,000_ a respectable number for a Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``The winning is the reason I'm here tonight,'' said
Cincinnati's Brian Stover. ``We know they can do it on the road but
now they need to start doing it at home and we need to support
them.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Borden writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
