<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 21:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3872 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMERICAN-BALLET-DANCE     06-29 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICAN-BALLET-DANCE-2TAKES-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERFECTING THE ESTHETIC OF THE PAST  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 4) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ANNA KISSELGOFF    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Going forward by looking back may be bad advice, but American
Ballet Theater has danced better and better the more it has
concentrated on the past _ a 19th-century repertory.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the seven full-length ballets in the company's recent
season at the Metropolitan Opera House were French and Russian
classics created more than 100 years ago. The 20th century did
intrude, chiefly through the questionable transfer of Kenneth
MacMillan's ``Anastasia'' (1971) from the Royal Ballet. To see
Ballet Theater at its best, however, was to see it in ``Giselle''
and ``La Bayadere.''
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the arc between these two poles of 19th-century
ballet esthetics symbolized the season as a whole. ``Giselle''
embodies the Romantic era at its peak; ``La Bayadere'' introduced
high Classicism.
</P>
<P>
   To define these distinctions is to recall how differently each
work tells a similar story: A man who has betrayed his beloved
seeks her after her death in the realm of the spirits. Yet the
style of choreography is not the same, and style is often much
harder to master than steps.
</P>
<P>
   Over the decades, such ballets have been frequently altered,
especially when male bravura of the kind unimaginable in the 19th
century has been added by Soviet choreographers. Nonetheless, the
touchstone of classical dancing is contained within these old
works.
</P>
<P>
   Without academic form, the classical style of the Shades scene
in ``La Bayadere,'' for instance, immediately disintegrates. As
each member of the female corps steps into arabesque, repetition
multiplies the same single image.
</P>
<P>
   To depart from that image, Nikiya, the heroine, would exile
herself from her fellow ghosts. Form tells the story here. Nikiya's
arm must be as carefully curved and placed as that of the other
Shades. This season, Angel Corella, as Solor, the hero, and Amanda
McKerrow, as Nikiya, triumphed through the harmony of their style.
They had the same purity and spoke the same language. It was that
of the choreographer, Marius Petipa.
</P>
<P>
   Petipa had a hand in revising ``Giselle,'' which was
choreographed in 1841 by Jean Coralli and Jules Perrot. But the
ballet dates from an era that did not aim for the spectacle of
``Bayadere'' (1877). The steps belonged to classical ballet, but
the movement, fused with gesture, was openly expressive. Giselle's
celebrated mad scene, now mostly acted, was once the embodiment of
dance and mime united.
</P>
<P>
   Ballet Theater obviously does not dance ``Giselle'' as if it
were ``Bayadere.'' It keeps to a style suitable to Romantic ballet.
But it is a tribute to the company's coaching and the dancers'
artistry that the season could also encompass a range of
interpretation.
</P>
<P>
   At one end, Julio Bocca and Alessandra Ferri continued to favor
a degree of verismo as Giselle and Albrecht. At the other extreme,
Julie Kent and Vladimir Malakhov carried off an experiment in
elegant restraint, superbly bringing out the choreography's
underlying classicism.
</P>
<P>
   Viviana Durante, a guest previously seen here with the Royal
Ballet, offered something different. Her Albrecht, Jose Manuel
Carreno, was a forceful repentant sinner, and Ms. Durante met him
on the same dramatic ground.
</P>
<P>
   Her drama came not from acting but from quality of movement:
technique made expressive. This was no fragile Giselle but a lively
village girl whose bold, powerful dancing made her as fierce a
ghost as her vampirish sisters.
</P>
<P>
   Within a variety of casts, these dancers suggested a new level
of accomplishment at Ballet Theater. As usual, not everyone danced
best in everything. But there is no doubt that dancing the
19th-century classics over two months produces results.
</P>
<P>
   Even the mongrelized productions of ``Don Quixote'' and ``Le
Corsaire'' gave the dancers a classical workout. Petipa's dance for
three odalisques in ``Le Corsaire'' remains a gem because it is
danced right. Technique and style conform to a codified standard.
Anyone can spot the equivalent of a wrong note on the piano if that
standard is not met in the dancing.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Twentieth-century ballets were not excluded. They popped up on
two mixed bills that were a welcome respite from the run of
three-act ballets. There was a pallid revival of Twyla Tharp's
``Push Comes to Shove'' on a program shared with Paul Taylor's
``Airs'' and Jiri Kylian's ``Stepping Stones.'' Presumably, this
was the nonclassical program.
</P>
<P>
   For fun, there was a revival of Leonid Massine's ``Gaite
Parisienne'' in Christian Lacroix's still amusingly extravagant
costumes. Corella gambled and won with his over-the-top, hilarious
debut in Massine's own role as the Peruvian carpetbagger in Paris.
The strange bedfellows on the same program were George Balanchine,
Anton Dolin and MacMillan (a motley, not a mixed, bill).
</P>
<P>
   Three-act ballets, nonetheless, are what Kevin McKenzie, the
company's artistic director, believes he needs to fill the Met.
Among 20th-century choreographers, this makes for slim pickings.
MacMillan's ``Romeo and Juliet,'' a Ballet Theater staple, is now
only as good as its cast. The surprise was how much better Ben
Stevenson's ``Snow Maiden'' looked a year after its premiere,
thanks to some judicious cutting.
</P>
<P>
   The wild card was MacMillan's ``Anastasia,'' a permanent work in
progress that the Royal Ballet presented only one season in New
York (1972). It is a ballet that was created backward.
</P>
<P>
   In 1967, MacMillan choreographed a one-act work about Anna
Anderson, who claimed to be Anastasia, the youngest daughter of the
Russian Czar Nicholas II. MacMillan offered a sympathetic portrait
of a woman in an asylum, driven mad by a jumble of real or supposed
memories.
</P>
<P>
   Then he created a prequel in 1971. The Romanovs and the
Bolshevik troops of the hospital scene were expanded upon in two
introductory acts, whose classical style clashed with the
expressionism of the original ballet. In the three-act version,
which has now been gloomily redesigned by Bob Crowley, the real
Anastasia grows up from playful child to young princess.
</P>
<P>
   In Act I, she is surrounded by young officers (Ethan Stiefel and
Maxim Belotserkovsky were outstanding) whose straight-limbed
virtuosity shows MacMillan at his most polished. But in Act II, one
can barely keep track of the heroine in a royal court whose dances
are so dull that it almost merits the fiery end that Crowley has
thought up (a miniature Hermitage palace in flames).
</P>
<P>
   The audience, led to believe it is watching a faux-classical
ballet about royalty, danced to Tchaikovsky, is suddenly confronted
with the angular ugliness of the Anderson character, accompanied by
the dissonance of Bohuslav Martinu's music. MacMillan's attempt at
shock tactics suggest that life was rough for either a princess or
a pretender.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the break in style recalls that the third act was once a
free-standing ballet. And now that DNA tests have proved that
Anderson was not Anastasia, the ballet has become a confusing
fantasy.
</P>
<P>
   The hospital room encases the set for the Romanovs at play,
suggesting that even the scenes with the real Anastasia may not be
true. Ms. Durante, Susan Jaffe and Ms. Ferri (I missed Ms. Kent)
were lively and committed in the leading role. They did not have to
cope with the impossible changes in direction and off-center
choreography that cropped up elsewhere in a ballet that does little
to enhance Ballet Theater's image.
</P>
<P>
   This is MacMillan still groping for the maturity of his later
and more successful costume dramas, ``Manon'' and ``Mayerling,'' a
gory tale about the Hapsburgs. Ballet Theater simply picked the
wrong dynasty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-99 2127EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990629.0375 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 21:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3875 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INS-RAILKILLER-COX     06-29 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INS-RAILKILLER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Border Patrol's release of suspected serial killer Rafael
Resendez-Ramirez
 &HT;    By Dave Harmon
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The Border Patrol's release of suspected serial
killer Rafael Resendez-Ramirez this month has exposed a gap in the
agency's procedures: the Border Patrol, which processes roughly 1.5
million illegal immigrants on the southwest border every year, does
not routinely check the criminal backgrounds of the people it
apprehends.
</P>
<P>
   When Border Patrol agents caught Resendez-Ramirez June 2 after
he entered the United States illegally in southern New Mexico near
El Paso, his fingerprints were on file in law enforcement
databases, along with an arrest warrant issued by federal agents
who wanted to question him in connection with four slayings.
</P>
<P>
   Even though agents processed the Mexican citizen using high-tech
electronic fingerprint scanners and automated identification
computers installed all across the southwest border,
Resendez-Ramirez was returned to Mexico. Authorities believe he
quickly snuck back across the Rio Grande and killed four more
people in Texas and Illinois over the next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   According to Immigration and Naturalization Service sources,
Resendez-Ramirez's history of repeatedly sneaking into the country
should have appeared on the agency's computer and triggered further
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   INS officials in Washington were not commenting on the case this
week beyond stating that Resendez-Ramirez was apprehended and
removed by Border Patrol agents. They did not immediately respond
to requests for information on Border Patrol's computers and
procedures, saying they were preparing a written statement.
</P>
<P>
   According to INS sources, the agency's computerized
identification system, known as IDENT, doesn't give agents
important information about whether an individual is wanted or has
a violent history _ unless another agency specifically passes on
that information and someone puts it into the system.
</P>
<P>
   IDENT is not linked to the FBI's National Crime Information
Center, or NCIC, a database that law enforcement officers
nationwide tap into roughly 2 million times a day to determine
whether an individual has a criminal history or is wanted for a
crime. And although Border Patrol agents in El Paso and other
offices have access to NCIC, it is not standard procedure to check
each illegal immigrant against that nationwide criminal database,
several INS sources said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a logistical nightmare'' to run every immigrant
through both computer systems, said one source.
</P>
<P>
   The case promises to become a political nightmare for the INS,
the Border Patrol's parent agency. One angry congressman, U.S. Rep.
Hal Rogers of Kentucky, has called the case ``deplorable'' and
demanded an explanation from U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno. U.S.
Rep. Lamar Smith, R-San Antonio, chairman of the House immigration
subcommittee and a frequent INS critic, and subcommittee member
Elton Gallegly, R-Calif., have scheduled a press conference this
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``What good is an electronic background system if it doesn't
tell you the (criminal) history, and it doesn't,'' said Allen Kay,
spokesman for Smith. ``If (agents are) sitting down with someone
who's a cop killer or something like that, they need to know that,
for their safety as well as ours.'' Resendez-Ramirez
Resendez-Ramirez, a 39-year-old migrant worker and day laborer who
for at least two decades has drifted across the United States using
dozens of aliases _ his real name is Angel Leoncio Reyes Recendis,
the FBI announced this week after locating his Mexican birth
certificate _ is wanted in connection with at least eight slayings
in three states since 1997. Five happened in Texas, and all were
close to railroad tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Six months before the Border Patrol captured Resendez-Ramirez,
police in West University Place, a community located within Houston
city limits, sent fingerprints from a slain doctor's abandoned
vehicle to the Texas Department of Public Safety, which matched the
prints to Resendez-Ramirez. On May 27, according to the FBI's
office in Houston, a federal warrant for his arrest was issued.
</P>
<P>
   When Border Patrol agents brought Resendez-Ramirez into their
station on June 2, he was just another Mexican immigrant caught on
the wrong side of the border. Sources say he went through routine
processing: An agent typed basic biographical information into the
computer, then Resendez-Ramirez was photographed and fingerprinted.
</P>
<P>
   Since introducing IDENT to its border offices over the last five
years, the Border Patrol has touted the system's success in helping
to catch murderers, rapists and other wanted felons. But the system
is mainly used to tell agents how many times an immigrant has been
apprehended, said William Suddeth, spokesman for Local 1613 of the
National Border Patrol Council in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   During processing, Resendez-Ramirez's immigration record _
including at least four previous deportations _ should have caused
a computer ``hit'' and triggered further investigation, Suddeth
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say 99 times out of 100, that . . . hit is going to make
you do a lot more digging,'' said Suddeth, who is also a Border
Patrol agent. He also noted that the computer system is prone to
crashing.
</P>
<P>
   More digging would have revealed that, in addition to the active
federal warrant, Resendez-Ramirez had served prison time in the
United States for illegal immigration, burglary, auto theft, and
aggravated assault.
</P>
<P>
   But it is unclear how much, if any, of that information came up
on the Border Patrol computer. An INS source said no ``red flag''
came up on the computer that would warrant further investigation by
the agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was nothing to prompt that Border Patrol agent to do
anything other than what he did,'' the source said.
</P>
<P>
   Resendez-Ramirez was sent back to Mexico as a ``voluntary
removal,'' meaning he avoided formal deportation by agreeing to
return to Mexico. The same process is used to quickly remove tens
of thousands of illegal Mexican immigrants each year.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Harmon writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
