<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990629.0377 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 21:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3882 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBADRAFT-ARCHDEAC     06-29 1420
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBADRAFT-ARCHDEACON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The NBA: Where nice guys get to be ruthless
 &HT;    By Tom Archdeacon
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Wally Szczerbiak may well be the surest bet in
tonight's NBA draft.
</P>
<P>
   He believes it. League executives like Bob Bass of the Charlotte
Hornets, Jim Paxson of the Cleveland Cavaliers and Indiana's Mel
Daniels think it. And Gary Wichard, the West Coast agent who
represents the 6-foot-8 Szczerbiak, has said it over and over
again:
</P>
<P>
   ``Wally is the Great American Hero, a real breath of fresh air.
He's the basketball player who can help this league right itself.
He's this gorgeous, strapping young man, who's as articulate as can
be _ a guy with skill, a shot, defense, marketability and character
_ and, by the way, he can kick your butt on the basketball court.
Add that up and by far you've got the number one pick in the
draft.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if you let the promotional air out of that assessment,
Szczerbiak's NBA status still doesn't sag. The former Miami
RedHawks star is a definite top five choice and that's just on the
basketball alone. Mix in everything else that comes with pro sports
and you've got an irresistible package.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, there's never going to be another Michael Jordan,''
Szczerbiak said. ``No one is going to fill his shoes. But maybe the
NBA is looking for a different angle. And if I can take care of
things on the court and become better and better, maybe I can
provide a little of that.''
</P>
<P>
   If the past few years are any indication, Szczerbiak should have
no trouble handling himself in the pro game. In the weeks leading
up to this draft, he is the one lottery pick who has enhanced
himself. While several leading prospects hurt their stock with poor
workouts, refusals to take part in physicals and interviews or the
resurfacing of off-the-court character glitches, Szczerbiak,
literally, got a standing ovation from some 60 NBA scouts and
league officials who watched a high-energy workout he put on in
Chicago early this month. He is said to have been just as
impressive in private workouts he had with teams holding the top
seven picks in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   These last minute assurances add to a portfolio that includes a
lead role in the last NCAA Tournament, where he carried the
outmanned RedHawks into the Sweet 16 round. That capped a Miami
career where he scored in double figures in 80 of 105 games,
including the last 39 in a row, most coming in a senior season
where he was the nation's third leading scorer.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's last summer, where he was the leading scorer on the
U.S. team that won gold at the Goodwill Games. And next summer _
where he's one of just two college players already added to a team
of existing NBA stars _ he will play in 2000 Olympic Games in
Australia, provided the U.S. team qualifies.
</P>
<P>
   Off the court, Szczerbiak is getting an even bigger build-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job is to make Wally the most well known, out-front player
in all of sports,'' said Wichard. ``And it can happen. Wally is
easiest sell in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Already people are buying. Kellogg's already has worked a deal
with Szczerbiak to promote Eggo waffles. Mattell is negotiating to
sign him and Wichard said discussions are underway with Universal
Studies, who would make him their first team sport's athlete,
Wichard said, because ``they believe this kid will be the
cornerstone of sports, the kind of hero everyone wants.''
</P>
<P>
   The seeds of Wally World already are sprouting. Tuesday,
Szczerbiak's photo filled the back cover of the New York Post and
he was featured in USA Today. This week he's been a guest on the
Fox Network's The Last Word. Last week he was on ESPN's Up Close
and The Late Late Show with Craig Kilborn. He's already filmed a
segment of HBO's Arliss to be shown in August and he's featured in
a five-page article in the current issue of ESPN The Magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, New York gossip columnists gushed about him
when he showed up at a party thrown by Vanity Fair at Patroon in
Manhattan. Over the weekend he was in Los Angeles for a tribute to
Wayne Gretzky and Tuesday night he was featured at a special media
party in Washington D.C., site of tonight's draft, where he has
been contracted by a clothing manufacturer to wear its line of
clothes.
</P>
<P>
   The fuss that's being made has to do with skills, his style and
_ whether it's tasteful to you or not _ his skin color.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a 6-8 white kid with talent. Home run,'' said Daniels,
the Pacers director of player personnel, who is black. ``He'll make
more money his first season off the court than on the court.''
</P>
<P>
   The race issue rankles Szczerbiak, but he doesn't dodge it. ``He
decided to be pro active on this issue from the start,'' Wichard
said.,
</P>
<P>
   Szczerbiak believes white basketball players get forced into the
same little box that people so often pushed black quarterbacks. It
was all about stereotypes and trying to say what an athlete can't
do strictly because of pigmentation.
</P>
<P>
   While he's heard draft analysts compare him to Tom Gugliotta,
Dan Majerle or even Larry Bird, Szczerbiak likes to compare himself
to Glen Rice, who is also 6-foot-8 add a pure shooter. Rice is
black.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why not compare me to a black guy?'' Szczerbiak asked. ``I've
got nothing to hide and if you take that approach you're not scared
of the stereotypes _ you just prove them wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knows I can shoot, but I haven't liked a lot of the
questions put to me. It's all, 'But can he play defense? Can he go
to the hole. Is he athletic?' It's that whole white man myth and I
wanted to dispel it.''
</P>
<P>
   That was one reason for the Chicago open workout. ``He knocked
down the stereotypes right there,'' said Walt Szczerbiak, Wally's
dad, who was courtside. ``Afterward all these people in the NBA I
know came over and congratulated me in what a complete player Wally
has become.''
</P>
<P>
   A lot of the credit goes to Walt, a college star himself at
George Washington, who was a decent player in the old American
Basketball Association and then caught on big in Europe. He played
for a decade in Italy, the Canary Islands, and Spain, leading Real
Madrid to three European titles.
</P>
<P>
   Wally was born in Madrid and was at his first game by the time
he was three months. As soon as he could toddle, he was on the
sidelines at his dad's practices and soon he moved to the court. He
picked up the fundamentals of the game _ how to screen, box out and
most important, face the basket _ from the crafty old-timers of his
dad's day.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was like a sponge,'' Walt said. ``He loved to hear us talk
about the game. He let it all soak in and he learned all the
nuances of basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the bruises of the game, they came in pitched one-one-one
battles with his dad in the driveway of their home, once they moved
from Tenerife back to the States and a tony neighborhood in Cold
Spring Harbor, N.Y., on Long Island. Early on, Walt would handicap
himself, shooting left-handed and blocking shots only with is head.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was a kid, I'd always win because because he let me
win. It could be 14-14 and then he'd make sure I got the last
points,'' Szczerbiak said with a laugh. ``Now he regrets that, of
course, because now I bury him.''
</P>
<P>
   Szczerbiak, it turns out, is an old-school player in a new-age
body, a sculpted physique that comes with just five percent body
fat. He's a sit-ups addict, who values fitness. Thanks to Wichard,
he has acquired a taste for sushi and, for a long time, has not
eaten fried foods. ``He's really conscious of anything that's bad
for him,'' the agent said.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't just talking about diet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NBA needs to get away from some of the stuff it's mired in
now,'' Wichard said. ``All this no regard for anyone else stuff _
this gangster mentality _ is hurting the league. It's eroding pro
sports. Wally's the antithesis. He's the anti-Rodman. He shows that
you can be engaged to your sweetheart (he's to wed Miami girlfriend
Shannon Ward next summer), come from a good family and be sincere
and humble. And at the same time, not back down from anyone on the
court.''
</P>
<P>
   As Szczerbiak explained it: ``The thing about me is that I may
look like a nice guy, that All-American boy they keep talking
about, but when it gets down to being competitive, I am ruthless.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's just what the NBA teams want to hear.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Archdeacon writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
