<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPERMODELS, AN IDEA WHOSE TIME HAS GONE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``l'' lifestyle file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you have been worshiping supermodels, you'd better think
about converting to another church, &LR;  because ``everyone on the
planet knows that supermodels are totally over,'' writes  &UR; Robert &LR; 
 &UR; Sullivan &LR;  in Vogue magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Not only are they ``not showing up in movies'' and ``not opening
up restaurant chains,'' but many supermodel cover girls are also
being replaced by celebrities on the fronts of fashion magazines.
</P>
<P>
   This really hits the models in their Prada pocketbooks. Sullivan
says it's widely accepted in the modeling biz that covers ``are the
way to lucrative cosmetics contracts. To models and their agencies,
keeping models off magazine covers is akin to taking the home runs
out of baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   But as the magazines know, fashion is about change. Sullivan's
assessment may be just behind the curve of a waning trend that's
started waxing. The very issue of Vogue that contains his comments
is emblazoned with a picture of a model named  &UR; Gisele &LR;  and the
words ``the return of the sexy model.''
</P>
<P>
   P.S. The New York Daily News reports that actor  &UR; Kyle
MacLachlan &LR;  has broken up with supermodel  &UR; Linda Evangelista &LR;  and
is dating a ``power publicist'' empoweringly named  &UR; Desiree
Gruber &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IRONY IN THE FIRE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Monte Freidig &LR; , who teaches political science at Santa Rosa
Junior College, was surprised to learn that the 103-page Harvard
College thesis of  &UR; Al Gore &LR;  _ the man two-thirds of American voters
think is ``boring'' _ was on the importance of personality for
presidents in the age of television.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, &UR; David Cassell  &LR; was walking past the Sierra Club
bookstore in Berkeley on Saturday when he saw a monarch butterfly
``trapped in their window display, beating its wings futilely
against the window.'' He stepped inside and reported the sighting,
and two clerks sprang to the creature's rescue.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; REGIONAL SPECIALTIES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Guests at a fund-raising party at  &UR; Richard Miller &LR; 's house in
Tiburon, Calif., on Saturday night for NORML (the National
Organization for the Reform of Marijuana Laws) included  &UR; George &LR; 
 &UR; Zimmer &LR; ,  &UR; Ram Dass &LR; , Assemblywoman  &UR; Audie Bock &LR; , San Francisco
District Attorney  &UR; Terence Hallinan &LR;  and  &UR; Eugene Schoenfeld &LR; .
Founder  &UR; Keith Stroup &LR;  introduced Bock, who said, ``Three words: I
did inhale.'' She was followed by  &UR; Tony Serra &LR; , who said, ``I do
inhale''; he was followed by another speaker, anonymous, who said,
``I just inhaled.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The Kings Cross Steelers, a gay and bisexual rugby team, has
been granted membership in the English Rugby Football Union. ``The
only rule we have referring to sexuality is that ours is a men's
game,'' said an RFU spokesman. ``There is a separate governing body
for women's rugby.'' Team spokesman Alex Standish said that about
half of the Steelers ``formerly played for straight clubs at some
level or another.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The confluence of summer in San Francisco and last week's gay
and lesbian pride parade may have inspired  &UR; Connie Robeson &LR; 's
homage to  &UR; Mark Twain &LR; , as reported by her friend  &UR; Kit Schlich &LR; :
``The most beautiful woman I ever saw was a man in San Francisco.''
Meanwhile, one worker at a specialty boutique near Union Square in
San Francisco, warned by his boss not to wear a muscle shirt or
shorts last weekend, showed up for work on Sunday in a pink dress
and tiara.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Steve Finacom &LR;  was walking across Sproul Plaza in Berkeley on
Monday morning when one of the regular residents muttered, ``If a
day like this were a pizza, eat it all.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The rough and tough San Francisco Bicycle Coalition is having
a group art exhibition beginning Friday at the Unitarian Church in
San Francisco, for ``art by bicyclists and bicycle-friendly art.''
A gala reception on July 11 includes free valet bicycle parking.
</P>
<P>
   _ In Tampa, Fla., a recent concert by the rock band Sponge seems
to have been a success. ``We brought about 20 girls from the crowd
onstage to dance,'' singer  &UR; Vinnie Dombrowski  &LR; told Rolling Stone.
``And by the end, most of them were topless. The police came and
hauled them off. We accomplished a lot that day, I guess.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Gay men get drag queens and glitter; we get wheat germ and
flannel. What the Lesbian Nation really needs is a good
prefabricated pop band. We need something flashy to catch the
nation's attention, something with more style than substance (for
once). ... Don't you think the time is ripe for the Spice
Butches?''
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &LR; Lori Selke in Girlfriend magazine.
</P>
</TEXT>
