<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MEDICARE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON OUTLINES MEDICARE REFORMS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Offering a plan he called credible and sensible,
President Clinton outlined Medicare reforms Tuesday that would
extend the life of the program until 2027 and offer prescription
drug coverage for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans quibbled with some provisions of Clinton's proposal,
but key congressional leaders said they were willing to work with
the White House to find common ground on the sensitive issue of
health care coverage for the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   Both the White House and Congress bowed before the powerful
political bloc of senior citizens, 39 million of whom are Medicare
beneficiaries, and acknowledged the need for reform, especially
with the aging baby boom generation approaching retirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The plan is credible, sensible and fiscally responsible,''
Clinton told activists for senior citizens and the disabled as well
as lawmakers gathered in the East Room. ``It will secure the health
of Medicare while improving the health of our seniors, and we can
achieve it.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's plan would devote 15 percent of the federal surplus
over the next 15 years _ $794 billion _ to shore up the Medicare
program. The infusion would keep Medicare solvent until 2027, 12
years longer than current estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also would create a new Part D that would provide
prescription drug coverage beginning in 2002. The initial cost
would be a $24 monthly premium paid by beneficiaries. The
government would pay half of a patient's drug costs up to $1,000 a
year without a deductible.
</P>
<P>
   The premium would increase to $44 monthly and coverage would
increase to $2,500 per year by 2008. However, individuals earning
less than $11,000 a year and couples earning less than $17,000
would be exempt from paying premiums.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, beneficiaries pay a $45.50 monthly premium for
doctor's office visits.
</P>
<P>
   The Part D plan would cost $118 billion over 10 years, but the
administration said 60 percent of the costs would be offset by
savings contained within the Medicare overhaul.
</P>
<P>
   The plan contains a series of incentives to beneficiaries and to
doctors for competitive pricing, coordinated care and other
efficiencies. The plan also would encourage more preventive care by
removing the deductible for tests such as mammograms and prostate
cancer screening.
</P>
<P>
   The plan also would increase patients' co-payments on laboratory
services by 20 percent and increase the deductible for the Medicare
Part B outpatient care program by indexing it to inflation.
</P>
<P>
   In his opening remarks, the president acknowledged the presence
of several Republicans, including Sen. William Roth of Delaware,
chairman of the Senate Finance Committee, and Rep. Bill Thomas of
California, chairman of the House Medicare subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their presence here today indicates that we can all raise
concerns about each other's ideas without raising our voices,''
Clinton said. ``And that if we're really committed to putting our
people first, we can reach across party lines and other lines to
work together.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Republicans, while chiding Clinton on some specifics,
welcomed him to the debate.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas said Clinton's proposal ``at least allows us to sit down
and talk about a package,'' and that Republican attendance at
Clinton's announcement is ``a clear indication we are all willing
to work together.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas was among the Republicans participating in a commission
on Medicare that made several recommendations, including the
creation of a prescription drug coverage program, but one limited
to people in financial need.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Gene Green, D-Texas, among the lawmakers listening to
Clinton, said of Republicans, ``I think they'll give us an even
chance to get something together. Over the next few months we have
the best opportunity before the election.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Sheila Jackson Lee, D-Texas, said the issue of Medicare
reform and the creation of prescription drug coverage is an
emotional one for many Americans. ``I don't think that Republicans
will be allowed to sit still on this,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., called on
Republican leaders to ``reject the views of naysayers'' such as
Rep. Tom DeLay, R-Texas. He said DeLay, the House Majority Whip,
said Americans were unconcerned with Medicare reform.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay's office did not return telephone calls.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, said he was raising ``issues'' with
Clinton's proposal but did not outright reject the package. Gramm
said two-thirds of the Medicare recipients already receive
prescription drug coverage through private insurance or retirement
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea of having universal coverage makes sense politically,
but it makes absolutely no sense economically in terms of
displaying the private insurance and the coverage that roughly
two-thirds of the retired Americans have,'' Gramm said.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., also favors limiting
prescription coverage to those senior citizens in financial need.
``We do think that it really should be targeted to people that
cannot afford prescription drugs on their own. But again, we're
certainly willing to take a look at what his proposals are, and
maybe we can find some common ground,'' Lott said.
</P>
<P>
   The American Association of Retired Persons defended the
administration's effort to extend drug coverage to all Medicare
beneficiaries _ an issue that was also debated among Clinton's
aides.
</P>
<P>
   AARP said Clinton's plan ``acknowledges what millions of
American families know: that even many middle-class older Americans
find that their prescription drug costs can be unaffordable.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton maintained that nearly 15 million Medicare beneficiaries
lack prescription drug benefits and half of them are middle class.
Because of rising drug prices, fewer retirees are getting drug
coverage from their employers health programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a drug benefit our seniors can afford at a price
America can afford,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   A USA Today/CNN/Gallup poll released Tuesday indicated about 57
percent of those surveyed said they feel Medicare needs major
changes or a complete overhaul.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
