<HEADLINE>
A QUEEN'S MEAL IS REMEMBERED
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``l'' lifestyle file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Justifiably disgruntled, disgusted and disappointed by our
erroneous report that  &UR; Queen Elizabeth &LR;  had her first restaurant
meal last week, many readers remembered the queen's meal at Trader
Vic's in San Francisco in 1983. Several remembered that she had
dined in Yosemite at the Ahwahnee, too.
</P>
<P>
   We called  &UR; Jane Kerr &LR; , who covers the royals for the Mirror in
London, whence the report had come. She said it was the queen's
first restaurant meal in Great Britain; strictly speaking, her
first outside of London, because she had attended several banquets
at Claridge's hotel in London. Three years ago, said Kerr, &UR; Prince
Edward &LR; 's plans for a 70th birthday party for Her Majesty had been
``hastily canceled'' when the press found out the name of the
restaurant where the event had been planned. She also said the
queen had eaten at several restaurants in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Lynn Bergeron &LR; , who was manager of Trader Vic's at the time,
recalls getting notice that morning that the royal party had come
to town a day ahead of schedule and would be coming to dinner with
 &UR; Nancy Reagan  &LR; in the evening. Bergeron remembers being surprised
that evening that the queen had only two security people with her,
one from the State Department and one from her own government (in
addition to San Francisco police officers).
</P>
<P>
   She came to the Sutter Street entrance of the restaurant and
entered unseen by other diners. Bergeron had been told that he'd be
introduced and warned not to try to shake hands in greeting, but
``she reached out to shake my hand,'' he recalls. To the best of
his recollection, Nancy Reagan didn't. ``She was kind of in the
background.''
</P>
<P>
   As Bergeron had been informed, the queen drank martinis made
with Beefeater gin; two of them, he recalls, before she sat down to
dinner.
</P>
<P>
   P.S. The Times of London reported on Sunday that  &UR; Princess &LR; 
 &UR; Beatrice &LR; , 10, and  &UR; Princess Eugenie &LR; , 9, daughters of  &UR; Prince &LR; 
 &UR; Andrew  &LR; and his former wife,  &UR; Sarah Ferguson &LR; , will be asked to
renounce their titles _ ``Princess'' and ``Her Royal Highness'' _
when they turn 18. The Times said this was part of a campaign to
streamline the monarchy. Buckingham Palace said it was unaware of
the proposal, which ``would be unusual, although it has been done
before.'' The girls are fifth and sixth in line for the throne.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAPITOL COMMANDMENTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ A Roll Call story about the members of Congress _ mainly
conservative Republicans _ whose office decors include copies of
the Ten Commandments mentions that Rep.  &UR; Mike Simpson, &LR;  R-Idaho,
has posted in his office his own 12 Commandments.
</P>
<P>
   They include ``Never compromise your integrity, keep your
promises, keep secrets'' and ``Take time to lie on your back and
look at the stars.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Visiting the House of Representatives Members Dining Room,
Senator  &UR; Rick Santorum &LR; , R-Pa., liked the rice pudding so much that
he asked for the recipe. ``Let them eat cake,'' said House
Administration Chairman  &UR; Bill Thomas &LR; , R-Calif., who said the
dessert had been made from a secret recipe of one of its employees
and would remain secret.
</P>
<P>
   Senate chefs analyzed a sample portion and served their own
version at a weekly meeting of Republicans. ``I am confident that
as the chef continues to refine it,'' said Santorum, ``the Senate
rice pudding will some day surpass the House rice pudding.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GROWN UP AND RENAMED &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Baby Boomer children of the '60s had their own offspring in the
'70s, and labeled them with names that many wanted to forget. One
of those young adults, for example, is the former  &UR; Raspberry &LR; 
 &UR; Hummingbird Sundown Wheeler &LR; , who was on hand at the opening of a
show of paintings by her father,  &UR; William Wheeler &LR; , at the
 &UR; George Krevsky &LR;  Gallery in San Francisco last week. This daughter
of the counterculture worked in sales for Oracle, is working in
Silicon Valley for  &UR; Al Gore &LR;  and calls herself Jessica now.
</P>
<P>
   Also at the event was &UR; Sol Ray Sender &LR; , born at the same commune
and named after a ray of sun; he's presently Sol, teaching at the
Chicago Art Institute.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``I think sex is a metaphor for everything else in life, and the
sooner you get over the idea that it's not going to be perfect, the
sooner you're going to realize that nothing is really.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Natasha Lyonne, star of ``American Pie,'' in Interview
magazine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
