<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 21:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3906 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ASSAYAS-FILMS-2TAKES-     06-29 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASSAYAS-FILMS-2TAKES-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPINNING DIALOGUES ON LOVE AND TIME'S INCURSIONS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 4) 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: No dateline with this story)  
 (af)  
 Laura Winters most recently wrote for Arts and Leisure about the
German film ``Run Lola Run.''  
 By LAURA WINTERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The office of the filmmaker Olivier Assayas is in an
out-of-the-way corner of the Ninth Arrondissement in Paris, off a
courtyard with a small fountain. Inside, the rooms have the
white-washed airiness of a summer house. When the director arrives,
he steps carefully and abstractedly over his assistant's puppy,
asleep in the doorway.
</P>
<P>
   It takes only one look at this office _ idyllic and intensely
busy at once _ to understand that Assayas is someone who believes
in spontaneity and openness to the world. One of the most
significant talents among the new generation of filmmakers working
in France, he is known for his mobile, often handheld, camera style
and for his probing explorations of young people's lives.
</P>
<P>
   Assayas' new film, ``Late August, Early September,'' which opens
on Wednesday, is a loosely structured, evocative depiction of a
group of 30ish Parisians who are drawn together by the untimely
death of a slightly older writer friend.
</P>
<P>
   The film, shot in the spring of 1998, has proved to be Assayas'
most successful in France so far and won praise last fall at both
the Toronto and New York film festivals.
</P>
<P>
   Part of its appeal lies in the warmth of its tone and the
tapestry-like layering of its storytelling. ``Late August, Early
September'' takes place over one year and explores four characters.
There is Gabriel (Mathieu Amalric), an editor breaking up with his
old girlfriend, Jenny (Jeanne Balibar), and beginning a
relationship with Anne, a volatile young clothing designer
(Virginie Ledoyen). Both Gabriel and Jenny are close to Adrien
(Francois Cluzet), the ailing writer.
</P>
<P>
   The film was born, Assayas says, out of an idea for a series of
dialogues about an individual's death: ``It came to me as the story
of one man's death and how it affects the people around him, how it
changes their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the project started with this notion, however, it soon
became something else. ``I thought I was making a film about death,
but gradually I realized how much the film is really about life,''
says Assayas, 44, speaking in almost unaccented English. Casual and
boyish, with close-cropped black hair, he laughs easily and
radiates nervous energy. As he describes the evolution of the
story, he gives an impression of both quicksilver intelligence and
of warmth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Late August'' became, for him, a celebration of the minute
texture of everyday life _ the subtle changes in people's work,
emotions and relationships that in retrospect prove to be
significant. Though the film has autobiographical elements, Assayas
said, he also wanted to give it a certain universality, to make it
``everybody's autobiography.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has gone through what goes on in this film,'' he
said. ``Everybody has broken up with a lover and fallen in love
again. Everybody has moved from one apartment to another. Everybody
has had someone dear disappear.'' He structured the film as a
series of chapters, with scenes separated by fade-outs, partly to
allow the audience to fill in the gaps with their own experiences.
</P>
<P>
   In its development of an ensemble of actors and in its emphasis
on conversations and relationships, ``Late August'' has surface
similarities to some other contemporary French films. The venerable
filmmaker Eric Rohmer, who has done a series of seasonal tales (the
most recent of which, ``Autumn Tale,'' opens Friday) is a master of
the literate French comedy-of-manners and someone Assayas admires.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the two directors present contrasts, too. ``There's a sense
of ironic observation in Rohmer's work, of a director standing back
and looking at the problems of young people,'' said Piers Handling,
director of the Toronto International Film Festival, which has
shown films by both. ``Whereas in Assayas' work there's a pretty
close identification between his sensibility and that of his
protagonists. He's very close to their predicament.''
</P>
<P>
   Another filmmaker who is often mentioned as similar to Assayas
is Arnaud Desplechin, whose 1996 film ``My Sex Life ... or How I
Got Into an Argument'' is a comedic drama about a clique of highly
self-analytic Parisian philosophy students and their assorted
loves. Both filmmakers have used the same actor ( Amalric) as their
alter ego. Both have also been described as depicting an
intellectual Parisian milieu, as opposed to the group of young
French filmmakers who portray the working class travails of the
provincial French.
</P>
<P>
   It's just a small step, however, from talking about an
intellectual milieu to calling a film ``intellectual'' or
``privileged,'' terms that make both Assayas and Amalric wince.
``Frankly, `Late August' is not intellectual,'' Amalric said over
coffee in a Paris cafe. ``It's about emotions, and themes as primal
as time passing.''
</P>
<P>
   Assayas himself sighs when asked about these classifications.
``I'm always so irritated by the description of French independent
films as being about Left Bank intellectuals and not concerned with
the real questions of life,'' he said. ``I'm sorry, but the
characters I'm dealing with are not Left Bank intellectuals. They
are people with very little money, struggling for what they believe
in. I don't know why they should be considered as privileged. Their
social problems are as serious as any other people's.''
</P>
<P>
   One factor distinguishing Assayas in the politicized arena of
French filmmaking is his insistence on approaching characters on a
personal level. ``To me, people are not defined through
sociological notions,'' he said. ``They are defined by the fact
that they are individuals, be they rich or poor.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
