<DOCNO> NYT19990629.0391 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3908 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ASSAYAS-FILMS-2NDTAKE     06-29 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASSAYAS-FILMS-2NDTAKE-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: or poor.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In that, Assayas has a lot in common with his friends and fellow
filmmakers Claire Denis and Andre Techine. Though Ms. Denis has
portrayed characters ranging from pregnant teen-agers to immigrant
workers, they are never treated as stereotypes.
</P>
<P>
   Techine, who is somewhat older and who has directed such
high-profile films as ``My Favorite Season,'' starring Catherine
Deneuve, is also known for his characters' psychological
complexity. Techine played a crucial role in Assayas' career,
inviting him to collaborate on two scripts before Assayas made his
first feature.
</P>
<P>
   On the telephone from Morocco, where he is beginning a new film,
Techine recalled spotting Assayas when Assayas was a journalist.
``I needed someone who could work at top speed,'' Techine said,
``and Olivier is as quick as lightning. But he also has an
audacious sense of form and a very rich critical spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   This collaboration certainly encouraged Assayas in his
aspiration to make films. He had been interested in film from an
early age, partly, he says, because his father was a screenwriter
well known in France under the name Jacques Remy.
</P>
<P>
   Assayas' mother, who is Hungarian, had arrived in France in
1946, fleeing communism. His parents were divorced when he was a
child, and he and his brother lived with his father. Olivier
studied painting and French literature before starting to make
short films and was a film critic for the French film journal
Cahiers du Cinema from 1980 to 1985.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, he made his first feature, ``Disorder,'' a jagged film
about an unintentional murder by the members of a young rock band.
Four other features soon followed. In them Assayas showed a special
understanding of the futile rebellion and willful opacity of the
young women whose stories he told, whether it was the drug-taking
Louise in ``Paris Awakens,'' (1991) or the desperate runaway
Christine in ``Cold Water'' (1994).
</P>
<P>
   Turbulent characters have long fascinated him. ``I think Olivier
likes to structure his films around people who are at a certain
moment of crisis,'' said Richard Pena, program director of the Film
Society of Lincoln Center, which held an Assayas retrospective in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   With ``Cold Water,'' the story of two troubled teen-agers,
Assayas found himself edging toward a more spontaneous way of
filmmaking. His sixth film, ``Irma Vep'' (no relation to the
Off-Broadway play), spun him in a thoroughly new direction,
improvisational and light-hearted. ``Irma'' is a satire about a
chaotic French film shoot graced by a visiting Asian film star
(Maggie Cheung, playing herself).
</P>
<P>
   The film's enthusiastic notices and widespread release
encouraged Assayas to continue in this vein. While ``Late August''
is not a comedy, it owes its freedom of spirit to ``Irma Vep.''
``Irma Vep'' was significant for him on another level as well: he
and Ms. Cheung were married in December.
</P>
<P>
   ``Late August'' certainly arises from currents in Assayas'
previous work, but its emotional immediacy still feels like a
departure for him _ and not because the people he depicts are
older. ``I think `Late August' is more generous and optimistic than
Olivier's earlier films,'' said Georges Benyahoun, the film's
co-producer. ``Somehow, we get closer to his characters here.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Assayas is feverishly preparing his next project, a period
drama adapted from a trilogy called ``Les Destinees
Sentimentales,'' (``Sentimental Destinies'') by the writer Jacques
Chardonne. The project, which Assayas has long been wanting to
direct, will begin filming next month.
</P>
<P>
   Set in the early 1900s, it is the story of a former clergyman
who divorces his wife, marries another woman and settles in
Switzerland. When he must return to France to take over the family
porcelain business, the move affects his marriage. The stars will
be Charles Berling, Isabelle Huppert and Emmanuelle Beart.
</P>
<P>
   The film entails a lot of firsts for Assayas: his first costume
drama, his first big production, his first work with major stars.
He seems both anxious and exhilarated at the prospect. When asked
how he plans to handle it, he replies, ``It's up to me to make this
big movie as light as I can, to try to inject into it whatever I
have learned making smaller films.''
</P>
<P>
   He laughs when reminded of the new maturity people have observed
in ``Late August.'' ``I think the one thing that I've found out
about myself is that I'm absolutely not interested in maturity,''
he said. ``It means that suddenly you're going to turn into this
person who's grown up now, and there's nothing more. No, the
exciting thing is when you understand that you are the same person
but you will keep on changing, transforming yourself as you go
through different experiences.''
</P>
<P>
   He pauses, then resumes: ``Hopefully, you will learn something
about it and you will grow. That's the thing that should never
end.''
</P>
</TEXT>
