<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Tuesday, 06/29/99. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) UNDATED -- June 29, 1999 -- MEDICAL-SCHOOL-DISPUTE, 6-29
-- Robert Ross, a New Yorker who founded Ross University, a medical
school in the Caribbean island nation of Dominica. A project to
open a branch of the school in Casper, Wyo., has stalled amid fears
that permitting a foreign medical school to operate in the United
States would lead to a proliferation of unlicensed and unregulated
schools. (Marilynn K. Yee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) NEW YORK -- June 29, 1999 -- NY-FORTUNE-TELLING, 6-29 --
A fortune telling store in New York's Eastside. Operation Crystal
Ball, a seventh-month-old effort by the New York City Police
Department's Special Frauds Squad is trying to address the problem
of illegal fortunetelling. While some stores are operating
legitimately, the police say scores of others are preying on
vulnerable people hungry for psychic solace or metaphysical wisdom.
(James Estrin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) NEW YORK -- June 29, 1999 -- HONDURAN-IMMIG, 6-29 --
Jose Basora, the taxi driver who took 13-year old Edwin Sabillion
to the airport, talks to reporters on Tuesday. Sabillion, who
captivated the city with his tale of traveling solo from Honduras
to New York in search of his father, appears to have apparently
manufactured much of what he told the police and people who helped
him, according to accounts offered on Tuesday by relatives. (Susan
B. Markisz/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NY29) UNDATED -- June 29, 1999 -- OBIT-WAYNE-B&AMP;W, 6-29 --
Marshall Wayne won two medals in the Olympic Games in Berlin. He
died at Pardee Hospital in Hendersonville, according to his sister,
Dever Antes, after he suffered a cerebral hemorrhage while working
on a book on his home computer. He was 87. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) WASHINGTON -- June 29, 1999 -- AMTRAK-2, 6-29 -- Amtrak
unveiled the Acela Express which will begin running late this year
between Boston, New York and Washington. More comfortable
surroundings and ample lavatories are part of the amenities in the
new train which makes the New York to Washington route in two hours
and 43 minutes, 16 minutes faster then the current Metroliner.
(Shana Raab/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) WASHINGTON -- June 29, 1999 -- AMTRAK-1, 6-29 -- Amtrak
unveiled the Acela Express which will begin running late this year
between Boston, New York and Washington. More comfortable
surroundings and ample lavatories are part of the amenities in the
new train which makes the New York to Washington route in two hours
and 43 minutes, 16 minutes faster then the current Metroliner.
(Shana Raab/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) PHNOM PENH, Cambodia -- June 29, 1999 --
CAMBODIA-PRISON-3, 6-29 -- Guides play volleyball outside the Tuol
Sleng high school building which was used as a torture chamber by
the Khmer Rouge and is now a museum. From 1975 to 1979, some 14,000
people are believed to have been killed at this former school.
(Darren Whiteside/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) PHNOM PENH, Cambodia -- June 29, 1999 --
CAMBODIA-PRISON-2, 6-29 -- A cot in one of the rooms of the Tuol
Sleng high school building which was used as a torture chamber by
the Khmer Rouge and is now a museum. From 1975 to 1979, some 14,000
people are believed to have been killed at this former school.
Twice a year monks visit to chant Buddhist exorcisms to calm the
ghosts which are said to haunt the facility. (Darren Whiteside/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) PHNOM PENH, Cambodia -- June 29, 1999 --
CAMBODIA-PRISON-1, 6-29 -- A young cyclist walks past the Tuol
Sleng high school building, the most efficient and terrifying
torture chamber during the Khmer Rouge years, which is now a
museum. From 1975 to 1979, some 14,000 people are believed to have
been killed here. Twice a year monks visit to chant Buddhist
exorcisms to calm the ghosts which are said to haunt the facility.
(Darren Whiteside/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) UNDATED -- June 29, 1999 -- GUN-SHOWS-2-BOS, 6-29 --
Mary Cummings, licensed gun dealer. How do you keep kids from
playing with guns? ``That's the responsibility of parents,'' she
says. ``You don't go around leaving Clorox and chemicals around the
house, so why do it with guns? Keep guns secure. Instead of a gun
lock and hiding it and saying don't touch it, try explaining that
its not like you see on TV where the bad guy gets shot and he's
back next week.'' (Stan Grossfeld/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) UNDATED -- June 29, 1999 -- GUN-SHOWS-1-BOS, 6-29 --
Stephen Tressler, 38, a firearms collector and father of 3-year-old
Gage. Why did Littleton happen? ``It's not because of guns,'' he
says. ``It's the way parents bring up their children. They don't
teach them right from wrong.'' (Stan Grossfeld/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) NASH, Texas -- June 29, 1999 -- INFANT-DEATHS-2-COX,
6-29 -- Anthony Zimmerman's memorial plaque at Chapelwood Memorial
Gardens in Nash is decorated with flowers and toys. Zimmerman died
of undetermined causes in February when he was six-months-old; more
than 2,000 couples suffer the loss of a child younger than
1-year-old each year in Texas. (Longview News-Journal photo,
Anntoinette Moore)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) LONGVIEW, Texas -- June 29, 1999 -- INFANT-DEATHS-1-COX,
6-29 --Tina and Richard Zimmerman holding a photo of Tina's
daughter, Katelyn, and their son, Anthony, who died of undetermined
causes in February when he was six-months-old. ``He was clinging to
me and looking at me,'' but he wasn't breathing, says Zimmerman,
22. He and his wife, Tina, 18, are just one of the more than 2,000
couples who suffer the loss of a child younger than 1-year-old each
year in Texas. (Anntoinette Moore/Longview News-Journal Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) ATLANTA -- June 29, 1999 -- R-MOVIES-TEENS30-COX, 6-29
-- From left, Matt Malissa, 14, Priya Wijesinghe, 14, and Whitney
Simmons, 13, outside an Atlanta multiplex. In the wake of recent
high school shootings in Colorado and Georgia, many theaters have
pledged that they will be stepping up efforts to keep younger teens
out of R-rated movies. ``We could buy tickets for 'Tarzan.' It's
not like they guard the doors,'' says Matt. ``A lot of kids look
older than they are,'' says Priya. ``My parents are like, 'We trust
you,' `` says Whitney. (Phil Skinner/Atlanta Journal-Constitution
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) WASHINGTON -- June 29, 1999 -- COUNSEL-LAW, 6-29 -- Sen.
Arlen Specter, R-Pa., left, talks to reporters about sponsorship of
legislation to preserve the office of the independent counsel but
with new restrictions on Tuesday. Looking on are Sens. Susan
Collins, R-Maine, Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., and Carl Levin,
D-Mich., all of whom are co-sponsors of the legislation. The
independent counsel law, born of scandal and steeped in
controversy, expires on Wednesday. (Justin Lane/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) WASHINGTON -- June 29, 1999 -- Y2K-LAWSUITS, 6-29 --
Sen. Ron Wyden, D-Ore., left, and Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn.,
second from left, talk with Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., right, about
legislation on liability over Y2K computer problems on Tuesday. At
center is General Counsel on the Commerce Committee Marti Albright.
Infuriating many Democrats, the White House on Tuesday was on the
verge of an agreement with Republicans in Congress on legislation
to limit lawsuits arising from Year 2000 computer breakdowns.
(Justin Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) WASHINGTON -- June 29, 1999 -- MEDICARE-CLINTON-3, 6-29
-- Reporters on Capitol Hill question Senate Majority Leader Trent
Lott about Medicare legislation just before President Clinton
outlined his Medicare proposals at the White House on Tuesday. In a
joint statement, House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., and Sen.
Lott, R-Miss., pledged to seek ``a bipartisan solution to expand
access to affordable prescription drugs.'' (Justin Lane/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) LITTLETON, Colo. -- June 29, 1999 --
COLO-SCHOOL-MURDERS-4, 6-28 -- The house of Eric Harris in late
April. On April 20, when Harris and Dylan Klebold stormed into
Columbine High School in this Denver suburb and killed 12
classmates and a teacher, then themselves, their parents suffered
more than the loss of a child. The boys' bombs and bullets
shattered their parents' very view of the world, undermining what
had seemed to them and others to be18 years of responsible
child-rearing. (Andrea Mohin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) WASHINGTON -- June 29, 1999 -- MEDICARE-CLINTON-2, 6-29
-- Rep. Bill Thomas, R-Calif., puts his arm around Sen. John
Breaux, D-La., with whom he co-chaired the Medicare Commission,
while talking with outgoing Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin and
Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., right, on Tuesday in
the East Room of the White House. Promising better Medicare
benefits to match scientific advances, President Clinton proposed
free preventive health services plus a $1,000-a-year prescription
drug benefit for older and disabled Americans. (Paul Hosefros/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) WASHINGTON -- June 29, 1999 -- MEDICARE-CLINTON, 6-29 --
President Clinton in the East Room of the White House during his
speech proposing improved Medicare benefits on Tuesday. Promising
better benefits to match scientific advances, President Clinton
proposed free preventive health services plus a $1,000-a-year
prescription drug benefit for older and disabled Americans.(Paul
Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) FALL RIVER, Mass. -- June 29, 1999 --
TRAVEL-CAROUSELS-BOS, 6-29 -- The Fall River Carousel at Battleship
Cove was built in 1920 by the Philadelphia Toboggan Co. This
spectacular 48-horse carousel was meticulously restored in Ohio
before settling into the Fall River waterfront. (Michael
Robinson-Chavez/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) BOSTON -- June 29, 1999 -- GRAPHIC-PLANES-BOS, 6-29 --
USAir jets at Logan International Airport with the new, foreground,
and old, rear, paint schemes. Airlines must seem modern and cutting
edge, so colors or print type that were fashionable a decade ago
can seem terribly passe, industry specialists say. As a result an
airline's colors - what the industry calls livery - get changed
frequently. (Michael Robinson-Chavez/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) HOUSTON -- June 29, 1999 -- FOOD-AIRLINES-HNS, 06-29 --
Chef Resa Kelly displays two trays of food she developed for
Continental Airlines' Chef-on-Board program. ``It's the upside-down
world of what I do,'' says the Houston chef. Ms. Kelly joins a long
list of culinary luminaries upgrading and updating airline food,
including Paul Prudhomme for American Airlines, Michel Roux for
British Airways and Raymond Blanc for Virgin Atlantic. (Buster
Dean/Houston Chronicle Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) KOSOVO POLJE, Yugoslavia -- June 29, 1999 --
KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC-BOS, 6-29 -- Residents line up to buy bread at a
local bakery in Kosovo Polje. As the cycle of violence turns
against the Serbs, disillusionment with Slobodan Milosevic's
nationalist dreams seems to be cresting. Each day Serbs in Kosovo,
the southern province of what is left of Yugoslavia, are turning
against Milosevic. (Bill Greene/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- June 29, 1999 -- CARNEGIE-EDUC, 6-29 -- Many
students attending a concert in Carnegie Hall this month had taken
part in Linkup, the hall's music education program, which involved
22,000 children in grades four through six this year. Linkup
emphasizes basic music concepts and music's relationships to other
academic subjects through classes, planning sessions for teachers
and artists, and concerts in schools and neighborhoods. (Ozier
Muhammad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) UNDATED -- June 29, 1999 -- KITCHEN-WARES, 6-29 -- The
Coleman Powermax Grill Stove. Miniature gas grills are, relatively
speaking, pristine. By comparison with their charcoal brethren,
they are nearly effort free. But by definition, they are also less
powerful than a full-size gas grill; even a small charcoal grill
can get hotter. (Tony Cenicola/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- June 29, 1999 -- ICE-CREAM, 6-29 -- It
happens every summer now. Chefs and their pastry pros get an urge
to start throwing everything but the dish washer into their creme
anglaise. And their customers keep pushing them even further by
actually eating the stuff. From left, Hyssop (Picholine), Raspberry
Hibiscus (Daniel), Sweet Potato (Mesa Grill), Curry (Acquavit),
Beet-Yogurt Swirl (Acquavit), Black Bean (Avenue) and Mango-Pink
Peppercorn (Pacific East). (Kiyoshi Togashi/New York Times Photo)
LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) UNDATED -- June 29, 1999 -- GEHRIG-AUCTION, 06-28 -- The
uniform worn by Lou Gehrig at Yankee Stadium on July 4, 1939, when,
between games of a doubleheader, he declared himself ``the luckiest
man on the face of the earth'' despite a diagnosis of amyotrophic
lateral sclerosis. Leland's auction house in Manhattan hopes to
sell the flannel jersey and pants for at least $295,000 when
bidding, which began last week, concludes on July 9. (Carol
Halebian/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) HOUSTON -- June 29, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SAT. JULY 3 --
MILLENNIUM-GENETICS-HNS, 06-29 -- Baylor engineer Seth Paxton
operates the robotic arm that sets up trays of ingredients for DNA
sequencing at Baylor College of Medicine's Genome Sequencing
Center. The school is a leading participant in the federal
government's Human Genome Project, whose mapping of the human
body's estimated 100,000 genes is expected to provide the knowledge
that one day will lead to designer babies. (Smiley N. Pool/Houston
Chronicle Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) ROGOVE, Yugoslavia -- June 29, 1999 -- KOSOVO-BUILD-2,
6-29 -- Ibrahim Berisha, 48,an ethnic Albanian, scrubs graffiti
from his home's wooden doors on Monday. Serb soldiers scrawled
phrases like: ``Death to Albanians.'' There is not much money in
Kosovo, and aid groups are just beginning their work. But the
Kosovar refugees who have returned here in the last two weeks are
already working hard to rebuild the best they can. (Tyler Hicks/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) DJAKOVICA, Yugoslavia -- June 29, 1999 -- KOSOVO-BUILD-2,
6-29 --Rasim Thaqi pries wood on Monday from the roof of a building
which was part of a Serb police barrack bombed by NATO. Thaqi is
rebuilding his life using what is left of the village which is not
at all surprising given how much raw material sits in twisted heaps
following NATO's bombing campaign. (Tyler Hicks/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) DJAKOVICA, Yugoslavia -- June 29, 1999 -- KOSOVO-BUILD-1,
6-29 --Shan Salihu, 64, an ethnic Albanian, carries a wooden door
on Monday which he had just removed from what is left of the local
Serb police barracks. Salihu is rebuilding his life using what is
left of the wreckage in the village which is not at all surprising
given how much raw material sits in twisted heaps following NATO's
bombing campaign. (Tyler Hicks/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
