<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3917 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-DRAFT-PREVIEW-COX     06-29 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-DRAFT-PREVIEW-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hawks get 10th pick in Blaylock deal
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There is a price to pay when a good team collapses in
the playoffs, and Tuesday night Mookie Blaylock became the first
Hawks player to pay.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks shipped him along with the 21st pick of tonight's NBA
draft to Golden State for the No. 10 pick, point guard Bimbo Coles
and former Hawks and Georgia Tech forward Duane Ferrell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mookie gave us seven great years,'' general manager Pete
Babcock said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really did,'' coach Lenny Wilkens said, ``but when you have
an opportunity like this, you have to move on. Mookie did a fine
job for us, but we have to keep getting better.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks will grab one of the draft's talented young point
guards tonight and allow him to learn on the job with Coles and
Anthony Johnson acting as parachutes.
</P>
<P>
   Who are the Hawks going to take?
</P>
<P>
   Figure Maryland's Steve Francis and UCLA's Baron Davis will be
among the first three players taken in the draft. That leaves
Utah's Andre Miller, Arizona's Jason Terry and Duke's William
Avery. Some scouts are predicting that Miller could be available,
especially if Cleveland decides to trade Brevin Knight, a poor
shooter, and takes Terry with the eighth pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can live with any of them,'' said Babcock, who also refused
to limit himself to a point guard at No. 10, ``in the event a
player with great potential falls. We'd have to take him. The big
thing is we wanted to move up, and now we're in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   But figure a point guard. If it's Miller, they get a consummate
playmaker who is mature at 23, ready-made for the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   If it's Terry, they get a point who is very quick, can score and
make plays, another four-year player, who played with Mike Bibby.
</P>
<P>
   If it's Avery, an Augusta native, the Hawks get a brilliant
athlete, who spent two years at Duke, a former teammate of young
forward Roshown McLeod.
</P>
<P>
   ``Huge upside,'' assistant coach Phil Hubbard said, adding that
the Hawks could rotate three points if necessary until their rookie
is comfortable early.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves the Hawks with picks Nos. 17, 20 and 27, pending
further dealing.
</P>
<P>
   What's more they apparently are very close to pulling off
another trade involving an established player on the team. The only
problem here: the deal cannot be consummated until Aug. 1 when new
contracts can be signed. That means a sign-and-trade deal.
</P>
<P>
   More cautious than his boss, team president Stan Kasten, Babcock
rated the chance of getting this one done at 65 percent.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Hawks have already made a statement, dealing a
seven-year starter who led the NBA in steals for three straight
years before dropping off last season.
</P>
<P>
   The problems with Blaylock were evident to all. He liked to walk
the ball up the floor. He liked to shoot and he did not shoot very
well. From a peak of .432 in 1996-97, he slipped to .392 and .379,
reflecting the difficulty of making three-pointers once the line
was moved back to 23 feet, 6 inches.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor: Coles ($2.1 million) and Ferrell ($1.6 million)
have only one year remaining on their contracts. Blaylock has three
at $4.2 million, $4.8 million and $5.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Blaylock was willing to step up and take big shots in
games. He is a hard-nosed defender and with Dikembe Mutombo gave
the Hawks a lethal combination of ball thief and shot blocker.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll still emphasize defense,'' Wilkens said. ``That will
never change. We'll play hard, but assignments could change.''
</P>
<P>
   Babcock said Blaylock realized that he might be traded, ending a
relationship that predated Wilkens by one year when Rumeal Robinson
was dealt to New Jersey for the sturdy Texan. ``He read the
(Journal-Constitution) this morning and he called me and then he
called Lenny. He understood what we were doing. When we completed
the deal (at 6:30 p.m.) we called him back and told him. He was
okay with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Blaylock could not be reached for comment Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the tempo will change. The Hawks always play best
when they play fast and this trade virtually assures a more
up-tempo game when they move into Philips Arena in November.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is more to be done, even with the mystery trade.
Babcock said Tuesday night the team's needs include a backup
center, preferably one who can score, and a shooting guard who can
play behind Steve Smith. The Hawks will test the draft for that,
but there remains a possibility that they are not finished dealing
with the Warriors, especially if Golden State is successful in
bringing back free agent guard Mitch Richmond, who played with
Washington last season.
</P>
<P>
   Richmond going to Golden State would make the combustible John
Starks available and he would be the perfect antidote to offensive
lulls.
</P>
<P>
   As for the ex-Warriors who were acquired Tuesday, Coles, 31, is
a competent backup who averaged 9.5, 4.6 assists in 26.5 minutes a
game last season. He spent his first five seasons in Miami where he
played three seasons with Smith. Ferrell spent his first six NBA
seasons with the Hawks. Often an effective backup, he signed as a
free agent with Indiana and was dealt to the Warriors. At 34, his
playing time had diminished dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Denberg writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
