<SLUG> BC-LATIN-EURO-SUMMIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATIN-EUROPEAN SUMMIT ENDS WITHOUT MAJOR AGREEMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also LATIN-ECON) 
(mk) 
 By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil _ The first-ever summit of Latin American
and European nations ended here Tuesday with leaders of the world's
second- and third-largest trading blocs unable to agree on a
timetable or an agenda for negotiations for a free-trade agreement.
They opted instead for a much vaguer ``strategic partnership'' and
commitment to ``encouraging the increase and diversification of
trade.''
</P>
<P>
   In a joint communique, the 15-member European Union and
Mercosur, the South American customs union composed of Argentina,
Brazil, Paraguay and Uruguay, set this November for the start of
meetings to consider proposals ``regarding the definition of the
structure, methodology and calendar'' of future talks. But formal
negotiations on tariff issues are not scheduled to begin until at
least July 2001, and no deadline was set for their conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   That modest commitment fell far short of what advocates of
stronger commercial ties between the two blocs had sought. At a
news conference here Tuesday morning, Antonio Guterres, the prime
minister of Portugal, said he ``had hoped the process would have
moved further ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mercosur group, with 200 million people and a combined
economy of more than $1 trillion, has been pushing Europe to grant
more access for its agricultural products like meat, wheat, sugar
and oil seeds, over the objections of France and a few other
countries. The Europeans, in turn, are insisting the South
Americans open up their service sectors further and reduce barriers
to imports of automobiles and car parts.
</P>
<P>
   With Mercosur and the rest of Latin America already negotiating
a free trade pact with the United States, ``it is necessary to work
with urgency,'' said Guterres, whose government will assume the
presidency of the European Union in January 2000 and has been one
of the strongest advocates of closer ties between Europe and Latin
America. At a news conference following the formal closure of the
summit, Germany's chancellor, Gerhard Schroeder, speaking for the
European bloc, described the two-day meeting here, attended by
leaders of 48 countries, as a ``historical landmark.'' He expressed
confidence that both regions would act in concert on some issues
during the next round of talks at the World Trade Organization this
fall.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder and the president of Brazil, Fernando Henrique
Cardoso, along with his Mexican counterpart, Ernesto Zedillo, all
made an effort to deny that one of their goals in meeting here was
to outflank the United States or create a counterweight to it.
Though not invited to the conference, American officials have
praised the meeting here as a positive step toward freer world
trade.
</P>
<P>
   Cardoso said Europe and Latin America together were seeking to
create ``a diversity of centers of decision.''
</P>
<P>
   But even on those nontrade issues, some negotiators went home
frustrated. The president of Chile, Eduardo Frei, could not
persuade Britain and Spain to halt judicial proceedings against
Gen. Augusto Pinochet, the former dictator of Chile held in Britain
pending an extradition request from Spain.
</P>
<P>
   Fidel Castro failed to get a condemnation of the Helms-Burton
Act, the American law imposing sanctions on foreign investors in
Cuba, included in the summit's final declaration. Britain's foreign
secretary, Robin Cook, who met with his Cuban counterpart in the
highest level contacts between those governments in 40 years,
lobbied unsuccessfully on behalf of four political prisoners held
by Castro's government.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Latin American countries were quick to take
advantage of the opportunities offered by the summit to strengthen
trade ties among themselves. In an advance toward economic
integration within South America, for instance, the host country,
Brazil, reached an agreement with the five members of the Andean
Pact to reduce or eliminate tariffs on more than 3,000 products.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Brazil and Venezuela, which have been working
quietly to strengthen their electricity and transport links,
reached an agreement Tuesday to step up cooperation in the oil and
natural gas industries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
