<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: JWT HIRES EXECUTIVE TO MARKET AGENCY ITSELF 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Ill.)   (bl)  
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In another high-profile hire, J. Walter Thompson is
naming a top executive to a new post with duties that include
marketing the agency itself.
</P>
<P>
   The executive is Mary Baglivo, who unexpectedly announced in May
that she would resign as chief executive at Euro RSCG Tatham in
Chicago for personal reasons and return with her family to the East
Coast. Ms. Baglivo, 41, will join Thompson, effective Sept. 1, as
executive vice president and chief marketing officer-U.S.A.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Baglivo, a specialist in advertising for packaged-goods
marketers like Procter &AMP; Gamble Co., has been one of the three top
managers at Euro RSCG Tatham, part of the Euro RSCG Worldwide unit
of Havas Advertising. She also helped that agency land clients
including Midas International, the Red Lobster unit of Darden
Restaurants Inc. and the Sam's Clubs unit of Wal-Mart Stores Inc.
</P>
<P>
   For Thompson, part of WPP Group PLC, Ms. Baglivo will work on
accounts to be determined, assist in seeking new accounts, try to
persuade clients to award the agency additional assignments and
serve broadly to promote the Thompson brand in the United States.
Her hiring and the nature of her new job are indicative of the
steps big agencies are taking to reinvent themselves and
reinvigorate their offerings.
</P>
<P>
   ``This agency is such a believer in the power of branding,'' Ms.
Baglivo said Tuesday in an interview in midtown Manhattan during a
visit to New York, ``that it believes branding is pivotal to its
own success.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to market us to our new-business prospects,''
she added, ``to our current clients who can be further developed,
to prospective business partners and to prospective employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The essence of this marketing job will be to tap the creative
brains of this agency, and to articulate in the most provocative
way what J. Walter Thompson can stand for.''
</P>
<P>
   This was not the first time that Thompson executives had pursued
Ms. Baglivo, who spent 18 years at Euro RSCG Tatham and its
predecessor, Tatham-Laird &AMP; Kudner. She was among the contenders
last year for the presidency of the agency's flagship New York
office, a post that eventually went to Bob Jeffrey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I met Mary three years ago, and we've talked about all kinds
of things ever since,'' said Thompson chief executive Chris Jones
in a telephone interview. ``I'm really pleased we persuaded her to
do this.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked why he thinks there's something about Mary, Jones laughed
and replied: ``She's someone who excites creative people and
clients. She combines emotion and intellect. She can talk about
brands in a very human way, as well as in a very analytical way.
And she has the skills and lightness of touch to do all that
diplomatically.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Baglivo will report to Jones and to Charlotte Beers, who was
named chairwoman at Thompson in March. The two women worked
together for many years at Euro RSCG Tatham, where Ms. Beers was a
predecessor of Ms. Baglivo as chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Baglivo joins a lengthening list of new managers at Thompson
who have arrived from elsewhere. Among them are Marina Hahn,
executive vice president for strategy and entertainment at the
Thompson New York office, who came from an executive post at the
William Morris Agency in New York; Jeff Chesebro, senior partner
and business development director at Thompson New York, who had
been vice president and new-business director at Partners &AMP;
Shevack/Wolf in New York, part of Wolf Group, and Patrick Corry,
executive vice president and director in charge of the Unilever
North America account, who had been executive vice president and
worldwide director for the account of the Frito-Lay unit of Pepsico
Inc. at BBDO Worldwide in New York, part of the Omnicom Group.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson ``is passionate about bringing in new kinds of talent,
people from different backgrounds with what I call an
entrepreneurial energy,'' Ms. Baglivo said. ``The fusion should
result in some very interesting work.''
</P>
<P>
   Those arrivals are emblematic of Thompson's improving fortunes.
The agency had suffered a spate of account losses and executive
departures in 1997 and 1998. In addition to the new hires, the
agency has recently landed new accounts with billings estimated at
more than $600 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``The timing is great,'' Ms. Baglivo said of her arrival. ``What
Chris had as a vision is starting to materialize and turn
tangible.''
</P>
<P>
   The trade publications Advertising Age and Adweek had reported
that Ms. Baglivo was considering joining Thompson to reunite with
Ms. Beers, though they also said she was in talks with other
agencies like DDB Worldwide Communications Group in New York, part
of Omnicom.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was fun for me to look every week and see who I was talking
to,'' Ms. Baglivo said. ``I got a couple of ideas from what they
were writing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
