<SLUG> BC-CALIF-RADIO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POWER STRUGGLE DISRUPTS OLDEST PUBLIC RADIO STATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By EVELYN NIEVES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERKELEY, Calif. _ The trouble at radio station KPFA has come to
this: When two folk singers scheduled to perform as a duo on Sunday
afternoon arrived at the building, armed security guards would only
let one of them inside.
</P>
<P>
   Security measures taken last week after 30 people stormed the
station allow staff members to bring only one guest unless names of
guests are submitted beforehand. The duo's names were not on the
security list, so the show did not go on.
</P>
<P>
   The incident on Sunday was just one small example of how serious
the fight has become between KPFA, the nation's oldest public radio
station, and the Pacifica Foundation, which owns the station and
four others in Los Angeles, Houston, New York and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last few months, KPFA, known for its leftist point of
view and reporting that ranges from East Timor in Indonesia to
People's Park a few blocks away, has been at the center of street
protests and arrests, the firing of veteran reporters and other
employees, potential lawsuits, even gunshots and death threats.
</P>
<P>
   At the core of the increasingly ugly run-ins between KPFA's
staff members and supporters and its management _ a conflict that
local public radio stations across the country are following with
intense interest _ is a classic power struggle over who controls
what goes on the airwaves.
</P>
<P>
   KPFA, founded 50 years ago by pacifists, receives 80 percent to
85 percent of its financing from donations (the rest from grants
and bequests) and emphasizes programs with community members and
militants as guests and hosts.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first station to broadcast Allen Ginsberg reading
``Howl,'' Che Guevara trying to foment revolution just months
before his killing in Bolivia, and Patty Hearst, the kidnapped
heiress, calling her parents ``capitalist pigs.''
</P>
<P>
   The continuing protests here _ the latest was on Monday evening,
with more than 100 people holding placards and chanting ``Free
KPFA'' _ began as rumblings of discontent from staff members and
listeners, who say they started noticing a shift in the last two or
three years away from Pacifica's traditional style of
community-influenced programming and decision-making, toward a
hierarchical bureaucracy that wants to dictate its orders to a
community that, in essence, owns the station.
</P>
<P>
   The rumblings grew louder when Pacifica unveiled a ``strategic
plan'' several months ago that called for more national programming
and removed local advisory board members from the central governing
board. The unrest exploded into full-scale protests and picket
lines when KPFA's general manager, Nicole Sawaya, was fired on
March 31, two weeks before the station's 50th anniversary
celebration.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Lasar, a former news reporter at the station and author
of ``Pacifica: The Rise of an Alternative Network'' (Temple
University Press, 1999), said that the firing of Ms. Sawaya _ on
the ground that she was not a team player _ made the perceptions of
top-down decision-making concrete.
</P>
<P>
   ``KPFA is the closest thing that the Bay area secular left has
to a church,'' Lasar said, ``and Pacifica threw out the preacher
two weeks before Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   While Pacifica circulated a memorandum warning programmers not
to discuss the firing on the air, they promptly did. When KPFA's
veteran national news reporter and signature voice, Larry Bensky,
objected to the dismissal of the general manager, he too was fired.
</P>
<P>
   Pacifica's executive director, Lynn Chadwick, said all the
protests started because a small group of people refused to allow
KPFA to grow. She said Pacifica wanted to broaden its appeal and
reach more than 200,000 of the 6 million potential listeners in its
59,000-watt channel, and that a hard-core group of listeners and
staff members did not want the station to change.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the people who have called me are still talking about
some of the programming changes made in the mid-'90s,'' Ms.
Chadwick said. ``Whenever there is any change, there are some
people who want things to be the way they think they were when we
started, who are going to resist it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Chadwick, who has become the focal point of the protesters'
wrath, said that tighter security measures had to be imposed last
week after she was cornered in her office by 30 protesters who
refused to leave. In addition, the day after the general manager,
Ms. Sawaya, was let go _ Ms. Sawaya's contract was not renewed, but
she was not technically dismissed, Ms. Chadwick said _ gunshots
were fired into Pacifica's headquarters, next door to KPFA. Ms.
Chadwick said she had also been called names by protesters and
received death threats.
</P>
<P>
   ``The level of heat is not good,'' she said. ``It's not good for
any of us. After all, we're all on the same side _ we want a good
community radio station.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
