<HEADER>
A3927 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COUNSEL-LAW-1STLD-WRI     06-29 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COUNSEL-LAW-1STLD-WRITETHRU-720&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW RULES FOR INVESTIGATIONS TO TAKE EFFECT AS INDEPENDENT COUNSEL
LAW EXPIRES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDS: Subs graphs 1 thru 5 to add details and clarify these are
rules, not draft provisions; subs graph 7 to add details of law's
history) (rm) 
 By DAVID JOHNSTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Corruption investigations of presidents and high
government officials will change significantly at midnight
Wednesday with the expiration of the law that gave the country
Whitewater prosecutor Kenneth Starr and 19 other independent
counsels during the last two decades.
</P>
<P>
   Starting on Thursday, decisions about how and whether to launch
ethics investigations of top officials will be left to Attorney
General Janet Reno, who has sent to Congress the rules under which
her department will name special prosecutors in certain cases.The
rules give the attorney general far more discretion than the
current independent counsel law, the Ethics in Government Act.
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, Ms. Reno quietly dispatched a draft of the rules to
Congress for the information of its members. The new rules
dispensed with the convoluted and sometimes controversial
procedures of the independent counsel law, with its three-judge
panels to appoint the counsels and multiple preliminary inquiries
on whether the attorney general should request such an appointment.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, she left to herself the authority to decide crucial
matters now strictly governed by the statute, such as when to
appoint someone from outside the Justice Department to carry out an
investigation of a high-level administration official.
</P>
<P>
   Under Reno's rules, she alone would be responsible for
appointing a special prosecutor, as such prosecutors would now be
known, only after she decided that an investigation would pose a
conflict of interest within the Justice Department and that such an
outside prosecutor was in the public interest. Under existing law,
appointments are not made by the attorney general, but by a
three-judge panel.
</P>
<P>
   There will be few mourners of the Ethics in Government Act and
not a chance that lawmakers will revive the statute in its present
form.
</P>
<P>
   The law, enacted in 1978, stands as a crumbling monument to
Watergate and the Saturday Night Massacre, the crisis over
President Nixon's successful effort to fire a special prosecutor.
But after 21 years, support for the law eroded in Washington's
scandal glutted culture because of accusations that both parties
had turned the law into a political weapon against incumbents. The
total cost of all independent counsel inquiries as of April was
$167 million.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general was an enthusiastic supporter of the
independent counsel law shortly after taking office in 1993. But
after years of being bludgeoned over her decisions, she announced
at a congressional appearance in March that the statute was too
``structurally flawed'' to be saved.
</P>
<P>
   A few lawmakers have offered proposals to preserve aspects of
the current law, including one offered Tuesday by a bipartisan
group including two Republicans, Arlen Specter or Pennsylvania and
Susan Collins of Maine and two Democrats, Carl Levin of Michigan
and Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut. Theirs would keep the law
largely intact, but tinker substantially with central provisions,
narrowing the number of officials covered, raising the threshold
for appointment, improving the quality of independent counsel
appointees. Few lawmakers give such ideas much chance of winning
much support _ at least not unless the Justice Department's new
approach fails.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the new regulations nor the expiration of the law has
any impact on existing independent counsels like Starr and the four
other currently serving prosecutors. These independent prosecutors
are investigating the activities of Interior Secretary Bruce
Babbitt, Labor Secretary Alexis Herman, former Housing Secretary
Henry Cisneros and events surrounding former Secretary Mike Espy's
tenure at the Agriculture Department. Espy was acquitted of charges
that he accepted illegal gifts.
</P>
<P>
   Of the sitting prosecutors, only Starr has hinted that he might
consider closing down when the law expires. He offered a possible
sign of his intentions on Monday when lawyers following the case
said that he had reached a plea bargain agreement with Webster
Hubbell, a former top Justice Department official.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The deal, in which Hubbell would plead guilty to lying about the
role he and Hillary Rodham Clinton played in a failed Arkansas land
deal, would avert a trial and end the last pending prosecution in
the nearly five-year investigation of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The ethics law lies in ruins largely because it failed,
abysmally, in the view of almost every official who has been
scrutinized by independent counsels, in its goal of extracting
politics from inquiries into alleged abuses by top government
officials. Starr himself is a critic of the statute and testified
against its renewal.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Fred Thompson, a Tennessee Republican and chairman of the
Governmental Affairs Committee, said after his committee held a
series of hearings to consider amending the law, that he had
abandoned any effort to fix it. He instead recommended: ``Give it a
decent burial.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was not the first president to complain of excesses by
an independent prosecutor armed with grand jury subpoenas. But no
other president has been so seriously threatened. After Starr's
referral of alleged misdeeds involving Monica Lewinsky, Clinton was
impeached by the House but acquitted after a Senate trial.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton's predecessors also complained that independent
prosecutors had turned political differences into criminal
offenses. During the terms of President Ronald Reagan and George
Bush, Lawrence E. Walsh, the Iran-Contra independent counsel, was
regularly attacked by Republicans for his aggressive investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh continued to investigate for six years until President
Bush delivered a death blow in the form of a Christmas Eve pardon
in 1992 _ after he had lost the election to Clinton _ absolving
former Defense Secretary Caspar W. Weinberger and five other
officials who had either been charged or convicted of wrongdoing in
the affair.
</P>
<P>
   Even Walsh, however, concluded that the law should be
drastically narrowed. ``It's had its moment and that moment has
passed,'' Walsh said. ``Let's see how we get along.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
