<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3931 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-FORTUNETELLING-ART     06-29 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-FORTUNETELLING-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE SAY ILLEGAL FORTUNETELLERS HAVE ARRESTS IN THEIR FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Also see sidebar, NY-FORTUNETELLING-MUSEUM)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
 (bl)  
 By ROBIN POGREBIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The green awning outside the quaint Greenwich Village
storefront advertises ``psychic,'' but the 37-year-old
fortuneteller who calls herself Pamela Miller probably will not
answer the door anymore. Police said she was arrested June 24 for
making a woman in her 40s believe she had a curse and taking
$50,000 of her money over three years to get rid of it.
</P>
<P>
   It was the 13th arrest under Operation Crystal Ball, a
seven-month-old effort by the the city Police Department's Special
Frauds Squad to address the problem of illegal fortunetelling.
</P>
<P>
   They can be seen all the time across all five boroughs: women in
storefronts promising to read palms or tarot cards. Police estimate
there are about 200 of the businesses in the city. While some are
operating legitimately, police said, scores of others are preying
on vulnerable people hungry for psychic solace or metaphysical
wisdom. Victims have paid out as much as $500,000 over an extended
period, police said, including a psychologist who was taken for
$250,000.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunetelling is legal for entertainment _ like hiring someone
to read tarot cards at a party. But the penal code calls it a
misdemeanor when a person ``holds himself out as being able, by
claimed or pretended use of occult powers, to answer questions or
give advice on personal matters or to exorcise, influence or affect
evil spirits or curses.'' Those who extract large sums are often
charged with larceny, a more serious crime.
</P>
<P>
   Simply put, the problem starts when fortunetellers _ who are not
licensed by the city _ start telling customers that they have
serious problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fortunetelling isn't a crime in itself,'' said Lt. Robert
Groth, who heads the Special Frauds Squad. ``It's when they start
predicting things, putting people in fear, telling them they're
cursed or possessed.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem is not limited to New York City. Jeanine Giacalone,
a 26-year-old Long Island woman, was having trouble sleeping and
had consulted psychiatrists, priests and physicians. Nothing
worked. So she went to see a psychic she had driven past in Hampton
Bays, and the woman told her she had ``a lot of negativity in her
aura.''
</P>
<P>
   To cure her, Ms. Giacalone said the fortuneteller, charged for
various supplies: wax molds of her to meditate over, beeswax
candles, holy oil. She also told Ms. Giacalone to give her $2,000
for a retreat to the Middle East to get a special root.
</P>
<P>
   Six months and $3,000 later, Ms. Giacalone said she realized she
had been defrauded and went to the police. Ms. Giacalone said the
fortunteller returned the money in exchange for Ms. Giacalone's
dropping the charges. ``I wanted to believe in something,'' said
Ms. Giacalone, who owns an insurance agency. ``I'm not naive or
unintelligent.''
</P>
<P>
   In New York City, Operation Crystal Ball has shed new light on a
business that dates back at least 100 years and has been a source
of livelihood for immigrants through many generations. Research by
the Lower East Side Tenement Museum has found that fortunetellers
were once respected among European immigrants and considered
authorities in the community on a par with religious leaders or
doctors or other professionals.
</P>
<P>
   Such days appear to be long past. While police said that
fortunetellers today are mostly Gypsies _ a people originally from
India who came to the United States via Europe _ who pass the
tradition down through their daughters, the approach that some of
them use is hardly noble.
</P>
<P>
   Detective Bob Geis, who specializes in such cases and related
crimes, said some fortunetellers work out of their own apartments _
often in upscale neighborhoods _ all over the city, drive expensive
cars and make on average about $200,000 a year. After all, they are
offering services to a society in which at least one White House
has consulted an astrologer and millions call psychic hot lines.
</P>
<P>
   A number of self-professed psychics say the criminal element is
not necessarily representative of their business. ``Some psychics
are good and some are bad, just like doctors and dentists,'' said
Destiny, a psychic on East 75th Street who sees people by
appointment only and would only be interviewed using her
professional name.
</P>
<P>
   Destiny said her kind of work can get expensive. ``People who do
intense spiritual work use very rare and sometimes hard-to-get
items to help a person reach a higher spiritual plane or to unlock
something negative either around them or in them,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   So how can people tell if they are being enlightened or duped?
The repertoire of illegal fortunetellers, police said, is fairly
standard: customers go in for an initial consultation at the
advertised fee of $5 to $25. The fortuneteller immediately assesses
their potential profitability. But it is not ostentatious wealth
that they see as the most promising, police said. Instead, they
look for customers with one expensive item _ like a watch or a
handbag _ indicating that they are casual about money.
</P>
<P>
   The fortuneteller then says she senses evil or a curse and wants
to explore it further, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Some clients are told to pour a potion into their bath water and
to bring it back for analysis, police said. One woman was told to
breathe into a chicken's face, and the chicken died before her eyes
_ a trick arranged by the fortuneteller. ``You can't make up these
stories,'' Groth said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   To exorcise the danger and evil, these fortunetellers prescribe
various remedies _ all at a price. If people are short of cash,
some fortunetellers have asked clients to purchase items for them
on their credit cards, the police say, including expensive watches
(to travel back in time and remove the curse placed three
generations ago) or even couches (to use the leather for effigies).
</P>
<P>
   A 30-year-old woman recently arrived in New York City from
Scotland was one such victim. Interviewed on the condition of
anonymity, she said she lost about $9,000 to a fortuneteller named
Sylvia Johns over a year. The fortuneteller told the woman she had
a tumor in her stomach, told her to rub $7,000 in cash over her
belly at home to draw out the evil and then told her to bring the
money in so the fortuneteller could bury it in a grave.
</P>
<P>
   It was only after the woman saw a report about fortunetelling
crime on television that she went to the police. ``I was so
upset,'' she said. ``I just couldn't believe somebody I thought was
a friend _ I had believed them and trusted them _ turned out to be
a big scam.''
</P>
<P>
   If more fortunetellers have not been apprehended, police said,
it is in part because victims of such crimes are embarrassed to
report them. And when fortunetellers are arrested _ usually on
charges of grand larceny _ they are quick to plead guilty and pay
restitution rather than submit to a drawn-out prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Pamela Miller, the fortuneteller arrested last week, who also
goes by the last name Alvarez, was charged with grand larceny in
the third degree and released pending her next court date Aug. 21.
Her number was unlisted, and she was not home on a recent visit by
a reporter.
</P>
<P>
   Penalties for grand larceny range from a maximum of 4 years for
stealing $1,000 to a maximum of 25 years for stealing more than $1
million. But typically, a fortuneteller convicted of grand larceny
for the first time gets no jail time and has to pay only a small
fine, said an official in the Manhattan district attorney's office.
</P>
<P>
   Mel Sachs, a lawyer for another fortuneteller facing charges,
said it was important to note that people are consulting
fortunetellers and paying them of their own free will. ``People
exercise a choice,'' he said, ``whether or not they want to go to a
psychiatrist, psychologist, astrologist, phrenologist,
graphologist.''
</P>
<P>
   The fortunetellers use pseudonyms and among the most commonly
used family names are Miller, Nicholas, Mitchell and Costello.
</P>
<P>
   They guard their turf in much the same way as do organized crime
families, police said, staking out territories around the city.
Each territory is run by a chief or, as Gypsies call him, a Rom
Baro, meaning ``big man'' in their language, Geis said.
</P>
<P>
   There is a three-block rule, meaning sidewalk storefronts _
known as ``ofisas'' _ have to be spaced out, the detective said. If
an outsider tries to violate this provision, she is ostracized, he
said, ``a fate worse than death'' in Gypsy culture.
</P>
<P>
   They are a closed, tight-knit group with an us-against-them
mentality, said Geis, who has studied Gypsies _ or Roma _
extensively. When two fortunetelling sisters were to appear in
court, about 30 members of their extended family showed up to
support them, police said.
</P>
<P>
   With up to 1 million fortunetellers operating in the United
States, police said, such scams are a nationwide problem and occur
in cities like Chicago, Houston and Los Angeles. Through a network
of law enforcement officials specializing in Gypsy crimes, the
Baltimore-based National Association of Bunko Investigators helps
track down suspects who have left any given state.
</P>
<P>
   To some extent, Geis said, fortunetellers are victims
themselves: women who learned fortunetelling as little girls and
know no other way to earn a living. He said he respects their
tenacity and sympathizes with their struggles as outsiders. But
when it comes to bilking people of their savings in the guise of
offering succor, the detective said, New York is no longer a place
that looks the other way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Word is out that this is not a safe town to do business in,''
he said. ``They know the heat is on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-99 2157EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990629.0409 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3935 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DAYS-BEFORE-THEATER-A     06-29 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAYS-BEFORE-THEATER-ART-3TAKES-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PROCESSION OF ELUSIVE IMAGES FROM THE MERLIN OF SURREAL FORM 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 4)  
 (af)  
 Anne Midgette writes on international art, music and theater.  
 By ANNE MIDGETTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MODENA, Italy _ Flat, empty suits of clothing laid out across
the stage rise and walk as the actress Fiona Shaw reads a graphic
description by the novelist Umberto Eco of decaying corpses that
dwell in the land of the dead.
</P>
<P>
   A rampant red rooster violently tears sections from a long
scroll of paper drawn from the hands of a blue angel hanging over
the stage. A little girl, a doll figure with a Buddha-like china
head, mimes joyful wonder as she gazes at meteorites through a huge
telescope, while a snow owl undulates its feathery sleeves.
</P>
<P>
   The work, in rehearsals and previews here about 60 miles north
of Florence, is called ``The Days Before: Death, Destruction and
Detroit III.'' It was originally conceived as a piece about the
Apocalypse, and its 12 scenes are filled with bizarre imagery and
stylized movement. Each includes an excerpt read by Ms. Shaw from
Eco's novel ``The Island of the Day Before,'' the texts seemingly
unrelated to the onstage action.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Wilson, who conceived, designed and directs it, calls
``The Days Before'' ``a celebration of humanity.'' Originally
commissioned by the Lincoln Center Festival, it will have its world
premiere in New York on Wednesday, the festival opening night, at
the New York State Theater.
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, ``The Days Before'' may seem less celebratory
than opaque. ``Bob's dream world,'' Ms. Shaw calls it. Ines
Somellera, a Mexican actress who plays the owl and other roles,
says, ``Bob's pieces are like underwater, the way people move.''
And Wilson himself is flexible about the definition. ``How would
you describe it?'' he asks people in the course of a rehearsal.
``It's a journey. It's a poem.''
</P>
<P>
   But is it a ``celebration of humanity''? In the United States,
Wilson is better known for the abstraction of ``Einstein on the
Beach,'' the music-theater piece he created with Philip Glass in
1976, or, more recently, for the formalism of his beautiful looking
but ill-received ``Lohengrin'' at the Metropolitan Opera last year.
</P>
<P>
   Since he began staging theater in the 1960s, Wilson has
developed a distinctive theatrical language involving precision,
stylization and a bypassing of intellectual logic in favor of one
that is visual or esthetic. Some people have found his work cold
and unemotional; others dismiss him as a creator of pretty
pictures; but few have discerned the ebullience that a
``celebration of humanity'' would seem to connote.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview here, Wilson said that one reason for his
attention to form and movement _ ``I do the piece silently at
first; we add the words later'' _ is that he does not want to
dictate too much to his actors. ``It has to come from them,'' he
said. ``It can't be mechanical.''
</P>
<P>
   He envisions a human element emerging from the tightly
controlled movements. ``This piece reminds me of my early work,
where people could be themselves in the context of a situation and
didn't have to assume a role,'' he told the young cast of ``The
Days Before'' prior to the last rehearsal. ``The most touching
thing about the piece are the moments when I see who you are as
individuals. Sometimes you're trying to act what's in your head,
and then I don't believe you. But if you feel something, that's
truth, it's your experience.''
</P>
<P>
   The director can appear distant and forbidding in photographs,
but in person, tall, good-looking and soft-spoken, the 57-year-old
Texan resembles a combination of the actors Larry Hagman and Kevin
Costner. Brought up in Waco, he had a distant relationship with his
father, a lawyer, and a mother who has been described as
unemotional and controlling. But the initial impression of distance
that the director himself can sometimes project is belied by the
warm embraces he exchanges with his cast as they prepare to leave
Modena.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson trained as a visual artist, graduating from the Pratt
Institute in 1965. ``If I had studied theater,'' he said, ``I would
never make the work I do.'' These days, his schedule includes
gallery and museum installations and shows of his own drawings,
paintings and furniture designs (chairs are a Wilson leitmotif).
</P>
<P>
   Images are central to his theater work, as well; he tends to
describe his plays with the aid of drawings. ``The best way to know
about my work is through the experience of seeing it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But images are only part of the story. ``The pictures are the
surface,'' Wilson said. ``The audience at tonight's preview wasn't
particularly sophisticated. Many of them don't speak English, and
they're looking at the pictures. It's a universal language. That's
the skin of the piece. And you have meat under that; and you have
bones, the megastructure, like columns.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether it is a work by Euripides or one of his own, Wilson
said, he starts with the architecture. ``It's like an apartment
building,'' he said. ``You may like Baroque in your apartment, and
I may like Zen, but the building as an architectural whole has a
certain cohesiveness. So you create a megastructure for the whole
piece, and within that everyone has a certain freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   A model for this blending of formalism and freedom is the work
of George Balanchine, whom Wilson calls ``the Mozart of the 20th
century.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Who else could line up a row of 17 dancers, and you think
they're absolutely in sync, but in fact, every one of them is doing
something slightly different,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He described watching Balanchine in rehearsal with Allegra Kent.
`` B. said, `Do this''' _ he mimed an elegant gesture. ``And she
did this'' _ he repeated the gesture imperfectly. ``And he just
said, `Mmm.' He didn't correct her. That was his greatness: he left
them their space.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson codifies the structure of each piece in sequences of
numbers and letters that he can summon up years later. ``The
structures aren't even perceptible after you put the piece
together,'' he said. ``The audience doesn't have to know.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The audience, however, might note the correspondences between
different scenes: a dark stage with a light-filled cave in the
lower left-hand corner may be reversed in a later scene with a very
bright stage with a dark area in the upper right. ``The Days
Before'' is set up as two columns of six scenes each: ``Scene 1
relates to 12, Scene 2 to 11, and so on,'' Wilson said, connecting
the columns with a shoelace network of crossing lines.
</P>
<P>
   In other works, like ``Einstein on the Beach,'' the acts are
separated _ or linked _ by intermediate scenes called ``knee
plays.'' ``I call them that because the piece is like a limb, and
that's the joint,'' Wilson said. ``Knee plays'' also figured in the
structure of the mammoth ``The Civil Wars: A Tree Is Best Measured
When It Is Down,'' another collaboration with Glass, which was
supposed to extend over five acts, 12 hours and six countries.
</P>
<P>
   Although a number of its scenes were realized, the complete
epic, which had been planned to accompany the 1984 Olympics, was
canceled when financing fell through. Wilson's reaction to this
setback is reflected in his oeuvre. In work before ``The Civil
Wars,'' he often tested the boundaries of theater, including the
limits of time and geography (``Ka Mountain and Guardenia Terrace''
was staged in 1972 on a mountaintop in Iran and lasted seven days).
</P>
<P>
   Since ``The Civil Wars,'' he has (until now, at least) avoided
the plotless dreamscapes of his youth and tended to keep his work
within more conventional boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, the Schaubuhne in Berlin asked Wilson to stage the
piece that became the first ``Death Destruction and Detroit.''
(``Death Destruction and Detroit II'' had its premiere at the same
theater in 1987; the title seems to have gained a comma in its most
recent incarnation.) It was Wilson's first opportunity to work in a
professional ensemble theater and other invitations followed.
</P>
<P>
   The logical next step was to take on the theater repertory.
Within a few years, he was staging Shakespeare and Brecht, Mozart
and Puccini, rather than, as before, exclusively original pieces.
Most of this work was done in the relatively well-to- do,
state-supported theaters of Europe, where Wilson is widely
venerated. In the United States, his work is generally known more
by reputation than through extensive exposure.
</P>
<P>
   Compounding his busyness since ``The Civil Wars'' has been a
range of other, sometimes commercial, projects: mounting an
installation at the Galeries Lafayette in Paris, or creating an
original theater work in Milan to commemorate the 70th anniversary
of the magazine Domus in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In scope and ambition, these projects are markedly different
from Wilson's earlier work. With ``The Days Before,'' he said, ``I
feel I'm going back to something'' _ not least, perhaps, because
this is the first large-scale original noncommercial theater piece
he has mounted for some time.
</P>
<P>
   Where actors' movements in his earlier pieces had been unusual
or inexplicable, they took on an elegance and refinement _
perceived by some as stilted mannerism _ as the director reacted to
the conventions of Western theater and opera by turning to other
traditional genres like Noh drama.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I approach an opera,'' he said, ``I think, `How can I
hear it?' Usually I can hear it best when I close my eyes. Many
stagings get in the way of the music. I want to create pictures
that will let me hear the opera. It's hard to find the
counterpoint. In `Lohengrin,' I had the chorus moving downstage
very slowly; the music is fast, but I tried to have them walk
against the music. Counterpoint is the most difficult thing to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Days Before,'' Wilson's operatic style tempers the kind
of bizarre, tough imagery evident in the earlier versions of
``Death, Destruction and Detroit,'' creating a gentler, more
polished, fairy-tale whole. Even when the Romanov family is
assassinated onstage by a troupe of baboonlike soldiers, the
violence is graceful rather than provocative.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the director cites the presence of ``rough edges,'' in
part because, while the piece's architecture has been in place
since the first workshop in 1996, the scenes are still being worked
on at the last minute. On the final day of rehearsal, Wilson
rejects a shining skirt, perhaps 20 feet long, that would have
reached to the floor from a figure elevated above the stage;
approves a new head for the angel; shifts blocks of text, and makes
decisions about which of the recorded works by the Japanese
composer Ryuichi Sakamoto to use.
</P>
<P>
   The show's Italian producer, Franco Laera, even had to relocate
the rehearsals here when the German city of Weimar, which was to be
a co-producer, pulled out. (The co-commissioners, with Lincoln
Center Festival, are now MC93 Bobigny, a performing arts festival
in France, and the International Istanbul Theater Festival.) And
the other readers besides Ms. Shaw _ including Isabella Rossellini
and Tony Randall _ will not be coming aboard until New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had an idea about what this piece should be,'' Wilson said,
``and I kept trying to make it be that. But you have to go with
what it is; you can't make it be something else. So the work has
been a process of paring down; I've thrown so much out.'' As a
result, something that started as a vision of the Apocalypse and
developed into a sequence of individual tales has been condensed
into a flow of distinct but elliptical images, and the original
four-plus hours have been reduced to one and a half.
</P>
<P>
   Eco's texts, too, have been distilled until, freed of character
and plot, they form an abstract descant to each scene. ``This text
is difficult because it makes its own pictures,'' Wilson noted.
``It's an interesting text to set because it's not theatrical, it's
not poetic.'' The novel, in fact, is the tale of a shipwrecked
Italian, set in the 17th century.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eco and I are completely different,'' the director said.
``He's an intellectual and I'm not. You ask me, Do I like red wine?
I say, Yes. You ask him, and half an hour later he's still talking.
I don't know what this is, but it's fascinating. His text, his
ideas are very dense, like a rock. I put some space around them.
And the text weights down my ideas, keeps them from flying up.''
</P>
<P>
   The piece is not a collaboration with Eco in the strictest
sense; the texts did not enter the picture until the third workshop
of ``The Days Before'' last year. But, Wilson said, ``It's always a
collaboration, even with Puccini. If it was a William Burroughs
text, it would be a different piece.'' Wilson collaborated with
Burroughs on the 1990 ``Black Rider.''
</P>
<P>
   Working with an author's pre-existing text is different from the
kind of creative planning that marked Wilson's collaboration with
Glass on ``Einstein on the Beach.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Days Before,'' Eco's words and Sakamoto's music seem
more a part of the furnishings than of the structure. The composer
made some suggestions, and came to last year's workshop, but the
final decisions were Wilson's.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   True collaborators in the more conventional sense include the
choreographer Suzushi Hanayagi, a dancer who began her formal
training in Noh and Kabuki at the age of 2{. She has worked with
Wilson on 15 pieces and weighs in on many aspects of the work
during rehearsals.
</P>
<P>
   Another collaborator is the autistic poet Christopher Knowles,
who recites his own texts. After graduating from Pratt, Wilson
worked in various institutions with handicapped children. Later,
deaf and autistic children became collaborators with him on
original theater pieces. Knowles' abstract use of language has been
a major influence on Wilson; his poetry is featured, for example,
in ``Einstein on the Beach.''
</P>
<P>
   Other collaborators are the young actors and production crew.
``Most of them have been involved with this project since the
beginning,'' Wilson said. ``The Days Before'' was almost entirely
developed at Watermill, the arts center that Wilson established on
Eastern Long Island in 1991 as a kind of creative laboratory in
which to develop his own and others' work _ and as an American base
for a director who works so much in Europe. Some people apply to
spend time there; some, like Ms. Somellera, wrote to Wilson about
his work and landed an invitation to Watermill in response.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't walk the same, after working with Bob,'' Ms.
Somellera said. ``At Watermill, he came up to me and said, `Remind
me to teach you how to walk.' I thought, `Excuse me, I've been
doing it all my life.' But afterward, you walk down the street, and
instead of just looking straight ahead, you're also aware of what's
happening on the sides, and of the back of your head.''
</P>
<P>
   For Ms. Somellera, this awareness peaks in Scene 12 of ``The
Days Before'' when she follows Ms. Shaw across the stage. ``I'm in
many scenes, but that scene is it,'' she said proudly. ``That's my
walk.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson is working on three projects between his departure from
Modena in late June and the Lincoln Center premiere in July. With
so many things going on at once, he tends to view individual
projects in light of a greater whole, the Wilson oeuvre. ``De
Kooning once said that you reach a point where it's hard to tell
the difference between your art and your life,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His overextension is sometimes reflected in his work. In some of
the repertory pieces, the stylization can seem formulaic,
``Wilsonized,'' as it were. The imagination and tautness that
informed his beautiful Paris-Zurich production of ``Oedipus Rex''
had faded somewhat from his 1998 reprise of ``Dantons Tod'' in
Salzburg.
</P>
<P>
   He also doesn't always have time to monitor everything. Take
``Monsters of Grace,'' a 3-D film project with Philip Glass, shown
in America and Europe. ``I hated that!'' Wilson said. ``It was one
of the most embarrassing things in my life. They took my drawings
and animated them, but it wasn't me. I would have done it
differently: lighting, drawing. But there wasn't time.''
</P>
<P>
   In Italy, he has the air of Marcello Mastroianni in the movie
``8{'': a weary director, plagued by a constantly ringing phone,
struggles to find peace of mind and takes characters from every
walk of life to create a work that is, ultimately, indeed a
celebration of humanity.
</P>
<P>
   Federico Fellini might be the last director one would associate
with Wilson, but there is something of his all-embracing warmth in
Wilson's approach. It does not get more Felliniesque than the
90-year-old Turkish opera singer Semiha Berksoy, who moves across
the stage in ``The Days Before'' on a velvet sofa, bellowing out
Isolde's ``Liebestod.'' ``People said I shouldn't do it,'' Wilson
confided, ``but she's been practicing, and she wants to do it, so
what the hell.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Days Before,'' there is room for both the random and
the human. The first scene opens with Dadon Dawadolma, a Tibetan
singer, chanting hauntingly in the twilight; Wilson doesn't find
out the meaning of what she is singing until she tells him after
the last preview. In the poignant final scene, under a luminescent
gray sky like dawn, a tiny, ancient man walks slowly, childlike,
around the deck of a ship peopled with frozen passengers, while Ms.
Shaw reads achingly of death.
</P>
<P>
   If images are the best conveyor of the content of a Robert
Wilson work, one reading might be that Wilson is not afraid to try
to make something beautiful. And as the stylized violence of the
work's first half is healed in the corresponding scenes of the
second _ shipwreck is answered with transcendence, an old woman's
death by a child's apotheosis _ it emerges that ``The Days
Before,'' beautiful or kitschy, impenetrable or facile, is
ultimately not only about apocalypse but also redemption.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
