<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-DRAFT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA FINDS LEAN PICKINGS IN THE DRAFT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jerry Krause has been in sleuth mode for a week, trying to
uncover the one clue that will return the Chicago Bulls to
respectability. If he was not administering a three-hour
psychological test to Maryland's junior all-America guard Steve
Francis, the Bulls' general manager was dispatching an assistant
coach to Rhode Island in search of the elusive Lamar Odom.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of good it did him. Owning the No. 1 pick in Wednesday
night's National Basketball Association draft at the MCI Center,
Krause found out what most teams already knew: With no clear-cut,
impact player among the top five, the crapshoot is on.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's literally a bull market,'' Golden State general manager
Garry St. Jean said. ``We're dealing with junk bonds. The trading
is very volatile. These guys go up and down every day, depending on
what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls, who have contemplated trading the pick, are leaning
toward taking Elton Brand, the player of the year from Duke
University, said one Eastern Conference official who requested
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a very good possibility that we will not make any
decision on the draft choice until Wednesday afternoon,'' Krause
said. ``We don't feel there's an advantage to us to making it
sooner.''
</P>
<P>
   If Odom isn't taken No.1, Miami is making a serious push to
acquire him at No.2. Heat president and coach Pat Riley flew the
19-year-old forward down to Miami Tuesday to work out and be
interviewed. The Heat was pitching P.J. Brown, Voshon Lenard and
its first-round pick (No.25 ) to Vancouver for the pick. If the
Grizzlies keep the pick, they appear to be interested in Francis.
The Charlotte Hornets have said they will take Baron Davis, the
UCLA point guard, with the No. 3 pick, even though Davis has said
he would like to go to the Clippers at No. 4.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers may have to make a huge decision: Take the
multitalented freshman Odom or the Miami of Ohio senior
all-American Wally Szcerzbiak who lighted up the NCAA tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto picks fifth but has been one of the most active teams
trying to swing a deal over the last two days. The Raptors were
said to be interested in moving up to No. 2 to acquire Francis.
</P>
<P>
   There was one major trade Tuesday and talk of a blockbuster that
never materialized.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Hawks sent Mookie Blaylock and their 21st pick to
Golden State for Bimbo Coles, Duane Ferrell and the Warriors' No.
10 pick, with which the Hawks could go after another point guard.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto negotiated with Houston about acquiring Hakeem Olajuwon.
They were offering Kevin Willis, Doug Christie and draft picks for
the future Hall of Famer, but the Rockets said no.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be very hard for me to pull the trigger on something
like that,'' said the Rockets' coach and general manager, Rudy
Tomjanovich.
</P>
<P>
   Francis and Brand have emerged as the consensus choices for the
No. 1 pick. Szczerbiak, Odom and Davis are widely considered to
fill out the top 5. Minnesota, Washington, Cleveland and Phoenix
have the sixth through ninth picks. Jonathan Bender, a
6-foot-10-inch, 18-year-old from Picayune, Miss., High School, may
go as high as No. 5 and will probably not last past No. 9. The
Wizards are said to be interested in Connecticut's Richard Hamilton
at No. 7.
</P>
<P>
   And then a trio of talented point guards _ Jason Terry of
Arizona, Andre Miller of Utah and William Avery of Duke _ should go
next. The Knicks, who have the 15th pick, are hoping one of those
players falls out of the top 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty-four hours before the draft, and you don't have
concrete levels where certain players will go,'' St. Jean said.
``It's a strange situation. You may get a guy at No. 5 and the team
with No. 15 might get essentially the same player or a better guy.
It's not like last year where you had Paul Pierce, Vince Carter and
Antawn Jamison all slotted. This top five, you just don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   The last time so much uncertainty clouded the draft was 10 years
ago, when the Sacramento Kings chose Pervis Ellison No. 1 over
Danny Ferry, Sean Elliott, Glen Rice and J.R. Reid. If gauging the
talent pool has been rough on team officials, it has also
confounded the draftees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nerve-racking,'' Francis said Tuesday. ``It's the last
day, and you hear so many rumors and so much that's going on. It's
a mystery to me, just like every other player is really wondering
where they're going.''
</P>
<P>
   Odom may be the most nervous, especially after he skipped the
league-mandated physical, failed to show for scheduled workouts and
flirted with the notion of returning to school before firing his
agent and finally working out for four teams Monday in Providence,
R.I. Heralded as the most talented but troubled player in the
draft, he missed the news media availability session in Washington
Tuesday afternoon before eventually showing up an hour late.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the teams out there, there's nothing to be scared of or
harmful of,'' Odom said in an interview with an NBA public
relations employee Tuesday afternoon. ``I'm not a cancer. I'm a
great kid, a little misunderstood. The reason for me not going to
Chicago was the problems I was having with my representatives and
the people that were around me. I had to just clear the attic out
and take a step back. I just needed to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great kid. I don't understand what's going on,'' said
Szczerbiak, who once played on an Amateur Athletic Union team with
Odom. ``You'd think two days before the draft there would be
something on his whereabouts, what he's doing. He probably has a
lot of people pulling him in all kinds of different directions,
like a rubber band. It's a tough situation, but at the same time,
he's a grown man now, and he's got to make these decisions and show
up for the things he's supposed to show up for.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is no high school, this is no joke here, this is the NBA
draft. It doesn't get any bigger than that. You can't be playing
games with NBA general managers and NBA coaches, especially with
the lucrative career he's about to embark on.''
</P>
<P>
   Chicago (Nos. 1 and 16), Toronto (5 and 12), Cleveland (8 and
11) and Minnesota (6 and 14) have two picks apiece.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets, Dallas, Sacramento, Milwaukee, Philadelphia, Detroit,
Orlando and Portland do not have first-round picks. Twelve players
withdrew their names from the draft last week, leaving 27
underclassmen, high school and foreign players eligible.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
