<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3950 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HONDURAN-IMMIG-NYT     06-29 1132
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONDURAN-IMMIG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELATIVES SAY HONDURAN TEEN EMBELLISHED STORY OF ODYSSEY TO NEW
YORK
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The doe-eyed 13-year-old boy who captivated the city
with his tale of traveling solo from Honduras to New York in search
of his father apparently manufactured much of what he told the
police and people who helped him, according to accounts offered
Tuesday by relatives.
</P>
<P>
   The youngster's story _ that his mother was killed by Hurricane
Mitch and that his only living relative was the father he had never
seen _ is not true, said family members in Honduras and in the
Miami area, where the boy had been living until being reported
missing last week.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives of the boy, Edwin Daniel Sabillon, said his mother was
alive and living in Honduras, as was the grandmother who raised
him. It is the boy's father, Grevis Sabillon, who is dead,
something that relatives said young Edwin never seemed to accept
fully.
</P>
<P>
   ``His problem is that he does not want to accept that his father
died,'' said Jemmy Rodriguez of Hialeah, Fla., who said she is
Edwin's cousin.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rodriquez said in a telephone interview that the boy ran
away from his aunt's Hialeah home, where he had lived for two
months, on June 24. Relatives reported him missing and realized
where he had gone only when they saw his picture on television
Tuesday. The police in Hialeah confirmed Tuesday night that the
family had filed a missing-person report on the boy.
</P>
<P>
   With his poignant saga of longing and gumption, Edwin was
national news on Tuesday. His tale was on the front pages of
newspapers. His adventure was recounted on television. People who
heard and read of him offered, in calls to reporters and to the
city's Administration for Children's Services, to care for him and
give him money.
</P>
<P>
   The taxi driver who had picked Edwin up on Sunday night said he
wanted to adopt the boy. Police officers in the Bronx cared for
him, fed him treats and eagerly conveyed his account of his odyssey
to the news media.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani even figuratively embraced the boy as a
plucky symbol of immigrant virtues. ``He's in a city that
appreciates and values immigration, so he should feel very
comfortable here,'' the mayor said Tuesday, a few hours before the
doubts about Edwin's story began to surface at City Hall. ``All of
us came here from somewhere else at one time or another.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night Giuliani, who was in Chicago for a fund-raiser,
confirmed that the police were investigating parts of Edwin's
account ``that turned out not to be, at least at this point,
corroborated.'' But he praised officers for responding sensitively
from the outset to a boy who apparently needed help.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Edwin's real story, if the accounts of his relatives are
confirmed, may be nearly as poignant _ that of a resourceful but
troubled youngster whose impulsive behavior after his father's
death made him hard for relatives to handle.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rodriguez said Edwin grew up in the care of his paternal
grandmother in the Honduran town of San Buenaventura. His mother,
who now lives in the northern Honduras town of Choloma, gave him up
when he was three months old.
</P>
<P>
   Edwin had told the police, as well as friendly strangers in
Miami and New York City, that his mother had died in a mudslide
after Hurricane Mitch plowed through their home last October.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The grandmother, Paula Vazquez Hernandez, told The Associated
Press in an interview at her home Tuesday that she has no idea why
Edwin would have concocted a story for strangers about being alone
and then run away to New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want him back,'' she said. ``I want him to return to me.
I'll put him in a reform school until he straightens out.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Edwin's relatives said the boy's father had left Honduras eight
years ago and worked in Miami on construction jobs, sending money
home regularly to his mother and his son. As far as they know, he
never lived in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, they said, he discovered he had contracted AIDS and
returned to Honduras, where he died on Oct. 11.
</P>
<P>
   After the death of his father, Edwin went to Hialeah to live
with one of his father's sisters, Aurora Sabillon. Ms. Rodriguez,
who is Mrs. Sabillon's daughter, said the boy was sometimes defiant
and refused to be registered for school, saying he wanted to go to
work and support his grandmother as his father had.
</P>
<P>
   Then, last Thursday, shortly after 1 p.m., his aunt went to the
Hialeah police station and reported him missing. She said she had
last seen him at 10 that morning. She did not indicate why she was
sure so soon that he had run away, said Susan Shaw, a Hialeah
police supervisor.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear what Edwin did that day or the next. But on
Saturday, he showed up at a Miami restaurant, telling patrons that
his mother had died in Honduras and he was on his way to New York
City to meet his father.
</P>
<P>
   Touched by his story, they took up a collection and bought him a
bus ticket.
</P>
<P>
   At the restaurant Tuesday, there was disappointment at the new
revelations, especially since some of the regulars had heard a
rumor that the boy had really found his father after arriving in
the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very disappointed,'' said Emilio Jose Jimenez, who had
chipped in for Edwin's transportation. ``We don't care so much
about the money, but we felt a special sentimental unity with this
child.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Edwin apparently arrived by bus in New York City, alone, on
Sunday afternoon. He later told the police that he wandered around
for about six hours before telling a sympathetic taxi driver that
he had to meet his father at LaGuardia Airport. The police, who
took custody of Edwin after being notified by the taxi driver, said
he had his birth certificate and a change of clothes with him in a
paper bag.
</P>
<P>
   Edwin was placed with a Spanish-speaking foster family.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day on Monday _ and continuing Tuesday _ police
officials said that they had been able to confirm parts of Edwin's
story, contributing to the boy's general aura of credibility.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, detectives said they had talked by phone to a
family in Honduras where, according to the boy's account, he had
lived until leaving on his trek on May 22. They also indicated that
they had seen the letter that Edwin said his father had written him
earlier this year, with the instructions for meeting up at
LaGuardia Airport.
</P>
<P>
   The police also were kept busy following local leads, one
investigator said, after the publicity about the case generated
calls from a number of people who claimed to know the whereabouts
of Edwin's father in New York.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
