<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3952 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-WCUP-NYT &LR;      06-29 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WCUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOBRERO OF U.S. MADE IT IN FITS, STARTS AND TRIPS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., Ind.)  (jt) 
 By JERE LONGMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAIRFAX, Va. _ Kate Sobrero realized that women's soccer had
crossed a new threshold of popularity last week as she sat on the
American team bus following a 7-1 victory over Nigeria in Chicago.
A college friend from Notre Dame, Julie Maund, was tailgating in
the parking lot at Soldier Field, talking to Sobrero by cellular
phone.
</P>
<P>
   Maund held the phone up, and kids began screaming things like,
``You played great,'' and the inevitable, ``Do you know Mia?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Julie said one man offered her money to put his daughter on
the phone with me,'' Sobrero said.
</P>
<P>
   Having sat out Sunday's 3-0 victory over North Korea in the
Women's World Cup with a wrenched ankle, Sobrero is expected to
return to the lineup in central defense Thursday night for a
quarterfinal match against Germany in Landover, Md. She has become
a tough, reliable defender with speed, agility and a ruggedness
forged by learning the game from three older brothers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she will develop into one of the best defenders in the
world,'' said Tony DiCicco, coach of the American team.
</P>
<P>
   This is far more than Sobrero thought she would ever achieve,
given the queasy first impression she made on the national team in
1995. Some players immediately stand out from the crowd, and so did
Sobrero, though not in the way she had hoped. Weakened by flulike
symptoms, lacking fitness, she passed out during a running drill.
Her very first practice, and she folded like a beach chair in the
Florida sun.
</P>
<P>
   Devastated, Sobrero did not accept another tryout offer from the
national team for three years. When DiCicco called, Sobrero turned
him down. Embarrassed, she could not face up to such stars as Mia
Hamm, Michelle Akers, Julie Foudy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It destroyed my confidence for a couple of years,'' said the
22-year-old Sobrero, who is from Bloomfield Hills, Mich. ``These
were people I worshipped, and I passed out in front of them. I
wasn't fit. And I wasn't mature enough emotionally to be on the
national team.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, collegiate soccer restoked her competitive fire. She
helped lead Notre Dame to four consecutive Final Fours and was
named defensive most valuable player of the tournament in 1995,
when the Fighting Irish won the national championship.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Sobrero felt assured enough to play as one of the
allowed overage players on the American under-20 team that won an
important tournament in Denmark. In January 1998, she was invited
back to the national team tryouts, and this time she accepted. But
her second impression was even more painful than her first.
</P>
<P>
   While attempting to score a goal during a scrimmage, Sobrero
collided with goalkeeper Saskia Webber and suffered a broken jaw.
She lost a tooth, and her memory for about half an hour. ``I must
have been thinking I was a forward,'' she said. For six weeks,
Sobrero had her jaw wired shut, which left her with a diet of
milkshakes and mashed potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gained 15 pounds,'' she said. ``I'm the only person in
history to gain weight with their jaw wired shut.''
</P>
<P>
   This was not the first time Sobrero had spent more time in the
emergency room than George Clooney. As a child, she learned soccer
from her three brothers _ ``I was a tomboy, and I was so mad when I
learned I couldn't play football'' _ and what they taught her were
not always the finer points of the game.
</P>
<P>
   As a 14-year-old, Sobrero was kicked by one of her brothers
during a game in the yard. ``I beat him and he got mad and kicked
me,'' she said. Sometime later, it was determined that the kick had
broken a bone in her leg. The doctors realized this while they were
treating her for a fractured ankle suffered in a high school
playoff game.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder her nickname is Sobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the klutz,'' Sobrero said.
</P>
<P>
   Among her teammates, she is unfailingly popular and amusingly
described as goofy or quirky. A dean's list student at Notre Dame,
Sobrero possesses an endearing absent-mindedness. Or, as midfielder
Julie Foudy puts it, ``She's a few feathers short of a duck.''
</P>
<P>
   Most people don't turn the act of getting onto an elevator into
a potential 911 call. But before the North Korea match in Foxboro,
Mass., Sobrero was squeezed between the elevator doors at the team
hotel. Had this collision occurred on the soccer field, the
elevator would have received a red card. Sobrero looked at
teammates and said, ``I think I broke my wrist.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll see her with her shoes untied and say, `Tie your laces
before you trip,''' said her fellow defender Brandi Chastain.
``She'll say, `I feel I'm in balance when my shoes are untied.'''
</P>
<P>
   This eccentricity disappears on the soccer field, replaced by
what soccer people call ``hardness,'' a grittiness in one-on-one
matchups. She ran down a Danish forward and made a sliding tackle
to save a goal in the opener against Denmark. And, even on a bad
ankle, Sobrero backpedaled for 25 yards in one nimble maneuver
against Nigeria, forcing a Nigerian forward to change direction
several times until she ran out of energy and ideas.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has a marking mentality bar none,'' said Lauren Gregg, the
assistant coach of the American team. ``There's a psychological
dimension. She loves a duel.''
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen months after her jaw was broken, Sobrero is hoping to
get a replacement tooth soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm finally on the insurance plan,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean that paramedics can go off red alert.
After practice the other day at Babson College in suburban Boston,
a foul ball from a nearby baseball game strafed the area where
Sobrero and her teammates were speaking to reporters.
Instinctively, she ducked.
</P>
<P>
   ``With my luck,'' she said, ``I'm surprised it didn't hit me.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
