<SLUG> BC-TV-ALBERT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBC REHIRES ALBERT TO CALL NBA GAMES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (s and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GREGG KRUPA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Add an announcer to the list of sports figures who return to
their jobs after a criminal conviction.
</P>
<P>
   NBC rehired Marv Albert Tuesday, less than two years after the
network fired him when he pleaded guilty to assaulting a former
lover. NBC executives acted amid fears that Albert was about to be
hired by a competitor, Fox Television, officials of both networks
confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   Albert's admission of guilt in September 1997 came after court
testimony about cross-dressing and unusual sex. It transformed the
acclaimed announcer into a wanted-poster boy for some women's
groups and an easy target for comedians on late-night television. A
prosecutor agreed to drop sexual assault charges, alleging that he
had forced the woman to perform oral sex, in return for Albert's
plea to a misdemeanor charge of assault and battery _ the announcer
admitted repeatedly biting the woman in the back in a Virginia
hotel room.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very happy day for NBC Sports,'' said Dick Ebersol,
chairman of NBC Sports. ``Marv has been a great friend to all of us
here for a long time, above all to me, in particular. He is my
friend. He is a great talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always stayed in touch, in the last two years,'' Ebersol
told reporters. ``I made it clear to many of you that I always
wanted him, at some point, to return.''
</P>
<P>
   Albert will do play-by-play for some NBA games on NBC, beginning
in the fall, joining the existing broadcast team with a partner yet
to be determined, Ebersol said.
</P>
<P>
   NBC suffered some ratings losses for NBA games this year,
especially during the recently completed playoffs, a decline
largely attributed to a strike-shortened season and Michael
Jordan's retirement. And the network's investment in the television
rights for the NBA is significant, with the number of broadcasts
jumping from 25 this year to 55 next year. The NBA and the Olympics
(which are broadcast only every two years), are NBC's major sports
holdings, having lost NFL broadcasts to network competitors two
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Albert, meanwhile, is considered among the top basketball
announcers of all-time. He called New York Knicks games for 30
years, until he resigned his job with the Madison Square Garden
Network after his guilty plea. Albert earns the near universal
praise from critics for his style, knowledge and preparation, and
he has won the Curt Gowdy Media Award from the Naismith Basketball
Hall of Fame, six CableAce Awards, and 20 times being named New
York State Sportscaster of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   His trademark call of ``Yessss!'' is recognized even by people
who know little about sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just walking back into the building at 30 Rock was a wonderful
feeling,'' Albert said at the news conference Tuesday, referring to
the NBC headquarters in 30 Rockefeller Plaza. ``I think it's hard
for me to make a judgment on the word redemption. I'm just glad to
be back.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he anticipated any negative reaction from fans,
viewers, or the media, Albert said, ``It's better to look ahead
rather than look back and get involved with any issues about how
the media handles things. Everything's gone in the right direction
the last year or so.''
</P>
<P>
   Albert first was rehired by MSG, just 10 months after he
admitted the assault, to do radio broadcasts of Knicks games and a
30-minute sports wrapup show called ``SportsDesk.'' Seven months
later, Turner Sports hired him to call NBA games and other special
events on TNT.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, he garnered almost universal support from
sportswriters in New York and fellow broadcasters, many of whom
said he had paid publicly and privately for his offense. ``Bob
Costas, in particular, has gone out of his way throughout these two
years to encourage us to bring Marv back.'' Ebersol said Tuesday,
referring to NBC's lead play-by-play announcer.
</P>
<P>
   Public relations officials in New York Tuesday credited Albert's
gradual return to national broadcasting as key to the success of
his comeback. ``There was no rushing to this point,'' said one.
</P>
<P>
   Albert will continue with his duties at Turner and MSG,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if, at any point, he was disturbed by NBC's original
decision to fire him, Albert said, ``Dick and most of the people at
NBC have been very, very supportive throughout the whole situation.
I understand what had to be done at that time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
