<SLUG> BC-NCR-POSTAL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NCR lands Postal Service contract
 &HT;    By Laura A. Bischoff
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Dayton-based NCR Corp. won a $67 million contract
to provide hardware and software to the U.S. Postal Service for
customer service counters.
</P>
<P>
   As options are exercised by the Postal Service, the contract
value could hit $176 million, NCR officials said. The contract
extends a $150 million deal that the Postal Service awarded NCR in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   For customers, it means less time in line at the post office.
</P>
<P>
   Paying for mail services and products will become easier with
automated, online check and debit/credit card authorization, NCR
officials said. And, improved inventory management will allow the
Postal Service to keep enough special issue or commemorative stamps
on hand at post offices.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the 10-year deal, NCR will install printers,
point-of-service terminals, bar code scanners, thermal printers,
electronic signature capture devices, scales and database
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   The new retail systems will replace more than 63,000 outdated
retail terminals. As part of the agreement, NCR will install 3,500
machines in this stage of the project.
</P>
<P>
   The Postal Service will install 73,000 such machines from NCR
and IBM Corp. in 20,000 locations during the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   The machines will be linked to NCR's data warehousing software
so the Postal Service can study customer buying habits.
</P>
<P>
   NCR, which employs 33,000 people worldwide, makes automatic
teller machines, computerized cash register systems, data
warehouses, software and bar code scanners.
</P>
<P>
   NCR stock (NYSE:NCR) rose 7/16 on Tuesday to 48 per share.
</P>
<P>
   Laura A. Bischoff writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton,
Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
