<SLUG> BC-SENATE-PATIENT-RIGHTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATIENT RIGHTS BILL DEAL FREES FARM BID 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After days of angry deadlock over a routine farm
bill, Senate leaders finally found a way late Tuesday to push on
with the legislative year.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, the deal had nothing to do with farming.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats agreed to stop blocking the annual agriculture
appropriation legislation in exchange for being allowed to debate a
health-care bill known as the ``Patients Bill of Rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Senator Edward M. Kennedy led the Democrats' crusade, using
complex procedural moves to hold the farming bill hostage until he
got his health bill on the calendar. He spent nearly 20 hours in
the Senate chamber over the past week, thundering about the need
for change in the health-care system, demanding limitations on the
power of health maintenance organizations. Throughout, Kennedy
insisted his only motivation was securing patients' rights.
</P>
<P>
   But in the current political climate, with each side struggling
to seize center stage in the 2000 elections, members of both
parties said the bitter wrangling was about far more than health
care, or any single bill.
</P>
<P>
   Senate minority leader Thomas A. Daschle of South Dakota said he
was thrilled the standoff was over because it meant a ``great
victory for the 160 million Americans who are today demanding that
Congress fix the problem in managed care.''
</P>
<P>
   Privately, however, several Democrats admitted they were happy
the lengthy deadlock played out the way it did. Not only did
Republicans appear paralyzed for a week, but they also will be
forced to vote on health care, a popular issue among voters and a
point of vulnerability for the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the delay in the appropriations process might
force Congress to resort to a last-minute overall spending bill
this fall, a process that could cede more power to the president,
and therefore Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, it's an orchestrated strategy,'' said Jim Jordan,
political director of the Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee.
The main purpose, he said, was to bring up the health-care bill.
But, he said, ``like most good public policy, it's also good
politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Moore, director of fiscal policy studies at the Cato
Institute, a conservative think tank, agreed, saying it was ``very
clearly in the Democrats' interest to try to throw sand in the
machinery of Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of Democrats have been very forthright about it. They
don't want the Republicans to have legislative victories to
campaign on in 2000,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   By working out Tuesday's agreement to dislodge the agriculture
appropriations bill, Republican leader Trent Lott of Mississippi
put an end to the chief accusation lodged by Democrats: that
Republicans were a ``do nothing'' party.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders, meanwhile, scrambled during the last week to
show that Democrats were slowing down Senate business. The
difficulty they had drawing attention to the agriculture bill
prompted Lott and several others to use tractors at a news
conference on the Senate lawn, a reminder that the issue was
farming, not health care.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the issue was, in fact, health care. The deal was
struck late Tuesday afternoon when Republicans agreed to bring the
Patients Bill of Rights to the floor for four days of debate
beginning July 12. The Democrats' proposal would give patients a
host of benefits, including the right to sue their HMOs, and would
give doctors, not an HMO, the power to determine when a patient has
a medical need.
</P>
</TEXT>
