</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-HMO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Legislation sent to governor despite charges of influence
 &HT;    By Mike Wagner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS _ Legislation designed to offer patients more leverage
with their health insurers is on its way to Gov. Bob Taft amid
charges from Democrats that he broke a campaign promise on the
issue and other Republicans caved into the ``deep pockets'' of
insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   The Ohio House of Representatives on Tuesday voted 83-14 in
favor of the minor changes the Senate made on a controversial new
patient protection plan. The bill would allow patients to request
an independent, external review when treatment or medicine
prescribed by a doctor is denied by their health maintenance
organization.
</P>
<P>
   But it does not offer patients the right to sue their insurers.
</P>
<P>
   The liability provision, proposed by Taft during his
gubernatorial campaign last year, was cut out of the bill in the
Ohio House after insurance companies and big business complained it
would increase the cost of health benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Taft has said his support for the liability issue never wavered,
but he was fighting an uphill battle because House Speaker Jo Ann
Davidson, R-Reynoldsburg and Senate President Richard Finan,
R-Cincinnati, were against it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it became dead some time ago. It was obvious neither
the House or Senate would go along with that,'' Taft said.
</P>
<P>
   The governor added that the ``chances are very good'' he will
sign the bill. ``I think the independent right of appeal is a very
significant improvement in the rights of patients in Ohio.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, some Democrats were critical of Taft and other
Republicans for not fighting harder for a patient's right to sue.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill is a breech of the promise the governor and other
legislators made to protect people from their HMO's,'' said Betty
Sutton, D-Barberton.
</P>
<P>
   Under the external review process, appeals from patients would
be decided within seven days for life-threatening cases and within
30 days for other disputes.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation would also require health insurers to make
information available to enrollees through a toll-free hot line;
allow women to go to a gynecologist without referral from a
primary-care physician; and provide $80 million in tax deductions
for certain medical expenses.
</P>
<P>
   House Democrats and a few Republicans tried to reinsert the
liability provision, but couldn't collect enough votes. One
supporter of liability, state Rep. Jeff Jacobson, R-Phillipsburg,
accused the insurance companies of swaying votes on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not dealt with the issue of unequal power of the
insurance companies and the people who are in need of the
treatments,'' Jacobson said. ``I will vote yes, but with some
sadness.''
</P>
<P>
   Some lawmakers were concerned about the amount of campaign money
insurance companies made to some House members who opposed the
liability clause and Democrats said it would be easy to see why the
general public might believe politicians sold out to the insurance
companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly has the appearance that we were bought,'' said
Sen. Robert Hagan, D-Youngstown on Monday. ``We are all
politicians, and they don't trust us because we don't keep our
promises.''
</P>
<P>
   Some lawmakers said they were against the right to sue because
patients typically gain little by spending years fighting claims in
court against insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   But some officials say the external review process is not going
to be all that beneficial for customers. ``The insurance companies
have influenced this legislation from the beginning and use their
power the same way in what's supposed to be a fair external
review,'' said Diane Lardie, director of the Universal Health Care
Action Network in Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Wagner writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
