<SLUG> BC-REYNOLDS-EBUSINESS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    R&AMP;R gets into e-biz
 &HT;    By Laura A. Bischoff
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Reynolds and Reynolds formed an e-business group
that will focus on Internet-based business and may eventually
employ as many as 1,000 people, Reynolds officials said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, 200 to 300 people, including some new hires, will be
assigned to the new group, said Lloyd ``Buzz'' Waterhouse,
Reynolds' new president and chief operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we'll be cooking in three months _ that's a Web
year,'' said Waterhouse, a 26-year IBM Corp. veteran who recently
headed Big Blue's $2.7 billion e-business services unit.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds aims to expand its existing Internet-based projects,
including CarPoint, a car-buying site run in conjunction with
Microsoft Corp., and Customer Advantage, a way for Reynolds clients
to order forms and check accounts via the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   New Internet-based ventures will be announced soon, Waterhouse
said. These ventures will be based in Reynolds' current areas of
expertise: document management and documents for the automotive and
general business markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Speed wins in e-business. We're establishing an
Internet-focused organization that will move quickly and
aggressively to leverage the Internet to provide value to our
customers,'' said Waterhouse, who joined Reynolds May 1 and is
expected to succeed Chairman and Chief Executive David Holmes
within five years.
</P>
<P>
   The e-business group will be headed by Greg Collins, formerly
vice president for corporate strategy and development. The group
will tackle automotive retailing and document management projects
first. Reynolds' Chief Information Officer Frank Caccamo will
establish an e-business center to support the internal and external
Internet based business.
</P>
<P>
   Waterhouse said the cost of the new group is unknown and he
declined to predict how much more the effort will bring in sales.
However, he noted that Reynolds' existing Internet-based
initiatives are growing more than 100 percent annually, which is
not atypical in e-business.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds reported revenues of about $1.5 billion for the 12
months ended March 31, 1999. Reynolds stock price (NYSE:REY) closed
Tuesday at 23 1/4, up 1/8.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Bishoff writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
