<HEADLINE>
BOY'S ODYSSEY IS FOUND TO BE FICTION-BASED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was a story that sounded too good to be true.
</P>
<P>
   Edwin Daniel Sabillon, a 13-year-old boy from Honduras, travels
3,200 miles to New York City to meet his long-lost father _
walking, hitchhiking, and riding buses, relying on charm, gumption,
and the kindness of strangers. But when he finally arrives, after a
37-day odyssey, his father is nowhere to be found.
</P>
<P>
   The story of his journey made a splash on the front pages of The
New York Times and the Daily News, obsessed the Spanish-language
press and radio stations, won the sympathy of the mayor, and
sparked an intensive hunt for the father by the New York Police
Department.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday night, the boy's story was unmasked as a lie.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently he did travel here from Honduras, a remarkable fact
in itself. But the tale that the boy told everyone along the way _
the story that broke hearts and opened wallets _ was an invention,
part of an elaborate scheme to become a New Yorker, a secure
American citizen, the easy way.
</P>
<P>
   He told people that his mother and brother had died in the
mudslides of Hurricane Mitch. His father, Grevi Sabillon, wired him
$200 and instructions to come to New York, saying he would meet him
by the bridge at the entrance to LaGuardia Airport. He would be
waiting there all day on June 25, 26, and 27.
</P>
<P>
   So, on May 22, Edwin's story went on, he left Honduras, walking
and hitchhiking up through Guatemala and along the Gulf Coast of
Mexico. He befriended smugglers who got him across the Rio Grande
into Texas, then took a bus through New Orleans to Miami. There, he
told his tale to the patrons of a Cuban-American-owned cafeteria,
who were so touched by his plight that they raised enough cash on
the spot to put him on a bus to New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday, having arrived, he hiked up to the Bronx and
stopped a taxicab driver, who took him to the airport. When no
father showed up by the bridge, the driver brought him home,
cleaned him up, and took him to the 43d Precinct, where he charmed
every cop in the stationhouse.
</P>
<P>
   He was put in a Spanish-speaking foster home, and the police
launched a major investigation. But then the evidence started
tumbling in that Edwin's story did not add up.
</P>
<P>
   A relative of Edwin's named Gilma Sabillon, who lives in
Newburg, N.Y., told El Diario, New York City's leading
Spanish-language newspaper, that Edwin's father had died of AIDS in
Honduras on Oct. 11 _ and that Edwin knew this. The father had
lived in New York for a while, but went home when he got sick.
</P>
<P>
   The relative told El Diario, for a story to be published in
Wednesday's edition, that Edwin had long dreamed of living in New
York, and in fact left Honduras shortly after his father died,
before Hurricane Mitch. He returned after hearing about the
devastating storm, but could not find his mother. So he made his
way back up, this time crossing the Rio Grande into the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Gilma Sabillon could not be reached Tuesday night; an operator's
recorded message said the telephone had been temporarily
disconnected.
</P>
<P>
   In another twist, the Associated Press reported from Honduras
Tuesday night that Edwin's mother is still alive. Edwin's
grandmother, Paula Vazquez Hernandez, told the AP that she wants
him to come home so she can send him to reform school.
</P>
<P>
   One mystery in Edwin's story was why he turned south from New
Orleans toward Miami. News reports treated it as a result of
confusion. However, according to El Diario, Edwin has aunts who
live near Miami, with whom he stayed for a while _ and who helped
him _ before he went to the cafeteria and conned a bus ticket to
New York.
</P>
<P>
   Officials here were reeling Tuesday night from the revelations
of Edwin's deception, one of the grander scams in recent years.
Police spokeswoman Marilyn Mode said officers were questioning
Edwin Tuesday night, but declined to comment further until all the
facts were known.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, before the boy's story unraveled, Mayor
Rudolph W. Giuliani held a news conference, calling on Edwin's
father to come forth and, if he was an illegal resident, not to be
fearful of the Immigration and Naturalization Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since your son is here and he wants you, who cares about legal
status?'' Giuliani said with passion, adding that the city would
help ``work through any legal entanglements that might exist.''
</P>
<P>
   Jose Basora, the cabdriver who picked Edwin up on Sunday and
brought him home, had told reporters earlier in the day that he
would like to adopt Edwin if his father could not be found.
</P>
<P>
   The police put a on full-court press to find the father the past
two days. Every precinct in the city was told to check around for
someone of his name. Bronx detectives checked the books of several
money-transfer firms, looking for a record of the $200 money order
that he supposedly sent Edwin, hoping it would link a name to an
address.
</P>
<P>
   Miguel Ramirez, head of Centro Hispano Cuzcatlan, a private
immigrant-aid service in Queens, phoned hundreds of contacts to see
if anyone knew someone named Grevi Sabillon, but, he said Tuesday
morning, ``Nobody's ever heard of this guy.''
</P>
<P>
   El Diario, which is read by over 80,000 Spanish-speakers in New
York City, printed Edwin's photo on its front page and put six
reporters on the case.
</P>
<P>
   Jacqueline Donado, an assignment editor for El Diario, said
early Tuesday that she was surprised nobody had yet come forth with
information about the father. Earlier this month, when an
unidentified man died in a subway car, El Diario put his picture on
the front page and, Donado said, a relative called to name him just
hours after the paper hit the newsstands.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 200,000 Central American immigrants live in New York
City, not counting illegal immigrants, who would probably double
the number. So, until late Tuesday afternoon, nobody had any reason
to think it strange that Edwin Sabillon's father still could not be
found.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
