<HEADLINE>
NASSAU COUNTY'S BOND RATING IS DOWNGRADED AMID FISCAL CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVID M. HALBFINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GARDEN CITY, N.Y. _ Nassau County's financial problems took a
significant turn for the worse Tuesday when Standard &AMP; Poor's
downgraded the county's bonds by two notches, to the lowest
investment-grade category, and delivered a scathing critique of the
county's fiscal management.
</P>
<P>
   The new rating of BBB, two notches above that given to junk
bonds, could make it much more expensive for Nassau to raise money
through bond sales, and gives it one of the worst credit ratings
among wealthy suburban counties nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Only Orange County, Calif., which declared bankruptcy in 1994
after making disastrous investments in risky securities, has a
lower rating among such counties, officials at the rating agency
said. In New York, only Erie County has a rating as low as BBB, but
Erie's battered industrial economy stands in sharp contrast with
Nassau's high per capita wealth and low unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   In lowering the rating on Nassau's $2.6 billion in bonds to BBB
from A-minus, S&AMP;P officials also dismissed the county's protracted
effort to eliminate its budget deficit, which now stands at more
than $200 million, as too little, too late, and too full of holes.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement is a blow to Nassau's Republican machine, which
has maintained its grip on power in recent years largely by
avoiding property tax increases even as it doled out increasingly
generous wage increases to the county's civil servants, police and
patronage workers. The political cost of that fiscal imbalance
could be paid as early as this fall, when all 19 county legislative
seats, of which Republicans hold 14, are up for election.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, and imprudently, said S&AMP;P, county officials have
relied on one-time-only revenue measures like the sale of assets,
including the county medical center, which is now being spun off to
a quasi-public corporation.
</P>
<P>
   One of the many problems caused by those one-shot sales,
Standard &AMP; Poor's said, is that many of them take years longer to
complete than expected by county officials. The revenues from the
hospital sale, for example, were first placed in the budget two
fiscal years ago.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the agency said, the county has had to increase its
short-term borrowing substantially to cover current expenses like
salaries and wages.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the county expects to incur $430 million in that
costly short-term debt, or about 20 percent of its $2.2 billion
budget, said S&AMP;P analyst Diane Brosen. Since 1994, she said,
Nassau's short-term debt has jumped 70 percent, even though the
total amount of the budget is largely unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most damaging news in Standard &AMP; Poor's review of
Nassau's predicament was its opinion that a deficit-closing plan
the county is promoting in Albany will not be enough to do the job.
</P>
<P>
   Desperate to avoid raising property taxes, County Executive
Thomas Gulotta, has sought legislative approval for a new 1 percent
tax on real estate sales, which would produce an estimated $50
million to $70 million a year in revenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if the county were to realize the major components of its
fiscal recovery plan,'' said S&AMP;P, ``it is unlikely that the plan
would fully correct the current year's fiscal imbalance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
