<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-REPUBS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP, RAISING THE STAKES, SAYS SURPLUS SHOULD GO TO TAX CUTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Confronted with federal budget surpluses of a size
that would have defied imagination not long ago, Republicans raised
the stakes Tuesday in their standoff with President Clinton, saying
they would increase their proposed tax cut to $1 trillion or more.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders said any windfall not generated by the Social
Security system should go straight to tax cuts and not to
additional spending, a stance that amounted to a rejection of
President Clinton's call on Monday for the money to be divided
among a variety of needs.
</P>
<P>
   By the calculations released by the White House on Monday, the
budget surplus, excluding excess Social Security payroll taxes,
will amount to slightly more than $1 trillion over the next decade,
$333 billion higher than projected just a few months ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Congressional Budget Office is scheduled to release its own
updated surplus estimates on Thursday. Republicans said that if, as
expected, they show a windfall as big as or bigger than the
administration's figures show, all of the new money should go to
augment the $778 billion tax-cutting proposal they will seek to
pass next month.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, chairman of the House Ways and Means
Committee, said that meant a tax-cut bill that could well be $1
trillion or bigger, allowing his party to include many of its
long-cherished goals. They include cutting taxes for married
couples, reducing the capital gains tax, eliminating the tax on
estates, providing breaks to the self-employed and creating new
incentives for savings and investment.
</P>
<P>
   Archer's approach was backed by Senate Majority Leader Trent
Lott of Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we should say, `Oh, goodie! We have more money'
'' Lott told reporters on Capitol Hill. Rather, he said, the extra
money ``makes it a lot easier and more justifiable'' for Congress
to pass a tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   The White House has made clear that Clinton will veto any
sweeping Republican tax bill, and will consider some form of tax
cut only after Congress and the administration agree on plans to
shore up Social Security and Medicare, both of which will face
insolvency in coming decades as the baby boom generation retires.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton had signaled on Monday that he is open to a
compromise on tax cuts. Democrats in Congress said Tuesday that by
replying to Clinton with a demand for an even bigger tax cut,
Republicans were going to force both parties onto a confrontational
footing that would make a deal more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   At this point neither the White House nor the Republican
leadership has a strategy that would lead them to negotiations over
the tangle of high-profile issues linked to the budget outlook,
from the long-term health of the retirement-security systems to the
more immediate difficulty in passing spending bills for next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little early to predict the next steps,'' said Jacob J.
Lew, the White House budget director. ``We've taken a very big
step. We put some ambitious ideas forward. Now we have to see what
the reaction is.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats in Congress said the most likely scenario is for both
the House and the Senate to take up the Republican tax cut bill
next month, pass it and send it to Clinton, who would promptly veto
it.
</P>
<P>
   The action would then be concentrated on an endgame negotiation
in September or October in which both parties would have to make a
choice whether to compromise or fight it out in the 2000 elections.
</P>
<P>
   For all the tough talk, some senior Republicans, including Sen.
William V. Roth Jr. of Delaware, chairman of the Senate Finance
Committee, have been publicly conciliatory toward the White House
and upbeat about the prospects for cooperation. And Lew suggested
that while the White House is not ready to start dealing yet, it
sees the surplus as large enough to accommodate the needs of both
parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the goal is to have a balanced package, we've shown in the
framework we put out that it's possible to have a balanced
package,'' he said. ``We can take care of Social Security and
Medicare solvency, and fund a tax cut in a balanced package.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton so far is sticking to his demand that the main tax cut
be his plan for tax breaks intended to help low- and
moderate-income families save more money for retirement. The plan
would result in a tax cut of $250 billion over 10 years, or roughly
a quarter of what Republicans now want for their much more broadly
based tax cut plan.
</P>
<P>
   Lew said the debate now was over the size and content of a tax
cut, not over whether there should be one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
