<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CAMP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3 SLEEPERS COULD BE EYE-OPENERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also BKN-DRAFT) 
(mk) 
 By STEVE POPPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Andy Panko slipped into Chicago early this month for the
National Basketball Association's predraft camp with little notice.
In Chicago, they were dreaming about the top pick in the draft, so
fans did not camp out outside the Moody Bible Institute for a peek
at a 6-foot-9-inch shooting guard who would not be the first pick.
The Bulls have the top pick in Wednesday's draft. But Panko is good
enough to have drawn scouts to Division III Lebanon Valley College,
an 1,100-student campus in Annville, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of scouts came in this year and that was exciting for
the town,'' Panko said. ``It's just one stop light there and
everybody knows everybody. When a scout comes to town, everybody
knows.''
</P>
<P>
   Panko was only one of many aspiring pros who were part of three
predraft showcases for NBA prospects. In Chicago, the last of the
three camps, 62 players went through four days of bruising
sessions, each trying to catch an eye, to change a mind and fulfill
a dream of claiming a spot in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the top players, the sure lottery picks, did not play in
those games or subject themselves to the drills, opting simply to
take a physical for the team doctors. Some well-known talents,
those on the verge of the lottery like Kenny Thomas of New Mexico
or Lee Nailon of Texas Christian University, were in Chicago,
hoping to solidify their status. But others, like Panko or Duke's
Taymon Domzalski, were in Chicago on a mission: to attract
attention. And still some others, like Leon Smith, a Chicago high
school senior whose skills are unfamiliar to the NBA scouts, stayed
away. They are a few of the draft's long shots; here are their
stories.
</P>
<P>
   ANDY PANKO, 6-9, GUARD
</P>
<P>
   Panko grew nine inches between his senior year in high school
and his senior year at Lebanon Valley. In becoming the Division III
player of the year for the second straight season, he averaged 26
points a game and made 55.2 percent of his shots. Now, with the
height of a forward and the skills of a guard, as well as a
shooting touch that has been compared with Duke's Trajan Langdon,
Panko is expected to be the first player from his college to be
drafted by the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Panko tries not to think about the pressure, and that he is
being mentioned in the same breath as players he was watching on
television recently.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't get nervous,'' Panko said in Chicago. ``I just look at
this as an opportunity. If I do well, everything will fall into
place. I see Langdon on TV. I see him at Duke, but I don't look at
it like that now. You've just got to concentrate on putting the
ball in the hole. I look at him and think, `I'm 6-8, 6-9, and I can
do the same things as him. I think I'm more versatile.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Wally Szczerbiak is the best shooter in college basketball,
but Panko can shoot it and he can pass the ball,'' Marty Blake, the
NBA's director of scouting services, said.
</P>
<P>
   Panko knows the odds, noting, ``There are only a few Division
III players that make it to the NBA, maybe one every 10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, no Division III player has been drafted since 1991 when
the Golden State Warriors chose Lamont Strothers, but a few _ Terry
Porter and Greg Grant _have found a place in the league. And Devean
George, a 6-8 forward from Augsburg College in Minnesota, hopes to
join Panko as a draft pick from Division III on Wednesday. George
averaged 27.5 points and 11.3 rebounds this season.
</P>
<P>
   Panko remains the most tantalizing, to the folks in Annville
anyway. ``Because of his size, he came out of the blue even here,''
said Lou Sorrentino, the Lebanon Valley athletic director. ``Nobody
anticipated anything great, but he broke every record we had here.
By this season, the word was out.''
</P>
<P>
   TAYMON DOMZALSKI, 6-10, FORWARD
</P>
<P>
   A power forward, Domzalski started 18 games as a freshman for
Duke, finishing out the 1995-96 season with a 14-point,
seven-rebound performance against Maryland in the Atlantic Coast
Conference Tournament. But after that his finest moments came on
the practice floor, banging against Elton Brand, Shane Battier and
Chris Burgess, the blue chips of the Blue Devils' recruiting class.
Domzalski, a former McDonald's all-American, found himself coming
off the bench only 10 minutes a game. With Duke sending Brand,
Battier, William Avery, Corey Maggette and Langdon, Domzalski is
again coming off the Blue Devil bench in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting a shot now,'' Domzalski said at the camp in
Chicago. ``I could have gone to a number of schools and started,
but that wasn't my sole motivation. Day in, day out, playing
against Elton, Shane and Chris, guys that are lottery picks, I feel
my game has gotten better. I believe my work on the court will
shine through. That's the great thing about the process here. It
gives you an opportunity to show your stuff no matter where you
come from.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like in the NBA, at Duke you have to accept a role. I wasn't a
superstar, but in the NBA there are few of those. Most have to
accept a role. That's not a bad word. A role player makes stars
better. I accepted that in college. I felt like when I played, I
played well. I graduated cum laude.''
</P>
<P>
   Domzalski added: ``I can rebound and play defense. That's there
every day. I'm not coming in to be a superstar. My whole thing is
to make everybody around me better.''
</P>
<P>
   He has impressed Blake. ``He's very active and can do a lot of
things. He's different than someone like Elton Brand. He's more
versatile. I like him.''
</P>
<P>
   LEON SMITH, 6-11, CENTER
</P>
<P>
   A hardship case, Smith is also a question mark because he opted
to avoid the NBA's predraft camps. While finishing up at King High
School, he lived at a South Side group home and was a ward of the
state until he turned 18 on Nov. 2. Then, after averaging 25.5
points and 14.5 rebounds in his senior season, he backed out of a
verbal commitment to attend Fresno State on a basketball
scholarship to enter the draft, hoping to change a hard life as
quickly as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Jonathan Bender, another high schooler in the draft,
Smith is not ranked among the lottery picks. An athletic big man
with almost untapped physical talent, some scouts predict the
second round for him, but others believe that some team will take a
chance on his raw potential and he could go in the first round.
Still others think he is still a boy in a man's body and is not
ready for the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Smith has maintained that he will play professionally, whether
it is in the NBA or overseas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-99 2218EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
