r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-ROBLEDO-COLUMN-LA     06-29 0689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-ROBLEDO-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. WILL AVOID UPSET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now that the United States is headed for the quarterfinals of
the 1999 Women's World Cup, what are Germany's chances of upsetting
the Americans in Thursday's elimination match in Washington, D.C.?
</P>
<P>
   Pretty good, if history means anything.
</P>
<P>
   But if you're confident of a U.S. victory and you like to look
ahead, you have to like Team USA's chances of reaching the July 10
final at the Rose Bowl. If Mia Hamm and her teammates can survive
the kind of vicious tackles that Nigeria and North Korea doled out
in Group A qualifying, they might survive anything.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how one observer sees the tournament playing out for the
Americans:
</P>
<P>
   Let's start with Germany. The reigning European champions
reached the final of the 1995 Women's World Cup before losing to
Norway, 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   And although they haven't played a solid game yet (except
against Mexico), the Germans have beaten the U.S. as recently as
1997. The 3-1 victory in a driving rain at Duisburg snapped the
Americans' 30-game winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. avenged that defeat days later during a German tour,
handing Germany a 3-0 loss in Salzgitter, with Hamm scoring two
goals.
</P>
<P>
   But back on home soil last summer, the U.S. had another hard
time with the Germans, rallying from a goal down to find the
equalizer in the 76th minute to draw, 1-1, in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Worried? Relax.
</P>
<P>
   There won't be an upset here, not with German midfield captain
Martina Voss out of the tournament with a torn muscle, and not with
the U.S. firing on all cylinders.
</P>
<P>
   Going out on a limb, let's call it U.S. 2, Germany 0.
</P>
<P>
   In the rest of the quarterfinals, the picks are Brazil over
Nigeria, Norway over Sweden and China over Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterfinal victories by the U.S. and Brazil would set up one
of the most exciting games of the tournament Sunday at Stanford
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Sissi, truly the MVP of the tournament so far with six goals for
Brazil, would provide the U.S. with its toughest test thus far.
</P>
<P>
   And to add to the intrigue, one might remember another Fourth of
July game at Stanford Stadium five years ago against another
Brazilian team.
</P>
<P>
   On that day, the Brazilian men defeated the U.S., 1-0, in the
second round of the 1994 World Cup -- eventually winning the title
two weeks later in Pasadena.
</P>
<P>
   There is no way our women's team is going to go down on our
nation's holiday.
</P>
<P>
   Nervous energy will allow Brazil to score the game's first goal,
but the U.S. is going to prevail, 4-1.
</P>
<P>
   In the other semifinal, Norway will win an injury-plagued match
with China, 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   That sets up the game most fans want to see in Pasadena: Norway,
the defending Women's World Cup champion, against the U.S., the
1996 Olympic gold medalist.
</P>
<P>
   Asked in February about a possible U.S.-Norway match, Norwegian
captain Lina Medalen spoke of the U.S-Norway rivalry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't like them,'' she said. ``It has nothing to do with
their personalities or how they are, but we both want the same
thing. And any team that gets in our way, we just say, `Okay, lets
kick their (butts).'''
</P>
<P>
   It won't happen. Not on this day. The crowd and emotion will
favor the U.S., just as it did at the Olympics in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The final: U.S. 3, Norway 1.
</P>
<P>
   -- After last week's 2-1 victory over D.C. United, Galaxy coach
Sigi Schmid was reminded that United played without its best
players -- Marco Etcheverry, Jaime Moreno and Eddie Pope -- for
various reasons.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't bother Schmid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, when they have those three guys, they're an easier
team to play because everybody has a more defined role,'' said
Schmid, whose team notched its fourth consecutive victory over
Tampa Bay on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way they were playing, everyone was young and excited and
moving all over the place, and sometimes it's harder to play a team
like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Etcheverry's there, you know he's going to be the
attacking midfielder. It makes them a little less predictable when
their big three are not there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
