</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-KAREKIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KAREKIN I, ARMENIAN PATRIARCH, DIES AT 66
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Catholicos Karekin I, the spiritual leader of Armenian Orthodox
Christians worldwide, who faced the enormous task of reinvigorating
his ancient church after the fall of Soviet Communism, died Tuesday
at his pontifical residence in Echmiadzin, near the Armenian
capital, Yerevan. He was 66.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of death was throat cancer, for which he received
treatment in the last year in New York, said a spokesman for the
Diocese of the Armenian Church of America.
</P>
<P>
   An Oxford-trained theologian fluent in English, French and other
languages, he held the title Supreme Patriarch and Catholicos of
All Armenians, with a flock of more than six million.
</P>
<P>
   Head of one of the world's oldest churches, he was a leading
exponent of ecumenism among Christians and was well known among
church leaders in Europe, the Middle East and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In March, returning to Armenia from New York, he stopped at the
Vatican, where he and Pope John Paul II made plans for the pope to
visit Armenia in July. As Karekin's health deteriorated during the
spring, the pope tried to schedule a private visit this month but
called it off because of his own health problems.
</P>
<P>
   Karekin became head of the Armenian Apostolic Church in April
1995; he was the first such leader elected in centuries within an
independent Armenia.
</P>
<P>
   The nation, with a population of about 3.5 million, had emerged
only four years earlier after seven decades of rule by the Soviet
Union. Even before the Soviet domination of the present republic,
Armenia was often divided up and ruled by countries including
Russia, Turkey and Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Karekin was the 131st in a line of church leaders stretching
back to St. Gregory the Illuminator, who converted King Tiridates
III of Armenia in 301. Christianity became Armenia's official
religion a decade before the conversion of the Roman Emperor
Constantine.
</P>
<P>
   Along with churches in Egypt, Syria, Ethiopia and India, the
Armenian Church belongs to the branch of Orthodox Christianity that
did not accept the definition of Christ's nature as human and
divine promulgated by the Council of Chalcedon in 451.
</P>
<P>
   He visited the United States in May 1998 of last year to help
celebrate the 100th anniversary of the Armenian Diocese.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview then, he said he faced three major challenges in
revitalizing the Armenian church: overcoming the negative
influences of Soviet-sponsored atheism, persuading Armenians that
Christianity is a way of life and not simply an ideology, and
persuading them that faith offers spiritual and moral sustenance.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Joan Brown Campbell, general-secretary of the National
Council of Churches, who met several times with the catholicos,
recalled him as unaffected and considerate. During a visit to
Echmiadzin, she went to early morning prayers and saw him beckon
her to stand beside him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know you don't know the language _ I'll translate for you,''
Ms. Campbell recalled him saying.
</P>
<P>
   ``That just amazed me,'' she said. ``He never saw himself as too
lofty to be a teacher when you needed help.''
</P>
<P>
   Karekin was born Neshan Sarkissian in Kessab, Syria, on Aug. 27,
1932. After graduating from a seminary in 1952, he was ordained a
celibate priest and took the name Karekin in honor of an earlier
church leader.
</P>
<P>
   He studied at Oxford from 1957 to 1959, served as a seminary
dean and then became an aide to Catholicos Khoren I, head of the
Catholicate of Cilicia, a self-governing see within the Armenian
church. He was also sent as an observer to the Second Vatican
Council.
</P>
<P>
   He became a bishop in 1964 and an archbishop in 1973 and later
was elected Catholicos Coadjutor of Cilicia, to succeed Khoren I.
After Catholicos Khoren died in 1983, Karekin made visits to the
Vatican, the Church of England, European Protestant churches and
the Coptic Church of Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   As head of the separate Cilician see, he was seen as a long shot
to succeed the Armenian Apostolic Church's long-reigning head,
Vasken I, who died in 1994. But after favorable statements were
made by Armenia's president, opinion began to shift toward him and
he was elected in a gathering of 400 church delegates.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
