<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 22:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3976 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      06-29 1242
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINNESOTA: EX-WRESTLER GOES TO THE MAT FOR REFORM  
 ARKANSAS: SENATOR BILL CLINTON? THE PLOT THICKENS  
 DAN QUAYLE: A VICTIM OF GAFFES IS NOW KEEPING SCORE  
 NEW HAMPSHIRE: PULLING OUT THE STOPS IN THE RUSH TO BE FIRST 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   An Ex-Wrestler Goes To the Mat for Reform
</P>
<P>
   Jesse Ventura wants to reform the Reform Party.
</P>
<P>
   The in-your-face Minnesota governor, a former professional
wrestler whose surprise victory last November made him the most
successful candidate in the party's brief political history, has
been saying for weeks that Ross Perot, the party's founder and
all-powerful eminence, should step aside and give others a chance.
</P>
<P>
   Now he's going after Russell Verney, the party chairman and
Perot's closest political ally since the heady days of 1992, when
the billionaire Texan first ran for president and won nearly a
fifth of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura insists that he does not want to run the party himself
and has no plans to try to parlay his successful campaign for
governor into a campaign for the presidency. His only interest, he
says, is to strengthen a party whose hierarchy has become too
dictatorial in its ways.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter sent Monday to delegates who will attend the Reform
Party's annual national convention in Dearborn, Mich., in late
July, Ventura endorsed Jack Gargan, a party stalwart from Cedar
Key, Fla., to replace Verney.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like me,'' the governor wrote, ``Mr. Gargan believes party
rules should vest power at the grass-roots level, empower all
members equally, hold party leaders accountable to the members and
create a fair and open playing field for any candidate who may seek
the party's nomination.''
</P>
<P>
   Verney says he has not decided yet whether to seek re-election.
``But I welcome as many candidates to go after the job as possible
because competition is healthy,'' he said Tuesday. ``On the other
hand, Jesse's letter sounded a little dictatorial itself, too much
like an ultimatum. I prefer to think he's been badly served by his
staff.''
</P>
<P>
   Gargan says that if he is voted party chairman he will not only
work to reunify the party but will also move its headquarters from
Perot's hometown, Dallas, to Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the party's presidential nomination for Election 2000
is being eyed carefully by a number of White House hopefuls,
especially some hard-right conservative Republicans who say their
own party is abandoning them. The Reform Party is not a very good
fit for a hard-right Republican, being more reformist and populist
than conservative. But the $12.5 million that its nominee will get
in Federal election money, based on the party's past election
performance, will surely be a good fit.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton as Senator? The Plot Thickens
</P>
<P>
   People in Arkansas, as in the rest of the country, seem more
amused than anything else by the rumor that President Clinton might
run for the U.S. Senate from his home state in 2002, the year after
he leaves the White House. Most of them were still trying to digest
the possibility that his wife, Hillary, might run for the Senate in
New York next year when the rumor first hit.
</P>
<P>
   The White House has officially described the rumor as ``crazy.''
But it has not gone unnoticed in Arkansas, as in the rest of the
country, that Clinton, when asked if he would run, essentially
changed the subject.
</P>
<P>
   The Arkansas senator up for re-election in 2002 is Tim
Hutchinson, a ``family values,'' Christian-right Republican who,
before entering politics, was a Baptist minister and a college
professor.
</P>
<P>
   Under normal political circumstances, Hutchinson would be
reasonably well-positioned to win re-election, given that in
Arkansas in recent years Republicans have had a lot of Democrats on
the run. But of course, Bill Clinton is no ordinary political
circumstance.
</P>
<P>
   Still, when the rumor hit, the senator gave no sign of being
cowed by the prospect of a Clinton challenge.``I would relish the
race,'' he told The Northwest Arkansas News on Monday. ``It would
be fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Or would it?
</P>
<P>
   No sooner had he proclaimed what a joy a Clinton-Hutchinson
dust-up would be than he had to deal with an article in a new
magazine, Arkansas Review, that may have all but wiped out what he
was counting on for a winning edge: l'affaire Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The article said that despite all of Hutchinson's emphasis on
family values, his marriage was coming apart. And the article
asserted that he was involved in a ``growing relationship'' with a
woman who had been one of his Senate aides.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Hutchinson announced that he was filing for a divorce
from his wife, Donna, after 29 years of marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been tremendous strains on our marriage during the
past few years,'' he said. ``We sought extensive counseling prior
to taking this action.''
</P>
<P>
   A Victim of Gaffes Is Now Keeping Score
</P>
<P>
   Former Vice President Dan Quayle, out on campaign trail again,
no longer mangles ideas and lines as he did in the past, at least
by all accounts. Certainly there is nothing yet to top the spelling
of potato as ``potatoe'' or proffering that a mind is a terrible
thing to ``lose,'' as opposed to ``waste.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, says the Republican presidential aspirant, like Rodney
Dangerfield, he don't get no respect.
</P>
<P>
   After a speech in Washington on Monday _ no verbal slips of note
_ he told reporters it seemed that no matter how well he performs
on the stump these days, his reputation for gaffes continues to
adversely affect his poll numbers and fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, he argued, his rivals _ especially the
front-running Texas Gov. George W. Bush _ are getting an easy ride
on gaffes.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that Bush had mistakenly referred to Timorese as
``Timoreans'' and to Kosovars as ``Kosovarians,'' and then had
confused Slovakia and Slovenia, and contended that other Republican
candidates and the press had taken only the briefest notice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Use you wldest imagination and multiple it by a factor of
three,'' Quayle lamented, ``and then you'd come close to what would
be happening to me if I had made similar gaffes.''
</P>
<P>
   Pulling Out the Stops In the Rush to Be First
</P>
<P>
   For years, New Hampshire had a law that required its
presidential primary to take place in the early spring of each
presidential election year, no fewer than seven days before any
other state's primary. That meant, usually, that sometime in late
February or early March, a week after Iowa's first-in-the-nation
caucuses, New Hampshire would hold the nation's first primary.
</P>
<P>
   The two events became a fixed part of the U.S. political scene,
and both states soon acquired outsized political importance, given
their size and political make-up.
</P>
<P>
   Then other states began to horn in to get some of the clout and
glory. Dozens advanced the dates of their caucuses and primaries,
and many others still plan to join the forward rush.
</P>
<P>
   In Election 2000, the caucus and primary calendar will be so
front-loaded that the nominating process could be over in just a
few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   But Iowa says it is determined to remain first in caucusing, and
will set whatever date it must to do so. And Tuesday, New Hampshire
followed suit. Gov. Jeanne Shaheen signed a law that permits the
New Hampshire secretary of state to move the date of the state's
primary into 1999, if necessary, to keep New Hampshire out in
front.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
