<SLUG> BC-GOLF-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S., STRONG ON PAPER, IS A MATCH FOR EUROPE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ben Crenshaw was in a hotel meeting room Tuesday, watching a
video that recalled some of the great moments in Ryder Cup history.
</P>
<P>
   When the video concluded, Crenshaw stood up to speak. But for a
few moments, his voice quavered with emotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``That video moves me quite a bit,'' said Crenshaw, who will be
captain of the U.S. team that will face Europe for the Ryder Cup at
the Country Club in Brookline, Mass., Sept. 24-26. ``Being Ryder
Cup captain is quite an honor, and it's my job to get the best out
of these guys. Quite frankly, I think we're due.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Crenshaw and the U.S. team will feel the pressure
during Ryder Cup week, as Europe will try to capture the event _
held every two years _ for the third consecutive time, something
that Europe has never done.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, the American team will look extremely strong on
paper, with David Duval, Tiger Woods, Payne Stewart, Davis Love III
and Mark O'Meara having already secured positions. But the
Europeans have flourished in the role of underdog, and this year
the European team will be anchored by three of the world's best
players _ the Masters champion, Jose Maria Olazabal; Colin
Montgomerie and Lee Westwood. In the past two Ryder Cups, the
longer-hitting U.S. team has been outplayed around the greens, as
Europe has chipped and putted its way to crucial points. Crenshaw
would like to halt that trend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm encouraging all our guys to work on their short games,''
said Crenshaw, who played in four Ryder Cups, two won by the United
States. ``In match play, what really helps you is to hole out a
shot at an opportune moment. Our side has not done enough of
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Crenshaw will have a difficult choice to make when he
announces his two picks for captain in August.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Mickelson, No. 8 in the points standing, has said he will
not play much this summer because he wants to be at home with his
wife, Amy, who delivered a baby girl last week. But if Mickelson
falls out of the top 10, don't be surprised if he is one of
Crenshaw's captain's picks.
</P>
<P>
   Tough Year for Steve Jones
</P>
<P>
   This has been a difficult year for Steve Jones, the 1996 U.S.
Open champion, who did not play between this year's Masters and the
Open because of a sore right shoulder. Jones also suffered from an
irregular heartbeat in February for the third time in his career,
but that problem was corrected, and Jones hopes to salvage his
season with a strong finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been rehabilitating my shoulder for nine weeks, and even
though it's not 100 percent, it's getting closer, and I'm not going
to have surgery,'' said Jones, who will defend his title at the
John Deere Classic next month.
</P>
<P>
   Inkster Takes Money Lead
</P>
<P>
   In the process of winning the Ladies Professional Golf
Association McDonald's Championship, Juli Inkster took the lead
from Karrie Webb on the LPGA Tour money list. Inkster has won
$952,994 this year, while Webb has won $941,198. Despite her many
accomplishments, including winning the modern career Grand Slam,
Inkster has never won the LPGA money title. She came closest in
1986, when she finished third on the money list, winning $99,651.
</P>
<P>
   MacDonald Wins Ike by a Shot
</P>
<P>
   Ken MacDonald no longer has to be content with winning last
year's New Jersey State Open. MacDonald, 21, captured the Ike, the
stroke-play championship of the Metropolitan Golf Association,
Tuesday at Hollywood Country Club in Deal, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   MacDonald won by a shot over Jeff Thomas by rallying from a
five-shot deficit going into the afternoon's second round of the
day in the 54-hole event. After a two-over-par 74 in the morning,
MacDonald shot two-under 70 in the afternoon on the 6,772-yard
course. He finished at 216, the only player to play the course at
even par.
</P>
<P>
   ``I honestly didn't think I was in contention when I
three-putted the eighth hole,'' said MacDonald, a member at Upper
Montclair, who will be a senior at the University of Richmond this
fall. ``It's been a year since the New Jersey Open. Now, I can talk
about something else.''
</P>
<P>
   MacDonald rallied for his victory with birdies at the 459-yard
16th and the 230-yard 17th, where he hit a 4-iron to within three
feet to take the lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
