<SLUG> BC-GORE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `I am pro-union,' Gore tells textile workers
 &HT;    By Brian E. Crowley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI BEACH _ Singing ``look for the union label,'' Vice
President Al Gore promised labor leaders Tuesday that he will ``not
let Republicans weaken the unions.''
</P>
<P>
   If elected president, Gore, who sang to a cheering crowd, said
he would veto any legislation that he considered to be anti-worker
and he vowed to push to increase the minimum wage by $1 over the
next two years to $6.15 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``The gains you've made in the 20th century are just the
beginning of the gains you are going to make in the 21st century,''
Gore said during a speech to the Union of Needle Trades, Industrial
and Textile. ``Let me say loud and clear, I am pro-union.''
</P>
<P>
   Proposing a plan similar to 401(k) savings plans, in which both
the employer and the employee contribute, Gore said he wants a
401(j) plan, where the money would be saved and used for job
training.
</P>
<P>
   Deductibles for preventive care under Medicare should be
eliminated, he said, because, ``no senior should have to put off
preventive care because they don't think they can afford it.''
</P>
<P>
   Promising to open trade barriers overseas, Gore said the United
States also has an obligation to make sure that goods coming into
this country meet high environmental and safety standards in the
factories where they are produced.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also held two money-raising events, a lunch in Miami Beach
and a dinner in Tampa. According to his campaign, Gore collected
about $350,000. Today marks the end of the first six months of
gathering contributions. Gore is expected to report to the Federal
Elections Commission next month that he has collected a total of
about $18.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   His only rival for the Democratic nomination, former New Jersey
Sen. Bill Bradley is expected to have about $11 million, according
to his campaign. While that is far less than Gore, Bradley has
raised enough money to be a credible adversary.
</P>
<P>
   Among a large field of Republicans, Texas Gov. George W. Bush
has raised more money than all his GOP rivals combined. He is
expected to report at least $23 million, with most of it collected
in the past three months. Bush collected $2 million of that total
during a one-day, four city campaign trip to Florida last week.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to supporters at the luncheon here, Gore said Florida
will be crucial to his effort to win the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``We carried this state in 1996 and we can carry Florida
again,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Brian E. Crowley writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
