<SLUG> BC-PUBLIC-LIVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT YOUR USUAL RUNWAY WALKER  
 JUST SPELL HIS NAME RIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JAMES BARRON with LINDA LEE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``I'm a fashion model now,'' the actress Camryn
Manheim declared. ``I'm fabulous.''
</P>
<P>
   Is this an over-the-top scene from a David E. Kelley script?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' said Ms. Manheim, who won an Emmy last fall and a
Golden Globe in February for her role on Kelley's Sunday-night
drama ``The Practice.'' ``He writes that I fall off the stage and
sue Venezia. The real-life version is, I walk down the glamorous
runway and the man of my dreams is waiting in the audience and I
pick him out. All my other dreams have come true this year, so why
not this?''
</P>
<P>
   So it went Tuesday for Ms. Manheim. Her on-screen character
brawls with partners in her law firm; off-screen her name was
mentioned in May in newspaper accounts of a barroom brawl provoked
by guests at a private party in a Manhattan pub who bothered Monica
Lewinsky as she and Ms. Manheim dined together. Tuesday, Ms.
Manheim was preparing for what was billed as her runway debut: a
fashion show for Lane Bryant's Venezia collection. Lane Bryant is a
plus-size retailer, meaning that it specializes in sizes 14 to 28.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Manheim, who, a spokesman said, wears a size 22, sounded
elated.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole year has been about realizing my fantasies because
they've all been coming true,'' she said, backstage at the
Hammerstein Ballrooms of the New Yorker Hotel. ``I can't tell you
how many times I've walked up and down my living room in high heels
that don't fit and pretended I'm a fashion model. Now the slipper
fits.''
</P>
<P>
   So did the clothes, which she helped design.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got on television and people wanted to put me in
beautiful clothes, I didn't even know how to wear them,'' she said.
``There's a way you strut down the runway. There's a way you walk
through your life that you have to learn.''
</P>
<P>
   A Dropped Z Is All in the Game
</P>
<P>
   Ben Gazzara, 68, has been in a string of movies lately,
including ``Happiness,'' ``Buffalo 66'' and now Spike Lee's
``Summer of Sam,'' which opens on Friday. In that film he plays
Luigi, the center of a large and powerful Italian family determined
to help capture Son of Sam. Dignified Luigi has one of the best
lines in the film: ``What do you want me to do, arrest myself?''
</P>
<P>
   A somewhat different question was on Gazzara's mind at the
premiere party at Roseland on Monday: Was it too much to ask that
his name be spelled right in the closing credits? There it was:
Gazarra, with one z and two r's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe they did that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'll get into it tomorrow with my agent and my
lawyer,'' he added. ``I'll sue.'' But he was clearly joking.
</P>
<P>
   He tried to sound philosophical. ``What can I do? It could
become a legend, like a parlor game in the year 2500.''
</P>
<P>
   He jumped up to accept congratulations from Ed Bradley, a
correspondent on the CBS News magazine ``60 Minutes,'' for his
performance, credit or no.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in the crowd, people doing the Hustle dominated the
dance floor while Wesley Snipes stood at the bar, waiting for his
drink.
</P>
<P>
   The male bartenders, incidentally, were wearing white sleeveless
undershirts; the female bartenders had on long blonde wigs. The
idea was to re-create the working-class ambiance of that
disco-crazed summer of 1977, a decided contrast to the equally
authentic look of the two female stars of the film. Mira Sorvino, a
brunette these days, wore an ice-blue-beaded Bob Mackie. Jennifer
Esposito wore a strapless, backless Donna Karan dress that left no
doubt about an Egyptian-looking tattoo on her left shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told me it was the `third eye of insight,''' she said.
``I got it when I was 17 in Manhattan. I thought it sounded good _
the `third eye of insight.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
