<HEADER>
A3987 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBA-DRAFT-LADN     06-29 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-DRAFT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO EASY ANSWERS IN DRAFT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ You know it's a scary draft for NBA executives
when your options include trusting Chicago Bulls general manager
Jerry Krause or 19-year-old Lamar Odom.
</P>
<P>
   Today's ceremony at the MCI Center in Washington, D.C., is
considered the most muddled draft in recent memory. There is no
franchise player, no clear-cut No. 1 pick and no centers. That's a
GM's nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   It gets worse. Teams wanting to make deals for the top pick are
forced to deal with Krause, who is notoriously paranoid about his
draft decisions, and known for trying to hardball teams in trade
talks.
</P>
<P>
   It might be fitting that the one player Krause coveted early,
Rhode Island's Odom, has proved to be a headcase for the Bulls and
just about any other team that expressed interest. As late as
Monday night, Odom blew off a scheduled meeting with Bulls coach
Tim Floyd in Providence, R.I.
</P>
<P>
   Odom did graciously agree to an unimpressive workout Monday with
the Bulls, Clippers, Toronto and Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way he'll drop far,'' Floyd said. ``He's probably
made some errors in judgment, but you can't confuse that with a
person's character.''
</P>
<P>
   Translation: Someone else in the lottery can gamble on Odom, who
tried (and failed) to return to college after signing with an
agent.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago will be fielding offers up until it selects first, but
if it doesn't make a deal, is expected to take Maryland's Steve
Francis.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves Vancouver, which needs a power forward. Common sense
dictates the Grizzlies take Duke forward Elton Brand, especially
since he actually turned out to be 6-foot-8 when measured at a
predraft camp.
</P>
<P>
   But the Grizzlies also were the only team that Odom privately
worked out for, so that leaves him as an option at No. 2. And then
there are the 20 or so clubs wanting Vancouver's pick, so they can
claim point guard Baron Davis.
</P>
<P>
   If the Bulls do something crazy and select Brand, every team in
the league will be calling Vancouver so they can select Francis.
</P>
<P>
   A logical projected deal already confirmed by the Grizzlies had
Vancouver shipping the No. 2 pick to Minnesota, which would then
send point guard Terrell Brandon to Indiana. Vancouver would then
receive Pacers forward Antonio Davis and the Timberwolves' pick at
No. 6. Brandon would have to be signed to a new contract, but he
was not resisting a potential move to Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Less discussed has been a three-way trade where the Lakers would
send Glen Rice to Miami, the Heat would ship P.J. Brown to the
Grizzlies and the Lakers would get the No. 2 pick to draft Davis.
</P>
<P>
   But Vancouver figures to get even better deals by this
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Charlotte, which picks third, has made no secret that it wants
Davis, even though he refused to work out for the Hornets.
Privately, they are believed to want Francis more but expect him to
be gone.
</P>
<P>
   The Hornets also like Odom, but Charlotte GM Bob Bass said, ``At
some point, you have to say enough is enough.''
</P>
<P>
   That might be a smokescreen, but the Hornets do need a point
guard.
</P>
<P>
   If Odom falls to No. 4, it presents quite a dilemma for the
Clippers. They want Davis but would gladly take forward Wally
Szczerbiak, who made 34 of 50 of his 3-pointers during a workout
for Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   His character is perfect, but won't it at least cause the
Clippers pause to pass on the potential of Odom? Not when they
consider the chances he would leave as soon as he is eligible for
free agency.
</P>
<P>
   It's quite possible there has been too much trade talk, and this
could be a limited-activity draft, with minor deals like the one
sending Atlanta's Mookie Blaylock to Golden State for the No. 10
pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's just feeling each other out, throwing a lot of
stuff against the wall, trying to see what sticks,'' Wizards
general manager Wes Unseld said. ``For me, it's as thick as I've
seen it. I'm not getting a straight answer from anyone. Maybe
because nobody has any.''
</P>
<P>
   Toronto, which picks fifth, has been after the Bulls for the
past month, but refuses to part with Tracy McGrady or Doug
Christie. It's more likely the Raptors will be involved in
something small.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Washington and Toronto were tossing around a trade
that would give the Wizards the No. 5 selection (where they would
take Odom) and the Raptors would get Tracy Murray and the No. 7
(where they could take high schooler Jonathan Bender).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
