<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MANATEES-BOAT-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Club gives boat to state to help save manatees
</P>
<P>
   By Sally D. Swartz
</P>
<P>
   C. 1999 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   PORT SALERNO, Fla. _ Manatees from St. Lucie County to Key West
got a present on Tuesday _ a new boat biologists will use to rescue
them when they're in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Save The Manatee Club, the group singer Jimmy Buffett started in
1981, gave the $17,000 boat to Department of Environmental
Protection staffers. DEP's Florida Marine Research Institute
station in Tequesta will use it to rescue manatees and to collect
dead ones to learn what killed them.
</P>
<P>
   Manatee deaths are increasing, biologist Amy Perry said. The DEP
recorded 231 last year, and so far this year has counted 147.
Collisions with boats killed the highest number _ 37 _ of 123
deaths in which cause has been determined.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're only halfway through the year,'' Perry said, ``and the
numbers are way up.''
</P>
<P>
   Other high numbers: 24 newborns died; 22 died of natural causes;
and 10 died from red tide on Florida's west coast. The remainder
died in floodgate or canal lock accidents, were trapped in pipes
under roads or storm drains, or became entangled in monofilament
fishing line. Cause of death was not determined in 25 animals.
</P>
<P>
   Four manatees have died in Martin County and four in Palm Beach
County so far this year, Perry said. No deaths have been reported
in St. Lucie or Okeechobee counties.
</P>
<P>
   The 17-foot Mako boat, with a 115-horsepower motor and trailer,
will help researchers find and rescue manatees, and aid in a
photo-identification project.
</P>
<P>
   Many individual manatees can be identified by scars from
previous encounters with propellers, Perry said.
</P>
<P>
   Club board members Ross Wilcox of Palm Beach County and Pete
Meier of Martin County said the club bought the boat with money
from its $1 million annual budget.
</P>
<P>
   The Save the Manatee group has more than 40,000 members
worldwide and an estimated 12,000 Florida members, Wilcox said.
</P>
<P>
   The group promotes education and research and lobbies for
legislation to protect manatees, Wilcox said.
</P>
<P>
   The DEP can't afford extras such as the boat, Perry said. Money
to support manatee programs comes from the sale of manatee license
tags, buthas dwindled as other specialty plates were introduced.
</P>
<P>
   For information about the club or DEP's manatee research and
rescue programs, visit web pages: www.savethemanatee.org or
www.fmri.usf.edu/manatees.htm
</P>
<P>
   Sally D. Swartz writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-99 2310EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
