<HEADER>
A4105 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-ABORTION-NYT &LR;      06-29 0402
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-ABORTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A CRUEL SCHEME TO CURB ABORTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Wednesday, June 30:
</P>
<P>
   Don't be misled by the label. The benignly titled ``Child
Custody Protection Act'' scheduled for House action Wednesday is in
fact a cold-hearted piece of legislation that would jeopardize the
health of desperate young women seeking abortions and potentially
imprison adults who help them. The bill also flouts the
Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, the measure seeks to broaden the reach of strict
laws that are now on the books in 22 states requiring teen-agers to
notify or consult their parents before obtaining an abortion, or
else seek a judge's permission. It would do so by putting anyone
other than a parent who accompanies a minor seeking an abortion
across state lines at risk of criminal prosecution _ if the minor
has not met her home state's requirements for parental consent. The
House Judiciary Committee rejected Democratic attempts to soften
the measure, including a proposed exception for cases of incest.
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, parents should be involved in medical decisions
affecting their children. But the effect of this bill would be to
further isolate children who are already afraid to consult with
their parents about abortion. It might also cause them to risk
their safety by traveling to distant states alone.
</P>
<P>
   The potential damage to the Constitution is no less serious.
Apart from undermining the constitutional right to an abortion, the
legislation violates the right of citizens to travel freely and to
be treated as ``a welcome visitor rather than an unfriendly alien''
when entering another state _ a right recently upheld by the
Supreme Court in a California welfare case.
</P>
<P>
   The bill's backers can show no compelling justification for
giving different treatment to state residents and nonresidents
seeking medical services. In addition, the bill could result in
legal chaos as federal prosecutors try to figure out the
interaction between this new federal statute and and a host of
different parental notification laws in the states.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers on both sides of the aisle and the abortion debate
should join to defeat this misguided proposal. If not, President
Clinton must stand ready to use his veto pen in the event
election-year expediency prevails over principle in both chambers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
