</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-HOLBROOKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: UNTIMELY DELAY FOR HOLBROOKE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Wednesday, June 30:
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Foreign Relations Committee is set Wednesday to
approve the long-delayed nomination of Richard Holbrooke to be
chief American representative to the United Nations. Full Senate
confirmation could take place before the July 4 recess. But Sen.
Charles Grassley, R-Iowa, now threatens to delay the nomination
over an unrelated civil service dispute. Holbrooke's presence is
urgently needed at the U.N. The majority leader, Sen. Trent Lott,
R-Miss., should advise Grassley to drop his obstruction.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute is over Linda Shenwick, an employee of the American
U.N. mission who says she was punished for telling Congress and the
press about wasteful spending at the U.N. The validity of her claim
should be decided by the Merit System Protection Board, a civil
service panel that protects whistle-blowers. Her complaint has
nothing to do with Holbrooke. Pressing business awaits him. The
U.N. is setting up a new administration for Kosovo and Holbrooke
can help assure that mistakes made in Bosnia are not repeated. His
assistance is also needed in a new effort to rebuild Security
Council consensus on disarming Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke's wide diplomatic experience in Europe and Asia and
his Balkan peacemaking achievements well suit him for the U.N. His
nomination has been thoroughly reviewed on ethical and policy
grounds and has support from a wide range of senators, including
Jesse Helms, R-N.C. Grassley ill serves the nation by delaying
confirmation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
