<HEADER>
A4109 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-WAYNE-ART-NYTR     06-29 0420
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-WAYNE-ART-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARSHALL WAYNE, 87, OLYMPIAN WHO RILED HITLER IN '36 GAMES
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: N.C., Fla., Calif.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By DEAN HENSLEY   
 The Times-News in Hendersonville, N.C. 
  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HENDERSONVILLE, N.C. _ Marshall Wayne, who displeased Adolf
Hitler by winning gold and silver medals in diving in the 1936
Berlin Olympics and was later shot down over Italy fighting the
Nazis, died June 16. He was 87.
</P>
<P>
   He died at Pardee Hospital in Hendersonville after suffering a
cerebral hemorrhage while working on a book at home, said his
sister, Dever Antes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had met Ernest Hemingway and had wanted to write stories
like Hemingway's for a long time,'' said Ms. Antes, also of
Hendersonville.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Antes said her brother spoke with Hitler and the Nazi leader
was very displeased with Wayne for winning the gold medal in the
platform diving competition. Wayne also won the silver medal in the
3-meter springboard diving.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hitler wanted his man from Germany to win it, so he wasn't too
happy at all seeing my brother win,'' Ms. Antes recalled.
</P>
<P>
   She said the family lived in Miami close to a pool where Wayne
did most of his practicing. He excelled at diving in high school
and at the University of Miami.
</P>
<P>
   While serving in World War II as a colonel in the Army Air
Forces, Wayne's plane was shot down in Italy and Italians helped
Wayne get to a British Aid Station and then to England for surgery.
The fall from the plane had torn ligaments and tendons in his leg,
Ms. Antes said.
</P>
<P>
   After the war, Wayne became a Pan American Airways pilot, and
retired as a captain in 1972, the same year he moved to
Hendersonville.
</P>
<P>
   His love for the Olympics landed him a spot on the 1996 Atlanta
Olympic Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Olympic torch was making a run through town and Wayne was
invited to take part in the ceremony,'' Ms. Antes said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My brother was wearing a fake medal around his neck and when
he climbed out of the car downtown, someone shouted, `Hey where'd
you get that medal?' And Marshall said, `From the '36 Olympics in
Berlin.' ''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his sister, Wayne is survived by his daughter,
Marilyn Wayne of San Pedro, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne's other daughter died a couple of years ago, Ms. Antes
said.
</P>
<P>
   (The Times-News on Hendersonville, N.C., is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-29-99 2319EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
