<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-29 23:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4112 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-TIGERS-NYT     06-29 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-TIGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEMENS DOMINATES TIGERS AS YANKS WIN, 3-0 
</HEADLINE>
 (nk) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It is understandable that Roger Clemens has not been
elated with his first four and a half months as a Yankee. He has
not consistently pitched like a five-time Cy Young Award winner or
even like the best starter on a powerful team. He has not
repeatedly reached that level. Clemens has been decent, not
dominating.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees keep waiting for Clemens to purposefully saunter to
the mound and take over. Not just for one gaudy start here and one
glossy start there, but for that night and for the rest of the
season. That is why the Yankees jumped at the chance to snatch
Clemens from the Blue Jays, because he can dominate.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens was pretty close to dominant as the Yankees edged the
Tigers, 3-0, Tuesday night at Yankee Stadium to win their seventh
straight game. The Tigers had several scoring chances and proved
that Clemens was mortal, but Clemens actually was most dominant
when those situations arose and recorded his first shutout as a
Yankee.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, Clemens took over. The Yankees hope it lasts.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Jeter belted a two-run homer off Justin Thompson and Shane
Spencer, who dyed his hair a shocking platinum blonde, also homered
to begin the scoring and continued trying to seize control of the
unpredictable left field job. Spencer played right field while Paul
O'Neill was rested against Thompson, but he has four homers in his
last seven games and is giving the Yankees hope that he might
finally be the answer in left.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens must be the answer at the top of the rotation or the
Yankees will need a new ace for October. He was gritty enough
against the Tigers, escaping a jam in the sixth inning with runners
on second and third by striking out Tony Clark on a split-finger
fastball and retiring Damion Easley on a flyout. He also stranded
runners at second in the third and the fifth. The Tigers were 0 for
5 with men in scoring position as Clemens scattered their eight
hits over six innings.
</P>
<P>
   After Clemens pitched poorly in a 12-4 victory over Tampa Bay
last week, Manager Joe Torre met with him and pitching coach Mel
Stottlemyre the next day. Torre wanted to ask Clemens about his
philosophy and tell him what the Yankees had observed through his
first 12 starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to see what was going on,'' said Torre.
</P>
<P>
   The conversation must have helped. Clemens had a fierce
fastball, a nifty split-finger fastball and precise control as he
struckout eight, walked one, won for the third time in four starts
and shaved his ERA from 5.13 to 4.52. The fans roared when Clemens
(8-2) trotted out of the dugout for the ninth and he completed the
130-pitch effort with three strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Spencer and Knoblauch were in the Soho section of Manhattan
Tuesday when they both decided to pop into a salon for some hair
lightening. Knoblauch merely had blonde streaks placed in his hair,
but Spencer bleached his hair so severely that it looked white.
Spencer said that he and Knoblauch had their hair bleached
simultaneously so Knoblauch had not tricked him by being more
conservative. Both players followed Clemens, who had his hair
lightened last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``It came out a little lighter than I thought it was going to,''
admitted Spencer. ``My head was on fire. I'll go black the next
time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
