<P>
   CONGO-ASSESS (Johannesburg) _ As talks in Lusaka, Zambia falter,
a news analysis on efforts to end the 11-month civil war. By Donald
G. McNeil.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Locator map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   POPULATION-U.N. (United Nations) _ With a special U.N. General
Assembly session on Wednesday, delegates from 180 countries are
striving to repair a shattered consensus on limiting world
population growth. By Paul Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BUILD (Djakovica, Yugoslavia) _ Kosovo Albanians, often
using Serb wreckage, rebuild their lives. By Ian Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Locator map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.
Photos [NYT1,2,3) have been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   CAMBODIA-PRISON (Phnom Penh, Cambodia) _ The ghosts seem to
think this old schoolhouse belongs to them, thumping and moaning,
crying out for help, offering themselves for sex, turning
themselves into white cats. People who work here say the ghosts are
the restless souls of victims of the Khmer Rouge, and their forms
are as varied as the imaginations of the people who describe them.
Lately, these people say, the ghosts have become newly agitated.
Their master is back: the buck-toothed schoolteacher nicknamed Duch
who turned the Tuol Sleng high school building into the most
efficient and terrifying torture chamber of the Khmer Rouge years.
By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT24,25,26) have been sent to NYT photo
clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CONTRACEPTION-INSURE (Boston) _ Viagra, it turns out, has a
political side effect. Last year's anti-impotence sensation has led
to this year's byproduct: Around the country, more than a
half-dozen state legislatures, swayed largely by insurers' coverage
of Viagra treatment, have recently passed measures requiring
carriers that cover prescription drugs to pay for women's
contraceptives as well. More states are expected to follow. By
Carey Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HEPATITIS-DRUG (Undated) _ Advocates for people with
hepatitis C announced that they have found a way for patients to
bypass a major drug company and purchase a medications at far below
the usual price. The medication is an antiviral drug, Ribavirin,
that works against hepatitis C only when it is combined with
another treatment, interferon. By Denise Grady.
</P>
<P>
   MEDICAL-SCHOOL-DISPUTE (Undated) _ The idea seemed simple
enough. Ross University, a medical school in the Caribbean island
nation of Dominica, would open a branch in the United States _ in
Wyoming, to be specific, which lacks a medical school of its own.
Casper, the city chosen for the branch, would get 200 jobs and a
projected $10 million a year in economic development. Ross would
get a mainland campus for 600 to 1,000 students _ the first
for-profit medical school to open in the United States in nearly a
century. But the devil was in the details, and now the project has
stalled amid fears that permitting a foreign medical school to
operate in the United States would lead to a proliferation of
unlicensed and unregulated schools. By Sharon R. King.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Locator map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.
Photo [NYT32) has been sent to NYT photo clients)
</P>
<P>
   NY-FORTUNE-TELLING (New York) _ The green awning outside the
quaint Greenwich Village storefront advertises ``psychic,'' but the
37-year-old fortuneteller who calls herself Pamela Miller probably
will not answer the door anymore. Police said she was arrested June
24 for making a woman in her 40s believe she had a curse and taking
$50,000 of her money over three years to get rid of it. It was the
13th arrest under Operation Crystal Ball, a seven-month-old effort
by the the city Police Department's Special Frauds Squad to address
the problem of illegal fortunetelling. By Robin Pogrebin.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT31) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
