<HEADER>
A4126 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ESTATE-SETTLEMENT-SPI     06-29 1157
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ESTATE-SETTLEMENT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMAN FALSELY CHARGED GETS $230,000 SETTLEMENT, APOLOGY FROM
COUNTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ELAINE PORTERFIELD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ It's been a few years since 74-year-old Laura Park
taught fifth-graders constitutional law and U.S. history, but she
still had a few lessons for King County about justice.
</P>
<P>
   Park, a former Washington state teacher of the year, has
received a record settlement from the King County Prosecutor's
Office after she was falsely charged in 1994 with theft by Deputy
Prosecutor Ivan Orton.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to $230,000 for violation of her constitutional
rights, Park received a formal apology from the Prosecutor's Office
June 16. Top prosecutors have also outlined administrative changes
to increase supervision of deputy prosecutors in the fraud unit to
prevent similar incidents.
</P>
<P>
   The theft charge grew out of a simple probate dispute with
relatives over the estate of Park's late mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is humiliating for me to have to say this, but I am not a
thief and to have been so labeled was an experience traumatic
beyond belief,'' Park said in court papers. ``When I taught fifth
grade, I instructed my pupils on American history and our
constitutional rights, and during the course of the criminal
litigation, I felt like I had none.''
</P>
<P>
   Park recalled being arrested, fingerprinted and being led to
jail with two women suspected of prostitution.
</P>
<P>
   Said Franklin Shoichet, Park's civil attorney:
</P>
<P>
   ``We are all still shaking our heads in amazement that a
prosecutor would file this case. ... In 23 years as a lawyer, it's
the most cockeyed use of prosecutorial resources I've ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Satterberg, chief of staff for Prosecutor Norm Maleng,
personally issued the apology to Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately, we regret the action,'' Satterberg said Tuesday.
``We have apologized to her and made her whole because we have done
harm to Mrs. Park. With 20-20 hindsight, it's a case we regret
filing.''
</P>
<P>
   Satterberg said Orton filed the case and its appeal without
consulting his supervisors. His agency was unaware of it until the
Appeals Court threw it out, he said. Prosecutors have instituted a
new tracking system for the fraud division to keep supervisors
informed of all fraud cases, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Satterberg called Orton a highly skilled deputy prosecutor with
17 years of experience. No disciplinary action is planned, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He understands that his judgment has been questioned by two
courts and his bosses,'' Satterberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Orton was on vacation and could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Shoichet said the settlement is a state record for a plaintiff
whose constitutional rights were violated by a prosecutor. It also
appears to be one of the top such settlements in the nation, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement, however, will be eaten up by taxes and legal
costs to a number of lawyers, Shoichet said. Park said she sued
King County in federal court not for the money, but because she
believed the system had failed her.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I paid in lost sleep, nightmares and emotional upheaval
is incalculable,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The case began when Park, who was the personal representative
for her mother's estate, used money from a joint account held with
a second heir to repair her mother's home and subdivide a lot for
sale.
</P>
<P>
   She never used any of the jointly held funds for personal use.
But how she used the funds angered a third relative and heir, who
believed that was an improper use of money, even though Park did
not need any court approval to spend the money.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the third heir complained to both probate court and
the fraud unit of the King County Prosecutor's Office, eventually
leading Orton to file first-degree theft and attempted-theft
charges against Park.
</P>
<P>
   Orton alleged in the 1994 charges that Park committed theft by
exerting unauthorized control of the second relative's share of the
joint account, even though he conceded she had not used the money
for personal gain and had ``no intent to steal.''
</P>
<P>
   A number of local attorneys involved with the case say they
found Park's prosecution nearly unbelievable. Such disputes over an
estate are common and best handled by a probate court, they say.
</P>
<P>
   ``... I have never encountered or even heard of a prosecutor
attempting to end-run around the power of a probate court and
attempting to become involved in an ordinary civil dispute over
ownership of a joint bank account, as Mr. Orton did,'' Scott
Easter, a former King County prosecutor who represented Park in
probate court, said in court papers.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Michael Kolker successfully argued to have the criminal
case against Park thrown out at both the Superior Court and the
state Appeals Court levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was totally inappropriate for a criminal case,'' said
Kolker, who still fumes when he recalls the case. ``Ivan Orton was
out of control; that's the bottom line.''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle police properly refused to investigate the case, he said
in court papers.
</P>
<P>
   Park, who was named Edmonds School District teacher of the year
in 1973 and 1975-76 state teacher of the year by the Council of
Chief State School Officers, fought the case even as she nursed her
husband through Alzheimer's disease, to which he succumbed to last
year.
</P>
<P>
   She required anti-depressants after she was charged with the
theft, which she takes to this day, court papers said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the hardest moments came when she was arrested and taken
to the King County Jail to be fingerprinted and have her mug shot
taken, Park said. She was led from the courthouse to the jail along
with two women arrested on prostitution charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an unreal experience,'' she said. ``I was taken in
handcuffs to the jail. ... The two gals who were prostitutes, well,
they were very interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Park said in an interview this week that she was immensely
frustrated by the fact Orton refused to talk with her before or
after filing the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still do not understand why Mr. Orton, during the course of
his five-month investigation, could not simply (have) picked up a
telephone and asked my lawyers and me to submit to an interview,''
Park said in court papers. ``I would have been happy to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   Satterberg said he regretted Park was never interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost always critical to an investigation to talk to a
suspect,'' he said. ``I don't have a good explanation for failing
to get her side of the story.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the new tracking system instituted by the Prosecutor's
Office, each case is now entered onto a log, which is constantly
updated, allowing supervisors to track its program, he said. No
such system existed previously.
</P>
<P>
   Park said the changes in the fraud division was what really
mattered to her.
</P>
<P>
   ``An apology was greatly appreciated, but action is more
important,'' Park said. ``It's been five years of misery.''
</P>
</TEXT>
