<HEADLINE>
HERSHISHER PITCHES METS PAST MARLINS, 5-1 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ He is two and a half months shy of his 41st birthday.
But for one night, at least, Orel Hershiser demonstrated that every
now and then he can pitch as if her were still in his 20s and
dominating the National League.
</P>
<P>
   Sinker ball. Ground ball. Sinker. Grounder. The inexperienced
young hitters of the Florida Marlins kept beating the ball into the
ground, like some sort of strange highlight film straight out of
1988.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing missing in the Mets' 5-1 victory Tuesday over the
free-swinging Marlins was Hershiser's old Dodgers uniform. The one
he wore in `88 when he tossed 60 consecutive scoreless innings to
end the season and break Don Drysdale's old record, before pitching
Los Angeles past the Mets in the NL Championship Series and then by
the Oakland A's in the World Series on his way to a Cy Young award.
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser (8-5) allowed just one run and five hits in 8 1/3
innings as he fell two outs short of the Mets' first complete game
of the season and Hershiser's first in nearly two years.
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser also missed his first shutout in over four years when
Alex Gonzalez tripled to right to open the ninth and Bruce Aven
grounded to short to score Gonzalez. Kevin Orie then blasted a
double and Hershiser was done after 93 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Mets' longest outing from a starter this season, and
Hershiser left to a standing ovation from the handful of fans
remaining of the announced crowd of 11,256 at Pro Player Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   He earned the applause against the team with the worst record in
the major leagues, and after the start of the game as delayed 1
hour 12 minutes because of rain.
</P>
<P>
   The victory was Hershiser's fourth in a row and the Mets' 17th
in their last 22 games. The Mets, who again pulled to within three
games of the Atlanta Braves in the NL East, have now won the last
five times Hershiser has pitched. And Tuesday night was easily the
40-year-old right-hander's strongest performance since signing with
the club during spring training.
</P>
<P>
   It was also Hershiser's 198th career victory, leaving him just
two shy of the 200-plateau he covets.
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser's longest outing in 14 previous starts with the Mets
had been 6 2/3 innings. He was averaging just 5 1/3 innings a start
coming into Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   But through seven shutout innings Tuesday, Hershiser had thrown
just 68 pitches, an average of 9.7 pitches per inning, nearly six
fewer than his average coming into the game.
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser needed just five pitches in both the third and fourth
innings to retire the side, with all six outs coming on ground
balls. After an 18-pitch fifth, it took Hershiser just five pitches
again to retire the side in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Until Jorge Fabregas flew to center to end the fifth, only one
ball had left the infield: Aven's bloop single.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven of the first 14 outs Hershiser recorded were on ground
balls. Eight of them went to Rey Ordonez, who had an outside shot
at a 96-year-old record for assists in a game by a shortstop: 14 by
Tommy Corcoran of the Cincinnati Reds in 1903. Ordonez fell short,
finishing with 11 assists.
</P>
<P>
   But Hershiser needed 17 pitches to complete the eighth, as the
Marlins put two runners on in an inning for the first time, one on
another infield hit to third, another on an error by third baseman
Robin Ventura.
</P>
<P>
   The red-hot Ventura more than atoned for himself. His two-out
bases-loaded single off Livan Hernandez (3-8) in the third inning
gave the Mets a 2-0 lead. Rickey Henderson, who had three hits,
drove in a run in the fourth with a sacrifice fly. And then Alfonzo
chased Hernandez with a prodigious two-run homer over the left
field scoreboard in the seventh to complete the scoring.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
