<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN INSISTS CAMPAIGN FINANCE REFORM AND SPECIAL-INTEREST
DONATIONS ARE COMPATIBLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF BARKER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It is daunting enough for a presidential candidate
to have to raise $20 million to establish himself as a serious
contender.
</P>
<P>
   It's even tougher when the candidate is running, as is Sen. John
McCain, as a reform-minded alternative who has spent years pushing
to end the reliance on big money in election campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a complicated dance step, and it's most complicated for
John McCain and (Democratic candidate) Bill Bradley because both
are trying to take the money and look clean simultaneously,'' said
Larry Makinson, executive director of the Center for Responsive
Politics, a public interest group.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who plans to speak out again on behalf of campaign
reform during a major speech today in Bedford, N.H., says he has
heard people express sentiments similar to Makinson's before, and
expects he will again in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Arizona Republican said it irks him when it is
suggested that there is something unusual, or inconsistent, about
taking special-interest money while running as a reform candidate.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has spent years trying to prod his fellow Republicans
into supporting his proposals to reduce the impact of the
wealthiest donors during election campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he finds himself having to raise about $20 million to
establish himself as a serious alternative to front-runner George
W. Bush, the Texas governor.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's world, like those of the other presidential candidates,
has become dominated by fund-raisers. Only the locations, and
sometimes the menus, vary.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so foolish and ignorant for someone to say, `Hey, well,
you're raising money, and you're for campaign-finance reform?'''
McCain said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   He told ``The Arizona Republic'' that if he wins the GOP
nomination, he will instruct the Republican National Committee not
to spend ``soft money'' on his campaign. Soft money, which is
collected from corporations, wealthy individuals and labor groups,
is not supposed to be spent on behalf of candidates for federal
office. But both parties bent the rules in the 1996 election, and
may do so again.
</P>
<P>
   While he eschews soft money, McCain has been accepting
contributions from political action committees.
</P>
<P>
   He has amassed a broad array of thousands of contributors and is
reaping significant sums from businesses _ notably those in
telecommunications and transportation _ that fall under his
jurisdiction as chairman of the Senate Commerce, Science and
Transportation Committee.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's largest contributors include employees or PACs of
communications giants such as Viacom, US West, Ameritech and Bell
Atlantic. Through their PACs, transportation companies such as
Burlington Northern-Santa Fe and America West have also donated
heavily.
</P>
<P>
   His campaign staff estimates McCain will have raised some $2.5
million from all sources during the second quarter, which ends
today. That would top his first-quarter total of $1.8 million
raised. McCain also has been able to draw on $1.9 million in
leftover contributions from his 1998 Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   No one is going so far as to accuse McCain of hypocrisy over the
money issue. Even McCain's rivals concede that he would foolishly
undercut his prospects if he sought to make a point by adopting
more stringent campaign-finance guidelines, in addition to his
soft-money restriction, than the rest of the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a terrible position for him to be in, and I'm sure an
uncomfortable one,'' Makinson said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said he hasn't been influenced by the money he accepts
from executives with business before his committee. In fact, he
says he has been fighting with some of his high-powered donors such
as AT&AMP;T over regulatory matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would expect the constitutional right that every citizen has
_ innocent until proven guilty,'' McCain said, adding that there's
``never been any connection'' between contributions and committee
policy. ``Yes, I've gotten money from the telecommunications
industry, but I've gotten money from people all over America.''
</P>
<P>
   Makinson said the scramble for cash creates, at least, the
perception that candidates are being compromised. ``The structure
of the system makes it very difficult. It's like the old biblical
thing that it's easier for a camel to go into the eye of a needle
than for a rich man to get into heaven,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's committee purview is vast. He oversees issues ranging
from cable and satellite television rules, to airline deregulation,
to access to long-distance markets. His verdicts on legislation can
affect the direction of entire industries.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Davis, McCain's campaign manager, said in an interview that
he didn't believe McCain enjoyed any special advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it an advantage to be Elizabeth Dole, who got 300,000 names
(of contributors) from her husband on the day she announced?''
Davis asked. ``Whether Elizabeth's 300,000 names are better than
what we've got, I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dole, a Republican former Cabinet secretary, is
competing with McCain for the GOP nomination. Her husband, Bob, was
the Republican nominee in 1996, but lost to President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, McCain has traveled around the country with
Sen. Russell Feingold, D-Wis., promoting their legislation to
minimize the influence of wealthy contributors on congressional
elections. The bill, which McCain intends to push in his speech
today, would ban soft money.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Feingold, on principle, declined all soft-money
assistance from the Democratic Party, and severely limited
donations from political action committees. He just barely won
re-election to the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has been promoting his reformist credentials. On Friday,
his campaign sent dozens of reporters a column by the ``Washington
Pos''t's E.J. Dionne saying McCain ``could once again lift himself
above his competitors'' by pushing a campaign-finance reform bill
toward passage in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The column also noted that McCain was ``not pure on this issue''
because he was ``working the Washington cash circuit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You can be for trying to change the system, but play by the
rules of the games,'' Davis told the ``Republic.'' ``There is no
strategy other than to identify Republican givers and go after them
for their contributions, whether it's $20 (or more).''
</P>
<P>
   McCain began raising funds in earnest at the beginning of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Hart, managing partner of a Washington legal and
governmental-affairs firm, said he got a call on Jan. 29 inviting
him to an organizational meeting at a club in Georgetown. Hart
described the crowd as ``a cross section of friends, including sort
of the military establishment, and lobbyists.''
</P>
<P>
   Hart, who later donated $1,000, said there was no pressure to
contribute.
</P>
<P>
   McCain subsequently held large fund-raisers, which cumulatively
raised hundreds of thousands of dollars, at the Arizona Biltmore in
Phoenix and the Red Sage restaurant in downtown Washington, among
other locations.
</P>
<P>
   Attendees at the events have included John Timmons, a lobbyist
for America West; Will Ball, president of the National Soft Drink
Association; Mary McAuliffe, vice president of external relations
for Union Pacific; and Robbie Aiken, head of the Washington office
for Pinnacle West, of which the Arizona Public Service utility is a
subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   McAuliffe invited more than 100 people to yet another
fund-raiser for McCain on Monday night. It was a catered event,
with the menu calling for Southwestern hors d'oeuvres to be served
at her Virginia home. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
