r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PHOENIX-CENSUS-AZR &LR;      06-29 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHOENIX-CENSUS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHOENIX SOON TO BE NO. 5 CITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By SHAUN MCKINNON AND KATHLEEN   
 Ingley  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   We're No. 7.
</P>
<P>
   Which may come as a bit of a surprise to those of us who thought
we were No. 6.
</P>
<P>
   But the Census Bureau, in a report to be released today, is very
clear: Phoenix is the seventh-largest city in the country, still
trailing San Diego, which many of us thought we had passed a couple
of years back.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix officials can produce a set of home-grown numbers that
show otherwise. But it may not matter for much longer. Based on
Census Bureau figures, Arizona's capital city should blow by both
San Diego and Philadelphia by 2006 to become the nation's
fifth-largest city.
</P>
<P>
   That's the meat of the bureau's latest statistics: Phoenix
remains the nation's fastest-growing big city, adding more than
200,000 new residents from July 1990 to July 1998, a 21.3 percent
rate of increase that census officials say is rewriting the books
on population booms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phoenix is in a growth class of its own as far as the largest
cities go,'' Census Bureau demographer Marc Perry said Tuesday.
``It's not just that it's gaining a lot of people, it's gaining a
lot of people at a fast rate. You don't see many other places that
are continuing to grow at that clip.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only did Phoenix grow faster, both in numbers and
percentage, than any of the nine U.S. cities with a population of
more than 1 million, it grew at a faster clip than all 26 U.S.
cities with a population of more than 500,000.
</P>
<P>
   Even more fascinating to demographers is the growth of Phoenix
suburbs. In many metropolitan areas, Perry said, the big, central
cities have leveled off in growth, with most new people siphoned
off to the outer suburban rings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gilbert, Chandler and Mesa are booming on their own,'' Perry
said.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler, in fact, led Arizona among all cities of more than
100,000 population and nearly led the nation, adding more than
70,000 new residents from 1990 to 1998, a rate of 78.4 percent.
Only Henderson, Nev., an exploding Las Vegas suburb, grew faster,
more than doubling in eight years.
</P>
<P>
   Homes for newcomers are surging into once-isolated areas.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Road, a dozen miles north of downtown Phoenix, was home to
a string of horse farms as recently as a decade ago. Now, the
pastures have given way to housing tracts and apartment complexes
with such names as Equestrian Manor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sad to see them go,'' said Cindy Chavez, who works at
nearby Greenway Saddlery. But the growth has been great for her
employer, who gets new customers.
</P>
<P>
   At the start of the 1990s, Waterworld Safari was an oasis among
the cactus and creosote in northwest Phoenix at 43rd Avenue and
Pinnacle Peak Road.
</P>
<P>
   From the top of a slide at the water park, ``the scenery was
gorgeous, you used to see the whole desert,'' said Pam Walters,
revenue manager. ``Now you see rooftops.''
</P>
<P>
   Valerie Manning, president of the Phoenix Chamber of Commerce,
sees the latest statistics as a point of pride.
</P>
<P>
   Growth fuels economic growth, Manning said, although the
business community is ``certainly concerned about how to manage our
growth more effectively in the future and are working on that as a
very high priority this year.''
</P>
<P>
   The galloping growth has spurred critics to look for ways to
rein it in.
</P>
<P>
   The Sierra Club is gathering signatures to put the Citizens
Growth Management Initiative on the ballot in November 2000. A
centerpiece of the initiative is a requirement for cities to set
boundaries on where growth can occur.
</P>
<P>
   ``People feel unsettled by how fast things are growing,'' said
Sandy Bahr, lobbyist for the club's Arizona chapter. ``Our quality
of life has suffered and will continue to suffer unless we get a
handle on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Jane Hull has been pushing her own plan, known as Growing
Smarter, partly as a way to head off the Sierra Club's initiative.
It includes requirements for better local planning and money to buy
open space, which voters approved last fall.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Rex, research manager at the Center for Business Research at
Arizona State University, maintains that the city is past the point
of reaping many benefits from growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're big enough to have just about anything here, at least in
terms of mass size,'' Rex said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the last hurdles was getting big enough for major league
sports. During the 1990s, the Phoenix area reached the critical
mass, and is now one of just 11 cities to have all four major
professional sports.
</P>
<P>
   Perry, the census demographer, said it's impossible to predict
if Phoenix and the rest of the Valley can sustain such a high rate
of growth for many more years. Some census watchers predicted the
current expansion would never last through the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   Outside factors almost certainly will influence future growth,
Perry said.
</P>
<P>
   Chief among those other outside areas is California, home to
about half the population of the 11 Western states. An improving
economy there in recent years has begun attracting people back to
the state.
</P>
<P>
   As for the discrepancy over who's No. 6, Phoenix city spokesman
Mark Hughes said the Census Bureau estimates are based on the 1990
head-count. The Maricopa Association of Governments produces its
own estimates based on a 1995 special census, which would better
adjust for growth.
</P>
<P>
   MAG estimates the population of Phoenix at 1,238,120, as of July
1, 1998, the date corresponding to the Census Bureau's report. A
MAG estimate dated Thursday will show an even-higher figure of
1,263,895, Hughes said. &QL; 
Shaun McKinnon can be reached at (602) 444-7116 or at
shaun.mckinnon(at)pni.com via e-mail. Kathleen Ingley can be
reached at (602) 444-8171 or at kathleen.ingley(at) pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
